<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SENATOR TORRICELLI RETREATS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Aug. 3:
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best that can be said of Sen. Robert Torricelli's
leap into the icy preliminaries of next year's gubernatorial race
in New Jersey is that he leapt out again so quickly. Three weeks
after declaring plans to run for governor, the ambitious senator
suddenly decided to keep his job in Washington. Many of the state's
most powerful Democrats had refused to desert his rival James
McGreevey, who almost defeated Gov. Christie Whitman in 1997. Their
reasons ranged from fair play to political revenge against
Torricelli to the results of a quick weekend poll that showed
McGreevey more popular.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of his public misstep, Torricelli said he had been
``humbled,'' an added value for any senator in the grand hallways
of Congress. But back in his home state, the senator's intrigues
leave his own wounded political party with a few new fractures. One
of the more telling plots starred Rep. Robert Menendez of Union
City, who has been simmering for months over a broken Torricelli
promise of support in this year's Senate race. Menendez and other
state leaders basically stalled a few public endorsements for
Torricelli while McGreevey lined up enough supporters to ruin the
senator's sudden appetite for one of the most powerful
governorships in the country.
</P>
<P>
   As he backed out of the race, Torricelli refused to endorse
McGreevey while McGreevey sniped that ``The Democratic Party is
greater than any individual's political ambitions,'' meaning
greater than Torricelli's. For Democrats, the only good news is
that this important state election is still more than a year away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
