<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-HELLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLING BOOSTS CHANCES AT ANOTHER 20-WIN SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rick Helling shrugs when the topic turns to
his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wins and losses, I don't think I have too much control over
it,'' the Rangers' pitcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Helling has a point. If he pitches brilliantly but the team's
offense doesn't score, he can lose. If he pitches poorly but the
offense lights up the scoreboard, he can win.
</P>
<P>
   But Helling's theory doesn't do justice to the way he is
pitching this season.
</P>
<P>
   Helling won his 13th game last night, and is tied with Gil
Heredia of Oakland for second in the American League behind David
Wells' 16. There is nothing fluky about it. His 13-7 record is
evidence that Helling is making the transition from solid starter
to bona fide ace.
</P>
<P>
   Helling allowed two runs in 62/3 innings as the Rangers defeated
the Chicago White Sox, 7-2, last night. It was his sixth
consecutive victory, and the fifth time in his past seven starts
he's allowed two earned runs or less.
</P>
<P>
   High victory totals are nothing new for Helling, who won 20
games in 1998 and 13 last season.
</P>
<P>
   In those seasons he did benefit from a potent offense. He had a
4.41 earned-run average in '98 and a 4.84 ERA last season.
</P>
<P>
   But this season, he's seventh in the AL with a 3.82 ERA. He's
also fourth with a .240 opponents' batting average, and fourth in
innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to get better every year,'' Helling said. ``I'm
throwing the slider this year, which is a new pitch. Every year you
have to do that. There's always things you can learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The slider was a key pitch last night. He used that and his
fastball to get ahead of hitters and set them up for his curve.
</P>
<P>
   That was the sequence in the biggest matchup of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Helling breezed through the first three innings, allowing only
one hit, but ran into trouble in the top of the fourth when he gave
up two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had scored four runs in the bottom of the third, so
he still was in control, but the game almost got away from him in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Two walks and a single loaded the bases with two outs and
brought White Sox third baseman Herbert Perry to the plate. Helling
got ahead in the count, then struck Perry out looking at a curve to
end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the next five batters before walking Jose Valentin
with two out in the seventh, and was pulled after throwing 125
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a decent job of keeping them in check,'' Helling said.
``The key is keeping them off-balance. You can't go with the same
pitch in the same location.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling has about 13 starts remaining this season. There's a
good chance he can win 20 games for the second time in the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what he says about wins and losses, the ERA, the
opponents' batting average and the ability to make the big pitch in
key situations indicate that it's not by accident.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
