<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BIGGIO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Biggio vows to be as good as ever
<TEXT>
<P>
   With torn knee ligaments, iron man faces major rehab for first
time
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ One day after his season had been literally torn apart,
Craig Biggio was trying to find a way to somehow put the pieces
back together and prepare for what most likely will be the biggest
challenge of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Rehabilitating a surgically repaired knee is no easy task for
anyone, let alone a 34-year-old player who never has had to go
through any sort of major rehab.
</P>
<P>
   But if you know anything about Biggio, you know nothing excites
him more than a challenge. He'll no doubt approach surgery and
rehab with the same attitude he approaches a 3-2 fastball: Bring it
on!
</P>
<P>
   ``Bidge has a young body,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell
said. ``Knowing how psycho he is about everything, you know he's
going to come back from this with flying colors. He's not going to
settle for coming back as an average player.''
</P>
<P>
   As a seven-time All-Star and three-time team Most Valuable
Player, Biggio is hardly average. For the better part of the last
13 years, he has been synonymous with Houston baseball, and an aura
of invincibility hovered above him like a guardian angel.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it seemed so surreal Wednesday to see him hobbling
around the visitors' clubhouse at Pro Player Stadium, supported by
a pair of crutches _ the result of torn anterior cruciate and
medial collateral ligaments in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   But as devastated as everyone, including Biggio, is by the
injury, the hard-nosed second baseman refuses to allow himself to
wallow in self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a lot better than I thought I would today,'' said
Biggio, who is on the disabled list for the first time in his
career. ``I really didn't know what to expect. This is new
territory for me. I guarantee you I'll know a lot more about the
knee in the next five months. This whole thing is frustrating and
annoying, but I'm not going to let it get me down. I can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to have a defeatist attitude about this. Sure,
I'd much rather have tendinitis than torn ligaments in my knee, but
there's not much I can do about that. It's going to take a lot of
work to get back to where I need to be, but I'm ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be the same player again; in fact, I'll be better. I'll
be stronger, and I'll be faster. I'm looking forward to the
challenge. I'll be ready. You have to be confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio's injury occurred in the seventh inning of Tuesday's game
when Marlins center fielder Preston Wilson slid into his left leg
while trying to break up a double play. Unfortunately for Biggio,
it came when he was playing his best baseball of the season.
</P>
<P>
   His final 2000 batting numbers will read as follows: .268, eight
homers and 35 RBIs. They're hardly the caliber of statistics you
would associate with Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't having his best season,'' Bagwell said. ``I'm sure
that makes it tougher. But he was starting to swing the bat well,
and I know he was going to come back over the second half and have
the kind of season we're all used to him having.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to see something like this happen to anyone,
especially Bidge. Obviously, this is a major blow to this club.
This organization has never been without Craig for the last 13
years. Still, you can't just throw in the towel.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just another in a long line of injuries for the Astros, who
have used the disabled list 12 times this season, including three
times _ for Biggio, Shane Reynolds and Mitch Meluskey _ in August.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio knows what it's like to play without Bagwell for extended
periods of time, considering Bagwell has had disabling injuries,
including a broken hand in three consecutive years. But Bagwell has
no idea what it's like to play with a second baseman other than
Biggio for more than a couple of days at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``People start to take guys for granted after a while,'' Bagwell
said. ``Once you watch what goes on without (Biggio), you're going
to realize how much Craig means to this club. He truly is a special
player. There aren't many people who can do what he does as a
second baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact Biggio played in 1,800 big-league games before he
suffered an injury serious enough to send him to the disabled list
is proof of his toughness. It also means he has played through
injuries that might have disabled others.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was the muscle tear in his shoulder last season, the
torn ligament in his ankle this season, or the aches and pains that
have been more prevalent in his back over the last few years,
Biggio always has managed to stay in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way I was raised,'' Biggio said of his
penchant for playing through injuries. ``You're going to have
things that hurt; you just deal with it. I love this game, and I
respect it. As long as I can go out there and I'm not hurting the
team, I want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his career, that's not possible.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
