<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1307 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-RDP-3RDLD-WRITETH     08-03 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RDP-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH-CHENEY TICKET NOMINATED AND THE ATTACKS ON GORE BEGIN
</HEADLINE>
  (CHANGES ``failed'' to ``misguided'' in 2nd graf;   ADDS grafs 6, 
 15 and 20 with color, background)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT32, NYT34, NYT35, NYT39, NYT42, NYT43, NYT44,
NYT45, NYT46, NYT47 and NYT48 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Burning to reclaim the White House after eight
years on the outside, the Republican Party nominated George Walker
Bush for president on Wednesday night and sent forth his running
mate with the most stinging and unabashedly partisan attack of the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, Bush's No. 2, asserted that the election of Al Gore
would perpetuate what he called the misguided policies of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all a little weary of the Clinton-Gore routine,''
Cheney declared. ``But the wheel has turned.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, appropriating Gore's slogan from the 1992 campaign as his
own, he said, ``It is time for them to go!''
</P>
<P>
   In the ritual roll call, the 22 votes from Cheney's home state
of Wyoming cast at 10:04 p.m. gave Bush more than the 1,034 votes
needed for the nomination. As Latin music blared, the hall erupted
in a prolonged ovation as jubilant delegates, many of them dancing,
were awash in a sea of beach balls, confetti, balloons and banners
that proclaimed, ``Bush-Cheney.'' Former President Bush and his
wife, Barbara, jumped to their feet to join in.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates, who had endured three nights of sunny, even
apolitical speeches, roared in delight as Cheney made full-throated
put-downs of the Democrats. But with Cheney's mild and even-toned
delivery, his well-crafted punch lines did not carry the same
weight on television.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a secretary of defense under President Bush before
becoming a business executive, said he was lured back into public
service because of his belief in George W. Bush and his fear that
Gore's election would perpetuate everything that he believed was
wrong with Clinton's stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a contrast with Bush's achievements as governor of
Texas, Cheney contended that the Clinton administration had made no
headway on Social Security, taxes or military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Casting aside the high-minded oratory that had marked this
convention until now, Cheney portrayed Gore as mean-spirited by
reviving former Sen. Bill Bradley's pungent dismissal of Gore just
six days before the crucial New Hampshire primary: ``A thousand
promises. A thousand attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's address capped Bush's night of triumph that had been
meticulously crafted for weeks, if not months. Even so, it was a
political and emotional peak for the two-term governor, former
baseball team owner and son of a former president who did not
rocket onto the public stage until he first won election as
governor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Just eight years ago, Republicans gathered in Houston to
nominate Bush's father for a second term _ only to have their
president ousted by Bill Clinton. But Wednesday night, after being
introduced by his wife, Lynne, Cheney stood before the 2,066
delegates and told them that the era of Clinton and Gore had been
one of dashed hopes and squandered opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney depicted Gore as intimately connected to an
administration that had been mired in scandal and was clearly
seeking to turn Gore's attacks on Bush's ``risky tax scheme'' back
against the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this election, they will speak endlessly of risk,'' Cheney
said. ``We will speak of progress. They will make accusations. We
will make proposals. They will feed fear. We will appeal to hope.
They will offer more lectures, and legalisms, and carefully worded
denials. We offer another way _ a better way _ and a stiff dose of
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's comments were his harshest thus far against the
Democrats, and left no doubt that despite his mild-mannered
demeanor, the Bush campaign intends to employ him in the somewhat
traditional role of running mate as attacker. In his acceptance
speech four years ago as Bob Dole's No. 2, Jack Kemp was far more
restrained; he mentioned Clinton only once, and his sharpest words
were casting Democrats as ``elitist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney picked up a mantle that has been carried in the past
by Bob Dole and Gore himself.
</P>
<P>
   The speech by the vice presidential nominee is usually delivered
on the final night of the convention _ and is usually overshadowed
by the one delivered by the head of the ticket. But by giving
Cheney his own night, the campaign was able to showcase Bush's
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   And though Bush had planned the break with tradition well before
Cheney was chosen, the move offered the public an opportunity to
take a measure of a man who has been out of the public eye since
leaving the Pentagon eight years ago after playing a key role in
the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's speech provided delegates with yet another reason to
revel in a quadrennial gathering that has been remarkably devoid of
controversy _ in public at least.
</P>
<P>
   After his defeat to Clinton, former President George Bush had
been shunned at many Republican events. But this week, delegates
expressed supreme confidence that his son was their best hope to
retake the White House.
</P>
<P>
   For the third night in a row, the former president sat through
the convention, logging more time there than many of the delegates.
At the very end of the night, he smiled and sang along as Lee
Greenwood appeared on stage to sing what had been Bush's campaign
anthem, ``I'm Proud to be an American.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night was clearly the most festive of the week on the
convention-hall floor, as delegates tossed beach balls amid blaring
Motown music. The one somber note on the otherwise exuberant mood
was many delegates' preoccupation with the health of former
President Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who had delighted party loyalists on Tuesday night when he
appeared on the floor as part of a tribute to past Republican
presidents, was admitted to a hospital here Wednesday after
suffering at least one minor strokes.
</P>
<P>
   As he delivered the invocation, Steve Young, the former
quarterback for the San Francisco 49ers, asked a special blessing
for Ford's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney had been Ford's chief of staff at the White House. From
there, he was elected as a congressman from Wyoming, rising to the
rank of Republican whip.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that Cheney's speech was the most hard-edged
of the convention, Bush's aides insisted that it did not violate
their pledge to keep the discourse from Philadelphia largely
high-minded and positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary's speech sets a new tone,'' said Ari Fleischer,
a spokesman for Bush. ``It draws contrasts with Vice President
Gore, but far more respectfully than typical politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said to expect some barbs aimed at Gore. Yet some
passages in the speech veered closely to the personal _ especially
those that linked Gore to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the man from Hope goes home to New York,'' Cheney said, ``
Gore tries to separate himself from his leader's shadow. But
somehow we will never see on without thinking of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he added, ``Does anyone, Republican or Democrat, seriously
believe that under Gore the next four years would be any different
from the last eight?''
</P>
<P>
   In the eight days since Bush named him as his running mate,
Cheney has found himself largely on the defensive, fighting off
attacks by Democrats that his voting record was too conservative
for most voters. They concentrated on his opposition to the Head
Start pre-school education program and his votes against a ban on
armor-piercing bullets.
</P>
<P>
   But in his speech Wednesday night, Cheney did not even allude to
the controversy _ or his own ideology _ and instead took the
opportunity to say glowing things about his former boss, then
President Bush, and about Bush's son.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Governor Bush, who arrived in Philadelphia Wednesday after a
six-day tour through six states carried by Clinton and Gore in 1992
and 1996, took to the sprawling stage at the convention hall
Wednesday afternoon to run through his acceptance address for
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing, perhaps, Bush's disdain of long-winded addresses _
and perhaps his own self-assuredness _ his aides said that his
acceptance speech might be the shortest in years.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, the campaign's communications director, said that
Bush speech had been completed and that _ allowing for applause
lines _ it would last roughly 38 minutes. In contrast, acceptance
speeches by his father in 1992 and Bob Dole in 1996 each ran 57
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the effort Wednesday night for Cheney to extoll Bush's
virtues, the program was intended as an opportunity for the party
to highlight its signature economic issue: tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But _ as throughout the convention _ the focus was on portraying
the party not as the party of plutocrats, as Democrats have long
sought to label it, but as a party of working people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax cuts matter to every American, especially the working
poor,'' Gov. James Gilmore of Virginia said in his prepared
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   To drive home the point, featured speakers included a Hispanic
small-business owner, Hector Barreto, who spoke of how Bush would
help entrepreneurs by reducing the burden of taxation and
regulation, and Kim Jennings, a single mother, who spoke about how
Bush's tax plan would help her edge toward the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials countered that the Republicans were trying
to distract attention from the fact that Bush's tax cut proposals
would disproportionately benefit the wealthy. And Gore's aides
pressed their case that both the Republican tax cuts passed this
year by Congress and those proposed by Bush would endanger the
nation's newfound fiscal health and the economy's long-term
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The very theme of the evening, ``prosperity with a purpose,''
contained a tacit acknowledgment that the economy is hearty, a fact
that could ultimately be expected to help Gore.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush arrived at the airport here Thursday morning, he was
greeted with a red-carpet welcome, replete with a fife and drum
corps and a replica of the Liberty Bell which he gonged. Then he
was off to the Philadelphia Museum of Art for what was billed as a
Hispanic welcome event. Latin music blared.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was introduced by his Hispanic-American nephew, George P.
Bush, who said, ``Are you excited about electing a president who
represents the diversity of our society?''
</P>
<P>
   The governor and his wife, Laura, then appeared along with Sen.
John McCain and his wife, Cindy. Bush praised his one time bitter
foe _ who offered a tribute to him at the convention on Tuesday _
as a ``living example of duty, honor and country.''
</P>
<P>
   The two couples then stood with a batch of Latino children who
sang what was called a ``Spanglish'' version of America the
Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, Bush was off to a Republican gala lunch that was
expected to raise $10 million for the party. A large, almost life
sized, backdrop of the White House viewed from the South Lawn was
beamed on the stage behind Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech on Thursday, Bush said, he would ``share with
America how proud I am and how much I love my parents.'' He told
the crowd, ``I want to thank you from the bottom of my heart. If
all goes well, if all goes well, you're looking at the next
president of the United States. God bless you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
