r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-TIGERS-LAD     08-03 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TIGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD HABITS DOOM ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ For a team in the midst of a pennant race, the
Y2K Angels on Wednesday looked more like last year's model, losing
5-3 to the Tigers in front of 29,017 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Angels are 13 games ahead of where they were in the
standings at this point last season. And, this year's model has
seen a marked increase in morale and heart compared to last year's
version.
</P>
<P>
   However, to reach the pinnacle of Major League Baseball, they
must avoid pitfalls such as dropping two out of three in a
late-season series to the mediocre Tigers, who improved to 50-56.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Ken Hill (5-7), who hasn't recorded a victory
since July 8, absorbed his third consecutive loss after allowing
seven hits and four earned runs in six innings. He struck out two
and walked three. Brian Moehler (7-7) earned the win for Detroit,
yielding just one run and six hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   An unusually sluggish offense, coupled with an erratic start
from Hill, sunk Anaheim, manager Mike Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get production from our whole lineup,'' he said.
``We didn't execute a couple of times fundamentally and that cost
us a chance to get a couple of early runs that would have changed
the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill's troubles began right away, when he walked Tigers leadoff
batter Damion Easley and gave up a 428-foot home run to Bobby
Higginson, staking the Tigers to a 2-0 lead before many in the
crowd had even taken their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Hill did his best to keep the Angels close, although he got
little help from the offense. The team had just four hits through
four innings and two of those belonged to Tim Salmon, who went 4
for 4 with two doubles and one RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly not counting on one guy to carry us,''
Scioscia said. ``We hope he can continue that kind of hitting into
the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Deivi Cruz led off the fifth inning with a single. He reached
third base when Hill made an errant throw to first on Shane
Halter's sacrifice bunt attempt, allowing Halter to advance to
second. Both runners scored when Easley followed with a single,
pushing Detroit ahead 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   A sacrifice fly by Dean Palmer, scoring Easley, capped Detroit's
three-run fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look around after so many innings and you don't think
Kenny Hill is pitching too badly,'' Scioscia said. ``But somehow
you're down 5-0. We have to tighten up in some areas and obviously
nothing's changed _ we need some starting pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence of the Angels' shortcomings in their starting
rotation was seen in the sixth inning, which started when Hill
struck Juan Encarnacion in the chest with an 88 mph fastball. He
did, however, manage to get out of the inning without further
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we battled back,'' Scioscia said. ``We had the tying
run at the plate in the ninth inning, which, when you're down 5-0,
that's about all you can really hope to do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
