<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLEY-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-WILLEY- COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MCCAIN FINDS IT HARD TO MIND HIS MANNERS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KEVEN WILLEY(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain put on a good face at the Republican
National Convention here this week and performed all the right acts
of support for the GOP presidential nominee, George W. Bush. He
defended Bush at Arianna Huffington's Shadow Convention, resisted
the temptation to bang the drum for campaign finance reform,
delivered a stirring endorsement of Bush as the convention's
prime-time speaker Tuesday and generally tried to do all the right
things at all the right times.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't been easy. And every now and then, like the Dennis
the Menace who just couldn't control his mischief, McCain let slip
glimpses of the struggle behind the facade.
</P>
<P>
   McCain noted on a Phoenix radio station last week that he
planned to leave the convention midweek so as not to be a
``distraction'' at Bush's party. This left even some of Arizona's
convention delegates, among the most loyal McCain supporters in the
country, wondering if McCain's ego hadn't gotten the better of him
and worrying whether the move would detract from the party's effort
to show full-scale unification behind Bush as the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   McCain hauled out the ``Straight Talk Express'' and conducted a
highly publicized (not to mention ``distracting'') bus trek from
Arlington, Va., to Philadelphia reminiscent of Jesse Jackson's
infamously distracting airport landing at the start of the 1988
Democratic convention in Atlanta. Bush and Michael Dukakis have
little in common except perhaps for the convention heartburn caused
each by their vanquished primary opponents.
</P>
<P>
   While chatting it up with rotating clusters of national
reporters on the Straight Talk Express, McCain couldn't resist
speculating about his own national political future, at one point
going so far as to suggest, that, yes, he might be interested in
running again in 2004. The unspoken assumption in that
extemporaneous meander, of course, is that Bush loses this fall so
as to deprive the GOP of an incumbent seeking re-election in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The first private dinner McCain hosted upon arriving in
Philadelphia wasn't for his dedicated delegates or donors - or even
for anybody remotely connected to Bush - but rather for the
often-fawning national press, including such Big Feet as Dan
Rather, Tim Russert and R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's wife, Cindy, however, was by most accounts nearly
flawless in her demonstration of support for Bush. When a leader of
the Connecticut delegation fought his way over to the Arizona
seating area minutes before the start of the roll-call vote Monday
night to ask Cindy McCain to personally persuade his state's lone
McCain holdout to convert to Bush so the state could go unanimously
for Bush, Cindy McCain was prepared to accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   Time was simply too short, however, and she couldn't make it
across the hot and crowded convention floor prior to the start of
the roll-call, which featured Arizona, alphabetically, near the
front of the tally. Cindy McCain made sure in her nationally
televised roll-call statement to note that Arizona
``enthusiastically and unanimously'' cast its 30 votes for Bush.
Minutes later, a unanimous Connecticut delegation followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, John McCain's support for Bush from the
convention podium was unqualified. The loudest applause came when
McCain noted somberly of Bush: ``I support him. I am grateful to
him. And I am proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   And McCain has let it be known that he plans to stump for Bush
in California later this month and again next month elsewhere in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the starched suit of a supporter will feel more
comfortable by then. But this week, to McCain, it seemed to still
feel a bit stiff.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Willey at keven.willey(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8499.
</P>
