A1326 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-APPLE-LAWSUIT &LR;      08-03 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-LAWSUIT </SLUG>
  
 APPLE SUES OVER WEB POSTINGS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; Opening a new front in its a continuing &LR; 
 &LR; battle to prevent leaks about its future products, Apple Computer
filed suit Wednesday against as many as 25 individuals it accuses
of disclosing its trade secrets on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed with the state Superior Court in Santa Clara,
alleges that someone, so far identified only as ``Doe 1,'' acting
alone or in concert with up to 24 other ``Does,'' began posting
information about unannounced Apple products around February of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the complaint charges, the defendants posted
digital images of a dual-processor Mac G4 on February 16. The
company did not announce that product until July 19. Likewise, the
defendants are alleged to have posted on June 22 a picture of
Apple's new optical mouse, which was also announced in July. .
</P>
<P>
   The suit does not specify where the images were posted, but
MacNN, a Web site dedicated to Mac news, reported yesterday that
the Cupertino computer-maker had issued a subpoena to Yahoo asking
the popular online site to identify the Internet address of a user
who created a site on its Geocities section, where the images were
allegedly posted.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo officials refused to confirm or deny receipt of an Apple
subpoena. Apple also declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   G. Gervaise Davis, an attorney at Davis &AMP; Schroeder in Monterey
who also teaches a course on intellectual-property litigation at
the University of California at Santa Clara's law school, said it
is common for companies to file suits against John Does when they
don't know the identity of individuals involved, especially in
cases involving the Internet. Once such a suit is filed, the
plaintiff can take discovery or issue subpoenas compelling Internet
service providers or Web hosting companies to reveal information
about the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 42 years in this field, that's the only way I know of to
do it'' in such circumstances, Davis said. ``Under federal
procedures and in most states, there's no alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   The Apple brief cites two ways the company suffers when
information about new products leaks prior to a formal
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   First, it says, ``In Apple's experience, public knowledge of
future products often lessens sales of existing Apple products.''
Second, the brief says, advance knowledge of Apple innovations lets
competitors direct their own product development and marketing to
counter the company's plans.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks a permanent injunction restraining the defendants
from further misappropriation of information about Apple's future
products as well as unspecified compensatory and ``exemplary''
damages.
</P>
<P>
   The suit apparently represents a new tactic for Apple. Since
co-founder and CEO Steve Jobs regained control of the company in
1997, it has taken aggressive steps, detailed in yesterday's
filing, to prevent the leaks about its products.
</P>
<P>
   But when leaks have occurred, Apple has until now relied on
legal threats against the sites publishing the information, rather
than going after the leakers themselves. Last month, for example, a
popular Web site called MacInTouch.com published a note from a
reader describing products to be announced at July's Macworld Expo
trade show. Apple attorneys e-mailed the site's publisher and its
Internet service provider, demanding that he ``cease and desist
from disseminating the material'' in question. The site complied
with the demand, saying it wanted to avoid further legal costs, but
posted a strong response from its own attorney challenging Apple's
legal arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the law doesn't give ``commercial speech'' the same
strong protections afforded to political or expressive speech, the
courts are traditionally cautious about efforts to restrain
publication of leaked material, according to intellectual-property
expert Davis.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry norr at hnorr(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
