   &UR; CIRCUITS (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-SELLERS (Undated) _ Online sellers using auction
sites like eBay are even more vulnerable to fraud than online
buyers, experts say. Those who buy faulty or fake goods through
online auctions or Web shops have some recourse; insurance programs
and credit-card companies will often come to their rescue and
credit their accounts, at least up to a certain amount. But
individuals who are selling goods in online auctions have little
protection. Stolen credit cards, fake money orders and bounced
checks are risks they face. For them, the adage is turned on its
head: Seller beware. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-VOICE-PORTALS (Undated) _ As manufacturers of wireless
phones, handheld computers and other Internet gadgets scramble to
make Web information accessible without the need to boot up a
computer, some companies have a different plan. They are adapting
the Web to the one device that virtually everyone has: the
telephone. And they don't mean one of those Web phones that connect
you to e-mail and stock quotes after you set up a special
wireless-service account and scroll through a series of menus and
buttons. All you need is a telephone, even an old-fashioned rotary
dial phone. These voice portals _ like Tellme, BeVocal and
Quack.com _ let you pick up a phone and let your voice do the
surfing. By Catherine Greenman.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The column: It's never easy
living as a Mac user in a Windows world, but it is a lot easier
than it used to be. Microsoft, maker of Windows, was once thought
to be Apple's greatest enemy. But then things got better. Instead
of trying to squash the Mac, Microsoft has actually spun off a unit
to create Mac software from the ground up, instead of merely
recycling old Windows code into Mac versions of its programs. A
guest column by J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GEEK-NOTES (Undated) _ Techno news and notes: CD-rewritables
get faster; voice-activated browsing; reducing emails to their bare
essentials; turning cars into advertisements; the Claudia Schiffer
palm.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING (Undated) _ The column: Forget the outlet
mall. These days, the best place to shop for old-fashioned,
outlet-quality blemished bargains is online. By Michelle Slatalla.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Techno questions answered: Getting photos
onto eBay; erasing a hard drive. By J.D. Biersdorfer.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GOP-CONVENTION (Undated) _ Visiting ``Internet Alley'' at
the Republican National Convention, where dot-coms are showing
their wares and talking about shaking up politics. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-SITE-REDESIGN (Undated) _ When Salon.com revamped its Web
site in May, readers greeted it with hundreds of e-mail complaints.
They criticized the horizontal scrolling, the small type and the
headlines that no longer linked directly to articles. Within days,
Salon's editor, David Talbot, posted a note to readers saying,
``You win!'' and the site reverted to some of its old design. The
Salon revolt speaks volumes about the growing impatience that Web
users are having with constant face lifts of their favorite sites
or with sites that are difficult to navigate. Site redesigns and
changes. By Jeffrey Selingo.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-DUES-GAME (Undated) _ Deus Ex, the game. By Peter Olafson.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-LYRIC-GENERATORS (Undated) _ The best current lyrics
generators. By Ed Boland Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-HUMAN-POWER (Undated) _ Human-powered radios, lanterns and
other gadgets. By Christine Kenneally.
