<P>
   BILLY-JOEL-YACHT (Undated) _ Long before stepping into the
recording studio and racking up gold records, Billy Joel began his
nautical career by swimming out to other people's moorings off the
North Shore and ``borrowing'' their boats. He has owned many since
and now also lures other millionaires into the boater's morass with
a high-end speedboat he helped design. By Stephen P. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-COMPOSER (New York) _ Sitting in his 5.1 Surround format
sound studio installed in his newly renovated apartment on Hudson
Street, Carter Burwell, a film composer, was talking about romantic
comedy. ``I find it the most difficult thing,'' Burwell, 44, said.
``People on screen are happy _ the music is happy. People are sad _
the music is sad. I prefer a more ironic approach. If people are
being killed on screen, then I can be carefree,'' he said, speaking
musically. Burwell's latest deadline is ``Blair Witch 2,'' to be
released on Halloween. The scrupulously spare 3,000 square foot
loft that Burwell shares with his wife, Christine Sciulli, a
lighting designer and video artist is a creative contradiction in
terms: it conceals over five miles of analog and digital audio,
video and Ethernet cable and eleven electronic patch boxes that
allow Burwell to compose in the peace of his own apartment _
anywhere from his studio to the bathroom tub. By William L.
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   SOFITEL-ARCHITECT (New York) _ The new Sofitel hotel, between
Fifth Avenue and Avenue of the Americas, is a coltish performance
by its architect, more promising than accomplished, of interest
mainly on account of where it might lead Yann Leroy in the future
and where it sits in relationship to his bad-boy past. By Herbert
Muschamp.
</P>
