<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1331 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-DAVIS-DONOR-SFCHRON &LR;      08-03 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-DONOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIG DONOR TO DAVIS GOT EXEMPTION FROM NEW EMPLOYEE OVERTIME LAW  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ After hosting a fund-raiser that netted $76,000 for
Gov. Gray Davis, a ski industry group won a break it sought on
paying overtime to resort employees from a Davis-appointed
commission.
</P>
<P>
   This is the latest in a series of incidents in which actions of
the Davis administration appear to be linked to contributions
received by the Democratic governor.
</P>
<P>
   Both Davis and the California Ski Industry Association, a San
Francisco group, deny any connection between the fund-raiser and
overtime exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly this group makes a substantial contribution and then
gets a favorable policy product from the governor. It's
distressing, but not surprising,'' said Craig Holman, project
director of the Center for Government Studies in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At $76,000, the ski industry association was the 11th-largest
contributor to Davis during the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it made no contributions to the Democratic governor _
only three contributions of $900, $1,00 and $500 to lawmakers,
according to StateNet, a contribution tracking service.
</P>
<P>
   The money was generated by a fund-raiser this spring held near
the Sacramento airport at which members of the association were
asked to contribute to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The most important issue for the group at the time was being
granted an exemption from the Davis administration on the state's
law that workers be paid time and a half for every hour beyond
eight hours in a day or 40 hours in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group made that known to Davis at the
fund-raiser, sources said, during a briefing for the governor about
how the ski industry operates.
</P>
<P>
   About 16,000 people are employed by the 34 resorts represented
by the association. Of those, 14,500 are seasonal employees.
</P>
<P>
   Having to follow the overtime law would cost the resorts
represented by the association $100 million, Bob Roberts, the
association's executive director, told the state's Industrial
Welfare Commission at a May 7 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   With a 5 percent profit margin and $300 million in annual sales,
being subject to the overtime rules ``basically takes out the
profitability of the industry,'' Roberts testified.
</P>
<P>
   The Industrial Welfare Commission, whose members are appointed
by Davis, has the power to grant exemptions to the state's overtime
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Before Davis took office, the ski industry enjoyed an exemption
from paying any daily overtime. Employees did not receive overtime
unless they worked 56 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   That exemption expired last year, and without some accommodation
the resorts would have been subject to the overtime laws governing
most other industries starting July 1 of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Working with members of the governor's staff, the ski group
offered a compromise to the commission:
</P>
<P>
   During the ski season, employees would receive overtime only
after 48 hours a week or 10 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise was offered by Bill Dombrowski, chairman of the
five-member commission, and it was approved on a 3-to-2 vote at a
June 30 meeting of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see the rationale,'' said Barry Broad, a Sacramento
labor lobbyist and one of two commissioners who voted against the
special treatment for ski resorts. ``Canneries and other seasonal
industries have 40 hour work weeks and overtime after eight
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski was traveling outside the state Wednesday and was
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Garry South, the governor's top political consultant, said Davis
favored the exemption long before the fund-raiser. ``To suggest
such a cause-and-effect connection between a ski association event
and action by the commission completely misunderstands the
governor's position, which certainly has not been formed since
March,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, the ski association director, was traveling in Europe
and could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephanie Neff, deputy director of the ski association, said
there was no connection between the fund-raiser and the actions of
the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked with everybody to try and find a compromise that was
fair but allowed for flexibility for employees and employers,' Neff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' voracious fund-raising _ he has amassed $21.4 million
since he became governor _ has led to repeated criticism that
special interests groups who contribute to him, get his ear.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than a year ago, Davis attended a fund-raiser in
Los Angeles sponsored by some of the state's largest health
maintenance organizations. Press reports said he raised at least
$125,000.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Davis called key lawmakers to his office
asking them to slow the progress of bills pending in the
Legislature that stiffened regulation of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before the HMO fund-raiser, Davis attended a
reception hosted by Sierra Pacific Industries that included key
timber industry executives.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting coincided with the release by the state Board of
Forestry of draft regulations governing logging practices on
private lands.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations have been criticized by environmentalists as too
generous to timber companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Gov. Davis has placed a higher priority on
fund-raising than any of his predecessors,'' said Jim Knox,
director of California Common Cause. ``What he's doing is
collecting huge IOUs to wealthy interest groups that have a huge
stake in state politics.''
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign for governor, Davis pledged to restore
overtime pay after an eight-hour workday, which had been eliminated
by his GOP predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Davis signed a bill to do so but has used the
commission to grant exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Davis pushed an exemption for some hourly paid
employees who receive stock options. The commission never acted on
the proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
