<SLUG> BC-POWER-SUPPLY-LADN </SLUG>
 
AS OTHER CITIES SWEAT, L.A. MAKES COOL CASH &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With state officials in an uproar over soaring
energy prices and low supplies, the L.A. Department of Water and
Power boasted that it made a $35 million windfall profit last month
selling its surplus electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Long criticized for overbuilding power plants and locking in
fuel supplies at high prices in the 1970s oil crisis, the DWP now
is virtually alone in its energy prosperity in a region facing
doubling of electricity rates and threats of rolling blackouts due
to a heat wave that has sent demand soaring throughout the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles did not go the deregulation route and we're in
great shape,'' said DWP manager S. David Freeman said Wednesday.
``We're not asking people to turn off their power on the hottest
day of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the DWP still controls more than 7,000 megawatts
of generating capacity, and the city rarely uses more than 5,000.
On Wednesday, the city-owned utility reached a peak demand of 4,900
megawatts while selling 1,000 at a floating rate that sometimes
hits a ceiling of $500 per megawatt.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the DWP made about $35 million selling electricity to
the statewide power manager, the California Independent System
Operator, compared with about $20 million the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was far different in much of the rest of the state
as the ISO declared its third straight Stage Two emergency, cutting
power temporarily to some residential air conditioners and
industrial customers in exchange for discounted electric rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can recall any periods when we've had as
narrow an operating margin as we've had this summer,'' said Ron
Nunnally, Southern California Edison's director of federal
regulations and contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But Nunnally remembered a time when Edison owned and controlled
all of its own power plants. Now it must sell what it does produce
from its remaining hydroelectric and nuclear plants and buy more
power on the commercial market each day.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of calling the first Stage Three alert that would
force rolling blackouts across much of the state remained high as
forecasters predict little relief from the hot weather until this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, customers in San Diego have seen their
electric bills double and stepped-up conservation efforts are being
pushed in areas served by Edison and other utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The power crisis sent off shock waves in Sacramento, where Gov.
Gray Davis issued a series of executive orders, raising questions
about possible price-fixing and questioning the state's decision
four years ago to lead the nation in deregulating utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Bill Lockyer immediately began an
investigation, while others blamed deregulation as the cause of the
short power supplies and rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   Under state-mandated power deregulation, which exempts public
suppliers like the DWP and Burbank and Glendale power authorities,
utilities were forced to sell off generating capacity and instead
buy power from a nonprofit Power Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other utilities are relying on the marketplace and the
suppliers are cleaning up because there's a shortage,'' Freeman
said. ``Right now, we're the island where the light is shining
bright in the valley of despair.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern California Edison, which services the metropolitan area
outside Los Angeles' city limits, including the city of San
Fernando, is grappling with high prices in the face of a rate
freeze that doesn't end until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   While residential customers pay about 5.9 cents per kilowatt
hour for electricity, the Power Exchange rates for power have
averaged about 16 cents per kilowatt hour for the past five weeks,
said Akbar Jazayeri, Edison's manager of pricing and tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   The freeze is a result of Edison being in an earlier phase of
deregulation than San Diego Gas &AMP; Electric, whose customers have
been blindsided with rates as high as 50 cents per kilowatt hour.
</P>
<P>
   Without the freeze, the average Edison customer, who pays about
$58 a month, would now be paying about $110.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the power shortage goes back to the beginnings of
deregulation, Nunnally said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people who were hesitant to invest in new
generation until they could see what the new rules were going to
be,'' he said. Now, however, there are 26 California plants in some
phase of development, ``so in the next couple years we will work
our way out of that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
