<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDER NOW, CONVENTION ENDS SOON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ It's not exactly a convention they're throwing
in Philadelphia, because at an actual political convention, things
happen.
<P>
   Reader Tyler Hollingsworth is getting close when he identifies
the group activity in progress as an infomercial.
</P>
<P>
   Let's call it the Republican National Infovention.
</P>
<P>
   People are grinning and laughing, people are giddy about the
product, people all agree that the product is a miracle, people are
endorsing the product with every fiber of their straw hats.
</P>
<P>
   Happy-person testimonial: ``You know, I used to vote Democratic.
I was constipated, I had no energy, my social conscience was always
dragging me down, I was constantly broke because I was giving away
my hard-earned inheritance to deadbeats, drunks and orphaned
lepers. But now, gosh!''
</P>
<P>
   And if you call within the next 10 minutes, we'll throw in a
curly-fry maker and John McCain, who weighs only ounces and folds
up conveniently to store under your platform!
</P>
<P>
   MEANWHILE, it's wonderful that the Republicans are so unified,
except shouldn't it raise some flags of alarm  &LR; that all these very
political people from various disparate corners of conservative
political thought all agree completely on
 &UR; everything? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that if all the delegates were to disappear,
they could be replaced by 20,000 of those novelty mounted fish that
wag their plastic tail fins and sing, ``Don't Worry, Be Happy.''
</P>
<P>
   THIS SPACE may be blank.
</P>
<P>
   If it is, do not be alarmed. The Bay Area heat wave has brought
threats of rolling blackouts and necessitated some energy-saving
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving this space white will save printing-press energy and
ease widespread reader strain caused by trying to figure out what
it is I'm trying to say.
</P>
<P>
   The plush Dinah's Garden Hotel in Palo Alto got a call yesterday
from the power people, saying, ``We expect a rolling blackout late
this afternoon. ... You are in Sector 14.''
</P>
<P>
   It's good to know your sector, comrades. If nothing else, it
gives you a couple of more ice-breaking questions for the singles
bar: ``What's your sector?'' and ``Lose your power often?''
</P>
<P>
   IN A PINCH, we've got the barge.
</P>
<P>
   Up from Brazil is steaming the Rio de la Luz (River of Light), a
monstrous generator-on-a-barge that can light up 55,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   I just hope they don't park the barge anywhere near where I
live. When it's cranked up, it probably sounds like a leaf blower
the size of an oil tanker.
</P>
<P>
   I do worry that if we use the Rio de la Luz, which runs on jet
fuel, the barge pilot will ask us all to kick in some gas money.
I'm pretty sure I saw on the side of the barge one of those
hippie-days bumper stickers that warn hitchhikers that they are
expected to contribute to the cause: ``Gas, (sex) or grass _ Nobody
rides for free.''
</P>
<P>
   TIGER WOODS, when he played (and won) the U.S. Open at Pebble
Beach recently, wanted to stay at the same hotel where he stayed on
his previous trip.
</P>
<P>
   But the entire hotel was booked by Bank of America execs. So
Tiger's manager (my sources say) asked the B of A people if they
might spare a room for Tiger, which he would gladly pay for.
</P>
<P>
   The bank people didn't say no and didn't say yes, but did ask if
Tiger would agree to give a little speech to their group. What the
hell, he had nothing better to do that week.
</P>
<P>
   The ``negotiations'' dragged on for about two weeks. Any other
group would have jumped like a tiger at the honor of sharing
quarters with the world's hottest athlete. Apparently the B of A
people saw it the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger stayed at The Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   TRIHACK THE cabbie had a lawyer from the Organized Crime
Division of the Justice Dept. in his cab.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' the mob-buster told Trihack, ``whenever I
mention my line of work to San Francisco cab drivers, they all
start talking about the same two things _ the Russian Mafia and
Willie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT TO repeat myself again and again, but it's clear that
readers are avid collectors of redundancies.
</P>
<P>
   Some are worth repeating again: Hot-water heater (several
readers) ... Close personal friend (Anon) ... NIT (National
Invitational Tournament) and Giants win  &UR; by a score of  &LR; 10 to 3
(Dan Engler) ... Forever and ever (Don Novello, who says, ``Forever
kinda covers it, don't you think?'') ... An all-new episode of your
favorite TV show. Why no partially new episodes? (Mark Frankel) ...
Offsides, before the snap (Al Markel) ... Sitting on your rear end
(Dick Vartanian).
</P>
<P>
   MORE POWER to carry us through energy crunches caused by heat
waves, that's what we need. What to do?
</P>
<P>
   Why not round up all the city's rats and put 'em on a million
hamster wheels wired to storage batteries?
</P>
<P>
   UNCLEAR ON the laws of physics:
</P>
<P>
   Joanna Beck saw an Infiniti in the parking lot of Marin Joe's.
It was a fancy model, so designated by the stamped-chrome word
``Limited.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What would Einstein have to say about this?'' Beck wonders.
</P>
</TEXT>
