<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHENEY LAUNCHES ASSAULT ON CLINTON-GORE ADMINISTRATION  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Leading a partisan attack that shattered the
Republican National Convention's air of congeniality, newly
nominated vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney launched a
full-fledged assault on the Clinton-Gore administration Wednesday
night, declaring: ``It is time for them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in together,'' Cheney said. ``Now let us see them
off together.''
</P>
<P>
   The sharp words, which came immediately after the party formally
selected Texas Gov. George W. Bush as its presidential nominee,
punctured the polite tone of the convention's previous two nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all a little weary of the Clinton-Gore routine,'' said
Cheney, who served as President Bush's secretary of Defense after
11 years in the House of Representatives. ``But the wheel has
turned. And it is time. It is time for them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican faithful gathered in Philadelphia's First Union
Center, who had sat patiently through hours of cordial speeches,
erupted in wild cheers, chanting: ``Time to go. Time to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The barb, which Cheney repeated several times, was a play on
Gore's acceptance speech at the Democratic convention in 1992 that
had been aimed at Bush's father. It climaxed a day in which the
delegates were abuzz about an escalating war of words between the
Bush family and President Clinton, who had belittled their son's
credentials to be president.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush said on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' that she
doubted Gore could return honor to the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very difficult, I think, with some of the things
he's done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, former President Bush responded to Clinton's
derisive comments, saying: ``If he continues that, then I'm going
to tell the nation what I think about him as a human being and a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Republicans had said their convention would remain
upbeat, and that Cheney would not take on the traditional role of
attack-dog on the campaign trail, he delivered the convention's
most scathing rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the administration of ethical lapses, depleting the
military, failing schoolchildren and offering up ``lectures,
legalisms, and carefully worded denials.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he said of Bush: ``On the first hour of the first
day, he will restore decency and integrity to the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he made it clear that Republicans will
campaign against Gore as Clinton's political twin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gore will try to separate himself from his leader's
shadow,'' he said. ``But somehow, we will never see one without
thinking of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who arrived in Philadelphia earlier in the day, will
address the delegates in a prime-time speech this evening.
</P>
<P>
   It was delegates from Cheney's home state of Wyoming who put
Bush over the top at 7:03 PST in an action carefully scripted to
coincide with network coverage of the convention. Though Bush's
nomination had been assured since he won the California primary on
March 7, the delegates erupted in cheers, and confetti streamed
from the ceiling of the basketball arena.
</P>
<P>
   The third night of the Republican convention began with a
invocation by former 49ers quarterback Steve Young, whose solemn
prayer was preceded by a yelp from an adoring female fan.
</P>
<P>
   Young was followed by World Wrestling Foundation star ``the
Rock,'' known for his skimpy attire and violent wrestling moves. In
a testament to the GOP's effort to expand his voting base, ``the
Rock,'' aka Dwayne Johnson _ who boasted that he has 16 million
loyal fans _ was then given a seat of honor in front of former
President Bush in the same row where ex-President Gerald Ford had
been the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Ford remained in a hospital a few miles away after suffering two
small strokes. His doctor said Ford, 87, appeared to have suffered
no brain damage or permanent disability, and chances for a full
recovery were good. Convention speakers throughout the night asked
for prayers and extended best wishes to Ford and his wife, Betty.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was buoyant as he arrived at a Philadelphia airport after a
six-day campaign swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all goes well, you're looking at the next president of the
United States,'' he told the crowd that greeted him and his wife
Laura.
</P>
<P>
   Americans ``don't want four more years of Clinton-Gore,'' Bush
said in a series of fast-paced appearances. ``They want somebody to
appeal to our better angels, not our darker impulses.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing before a Latino audience, he blended English and
Spanish in brief remarks, concluding, ``Y juntos podremos ganar en
Noviembre (And together we can win in November.)''
</P>
<P>
   He also spoke to a luncheon attended by more than 3,300 donors
that was expected to raise $10 million. He then made a brief visit
to the First Union Arena and went to the podium where he will
deliver his own acceptance speech tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans, I accept your nomination,'' he said in a
sound check to an empty hall.
</P>
<P>
   But the evening's most anticipated moment came when Cheney, once
President Ford's chief of staff, was reintroduced the delegates as
the No. 2 man on their ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney attempted to make the case that Republicans would restore
decency to the White House and appeal to Americans' best values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see in our nominee the qualities of mind and spirit our
nation needs,'' Cheney said. ``You will never see him pointing the
finger of blame for failure... You will only see him sharing credit
for success.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Gore's political rival, Sen. Bill Bradley,
characterized the vice president's campaign as ``a thousand
promises, a thousand attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this election, they will speak endlessly of risk,'' Cheney
said of the Democrats. ``We will speak of progress. They will feed
fear. We will appeal to hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton vowed not long ago to hold onto power until the
last hour of the last day,'' Cheney said. ``My friends, that last
hour is coming. That last day is near.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bush characterized by Democrats as challenged as &LR; 
 &LR; inexperienced in foreign policy and national leadership, Cheney
sought to underscore the governor's credentials while saying he
himself has been ``in the company of leaders,'' serving under
presidents Reagan, Ford and Bush. And he attempted to reassure
Republicans that his running mate was their equal in stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am glad to be back in the arena,'' he said. ``I have been
given an opportunity to serve beside a man who has the courage, and
the vision, and the goodness, to be a great president.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he had considered retiring to a life of ``fishing
and grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``to serve with this man, in this cause,'' he concluded,
``is a chance I would not miss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
