<SLUG> BC-RIORDAN-RNC-LADN </SLUG>
 
L.A. MAYOR ADDRESSES CONVENTION DELEGATES &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ORITH GOLDBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In an impassioned speech made to delegates at the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, Los Angeles Mayor
Richard Riordan called on the community to reach out and make a
difference in the lives of children.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan urged all listening to get involved with their
communities and attempt to cultivate a better environment in which
children can be nurtured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I implore every American to join the giving revolution in the
spirit of Hillel, who asked the questions, `If not now, when? If
not me, who?' The when is right now,'' he said. ``The who is each
and every one of us. Our children are waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   While some called Riordan's Wednesday-night address a
no-nonsense speech hitting the key points of the Bush campaign --
the need for education reform and community involvement at all
levels -- one California delegate said Riordan hasn't committed
himself enough to the education of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave a speech on education but has not taken a public
position in support of the Opportunity Scholarship Initiative,''
said Los Angeles County Supervisor Michael Antonovich from the
convention. ``If we want to reform education, we can't give $1
million for the Democratic campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's address via satellite, from the Simon Wiesenthal
Museum of Tolerance, earned him no congratulations from Antonovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inappropriate to use the Museum of Tolerance for
a political speech,'' Antonovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Others at the convention, however, praised the content and
delivery of the speech and said Riordan was at his peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spoke from the heart and made some excellent points,'' said
Thomas Kranz, a state delegate who serves on the Board of Civil
Service Commission for the city of Los Angeles. ``It was very well
received.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
