<HEADER>
A1338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-STAB-ARREST-1STLD-     08-03 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STAB-ARREST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED WITH FATALLY STABBING STUDENT IN BROOKLYN IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) 
(ATTN: Kan.)   (Editors: Antoinne, in 3rd graf, is cq.) 
By SHAILA K. DEWAN and WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a murder case that drew national attention but
seemed to be growing colder by the month, the police on Wednesday
charged a man with fatally stabbing Amy Watkins, a young graduate
student from Kansas, on a Brooklyn street a year and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   The man, David Jamison, 27, admitted to his role in the killing
in a videotaped statement, a senior law enforcement official said.
Jamison had a record of more than half a dozen arrests, mostly for
petty crimes and drugs and once for robbery, the police said. He
was arrested Wednesday morning at his home in the Park Slope
section of Brooklyn, mere blocks from where the stabbing took
place, and was later charged with first-degree murder, first-degree
robbery and possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Two other men, Pierre Antoinne, 26, an unemployed house painter,
and Felix Rodriguez, 21, a warehouse worker, were being questioned
by the police, relatives of the men said Wednesday. In his
statement, Jamison said that the two men were present during the
robbery and killing, law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After the stabbing, on March 9, 1999, the police were left with
a highly publicized crime and few clues. There were no known
witnesses, and the killer had been careful to obscure any
fingerprints by wrapping the murder weapon, a six-inch kitchen
knife, in a white plastic bag before using it.
</P>
<P>
   More than six months after Watkins, who had moved to New York
from Kansas to attend the Hunter College Graduate School of Social
Work, was robbed and killed, investigators reported that despite
thousands of hours of work, their leads had dwindled to zero. Their
only hope was that the killer would turn himself in, commit another
crime in front of witnesses or tell someone about the stabbing. A
$10,000 reward went unclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   The police said hundreds of people had been questioned since the
killing, but Jamison's name had never come up. At various times,
the police theorized that the crime was committed by a homeless man
or a boyfriend of Watkins, according to a senior investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, detectives got a break, an investigator said Wednesday:
in recent days, Jamison talked about the case, and word got back to
detectives through an informant in another part of the city and a
tip to the police Crime Stoppers hot line.
</P>
<P>
   News of Jamison's arrest came as a surprise to Watkins' friends
and family, many of whom said they had given up hope that the
killer would be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if it had all happened again,'' said Lawrence
Watkins, her father, a history teacher at the Dominican Academy in
Manhattan. ``What I'm feeling right now is that old wounds are
being reopened.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Green, Watkins' boyfriend at the time of her death, said he
had moved out of the neighborhood where she was killed. He said he
had thought that the police would never find a suspect. ``A good
part of me hoped it would stay that way,'' he said. ``I was not in
need of a name and a face, because that wasn't going to change
anything for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, who was 26 when she was killed, grew up in Topeka,
Kan., and enrolled at the University of Kansas to become a painter.
But a year and a half into college, she switched her major from art
to social work.
</P>
<P>
   In its brutality and apparent randomness, her killing was the
kind of homicide that had become an increasing rarity in New York
City, with crime declining. For that reason, it drew national
attention and tabloid headlines. Watkins' dedication to helping
others, particularly women who were victims of violence, and the
shock that the killing sent through the gentrified area near
Prospect Park made the story even more compelling.
</P>
<P>
   On that cold March night, Watkins, described by one classmate as
``a soldier of social work,'' was on her way home from the Bronx
Community Center where she worked with battered women. Residents on
the quiet street heard two screams, and found her less than two
blocks from her apartment with a knife in her back, surrounded by
fallen groceries. Her purse was later found nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The police said their initial suspicion, that the motive was
robbery, was borne out Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jamison's statement, investigators said, he and the
two other men were in a neighborhood luncheonette when they saw
Watkins walk by and decided that she would be ``an easy mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamison approached Watkins from behind while, investigators
believe, the two other men were in front of her. After Jamison
stabbed her, the three fled in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison apparently claimed to police that the stabbing was
unintentional. ``He's got some story that she moved backwards onto
the knife,'' a senior investigator said, ``which is inconsistent
wit the wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie West, the sister of Pierre Antoinne, said the police told
her that they believed that Antoinne and Rodriguez were present
when Jamison is alleged to have killed Watkins.
</P>
<P>
   But West and two other relatives of the suspects who were
waiting in the lobby of a police station house Wednesday night said
the men had nothing to do with the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Corea, 25, Jamison's sister-in-law and Rodriguez's
sister, acknowledged that Jamison had been in trouble with the law
_ he has prior arrests for robbery, petty larceny and drug dealing
_ but she said he was not violent.
</P>
<P>
   West said her brother was not capable of murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an idiot and a moron, but he wouldn't be able to do
that,'' she said. ``If you knew my brother, he's a real coward. He
doesn't have the heart to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said Rodriguez was cooperating with investigators,
but Antoinne was not. Antoinne, a Haitian citizen, began serving a
state prison term for an attempted drug sale in 1995. On Jan. 25,
1996, state records indicate, he was paroled to the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service. A police investigator said
Antoinne might have been deported to Haiti under a special program
and then returned, illegally, to the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
