<HEADER>
A1340 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ENERGY-A15STAR &LR;      08-03 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-A1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR ORDERS FAST TRACK ORDERED FOR STATE
POWER  PLANTS
</HEADLINE>
 5STAR   &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a threat of blackouts continued, Gov. Gray Davis Wednesday
ordered California officials to speed approval of new power plants
and created a top-level state energy panel to advise him and
coordinate actions by state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also called on Attorney General Bill Lockyer to
investigate ``possible manipulation in the wholesale electricity
marketplace'' in response to a doubling of average electricity
bills in San Diego, the first city to face the full effects of
state energy deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Davis termed the impact of deregulation ``an
unacceptable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   His new advisory panel, modeled after the National Security
Council, will consist of six top officials from state agencies with
expertise in energy matters.
</P>
<P>
   They include the chairmen of the state Energy Commission, Public
Utilities Commission and Electricity Oversight Board and the heads
of the state Resources Agency, the Environmental Protection Agency
and the governor's Office of Planning and Review.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for Davis, the panel will be up and
running within two weeks and will be charged with developing a
unified strategy for remedying recent power emergencies and
skyrocketing energy costs.
</P>
<P>
   However, beyond the governor's order for speedier approval of
power plants, his call to action was short on specifics, leaving up
in the air questions about how California will respond to its
current energy mess.
</P>
<P>
   His executive orders came just hours after he received a report
from the president of the state Public Utilities Commission and the
head of the Electricity Oversight Board acknowledging that
deregulation ``is not working for California.''
</P>
<P>
   As The Chronicle reported Wednesday, the report urged the
attorney general to expand his investigation of sky-high
electricity rates in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither the governor nor the attorney general has placed
blame for the state's surging power prices on any particular party.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Gas and Electric Co. and other major utilities again
interrupted power to hundreds of heavy users Wednesday after a
Stage 2 emergency was declared for the eighth time since May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Under a Stage 2 emergency, electricity reserves fall below 5
percent. A Stage 3 emergency, which has never been called on a
statewide basis, means reserves have been nearly depleted, and
utilities can cut power to all customers in so-called rolling
blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Dorinson, a spokesman for the California Independent
System Operator, which oversees most of the state's power grid,
said the danger of a Stage 3 emergency eased Wednesday afternoon
when rain began falling in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reserve picture looks pretty good right now,'' he said.
``But any major contingency puts us in the soup.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling this ``one of the toughest weeks we've ever seen,''
Dorinson said the state's power reserves should increase over
coming days.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term power picture, however, will not improve until
more generating facilities are brought online to meet the state's
ever-growing thirst for juice. No major power plants have been
built in California in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his executive orders, Davis instructed all agencies
involved in licensing new plants to submit their findings within
100 days of receiving a completed application. There is currently
no deadline for application reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Electricity prices in a deregulated market are largely the
function of supply and demand, and California agencies should work
faster to increase supply,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nettie Hoge, executive director of the Utility Reform
Network in San Francisco, said hastening the application process
for new power plants ``raises a red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot and should not build plants that have not been
subject to adequate environmental review,'' she said. ``The
question is: Is it possible to provide adequate review in these
shortened time frames?''
</P>
<P>
   To coordinate statewide efforts to increase the electricity
supply, Davis created an Energy Reliability Task Force that he
described as being modeled on the federal government's National
Security Council. The task force's specific duties were not
detailed.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also directed state agencies to reduce energy
consumption during Stage 2 and 3 power emergencies and to improve
energy efficiency in all state buildings.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had received numerous potential ``action steps'' in
the 40-page report from the PUC and Electricity Oversight Board,
but he did not say which of these steps, if any, he plans to
implement.
</P>
<P>
   Among the report's recommendations are employing computer models
to predict blackouts and hooking up commercial buildings to an
online ``emergency management control system'' that would help
authorities reduce power use during times of peak demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area blackouts, the run-up in prices in the wholesale
electricity markets and the rise in retail electricity prices in
San Diego show that the new system is not working for California,''
the report says.
</P>
<P>
   It adds that ``enough evidence of questionable behavior'' exists
in California's electricity market to warrant an investigation by
the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   PUC President Loretta Lynch said in an interview Wednesday that
this questionable behavior has been displayed by various ``market
participants.'' She declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer activists have charged that power companies are gouging
consumers by jacking up wholesale rates during periods of peak
summertime demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wholesale prices are out of control,'' Lynch said. ``The new
structures don't work.''
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to concede that California's 1996 deregulation of
energy markets is a failure, she acknowledged that ``there were
assumptions that simply haven't proven true.''
</P>
<P>
   With San Diego electricity bills soaring and the threat of
blackouts in the Bay Area persisting, Lynch said that ``by
anybody's measure, we have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The PUC is slated to take up the matter of San Diego's energy
crisis at its meeting Thursday. Lynch refused to speculate on what
the commission may decide, although it is widely expected to adopt
a measure allowing deregulation to run its course.
</P>
<P>
   She said her report to the governor is intended to initiate a
far-reaching discussion on how to address the state's electricity
woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report is a first attempt to call it like it is,'' Lynch
said. ``We shouldn't be concentrating on whose fault it is. We
should be concentrating on what works.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``It's still too early to tell exactly what direction
we should go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
