<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1341 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BUSH-SPEECH-SFCHRON(A     08-03 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SPEECH-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUSH SPEECH WILL ARGUE FOR CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  PHILADELPHIA _ Eleven years ago this week, as Sen. Al Gore
worked on arms control issues and Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
negotiated with NATO allies, George W. Bush was working on another
sort of deal.
<P>
   As managing partner of the Texas Rangers baseball team, Bush
approved a trade that sent a 20-year-old outfielder to the Chicago
White Sox in exchange for Harold Baines, a reliable veteran.
</P>
<P>
   The young prospect was named Sammy Sosa. Within a decade, he
would surpass Babe Ruth's single-season home run record. Bush calls
it the worst mistake of his professional life.
</P>
<P>
   Bush does not need to explain his flawed baseball calculations
when he addresses the Republican National Convention tonight to
accept his party's presidential nomination. But he will need to
demonstrate why a man who has served just 51/2 years in elected
office, who has never run a national campaign and who just a decade
ago was worrying about runs batted in and strikeouts is fit to
become commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has one fundamental challenge, which is to really raise the
comfort level of the American people and convince them he is really
capable of doing the job,'' said former White House press secretary
Mike McCurry and now a convention correspondent for Grassroots.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been working on tonight's address since May and told
reporters Wednesday it's ``ready to go.'' Karen Hughes, his
spokeswoman, said the speech will last about 38 minutes, which
would be considerably shorter than acceptance remarks offered by
nominees in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, Bush must accomplish at least three things: He
must look presidential. He must reach out to moderate and swing
voters. And he must make a case why, in times of economic
prosperity and world peace, the party in control of the White House
should be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's speech, scheduled to begin shortly after 7 p.m.
PST, is Bush's one and only chance during the 2000 campaign to go
on national television with no time constraints. More people will
watch Bush tonight, with the possible expectation of October's
debates, than at any time during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a small thing, but he needs to stand up
straight _ no slouching, no smirking,'' said Jack Pitney, a former
Republican Party official who teaches government at Claremont
McKenna College outside Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more about speaking confidently, boldly, speaking
from the heart about what you've been thinking,'' said McCurry, who
was Clinton's press secretary during the 1996 Democratic
convention. ``He has raised some considerable expectations for his
speech, and he will have to match them in order to claim this
convention as a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Success for most of the 10,000 delegates, supporters and
Republican officials inside the arena would entail a conservative
stem-winder, touching on red-meat Republican issues like tax cuts,
military might, banning abortions and the right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush will be speaking instead to the millions of Americans
in the political center, many of whom will be getting their first
extended look at the man who as a boy fantasized not about being
president, but about being Willie Mays.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made it clear that he intends to reach out to
independents and conservative Democrats, whose support he needs if
he wants to win the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a sentence in the speech that looks in the camera
and says, `I want you!''' Bush told the New York Times just prior
to the opening of the convention. ``But the speech itself should do
that. The speech, if it's done right _ and I think it will be _
will send a broadened message.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a luxury Bush can afford because of his overwhelming
support from conservative and moderate Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very united base,'' said Jim Nicholson, chairman of
the Republican Party. ``What we will do now is reach out and appeal
to those independent and swing voters and attract them to his
passionate conservative, positive reform agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Bush will touch on the same issues that have been the
basis of his stump speech since he began his campaign a year ago:
improving education, strengthening Social Security, rebuilding the
military, reducing taxes and ``unleashing the power'' of
faith-based and charitable organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult task for Bush may be to convince America that
change is necessary in a time of peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Clinton-Gore ticket successfully argued that change
was needed to jump-start a stagnant economy and to usher in a new
generation of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is staking his claim on the more subtle argument that after
eight years of slick, poll-driven politics, the nation is ready for
a new style in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling America's ready for change,'' Bush said Wednesday
in a preview of his address. ``They're interested in something
different. They want somebody to appeal to our better angels, not
our darker impulses. America is hungry for new leadership, and
that's exactly what Dick Cheney and I are going to give them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle political writer Carla Marinucci contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
