<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1344 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-JACKSON-     08-03 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-JACKSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE WIDEOUT SETS ASIDE HOOP DREAM, CATCHES ON WITH SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ Darrell Jackson breaks free up the middle and
leaps to meet the pass. He makes one move, then another, and even
throws in a third _ just because he can. As the defender closes
quickly from the side, Jackson ...
</P>
<P>
   Dunks the ball over Isiah Thomas?
</P>
<P>
   We interrupt Seahawks training camp to share Jackson's recurring
dream as a kid growing in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson always wanted to be a professional athlete, but figured
it would be in the NBA _ not the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was never supposed to happen,'' the rookie wide receiver
from Florida said during the players' lunch break at Eastern
Washington University. ``My dream was to play in the NBA. Everybody
always said I'd end up playing in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is Jackson doing here? And why has he been even better
than advertised when the Seahawks drafted him in the third round in
April?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the first question is, getting open and catching
passes. As for the second, it's a combination of outstanding
coaching and even better athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson returned to practice Tuesday after missing five days
with a strained hip. After an understandably slow start, he was
making the same kind of plays Wednesday that he made during the
first four days of camp _ displaying the talent that is making
Jackson the favorite to win the third spot behind starters Derrick
Mayes and Sean Dawkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that Darrell was a really good player, and he came in
and was every bit as good as we thought, and more,'' head coach
Mike Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``more'' Holmgren spoke of involves Jackson's route-running
ability. It was apparent during spring minicamps, and it is the
reason Jackson has not only been making catches here, but getting
open even when the ball doesn't come his way _ and not just a
little open, but open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, really. Some of the things you try to teach
guys, he already knows,'' quarterback Jon Kitna said. ``Some guys
never even fully understand what it means to work the top of your
route and come out of your route.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just does it naturally. Darrell is polished and fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   And a good student.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson credits his position coach at Tampa Catholic High School
_ Carl McGee, who played tight end with the Tampa Bay Buccaneers _
and University of Florida assistant Dwayne Dixon, who also played
three seasons with the Bucs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started me off young and taught me how to run routes _
get the proper depth and sticks and stuff,'' said Jackson, who
didn't begin playing football until his sophomore year in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   McGee and Dixon taught him well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrell seems to be so complete that the catch is actually the
least of his worries,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   That's another story _ those hands that are strong, yet supple.
</P>
<P>
   Again, credit Dixon. At Florida, he used the ``Jerry Rice
drill'' to transform the hands of a point guard into the hands of a
wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   In the drill, patterned after the way Rice strengthened his Hall
of Fame-caliber hands by snagging bricks for his father, a mason,
the Florida receivers would catch bricks, one in each hand, 50
times. Drop one _ whether it be the first or the 50th _ and it's
back to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me concentrate and improved my grip,'' Jackson said.
``It helped me to really focus on the ball because if you drop one
you've got to start all over again, no matter how far you had
gotten. It got me stronger, improved my confidence and really
helped me become a better receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Make that a very good receiver, and a very productive receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jackson led the Gators with 67 receptions for 1,156
yards and nine touchdowns. When Travis Taylor, the 10th overall
pick by the Baltimore Ravens, was injured, Jackson stepped in and
tied a school record with six consecutive 100-yard games.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Seahawks are counting on Jackson to help fill the
void created by the trade of Joey Galloway to the Dallas Cowboys in
February and the release of Mike Pritchard last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little more every day, I see glimpses of me as a rookie in
Darrell,'' said Derrick Mayes, the Seahawks' leading receiver last
season. ``He wants the challenge. He feels like he can do just as
much as anyone out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's awesome,'' Mayes said. ``You've got to feel that way in
this business. And it's not an attitude. Like I always say, `Don't
be confident. Be convinced.' He has shown a lot of signs of that
early.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those early dreams of playing in the NBA, Jackson had to
abandon them when he got to Florida. But he remains proof that
while you can take the point guard out of the game, it's much more
difficult to take the point guard out of the player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the ball. It comes from my basketball background,''
Jackson said. ``I was a point guard, so I always had the ball, or
was working to get free to get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He still is.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016 or
clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
