<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
  
 Nineteen innings later, it's back to work for Varitek  
 (Subs for previous version; edits throughout)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jason Varitek had a big night Wednesday night,
catching the best pitcher in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez was on the hill at Safeco Field for the Red Sox _
the closest thing to a guarantee as you can get in this game.
</P>
<P>
   Cagey, catlike, fierce _ Martinez performs magic on the mound,
unless you are the Mariners, who fizzled Wednesday night when the
Boston ace went nine innings to demoralize them, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Catching Martinez, Varitek said, is intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man has got such great stuff. It's explosive, so it can
really take off on you in a heartbeat. You have to be sharp,'' said
Varitek, who knows something big happens almost every time Martinez
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Varitek had had a big night the night before
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe it wasn't (BEGIN ITAL) big (END ITAL) so much as it
was (BEGIN ITAL) long. (END ITAL)
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen innings.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours and 34 minutes _ the longest game in the major
leagues this season.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek was behind the plate for every single pitch thrown by
all seven pitchers used by Boston, from knuckleballer Tim Wakefield
down to Jeff Fassero, who gave up the game-winning homer in the
bottom of the 19th to Mike Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek said it took him a long time to go to sleep after the
game and ``I had a few kinks I had to work out'' upon waking up.
Still, he had no complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never once during the game looked at it like I would have to
play 19 innings, that it would be all mine. You just keep going,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Boston manager Jimy Williams was eager to call
Varitek ``fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real warrior. And he (was) in there again (Wednesday
night). I told him if he played again, I'd give him (Thursday)
off,'' Williams said, joking since the Red Sox have an off day .
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason's done very well since he came over in that trade (from
Seattle). He's gotten an awful lot of big hits for us and behind
the plate, he's extremely durable.''
</P>
<P>
   Durability was a big buzz word.
</P>
<P>
   All around the Puget Sound area Wednesday, baseball fans were
separating the wheat from the chaff.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction to be drawn?
</P>
<P>
   Those who had stayed up as Tuesday turned to the wee hours of
Wednesday to watch the epic game, and those _ probably not real
baseball fans _ who succumbed to heavy eyelids and slinked off to
bed before the Cameron homer.
</P>
<P>
   All day Wednesday, from office water coolers to the clubhouses
of both the Mariners and the Red Sox, people who stuck out the
whole game wore their endurance like a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   But no one deserved the badge more than Varitek _ not even
Martinez, who said he went back to the team hotel after the 15th
inning and tried to go to bed.
</P>
<P>
   As Martinez tossed and turned in bed, Varitek was still behind
the plate as the clock struck 12:42 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Three summers ago, the Mariners packaged Varitek and Derek Lowe
in a trading-deadling deal and shipped them to Boston for reliever
Heathcliff Slocumb. And while the Mariners have been satisfied with
the superior defensive ability of Dan Wilson, Varitek has proved
more potent and productive with the bat. He has emerged as an
integral part of the playoff-contending Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a lot to learn, both as a hitter and a catcher,''
Varitek said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Varitek showed just how durable he is. After
the 19-inning marathon, he came out and hammered a two-run double
in the Red Sox's four-run first inning against Freddy Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   But his real thrill, and perhaps the primary reason why Varitek
was the first Red Sox player in the dugout Wednesday afternoon, is
because of the work he gets to do with Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Tired or not, Varitek was ready to work with the Red Sox ace,
who has not lost a road game all season, and who Boston believes
will lead them back to the American League Championship Series _
where Martinez was awesome last October.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Martinez watched from the dugout as his
teammates piled up a 4-0 lead in the first inning _ the kind of
cushion that let Martinez know he was in his control.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is the picture of precision, in his insightful
commentary and on the mound. He knew he had to go as deep as he
could to bail out his fatigued bullpen. He kept his pitch count to
120, throwing 87 for strikes, and keeping Alex Rodriguez and Edgar
Martinez from touching him.
</P>
<P>
   From where he was sitting, Varitek couldn't help but almost rave
about what it's like to work with Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such an intelligent pitcher. You want to get into a
rhythm with him so he's not shaking off the first 10 signs. It's
fun when you get two mind working together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has sort of evolved how we've been able to come
together out there. I caught about 30 of his starts last year, so
it's gotten to the point where you're a pitcher and a catcher
seeing the same thing together. I've gotten to be like him in that
you're staying one step ahead of the hitter. It's like we're on the
same page.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes an alert, fresh mind and spring in your knees to keep
up with Martinez. Varitek, barely rested after the 19-inning
marathon, found himself inspired to go back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what he does tonight, enjoy him,'' Varitek said
before the game. ``It's a wonder what he does, especially in a time
when hitters and teams are doing what they do. And he does it in
the American League where there's a designated hitter. He's got to
get nine hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
