<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 M's no match for Pedro; AL West lead shrinks to two  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On Tuesday night stretching into Wednesday morning, it
took the Red Sox and the Mariners 111 outs to determine a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, it took just one.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the dominance of Boston starter Pedro Martinez that when
the Red Sox scored four times off Freddy Garcia Wednesday night
before the Seattle starter recorded the game's second out, the game
was effectively over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was over right away,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   No false modesty here.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as they gave up four runs, I knew all I had to do was
throw strikes. They'd be desperate to score runs.''
</P>
<P>
   That they were. The two sides played the final eight innings to
make it official, of course. But there is little doubt as to the
outcome of any game in which Martinez is staked to such a lead. The
Mariners averted a shutout by scoring twice in the eighth inning,
but the Red Sox emerged with a 5-2 victory, their second win of the
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to come back any time from four runs down,''
Mariners designated hitter Edgar Martinez said. ``Against Pedro,
it's even harder. He's so good, you know you aren't going to get
many shots at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Alex Rodriguez said, ``As a player, it's your dream to
face him. He's a great pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the dream is a nightmare. It always has been for the
Mariners, who have faced Martinez six times since he defected from
Montreal to the Red Sox. He's 6-0 in those games, with a 1.00
earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been tough on us every time,'' Edgar Martinez said.
``He's got three great pitches. He can locate all of them all the
time. You only hope to get one rally going. We did, in the eighth,
but he made the pitch he needed to get out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   After an RBI grounder by Mark McLemore and an RBI single by Al
Martin gave the Mariners the faintest glimmer of hope in the
eighth, Pedro Martinez snuffed it, eliciting a double-play grounder
from Stan Javier.
</P>
<P>
   End of game. Or, as the Boston ace said, ``When you mix up your
three pitches the way I was doing, it doesn't make it any easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the man knows his place on the food chain. And he knows
he hurt, or at least briefly stalled, the Mariners' pennant drive.
The loss, coupled with Oakland's 5-4 win over Toronto earlier in
the day, leaves the Mariners just two games head of the A's in the
AL West. That's Seattle's slimmest lead in the division since July
9, the day before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The path ahead doesn't get any easier for the Mariners. They
leave Thursday for a seven-day, eight-game road trip that starts
with a Friday-through-Monday series in New York against the AL
East-leading Yankees, the defending World Series champs.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it's four games in three days in Chicago, including
a Tuesday doubleheader. The AL Central-leading White Sox have the
league's best record (65-42).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun,'' manager Lou Piniella said completely
seriously, mindful that his team has the second-best record in the
AL at 62-45. ``We're playing two good teams, and our competition
(second-place Oakland) is playing the same two teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming trip might not have quite as much importance had
the Mariners helped themselves more on the just-completed 13-game
homestand. Seattle owns the best record at home (37-19) in the
majors, but went just 7-6 at Safeco Field in their first series
after the All-Star break, failing to take advantage of 2000's
longest homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long stretch, 21 games in a row,'' Rodriguez said.
``We're a little tired. The day off is good for us. Playing 19
innings and then facing Pedro is going to be tough on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is one of those athletes of special qualities, one of
which is to be as well known by his first name as by his last.
Pedro is up there with Reggie, Nolan, Tiger, Shaq and Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro's victory also underscored the importance of Mike
Cameron's game-winning homer at 12:42 a.m. Wednesday morning, a
blast that gave the Mariners a 5-4 win in 19 innings. No game is
impossible to win, of course, but facing Martinez makes a
victorious outcome unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face facts. The Mariners have never beaten Martinez. Not
once. He's won every game he's ever pitched against Seattle. So by
winning Tuesday night, the Mariners were assured of at least one
win in the series.
</P>
<P>
   And by giving up four runs in the first, they were assure of
losing the finale.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella thought Garcia might have psyched himself up too much
for facing Martinez. Garcia disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to worry about him,'' Garcia said. ``I don't have
to hit against him. I have to worry about doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, four runs in the first isn't the best part of any
pitcher's day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like it, but what can you do?'' Garcia said. ``You
try to get them the next inning and stay close.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia did that.
</P>
<P>
   But with Pedro as the opposition, the Red Sox were already too
far away.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
