<HEADER>
A1380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-CO     08-03 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: An assault on the ``violent'' Bible
 &HT;    For release Aug. 6, 2000
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Germany last week, two lawyers asked the nation's Minister
for the Family and the Elderly to classify the Bible as dangerous
to children, much as some in the United States last month condemned
the latest Harry Potter book as not only violent but anti-Christian
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The latter complaint is based on young Harry's magical powers, a
dominion they believe is God's and God's alone _ not Harry
Potter's, not Superman's, not Batman's, not even Merlin's or Tiger
Woods'.
</P>
<P>
   Book police are everywhere. It was only a matter of time until
they got to the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the religious manuscript is violent, quite violent. It
also includes some segments dealing with sex that you wouldn't want
your children to read, or understand.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to condemn the Bible, or even to take sides as to
whether the book is the true word of the Almighty or a piece of
fiction written decades, maybe centuries, after the periods it
claims to represent. It simply is to point out that no written word
is safe from those who would anoint themselves as censors.
</P>
<P>
   The German lawyers, claiming to represent some parents, appealed
to the German cabinet member on the grounds that passages of the
Bible contain ``a gruesomeness difficult to exceed.'' An example I
would cite: I Samuel 18:27.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks on the written word, Bible included, are not new. They
are documented throughout history, most notoriously during the Nazi
era but also including the present time as evidenced by
organizations calling for _ and often receiving -- bans or
revisions of books that are considered, retrospectively, racist,
anti-God or obscene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huckleberry Finn'' and ``A Catcher in the Rye'' are among
those and, now, some would claim, so are ``Harry Potter and the
Goblet of Fire'' _ and the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know that many have called for the Bible to be
categorized as would a PG or R movie, but pointing out the violent
and fornication elements of, particularly, the Old Testament is old
hat and grist for discussion at a time when other publications are
under fire for their permissiveness or brutality.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most virulent and controversial studies of those
elements of the Bible was the 1926 publication of ``The Bible
Unmasked'' by the then well-known atheist Joseph Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Genesis and continuing book-by-book,
chapter-by-chapter, verse-by-verse, Lewis cited passages of extreme
violence and what he considered bizarre sexual behavior -- behavior
that many of our present-day fundamentalist leaders would be hard
pressed to defend, or explain. Example: Genesis 16:1-6.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' book never made any best-seller list and was more
strongly condemned by the public than any condemnations he meted
out. But I found a portion of his introduction to be quite
prophetic. ``...What is immoral in one age,'' he wrote in 1926,
``may, at some other time, be considered moral and what we today
may consider moral and acceptable, may at some future date be
condemned as being immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   What could have prompted the German lawyers to seek a likely
unpopular not-for-children classification of the Bible ? Other than
for personal publicity, it must have been on behalf of people who,
pushed to the limit over fundamentalist-imposed restrictive
classification of other reading material, have decided to strike
back.
</P>
<P>
   Had Huck Finn, instead of Rabshakeh, said what she said in my
version of Isaiah 36:12, the censors would taken out their long
knives. Little is expected to come of the German issue. Sadly, the
lesson it likely was planned to teach _ tolerance of expression _
will be lost on the general public in Germany or anywhere. It also
would show that book police don't really protect; they bully
selective targets.
</P>
<P>
   And even the Bible can be one of those targets.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
