<SLUG> BC-IMPULSE-TO-TRAVEL-ENDPAPER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME, WHEN THE HEART IS ELSEWHERE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Free to clients of Way to Go!) 
 (FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES) 
 BY SUSAN ALLEN TOTH  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    When I have finally opened the mail, unpacked my bags, started
the washing machine, restocked the refrigerator and riffled through
a few newspapers, I am ready to stay home forever.
 &HT;    Yes, I realize, I'm totally exhausted. I stroke our cats,
defrost some homemade soup and soon send my husband, James, to his
office so I can luxuriate in having the house to myself. No, I am
not going to travel again for a long time. Months and months, maybe
longer. Who knows when I'll ever be ready to study another
guidebook or decipher another map?
 &HT;    I am tired of looking at menus. I can't bear to sleep in any
more strange bedrooms. I want to forget all those uneasy searches
for public toilets.
 &HT;    Our friends applaud this decision. They think James and I travel
too much anyway.
 &HT;    ``Of course you have a cold,'' one says. ``Everyone knows you
can't travel on a plane without getting sick.'' Another chimes in:
``How can you complain of not getting any writing done? You're
never home.''
 &HT;    Some urge us to slow down, take it easy. Others suggest getting
back to work, enjoying my garden, volunteering for a local charity.
I'm sure they are right. In fact, as I nod in agreement, I feel
morally invigorated.
 &HT;    Travel is a kind of addiction, I tell myself, and I must simply
let it go for a while. I can. I know I can.
 &HT;    Then something happens. If I could predict it, I might be able
to ward it off. But the travel impulse is sly, mysterious and
dazzlingly sudden.
 &HT;    Last December, glad to be home for the holidays after a hectic
trip to London, I was savoring the prospect of quiet weeks ahead.
Then I opened a Christmas card from a family friend in my Iowa
hometown.
 &HT;    Close to 90 now, cheerful and bright but unable to travel,
Isabel wrote: ``You certainly travel a lot. But do keep it up as
long as you can! I wish I had seen York and Cornwall. But I am so
thankful I didn't miss the Alhambra and the Prado.''
 &HT;    The Alhambra! I thought. The Prado! Why is it we've never been
there? Immediately I began to think of Spain. Why not Portugal too?
Perhaps next fall?
 &HT;    A few days later, on New Year's Eve, I was transfixed by the
televised fantasy of fireworks that lit up the bejeweled Eiffel
Tower. Oh, Paris, beautiful City of Light _ had it really been five
years since we'd walked along the Seine?
 &HT;    I could instantly envision broad boulevards, thin women with
chic silk scarves, and a corner patisserie where I bought a moist
round mouthful of chocolate cake with an indescribably delicious
coffee-flavored icing. Definitely, back to Paris.
 &HT;    Cleaning my desk the following week, I took off the wall an
outdated calendar with large color photographs of waterfalls. I
hadn't really noticed it much. But now I was transfixed by a view
of Upper Yosemite Falls, tumbling down magnificent snow-covered
cliffs.
 &HT;    I hadn't been to Yosemite for more than 30 years, and I barely
remembered my one day there. How could I think of Paris, or Spain,
when I hadn't really experienced Yosemite?
 &HT;    I am helpless against unforeseen assaults on my homebound
intentions. Occasionally, when I am already on a trip, I have a
passing glimpse of a destination that calls to me so seductively I
know I must answer.
 &HT;    One June afternoon, on a fast train from Inverness to London, I
glanced, for only a whizzing moment, far across miles of empty
fields to a tiny village of snug houses clustered around a bay. The
surrounding countryside seemed so undiscovered, the village so
remote.
 &HT;    I studied my map: Alnmouth, Northumberland. Three years later,
we were walking through light rain down its long quiet beach.
 &HT;    On another afternoon, this time in early fall, I sat on a level
rock at the northernmost edge of Scotland and gazed, entranced, at
the distant gray-green shapes of the Orkney Islands half-hidden in
the mist. They seemed as if they belonged to a different world.
``James,'' I said, ``we have to go there.''
 &HT;    James smiled, partly in resignation. ``O.K.,'' he said amiably,
``but why don't we finish this trip first?''
 &HT;    Two Octobers later, we rented a cottage for a week on an Orkney
island called, disarmingly, Mainland.
 &HT;    Sometimes all it takes is a single picture or a few words. We
once spent a week near Cromer, on the north Norfolk coast, because
that was the phrase _ ``the north Norfolk coast'' _ occasionally
appearing in travel guides, that had begun to haunt my imagination.
It sounded so unlike the cozy Cotswolds, or the well-trodden and
prosaically named Lake District, or flowering Kent, the Garden of
England.
 &HT;    Then I read P. D. James' ``Devices and Desires,'' and her
intensely evocative description of that bleak, windswept land made
me determined to see if she was right. And she was.
 &HT;    Although P.D. James first sent me to Norfolk, Arthur Conan Doyle
to Dartmoor and Dylan Thomas to Wales, I am not often struck by the
travel impulse when I read nonfiction travel books. This may seem
odd, since I have indulged in such memoirs myself.
 &HT;    But, after closing a particularly atmospheric or vivid travel
narrative, I tend to think: ``OK. Wonderful. Now I've been there.''
 &HT;    If the author has filled my eyes with his or her personal
vision, I am perversely not moved to explore certain corners of
Provence, or Tuscany, or Patagonia.
 &HT;    If, however, I am swept into a place by reading a novel or
biography, I absorb the landscape sidewise, out of the corner of my
eye. Then I become intrigued.
 &HT;    After finishing Tim Binding's ``Lying With the Enemy,'' a novel
about life in occupied Guernsey during World War II, I asked James,
``Why haven't we ever been to the Channel Islands?'' He looked
blank. I handed him the novel, and the next year, we were off.
 &HT;    My love of Scottish islands began, not with a guidebook, but
with Gavin Maxwell's ``Ring of Bright Water,'' an account of life
with his beloved otters.
 &HT;    I soon tracked Maxwell through his later, much harsher, memoirs,
``The Rocks Remain'' and ``Raven Seek Thy Brother,'' and, after
many years, I eventually looked across the water to the lonely site
of his nearly inaccessible Camusfearna.
 &HT;    As James and I walked parts of the rocky coastline of western
Scotland, and explored Mull and Skye that year, I often thought of
Maxwell's intense, troubled spirit. His love of this land had
brought us there.
 &HT;    Or had it? As a young girl, I used to sit at the piano and play
through ``The Fireside Book of Folk Songs.'' One of my favorites
was ``The Skye Boat Song.'' Its simple, poignant melody had an
unforgettable refrain, especially alluring to an Iowa girl who
lived far from any ocean: ``Carry the lad who was born to be
king/Over the sea to Skye.''
 &HT;    I didn't know the story of Bonnie Prince Charlie, and I had no
idea where Skye was, but I knew loss and regret when I heard it.
Over the sea to Skye: someday perhaps I would know more.
 &HT;    So even a song can start me thinking of travel. After our trip
to Hawaii last winter, James began to play a CD we bought there. He
plays it a lot, especially when it gets really cold outside.
 &HT;    Like James, I had been delighted by our relaxing, balmy week on
Molokai. So when I hear ``Polynesian Love Song'' or ``Lovely Hula
Hands,'' I don't think, ``This is corny.'' No, I want to be back on
our screened lanai, listening to the warm splashing surf a few
yards away.
 &HT;    It doesn't take much. Sometimes I think I should look for an
antidote, but I haven't thought of one yet. Maybe if I muttered
Thoreau's proud boast, ``I have traveled much in Concord''? If I
repeated like a mantra, ``Home is where the heart is''? What about
a CD that played, again and again, ``Home Sweet Home''? I'm not
sure any of it would help. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Susan Allen Toth's most recent book is ``England for All
Seasons'' (Ballantine).)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Susan Allen Toth 
