<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASK THE TRAVEL EXPERT 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By WILLIAM T. TOMICKI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;     Q:  My husband wants adventure, I want a spa with a spiritual
nature and our kids don't fit into either category. Help! Know of a
vacation destination that will meet everyone's needs?
 &HT;     A:  The Enchantment Resort in Sedona, Ariz., and its new
destination spa, Mii Amo, will surely please all. Nestled within a
truly enchanting red-rock canyon, Enchantment offers scenic
relaxation and adventure, as well as Camp Coyote, ranked one of the
best kids programs in the world.
 &HT;    One of Enchantment's treasures is Uqualla, the shaman and former
chief of the Havasupai tribe, who acts as spiritual ambassador for
the resort. While children play and learn about the local cultures,
guests can be pampered by healing oils that are blessed each
morning. Spiritual consultations are available, and the staff
offers an array of innovative spa treatments.
 &HT;    The Enchantment concierge can arrange a variety of hiking and
rock-climbing tours for the adventurous or the mere stroller.
 &HT;    Your family should save an afternoon to fly by helicopter with
Uqualla to his tribe's village at the bottom of the Grand Canyon.
There you can enjoy a swim and picnic at the nearby falls.
 &HT;    At the end of the day, whether your crew is rested or exhausted,
Enchantment's restaurants offer an eclectic selection of spa
cuisine and hearty southwestern fare, as well as an excellent wine
list.
 &HT;    Book now for the holidays to reserve an Enchantment casita or
one of Mii Amo's 16 rooms and suites. Room rates begin at $195 per
night. For more information, call (800) 826-4180 or visit
www.enchantmentresort.com.
 &HT;     Q:  I've always been intrigued by the mystique of Harvard, but
the two times I visited Cambridge I felt like such an outsider. How
can I get a better feel for the place?
 &HT;     A:2 Home to Harvard, MIT and the JFK School of Government,
Cambridge may well be the premiere locale for intellectuals in this
country. Most visiting lecturers and dignitaries stay at the
Charles Hotel on Harvard Square.
 &HT;    Not only is it within walking distance, at times the Charles
Hotel seems like an extension of the Harvard campus. Relax in the
foyer library and watch the comings and goings _ or better yet, ask
the concierge to arrange a private tour of Harvard with a recent
graduate. Often the guide runs into buddies, conversations ensue
and the scene opens before you.
 &HT;    I would suggest arriving early for breakfast at the Charles'
lively Henrietta's Table, where writer David Mamet or Cambridge's
dot.com elite might just be doing business.
 &HT;    Lunch would be a good idea at a popular joint called Bartley's
Burger Cottage (1246 Massachusetts Ave.), but Casablanca (40
Brattle St.), with its fusion Mediterranean cuisine, is a more
original mainstay of Cambridge _ especially in the evening at the
bar.
 &HT;    Room rates at the Charles Hotel begin at $250 per night.
Facilities include a day spa and three-story health-and-fitness
center. For more information, call (800) 882-1818, or visit
www.charleshotel.com.
 &HT;     Q:  I have played on golf courses around the world and really
enjoy when courses throw a unique spin into the golfing experience.
Can you suggest a course that offers a bit of originality?
 &HT;     A:  The new ``Heli-Golf Package,'' offered by Rosewood Hotels &AMP;
Resorts in Little Dix Bay in the Virgin Islands, provides the
originality that adventurous golfers look for. This heli-golf
experience features a scenic helicopter flight to St. Croix, where
golfers are deposited right onto the green and are then processed
through customs and immigrations with minimal hassle.
 &HT;    Described as ``the Caribbean's most exclusive golf getaway,''
Little Dix Bay's Heli-Golf Package includes three nights'
accommodation for two; greens fees, cart and golf escort; daily
breakfast and dinner; and complimentary water activities. Rates are
based on double occupancy, with deluxe accommodations starting at
$3,500 and suite accommodations starting at $5,000.
 &HT;    Laurance Rockefeller founded exclusive Little Dix Bay in 1964.
These low-key yet upscale accommodations are set in a 500-acre
garden paradise and a pristine private beach. For more information,
call (888) ROSEWOOD.
 &HT;     Q:  I am a single female who enjoys traveling alone, but
occasionally I feel left out of certain social activities because I
am not part of a couple. Do other independent travelers ever feel
this way?
 &HT;     A:  Some people do _ and, unfortunately, it's usually women.
Because of this, Fred. Olsen Cruise Lines now feature their popular
gentlemen hosts aboard every cruise. With their gracious social
skills and dancing ability, these men are well-known for making
single female passengers feel at ease in all social activities.
 &HT;    Fred. Olsen Cruise Lines offers exhilarating cruises throughout
Africa, the Caribbean, Europe and South America. For more
information and reservations, visit www.eurocruises.com, or call
(800) 688-3876.
 &HT;     Q:  Over the years, I have noticed that some hotels are more
in-tune with the needs of female business travelers than others.
Can you recommend a good hotel that focuses on this segment of the
population?
 &HT;     A:  The Pan Pacific San Francisco recently surveyed female
guests _ focusing on those with business needs _ and has made
several adjustments.
 &HT;    The women who were surveyed reported that females appreciate
softer, more personal touches. For example, minibars are now
stocked with wines by the glass. There are lighter menu choices
available on the 24-hour room-service menu, personal butlers can be
provided and the staff is available to escort female guests to
their rooms. This is just a handful of the amenities that are part
of the hotel's signature luxury service.
 &HT;    For business travelers, the Pan Pacific has added a virtual
office to many rooms. Copy capabilities are now part of the in-room
fax machine, and all guest rooms will soon be wired for high-speed
Internet access. The hotel has also acquired a number of laptop
computers.
 &HT;    The Pan Pacific San Francisco is located just one block from
Union Square and is a cable-car ride away from the city's theater
district, fine restaurants and other tourist attractions. For more
information and reservations, call (800) 533-6465, or visit the web
at www.panpac.com.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions to William Tomicki, P.O.
Box 5148, Santa Barbara, Calif. 93150. Although he cannot answer
each query individually, selected questions will be included in his
column. Mr. Tomicki, who logs over 150,000 miles each year, is the
publisher of ENTREE, a travel newsletter. 
 &HT;    
 c.2000 William T. Tomicki 
