<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: LUXURY TRAIN TRAVEL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    The romance of the rails lingers in a handful of deluxe trains
that run on well-orchestrated trips throughout the world.
 &HT;    What's the appeal of such luxury train trips? Vintage rail cars
that have been lavishly restored; itineraries that take passengers
through some of the most beautiful landscapes and cities in the
world; impeccable service; and food that is extraordinary.
 &HT;    For those who can pay the price, here are some elegant journeys
to consider. Prices are per person, based on double occupancy.
 &HT;    The American Spirit (601 Union St., Seattle, WA 98101;
888-533-7245; www.americanspiritrail.com) features 1950s Budd-built
streamliner railcars. The company offers a variety of western
itineraries that include visits to the Glacier, Grand Tetons and
Yellowstone National Parks.
 &HT;    Trips last anywhere from two to nine nights. Accommodations are
in hotels, not on the train, and motorcoaches supplement the rail
service.
 &HT;    A typical itinerary is the ``Montana Rockies Rail Tour,'' which
begins in Post Falls, Idaho, continues on to Missoula, Mont., and
ends in Livingston, Mont. The cost of the two-night trip begins at
$499. Lodging and daily breakfast, as well as transfers from
Spokane Airport, are included.
 &HT;    The American Orient-Express (5100 Main St., Downer's Grove, IL
60515; 888-759-3944; www.americanorientexpress.com) utilizes 15
vintage rail cars on its luxury voyages. The train travels cross
country as well as on shorter trips throughout the West.
 &HT;    For example, the ``Rockies and Yellowstone'' itinerary is a
six-night trip that commences in Denver and visits Arches National
Park, Salt Lake City, Grand Teton and Yellowstone National Parks.
The cost begins at $2,990.
 &HT;    The best-known name in luxury-train travel is probably
Orient-Express Trains &AMP; Cruises (Sea Containers House, 20 Upper
Ground, London, SE1 9PF, England; 800-524-2420;
www.orient-expresstrains.com or c/o Abercrombie and Kent
International Inc., 1520 Kensington Road, Oak Brook, IL 60523;
800-323-7308; www.abercrombiekent.com). They offer a variety of
rail itineraries for the well-heeled traveler.
 &HT;    The most famous trip is the Venice Simplon-Orient-Express
(VSOE), which features restored period rail cars, lavish service
and fine dining. Sightseeing and meals are included in most
itineraries.
 &HT;    The classic VSOE trip is from London to Paris and Venice, or
vice versa. The cost of this one-night trip starts at $1,970. The
train makes other trips as well, such as from Venice to Florence
and Rome; Venice to Prague, Paris and London; Venice to Lucerne,
Paris and London; and Paris to Budapest, Bucharest and Istanbul.
 &HT;    Orient-Express also offers the Eastern &AMP; Oriental Express, a
luxury train that has three itineraries: Singapore to Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia, and Bangkok (and vice versa); Bangkok to Chiang Mai,
Thailand; and Bangkok to Angkor Wat, Cambodia, and Singapore. The
overnight Singapore to Kuala Lumpur itinerary begins at $600.
 &HT;    Among the other Orient-Express trains are the Northern Belle,
which calls itself the ``Orient-Express of the North.'' It offers
day trips and weekend getaways in Britain with departures from
Liverpool, Manchester and York. Again, vintage rail carriages, fine
dining and a high level of service are offered.
 &HT;    Orient Express also operates the Great South Pacific Express in
Australia, a restored luxury train that runs from Brisbane to
Cairns; Brisbane to Sydney; Brisbane to Canberra and Sydney; and
Sydney to Brisbane and Cairns. Contact them for more information.
 &HT;    The Royal Scotsman (c/o Abercrombie and Kent International Inc.
1520 Kensington Road, Oak Brook, IL 60523; 800-323-7308;
www.abercrombiekent.com or www.royalscotsman.com) takes visitors
through the rugged Scottish countryside on some of the beautiful
rails in Britain. The four-night Edinburgh to Edinburgh itinerary
is $4,150.
 &HT;    Beginning in the Scottish capital, the journey takes riders
through the dramatic West Highlands and rolling Perthshire hills
and then to the North East. Two-night trips start at $2,350. Rates
include all meals, wine and alcoholic and beverages as well as
sightseeing visits.
 &HT;    In Canada, the Rocky Mountaineer Railtours (1150 Station St.,
Vancouver, B.C. Canada V6A 2X7; 800-665-7245;
www.rockymountaineer.com) has a variety of trips through the
Canadian Rockies. These trains travel by daylight only, affording
the best views of the mountains. Overnights are spent in hotels.
 &HT;    One of the briefest excursions is the ``Two Day Redleaf Tour,''
a one-night trip through the Canadian Rockies, traveling from
Vancouver to either Jasper, Alberta, or Calgary, Alberta, with an
overnight hotel stay in Kamloops, Alberta. Prices start at $358 per
person and include the overnight stay and some meals.
 &HT;    Premier Selections (342 Madison Ave., Suite 916, New York, N.Y.
10173; 800-234-4000; www.premierselections.com) is the sales agent
for a number of great train journeys, including the Al Andalus
Express, the Royal Scottsman and the Venice Simplon-Orient-Express.
Rates start at $1,512 and include five nights on the train, one in
a hotel, most meals and sightseeing.
 &HT;    Premier also has a variety of other luxury trains, including the
Blue Train in South Africa. This train runs from Capetown to
Pretoria, with an overnight in Johannesburg. The price of this
five-night train/tour package _ which includes four hotel nights,
one night on the train itself and some meals _ starts at $1,946.
 &HT;    Finally, Copper Canyon's Sierra Madre Express runs from Tuscon,
Ariz., down into Mexico's fabled Copper Canyon region. The
seven-night trip, which includes hotel and train accommodation, as
well as most meals, begins at $2,545.
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
