<HEADER>
A1521 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-FIVESENSES-REVIE     08-03 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FIVESENSES-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
``FIVE SENSES'' PACKED WITH SMALL MOMENTS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By LOUIS B. PARKS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Watching ``The Five Senses'' feels like reading a good book of
interrelated character stories tied together by a loose plot.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the best Canadian film award at the Toronto Film
Festival last year, ``The Five Senses'' also was shot in that city.
</P>
<P>
   Several people living or working in the same upscale apartment
building progress through modestly eventful days of their lives,
many of them interacting with each other directly or obliquely.
</P>
<P>
   The film gets its title from the senses of touch, smell, taste,
sight and hearing. These play a significant role in the lives of
several characters. It sounds like a gimmick but isn't used that
way.
</P>
<P>
   One of the characters, an optometrist, is losing his hearing.
Because of it, he's losing what he cares about most: opera. Another
character, a masseuse, is out of touch with her daughter. And so
on. The senses merely are the starting point from which director
and writer Jeremy Podeswa started thinking about his film. If he
had named it ``The Ten People,'' we would not even notice that the
senses were represented.
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa has been compared to fellow Canadian (and friend) Atom
Egoyan, partly because they are fellow countrymen. Though ``The
Five Senses'' does have a lyrical quality, it feels more grounded
in daily reality than Egoyan's almost surreal naturalism (``The
Sweet Hereafter'').
</P>
<P>
   They do share, however, an interest in the minutiae of average
people.
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa gathered an excellent cast, and the ensemble acting is
superb. The only name well-known to American audiences is
Mary-Louise Parker (``Fried Green Tomatoes''), who plays Rona, a
baker whose amazingly constructed special-occasion cakes are
inedible.
</P>
<P>
   Rona, whose love life is flaky, has a house guest, a passionate
Italian (who (beginital)can (endital) cook) she met in Italy.
Roberto (Marco Leonardi of ``Cinema Paradiso'' and ``Like Water for
Chocolate'') doesn't speak English, and Rona doesn't speak Italian.
She wonders if he's using her to get a work permit to stay in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Parker (``Sunshine'') plays a mother who takes her small
daughter on a visit to the masseuse, Ruth (Gabrielle Rose of ``The
Sweet Hereafter''). Ruth sends her strange, troubled teen-age
daughter Rachel to the nearby city park with the little girl. While
Rachel is busy spying on some lovers, the child disappears.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the child (we know how she disappeared, but not
what's happened since, so there is some suspense) becomes an
ongoing news story and the closest thing to a dramatic plot this
film has.
</P>
<P>
   Other stories involve Rachel and an equally strange boy she
meets in the park working out identity problems; a bisexual
professional house cleaner (Daniel MacIvor of ``Beefcake'') with a
strong sense of smell who calls upon all his old lovers, hoping to
tell by scent if one really loves him; and the optometrist who is
seeking solace from a prostitute, Gail, who offers him something
much more important than sex.
</P>
<P>
   The film has no big moments but is packed with countless small,
quiet ones, some exquisitely done: a meeting between the mother of
the lost child and the mother of the teen who let her get away; the
house cleaner smelling, in wonder, a bottled fragrance after a
night of unexpected, loveless sex; Gail showing the opera fan how
to (begin ital) feel (end ital) music.
</P>
<P>
   One probably can't have a movie that tries to capture so many
tiny but profound moments of emotion, transition and connection
without sometimes stepping over that infinitely thin line where
insight and balance become the obvious and contrived. For some,
this movie may cross over several times. I was usually willing to
grant Podeswa his sincerity and go with him.
</P>
<P>
   Podeswa and his cast work in perfect harmony to capture a
melancholy mood and perfectly measured pace. Yet the movie is not
sad. While it's not exactly right to say the movie ends in an
upbeat way _ after all, each story has its own end (or non-end) _
Podeswa certainly doesn't intend to send us away bummed out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``The Five Senses'' &QL; 
Starring: Mary-Louise Parker, Molly Parker, Daniel MacIvor, Nadia
Litz, Gabrielle Rose &QL; 
Rating: R for sexuality and language &QL; 
Running time: 105 minutes &QL; 
Grade: B+ &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
