<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My daughter's first film: 'Is This Thing On?'
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My youngest daughter has it all figured
out. She just turned 19, has a year of college under her belt, is
still in relatively good graces with the powers-that-be at the
University of Texas, and now knows for sure what she wants to do
for a living.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to be a film director. The Stanley Kubrick of the Pine
Curtain, or maybe the Steven Spielberg of the Sabine. She already
has her first short film planned and is busily polishing the
screenplay. The location has been chosen, a coal mine up north of
here. I pointed out that the owners of the coal mine probably
wouldn't look kindly to her filming a movie amidst their mountains
of black gold, and she blithely informed me she planned to sneak
in. I told her to call her mother for bail money.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Goose planned to major in journalism but now says
it's not creative enough for her, we ink-stained scribes having to
attempt to adhere to the truth and all that. So she has switched to
radio-television-film, RTF for short, in one of the better programs
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   My approach to parental guidance when it comes to a child's
college career is simple. You can take whatever classes you like,
change your major every full moon if you wish, but know one
unassailable verity. I pay for four years, no more. At the end of
four years, the child is down-sized off the payroll and is
perfectly free to attend school until she is 35 as long as it's on
her nickel.
</P>
<P>
   This may seem harsh, but, hey, it's a tough world.
</P>
<P>
   Being the supportive sort, all her parents _ and she has a full
thermonuclear family what with divorces, remarryings and all _
chipped in and bought her a video camera for her birthday. It's
nothing fancy, just a step up from the cheapest you can buy, but
she was thrilled. That's one of Goose's strong points: she's easily
pleased. For the few days she was here, she busily recorded many
special moments, such as me staring dumbly at the camera while she
implored me to do or say something _ anything _ along with her
boyfriend, her step-brother, and step-mom, all of whom reacted by
saying, ``Would you please turn that thing off?''
</P>
<P>
   I don't see a lot of commercial potential in the footage
gathered so far, but who could have predicted the success of the
``Blair Witch Project?''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, that movie is a major point of contention
between Goose and me. I am no ultimate arbiter of good taste, but
that movie sucked eggs. She begs to differ, maintaining this is a
classic of modern cinematography. My wife has extended _ and blurry
_ home-video footage of her carpet when she didn't realize the
camera was on that reminds me of some of the more compelling
moments in ``Blair Witch Project.''
</P>
<P>
   The most common expression you will hear on the audio portion of
a video camera operated by us common folk is, ``Is this thing on?''
which is the non-lethal equivalent of that other cherished East
Texas expression, ``Is this gun loaded?''
</P>
<P>
   But I'm confident my daughter will overcome her genetic
shortcomings and succeed in whatever career she chooses to pursue.
And Lord knows she is the Queen of Movie Trivia. Darned few movies
make it to the big screen or even straight to video without passing
before her eyes. She knows not only the names of the actors and
actresses, directors and producers, but the key grips. And exactly
what is a key grip, anyhow?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in a few years, she will be the new hot director on the
cinema scene. And I, along with the rest of her parents, can
proudly take credit for having had some small role in her success.
</P>
<P>
   I figure her first film will be entitled, ``Is This Thing On?''
Look for it in theaters near you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
