<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1526 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0804-CO     08-03 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Democrat next in line for Texas governorshipBy Dave
McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ That guy on the famous steps here, getting his
picture taken, was Ricky, not Rocky.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that's what his momma calls him. Rick Perry, the
lieutenant governor of Texas who will become governor if his buddy
George W. Bush beats Al Gore on Nov. 7, was on the Philadelphia
Museum of Art steps featured in Sylvester Stallone's ``Rocky''
movie Wednesday, waiting for Bush to arrive at a rally.
</P>
<P>
   With his black hair slicked back and aide Eric Bearse holding
his coat, Perry joked with folks in the crowd _ and took pictures
with his own camera, like any other tourist. He asked the
plainclothes Pennsylvania state trooper escorting him to take his
picture with state Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, along for the
ride.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Perry had to leave before Bush made his
entrance, to speak at a National Federation of Independent Business
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush dominates this convention, Perry, who could be
Texas's next governor, has begun to show evidence in Philadelphia
this week that he is moving out of Bush's shadow.
</P>
<P>
   While he continues to cheer on Bush's candidacy, this former
Democrat is becoming better acquainted with the rank and file of
the Texas Republican Party as head of the state delegation.
</P>
<P>
   He has shown them a personable, quick-witted man whose quiet
leadership ability is credited for helping prevent a disastrous
display by Bush's home state, when he convinced many not to walk
out during a policy speech by an openly gay Congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, chosen at the Republican State Convention to lead the
Texas delegation here, has left most of the details of to State
Chairman Susan Weddington and her staff. But the humor he often
uses while presiding over the Texas Senate to lighten and liven
things is in evidence here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waffles today are offered by Al Gore,'' he joked at the
delegation's breakfast Wednesday. In introducing a spokesman for
Union Pacific, which was paying for Wednesday's breakfast, Perry, a
former Texas Aggie yell leader, led an Aggie-style yell for the
speaker's alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   When talk circulated Monday that some Texas delegates might walk
out during a speech on foreign affairs by a gay congressman, Perry
let it be known he'd be staying right in his chair.
</P>
<P>
   And when Perry was asked about some Texas delegates bowing their
heads in prayer during the congressman's speech, Perry said he
hadn't noticed because he was on the front row. ``I guess anytime's
a good time for prayer,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   The former Air Force captain talks about dropping the
``lieutenant'' in front of his title only when asked. Even then,
Perry, 50, says he's more concerned about smoothly handing off the
powerful lieutenant governor's job to the senator chosen by his or
her colleagues to succeed him than running the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Perry points out that he's often been acting governor, when Bush
is out of the state campaigning as he's been for the last 18
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our staffs are very closely coordinated,'' Perry says.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of which job he's in when the Legislature meets in
January, he'll be focusing on restructuring the state's higher
education system, and high-tech matters, including privacy, Perry
said.
</P>
<P>
   To delegates and other groups, Perry says he'll be proud to
point to the occupant of the White House as a role model if Bush
moves in, and that Bush with former defense secretary Dick Cheney
would restore emphasis for a strong military.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a regular guy _ a regular guy with a vision,'' Perry
says. ``I tell (people) that he's somebody that you could go
fishing with. . . . They obviously haven't sat next to him at a
Texas Rangers baseball game and listened to him banter with the
players, and talk to the fans, and be the regular guy at the
ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all of those stories and interactions that we've had for
a decade,'' Perry said. ``And this guy's fixing to be president of
the United States, on Air Force One. The personal part of this is
pretty overpowering on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
