<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-DAVIS-COLUMN04-COX     08-03 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When you think Texas and power and politics, think oil
 &HT;    By Mary Alice Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the new Texas, as in the old, when you talk about power and
money, you always end up talking about oil.
</P>
<P>
   As high tech, silicon-savvy and info-hip as we believe ourselves
to be, here in the world's 11th-largest economy, the well-being of
the oil biz is never far from our thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   So when the national Republican Party tops its ticket with ``two
Texas oilmen,'' as it plans to do this week, that sounds normal.
From childhood we've seen that while oil and water don't mix, oil
and politics do.
</P>
<P>
   When Texans elected George W. Bush as governor in 1994, what we
mainly knew of him was that his dad was ex-President Bush, a nice
man who called Houston home. The state embraced W. as an amiable
and fabulously successful sports investor with a lovely family.
</P>
<P>
   But it certainly didn't hurt his image that he had found his
adult identity and the seeds of a considerable fortune as that
mythic creature, the Texas oil man. Twice in recent decades, the
state had picked as governor another of that ilk, the gruff Bill
Clements, who once suggested that a good hurricane would tidy up
oil-spill damage his company had done in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was a footloose Yalie who had embraced the rough and tumble
of Midland by creating a drilling startup in 1977. The company
faltered and was absorbed by other oil outfits. Bush wound up as a
director of Harken Energy Corp., then as a phenomenally productive
short-term investor (returns of more than 2,000 percent) in pro
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   As stockholder Bush was leaving Harken, the company pulled off
what is recalled wondrously in the oil world as ``the Bahrain
deal.'' With no overseas experience to speak of, Harken won a
contract to explore for oil and gas in the Persian Gulf. The Wall
Street Journal, in an editorial page analysis, referred to this
Persian Gulf business coup as ``a piece of exceptional luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, the elder Bush's secretary of defense, spent most of his
life in government service before finding a niche directing a
Texas-based oil conglomerate. Since 1995, he has run the global
operations of Halliburton Co., an oil-field services and
construction company with headquarters in Dallas. He recently sold
about half his Halliburton stock for an estimated $5.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the new globalized economy, the oil business and politics are
pretty much the same thing, as they traditionally have been in
Texas. Cheney, as head of Halliburton, lobbied hard against U.S.
sanctions against countries such as Iran, on the grounds that it's
not good for business. The Gulf War was to a major extent, a war
about the oil business and fueling SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Bush is often photographed with black or brown
schoolkids, plugging away on the theme of education. But this week,
it seemed far more natural to see him again at the side of a
wealthy, pink-cheeked oil executive such as Cheney _ much like the
ones who have run Texas for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is struck from the mold of Bush's greatest mentors. Texas
oil millionaires (old think) and billionaires (new think) loom
large in the Bush history. Notable among them is Richard Rainwater,
a Fort Worth oilman and sports investor and former Bush business
partner who has contributed generously to his friend's political
life.
</P>
<P>
   Scrappy wildcatters such as Jett Rink of ``Giant'' may be scarce
in today's Texas, but gushers still come in. The New York Times
recently reported that major oil companies are expecting earnings
for the latest quarter to be double what they were a year ago.
Exploration and production companies were expected to report profit
increases averaging 371 percent. Refinery profits could double or
triple.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, here in the industry's spiritual homeland, oil
chieftains speak darkly of hard times and the urgent need to repeal
the severance tax _ the tax our income-tax-free state levies on
those who extract minerals from the land.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the state's three railroad commissioners (who, oddly,
regulate oil and gas, not railroads) recently said that might be a
good idea. Another Bush point man, Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo,
said the tax should, at the very least, be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Poignant stories of oil-patch hardship were a key feature of the
1999 legislative session. While oil industry tax breaks didn't get
a mention in Bush's opening address to lawmakers, they topped his
legislative priorities. Bush declared as a legislative emergency
the granting of an oil-industry ``hard times'' tax break of up to
$45 million. The bill passed easily, despite Democra
</P>
</TEXT>
