<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1535 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-EDITORIAL-CHILD-MOLES     08-03 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHILD-MOLESTATION-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmakers should look into lax notification about sex offenders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In theory, the United States has an ironclad system of keeping
tabs of sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Howard Thompson. He's not a theory. He's a sex offender who
moved into Waco, Texas while on probation in Georgia, and resumed
his heinous activities.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, it couldn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Only when he was convicted last month of three counts of
aggravated sexual assault of a child and one count of indecency
with a child _ these being children he and his wife baby-sat at a
Waco motel _ did local officials find out they should have been
watching him.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson nine years ago was convicted on three counts of child
molestation in Brunswick, Ga., and given 10 years unsupervised
probation. Effectively, Brunswick washed its hands of him, ordered
him to get out of a five-county judicial circuit and stay away for
10 years. Presto: No longer Brunswick's problem. Change-o: Now
others' problem.
</P>
<P>
   Since policies would have required notification, it is unclear
why Georgia failed to tell Texas about Thompson's relocation. It is
the least that a state could do.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is serving a 20-year prison term in Texas now after he
and his wife Mary Lou were convicted separately. She was sentenced
to three years in prison on a count of indecency with a child.
</P>
<P>
   Had McLennan County officials been notified about Thompson's
previous conviction, his comfort zone would have been diminished
considerably. He might even have steered clear of young people
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Probation officials in Georgia say the problem behind Thompson's
under-the-radar cross-county trip wasn't one of a too-lenient
sentence but the fact that procedures which should have applied _
requiring notification of any new state in which the sex offender
were to reside _ weren't followed.
</P>
<P>
   It seems, however, that at least one jurisdiction thought it
could resolve a terrible problem by sweeping one bad dude out its
door.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, Texas and all states have a compact to notify each
other about convicted sex offenders changing address. In this case
it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Texas Interstate Compact for the Supervision
of Probationers and Parolees, which handles these matters, say it
happens far too often _ sex offenders taking up residence out of
the state in which they were convicted without their new neighbors
knowing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it happens after a probationer gets a travel permit
and decides not to return home.
</P>
<P>
   This should concern everyone, certainly elected officials at the
state and federal levels. A convicted sex offender on probation
should not have the run of the country. Florida essentially
prohibits someone like Thompson from leaving the state.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's compact administrators are writing new policies to
tighten up procedures and better enforce policies about
notification. This will require the cooperation of participating
legislatures, and possibly Congress' leaning on all the players to
get their acts together.
</P>
<P>
   This also will require measures to get judges' attention about
their responsibilities in keeping track of sex offenders like
Thompson, or to blunt the dumping of offenders onto other states.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, he evaded the best-laid plans. In reality, the system
was full of holes, resulting in the worst-case scenario: Convicted
sex offender Howard Thompson was back in business once he crossed
the Texas state line.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
