<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-COLUMN0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traffic-only police might be the answer to slaughter on roads
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tragic and senseless. Understandable, but inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   I am referring to two recent events: the tragic death of a
rookie Atlanta policeman who was mowed down by a driver while in
the act of doing his job and the teenage driver and Transportation
Department personnel who were hit by a driver using the emergency
lane as a passing lane.
</P>
<P>
   Tragic goes without explanation. Senseless is also simple. None
of these deaths needed to happen. Had the drivers of the other
vehicles been acting in a responsible and legal manner, they would
not.
</P>
<P>
   It is the senselessness of these accidents that make them
inexcusable. They happened because someone consciously made a
decision to circumvent the rules and as a result, inflicted bodily
harm on others.
</P>
<P>
   Understandable? Sadly true. You only have to take one trip
around metro Atlanta to see enough outrageous behavior on our
roadways to last you a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember commenting on my first trip to New York City that
the city wasted all the money it spent on the paint for lane
markers because no one pays any attention to them. That comment has
come home to haunt me.
</P>
<P>
   Many, if not most, Atlanta drivers are now guilty of the same
thing. How many times have you been stopped at an intersection,
only to have the vehicle behind you pull around you on the shoulder
of the road? Heaven forbid they might have to wait a few seconds to
continue their progress.
</P>
<P>
   Will making left-hand turns from the far right lane, like New
York taxi drivers, become accepted practice? Circumventing
intersections through shopping center parking lots seems to have
become standard procedure.
</P>
<P>
   It is appalling that drivers are out of control. Road rage,
people passing in the emergency lane _ where will it all end? Or,
more importantly, how do we try to resolve this situation?
</P>
<P>
   The simple answer would be the police.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, I don't see that as the complete solution. First, there
just aren't enough law enforcement officers available to react to
the volume of offending drivers. When I see incidents like the guy
driving alone in the HOV lane recently and passing a police officer
who couldn't have cared less, I realize that law enforcement has
now become a prioritized situation.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line, they are going to put out big fires before little
fires. Or they are going to engage in traffic enforcement that
produces the most revenue first. These outrageous and senseless
acts that can potentially lead to the loss of innocent people's
lives need to carry a more substantial penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Would you think more seriously about driving in the HOV lane
alone if the fine were $1,000? What about passing in the emergency
lane? Is $1,000 enough, or should it be more?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we are now back to how we enforce these laws. Perhaps
we need to look at a new level of police, traffic police. These
officers would not work burglary or homicide; their only domain
would be watching our roadways.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that if we enacted fines that really got the
public's attention, it wouldn't take long before not only could we
potentially curtail much of this out-of-control behavior but also
produce a tidy little revenue source?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
