<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1540 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-THE-MECHANIC0804-COX     08-03 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lungs' of vehicles work hard to save yours
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last week, a student asked me what I thought was the
single most important pollution control device on any passenger
vehicle. Without hesitation, I mentioned the catalytic converter.
</P>
<P>
   I elaborated on my statement with a little history about the
whys and wherefores that have brought the internal combustion
engine to its current ``almost emission-friendly'' condition.
</P>
<P>
   Since my indoctrination into the automotive repair profession, I
have seen many pollution control devices come and go, giving way to
more sophisticated systems. The catalytic converter, with only one
improvement to its initial concept, has remained a steadfast
component of the exhaust system for over a quarter of a century.
</P>
<P>
   Long before complex computer controls, fuel injection and
electronic ignition systems, the cat was working its little heart
out to clean up exhaust byproducts produced by the engine. And for
all of its hard work, what kind of appreciation does it get? It's
frequently blamed for poor performance, putrid smells, melted
carpets, grass fires and just about anything else from transmission
slippage to poor mileage.
</P>
<P>
   The catalytic converter is really a marvelous creature. It has
the ability and the capacity (about three football fields worth of
active surface area) to breathe in exhaust gases from the engine,
chemically change or ``catalyze'' the nitrous oxides (or NOx),
hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide, and breathe out carbon dioxide
and water.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there are two kinds of cats, but both work on the
principle of absorbing, storing and releasing gases. The single-bed
converter, which dates to the beginning, controls hydrocarbons and
carbon monoxide, rendering a much lower amount of those gases along
with harmful NOx and harmless carbon dioxide and water. The
development of the three-way converter enabled the reduction of NOx
by incorporating a separate front chamber of different material.
</P>
<P>
   Usually both the reduction and the oxidation chambers are housed
inside one shell. However, some vehicle manufacturers use a small,
separate NOx reduction cat mounted before the oxidation cat. Either
way, they work the same. The exhaust gas first undergoes a cooling
NOx reduction before the hot oxidation. Oxygen is absorbed and
stored in the catalyst's membrane, then released as needed to
complete the chemical process.
</P>
<P>
   When not subjected to prolonged engine abnormalities such as
misfires, excessive or insufficient fuel quantities, coolant or oil
contamination, the cat can function efficiently for years. But if
it is abused, often giving a warning by way of an illuminated light
on the dash, it will suffocate and die.
</P>
<P>
   At best, the vehicle will continue to run OK, but the cat will
be unable to convert and clean up the exhaust gasses. At worst, the
inside of the cat will break apart, melt or plug up, causing an
exhaust restriction. In fact, 1996-and-newer vehicles have an
onboard diagnostic system that monitors catalytic converter
efficiency. If the computer ``sees'' that the cat is being damaged,
it will turn on the malfunction indicator light on the dash.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a medical person, but it seems to me that a catalytic
converter works a lot like our lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Breathe in. What is happening? Oxygen is going into your lungs.
It is being stored to be used by your body. Breathe out. You are
exhaling carbon dioxide and water. What happens when this process
is contaminated by the inhalation of abnormal air, not containing
enough oxygen? Inhaling chemical fumes, smoke and pollution can
cause lung damage.
</P>
<P>
   The length of time and amount of toxins consumed equate to the
severity of the injury to your respiratory system. Are your lungs
the cause or the victim of mistreatment? Don't blame your cat. It's
only trying to clean up what is delivered to it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
