<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX     08-03 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP's white-cell count barely masked by convention charade
 &HT;    By JOHN YOUNG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's times like these when those blessed with cable options give
thanks for A&AMP;E, the Discovery Channel and Animal Planet.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, for instance. She surfed upon a scene of African
children in grass skirts scampering across a stage. Jabbing the
remote, she bolted before realizing it was actually about Africans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' she said, ``I thought it was the Republican National
Convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy mistake, thanks to a unique seating arrangement at the
Philadelphia convention: everyone with white skin in a delegate's
chair, everyone non-white on stage in a speaking role, except for
those in janitorial roles.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about the Democrats and a president stalked by
the definition of ``is.'' At least when the Dems get together they
convey diversity without hiring the Broadway cast of ``Porgy and
Bess.''
</P>
<P>
   There are lies and there are damned lies. This portrait of
diversity is the damnedest lie. Covering the 1992 GOP convention in
Houston, I wrenched my neck on the case of the missing black
Republicans. The party-controlled big screens at the Astrodome kept
on showing blacks waving banners and wearing silly hats. But none
could be found by my eye. Finally I spotted two. I realized that
the camera wasn't showing a lot of black Republicans, just the same
ones over and over.
</P>
<P>
   They were like the Japanese pilot whose actual cockpit footage
got him shown over and over in World War II movies, always
spiraling into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Black-white photos
</P>
<P>
   Has anybody seen J.C. Watts lately? Dumb question.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to photo opportunities, the black Oklahoma
congressman is the Republicans' most valuable player. At Oklahoma
U. he played QB. Now, aside from congressman, he plays DB whenever
possible, DB for designated black.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, watch how often George Bush will have a
black individual positioned behind him on a stage when cameras
click. In Texas, the black most likely to appear will be Michael
Williams, a Bush pal from Midland who got an administration job in
Washington and then got appointed to the Texas Railroad Commission.
Williams shows that George W. is not the only one who owes a
political career to knowing just the right people.
</P>
<P>
   More than transparent
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bush gets credit for trying to put on a show of diversity
that reflects the nation he seeks to govern. The alarming fact
remains, however, that this major political party, at its base,
reflects bare tokens of a nation's cultural richness.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made modest inroads of support among Hispanics in
Texas, but nationwide he has to buck a party history that has mined
anti-immigrant passions and used ``English-only'' as a wedge issue.
</P>
<P>
   Education? The party line still seeks to demonize inner-city
public schools. With school vouchers, it reflects a white-flight
mentality which says to minorities, ``Come, flee with me.''
</P>
<P>
   All is added, in minorities' eyes, to a history of opposing
civil rights legislation and now making affirmative action a
villain, rather than acknowledging the disparities that remain in
every strata of business and governance. These disparities are self
evident at such a national convention.
</P>
<P>
   That is why a lingering image from a past GOP convention, for
me, comes from aboard a bus of all-white conventioneers returning
to their hotel. Up beside them momentarily pulled a city bus filled
with all the kinds of people who had cooked the meals, vacuumed the
rooms and made the beds.
</P>
<P>
   Then the buses split up, one bound for the expressway, one for
dark street corners down the line. The regulars and the hired help
had done their part for one more national made-for-TV event.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
