<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LASORDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LASORDA LOOKS FORWARD TO LEADING U.S. OLYMPIC BASEBALL SQUAD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID KING  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The jerseys will say ```USA'' on them, but make no
mistake _ this year's U.S. Olympic baseball squad will be Tommy
Lasorda's team.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball USA, the governing body for the sport, knew what it was
getting
</P>
<P>
   when it chose the Hall of Famer as its manager. His colorful
personality
</P>
<P>
   will overwhelm those of his players, who will be chosen from
retired
</P>
<P>
   major-leaguers and current minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest thing I will ever do,'' Lasorda said soon
after
</P>
<P>
   getting his new assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bigger than the Dodgers. It's bigger than the World
Series. It's
</P>
<P>
   bigger than any playoff game, and I've managed in 63 playoff
games. This
</P>
<P>
   is a chance to do something for my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Big talk from a man who bleeds Dodger blue, even after a heart
ailment
</P>
<P>
   forced him to retire as the team's manager in 1996. Lasorda, a
senior vice
</P>
<P>
   president of the club, has been affiliated with the Dodgers as a
player,
</P>
<P>
   coach, manager or executive for 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   With Lasorda in the dugout, Los Angeles won two world
championships,
</P>
<P>
   four National League pennants and eight division titles. His
teams won
</P>
<P>
   1,599 games. And, as with everything else he does, Lasorda will
approach
</P>
<P>
   the Olympics with passion and more than a fair amount of
bluster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we're not planning on going 6,000 miles to lose,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His job won't be easy. This is the first Olympics that will
allow
</P>
<P>
   professional baseball players to compete, but no major-league
players will
</P>
<P>
   be leaving their teams in the final weeks of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Former baseball executives Bob Watson and Bill Bavasi, along
with
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, will choose a team from a pool of 533 minor-leaguers
and retired big-leaguers. And in just about a month's time, Lasorda
will have
</P>
<P>
   to turn the group into a team. An announcement on the squad will
be made
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will convene in San Diego on Sept. 1 and leave for
a
</P>
<P>
   series of exhibitions and workouts in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda's team will be taking on the best from around the world.
The
</P>
<P>
   Japan League is suspending its season to allow its best players
to take
</P>
<P>
   part in the Olympics, and Cuba is building another strong team
after
</P>
<P>
   struggling in recent international competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have played a part in developing another challenger,
</P>
<P>
   Australia. Los Angeles has been in the forefront of signing and
developing
</P>
<P>
   players from the host country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba is going to be tough; Japan is going to be tough,''
Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   Players must pass stringent Olympics chemical testing. Along
with
</P>
<P>
   performance-enhancing drugs, the International Olympic Committee
also bans
</P>
<P>
   a number of substances contained in over-the-counter sinus
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said he did not have any reservations about taking on
</P>
<P>
   the job, no matter the circumstances. Since leaving the Dodgers'
dugout, he has spent the last four years traveling _ he makes more
than 100 speeches a year,
</P>
<P>
   scouts and evaluates Dodgers minor-leaguers and circles the
world
</P>
<P>
   spreading the gospel of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new challenge for me,'' he said of the Olympic job.
``I was
</P>
<P>
   enjoying what I was doing, but I'm looking forward to this, too
I've still got that fire in my belly, too. You give me players with
any kind of ability, and I'll do my best with 'em.''
</P>
</TEXT>
