<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PUBLISHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDOM HOUSE TO ESTABLISH EXCLUSIVELY DIGITAL WING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stepping up the race to stake out territory in the new world of
digital books, Random House, the largest U.S. trade publisher,
plans Sunday to announce the creation of a new purely digital
imprint.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in January, the house will publish under the name
AtRandom a list of about 20 purely digital books, by authors
ranging from the editor of Harper's magazine to a downtown
dominatrix. All will be sold online as electronic books or in
single copies printed on demand, but they will not be shipped to
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Random House becomes the second major house to begin a digital
imprint, following Time Warner Trade Publishing, which this spring
created a digital imprint of its own, iPublish.com.
</P>
<P>
   All the biggest New York publishing houses are now moving
quickly to prepare for the possibility that digital books will soon
take off. Over lunches at Michael's, the Four Seasons and other
industry hubs, editors are quietly courting agents and authors,
trying to sign deals for the digital rights to their new and
previously published books.
</P>
<P>
   As they acquire new titles, they are beginning to establish the
rules of digital publishing, from authors' royalties to the prices
consumers will pay. In many cases, especially for brand name
authors and older contracts, authors' agents have retained digital
rights. For publishers, that means there is a vast pool of
potentially profitable literary properties waiting to be claimed,
sometimes from another house's list. Time Warner, for example, will
publish the electronic versions of several books by the science
writer, James Gleick, previously published in hardcover by Random
House's Pantheon imprint.
</P>
<P>
   Both Random House and Time Warner are hoping to build their
reputations as desirable places for authors to publish digitally,
much the way places like Random House's sister imprint Vintage are
prestigious names to appear under in paperback.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the book business wonder why the rush. Even Ann Godoff,
president and publisher of Random House Trade Group and creator of
the digital imprint, admitted that she had not yet managed to enjoy
reading a book off a screen, or read a whole electronic book.
Neither has almost anyone else in the industry. Many others,
meanwhile, worry that online copyright protection is open to
question.
</P>
<P>
   Print-on-demand books, though roughly comparable in appearance
to trade paperbacks, remain expensive to produce. Lightning Source,
a company that provides the service to publishers, charges a
publisher $4.80 to produce a single copy of a 300-page book, which
is more expensive than traditional printing except in handling
titles that sell fewer than 1,000 copies a year.
</P>
<P>
   But many publishers have high expectations for the profits from
the new digital books. Laurence Kirshbaum, chairman of Time Warner
Trade Publishing, says selling electronic books will boost the
industry's annual growth rate from single to double digits.
Microsoft Corp. will release a new version of its electronic book
reader next week, the first version for reading on desktop and
laptop computers as well as on expensive hand-held devices.
Publishers say the company has estimated that 2 million people will
download free copies in the first two weeks. Dick Brass,
Microsoft's vice president of technology development, believes that
the market for electronic books will exceed $1 billion in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the brave new world we want to see,'' said Godoff at
Random House. ``No printing, no paper and binding, no need for a
sales conference or printed catalog _ we don't know the size of the
market, but it could be potentially very profitable for us.'' She
has particularly high hopes for print-on-demand technology, because
it enables publishers to profitably publish low-selling new and old
titles with narrow readerships, and it obviates the risk of holding
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Karp, vice president and senior editor at the Random
House Trade Group, will head the new imprint. He said he began this
spring approaching authors and agents about signing all-electronic
contracts for new books, swearing each one to secrecy and revealing
none of the other writers' names. Many have verbal agreements but
no formal contracts yet.
</P>
<P>
   Karp said he acquired the rights to projects he thought suited
the medium. ``The Quest to End Baldness'' by the New York Post
columnist, Gersh Kuntzman, and ``Mistress Ruby Ties It Together''
by Robin Shamburg, a dominatrix who also writes a column for
NYPress, may work better in electronic form because they can be
bought and read in private without the embarrassment of taking them
to a cashier. Others will be collections of previously published
magazine articles by Harper's editor, Lewis Lapham, and the writers
Tad Friend and Donald Katz. Such collections do not sell many
copies in paper, but the low volumes make sense in electronic form,
and new material might be added to the collections over time. Some
will be as short as the equivalent of about 150 pages; others, such
as the collections, as long as 300-page books.
</P>
<P>
   At least one of Random House's new electronic titles is a
full-length novel, ``Because She is Beautiful,'' by Cameron Dougan,
a first-time author. ``I couldn't be more flattered,'' he said.
``It doesn't matter if it is hardcover or paperback or downloaded
if it's getting attention and people are recommending it to their
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Other titles include ``The Secret of Life,'' a book of advice
from Elizabeth Wurtzel, author of ``Prozac Nation,'' and ``Walking
On Ice,'' a biography of the hockey player Mark Messier by Meredith
Berkman, a magazine writer.
</P>
<P>
   Random House will sell its digital books through online
booksellers and other organizations' Web sites. The house plans to
sell the books for about the price of a typical trade paperback,
for a little less in electronic form and a little more in
print-on-demand. It will pay authors royalties on electronic books
of about 15 percent of the price _ about the same as a hardcover
royalty rate. On print-on-demand titles, authors will receive 7.5
percent of the price, about the same as on a trade paperback.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Random House also plans to publish digitally a
hundred titles from its Modern Library imprint of classic titles.
Some sets of several books, like the volumes of Marcel Proust's
``In Search of Lost Time'' or the complete works of Jane Austen,
will be sold together as single bundles.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Random House, Time Warner, which includes Little, Brown
and Warner Books, will sell its electronic books from its own Web
site as well as through online bookstores. Most of its new print
books will also appear in electronic editions, as well as a handful
of new digital books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our digital business will allow us to expand beyond the
best-seller focus of the major chains,'' said Gregory Voynow,
general manager of iPublish.com, explaining that in chains titles
that sell in high-volumes are likely to get the most attention.
``This will allow us to have more control over our own destiny,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, both publishers said, will allow the marketing of
books directly to likely readers on Web sites that reflect their
interests, and letting them download an electronic book with a
click.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner also plans initially to discount its electronic
books aggressively, charging about $7 or less for electronic
versions of some books. Time Warner will also offer its authors a
potentially higher royalty rate, about 25 percent of the
publisher's net revenue, including income from any licensing or
other deals.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers and agents involved agree that the ultimate digital
royalty rates and book prices remain to be seen, along with the
extent of demand for electronic books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, sure, a 15 percent royalty rate, but it can't be
precedent-setting,'' said Amanda Urban, agent for Tad Friend. ``The
publicity attendant on this will compensate for the low advance,
and collections of reprinted journalism are hard to get published
today anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But other agents are already putting up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``These publishers are trying to divide up the new digital world
before we have even mapped it out,'' said Robert Gottlieb, an agent
at the William Morris Agency. ``It is like Antarctica. They have
landed and they are saying it's theirs. There is a tremendous
reduction in overhead from printing, distribution and all of that,
and authors aren't enjoying the benefits of the increased
profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-30-00 2132EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
