<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1585 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-03 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONVENTIONAL WISDOM ISN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend noted that the chairs and the walls at the Republican
National
</P>
<P>
   Convention are red and blue. He said, ``I guess the delegates
provide the white.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to take his word for it, although having been to
Republican
</P>
<P>
   conventions before, I'm pretty sure he was right about the white
part.
</P>
<P>
   All I've seen of this year's convention is five minutes of Tom
Brokaw
</P>
<P>
   opening the NBC evening news by saying, essentially, that the
convention
</P>
<P>
   is a tightly stage-managed non-news event where absolutely
nothing would
</P>
<P>
   happen. NBC had no prime-time coverage of this non-news.
</P>
<P>
   Then why were Brokaw and 15,000 other journalists in
Philadelphia? Why
</P>
<P>
   was the convention the lead story? Why should anyone pay any
attention at
</P>
<P>
   all?
</P>
<P>
   Like most Americans, I haven't watched any of what little
coverage
</P>
<P>
   there has been of the convention during ABC's and CBS' grudging
7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   convention hours. There are real things to watch, like
``Frasier''reruns
</P>
<P>
   and ``Entertainment Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Many conventions ago, political managers decided to take all the
</P>
<P>
   messiness out of conventions so they'd look good on TV. Thus
conventions
</P>
<P>
   became as interesting as one of those videos of a fireplace,
without the
</P>
<P>
   fire.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, I did watch something real about the fake convention, a
few
</P>
<P>
   minutes of ``Politically Incorrect,''a show which tries to find
pointed
</P>
<P>
   humor in pointless and unfunny modern conventions. Host Bill
Maher
</P>
<P>
   expressed amazement at all the African Americans the Republicans
managed
</P>
<P>
   to find to put on stage Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The headline in The San Francisco Examiner was funnier than
Maher, saying, ``GOP puts on new face.'' Two words: Al Jolson.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was inclusion night, in which the Republicans (whose
delegates
</P>
<P>
   are 83 percent white and 20 percent millionaires) brought on
Colin Powell
</P>
<P>
   and the Temptations to convince the nation that the GOP is the
party of
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln and not the party of the Lincoln Town Car.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's theme was military readiness, but I wasn't ready to
listen
</P>
<P>
   to speeches about the need to spend billions on anti-missile
systems to
</P>
<P>
   stop an ICBM fired by some Dr. No from his rogue island.
</P>
<P>
   The History Channel had a special on the U.S. Mint, which would
have to
</P>
<P>
   work overtime to keep up with Republican military proposals. So
I watched
</P>
<P>
   that instead.
</P>
<P>
   Where's that fireplace video?
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the Republicans' military experts are better at
targeting
</P>
<P>
   missiles than audiences. I'm a member of the target audience for
the
</P>
<P>
   Republican convention and they've completely missed me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm unhappy with the Clinton-Gore administration and would like
to see
</P>
<P>
   a more compassionate Republicanism. I'm highly likely to vote
and I'm a
</P>
<P>
   political junkie. So how come I'm not watching their show?
</P>
<P>
   Because you can watch the same ``Frasier'' episode over and over
again.
</P>
<P>
   But you have to be handcuffed to a chair to get through more
than five
</P>
<P>
   minutes of convention coverage. There hasn't been a good
convention since
</P>
<P>
   1972, when they were brawls.
</P>
<P>
   The best in my memory was in 1968, when there were riots outside
and
</P>
<P>
   inside the convention hall. The whole world was watching because
it had a
</P>
<P>
   reason to watch.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, protesters and police in Philadelphia finally got it
</P>
<P>
   together to create some telegenic action. Protesters blocked
streets and
</P>
<P>
   police raided a puppet factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come out, with all of your tiny little hands up.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, that I'd watch, but I found my fireplace video.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a political junkie, but political conventions as presented
on and for
</P>
<P>
   TV are very low-quality junk. Even junkies have standards.
</P>
<P>
   How do I get my information? I read newspapers, a medium often
called
</P>
<P>
   obsolete, but still not rivaled in its ability to be skimmed.
When I see a
</P>
<P>
   picture of some delegates in hats trying to boogie on the
convention
</P>
<P>
   floor, I can quickly flip to the comics before the onset of
nausea.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators criticized the major networks for their
incomplete
</P>
<P>
   coverage of the convention. Tom Shales, the TV critic for the
Washington
</P>
<P>
   Post, said networks ``displayed bad citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean they'd be good citizens if they showed every bit
of
</P>
<P>
   bunting, every filmed tribute and every contrived speech on
strength,
</P>
<P>
   compassion and doing it for the children?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, the modern convention is a sham meant to deceive the
public. If
</P>
<P>
   networks were good citizens, they wouldn't show conventions at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the public isn't watching.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans aren't the only ones who produce infomercials
and call
</P>
<P>
   them conventions. They're just better at it than the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   You can't tell me that Barbara is going to boost the ratings of
Al and
</P>
<P>
   Tipper. The only thing that might work is that the West Coast
has better
</P>
<P>
   rioters than the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason I'll watch the Democratic convention is because
I'll be
</P>
<P>
   there, and it'll be unavoidable. Fortunately, 14,999 other
journalists
</P>
<P>
   will be there, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's the real convention, getting together to eat, drink and
complain
</P>
<P>
   about how bad conventions have become.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
