<HEADLINE>
IBM CHIEF RECALLS DIFFICULT DAYS  
 ALLTEL EXPANDS TO LOUISIANA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In hindsight, success tends to look easy, even predictable.
That's as true in business as it is in sports, politics or other
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Yet things often look decidedly more unnerving from the vantage
point of the executive on the firing line. The company might just
as easily perish as prosper.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy interview last week, Louis V. Gerstner Jr., the
chairman of IBM, talked mostly about a management reorganization
that the company announced on Monday. But Gerstner, who is often
portrayed as blunt, gruff and seemingly arrogant, also candidly
described his early, uncertain days at IBM _ when he arrived as an
outsider suddenly in charge of a corporation that was both an
American icon and a business in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   After he took over in 1993, Gerstner ran the company for over a
year in a style he called ``survival mode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to cut $9 billion a year in expenses. We had to bring
the company back, literally, from the brink of death. We had to
deal with cultural and personal tragedies that resulted. And we had
to reassert that we were for real in the marketplace. That was a
very centralized, personalized leadership and organizational style.
It was focused on the short term, and it was very intuitive. There
wasn't a lot of time to study things. There was not a lot of time
to debate things.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it was a benevolent dictatorship with me as the dictator
and hoping _ just hoping _ that I was getting some good advice from
my colleagues who knew a heck of a lot more about IBM and this
industry than I would ever know.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR
</P>
<P>
   Alltel Expands to Louisiana
</P>
<P>
   Alltel Corp., the United States' fifth-largest wireless
communications carrier, is expected to announce Monday the
acquisition of wireless operations in Louisiana from SBC
Communications for about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Alltel, which is based in Little Rock,
Ark., expects to gain about 165,000 wireless customers and 300,000
paging customers in New Orleans and Baton Rouge. The transaction
also includes rural services in Iberville, St. James and
Plaquemines parishes.
</P>
<P>
   SBC is selling the properties to eliminate overlap resulting
from the linking of its wireless operations with BellSouth's.
Alltel, which already has about 6 million wireless subscribers in
22 states, is trying to expand its presence along the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike some other companies in this industry we're interested
in buying and not being bought,'' Joe Ford, Alltel's chief
executive, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the wireless industry in the United States has been
gripped by acquisition fever, most recently with Deutsche Telekom's
planned acquisition of VoiceStream Wireless Corp. for over $50
billion, which was announced last week. But Alltel, larger than
VoiceStream though still a relatively small wireless player, has
been strangely absent from the speculative talk on which wireless
companies will be the next takeover targets.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, companies like Nextel Communications, of Reston, Va., a
provider of wireless services for corporate customers, and
Powertel, a consumer-oriented wireless company based in Statesboro,
Ga., have been mentioned as likelier consolidation candidates.
</P>
<P>
   That may reflect the low profile of Alltel, which has made more
than 250 landline and wireless acquisitions since it began as a
local telephone company in Arkansas in 1947. The company has
typically focused on rural areas and relatively small metropolitan
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world is looking at wireless now, but we've been in
this business for a long time now,'' said Ford. ``We're happy to
keep blending together other companies into our own because that's
just what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   _ SIMON ROMERO
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-30-00 2104EDT &QL;
