 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Daring vacationer enjoys initial experience with Webvan
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I'm on vacation this week. As a high-profile sort of a
guy, my vacations are probably different from yours. It goes with
the territory of being a public figure and living in the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   This year for vacation I bought some tires for my 1991 Nissan.
But I didn't stop there. I also tried something new. After all,
vacations are the time to step outside the usual.
</P>
<P>
   So I tried Webvan. I used the online service that lets you order
groceries over the Web and then have them delivered to your door.
</P>
<P>
   I'll pause for a second and let your thumping heart get its
rhythm back and then tell you what that was like.
</P>
<P>
   My friends and co-workers will tell you that I am not wildly
experimental (I still find ATMs slightly frightening, but I believe
they will catch on) and _ maybe because I've worked for newspapers
for many years _ I can be a little cynical.
</P>
<P>
   So despite all the glowing press reports about the service and
even the praise I'd heard from some friends, I did not go into this
with a glad heart.
</P>
<P>
   But I was determined to try it, so I logged on at www.webvan
.com to set up an account. It was actually pretty easy, but I
figured that the real test would be in the ordering.
</P>
<P>
   The whole notion of Webvan makes me dizzy. Here you have a
company that sells groceries for about the same price as you'd pay
at the store, throws in free delivery and also gives you (for now
at least) $15 off on your first order.
</P>
<P>
   It either has to be run by the tooth fairy or a bunch of guys
with black shirts and white ties. So I was looking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, I didn't find any. Ordering was fairly easy, and I'm
pretty sure it will get easier in the future now that I understand
more about how it works. You use a series of menus to find your
items. The menus start with broad categories. For instance, there's
one called produce, another for meat and seafood, still another for
prepared food _ and they get progressively more specific. For
instance, if you click on the meat and seafood category, you get
new categories that include beef, ham, pork, etc. Click on those
subcategories, and things get even more specific.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as is my habit, I'd get confused and search for an
item in the wrong category. (Hey, I'm a guy.) That's when the
search feature came in handy. You can type in a specific product _
say garlic _ and find it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Once you find your item, you simply indicate how many of the
item you want and continue shopping. I finished ordering $100 worth
of groceries in about 10 minutes. Then I proceeded to check out.
Unlike at the regular grocery, I did not have to stand in line and
wait while the cashier told the customer ahead of me about the
first three decades of her life. Instead, you give a credit card
number and select a delivery time.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike scheduling the time for the cable guy to come to your
house, these are scheduled in 30-minute increments and _ both in my
experience and that of my friends _ that's when the Webvan folks
actually show up.
</P>
<P>
   My groceries arrived right on time the next day. The vegetables
and fruit looked like they should be on the cover of a food
catalog. The steaks were terrific. And it all _ including the
20-pound bag of cat litter _ was carried right into my kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't technology grand?
</P>
<P>
   What a terrific vacation. Maybe next year I'll do something
really wild and get the carpets steam-cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
