 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Photo e-mail isn't difficult
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Can you tell me how to e-mail a photo? I can get the photo on my
monitor, but the recipient can't call it up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Sholtis, Jupiter, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: You scanned the photo onto your hard drive. Half the battle
is won. Check some things before sending. First is file type. Some
photo file types include JPEG, TIFF, and EPSF. We suggest JPEG,
which compresses your photo.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Next is file size. Make sure it isn't huge. Some e-mail
systems don't accept large files (depends on the ISP), or your
e-mail system may strip a large file as it leaves the mail server.
It's best to use a compression program before sending. PC users can
use PKWare's PKZip or WinZip. For Mac users, DropStuff. Find the
shareware programs at www.zdnet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Once you check file type and file size, you're ready to
send. Start an e-mail message. Pop in the recipient's address.
Depending on your e-mail program, you should have an attachment
button on the message interface. If not, look for the word
``Attach'' under one of the pull-down menus. A window will pop up
asking where the item is you want to attach. Navigate to your photo
and double-click. The photo attaches to the e-mail. Write a message
and click Send.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   I plan to buy a Zip drive. I can't decide if I should buy an
external or internal model. Help.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ronald Harrison, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: You obviously need more storage space, a backup strategy
or a way to transfer data. Maybe all three. Ask the question, ``Is
portability important?''
</P>
<P>
   Sue: If it is, an external Zip storage drive is attractive
because it's easy to tote around, slick and easy to install.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Zip drives are popular, and they've been around.
Compatibility won't be an issue. You shouldn't have trouble
swapping disks for work or play.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Find out how your computer would interface with an external
storage drive. Like everything now, drives come in all flavors.
Interface terms such as USB, SCSI and parallel port may sound like
a string of Greek, but they are important. A tool called zip
configurator at www.iomega.com/zip/configurator/index.html can help
you match your computer with a compatible drive.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Also, think about what and how much you'll be storing.
Are you interested in a 100-MB drive? A 250-MB drive?
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Costs for external Zip drives range from $87 to $135 at
CNet Shopper (shopper.cnet.com/).
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: If drive portability isn't an issue, then an internal Zip
may fit the bill. At www.dealtime.com you'll see internal Zip
drives for $85 to $180. If you're not a do-it-your-selfer, plan on
an installation fee.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
