<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOOLS0801-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Freeware program SoomSoom a unique way to keep track of files
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Behold SoomSoom.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not another panda, nor is it a menu item at your local
Thai pad.
</P>
<P>
   What it is, is software. Free software.
</P>
<P>
   Free software is often more expensive than the price would
indicate, but SoomSoom does a little better than that. It has an
interesting premise and fulfills it fairly well, although not as
magically as its advance notice would have you think.
</P>
<P>
   SoomSoom's publicity billed it as the ``first-ever
name-recognition software,'' whatever that might mean, but it
doesn't recognize anything without instructions.
</P>
<P>
   It's intended for those of us who are forever losing files,
forgetting what we called them, unable even to remember a single
unusual word in them for which to search.
</P>
<P>
   SoomSoom serves as an interface between the user and Microsoft
Word, NotePad, WordPad Excel and other major applications installed
in the computer, as well as the Internet. It has its own e-mail
program and a Web browser based on Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   It's also an address book, which one uses to make sure SoomSoom
can locate files. Let's say you correspond with a fellow named
Otto. First thing you do is set up an address book page for Otto.
It can be quite extensive, but all it really needs is his name.
</P>
<P>
   When you want to write a letter to him or write something about
him, you select the New Document from the menu bar. This gives you
a dialogue box from which you choose the program you'll use to
create the file, name the file and put down the subject, which in
this case would be ``Otto.''
</P>
<P>
   Then whatever program you have selected comes up full screen,
you complete the document and save it wherever you wish. Returning
to SoomSoom's screen, you'll see the document listed when you
select Otto.
</P>
<P>
   One could, of course, accomplish the same thing in other ways,
such as creating a separate subdirectory named Otto. But that's so
pedestSoomSoom's mail program runs well enough, although it's not
nearly as fast at bringing in the mail as Eudora Pro.
</P>
<P>
   Considering its price, SoomSoom works well. It has the silly
rough edges that seem almost obligatory in freeware _ aggravating
misspellings on its screen, awkward phrases or usages that bespeak
an origin outside English and little mechanical things that don't
work as expected.
</P>
<P>
   In the e-mail program, for instance, you cannot delete an entire
batch of messages; it has to be done one at a time. When you get a
couple of hundred a day, that's not an option.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions are all on-board, festooned with exclamation
marks and not at all extensive.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, what's this SoomSoom name? Knowing that inquiring
minds would want to know, I asked. The answer was that SoomSoom is
the result of ``name-oriented computing, in which everything begins
and ends with a name.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. You can go to www.soomsoom.com, download the program
and try it out for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
