<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    DAVE WALKER'S WEB SITE AND MAGAZINE REVIEWS
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER  
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Dave Walker's reviews of a Web site and current
magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   http://liftoff.msfc.nasa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORES: the address has to have the http, and not www)
</P>
<P>
   It's a little complicated to set up, and it requires a
Java-enabled Internet browser. But the Liftoff to Space Exploration
Web site will tell you the best time to run outside, look to the
sky and gawk upon the International Space Station or, as it's known
in some Earthbound circles, Vastly Expensive Space Pork of Dubious
Utility. The site was developed by NASA's Marshall Space Flight
Center in Huntsville, Ala., and generates its data based on
information provided by the North American Aerospace Defense
Command (NORAD). Just plug in your longitude and latitude
coordinates, and, shazam, you're tracking like a big Sirius.
(''Hey, what's that Bob's Big Boy statue doing out there?'') Should
you, for some reason, not know your exact longitude and latitude
coordinates - what are you, lost? - the calculator also works with
ZIP codes. And if the Space Station doesn't turn you on, the site
also tracks Mir and space shuttle missions.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE:
</P>
<P>
   ``GEORGE''
</P>
<P>
   The JFK (Sr.) cover promises a convention primer, and the
interior mostly delivers. Pundits are handicapped, and Jane Hull is
mentioned as someone the GOP could call upon ``when the party wants
to highlight that its state chief executives are not all stern,
White Midwestern men.'' Elsewhere, find star-kissed profiles of
Christie Brinkley (''She's a super model citizen,'' says the
headline) and Tom Selleck. Plus, there's a piece promoting the
barmaid-chic movie (beginitalic)Coyote Ugly (enditalic)as ``the
(beginitalic)Flashdance (enditalic)of the 21st century.'' In a
sidebar, the movie's technical consultant - a former New York City
bottle slinger - advises: ``how to control your man - and blow fire
out of a bottle of Bacardi 151 at the same time.'' Now that's
service journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``ARIZONA HIGHWAYS''
</P>
<P>
   The 75th anniversary celebration continues with a nostalgic
retelling of the time the Soviet Union banned the magazine for
being ``ideologically subversive'' material that ``propagandized
the American way of life.'' It happened in February 1965 - a dark,
chilly season in Moscow, which is not exactly Sun Lakes in the best
of weather - and the Cold War clearly began to turn our way from
that moment on. Denied our fiery sunsets and gentle frontier humor,
the Russians were doomed to lose, (beginitalic)da(enditalic)? The
current issue, a shining salute to the triumph of capitalism,
visits the Chiricahuas, Oak Creek Canyon's West Fork, the Mogollon
Rim and the Navajo Nation's St. Michael's School. Also cool: Ralph
Freso's inside-cover photo of a lightning strike over Phoenix's
Tovrea Castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``REVOLUTION''
</P>
<P>
   Billing itself as ``The New Music Manifesto,'' this fledgling
mag positions itself as an outlet for rave-nation youths
underserved by mainstream music and lifestyle media. Features
within include profiles of musicmakers and gear reviews - content
sure to confuse or frighten everyone over the age of 22 who clings
to the delusion that they remain even remotely hip. The premiere
issue includes two CDs, both of which go heavy on synthetic drum
machines. If you can keep your head from bobbing like the nightclub
guys on (beginitalic)Saturday Night Live(enditalic), the throbbing
tunes, consumed through headphones while faking productivity in
your cubical/drone station, serve as an excellent sonic shield from
aimless co-worker yap. Subscription info: www.getrevolution.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``GQ''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Kournikova, the lobbin' Lolita, puts her hands on her hips,
looks the reader right in the eye - though the chances of
reciprocal eye contact are slim - and says, ``Don't call me
Lolita.'' Oh, OK. Sorry. Won't happen again. Interior fashion
layouts put (male) Olympic athletes in fancy duds and digitally
insert wild animals into shots of handsome chaps wearing garments
made of wild-animal skin. Funny, if you're not an alligator. But
the reason to buy is to read about Joe Queenan's ill-fated goodwill
mission to improve Franco-American relations. The writer applies
himself gamely at first but then takes to asking French citizens if
they feel like traitors for eating at McDonald's and asking
passersby where Jerry Lewis is buried. Funny, if you're not a surly
French person.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-31-00 0814EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1599 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-TV-INTERNET-BOS &LR;      08-03 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TV-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY IS THE OUTLOOK FOR INTERACTIVE TV SO FUZZY? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first interactive TV show debuted back in the 1950s, long
before anyone had ever dreamed of the Internet. It was a cartoon
called ``Winky Dink,'' which allowed the boys and girls at home to
participate by drawing onto a sheet of plastic attached to the set.
The only problem was, you had to have the ``Winky Dink'' kit, which
cost50 cents; more than a few youngsters ended up coloring directly
on the screen, which didn't endear the show to Mom and Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the concept died a fast death.
</P>
<P>
   But now, nearly a half-century later, interactive television is
the talk of the industry. This month, America Online is launching
AOLTV, a service that enables users to send instant messages and
conduct real-time chats on their television screens while watching
their favorite programs. Likewise, Microsoft has announced plans to
update its existing WebTV service to include such functions as
instant replay in addition to its combined television programming
and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial possibilities alone are enough to make the folks
on Madison Avenue salivate. If interactive television fulfills its
potential, viewers could click on a character's sweater, for
instance, and purchase it online. Sports fans could shift the
camera angles of the game or order pizza without having to pick up
the phone. Viewers of an educational documentary about, say,
African elephants could put the program on hold while they surfed
the Net for more information on a particular game preserve. The
ultimate application would be video on demand, signaling the end of
``appointment television.''
</P>
<P>
   All those futuristic features aside, the consensus is this:
Interactive television is an interesting experiment, and it's going
to fail, at least in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Simply put, we like to watch. Period. Over the years,
viewers have developed a seductively passive relationship with the
small screen. They're couch potatoes for a reason; they sit, they
click, they veg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television was the ultimate relationship,'' says Robert
Thompson, professor of film and television at Syracuse University.
``It gave and gave and gave and asked nothing in return.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the folks behind WebTV admit that getting viewers to
abandon such pleasant passivity has been a difficult challenge.
Launched in 1996, the service was touted as the wave of the future;
in four years, just more than 1 million units have been sold,
hardly a critical mass. ``The average American household watches
television seven and a half hours a day, and it's a big challenge
to get them to change their habits,'' says Joe Poletto, vice
president of Microsoft's network media group. ``The biggest change
people have made is to move the refrigerator closer to the couch.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, every experiment with interactivity since the early
days of ``Winky Dink'' has failed or fizzled. In the mid-'90s, Time
Warner Inc. launched something called the Full Service Network in
Orlando, Fla., an ambitious attempt to offer video on demand,
online shopping, and games via a set-top box. The service flopped.
Likewise, other attempts at so-called ``convergence'' of the
Internet and the television have been less than spectacular.
``Homicide'' offered a Web site that complemented the on-air story
line, a clever application but hardly groundbreaking. ``The Drew
Carey Show'' enhanced one episode with a ``live'' Webcast that was
little more than a marketing gimmick. &QL; 
Trying, trying again
</P>
<P>
   So why does AOL think it can succeed where others have failed?
``You simply can't discount our 23 million members,'' says Carlos
Silva, vice president of AOL's product studio.
</P>
<P>
   The new television service, which is being offered in a handful
of pilot markets including Phoenix, Sacramento, and Baltimore (but
not Boston), is part of the company's ``AOL Anywhere'' strategy.
Some of the features are pretty nifty _ particularly for
15-year-olds accustomed to talking on the telephone while drooling
over the latest episode of ``Dawson's Creek.'' Viewers can reduce
the television program to a small window on one side of the screen
while sending e-mail, participating in online chats, or surfing the
Web. AOL members have access to their Internet mail accounts and
buddy lists on the television set. Unlike WebTV, which has a
keyboard with commands that are not all that intuitive, AOLTV is
easy to navigate, with simple pull-down menus that fade away when
they are not being used.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging, of course, is the big draw. But is it enough
to justify the cost? ``Can you imagine a teenager going to a parent
and saying, `I want you to pay $14.95 a month, plus $249 for the
box, so that I can tie up a phone line and chat during my favorite
television program'?'' asks Josh Bernoff, a senior analyst with the
Cambridge-based Forrester Research Inc. ``I don't think the
parent's response would be printable in a family newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for those prices, you ought to be offering more than
that cheerful fellow proclaiming, ``Welcome, you've got mail.''
Both AOLTV and WebTV have a paucity of original content. Granted,
WebTV users can play along with ``Jeopardy'' or ``Wheel of
Fortune,'' but that's pretty much the whole enchilada. And AOLTV
has its own unique channels, but there didn't seem to be much on
them, at least during a recent demonstration at the company's
headquarters in Dulles, Va. The service currently offers
personalized programming from the Weather Channel, enabling viewers
to check the forecast in their own backyard, but that same service
is already available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the chicken-and-egg dilemma. Why should the
networks and cable stations produce expensive interactive
programming for a service that has yet to capture an audience?
WebTV's Silva insists that deals are in the works. ``We are in the
midst of doing all of the brainstorming with our broadcast partners
and coming up with the ideas for the fall,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But think about it. One episode of a half-hour sitcom can cost
more than $10 million to produce; an enhanced version would cost
significantly more, for an uncertain payback and a small potential
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, AOL and Microsoft (along with most major cable
companies) are betting that interactive television will replace the
tube as we know it someday. The current offerings _ the Web sites
that do little more than sell coffee mugs and T-shirts _ are hardly
reinventing the medium, but then again, television originally
mimicked radio before it evolved into a new genre. ``When they
invented television, they literally filmed radio broadcasts, and it
was horrible,'' notes David Card, a senior analyst with Jupiter
Research in New York. ``Milton Berle invented the new form. Well,
we are waiting around for interactive television's Milton Berle.'' &QL; 
Coming to a screen near you
</P>
<P>
   Despite the almost universal criticism of current services, some
analysts predict that the wait won't be that long. According to
Forrester Research, consumers will be spending $9 billion to $10
billion on digital and interactive television services by 2004. And
Jupiter Communications predicts that 15 percent of all US
households will have access to some sort of interactive television
by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But just what form that interactive television will take is
still uncertain; it will probably be some hybrid that combines
video on demand with selective Internet access as well as the same
kind of passive programming available today. ``There is going to be
a middle ground between the futuristic utopia and the reality of
what people want from their leisure time,'' says Thompson. ``I
don't want to be a Luddite and say we're all going to sit around
and watch reruns of `Mr. Ed.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, who is going to fork out the money to be the
guinea pigs for Microsoft, AOL, and the cable companies? To begin,
there are the gadget geeks, the early adopters who simply have to
have every new electronics device that comes on the market. The
irony with AOLTV, though, is that the service is designed for the
company's middle-of-the-road users; it's not sophisticated enough
to satisfy the folks who now own better global positioning systems
than the federal government does.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company has a vested interest in improving
the product. When its planned merger with Time Warner goes through,
the communications conglomerate will own the pipes that bring both
the Internet and cable television into millions of households. It
makes sense for the two services to merge.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the folks at AOL are crowing about a feature called
``You've Got Pictures,'' which allows users to run a personal slide
show on their television set. That hardly qualifies as a
revolutionary innovation, and it sure isn't worth $14.95 a month
for existing AOL members (or $24.95 a month for nonmembers).
</P>
<P>
   Back in the day, low-tech interactive programs such as ``Winky
Dink'' had a simple set of challenges; the producers simply had to
get the kids to buy the kits. Today, AOL and other companies have
to overcome long-entrenched beliefs about the medium itself. At the
same time, AOL has a distinct advantage that cannot be ignored _
its enormous user base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Videophones were tough because you had to buy two,'' says
Silva. ``If you only bought one, there was no one to talk to. But
if we sell one AOLTV box, there are 23 million people to talk to. I
can't stress that enough.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-31-00 1326EDT &QL;
</P>
