<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-MICROSOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT: CASTING A BROAD .NET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The largest software company on earth has launched its largest
new-product initiative ever.
</P>
<P>
   It's called Microsoft.NET, and though technology companies have
a bad habit of abusing capital letters, this time the odd spelling
makes sense. .NET is big _ perhaps as big as the antitrust ruling
that could dismantle Microsoft in a year or two. The company says
it'll spend $4.4 billion in research and development on the project
in this fiscal year alone. Microsoft chairman Bill Gates calls it
``a bet-the-company thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the best evidence of .NET's massive scope is the
fact that it's so difficult to describe. .NET isn't one thing _ a
new operating system or a new programming language. It's nothing
less than a complete rethink of Microsoft's basic business model.
</P>
<P>
   A company grown fat on selling separate chunks of software to
users of desktop computers has come to realize that this won't work
any more. Computers now come in all shapes and sizes, from laptops
to palmtops. More important, they're all learning how to talk to
each other, using the free, open communications standards found on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In a world of smart networked devices, almost every part of
Microsoft's business has to change. The .NET program is Microsoft's
remodeling blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Sanjay Parthasarathy, a software development vice president at
Microsoft, used to manage Microsoft's corporate Web site, one of
the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was running Microsoft.com, I had a kind of epiphany,''
he says. On a browser, ``what you see are pictures of information.
You don't have the real information.''
</P>
<P>
   You can cut and paste text from a Web page to a word processor
or spreadsheet on your own machine. But users would have a lot more
power if they could work directly on the data in the Web page
itself.
</P>
<P>
   .NET aims to make this possible by means of ``Web services,''
chunks of active code running on remote Internet servers but
available to people all over the network. A financial Web site
could use a service that would cause customer financial data to
appear inside a full-featured spreadsheet program. The customer
would be able to enter new data, run what-if financial scenarios,
and even save the results to the hard drive of his own machine.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about the idea of having a program running
remotely, but .NET aims to make the process seamless and nearly
invisible to the user. For instance, the spreadsheet wouldn't pop
up in a separate window, but would be built right into the
financial company's Web page, a concept that Microsoft calls the
``universal canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the system work, Microsoft has been forced to abandon,
at least in part, its traditional affection for ``secret sauce'' _
fancy features based on private Microsoft technology that can't be
emulated by other companies. The world's computer networks are
built around openly published software standards; to be taken
seriously, Microsoft.NET has to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   So the system relies on XML, a network language that's much more
powerful than the HTML language that's generally used to create Web
pages. XML is an international open standard, controlled by the
World Wide Web Consortium in Cambridge. Microsoft can use it, but
it can't control it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart and soul of .Net . . . is XML,'' says Parthasarathy.
``If you cut us around here, these days, we bleed XML.''
</P>
<P>
   The language is vital because it makes it easy to separate the
content of a document from the form in which a computer displays
it. That means that the same XML-coded information can be displayed
easily on many different types of electronic devices. Nowadays, Web
pages must be painstakingly modified to fit on pocket-size Web
phones. But in a .NET world, XML-based sites will automatically
format themselves to fit a PC, a cell phone, or any other viewing
system.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Microsoft developed a new communications protocol
called SOAP that allows its new Web services to work. But in a
break from Microsoft tradition, the company has released SOAP as an
open standard, allowing any software developer or Web designer to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   With XML, SOAP and Microsoft's universal canvas, Web designers
will be able to add powerful new features to their sites simply by
subscribing to them. Microsoft itself plans to offer a number of
Web services that it expects will be especially popular.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company already has a service called Passport
that lets you log into multiple Microsoft Web sites by entering a
password just once. Your personal information is then made
available to all other Passport sites, eliminating the need to sign
up for each one separately.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft figures there'll be considerable demand for such
services. It will offer a Web-identity service that will identify
users instantly to any site they choose. Other Web services will
include search engines, a calendar, and online data storage. A Web
site designer would simply subscribe to these services, and they'd
appear as integral parts of his Web page.
</P>
<P>
   And they won't have to buy from Microsoft. Using .NET
programming tools, other companies can create their own Web
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enables a whole new level of competition on the Web,'' says
William Zachmann, vice president of the Meta Group, an industry
analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
   Web services won't just be relatively lightweight applications.
Microsoft is going to deliver its entire office software suite this
way, in a service called Office.NET. Rather than buy Office
outright and install it on a home computer, a subscriber will be
able to pay a monthly fee for the right to use, say, the Excel
spreadsheet as a Web service.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft isn't just counting on software rental revenues to
turn a profit on the .NET initiative. If it's successful, the
company stands to sell lots of .NET-enabled versions of its Windows
operating system. Even if other companies embrace the .NET approach
and make their products compatible with it, Microsoft could give
itself a headstart so large that rivals could never catch up.
</P>
<P>
   The .NET strategy is also a direct assault on one of Microsoft's
most bitter rivals, Sun Microsystems Inc. Sun has garnered an
international following for its Java computer language. Programmers
like Java because the same piece of code written in Java can run on
many different kinds of computers with minimal changes. Instead of
writing software that'll only run on Microsoft's dominant Windows
platform, Java programmers know that their code can run on many
other kinds of computers as well.
</P>
<P>
   But only if you write in the Java language. That means throwing
away billions of lines of programming code already written, not to
mention the challenge of learning a new language.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says .NET offers a better way. The company will offer
new software development tools that'll make traditional computer
languages work more like Java. Already it's introduced C(NU), a new
version of the venerable C operating system that's intended to be
more Java-like. And the company is working to .NET-enable other
computer languages as well. The idea is for Microsoft to sell lots
of software development products, but also to encourage the fastest
possible rollout of .NET-compatible services.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive Software Engineering Inc. in Santa Barbara, Calif.,
makes a computer language called Eiffel that's used by banks and
financial institutions. The company has worked with Microsoft to
.NET-enable Eiffel by adding a feature called a ``common language
runtime,'' which is similar to the ``virtual machine'' that lets
Java programs run on many different kinds of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Bertrand Meyer, the company's president, says that with common
language runtime, .NET programmers will be able to write in any
language they like _ Visual Basic, C, COBOL, or Eiffel _ and get
the same kind of versatility now offered by Java. For example, five
programmers working on a large project might each write in a
different language, but their finished code would interact without
a hitch. ``It is in very much contrast to the Sun approach which
says, `Use Java or you are lost,' '' says Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Lowe, a programmer at ARINC Inc., an aerospace software
company in South Carolina, says the Microsoft approach is
well-suited to the way he works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common language runtime on the .NET platform . . . makes
our lives easier because we can now use one language to write
components, program SQL Server (a popular database program), and
develop Web pages.''
</P>
<P>
   But Java boosters are less than awed by Microsoft's approach.
Sun spokesman David Harrah says that the common runtime would only
work for people using a forthcoming new version of the Windows
operating system, Windows.NET, which is due out next year. Besides,
he notes that unlike .NET, Java has something of a track record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's five years old and it has a great deal of substance to
it, and 2 1/2 to 3 million developers,'' says Harrah.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Ross, president of the Java Lobby, an organization of Java
programmers, is even more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for me to believe that C(NU) and .NET isn't
just another way to dress the wolf up,'' Ross says. ``Just a
different color of sheep's clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Microsoft's reputation for harsh tactics used against
rivals and business partners alike, many a developer may hesitate
to stake his company's survival on the future of .NET. But
Microsoft has already done just that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-01-00 1010EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
