<HEADER>
A1601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-ANIMATION-SOFTWAR     08-03 1854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ANIMATION-SOFTWARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLIMPSES OF A MORE VIVID ENTERTAINMENT FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Fred Tepper grew increasingly voluble as he
described the wonders of Project: Messiah, the character animation
software that he was promoting at Siggraph, the leading annual
conclave for specialists in computer graphics, virtual reality and
interactive technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the beginning of time in computer animation, people have
been looking for more realistic characters,'' Tepper said. ``And
we're finally getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first convention for the company behind Project:
Messiah, pmG _ basically a bunch of friends and colleagues with
backgrounds in computer animation. And here they were at Siggraph,
with their own booth, their own line of products _ right in there
with the big guys .
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really have a company headquarters yet,'' Tepper
said. ``Basically, at the moment, we're kind of all working out of
our houses.''
</P>
<P>
   As computer graphics become increasingly important in the
production and distribution of popular entertainment in America _
whether it's three-dimensional animation or photo-realistic special
effects _ an argument can be made that the best way to see into the
culture's future is not to take in the latest Off Broadway
sensation or study the works of the current darling of the Iowa
Writers' Workshop, but to stroll around at Siggraph, ground zero in
the digital entertainment explosion.
</P>
<P>
   What would rapidly become apparent on such a stroll is that
several converging forces are at work that in the very near future
are likely to result in more plentiful, vivid and immersive
entertainment, whether it's in a movie theater, in front of a
computer screen or seated at a video game console.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving into a period of what I call lean-forward
entertainment, as oppose to lean-back entertainment,'' said Fred
Angelopoulos, chief executive of Pulse Entertainment. ``I am
talking about entertainment that doesn't allow you to sit back,
that pulls you right into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Using software that has just arrived on the market, animators
will be able to work more quickly and much, much more cheaply. Home
hobbyists and aspiring filmmakers will be able to create, on
personal computers no more powerful than the ones they probably
already have in their homes, special effects and animations of
astonishing sophistication. In addition, new methods in what is
called image-based rendering are emerging to make it easier to
create animation from photographs and other digital images scanned
into a computer.
</P>
<P>
   On the World Wide Web, three-dimensional animation will become
increasingly the norm, for shopping, for gaming, for attracting
people to Internet sites and keeping them there. New affiliations
like those just announced between Intel and Macromedia and between
Real Networks and Pulse Entertainment indicate that the science of
compressing huge volumes of data may finally make it possible to
stream complex three-dimensional images into personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Technologies like haptics, which makes virtual objects on a
computer or game screen ``feel'' as though they are real by adding
tension and vibrations to a mouse or joystick, will intensify the
online experience. And with a new generation of powerful video-game
machines like Sony's Power Station 2 and Microsoft's X-box, the
richness and realism of game animations will take a quantum leap
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest difference we will see in the coming months is in
the realism,'' said Roger D. Chandler, product marketing manager
for Intel's Internet Media Initiative. ``For a long time, we
weren't getting that realism because the processing power wasn't
there on people's desktops. But now the hardware is there. And the
software is becoming available to utilize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Siggraph was founded by the Association for Computer Machinery
and stands for Special Interest Group _ Graphics, a name given to
the show three decades ago, when the field was dominated by those
providing computer-enhanced applications for the military and
industry. Gradually, those innovations made their way into
commercial use and then into popular entertainment. Now, Hollywood
and computer games are the dominant flavor at the annual event.
</P>
<P>
   The trade floor, where the latest high-tech gizmos are unveiled,
is as big as the deck of an aircraft carrier, a labyrinthine grid
of blinking lights, overhead screens, twirling logos and
cacophonous pitches. Many companies use the event to introduce
their latest products, like Sony's Gscube, a video graphics
equalizer that allows animators to create complex scenes in real
time. (Until recently, animators had to punch in volumes of
computer code _ for characters, for textures, for movements _ and
then let it process for hours, or even overnight, before seeing how
the result looked.)
</P>
<P>
   Since Hollywood has become so central to the computer graphics
industry, Siggraph is held every other year in Los Angeles, where
it has attracted around 45,000 people in recent years. In the
alternate years, the conclave shifts to places like Orlando,
Washington and, this year, New Orleans, and the crowds are
generally smaller, around 25,000 to 35,000.
</P>
<P>
   The event is the largest get-together of the year for those
involved in the field, a time when college friendships are renewed
and resumes are passed around with zeal. Job seekers formed long
lines to apply to the leading animation companies _ Disney, Pixar
Animation (creators of ``Toy Story''), Pacific Data Images
(``Antz''), Sony Imageworks (``Stuart Little''), Blue Sky
Productions (making the forthcoming ``Ice Age''), Square Films
(making ``Final Fantasy'') _ and the top effects houses, like
Industrial Light and Magic, Digital Domain, Mantex and Rhythm and
Hues.
</P>
<P>
   It is a young field, and the bulk of those attending the event
are also young _ certainly under 40, many of them fresh out of
college. And, as might be expected when so many young people are
gathered together, there is a certain party atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Bulletin boards set up around the convention center were
festooned with graffiti (``I Love New Orleans!'') promoting parties
and Web sites and all-night raves. Each evening offered an array of
company-sponsored parties at French Quarter nightclubs and uptown
mansions, many of which lasted until near dawn and brought a
certain bleary aspect to the early morning reading of technical
papers.
</P>
<P>
   Siggraph also has a high-art component, a digital art gallery,
at which serious artists can display work built upon
computer-created images or effects. The results this year ranged
from the eerily beautiful to the perplexing and the whimsical.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Free Range Appliances,'' a corral full of toasters,
eggbeaters and other small household items, all mounted on wheels,
would spring to life when flashlights were shined on them.
</P>
<P>
   In a piece called ``Nosce Te Ipsum'' by a University of Michigan
artist named Tiffany Holmes, viewers were asked to walk along a
path toward a screen displaying a collage of images. As the viewer
got closer to the screen, pieces of it were torn away, to the
amplified sound of ripping paper, until finally a video image of
the viewer appeared on the screen, gaping back at himself.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearby room called the Studio, visitors could create their
own paintings and sculptures using the kind of high-end equipment
and software most of them never have a chance to use. And upstairs
in the convention center, in dozens of meetings room, classes in
computer techniques and theory ran throughout the five-day
gathering. Four auditoriums showed a rotating program of 135 pieces
of computer animation, chosen from more than 600 submitted from all
over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everywhere, the talk was about breaking through
boundaries to make the entertainment experience more vivid, and
about how inexpensive the whole field is becoming.
</P>
<P>
   Project: Messiah began as a plug-in to one of the dominant
animation packages, a common first step for animation software. A
studio will equip its staff with an animation package _ Maya,
Softimage and Houdini are among the bigger names _ and then buy
individual plug-ins that enhance a particular feature. Such a
plug-in might, for example, offer heightened facial animation
capabilities or a range of arcane textures.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, many of the plug-in companies move beyond that stage
and offer a stand-alone version, a soup-to-nuts animation package,
which is what Messiah was doing this year. The first Project:
Messiah stand-alone was selling for $395 at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge home hobby thing going on right now,'' Tepper
said. ``I can remember when I was in high school and wanted to make
movies, I got a Super-8 camera. Well, this is sort of the Super-8
camera of the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   And Messiah was far from alone; more than a dozen software
companies were offering animation packages and plug-ins that cost
well under $1,000 and promised sophisticated results, even on a
home computer.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Riley, the vice president for marketing and business
development at Face2Face, said that his company's software, which
turns flat images into three-dimensional ones, is aimed at creating
more sophisticated facial animation. At the moment, the company is
offering the product to animation studios, estimating it will save
25 percent in time and costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, we are hoping to move into animation in the
house,'' he said. ``Maybe creating the next generation of greeting
cards, where people can scan images of themselves into their
computer and then create animated versions of themselves to send
over the Internet as Christmas or birthday cards.''
</P>
<P>
   The savings were not limited to at-home animation. Scott Ross,
chairman of Digital Domain, said he had seen the cost of equipping
one of his company's effects animators plummet from his early days
in the business, when he created effects for films like ``The
Abyss'' (1986).
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to geek out on you,'' he said, ``but back in 1986 a
standard work station cost $65,000, plus $34,000 for the software.
So you were looking at a cost of about $100,000 per seat. Now, you
can get 10 times the power in a $7,000 computer.''
</P>
<P>
   In the convention's technical areas, where academic researchers
offered technical papers on the latest developments in the field,
much of the talk was about moving beyond the current vogue in
ultra-realistic animation.
</P>
<P>
   David Salesin, a University of Washington professor who won the
convention's top prize for technical achievement, has written
extensively on ways to create watercolorlike effects on the
computer and to imitate the brushstrokes and the feel of
impressionist paintings, moving computer animation away from the
kind of rock-hard accuracy that sometimes made it feel cold and
emotionless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a good job with photo-realism,'' Salesin said.
``Now is the time to look at more expressive forms of drawing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-01-00 1142EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-PRISONERS-INTERNE     08-03 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PRISONERS-INTERNET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMATES USE WEB SITES TO FORGE LINKS WITH THE OUTSIDE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Internet has given a platform to death-row inmates
and other American prisoners to plead their cases and seek pen
pals, sparking outrage among many families of victims and creating
a new debate about the rights of the growing number of prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   While no American prison allows inmates to have access to the
Internet, prisoners use third-party services, usually for a fee, to
reach out to a potentially huge audience.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, dozens of inmates like Michael Blue, who is on death
row, appear on Web sites saying they were wrongly convicted of
murder. On one Web site, Blue is described as ``a little shy,
honest, caring, loving.''
</P>
<P>
   A California inmate, Askia Ashanti, appears on a Web site
looking for ``a pro bono attorney or $5,000 to $10,000 in funds to
hire an attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   And Beau Greene, who is imprisoned in Arizona, appears on a Web
site in a picture, cradling a fluffy cat and asking for pen pals.
Greene is described as ``bored and lonely with a surplus of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, 32, does not mention that he was convicted in 1996 of
killing a slender, 58-year-old musician, Roy Johnson, by bashing
the man's head against rocks.
</P>
<P>
   When the victim's daughter, Jennifer Johnson Lopez, discovered
the Web site, she said she was horrified that the killer was able
to use the Internet to escape his feeling of confinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disgusted,'' Johnson Lopez said. ``He said he missed
companionship. I thought, `Serves you right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Victims' rights groups complain that it is humiliating for
victims and their families to see prisoners popping up on Web
sites. The groups also complain that people browsing the Internet
might begin correspondence with violent criminals or believe their
stories without knowing the real details of their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such criticism, officials in New York and Arizona
have enacted policies or laws that forbid prisoners from using
third-party Internet service providers. Washington and other states
have debated similar measures.
</P>
<P>
   But in the view of many civil libertarians, these measures
infringe on the First Amendment rights of inmates. Eleanor
Eisenberg, the executive director of the Arizona chapter of the
American Civil Liberties Union, said her group was considering
filing a lawsuit against the Arizona measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It clearly impinges on an inmate's First Amendment right to
communicate,'' Eisenberg said. ``It also chills the rights of third
parties who have committed no crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials, however, say they are frustrated by the Web
sites, and they say the Internet has allowed prisoners to have
soapboxes and to to prey on the innocent and softhearted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has given these criminals worldwide access and
the ability to raise huge amounts of money,'' said Gary Phelps, the
chief of staff for the Arizona Department of Corrections. ``Besides
that, we've got women coming from Australia, Belgium, England _ all
wanting to see these men they've met on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has also become a tool in championing the causes of
individual inmates, such as Mumia Abu-Jamal, who defenders contend
was wrongly convicted of killing a police officer in Philadelphia
in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen Web sites carry details about the case and
history of Abu-Jamal. One of the largest sites, operated by a
private anti-death-penalty group in New York called Refuse and
Resist, describes the inmate as ``a prominent radio journalist''
being punished because he ``allowed the angry and anguished voices
of the oppressed onto the airwaves.''
</P>
<P>
   It features a photograph of Abu-Jamal, smiling and raising a
clenched fist.
</P>
<P>
   A page on the Web site, under a headline reading ``The
Frame-Up,'' calls the police account absurd and says that witnesses
in Abu-Jamal's defense were harassed by law enforcement
authorities. The site invites people to join marches around the
country on Abu-Jamal's behalf. It also encourages Web site visitors
to print and distribute the posting to other potential supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal's lawyer, Leonard Weinglass, said the Internet had
allowed people around the world to closely follow Jamal's case.
``If something happens in court, it's important that our friends in
France, Germany and Denmark be informed,'' Weinglass said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, American prison authorities have long read inmates'
mail, except for legal correspondence and letters to elected
officials. But in recent years, prisons have made it more difficult
for inmates to have contact with people on the outside, said Steve
Bright, the director of the Southern Center For Human Rights, an
advocacy group for inmates' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be viewed as a positive to stay in touch with the
outside world, since the idea was that people would be
rehabilitated and then returned to society,'' Bright said. ``Now
the attitude is to make the prisons as punitive as possible and
make the prisoners as miserable as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, he said, the courts have almost always sided with
prison authorities in clamping down on the ability of inmates to
communicate with outsiders, especially reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, while inmates are forbidden to receive mail from
third-party services, they can send mail to these services, as long
as they disclose that they are prison inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in truth in inmate advertising,'' said James
Flateau, a spokesman for the New York Department of Correctional
Services. ``We want people to know who they're writing to.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other state prison systems, the New York correctional
department posts an ``inmate look-up'' on the Internet so the
potential pen pals can learn about a prisoner's record, Flateau
said, ``and decide for themselves if that's someone they want to
write to.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest third-party Internet services for inmates is
run by the Rev. Rene Mulkey, who operates in rural Missouri and has
a client list of about 1,500 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   For $10, a fee that Mulkey says is used to defray mailing costs,
inmates can have a biographical sketch posted on her Web site,
usually with a photograph, a first name and an identification
number. When people send messages to individual prisoners, she
forwards them through the United States Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the guys are asking for romance, or friends, or just
plain encouragement,'' Mulkey said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her empathy for inmates stemmed, in part, from what she
described as a ``false arrest record'' that had haunted her late
husband. ``Things are not always what they seem to be,'' she said.
``The press makes these guys out to be animals, but they're not.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jane McGrath, a Republican state legislator who sponsored
the bill prohibiting inmates from using third-party Internet
services, said it galled the families of victims to see the smiling
faces of criminals who describe themselves as decent people.
</P>
<P>
   ````The Internet allows these people to distort history. It's a
way of further victimizing the victim,'' McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-31-00 2021EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
