<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-CLARK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE YOUR ENEMY ALSO IS YOUR FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALEX PHAM   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ With enemies like Jim Clark, who needs
friends?
</P>
<P>
   Clark has become the talk of Silicon Valley this past week after
disclosing that he recently purchased 1 million shares of Microsoft
Corp., despite having helped the federal government in its
antitrust case against the software company.
</P>
<P>
   Most folks know the erstwhile Microsoft basher as one of the
founders of Netscape Communications, the firm whose Web browser
went toe to toe with Microsoft's Internet Explorer product and
lost. Clark got his revenge when he played a key role in the US
Department of Justice's successful bid to nail Microsoft for trying
to put Netscape out of business.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. Shortly after a federal judge ruled in favor of
the government and ordered the breakup of Microsoft, Clark quietly
bought the company's stock, which at the time traded between $65
and $73 a share. Microsoft shares inched up 31.25 cents Friday to
$69.6875 on the Nasdaq exchange. At around the same time, Clark
sold about 95 percent of his shares in America Online, the company
that purchased Netscape last year.
</P>
<P>
   Why the switch?
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to diversify,'' Clark quipped to an incredulous
audience who gathered here last week to hear him speak. Clark also
disclosed that he has started using Microsoft's Internet Explorer
browser.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is rich gossip for the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But is it shocking? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   There's a notion in the technology industry called
``coopetition.'' It's a ruthlessly pragmatic approach to doing
business, where companies can be ferocious competitors in one
market and cheerful partners in another.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Andreessen, who started Netscape with Clark and once
referred to Microsoft as ``Godzilla,'' agreed weeks ago to do
business with his former foe. Loudcloud, Andreessen's new Silicon
Valley venture, will team up with the Redmond, Wash., giant to
jointly market, sell, and license software.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems Inc. and Nortel Networks Corp. are brutal
competitors in the market for Internet switches and routers, but
the two are working together to come up with the Web's
next-generation infrastructure in a project called Internet2.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard Corp. and EMC Corp. compete in the market for
data storage devices. But when it comes to developing the software
to connect EMC machines with Hewlett-Packard's, the two companies
closely collaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle Corp. in Redwood Shores, Calif., and SAP AG in Frankfurt,
Germany, try to clobber each other when it comes to the database
software market. Both, however, work together to sell Oracle
hardware coupled with SAP software. Larry Ellison, Oracle's CEO,
recently acknowledged that SAP is ``both a competitor and a
supplier. We see no conflict there.''
</P>
<P>
   Other strange bedfellows are Apple Computer Corp. and Microsoft,
whose operating systems are direct competitors. Nevermind that
Microsoft is an investor in Apple and one of the biggest developers
of software for Apple's Macintosh computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``One the one hand, Microsoft is in a zero-sum game with
Macintosh,'' in selling operating systems, said Guy Kawasaki,
former chief evangelist for Apple and now chief executive of
Garage.com, an investor in early-stage start-ups. ``On the other
hand, Microsoft makes some of the best software for Macintosh. It
really gets complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Or mercenary.
</P>
<P>
   John Doerr, a prominent Silicon Valley venture capitalist with
Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, recently contrasted
``missionaries'' and ``mercenaries'' in the Valley, using Clark as
an example of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there's anything wrong with a mercenary approach. Many
companies simply look at it as survival. ``If you have to get in
with an enemy, well, that's life,'' said Judith Hurwitz, CEO of the
Hurwitz Group in Boston. ``That's how this industry has grown up.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Clark, the entrepreneur's relationship with his old
nemesis, Microsoft, has another twist. When Clark, who founded
medical Web site Healtheon, found out Microsoft would be investing
in rival WebMD, he decided to join Microsoft _ literally _ by
merging Healtheon with WebMD. Microsoft subsequently invested $250
million in Clark's company.
</P>
<P>
   What's Clark learned from his dealings with Microsoft?
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got overwhelming power,'' Clark told his audience of
800 last week. ``It's good to be in alliance with them . . . unless
they're in the same exact business you're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-01-00 1012EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
