<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LAKE GEORGE IS NOT LONGER AN ISOLATED RETREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DINA CAPPIELLO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE GEORGE, N.Y. _ It used to be a place to go and ``get away
from it
</P>
<P>
   all,'' a retreat for the tired and weary who came to the
Adirondacks to
</P>
<P>
   lose themselves in a landscape of endless mountains, water and
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Northway, a blacktopped trail opening the gateway
of
</P>
<P>
   the Eastern Adirondacks to anyone with a car.
</P>
<P>
   The retreat became a full-fledged resort that attracts nearly 3
</P>
<P>
   million visitors each summer, according to the Warren County
Tourism Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lake George is like a zoo during the summer. There's a
gazillion
</P>
<P>
   motor boats and around the village there's a real carnival
atmosphere,''
</P>
<P>
   said Jerry Pepper, the librarian for the Adirondack Museum, in
Blue
</P>
<P>
   Mountain Lake. ``It's like Coney Island.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, to escape campgrounds with tents stacked
side-by-side
</P>
<P>
   like rowhouses and the incessant whizzing of powerboats,
visitors must
</P>
<P>
   seek trails and camping spots far off upstate New York's major
</P>
<P>
   transportation artery. They literally must venture off the
beaten path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get away from Lake George village there are some
wonderful
</P>
<P>
   hiking opportunities,'' said Neil Woodworth, deputy executive
director of
</P>
<P>
   the Adirondack Mountain Club, which recommends the Tongue
Mountain range
</P>
<P>
   for a unique nature experience. The Tongue Mountains are one of
the few
</P>
<P>
   places where Eastern timber rattlesnakes, a threatened species
in New
</P>
<P>
   York, can be found.
</P>
<P>
   But to find true solace in nature near Lake George, the place
Thomas
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson once called ``the queen of America,'' follow the
compass point
</P>
<P>
   east or north, where the lean-tos are perched on much smaller
watering
</P>
<P>
   holes, but most days are left empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of wilderness around Lake George, it's just not
in or
</P>
<P>
   around the lake,'' Pepper said.
</P>
<P>
   Many spots, such as Black Mountain, offer those who reach the
summit
</P>
<P>
   views of Lake George from afar. Peaks such as Sleeping Beauty
and Shelving
</P>
<P>
   Rock Mountain are less-crowded alternatives to Buck Mountain,
according to
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Sweet, information services coordinator for the Adirondack
Mountain
</P>
<P>
   Club's Lake George office.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed between the mountaintops are a handful of ponds
</P>
<P>
   inaccessible from any major roads _ and thus, less visited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Mountain ponds look like something from Northern Maine.
All
</P>
<P>
   it's missing is a moose,'' said Russ Guard, who has maintained
the lean-to
</P>
<P>
   at Millman Pond in the Lake George Wild Forest for the last six
years.
</P>
<P>
   The retired state policeman and 46er _ meaning he has climbed
all 46
</P>
<P>
   peaks above 4,000 feet in the Adirondacks _ says the
``beer-drinking
</P>
<P>
   party-goers'' stop off at ponds north and south of Millman, and
tend not
</P>
<P>
   to disturb Millman Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've developed a following at Millman,'' Guard said, meaning
that
</P>
<P>
   people who discover it generally return.
</P>
<P>
   In the journal at the site, entries described Millman Pond as
</P>
<P>
   ``righteous'' and a ``wonderful place.''
</P>
<P>
   But it depends on what you are looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who go to Lake George to experience the
</P>
<P>
   attractions, and there are people who go to the Adirondacks to
get away,''
</P>
<P>
   said Steve Collyer, communications director for the Adirondack
Regional
</P>
<P>
   Chambers of Commerce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
