A1612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN04-COX     08-03 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now it's our turn to take care of them
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one asked Joe Levinson if he could afford to serve in three
wars. These days, however, Levinson is being told that the country
he defended in World War II, Korea and Vietnam can't quite follow
through on its promise to provide him free medical care for the
rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   That was part of the deal Levinson and millions like him made
with the government: 20 years or more of their lives in exchange
for, among other things, free medical care for life, assuming they
survived to collect it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should have read the small print. That's free medical
care for life at military hospitals and then only after active duty
personnel were treated. Even so, that wasn't a really bad deal
before the end of the cold war brought on a round of base closings.
Closing Bergstrom Air Force Base put Levinson, who now lives in
Buda, in a position of making some bad choices even as the years
and the exposure to the defoliant Agent Orange began to catch up
with him.
</P>
<P>
   He could either: a) get on a waiting list for an appointment at
the nearest active military base in San Antonio b) reach into his
pocket for Medicare and supplemental coverage or c) suffer.
</P>
<P>
   He chose b, but questions why he or any other military retiree
should. The government promised medical care for life, after all.
When is a deal not a deal?
</P>
<P>
   Levinson entered the military in March 1942, four months after
Pearl Harbor. He mustered out in 1946, having served as a Navy
radio operator and gunner. After the war, he joined the Army
National Guard in Illinois and got a commission. He was called up
for service in Korea and decided to make the military a career.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, Levinson commanded an aviation company that never
lacked for excitement during the early stages of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   A magazine article of the period described one night in
Levinson's life: ``. . . Somewhere below the major's (helicopter)
the Viet Cong first regiment was silently closing in on Soc Trang
airfield, the vital American base in the Mekong Delta . . . (its)
aircraft all sitting duck targets for VC mortars if the guerrillas
crept close enough to attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lose Soc Trang and there was a good chance the entire Mekong
Delta would fall to the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Levinson) had already made up his mind that there was only
one way to locate the VC guerrillas in the darkness below and that
was to use his own helicopter as bait.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what he did and survived to tell the tale. Just
another day at the office.
</P>
<P>
   His warrior days are long gone, but Levinson, 76, and others
like him _ an estimated 1.4 million military retirees are in the
country today _ have seen their access to health care shrink even
as their need for it grows.
</P>
<P>
   He signed up with a grass-roots movement to push for legislation
to give military retirees the same kind of health benefits civilian
federal employees and members of Congress collect.
</P>
<P>
   There is legislation that would do that, but members of
Congress, including U.S. Sen. Trent Lott, R-Mississippi, balk at
the price tag, maybe $40 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson, a congenial soul with a good-natured and quick wit,
notes with a chuckle that the potential costs go down daily as
World War II and Korean War veterans fall into the final formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they stall long enough, some of us won't be around to
collect,'' Levinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Levinson and his comrades in arms kept their end of the
deal with the nation. It's time for the government to keep its end
of the deal with those from whom much was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at (512) 445-3667 or
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
