<HEADER>
A1629 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MCMANUS-EASTERN-CHALL     08-03 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-EASTERN-CHALLENGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHALLENGE TO CHRISTIANITY FROM THE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Religion Commentary) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article is available from the
New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    While America was focused on the Republican Convention this week
in Philadelphia, Billy Graham, 81, attracted 10,000 evangelists to
a conference in Amsterdam.
 &HT;    Sadly, Graham was unable to attend the first week's events due
to the discovery of a buildup of fluid on his brain. It was hoped
he would be able to attend the final session on Sunday at least by
satellite hookup, so he can ''pass the torch'' of evangelism on to
a new generation.
 &HT;    However, Graham was ably represented by his son, Franklin
Graham, a daughter, Anne Graham Lotz, plus such notables as
evangelist Luis Palau, Anglican Archbishop George Carey, and by
Ravi Zacharias, the Indian-born Christian evangelist.
 &HT;    Zacharias, interestingly, challenges the ''tolerance'' of our
culture, which embraces everything from Eastern mysticism to New
Age spirituality, with the uncompromising conviction that Jesus is
the only way.
 &HT;    Speaking at an opening plenary session in Amsterdam, Zacharias
said, ''Religions from the East have come flooding in. Ideas like,
`Discover the God that is in you,' or reincarnation, or meditation
upon a mantra or a chant of another deity have gradually taken on a
huge following'' at the very time that western culture ''has
evicted Christianity as a dominant factor.''
 &HT;    ''The result, I fear, may well be the pointed question whether
Jesus Christ is indeed unique, or is He just one among many ways?'
 &HT;    Four days after Zacharias spoke, George Barna released a new
poll reporting that more than 100 million U.S. adults ''are stumped
as to the meaning and purpose of their life.'' Yet a substantial
majority describe themselves as ''deeply spiritual.''
 &HT;    How can people call themselves deeply spiritual while being
stumped on the meaning or purpose of life?
 &HT;    Zacharias identified some sources of dramatic change. First is
the ''dominance of the visual.... The camera controls the
imagination of young minds.'' True. The new generation does not
read newspapers, for example.
 &HT;    ''The increasing power of a youth-dominated world,'' is another
sign of the time. ''How are cultures that have cherished the past
going to cope with a generation which lives only for the moment?''
 &HT;    Another is ''the bold face of atheism'' seen on university
campuses where many even deny that good and evil exist.
 &HT;    Zacharias summed up these trends to the young evangelists in one
sentence: ''How do you reach a generation that hears with its eyes
and thinks with its feelings?''
 &HT;    First, ''We cannot just speak the Gospel. We will have to embody
the Gospel,'' as did the Belgian missionary Joseph Damien, who
ministered to lepers. One day Father Damien spilled hot water on
his foot and did not feel it. He changed his sermon opening from
''My fellow believers'' to ''My fellow lepers.''
 &HT;    Second, we need a ''proclamation that is not merely argued but
felt.'' Clergy who have to read their sermons to me are speaking
from the head, not the heart.
 &HT;    Finally, Zacharias suggests rescuing not only the ends of the
Gospel, but also the means. Find language that communicates with
power. He notes the way poet Alexander Pope described Jesus'
miracle of Cana turning water into wine, ''The conscious water saw
its Master and blushed.''
 &HT;    In his latest book, ``Jesus Among Other Gods,'' Zacharias
compares Buddha and Mohammed, who merely taught, with Jesus, who
''did not only teach or expound his message. He was identical with
His message.''
 &HT;    ''He did not just proclaim the truth. He said, `I am the truth.'
He did not just show a way. He said `I am the way.''
 &HT;    Zacharias argues, ''All religions are not the same. All
religions do not point to God.''
 &HT;    In an interview from Singapore, Zacharias elaborated: ''Buddhism
at its core is non-theist or atheist. It gives you a way of life
that gives you the retention of your autonomy, your own
sovereignty. Hinduism teaches that every life is a moral repayment
of the previous life, and in the next life you could be mothered by
a boar or a donkey.''
 &HT;    By contrast, Christianity teaches ''We are not in need merely of
a superior ethic, we are in need of a transformed heart and will
that seeks to do the will of God.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.2000 Mike McManus
