<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1643 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MEDICAL-ACCESS-ART-BO     08-03 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-ACCESS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ONLINE MEDICAL RECORDS SEEN EMPOWERING PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Richard Fosler arrived for his Friday afternoon appointment
cradling a sore elbow, his doctor immediately requested an X-ray.
He then sent the results to a specialist for confirmation. Three
business days later, Fosler logged onto the Internet and got his
final answer.
</P>
<P>
   He clicked open a file called ``review radiology results,''
spotted the words ``no evidence of fracture'' and was pleased. But
while he was perusing his medical records online, he discovered a
mistake: An ankle X-ray listed his age as 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately e-mailed my doctor with a correction,'' said
Fosler, 44, an electrical engineer.
</P>
<P>
   In a new program designed to give patients more control _ one
that worries some doctors _ the CareGroup hospital and doctors
network soon will roll out one of the country's first interactive
Internet medical-records Web sites to as many as 1,000 doctors and
700,000 patients. More than 500 patients, including Fosler, and 30
physicians have spent the summer testing the new site.
</P>
<P>
   PatientSite has the potential to propel the patient empowerment
movement far beyond researching medical conditions on the Web and
commiserating in chat rooms. It theoretically takes away the
doctor's power to decide what the patient should and shouldn't know
and makes the patient an equal partner in his treatment. Patients
can read their medical records, comment on them, review test
results, and search their doctors' schedules for openings.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Ives, a CareGroup doctor in Lexington, Mass. who has
signed up 100 patients, called it a departure from old-fashioned
paternalistic medicine where the physician has all the control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major thing this system will do is build trust,'' said
Ives, one of the most outspoken PatientSite supporters. ``Patients
think doctors are not telling them everything or they're not doing
a test because the insurance company won't let them. Mostly
patients are worried we're not telling them the full story.''
</P>
<P>
   But already PatientSite is rankling more than a few doctors, who
worry about alarming patients with information they don't
understand and allowing them to type their symptoms and maladies
into their medical record without an official medical opinion. And,
they don't necessarily want Mrs. Smith to know they've blocked out
a vacation day when they could be tending to her aching ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of resistance in a lot of
quarters,'' said Dr. Daniel Sands, clinical director of electronic
patient records and communication at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center in Boston and a PatientSite tester. ``Doctors are already
overwhelmed, and they want to know if this is going to increase
their workload.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he said, CareGroup leaders have struck a compromise by
letting doctors decide which PatientSite features to switch on or
off. While Sands applauds the overall concept, he does not give his
patients access to his schedule, or to the portion of their record
called the ``problem list,'' which is his roster of their medical
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use that to remind myself of issues that are going on with
the person,'' Sands said. ``If I think depression or alcoholism is
a problem and they're not ready to deal with it or discuss it yet,
then it's not helpful for them to see that in the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Ives, on the other hand, has turned on all of the PatientSite
components, and said he's willing to post his ``physician notes'' _
one portion of patients' medical records not yet included on
PatientSite. ``If you can't say it to the patient or the judge,
then you shouldn't be saying it,'' he said. As for his schedule,
Ives said, ``It all comes back to trust. I trust my patients to
realize that I have a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said some of their initial worries have been addressed:
The site, for which patients need a password, is more secure than
sending e-mail over the commercial Internet; test results are
posted after a 24-hour delay, so doctors can call patients first
with bad news; CareGroup has decided not to put up complicated
biopsy results; and patients enter new allergies or problems in a
separate file, letting the doctor decide whether to add the
information to the permanent record.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will send us notes saying, `While I was (at the beach)
this weekend I stepped on a rusty nail and I got a tetanus shot at
the ER,'' said Dr. Steven Flier, chief executive of Affiliated
Physicians Group, a CareGroup doctors network. ``If they waited
until their next appointment, they might forget.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sands said he does not like the function allowing patients
to add to their record any new medications they're taking. The site
does not automatically notify them of dangerous drug interactions;
they have to click a box labeled ``Drug Interactions _ Step 1.''
Some interactions may not be siginificant, such as mild nausea, and
Sands does not want to alarm patients unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies and hospitals across the country are racing
to develop medical records that patients can view securely over the
Internet. But the industry is young and most programs are still in
the testing phase. Cydney Kislin, an analyst with Tucker Anthony in
New York, said she knows of only one company _ MedicaLogic _ whose
product allows patients to add to their medical record. CareGroup,
she said, is on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so early,'' she said. ``A lot of the hospital
organizations are very interested in the Internet; they just don't
know what to do with it. The number one problem with electronic
medical records is that physicians are slow to adopt new technology
_ especially when they think it will disrupt their work flow.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1999 survey by the American Medical Association found that
while 47 percent of doctors use the Internet, they rarely employ it
to e-mail patients or access electronic medical records.
</P>
<P>
   CareGroup's chief medical information officer, Dr. John Halamka,
a former emergency room physician, created the hospital network's
PatientSite technology, which cost $250,000 to develop and
implement. CareGroup's flagship hospital, Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center, which is striving for a financial turnaround this
year, has a reputation for providing patients with the comforting
extras, and hopes PatientSite will give it a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, patients seem to love it.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Pierce, 51, had an MRI for a back injury last Sunday.
The results were posted on PatientSite by Tuesday. Since she didn't
receive a phone call from her physician, Flier, she assumed nothing
was seriously wrong. But by seeing the MRIS report firsthand, she
could be sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a nagging doubt in your mind that maybe
everything's not OK and your results just got lost in the
shuffle,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Kress, 70, regularly reviews all of his test results,
including his cholesterol numbers for the past five years, which
makes him feel good about his progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who want to deny all kinds of issues, health
issues particularly. This site is not for those people,'' he said.
``It's for people who don't want to hide from the facts so they can
aggressively help themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Fosler said the system is ``awesome'' but he worries about what
will happen when more patients have access. He asked, ``Will my
doctor have time to screen this day in and day out and still be
able to see his patients?''
</P>
<P>
   Flier said doctors will adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, they were saying the telephone would be an
intrusion on health care,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
