<HEADER>
A1645 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PARROT-RESCUER-ART-BO     08-03 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARROT-RESCUER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FOR PARROT LOVER, A DREAM TAKES WING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKLAND, Mass. _ Marc Johnson wants to make one thing perfectly
clear: ``I am not here to help people. I am here for the birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a former potter married to a cancer researcher, is in
the throes of a winged love affair that has brought him more than
150 avian roommates: macaws, cockatoos, Amazons, conures and a
dozen other kinds of parrots.
</P>
<P>
   His house and barn, located near town center, is home to Foster
Parrots Ltd., a non-profit sanctuary that takes in abandoned
parrots and offers some for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   But after taking birds in seemingly almost every week, Johnson's
home has become a crowded, parrot boarding house with birds perched
on cages, branches and ropes throughout the house.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with great joy that Johnson greeted Paula Foster on
July 5. The hapless parrot owner from Marshfield handed Johnson her
two blue-crown conures and the key to his wildest dream: enough
land to build a rainforest pavilion and other specialty aviaries
for his family of African, South American, Pacific, and Australian
parrots.
</P>
<P>
   It would become New England's largest parrot attraction that is
not part of a zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Foster and her husband plan to donate to Foster Parrots about
five acres of a 40-acre Marshfield property they inherited from a
relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we would donate some land for something, so I told
(Johnson) that we don't need it all and he could have a little,''
said Foster, 33, a advocate for children at a Marshfield shelter.
``So many animal shelters take in cats and dogs, but pet birds are
overlooked. I feel like I am giving back.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be a while though before Johnson's flock enjoys a little
more wing room.
</P>
<P>
   For the next few months, the acreage is tied up in land court.
Then there are zoning and other licenses needed from the town. Not
to mention the $3.5 million Johnson says he needs to raise for a
world-class sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, it's getting crowded at 35 Vernon St.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 parrots have arrived since January alone, 16 of which
Johnson has adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 46, doesn't make the situation any easier. Despite
insisting he's full up, he rarely says no to guilt-ridden parrot
owners who come to him bedeviled by their inability to care for the
wild, loud, and ultra-sensitive birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really want to impress upon people the emotional
requirements of these birds,'' said Johnson, adding that he knows
of about 20 other individuals and groups nationwide that rescue
abandoned parrots. ``Leaving a little parakeet alone in a cage to
look out a window is a sad scenario. We don't feel parrots should
be pets. They are wild animals.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson said 60 million parrots are kept as pets in the
United States, making them the second most popular American pet.
Cats are number one. He said he does not breed his parrots.
</P>
<P>
   Parrot owners and lovers apparently like what Johnson is doing
and many send his organization unsolicited monthly checks from as
far away as Alaska. He received $22,000 in donations last year and
expects $30,000 this year, including $10,000 from a computer
company.
</P>
<P>
   To raise the large sum he needs to build the sanctuary, Johnson
will have to be more aggressive about seeking donations. He said he
hopes to attract corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   For now, five cockatoos and one Amazon named Mexico Pete live in
Johnson's former breakfast room. The old barn, attached to the
breakfast room, is filled with more than 100 parrots, some in cages
and others flying free or snuggled next to their partners on
perchs.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's place is noisy _ it sounds like a rain forest _ and
hectic. Tending to them means sweet talk and cuddles, John Denver
and opera, fresh fruit and nuts, and three weekly dinners:
Spaghetti, sweet potatoes, and a rice-and-vegetable medley. He
gives some birds the nectars or pollens they would normally seek
out in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his parrots were severely neglected by former owners and
plucked themselves bald in despair. A macaw named Floyd, who had
four homes in one year, hates women because his previous female
owner threw shoes at him to shut him up when he squawked.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of volunteers, including Tufts Veterinary
School students, come by Johnson's home every day to help clean and
feed the birds. Given the size and the flight freedom of this bird
population, the place is downright clean and odor-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``These animals are like people. They go insane in solitary
confinement,'' said Laura Lafay, a law student and parakeet owner
who comes by weekly to talk and play with the parrots.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs in the barn, Johnson has built eight 10-foot-high
flight cages that hold some of the more incorrigible macaws, ones
he won't put up for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Wally, Johnson's first parrot. Wally bit the
flesh clean off Johnson's nose two years ago (it was sewn back on)
and a week later sliced his lip.
</P>
<P>
   But despite that Johnson understands what Wally and many of his
other birds have endured. That's why, few would-be owners get to
adopt his birds. If they do, they have to agree to visits by
Johnson during a two-year probation period. Johnson will take the
birds back if he gets even a whiff of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``As pets, birds seem a neat, tidy package with their cages and
their plastic toys,'' he said. ``But the reality is they are not
pets and we are denying them their lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
