<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME STUDENTS, CO-OP PROGRAM ISN'T DOING THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Some marketing majors fold shirts at clothing stores. A
student studying psychology hands out towels at the university gym.
And political science majors often pass months photocopying and
faxing at law firms.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past century, Northeastern University has been a
national pioneer in blending college studies with work. The goal
was to help provide the mainly working-class students an income.
</P>
<P>
   But today, when a typical $10-an-hour job barely dents the
annual $20,000 in tuition, Northeastern has begun selling students
on the idea that the work is part of their education.
</P>
<P>
   Promotional brochures trumpet Northeastern's
cooperative-education program as on-the-job training that ``focuses
on preparing students for the real-world challenges of professional
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   However, for many students, the new cooperative education still
translates into the grind of menial labor _ and they don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Students interested in law complain they rarely get the chance
to help prepare cases. Journalism students working at newspapers,
including about 50 every year at the Globe, say they tend to answer
the phones, instead of writing stories. And some criminal justice
students gripe that their training consists of little more than
staring at TV cameras on the graveyard shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a 100-year-old program. It's not going to
change overnight,'' said Northeastern's president Richard M.
Freeland, who's leading the effort to revamp the co-op program as
``practice-oriented education.'' ``This is very much a work in
progress. We're trying to reinvent the program. So, I think you'll
find a lot of unevenness throughout.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Freeland sparked a stir of dissent with a memo
heralding significant changes in the co-op program. In light of the
increasing competition and the declining value of students holding
clerical jobs, he called on the university to strengthen links
between the classroom and the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   With the rise of the new economy, liberal arts students seeking
computer-oriented jobs, and nearly 1,500 colleges around the
country offering a version of Northeastern's co-op program,
Freeland said it is vital that the university distinguish itself.
The niche it carves out, he says, must better bind academic theory
and practice.
</P>
<P>
   The lofty rhetoric led Northeastern to lengthen the time of a
typical co-op student's work from three months to six months,
station co-op coordinators at their respective academic departments
instead of in a central building, and create new surveys and
Internet-based feedback forums to ensure the quality of students'
work experiences as linked to the classroom. The changes stress
more of an academic connection.
</P>
<P>
   The new tack, however, was challenged by many of the
university's 50 co-op coordinators. They say students should have
more opportunities to explore different jobs, and students' work
should be just that, work, not a stress-free internship.
</P>
<P>
   They want to ensure the co-op experiences are legitimate work
experiences, not controlled academic environment. They fear that
stressing more of an academic connection will reduce the quality of
the work experience. the academic work
</P>
<P>
   The dean overseeing the co-op program, Robert Tillman, resigned
over the president's changes and coordinators sent trustees letters
and studies criticizing the plans. Tillman and others lambasted the
scattering of coordinators, warned that the co-op program's unique,
century-old attributes would be lost, and worried about an employer
backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's turning us into an internship program,'' said
Kathleen Finn, an associate professor and nursing co-op faculty
coordinator, claiming she and others have had their jobs threatened
because of their complaints. ``I think it's a travesty. His plans
are going to destroy the co-op program.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many students want more quality control and say they feel
they have been misled by Northeastern's promotional literature,
which conveyed the impression they would do serious work.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Eric Ewing's experience. The 21-year-old political
science major spent the majority of one co-op job answering phones,
clipping newspaper articles, and mailing out form letters from
Senator Edward M. Kennedy's office.
</P>
<P>
   In another job at Northeastern's Education Technology Center,
Ewing had little supervision and few responsibilities. Most days he
had little else to do but scour the Internet for a diversion. ``I'm
a little let down,'' he said. ``I was definitely hoping my creative
abilities would be harnessed more. But I think it's a fairly common
feeling for liberal arts students.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Switalski, 20, a psychology major, spends most of her time
as a teacher's helper at the Montessori Educare School in Newton.
The Northeastern student does everything from prepare toddlers'
lunches to accompany them on long walks around a nearby lake. But
as in her previous co-op job, she says she feels hemmed in,
restricted in what she can do and learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I interviewed, they didn't even care about my
experience,'' she said. ``They just wanted to know when I could
start. What I would like is more decision-making power. There's
only so much you can learn in some positions.''
</P>
<P>
   While many students complain they are not getting the training
they hoped for, other students, especially those studying business
and engineering, often land lucrative and interesting co-op jobs. A
survey of this year's graduates found nearly all would recommend a
co-op-based education to a friend. Frequently the jobs do more than
bolster a student's resume: 50 percent of all students receive job
offers from their co-op employers, according to Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   Further, some students, coordinators, and employers argue that
the work environment and a student's initiative is as important to
the learning experience as the work.
</P>
<P>
   After six months at PaineWebber Inc., Annie Nam, 20, a finance
major, got what she wanted out of her co-op experience, even if it
wasn't what she hoped for. While much of her job included
administrative work, such as answering phones, she learned a lot
about the mutual-fund business, she says.
</P>
<P>
   But just sitting in the office every day, Nam learned something
even more important: ``What made it such a good experience,'' she
said, ``is that I figured out it wasn't what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the main perks of the co-op program, students and
coordinators emphasize, is it allows for error. Students get a
chance to weed out a prospective career before plunging into it
after school.
</P>
<P>
   But the opportunity to try out different jobs will be
increasingly limited as Northeastern pushes to lengthen the term of
co-op jobs. By 2003, when the university switches from a quarter
system to a semester system, the average number of co-op jobs per
student will drop from seven to three, university officials say.
</P>
<P>
   That only makes it more important for Northeastern to live up to
its promise of providing students quality, hands-on training, says
Richard Porter, the university's acting vice president of
cooperative education.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a co-op is not contributing to a student's overall growth,
we need to be doing better,'' he said. ``We need more feedback, and
we are planning to get it. If the work is going well with the
employer, we should know that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Administrators know not all students will be satisfied, and
experienced seniors will often have better jobs than inexperienced
sophomores. But they say they're up against a culture that for too
long has settled for middling jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Like many co-op employers, Pheroza N. Madon, the head of
Newton's Montessori Educare school, says the best way for young
people to learn is by starting at the bottom and mastering rote,
mundane tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Co-ops are young, naive, and they have a lot to learn,'' she
said. ``Many haven't ever worked before. They should start off at
the lowest level. But that doesn't mean they can't learn. Nothing
is . . . boring, as long as you have an open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, many students who come to Northeastern arrive with higher
expectations. If they wanted to start at the bottom, collecting
faxes or folding shirts, they may have gone to another school, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   During a break in freshman orientation recently, incoming
students and their parents said they have high hopes for the co-op
program. Mollie Bisesi, for instance, said she is coming to
Northeastern for one reason: She wants to know for sure whether to
pursue a career in forensics. Bisesi, 18, of Buffalo, N.Y., could
have gone to Michigan State, the University of Delaware, or Boston
University, but only Northeastern promised legitimate job
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Although she's aware students can get stuck with menial jobs,
Bisesi's confident she won't get a raw deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't stand for being anyone's little helper,'' she said.
``I want to do real work, work that will help me prepare for my
career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-VIGILANTE-PRIEST-BOS &LR;      08-03 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIGILANTE-PRIEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEIZED PHILIPPINE PRIEST STRUGGLES TO TURN THE OTHER CHEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAMITAN, Philippines _ This is the story of a priest who was
kidnapped by Muslim rebels and nearly martyred for his faith, and
who cannot forgive those who trespassed against him.
</P>
<P>
   He struggles with his assigned mission to serve the poor and the
weak, and his adopted role as the spiritual leader of an army of
self-proclaimed, modern-day Crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   He wields the Gospel, but has an M-16 assault rifle ready if he
needs it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ready to die'' for the Roman Catholic Church, Rev. Cirilo
Nacorda said solemnly, his soft, boyish features clouded by a
thousand memories of his capture six years ago, and by as many
demons he has battled since. ``I am ready to be killed _ but I'm
bringing firearms with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nacorda, 43, says he needs an M-16 and a .45-caliber handgun
``not for abuse, but for protection'' from the Muslim rebels who
abducted him and well over 100 other Christians over the past
several years. ``I'm also willing to kill if they have the
intention of killing me or Christians whom I serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Nacorda's former captors are the group that seized 21 people
from a Malaysian resort in late April, and are still holding most
of them on the southern Philippine island of Jolo, 50 miles south
of here. A breakaway faction of Muslim separatists, the Abu Sayyaf,
which once had a clear Islamic agenda, now is more interested in
ransom than in greater rights for Muslims, experts on the rebellion
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be angry only at the Abu Sayyaf, but it seemed I was
angry at all Muslims. . . . I wanted revenge,'' Nacorda said. ``It
took me years to realize that Muslims are innocent and Abu Sayyaf
is a small group trying to divide us. Now I am able to focus my
hate on that group only. Hate is a bad word to use, but I have to
admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   With each new hostage crisis or massacre attributed to the Abu
Sayyaf, the Christians who represent one-third of this tiny island
of 295,000 people feel more embattled. The priest, to the dismay of
the local bishop and to the glee of a military that has failed to
wipe out the Abu Sayyaf, has become the inspiration for armed
Christians who want their justice against those they see as Muslim
troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Here on Basilan Island, Christian militias with ominous names
such as ``Chop-Chop'' and ``Dark World'' have joined to form the
Coalition of New Christians for Empowerment and Reform. CONCERN
claims 3,000 members, 4,000 unregistered fellow travelers, 1,000
financial backers _ and the man they call the ``warrior-priest'' as
their spiritual adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Nacorda admitted to having joined two posses that have searched
for ``known criminals,'' but added quickly, ``God did not allow me
to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Basilan's Bishop Romulo de la Cruz is appalled by Nacorda's ties
to the vigilantes, and fears militias are using the priest to gain
the seal of the church. ``Father Nacorda is not a warrior-priest,
and we are not into the Crusades,'' he said. ``He told me he wanted
to guide them so they will not take the law into their own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not at all clear, however, that the armed and angry
militants would listen even if their mascot-priest told them to
desist.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslims ``want to finish off the Christians,'' said Andy
Anoos, an irascible municipal councillor and member of CONCERN who
says he has led dozens of ambushes on Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Vigilante groups have existed here for almost 30 years, since
the start of a Muslim insurgency that has claimed 100,000 to
200,000 lives in the southern Philippines. Muslims make up 4
percent of the national population, but are a majority on some
islands such as Basilan.
</P>
<P>
   Some community members worry that Nacorda's ties to the militias
could provoke lawless elements to target his parish. Others, such
as municipal councillor Peter Eisma, say the priest's involvement
is to ``promote peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Nacorda's ordeal began on June 8, 1994, with a scene that has
repeated itself many times since, when armed men stopped a convoy
of vehicles. The rebels separated out the Muslims and let them go.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen Christians _ drivers, laborers and others too poor to
pay ransom _ were shot, and half were beheaded. The remainder _
Nacorda and 21 teachers _ were marched for 12 hours to a jungle
hideout. His wrists and ankles were chained so he couldn't escape.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers were released five days later, after the government
forked over a $7,700 ``board and lodging'' fee. But the group held
onto Nacorda.
</P>
<P>
   He said his captors threatened to chop off his head, cut him to
pieces, or shoot him in the back when he stood to urinate. The
rebel commander used him for target practice, hurling knives at his
sides. ``Sometimes I would close my eyes and say, `Just kill me,'
'' Nacorda recalled, his face stiffening.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that Islam was a peace-loving religion. They forced
him to wear a Muslim cleric's cap, jeering at his humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   He cried twice in captivity, once when their camp was bombarded
by marines and he was sure he would die. ``I was praying, `Lord,
protect the soldiers, help them in their rescue operation.' But
after three hours, I saw many soldiers scattered and killed, and I
said, `Lord, you are not listening, you are helping these bad guys.
What kind of a God are you?' I was shouting and crying, and for
three weeks, I stopped praying to the Lord,'' although he continued
to pray to the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The second time, he repented and cried for forgiveness. The same
day, they ambushed again, and Nacorda felt a force stronger than
nature pushing him to the ground. All around him, Abu Sayyaf rebels
were shot down. ``I don't know if you believe in miracles, but
bullets fell without hitting me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After 61 days and a payment, Nacorda was released, and he
insisted on returning to his parish.
</P>
<P>
   Nacorda had begun life here in Lamitan, a backwater town that
even today has no telephone service. He battled his origins, his
family, and the color of his skin to fulfill his dream of being a
priest, and he wasn't about to give up after his rebel ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   It took two months to persuade the bishop to let him stay. ``I
had told my parishoners to be strong, to have faith in the face of
Abu Sayyaf's rise. After that, how could I leave them? A priest
should lead the people, not run away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But neither could he run from the phantoms of his captors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially after my release, but even now, whenever there is a
massacre or kidnapping, I cannot understand my own feelings,''
Nacorda confided in a halting voice. ``Sometimes I would say to my
parish, even during my homily, `If this is a war situation, let's
give them some of their own medicine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Among themselves, parishioners wondered, ``What's happened to
Father Nacorda? He's always angry now.'' They hired a psychiatrist
to counsel him twice, and he poured out his emotions, but mostly he
could only shout and cry. He has been counseled a half-dozen times,
but nothing has made him whole. Last year in Manila, he saw a
psychiatrist, ``but I just cried for three hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Nacorda recently invited Muslim community leaders to his parish
and said he is trying to build a harmonious interfaith
relationship. ``But it's not easy to dialogue when you are
unarmed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop has tried for years to persuade Nacorda to take time
off to recuperate and get some perspective. ``We want him to be
healed,'' de la Cruz said.
</P>
<P>
   With every attack on Christians, wounds open anew for Nacorda. A
fellow Basilan priest, Rev. Rhoel Gallardo, 33, was kidnapped a few
months ago by Abu Sayyaf and killed in an encounter with the
military. ``Each time something happens, it triggers my anger,''
Nacorda said. ``I would really like to undergo healing, but I
cannot afford to be away from my parish.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Cruz disagrees. ``Nobody is indispensable in Basilan.
Perhaps he'll have a different perspective when he comes back.
Basilan will still be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six years to the day since his release, Nacorda admits
that his inner struggle between shepherding his flock and healing
his soul continues. ``Even though I am broken, wounded, I can be
useful. . . . But when I am alone in my room, alone in a silent
place, that is when I struggle to control myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
