<HEADLINE>
ROGUE TO RICHES: AN 18TH-CENTURY ACCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MILLIONAIRE 
The Philanderer, Gambler, and Duelist Who Invented Modern Finance 
By Janet Gleeson 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 303 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Law had the misfortune to be born 300 years too early. Had
he lived in our time, he would have been celebrated as a visionary
and an entrepreneur. He would have been on the cover of Time
Magazine, along with Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   In early 18th-century France, Law specialized in coming up with
new enterprises _ first a national bank, then the Mississippi
Company, a speculative venture that invested in colonizing America.
For a brief time Law's company captivated France and set off a
stock-market boom that made lots of people rich.
</P>
<P>
   But just as quickly the boom turned to bust as it became clear
the Mississippi Company's claims were mostly hype. Alas for Law,
the Parisians of his day were not as tolerant of money-losing firms
as we are today. They tried to hang Law and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Vive la difference.
</P>
<P>
   Law's life is the subject of ``Millionaire,'' a generally lively
biography by Janet Gleeson. The subtitle of the book lets you know
you are dealing with an interesting character. Law, in fact, liked
to gamble, dated lots of women, and killed a rival in a duel. And
he was interested in financial innovation, especially in banking.
</P>
<P>
   The European economies of Law's day all suffered from the same
problem: too little money. The amount of money in circulation
depended on finding new gold and silver. If new supplies were not
forthcoming, economic activity was constrained. Law and others saw
the solution in paper money, which could be backed by gold and
silver. If people would accept paper _ a big ``if'' in that era _
the supply of money could expand dramatically, and so could the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   A Scot by birth, Law couldn't sell his scheme in his home
country. He had better luck in France, where he fled after his
duel. In 1716 he started the Banque Generale, which later became
the Banque Royale, the official government bank. Letting the
government take over the bank was Law's first big mistake. The
government had a great temptation to print too much money, which
over time was bound to erode confidence in the bank and in paper
money in general.
</P>
<P>
   Law's second big mistake was selling shares in the Mississippi
Company, a government plan to develop the Louisiana territory. ``No
one knew what riches lay beneath its soil or within its forest,''
writes Gleeson of Louisiana, ``but it was whispered that this new
Eldorado was copiously endowed with seams of gold and silver with
emerald mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Substitute ``e-commerce'' for ``gold and silver'' and you get
some idea how excited investors became. The mere promises of riches
triggered an incredible bull market in Mississippi shares.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels to today are striking. Ordinary people were drawn
into the stock market. Law's coachman made so much money he quit
his job and hired his own coachman. The money earned in the market
led to a huge run-up in real estate prices and a boom in luxury
goods. Elegant cafes opened up where the newly rich could drink
fancy coffee ``while their brokers made them rich.'' How do you say
Starbucks in French?
</P>
<P>
   Information didn't travel as fast 300 years ago as it does
today, but eventually news filtered back from the New World that
the Louisiana colony was a loser. Investors lost confidence in Law,
shares prices plunged, and things turned ugly. Law barely escaped
from France with his life and spent his final years in exile. Along
the way he invested in art, including works by Titian, Raphael, and
Michelangelo. Clearly the man had a knack for being ahead of his
time.
</P>
<P>
   Gleeson's account of Law's life loses energy once the stock
market bubble bursts. The author is also never able to explain
convincingly how a smart guy like Law could make such disastrous
errors. Still, Law's story illustrates the timeless appeal of
investing and the hope, usually unrealized, that the new thing will
make us all rich. As the French say, ``Plus ca change . . .''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1347EDT &QL; 
