<HEADLINE>
`VEINY' WOOD, A SPIRAL GARDEN, AND A PLAGUE OF YELLOWISH STAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A little here and a little there on a lazy summer afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a question from J. Murman of Moline, Ill.:
</P>
<P>
   ``I painted my new wainscoting that the carpenter said was
somewhat `veiny.' When painted twice, the veins showed through. The
paneling is not smooth. Would more paint help or must the paneling
be sanded?''
</P>
<P>
   I think your wainscoting is oak, and oak is an open-pored wood.
So is mahogany, and walnut, but most wainscoting sold today is oak.
There are no open-pored softwoods that I know of.
</P>
<P>
   Those ``veins'' are the pores. When painted, the pores will
appear as little pockmarks or shallow streaks, no matter how many
coats of paint are applied. The paint simply will not fill them,
and the finish as a result is not smooth.
</P>
<P>
   There is a cure, and it does not involve heavy sanding. To get
the finish smooth, fill the pores with a paste wood filler. It is
not the same as wood filler used to fill nail holes. It is more
runny than paste, and can be painted on the surface. Paint it
against the grain, let it set for a few minutes, rub the filler
into the pores against the grain with a rough cloth; then rub
lightly with the grain.
</P>
<P>
   Filling the pores is best done on bare wood, but I think it can
be done on a painted surface as well. After drying overnight, sand
the finish smooth.
</P>
<P>
   If the filler does not stay in the painted pores, then the
wainscoting must, indeed, be sanded before filling.
</P>
<P>
   When you repaint, use a latex primer-sealer before applying the
finish coats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A spiral garden
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to innovating in the garden, you can't beat Bill
Downey, who made the most of a huge maple tree in his front yard.
</P>
<P>
   His yard is pretty well full of the usual things that grow in
summer.
</P>
<P>
   But Downey, 64, looked at the venerable maple and decided to
improve on it. Improving on a noble maple is quite an
accomplishment, but Downey did it.
</P>
<P>
   He bought two dozen square plastic flower pots, filled them with
annuals, and tacked them on the tree in a spiral, sort of like a
corkscrew, twisting up the tree higher than he could reach. A few
small nails or screws driven into a large maple tree will not hurt
it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great way of showing annuals: petunias, impatiens,
geraniums, and other plants that bloom brightly all summer, before
and after perennials have faded.
</P>
<P>
   When neighbors saw what Downey had done, they said, ``Call the
Globe!''
</P>
<P>
   He did, and the rest is history, with Downey's grandchildren
getting their picture in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those yellow stains
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellow stains. They're a plague on white vinyl kitchen floors,
it seems. The handyman gets many questions asking what they are,
what causes them, and most important, how to get rid of them.
</P>
<P>
   They are chemical stains, caused by water, and seem to hit only
white vinyl floors, although other colored floors may get them but
they are less visible.
</P>
<P>
   They cannot be removed, but can be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what Armstrong, maker of vinyl flooring, sent to the
handyman:
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong's vinyl floors have been formulated to be very stain
resistant to most reagents and traffic. Certain compounds added to
rubber can discolor a vinyl floor when in contact with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``These compounds, referred to as antioxidants, are formulated
into rubber material to extend the life of the rubber and prevent
brittleness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some antioxidants react chemically with ingredients
(plasticizers) in flexible vinyl to produce a yellowish stain. This
is referred to in the vinyl industry as `antioxidant staining.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Any source of rubber containing these antioxidants in contact
with the floor could produce this staining. Certain types of rubber
mats, rubber-backed rugs and rubber wheels on carts can cause this
discoloration.
</P>
<P>
   ``To avoid this problem, insure that the mats and wheels which
will be in contact with vinyl floors are of the `non-staining' type
of rubber.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   While water does not cause the stains, water is often associated
with them because rubber mats on the vinyl (the real cause of the
stain) often get water trapped under them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
