<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS PREPARE TO ANOINT BUSH AS CONVENTION ENTERS ITS FINAL
DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS Cheney quote in 5th graf from end (bgng `Governor Bush
doesn't...') to CORRECT `lights' to `lines' ; adds art note ) 
 (EDS: This early version will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a
story by R.W. Apple Jr.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 &HT;     
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republicans opened the final day of their
national convention Thursday, preparing to make Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas their presidential nominee and relishing the fight that he
has already started with his democratic rival, Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush officially became the party's nominee during Wednesday
night's roll call vote, when delegates from Wyoming _ the home
state of his running mate, Dick Cheney _ cast votes that put him
over the 1,034 convention votes needed for a majority. But the big
balloon-dropping celebration will come Thursday night when the last
of the 2,066 delegate votes will be delivered from the floor of the
First Union Center by the Texas delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening will be a defining moment in Bush's political
career. He and his speechwriter have been working for weeks on the
acceptance speech the governor will deliver before a nationwide
audience, albeit one that is likely smaller than in past
presidential elections. The campaign hopes the remarks will signal
to the nation that Bush is a different kind of conservative who has
transformed his party to appeal to groups that are not
traditionally receptive to the Republicans' message.
</P>
<P>
   It is also likely that Bush will devote a good portion of his
speech to critiquing the Clinton-Gore team. His spokeswoman, Karen
P. Hughes, has said that Bush will lament the current
administration's failure to accomplish critical tasks.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to his arrival here Wednesday, Bush
became increasingly aggressive in his criticism of Gore and of
President Bill Clinton. Bush's running mate, Cheney, turned up the
volume even more on Wednesday night in his acceptance speech,
bringing thunderous applause from the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all a little weary of the Clinton-Gore routine,''
Cheney told cheering Republicans. ``But the wheel has turned.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney tried to turn the vice president's own words against him.
Appropriating Gore's 1992 campaign slogan as his own, Cheney said,
``It is time for them to go!''
</P>
<P>
   While the attacks on the Clinton-Gore administration are popular
with the Republican rank and file, the Texas governor is also
trying to persuade independent voters, who in the last two
elections embraced the centrist position to which Clinton has moved
the Democratic Party, that Bush has transformed his party. But Bush
must also be careful not to alienate the conservatives who are the
Republicans' bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the opening days of the convention were devoted to
projecting a centrist image, with issues like immigration and
education dominating a stage filled with racially diverse speakers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many previous conventions, candidates in hard-fought
congressional races _ like Rep. Rick Lazio of New York, who is
battling Hillary Rodham Clinton for a Senate seat from New York _
were kept out of the spotlight. So too were many elements of the
Republicans' battles with President Clinton over the last six
years. Issues like family values, abortion rights and the culture
wars were not showcased.
</P>
<P>
   Bush used the week leading up to the convention to pacify
conservative delegates. He allowed a plank opposing all abortion
rights to stand and chose a conservative running mate with a voting
record to match.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A good portion of the news in Philadelphia has happened outside
the convention hall. Former President Gerald Ford was hospitalized
on Wednesday after suffering what physicians say was a minor
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Police also arrested hundreds of protesters after they blocked
traffic and held dozens of loosely coordinated demonstrations. But
the protests have been largely non-violent and nowhere near the
magnitude that city officials and convention organizers feared.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Much feistiness has occurred on the convention stage, and it has
come from Republican leaders raining blows on the Democrats.
Wednesday night, the Republicans showed their knuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Senate majority leader, used
his nominating speech for Cheney to deliver pointed criticism of
congressional Democrats opposed to tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But that was just a prelude to the main event of the evening,
when Cheney opened his speech by praising Bush for reaching out to
Democrats and governing in a bipartisan manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush doesn't accept old lines of argument and
division,'' Cheney said. ``He brings people together, reaching
across party lines to do the party's business.''
</P>
<P>
   But after condemning partisan bitterness and strife, Cheney
himself launched into a lengthy attack on Gore and Clinton. He
criticized the current administration for ``legalisms and carefully
worded denials,'' and for ``spreading fear and panic'' and
``dividing generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviving a criticism first made by former Sen. Bill Bradley,
Gore's rival in the primaries earlier this year, Cheney portrayed
Gore as a man who would make ``a thousand promises, a thousand
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also criticized the Clinton administration for failing to
reform Social Security, improve the nation's schools or maintain
the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offer another way, a better way, and a stiff dose of
truth,'' Cheney said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0114 </DOCNO>
