<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and f coding)  
 THE 1958 DUAL-GHIA WAS A CONCEPT AS LOFTY AS ITS FINS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are cruisin' through the rolling southwest Vermont
countryside like a land shark: sleek nose, fins raking the air like
razors.
</P>
<P>
   I've got both hands on a steering wheel that seems as big as the
wheel on a sailboat and the car's suspension lets it float enough
up front that you feel that you might, indeed, be making your way
over the water.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but we've also got a 329-hemi _ two four-barreled carbs and
400 horsepower _ under the hood. And we've got history on our side.
That's because we're behind the wheel of a Dual-Ghia 400, a one-off
prototype built for the 1958 New York Auto Show.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen this car before and now, at an invitational
drive-and-ride at Hemmings Motor News headquarters in Bennington,
Vt., and thanks to the trust and generosity of this rare car's
owner, I'm behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   That owner is Fred Kanter, who with brother Dan founded Kanter
Auto Parts, a major supplier of restoration parts for collector
cars. Fred Kanter was 13 when the car caught his eye at the auto
show. In 1977, three hours after he heard its owner had put it up
for sale, he bought it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it basks in unretouched original glory. The thick coat of
Italian paint that covers its Ghia body is cracked like enamel in
places, but original. The roof, patched here and there, is original
as well. Everything about the car remains as built by Dual Motors
of Detroit more than four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Its wedge shape was developed in a wind tunnel _ a first for its
day. Beneath its Italian-designer skin lurks a 1957 Chrysler 300C,
kin to the hottest cars of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The inside, chrome and leather _ even the door handles are woven
leather straps _ is part art deco, part fine Italian furniture.
It's three-speed Torqueflite automatic transmission is operated by
five rectangular buttons at the center of the dash. There is no
parking gear. To start the Dual-Ghia, you turn the key, then push
the ``Neutral'' button.
</P>
<P>
   You get a throaty, basso rumble that veritably roars when you
stomp the gas on the highway. You get a ride right out of the past
and, should you choose, you get Percy Faith and His Orchestra
playing from ``Romantic Moods'' on the 16 2/3-r.p.m. record player
built into the dash. You get a top speed of 140 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, you get to drive a piece of history, a car far ahead
of its time, whose shape, style, and power have been found in cars
down the decades ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But driving pieces out of history is what this annual Hemmings
event for automotive journalists, choice collectors, and others
with industry connections is all about, and here are some other
notables available for them to play with:
</P>
<P>
   --Besides the Dual-Ghia, my favorite was a 1946 Ford Super
DeLuxe station wagon. You'd recognize it immediately as a
``Woody.'' What you might not recognize it as is an early SUV. Sits
high, has huge legroom, headroom, three bench seats, plenty of
cargo space. The lingering throwback is the presence of two
ashtrays built into the dash _ back from the days when even doctors
told us in ads that cigarettes were good for us. A predictor of
things to come in SUVs is the gas mileage: 12-15 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   --In fact, driving old cars shows you how far we have come in
gas-mileage figures. Most six- and eight-cylinder cars from back
then got between 10 and 20 miles per gallon. The 1957 Ford Custom
V8, the 1940 Buick Century, and the Hudson Terraplane delivery
sedan all got 10-13. By 1958 you had a Volvo PV 445 that delivered
a whopping 15-20 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   --And of further interest at the Hemmings ride-and-drive: a 1973
Volvo P1800ES 2(plus)2. Always looked like an interesting sports
car to me. Drives like a truck. A 1934 Ford Tow Truck _ 90
horsepower V-8 engine, $600 new, about $175 extra for the
hand-cranked crane at the rear. And a 1930 Ford ``Doodlebug'' _ a
Sears, Roebuck creation with a ladder frame, 40-horsepower engine,
open cockpit, and gear-driven (as in gears at each end of the rear
axle transferring power to gears that line the inside of the rear
wheels). Talk about low-range torque.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
