<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1656 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-03 1645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAUNCHY LYRICS REQUIRE REAL CONVERSATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost everywhere Deirdre Houtmeyers goes these days, she brings
along a portable CD player, thrusts the headset at friends, and
fast-forwards to a rap song called ``Kim.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she watches her friends' horrified expressions.
</P>
<P>
   Houtmeyers is definitely into this for the shock value, but not
in the way you might think. A mother of two who lives in Belmont,
Mass., she hopes listening to the lyrics of rapper Eminem will be a
wake-up call to other parents, just as it was for her a few weeks
ago when her 15-year-old nephew handed her a headset and said,
``You need to know what your kids are listening to.'' He was
worried. He had heard 11-year-old Nick hum an Eminem song.
</P>
<P>
   When Ryan played ``Kim'' for her, Houtmeyers recalls, ``I could
feel the blood draining from my face. It frightened me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim'' is one of the cuts on Eminem's most recent,
much-publicized, top-selling album, ``The Marshall Mathers LP.''
It's a story of a husband who puts his baby to bed, then kidnaps
and murders his wife. The track contains words that are unprintable
here and vivid sound effects (gurgling as he cuts Kim's throat).
Eminem is a Grammy-winning white rapper from Detroit whose real
name is Marshall Mathers and whose wife is Kim. Their stormy
relationship, including her suicide attempt last month, has been
entertainment news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants their kids listening to this? Not me,'' Houtmeyers
says.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Eminem is the first or only songwriter to glorify
violence and profanity. As Globe colleague Renee Graham wrote
earlier this summer, there's a long tradition in music of
blood-drenched lyrics. Still, parents like Houtmeyers and teenagers
like her nephew are wise to be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   When Houtmeyers asked her son, Nick, about the music, his answer
was typical: ``It's only a song, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of answer worries sociologist Gail Dines, an associate
professor at Wheelock College. ``If it doesn't get a rise from a
child, it means they don't even see there's a problem,'' she says.
``That's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   She blames the nonchalance on our culture: ``It's so awash with
violence that children learn from an early age to accept it as
normal: not a big deal, just a song, just a video.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not so much that one song or one video can trigger a young
person to aberrant behavior, although that does sometimes happen,
says popular culture researcher Michael Marsden of Eastern Kentucky
University. ``The bigger issue,'' he says, ``is that children see
violence as an acceptable solution to problems in general because
that's the message they get over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   This has particularly serious implications for women, says
Houtmeyers. As a nurse and cochairwoman of the Domestic Violence
Taskforce at St. Elizabeth's Medical Center in Brighton, Mass., she
works with women who have absorbed the message that abounds in rap
lyrics: ``I'm not worth much. I deserve it if my boyfriend/husband
whacks me around.'' The message men get, she says, is that it's OK
to beat up a woman who displeases them for any reason, from
cheating to folding the laundry wrong.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Kim' is a blueprint for domestic violence,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents have a hard time believing the media have such a
powerful influence. They do, but they don't have to, Dines says.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, the developmental need teenagers have to
separate from their parents. ``It's something they're hard-wired to
do,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-cultural studies show they aren't hard-wired to separate
rebelliously, however. We've come to accept that the two go hand in
hand, says Dines, ``because the media in this country takes the
need to separate and shapes it into rebellion through consumer fads
like body piercing, tatooing, and rap.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes this more worrisome than in previous generations is
the level of violence. ``To get kids to buy your product, you have
to be more and more outrageous, which today translates to more and
more violent,'' Dines says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making the connections
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once teens understand the connections between the media,
consumerism, and real-life violence, they tend to become more
critical as consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are usually appalled and insulted. They don't like being
manipulated,'' says Jeff O'Brien, director of Northeastern
University's Mentors in Violence Prevention Program. Funded by the
state Department of Public Health, the free program is in 20 high
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what O'Brien does is help teenagers deconstruct cultural
messages and get them talking about the issues so they don't
automatically buy into them. Marsden says this kind of media
literacy is undervalued and underutilized in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most neglected part of kids' education,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Social historian Joe Boskin of Boston University, who studies
the connection between values and violence, wishes schools would
make these connections for kids in fifth and sixth grade. In fact,
he wishes they'd start this fall with ``Kim.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Kim'' is not yet being played on Boston-area stations
because it hasn't been released as a single, ``you know kids even
this young are hearing this song. If not this one, then other ones
just as bad. It's part of their social currency,'' says Boskin.
Indeed, he sees a danger in not talking about it: ``In the absence
of discussion, we leave them to their peers' interpretation, which
accepts messages at face value.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parents' dilemma
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giving them our spin presents a different problem.
</P>
<P>
   It means we need to listen to music most of us don't like. Even
if we do listen, we can't always understand it, so we either pay no
attention or, like Houtmeyers's sister, Carmel O'Doherty-Popp, we
ban it.
</P>
<P>
   She says, ``After my sister played `Kim' for me, I told my kids,
`I need to know the words you listen to. Since I can't understand
most of the words on the rap stations, no more rap stations.' ''
She has five children, 6 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   For children under 10, family rules about radio stations, like a
no-TV rule on school nights or no PG-13 movie rule, is something
they understand and even welcome. It helps them feel parents are
keeping them safe.
</P>
<P>
   With children over 10, censorship is problematic. ``They see you
as the parent who is not cool and doesn't understand,'' says Dines.
It also makes what you ban more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, however, it doesn't give them tools to make
informed decisions. Marsden tells parents, ``This is a chance to
reinforce your values, to put the media messages in a context that
says clearly, `This is not normal behavior.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raising the issue
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to do that:
</P>
<P>
   --Don't pay for music whose values you don't like: ``I can't
stop you from using your own money, but I don't want my money to
support this musician or his message, and here's why.''
</P>
<P>
   --Initiate conversations. About ``Kim,'' for instance: ``What do
you think of what he says? How does it make you feel to hear women
called derogatory names? Have you ever been mad enough to want to
hit a teacher or parent? Did you? Why/why not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you want to get to,'' says O'Brien, ``is that acting in a
violent way is a choice we don't have to make.''
</P>
<P>
   He frequently begins classroom conversation by asking, ``If you
saw a guy pushing a girl against a locker, what would you
think/do?'' When teens say it's none of their business, he talks
about how we learn behaviors that are antisocial.
</P>
<P>
   Some teens may be defensive if you talk about a rapper they
like. ``Don't let that stop you,'' says Dines.
</P>
<P>
   Her theory is that many children are walking around with low
levels of post-traumatic stress syndrome. ``The view they have
developed of the world is that it's a dangerous, violent place,''
she says. ``They are secretly reassured to hear what you have to
say, even if they don't tell you so.''
</P>
<P>
   Few teens will be won over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't even expect that,'' says Marsden. ``Your goal is to get
them to think about the issues you raise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One mother's goal
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houtmeyers's goal is to get an 800 number so parents can hear
``Kim'' and other lyrics without putting money into rappers' or CD
producers' pockets. (Speaking of producers, Eminem's label,
Interscope Records, did not return calls.) She also intends to be
more attentive and involved with her sons about media issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a parent, a woman, and a human being, I cannot not react to
this,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Suggestions for parents &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Other rappers to be wary of for their violent and offensive
lyrics include Juvenile, DMX, Jay-Z, Wu Tang Clan, and Sisqo,
according to Jeff O'Brien of Northeastern Unviversity.
</P>
<P>
   --It's not enough to have one or two conversations with your
kids about the values popular culture presents. To make a
difference, dialogues need to happen frequently.
</P>
<P>
   --Be explicit with both sons and daughters: ``This song can
subconsciously make a woman think she deserves to have a man treat
her badly/a man think it's OK to treat a woman badly. I want to
make sure you know that's never true.''
</P>
<P>
   --The leading cause of injury in the United States to women age
15 to 44 is men hitting them, according to the National Coalition
against Domestic Violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recently published: `Go to Your Room!
Consequences That Teach'' by Shari Steelsmith (Raefield-Roberts
Publishers). A little book but full of everyday problems. You may
not agree with all the solutions, but there's a lot of food for
thought here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com. Globe
contributing reporter David Fernandez helped research this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
