<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GREEN-HOTELS-ART-BOS &LR;      08-03 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-HOTELS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HOTELS URGE GUESTS TO SAVE WATER, ENERGY, REUSE LINEN  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHRYN TONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though William Moran is an administrative law judge at the
US Environmental Protection Agency in Washington, he would rather
have fresh sheets in his hotel room every day than reuse them to
conserve water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that since I'm with the EPA I should say that I want to
conserve water, but I like clean sheets and a freshly-made bed,``
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moran, 50, was in Boston recently for a two-day business meeting
and stayed at the Copley Square Hotel, which offers guests the
option of reusing towels and sheets during their stay at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to save money and to preserve the environment, many
hotels are asking guests to reuse their towels and sheets.
</P>
<P>
   It's a practice that has become commonplace in Europe and Asia.
Now US hotels are placing cards on doors and bedside tables urging
guests, ``Please reuse the towels.'' They tell guests to leave
towels on the floor if they want new ones or to hang them back up
if they want to reuse them.
</P>
<P>
   At the Boston Park Plaza Hotel, customers move a card from the
nightstand to their pillow if they don't want their sheets changed,
said Christopher Vicalora, the hotel's manager. The hotel
automatically changes every person's linen after the third day, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Moran had the option of recycling his linens, he said
he would not participate in the program. ``If I go out late and
come home and don't have the chance to take a shower, I want new
sheets the next day,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine hotels in New England participate in linen reuse
programs, said Patricia Skozelas, marketing representative for
Project Planet, a Georgia-based provider of environmental products
for the hospitality industry. The company's clients include Bass
Hotels &AMP; Resorts, the owner of Holiday Inn hotels, and Choice
Hotels, which owns Comfort Inn.
</P>
<P>
   An average-sized hotel with 150 rooms and 66 percent guest
participation can save about $32,000 a year by implementing a
linen- and towel-reuse program, said Skozelas. Savings come not
only from reducing water use, but also from reducing linen
purchases and the labor cost of doing laundry, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hotels are always looking to save money,'' said Arthur Canter,
executive director of the Massachusetts Lodging Association, the
industry's trade association.
</P>
<P>
   Many hotels contract with companies like Project Planet and the
``Green'' Hotels Association, a Houston-based, for-profit
organization promoting ecological consciousness, to supply the
cards requesting reuse of linen and towels. Hotels are afraid ``it
can come off as being cheap'' if the hotel apprears to initiate the
request, said Patricia Griffin, president of the ``Green'' Hotels
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The savings far outweigh the cost of buying the cards: Project
Planet sells a pack of 100 cards for $60.
</P>
<P>
   The water conservation benefits are significant. Project Planet
estimates that 72 million gallons of water would be saved if 11,000
hotels out of the 45,000 hotels in the United States participated
in a linen-reuse programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a crazy thing to demand fresh sheets and towels
everyday,' said Griffin. ``No one does that at home.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 40 percent of hotels with 250 rooms or more
participated in the program, according to the American Hotel &AMP;
Motel Association in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a wonderful response from guests,'' said Tedd
Saunders, executive vice president of the Saunders Hotel Group,
which includes the Lennox Hotel and the Copley Square Hotel in
Boston. The hotel group has had a linen-reuse program in place
since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders, also president of EcoLogical Solutions, a Boston-based
consulting firm to hotels, says that 40 percent of guests staying
at his hotels reuse their towels.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Green'' Hotels Association, which provides response cards
for guests staying at member hotels, says that business travelers
are most enthusiastic about recycling their towels.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Mars, a computer trainer for CompuMasters in Kansas,
travels on business twice a month and said he does not mind using
the same towel and sheets for more than a day.
</P>
<P>
   Mars, who originally thought that hotels were using the program
to save money, now hangs his towel back on the rack, signaling to
the hotel not to wash it. Although Mars said he did not notice the
linen reuse signs during his recent two-day stay at the Boston Park
Plaza Hotel, he said he has seen them at other hotels and always
participates in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the hotel changes the sheets in between guests,
that is the important thing,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Park Plaza Hotel has found that older guests prefer
to have their towels cleaned every day, while younger guests reuse
their towels, said Vicalora.
</P>
<P>
   Some hotels, like the Lenox and Copley Square hotels, have
implemented other enviromental programs, including
``climate-neutral rooms,'' which use renewable energy so that none
of the rooms have a negative impact on global warming, Saunders
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some hotels remain concerned about how guests will perceive the
quality of service if the hotel participates in the reuse program.
</P>
<P>
   The Harborside Hyatt in Boston cleans all three sheets on every
bed so that customers ``always sleep on clean bedding,'' said David
Martin, general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Although the hotel has won the Massachusetts Lodging Award for
recycling and energy conservation, the hotel has never considered a
linen-reuse program, Martin said. Because an average guest stays
1.1 nights, a reuse program would have very little water and cost
savings, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS &LR;      08-03 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON WORKERS SEEK SURVIVAL IN THE WIRELESS AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The differences between the two sides couldn't be starker.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is the old-line Bell Atlantic telephone company,
whose workers are unionized; on the other side is the new and
quickly expanding Verizon Wireless unit, whose employees are
nonunion and have less job security.
</P>
<P>
   At issue: the old economy workers want to unionize their new
economy counterparts. Verizon Communications, formerly Bell
Atlantic, says no.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 85,000 telephone workers on the East Coast are threatening
a walkout at 12:01 a.m. Sunday that, for both sides, underscores
concerns about survival in the wireless age.
</P>
<P>
   A strike by members of both the Communications Workers of
America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers
could cripple services to some 25 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   A central sticking issue is the labor groups' demand for the
right to voluntarily unionize the company's rapidly growing
wireless unit without interference from management. Currently, only
45 of the unit's 30,000 employees are union members.
</P>
<P>
   The unions also want higher wages, pension changes, and job
security for all workers, but the push to unionize Verizon Wireless
is, perhaps, the most critical matter on the table, say analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for wireless telephones has made the unit one of the
fastest growing divisions at Verizon, and it has fueled concerns
that such explosive growth will lead to increased hiring of
lower-paid, nonunion employees and a corresponding push to shed
traditional, old-line telephone workers.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in a walkout that focused largely on Bell
Atlantic's use of nonunion contractors and on who would fill jobs
created by new technologies such as the Internet, more than 70,000
telephone service representatives struck. Though the 2 1/2-day
strike granted some concessions to workers, it excluded employees
in cellular and wireless services from the contract.
</P>
<P>
   CWA represents 72,000 telephone workers. IBEW represents 13,000.
Of that 85,000, about 15,000 work in the New England region. Of
Verizon's total work force of 260,000, about 120,000 are local
phone company employees.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a push to gain a foothold in the rapidly expanding
wireless market, CWA President Morton Bahr says failure to secure a
satisfactory contract, including language permitting expedited
union elections or a voluntary card check agreement, could result
in a strike. Under voluntary card checks, companies agree to
recognize a union as the bargaining agent for their workers if a
majority of employees sign union cards.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Verizon likely will oppose any attempts to
unionize employees at its wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, what we are seeing with the unions and the company
is a transition from the old economy to the new economy or
marketplace within the telephone industry,'' said Atlanta analyst
Jeffrey Kagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company, in order to protect its competitive position and
subsequently its shareholder values, is going to fight this,'' he
added. ``Its ability to compete relies on having a low-cost
structure, and it can't charge too much for its products. So,
unionization in the wireless sector could be a ball and chain on
the playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   For the unions, the issue is just as critical. Having gained a
toe-hold at a handful of wireless companies, they are fighting to
secure membership in a subsidiary that, by all accounts, is an
industry leader. Unions are hoping a win at Verizon Wireless will
result in a domino effect that will trigger union expansion in the
industry as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fastest-growing area in the industry,'' said
Elaine Bernard, director of the Harvard University Trade Union
Program. ``It is also a life and death issue for the IBEW and the
CWA. If they do not break into these units, they will die, because
the other end of the industry is not growing. So this is not an
issue where either side will back down easily.''
</P>
<P>
   To bolster their argument, the unions point to the erosion of
pay and working conditions as key reasons to organize wireless
service units at Verizon and other leading firms.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, the CWA has made a little headway,
organizing about 5,000 wireless workers at SBC Communications. The
wireless division, which includes CellularOne, employs 14,400.
</P>
<P>
   At AT&AMP;T Wireless, meanwhile, the unions have won the right to
use a voluntary card check procedure and began organizing a few
months ago. If a majority of workers sign cards, an election can be
held within 10 days and certified by the American Arbitration
Association, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, 120 wireless workers based at an AT&AMP;T West Palm Beach,
Fla., unit have been organized. AT&AMP;T employs 22,000 wireless
workers.
</P>
<P>
   For both unions, there is another key concern: the decline of
union membership. In 1984, the year deregulation forced the breakup
of Bell Telephone, CWA boasted 500,000 members in the telephone
industry alone. Today, it represents 300,000 telephone workers
throughout the United States, a loss both labor leaders and
analysts attribute to automation and technological advancements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want a strike, but we will walk out if we cannot
settle key issues such as the unionization of Verizon Wireless,
increases in pay, job security, and certain pension issues,'' said
CWA spokesman Jeffrey Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that wireless communications and
Internet-related communications are the future growth areas in this
industry,'' he added. ``We want to give our people the opportunity
to move into these markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller argued that the lower-paid unit eventually could
undermine earnings at other divisions within the company. He said
service representatives at the top of the pay scale in the wireless
unit earn approximately $33,000 per year, $11,000 less than their
unionized colleagues in other divisions.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in an internal memo obtained by The Boston Globe,
Verizon disputed union wage reports that recently appeared in The
New York Times, saying senior service representatives in the
wireless division earn between $23,000 and $47,500, with annual
bonuses tied to job classifications and assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said union service representatives work 37.5 hours, but
Verizon Wireless service representatives work 40 hours per week for
the same pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Verizon Wireless worker has to work 40 hours before he or
she is eligible for overtime,'' he contnued. ``Our people are
guaranteed overtime after 7.5 hours a day. Health care is fully
paid for union workers. Wireless workers get HMO coverage but do
not have plan choice. They pay up to $210 per year toward HMO
coverage for a single person and up to $672 for family coverage.
They also pay for dental care. Our people do not. Plus, wireless
workers have no job security. Our people have protections against
layoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Verizon again disputed the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bell Atlantic Mobile (now Verizon Wireless) people actually
received 100 percent matching funds in their 401(k) programs for
the past three years,'' the company wrote in the memo. ``The actual
range of annual health-care costs to employees, depending upon the
coverage they elect, is $210 to $924.''
</P>
<P>
   Verizon spokesman Steve Marcus said the firm wants to see a
satisfactory resolution of the issues, but pointed to competition
as a central concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wireless business is really different from our wireline
phone business,'' said Marcus. ``It does not have a history of
union representation. It competes mostly with other companies that
are primarily nonunion. Yes, we are committed to fair compensation,
but we have to be able to compete and succeed in the face of rapid
changes. To do that, we have to offer compensation that is typical
for the work these employees do.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus said the company is continuing to expand its traditional
business, and has added some 3,000 workers, all union members, in
New York, New England, and the mid-Atlantic states. ``That is
tangible proof that this business is dynanmic and it has a great
future for union-represented employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, recent reports of second-quarter earnings at some of the
nation's biggest telecommunications firms suggest the biggest gains
these days are in new technology. AT&AMP;T Wireless Group, for example,
reported $2.5 billion in sales in the second quarter, its first as
a public company. The firm's gains were 32 percent higher than a
year ago. The company also reported a record 532,000 new
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the traditional consumer telephone market is being
battered by losses due to decreased prices, a crowded field of
competitors, and new advances in cellular and Internet phone
services that do not bill consumers for long-distance calls. With
wireless phones gaining popularity, even traditional local
telephone services may be threatened by the trend.
</P>
<P>
   That's what worries the unions. Indeed, nearly two decades after
the first wave of layoffs in manufacturing, telecommunications, and
focused attention on the technology revolution, many unions are
still smarting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past several years, we've seen extensive job loss due
to new technology,'' said CWA's Miller. ``We've also seen the
industry move into these new areas because that's where the growth
is. We know we have to be able to organize those areas so that we
can negotiate good standards and offer our members job mobility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
