<HEADLINE>
`QUEEN OF STEAM' HAS PRESSING NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to a recent survey, Bostonians lead the nation in
ironing curtains, but rank near the bottom for ironing T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   At least one respondent to the poll, conducted by the Rowenta
company, Medford, Mass. maker of $100 German-engineered irons, said
the hood of a car, presumably in a garage, was the pressing surface
of choice. Others ironed on a photo album or, not really
recommended, on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Some admitted to ironing nude.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara ``Queen of Steam'' Zagnoni, consumer education director
for Rowenta, takes all this in stride, hoping to spread the gospel
of ironing to those who find it too time-consuming, annoying, or
even destructive toward white shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Zagnoni kicked off a nationwide ironing tour in Boston in late
July, saying the first mistake of the wrinkled masses is buying a
$12 iron with an imprecise thermostat, which causes the appliance
to leak and spit or scorch clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Buy the right iron _ a Rowenta, of course _ and the job would be
so much easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to go over things more than once, you're working
too hard,'' said Zagnoni, who began ironing at age 12 when her
mother returned to work. ``You need more steam.''
</P>
<P>
   She demonstrated on a blue pinstripe oxford, explaining how a
shirt could and should be ironed in less than five minutes,
especially with a machine like hers that glides with the ease of a
BMW thanks, she said, to all the dimples on the soleplate.
</P>
<P>
   First, start with the back of the collar, placed toward the
narrow end of the ironing board, then move to the yoke and the
cuffs and the sleeves. Next, iron the front, then the back, and
finish with the exposed part of the collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you iron those other things last, you wrinkle the body
again,'' Zagnoni says.
</P>
<P>
   As for pants, begin by ironing the pocket pouches. The front
crease should approach the waistline. The rear crease should stop
at the ``crotch line.'' Don't just press one side of the slacks.
</P>
<P>
   Pleated skirts? Pin the pleats and iron in sections.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with the right iron, there should be no need for starch,
she says. If you insist, go light on spraying and let the garment
sit for a minute before ironing. Otherwise, one risks having the
starch stick to the iron, leaving those black smudges that can rub
off on clothes. There are cleaners available at hardware stores to
rid irons of the gunk, according to Zagnoni.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the need for her advice, Zagnoni insists ironing is not
a lost art, especially in these days of casual dressing. As proof,
she said Rowenta's sales have more than doubled over the last few
years. (However, the company does not disclose revenue figures.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole new generation of people who are ironing, and
it's due to that trend: casual attire,'' Zagnoni said.
</P>
<P>
   Advice for Boston: Forget about the curtains. Press your khakis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
