u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      08-03 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLERS MAY BE BEST WAY TO MOVE SHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have an 8- by 16-foot shed that I want to move from one
part of the yard to another. Is it feasible to put the shed on
rollers and push it bodily?
</P>
<P>
   LEVON CHORBAGIAN, Billerica, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sure is, if your property is relatively flat and even, and
you don't have to take the shed under any low branches. It was a
common way of moving small buildings in the olden days before
forklifts and other power machinery. Make sure you have plenty of
huskies along to push and pull, and move the rollers as the shed
makes its way to its destiny. Also, make sure you have a proper
foundation or platform to put the shed on when it gets there.
</P>
<P>
   Getting all those helpers is important, because manpower is
still the most important moving force in the world. Many years ago,
when the handyman was serving in Korea, a large building had to be
moved. The GIs did nothing but stand around trying to figure out
how to do it. But a Korean honcho gathered 200 or so young men,
most of them POWs, who lined up all the way around the building,
grabbed a bottom edge, and at a hoarse ``harrumph'' from the
honcho, lifted it bodily. At another ``harrumph,'' they started to
trot, literally, with this behometh in hand, yelling staccato
``harrumphs'' at every step, ending minutes later at the new
location.
</P>
<P>
   There were no strains, sprains, broken bones, or hernias. It was
a sight to remember.
</P>
<P>
   If moving the whole shed seems too much, or simply can't be
done, you could take the roof off, undo the walls, and carry each
wall to the new site. But remember, those walls are too heavy for
even two huskies to handle. You will need help. It can be done. The
handyman has already done half the same project with his old
toolshed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a fine-looking brass door knocker shaped like a
fireman's helmet. My daughter found it in an antiques store, and
being an ex-fireman, I appreciate it. Someone lacquered it, and for
the life of me I can't get it off. Using Wright's brass polish and
a Dremel brush helps, but it is tedious. Will anything do it
faster?
</P>
<P>
   DICK GILES, Duxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If it is really lacquer, lacquer thinner will do it, but work
outdoors with the thinner because it is very volatile. Put the
thinner in a container and soak the knocker. Then scrub with fine
steel wool. If it is plastic or varnish, use chemical paint remover
the same way. Once the knocker is polished and installed, let it
tarnish; you will have a good-looking antique brass knocker with no
maintenance. If you really want to coat it again, use a Krylon
clear spray finish.
</P>
<P>
   My door knocker is solid brass and beautifully tarnished, so I
do not have any extra chores to do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am putting a sheet of 3/8-inch plywood on a door on my
shed, to help reinforce it and make it look a bit better. How can I
paint it to withstand the weather and also look good for some
years?
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS CURRAN, Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Use an oil- or latex-based exterior primer, and be sure to
paint all edges as well. Finish with one or two coats of a latex
house or trim paint. It would not hurt to paint the inside of the
door as well.
</P>
<P>
   I think the primer and paint are musts for plywood. If the wood
were solid, you could apply a solid color stain, with no primer
needed, or a semitransparent stain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
