<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET CASUAL DAY: DRESS WAY, WAY UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when the idea of dressing down had seeped into the far
cubicles of America, dressing up, way up, is the trend for women
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of a cycle,'' says Laura Mandia, spokeswoman for
Bloomingdale's. ``We have gone as far as we are going with the
deconstructed casual look. And now it's fun to look elegant and
luxurious again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladylike suits are back. So are prissy heels and puny purses,
big belts, fluffy lapel flowers, and gold chains. Fabrics of choice
are boucle, lame, tweed and plaids from Glen to Burberry. And camel
is among the most popular colors.
</P>
<P>
   Animal skins (and prints), especially snake, ostrich, crocodile,
and leather are used for skirts, pants, jackets, and shoes, along
with fur trim, to the chagrin of animal rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing creative or visionary about ripping skin off
animals' backs,'' says RaeLeann Smith, Skins Campaign coordinator
for People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that there's not much creative or visionary
about any of the fall's fashion trends. Granted, most of it's
pretty. But despite the futuristic ring of 2000, the season's looks
are based almost entirely on the past.
</P>
<P>
   Helmut Lang five years ago was more forward-looking than just
about anything being offered this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is choice.
</P>
<P>
   It's not all about one designer or one look. You can wear '80s
redux with slanted zippers one day and a blouse with neck bow or
fitted blazer with puffy sleeves the next. Oversize logos appear on
everything from Chanel stockings to Gucci rain hats. Necklines
vary, but the cowl is in.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a `70s influence, some of it disco related (hoop
earrings and shimmery fabrics) and some of it right off the street
(cuff watches and knee-high go-go boots).
</P>
<P>
   You have to reach farther back in the closet of history to
qualify for the vintage look, which is also being pushed this
season through reinterpretations of schoolgirl dresses as well as
original old pieces that can be mixed with new ones. Graphic
swirly-patterned Pucci dresses, new or old, are fashionable too.
Suddenly, 1970 is modern again.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a 1940s tone to ladies' shoes, dominated by T
straps or ankle clasps, feminine edging, perforations, and accents,
such as leather florettes, on the toes. Stockings, in fishnet or
with a simple seam up the back, can be paired with such footwear. A
matching bowling bag _ or any top-handle purse _ completes the
look.
</P>
<P>
   The maxim that skirt lengths reflect the economy should be
refined this year to say that skirt lengths reflect the stock
market. Up, down, all over the place. Anywhere but just above the
knee. Make it much shorter or just a teeny bit longer.
Ankle-skimming skirts are also in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   For casual wear, there are chunky knits, dark denim, and
thin-wale corduroys with a retro feel. Ponchos and funky sneakers
are also back.
</P>
<P>
   To summarize: fluffy, puffy, Pucci, Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there are some of us who are still shopping for summer
things before heading out on vacation but are panic-stricken
because all the goods have been cleared out of the stores to make
room for fall merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   But one Web site, FlipFlopTrunkshow .com sells sandals
year-round to accommodate women from all climates who insist on
open-toe shoes, no matter the temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a large selection, including designers such as
Robert Clegerie, ESPACE, BCBG, Patrick Cox, and Freelance. Prices
range from $6 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another site, shesheme.com, offers all manner of things to buy
hidden in entertaining expository content, packaged a la ``Bridget
Jones's Diary'' in biweekly columns.
</P>
<P>
   By clicking on the underlined words (shown below in bold), the
shopper is linked to another site (amazon.com in the first instance
below, for example).
</P>
<P>
   A recent column read this way: ``Wednesday, while reading
Getting Over It (by Anna Maxted, a fashion editor), standing up
NAKED, and waiting for my self tanner to dry, I heard a knock at
the door. DREAD. Peering through the peephole, I saw adorable new
neighbor delivering my fly rod ``and fish purse, which was
strategically yet `mistakenly' delivered to his address at 518. It
was my big chance for an introduction . . . but there I was, lubed
up, sort of shiny, untanned-yet and clothed only in bikini outline
tape!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1666 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-03 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGINEST COULD MAKE GIANT IMPACT FOR THE PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ In those fragile years when one injury would
compound another every time he stepped onto the field, he gave you
the Willies. Now Bill Belichick is pretty grateful to have one
Willie: Willie McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous athlete who runs like a linebacker but has
more the power of a defensive lineman,'' said Belichick. ``He's a
very intelligent, instinctive player.''
</P>
<P>
   Here comes the punch line: ``In many ways he's like Lawrence
Taylor. Lawrence was a guy who . . . he may not have known
everything in the game plan, but when the ball was snapped he knew
how the play affected him and he knew how to defend it. Willie has
the same kind of instinctiveness. It's a unique trait to have
instinct recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick knows Taylor because he coached him with the New York
Giants. ``That's the highest compliment,'' said McGinest, sounding
a bit embarrassed by the praise. ``LT is a hero just like Andre
Tippett and Derrick Thomas. He's in a league of his own.''
</P>
<P>
   How are they the same? ``We both like to kill quarterbacks,''
said McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest nearly killed Jeff Garcia, the 49ers' heir apparent to
Steve Young, in Monday's 20-0 victory. McGinest sacked Garcia
twice, and his hard rush enabled Chad Eaton to swoop in for another
sack.
</P>
<P>
   After spending two years in and out of the trainer's room and
doctor's office for groin problems, McGinest returned to form last
year with 8 1/2 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Though he didn't play much Monday, he was a force when he was on
the field. In the new 3-4 defense (which occasionally switches to
4-3), McGinest's job is to chase the quarterback. Although McGinest
will at times drop back in coverage, Belichick wants to use
McGinest as he once used Taylor, raising havoc and being
disruptive. McGinest relishes the role. As the Patriots' No. 1 pick
out of Southern California in 1994, there were high hopes for him
to be one of the league's most disruptive players. Now he's getting
back to the point where he can make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   In the new defense, he begins the play upright and looks like
he's an outside linebacker _ even though he's listed as a defensive
end. Not that it matters. Technically, he played linebacker when he
first came up for Bill Parcells, then switched to defensive end,
then, under Pete Carroll, switched to ``elephant.''
</P>
<P>
   What is he? ``An elephant,'' said McGinest. ``I'm not a
defensive end or a linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he's LT-like, they should call him an ``animal.'' A
``monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the other members of the defense, McGinest feels he's died
and gone to heaven because Belichick is running the unit. He feels
Belichick will get the most out of his potential and put him in
position to be the centerpiece of the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, his teammates feel the same way, voting him cocaptain
along with Lawyer Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teammates voted for me and that's a great thing,'' he said.
``It means a lot to me. I want to lead, but I want to lead on the
field as much as anything. We do a lot of (talking) in practice,
but when it's time to get serious you have to make the plays to
prove yourself. That's what I hope I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys who don't show up all the time, but when you're
a leader you put yourself out there on the line every play and
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest has joined many of his teammates in saying the team
needed a taskmaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be a well-disciplined team,'' said McGinest. ``We need
discipline. It's proven that this group of guys plays its best
football when we have discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinest earned his only All-Pro berth under Parcells,
Belichick, and Al Groh in '96. But Ty Law and Milloy became Pro
Bowlers under Carroll, despite their praise of the current coach.
Chris Slade, McGinest's bookend, also became an All-Pro in the
Carroll regime, even though he was a ``situational player'' in
Parcells's final year, which included Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the maturing of players under Carroll, Belichick's
concept of team defense is a system the players would rather play.
No defensive back will be hung out to dry in single coverage.
Belichick stresses not giving up big plays in the secondary because
he stresses containment and aggressive play by the players up
front.
</P>
<P>
   What McGinest loves is the defense's unpredictability. Belichick
disguised the defenses well Monday, even fielding something that
looked like a 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go out there and execute what we're supposed to do, it's
hard to pick up what we're doing,'' said McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest said that, despite the public perception, the defense's
play was far from perfect. It was a message Belichick drilled into
his players. McGinest, for one, got the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made mistakes. It wasn't perfect,'' said McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   If the leader of the defense believes the coach's message, even
after pitching a shutout, then the rest of the unit had better
believe it. As Belichick said, he's setting a high bar for the team
_ and now he's setting a high bar for McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Belichick mentioned Lawrence Taylor in the same
breath as McGinest. Coaches say those things to the media for a
reason.
</P>
<P>
   And now McGinest knows what the coach expects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
