<HEADLINE>
HAMILTON TO MAKE OLYMPIC DEBUT IN SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tyler Hamilton admits he wasn't totally surprised Tuesday when
he got the call at his home in Nice, France, telling him he'd been
chosen to be on the US Olympic cycling team.
</P>
<P>
   But he was relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, of Marblehead, Mass., was on the 1996 Olympic team _
but as an alternate. He couln't even travel to Atlanta with the
team, let alone wear the team uniform.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, he knew he had a better chance, with four
Tour de Frances under his belt. Hamilton finished 13th overall last
year and 25h this year, both times playing a significant role in
helping teammate Lance Armstrong get to the winner's podium in
Paris. Hamilton also scored a big victory with two stage wins and
the overall title at a race in France last June.
</P>
<P>
   So he figured he was in a good position to be picked for Sydney.
``I felt like I had done everything I could possibly do, but you
never know,'' said Hamilton, 29, who was aware that there were
half-dozen qualified cyclists vying for the two remaining spots.
</P>
<P>
   It's exciting, and now it's official,'' he said Wednesday from
Nice, his home during the racing season. ``I knew I had a good
chance. I think in the time-trial race and the way I worked for
Lance, I opened their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' were US Olympic road coach Jim Ochowicz and Sean Petty,
the director of athlete performance at USA Cycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have assembled a first-rate team, that will no doubt be
favored in both the road race and individual time trial,'' Ochowicz
said when he announced the roster Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Hamilton and Armstrong will be Antonio Cruz, of Long
Beach, Calif., who won the Olympic trials road race; George
Hincapie, of Greenville, S.C., the top US cyclist in the World Cup
standings; and Fred Rodriguez, of Emeryville, Calif., who won the
national professional championship last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who rode in the Tour de France with Mapei, finished
in the top four places in three Tour stages. Like Hamilton, he felt
confident of his performance but realized his fate was out of his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've proven that I deserve a spot on the team,''
Rodriguez said during the Tour de France. ``It's up to them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong and Hamilton also will compete in the 29-mile
individual time-trial race. That was by far their forte in the Tour
this year and last year. Armstrong won the final time trial both
times, while Hamilton came in third last year and fourth this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is now off to a four-day stage race in Spain Sunday,
then has half-dozen more races until he heads to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Going to the Olympics, he said, is something he thought of when
he used to ski competively, in his precycling days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I always dreamed of,'' he said. ``But once I
broke my back and ended my ski career, I pretty much shelved the
idea of ever going to the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the dream is back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a good cause
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's not as old as the Boston Marathon or as grueling as
the Tour de France, but the Pan-Massachusetts Challenge has become
a mainstay for biking in Boston. The ride, which supports the
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute's Jimmy Fund, began in 1980 with 36
participants who raised more than $10,000. More than 3,000 cyclists
will make the ride this year on six routes from Sturbridge to
Provincetown beginning Saturday. Last year the ``everyday Lance
Armstrongs'' contributed $8.7 million to the Jimmy Fund . . .
Hamilton won't be coming to the United States later this month to
defend his record in the Mount Washington Hillclimb in New
Hampshire, but another world-class cyclist will be there. French
racer Jeannie Longo, who holds 11 world titles in both road and
track racing, is slated to climb the mountain Aug. 19. Longo, who
won won the women's Tour de France three times and has medals from
the 1992 (silver) and 1996 (gold) Olympics, apparently is using the
race as a tuneup for the Olympics. Hamilton won the race both in
1997 and 1999, and had a course record of 50 minutes 21 seconds for
the 7.4-mile climb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
