<HEADLINE>
SAVAGE COMPETITION SHAKES STAPLES' INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Staples is like the guy who owns a nice house in a run-down
neighborhood. Prospective buyers want to know: Will the blight
spread here, too?
</P>
<P>
   As far as investors are concerned, the office-superstore
neighborhood is a scary place to be. Staples' two main rivals,
Office Depot and Office Max, have both signaled that intensifying
competition is hurting their bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   Staples has yet to say that those same pressures are having an
impact, but investors, always a nervous lot, are bracing for the
worst. ``People are wondering when the next shoe will drop,'' said
Eileen Leary, a portfolio manager at State Street Research.
</P>
<P>
   If that were not enough, Wall Street is also on edge about
Staples' Internet business, Staples.com. When will it become
profitable? Will it become profitable?
</P>
<P>
   Investors will be looking for clues when the Framingham, Mass.
company releases quarterly earnings Aug. 15. Company executives
said they could not comment until then.
</P>
<P>
   How bad has life been for Staples? Real bad. The stock is down
50 percent since February and roughly 60 percent since the spring
of 1999. Office Depot is down 76 percent from its 1999 high. Office
Max is off 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This category has gone from one of the most attractive to the
least attractive retail groups,'' said Bill Sims, an analyst with
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The basic problem: too much competition. The once formidable
category killers are killing each other and, in turn, are being
killed by other category killers _ notably Costco and Wal-Mart.
Wal-Mart has been particularly aggressive in promoting its
back-to-school business.
</P>
<P>
   Office Depot, citing pressure from the discount chains, said in
July that it was cutting prices on paper, ink, and toner cartridges
to lure more shoppers into its stores. ``A price war is always a
significant negative,'' said Rary Delaney, an analyst with Fleet
Investment Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Staples followers may note a certain irony in the increasing
threat posed by the general discounters.
</P>
<P>
   When the government rejected Staples' proposed merger with
Office Depot in 1997, on antitrust grounds, it said that the office
superstore category represented a separate and distinct market
which the merged companies would dominate. Staples countered that
the discounters were going after the same business and that the
market still would have been very competitive.
</P>
<P>
   With the benefit of hindsight, it looks as if Staples was right.
But that is small consolation for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue for investors is the future of Staples.com. The
company launched its dot-com at a time when Internet retailing was
all the rage and the market was willing to tolerate start-up
losses. Those days are gone, and investors now want to see profits
_ fast.
</P>
<P>
   Staples.com lost $20 million in the first quarter on $75 million
in sales. Analysts don't expect the unit to become profitable until
some time in 2002. Staples has filed to create a separate tracking
stock for the dot-com business, but Wall Street now doubts the deal
will ever go through.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kully concedes Staples faces plenty of challenges, but he
says the market has overreacted to the company's troubles. ``At
this price, this stock is a helluva good buy,'' said Kully, a money
manager with Pegasus Associates in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Kully expects Staples' earnings to climb at a 25 to 30 percent
pace over the next three years. If he is right _ a big if _ then
the stock is definitely cheap, using traditional measures.
</P>
<P>
   Kully acknowledges that Office Depot's price cuts were bad news,
but he says that investors missed other news in the announcement
that was equally important. Office Depot in July said it was
scaling back its expansion plans and would close stores it operates
in very competitive markets. ``If you look at the whole
announcement, it was a net plus for Staples,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Leary, another Staples fan, says investors have also been
too gloomy about the dot-com business. She expects that in its
earnings report, Staples will say that the Internet operation is
growing more quickly than anticipated and that profitability will
come sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   Leary also says that because of the nature of Staples business _
customers buy significant quantities of supplies on a regular basis
_ the operation has much sounder economics than do many other
Internet retailers. ``This business makes sense,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Is it time to jump in and buy Staples? Brave investors like
Kully and Leary say it is. Chickens may want to wait until Aug. 15,
when presumably a clearer picture of Staples' future will emerge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
