<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-APRONS-ART-BOS &LR;      08-03 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-APRONS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 KITCHEN KITSCH: THE LOWLY APRON REAPPEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, musician Trix Kout bought a dresser at an auction
and found some unexpected treasures stuffed in a drawer: a dozen
handmade aprons, circa 1940s or '50s.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was made of flamboyant sheer red netting with a
satin sash. Another was a delicate granny print, lovingly stitched
together with floral patchwork scraps. A red floral cotton number
was the es-sence of casserole and canned string beans. Then there
was the demure Heidi-style apron, with its rickrack and dotted
Swiss and heart-shaped pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just so cute,'' says Kout. ``They were so
era-sensitive. They were like the ones my mother had, in the
'50s.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is they were like the ones a lot of mothers in
American kitchens wore: homemade, highly embellished, and as
essential to life in the kitchen as a wooden spoon or tea towel.
While these bow-in-the-back aprons aren't likely to return as a
fashion statement anytime soon, 50 years after their heyday, they
are coming back, this time as collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like there is an underground network'' of apron
collectors, says Joyce Cheney, Missouri-based author of the book
``Aprons: Icons of the American Home''(Running Press), and
organizer of a retrospective on aprons that is touring American
museums through 2002. ``This is a critical time for aprons.''
</P>
<P>
   It's critical because their original wearers are getting up in
years and aprons proudly worn five decades ago are now heading to
rubbish piles and thrift shops. There is a diminishing market these
days for cross-stitched gingham kitchen apparel with poodles on the
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   As they disappear, so does an era's worth of memories: that
first high school sewing project, fashion accessories, hostess
gifts, art form, clothespin holders. Aprons made from scrap fabrics
or feed bags, the ultimate in thrift. Aprons that wiped sweat off
foreheads in steamy kitchens, dusted furniture, doubled as hot
pads, and held peas from the garden when the bottom was pulled up.
Cooking aprons. Serving aprons. Holiday aprons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Symbols of home''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aprons ``remind us of mothers, grandmothers, and our own
pasts,'' Cheney writes in her book. ``They serve as symbols of
home, motherhood, and housewifery, from images of a colonial woman
fanning the cooking fire with her long apron . . . to a Fifties
housewife wearing a ruffled and rickracked apron to serve dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, 50, a writer and curator with about 400 aprons in her
personal collection, has charted the rise and fall of aprons in her
book. She says the use of aprons peaked in the postwar years, in
the late '40s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when you find the plethora of wonderful styles,'' she
said in a telephone interview from St. Louis. ``This happened for a
number of reasons. Fabric was more available after World War II,
and sewing machines were more common. And more importantly, all the
institutions in society at the time, the school, the church, the
government, the media, the whole marketplace, was pushing a certain
model of the family, which was the Cleaver family. Mom stayed home,
her job was to make the home, and the apron was the uniform of her
profession.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aprons as folk art
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The average mom had two kinds of aprons, Cheney says. the
``workaday apron'' she wore in the kitchen to prepare the food, and
the ``hostess apron'' she donned for serving it. While aprons were
commercially available, many women sewed their own, and apron
patterns were a staple of newspaper women's pages and magazines,
says Phoebe Erb Gallagher of Boston, a commercial textile designer
who has been an avid apron aficionado for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher curated an apron exhibit at the Newton (Mass.) Free
Library in March, and in it cited a 1953 sewing manual with
patterns for 41 aprons: the mend-while-you-iron apron, the
hair-washing apron, the vacuum-cleaning apron, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher has more than 100 aprons in her collection, mostly
acquired at thrift stores, ranging in price from 99 cents to $12.
She says part of what intrigues her about them is ``the variety of
doodads'' that were incorporated into their design.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the trimmings and shapes and patterns is sort of a
testament to the imagination and ingenuity of housewives, who on
the one hand we tend to think of as being repressed. . . . They may
symbolize the unfulfilled housewife,'' she says. On the other hand,
``they reveal the good-humored homemaker whose tasks never
ceased.''
</P>
<P>
   Among her favorite finds are an ecru-colored, doily-like,
crocheted apron with a yellow ribbon woven through it; an apron
made completely of handkerchiefs, with a sawtooth edge; an apron
with mah-jongg game designs on the skirt; an apron made from the
bags used by farmers for animal feed, and the piece de resistance,
the apron she calls the ``G-string,'' a kind of cotton loincloth
that suggested at least one cook in this country had more on her
mind in the kitchen than simmering soup stock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A discarded uniform
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the era of the apron came and went. As more families
acquired washing machines and wash-and-wear clothes became the
norm, it was less necessary for cooks to keep their clothes
covered. As women entered the work force, they spent significantly
less time in the kitchen. With the advent of the women's movement,
Cheney says, ``we were no longer just housewives and we didn't want
the uniform of housewives.''
</P>
<P>
   Now aprons are showing up in flea markets and old dresser
drawers, and Cheney acknowledges she has her doubts they'll make a
comeback, other than those full-length ones spotted around the
barbecue or on sales staff at retail outlets like Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Trix Kout, who has consigned the ``cute'' aprons she
found to an antiques shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a musician, I don't have cocktail parties,'' she says.
``What am I going to do with them?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1403EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
