<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, PEDRO RIDES TO THE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It took 19 innings spread over 5 hours 34 minutes to
determine a winner when the Red Sox and Mariners played Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, it took less than 10 minutes and less than one
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the first five Red Sox batters crossed home plate in the
opening frame. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   The game was over because Pedro Martinez was on the mound. Pedro
does not cough up a 4-0, first-inning lead. He gave up five hits,
walked two, and fanned seven in beating the Mariners, 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Pedro went nine when there was no one else left
to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was over right away,'' Martinez acknowledged. ``I knew they
were down after those four runs we scored. I just throw strikes and
keep the ball down and they get themselves out.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro presents himself as a legitimate MVP candidate on nights
like this. The Sox needed a win, but more than anything, they
needed him to go nine. He went nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no chance of pitching anything like three innings,''
said closer Derek Lowe. ``Everybody was pretty much done except for
emergency purposes. He knew that. I'm running out of things to say
about the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For this one, he gets a win and a save,'' said Boston pitching
coach, Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro is the best pitcher in baseball and he is the reason why
the motley crew that is the 2000 Red Sox still have a chance at
postseason play. He can neutralize a 10-game suspension to the star
center fielder. He can stabilize a clubhouse reeling from Dan
Duquette's revolving door. And he can guarantee rest for a
dog-tired bullpen that just chucked 18 innings in two days.
Martinez has pitched into the seventh inning in all 19 of his
starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were reeling after Tuesday's late-night loss. The relief
corps was depleted, spirits were low, and Jimy Williams was
desperately in need of a strong outing from a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, it was Pedro's day to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive righthander has been in a great mood all week.
After beating the A's in Oakland Friday, he served as interpreter
for Cuban righthander Rolando Arroyo. Martinez was good. If the
United Nations could match his $75 million salary, Pedro could get
work as a translator.
</P>
<P>
   He entertained a hoard of scribes at his locker before Tuesday's
game, then thrilled the early arrivals at Safeco Field, tossing
baseball after baseball into the stands during batting practice. It
was a delight to watch and Pedro seemed to be enjoying it as much
as the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Mariners sold out Safeco Field (45,121),
attracting an additional 10,000 fans simply because of Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   It was bad news for the Mariners hitters, however.
</P>
<P>
   In accordance with Pedro Rules, outfielder Jay Buhner was given
the night off. Against Martinez, Buhner is 0 for 8 lifetime, all
strikeouts. Pedro probably would have liked a little revenge since
Buhner hit a grand slam off Brother Ramon Monday, but Seattle
manager Lou Piniella wouldn't have it. Sweet Lou has decided that
letting Buhner hit against Pedro is inviting a funk that can carry
into the next week. So when Martinez pitches, Buhner sits.
</P>
<P>
   Typically terrific, Martinez gave up nothing but a couple of
scratch singles in the first five innings as the Sox coasted with a
5-0 lead. In the bottom of the sixth, Mark McLemore walked and
moved to third on a couple of ground outs, but Martinez fanned Alex
Rodriguez (swinging) for the second time and it was on to the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   He got the side in order in the seventh, fanning Tuesday's homer
hero, Mike Cameron, for a second time to end the inning.He had
thrown only 90 pitches through seven.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners reached him for three hits and two runs in the
eighth, but Martinez got out of the jam when Nomar Garciaparra
turned a nice double play on a hot grounder up the middle by Stan
Javier. By this time, Derek Lowe was warming up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth was 1-2-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had to go as deep as possible,'' said Martinez.
``I had to pick up the guy in the bullpen and there's no one better
to do that than me. I had more rest than most people and it was a
pleasure to pick them up.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wells is contesting for the Cy Young Award and Bob
Gibson's 1968 ERA of 1.12 may be tough to reach, but Pedro, now
13-3, hasn't lost since coming off the disabled list July 13 and 20
wins is within reach.
</P>
<P>
   So the trip through Oakland and Seattle produced a 4-3 record
(two wins from Martinez) and Boston is three games behind the
Yankees. The Sox are 4-5 since Carl Everett started his suspension
and Jurassic Carl returns Saturday at Fenway against the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Pedro has righted the SS Duquette. Again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
