<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CONVENTION-RDP (Philadelphia) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush
accepts his party's presidential nomination in a speech in which he
is expected to talk about the Clinton years in a ``regretful tone,
not a harsh tone,'' according to his press secretary. He is also
expected to tell the delegates that this is a ``unique moment'' of
peace and prosperity that provides the opportunity to solve some
long-standing problems. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-GAYS (Philadelphia) _ Leaders of the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's oldest gay political organization, hold a
news conference decrying what they call a Republican ``double
standard'' on homosexual issues. The party welcomes gays as
individuals but opposes laws protecting homosexuals from
discrimination or allowing them to serve in the military. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-LAURA-BUSH (Philadelphia) _ Texas First Lady Laura Bush
tells an audience of Republican women that if her husband wins the
presidency, she will work to help families around America. She
talks about the importance of parents teaching their children to
read. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-MEANS-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ Everyone knew they wouldn't _
couldn't, shouldn't _ keep it up. All that gooey sweetness just
wasn't real. Mama and papa Bush broke through the cocoon of
convention platitudes first, rising to President Clinton's bait to
defend their son Dubya with some sharp-tongued cracks about
Clinton's lack of character. Then GOP veep nominee Dick Cheney cut
to the chase, dropping those vague allusions to Democratic failings
in favor of a direct attack on the real target here, Vice President
Al Gore. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ The relationship between the
George W. Bush's Republicans and Bill Clinton is a fascinating
study in contradictions. On the one hand, GOP leaders express their
disgust with the president's behavior and speak longingly of having
a president worthy of their respect. On the other hand, their
decision to transform the GOP's image by opening the party's doors
widely to African Americans, Hispanics and gays copies the type of
strategy that twice won the presidency for Clinton and the
Democrats. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (For release Sunday, Aug 6.)
</P>
