<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Aug. 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE REPUBLICAN CONVENTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning a package of articles on the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia. A detailed budget
of stories, GOP-BUDGET-NYT, will move by 3 p.m. EDT. Stories
contained in that package will move in ``p'' category and include:
</P>
<P>
   GOP-RDP (Philadelphia) _ Ledeall on the Republican National
Convention, where Gov. George W. Bush is scheduled to accept the
presidential nomination and address the convention Thursday
evening. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ASSESS (Philadelphia) _ A News Analysis on what the GOP has
accomplished and what lies ahead for them _ and for the Democrats.
By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUSH-SPEECH (Philadelphia) _ On the speech Gov. George W.
Bush is scheduled to deliver Thursday evening. The speech, which
has been ready for two months, and how it was prepared offer a
window into the discipline and strategy of the candidate and his
campaign. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ECON-ASSESS (Philadelphia) _ The Bush campaign portrays his
economic agenda as all about helping single moms and small business
owners. Just as Clinton worked to give Democrats a claim to fiscal
responsibility, Bush is working to give conservatism a claim to
solving social problems. But Bush also was seeking here to avoid
drawing attention to the fact that his tax plan would largely
benefit the wealthy. And to the degree he engages Gore on economic
issues, he is moving onto tricky turf, given the widespread
prosperity. By Richard W. Stevenson. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FORD (Philadelphia) _ An update on former President Ford's
condition. By B. Drummond Ayres.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AMTRAK-GUARANTEE (Washington) _ Facing its first widespread
service problem since adopting a new ``Satisfaction Guarantee,''
Amtrak says it has had to give thousands of passengers coupons good
for a free trip, because of lengthy delays on 22 trains near
Philadelphia Sunday night, when strong winds knocked trees unto the
tracks and lighting zapped the signal system. The railroad, trying
to build confidence, is throwing extra equipment into service today
to help get people home from the Republican National Convention. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BEACHES-POLLUTION (Los Angeles) _ The number of
pollution-related beach closures and advisories nationwide
increased by 50 percent between 1997 and 1999, with more than half
in California, according to a report released by the Natural
Resources Defense Council. The numbers are thought to reflect not
increased pollution but increased monitoring, particularly in
California. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta) _ Sick, bewildered and besieged at
his home by angry protesters, former President Suharto was formally
charged Thursday with corruption during his 32 years of unchecked
power in Indonesia. The charge involves only a small portion of the
widespread corruption that characterized his rule, but it sends a
significant signal of Indonesia's attempts to overhaul its economy
and political system and lay the basis for the rule of law. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-EGYPT (Cairo) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, facing
a deadline to make peace with the Palestinians, met with Egypt's
president, Hosni Mubarak, to try to persuade him to help break the
impasse over Jerusalem's future. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   HONG-KONG-IMMIG (Hong Kong) _ Hong Kong said Thursday that it
will deport at least 1,000 of about 6,000 mainland Chinese who have
been fighting for permanent residency after a mob of them set fire
to the immigration building on Wednesday, injuring 50 people, six
seriously. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA (Shanghai, China) _ Taiwan President Chen Shui-bian
warned Thursday that a build up of the Chinese air force could in
five years overcome the island's ability to control the air space
over the Taiwan Strait, a key factor in repelling a mainland
invasion. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   SRI-LANKA-TAMILS (Chennai, India) _ Sri Lanka's ruling coalition
has proposed a new constitution that would give greater political
autonomy to the country's minority Tamil population in the hope
that _ if adopted _ it would help end the 17-year war waged by
separatist rebels for a Tamil homeland. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   BRITIAN-QUEEN-MOTHER (London) _ Queen Elizabeth, the Queen
Mother, turns 100 years old Friday, and the British have been
commemorating the event with what could be the last full-throated
hurrah for the crown. There have been full dress parades, Royal Air
Force flyovers, pageant-filled church services, ``God Bless You
Ma'am'' tabloid headlines and editorials crediting her with having
saved the monarchy from perils ranging from the abdication of her
brother-in-law to the bombing of Buckingham Palace by the Germans
to the dysfunctional family behavior of modern-day Windsors. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLY-LIFE (Undated) _ Based on the chemical composition of
ancient rocks, scientists have developed a method to deduce the
amount of oxygen in the early atmosphere, thus giving insight into
the rise of the earliest forms of life. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FORD-REDESIGN (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Ford Motor says that its next
generation of Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles, scheduled to go
on sale in January, will be extensively changed from current models
so as to reduce the danger to other motorists during collisions and
decrease the risk of rollovers. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly Norris column. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-LAWYERS (Paris) _ On the growing number of cross-border
mergers of law firms in Europe, a little noticed but important
sideshow to the corporate takeovers that are transforming business
here. John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-TELECOM (Tokyo) _ Telephone competition in Japan has taken
a new turn: Japan Telecom Co., one of Japan's largest
telecommunications companies, has announced its intention to offer
local telephone service, which would put it into direct competition
with Nippon Telegraph and Telephone. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Walt Disney is expected to report
third-quarter earnings after the stock market closes. Disney is
expected to earn 24 cents a share, excluding its interest in Go.com
Inc. A year ago, it had profit from operations of $418 million, or
20 cents a share. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Gail Collins'
``Public Interests.''
</P>
