<P>
   EDITORIAL-CHILD-MOLESTATION _ Howard Thompson nine years ago was
convicted on three counts of child molestation in Brunswick, Ga.,
and given 10 years unsupervised probation. Effectively, Brunswick
washed its hands of him, ordered him to get out of a five-county
judicial circuit and stay away for 10 yeablem. Change-o: Now
others' problem. (Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My youngest daughter has
it all figured out. She just turned 19, has a year of college under
her belt, is still in relatively good graces with the
powers-that-be at the University of Texas, and now knows for sure
what she wants to do for a living. She wants to be a film director.
(Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIS-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Cheney is struck from the mold of
Bush's greatest mentors. Texas oil millionaires (old think) and
billionaires (new think) loom large in the Bush history. Notable
among them is Richard Rainwater, a Fort Worth oilman and sports
investor and former Bush business partner who has contributed
generously to his friend's political life. (Davis, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ His warrior days are long gone, but Joe
Levinson, 76, and others like him _ an estimated estimates are that
there 1.4 million military retirees are in the country today _ have
seen their access to health care shrink even as their need for it
grows. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Forget what they say on the
Sunday morning news shows. The key to understanding this year's
elections is The Boredom Factor. This is a strange year. For the
first time there was more suspense in the Mexican presidential race
than in the American. (Lane, Daytona News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ PHILADELPHIA _ That guy on the
famous steps here, getting his picture taken, was Ricky, not Rocky.
Or at least that's what his momma calls him. Rick Perry, the
lieutenant governor of Texas who will become governor if his buddy
George W. Bush beats Al Gore on Nov. 7, was on the Philadelphia
Museum of Art steps featured in Sylvester Stallone's ``Rocky''
movie Wednesday, waiting for Bush to arrive at a rally. (McNeely,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas - It's times like these when those
blessed with cable options give thanks for A&AMP;E, the Discovery
Channel and Animal Planet. My wife, for instance. She surfed upon a
scene of African children in grass skirts scampering across a
stage. Jabbing the remote, she bolted before realizing it was
actually about Africans. ``Sorry,'' she said, ``I thought it was
the Republican National Convention.'' (John Young is opinion page
editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
