<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1699 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-CVN-NAC-DELEGATE3-COX     08-03 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NAC-DELEGATE3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delegate says Bush won't curb Social Security benefits
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ For Wayne Christian, a Center stockbroker who
represents Nacogdoches in the Texas House, perhaps the biggest
surprise for him as a delegate to the GOP national convention is
that there have been no surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from Texas and having served under Gov. Bush for the
past 3 1/2 years, I think it's quite amazing that the same message
is being given that we've seen in Austin and in Texas all along.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that consistency of politics, Christian said, that refutes
efforts by Democrats ``to try to portray this (party unity) as some
kind of fake scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian, 49, said he was not among those individuals who bowed
their heads in prayer as a protest to the Tuesday night appearance
on the program by Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona, the only openly gay
Republican member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prayer is always proper and good,'' he said, ``but the idea is
to hate the sin but love the sinners.
</P>
<P>
   Christian noted that Kolbe's four-minute speech on international
trade ``was in no way in regard to homosexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect anyone of any belief and any persuasion to be able
to exhibit their opinion and views and being able to participate in
the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian, who served as an alternate delegate in 1996, said he
has been especially impressed at this convention by the
participation of ``the diversity of racial groups that heretofore
have been labeled as Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more people, he said, have ``come to realize that the
best hope for the American dream is offered by the Republican
Party'' through programs that ``Gov. Bush has already proven in
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the programs of ``compassionate conservatism'' and
``faith in action,'' he said, that have resulted ``in moving 60
percent of the decrease in Texas welfare rolls to paying jobs,''
much of it ``through private enterprise and through churches and
other organizations coming in and helping.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian said the ``best assistance given to families is to
promote marriage and to promote jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compassionate conservatism realigns that area (of assistance)
by putting faith and hope and caring local individuals back in the
process, and not just the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is Christian's definition of a compassionate conservative:
</P>
<P>
   ``Caring about people who have needs and doing whatever we can
do to lift people to the greatest opportunity available for them to
pursue the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   On a personal level, Christian said he hopes the GOP convention
will denounce the ``fear factor'' being used by opposition groups
who claim Republicans will reduce Social Security benefits for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   As state representative, he said he had received phone calls
from Social Security recipients, including from his 75-year-old
mother, who are worried that they will be targeted for cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``No policy from pre-Reagan on, including the Bush and the Gore
plan, advocate any change to current recipients,'' he said. ``We
need to assure senior citizens who have worked and put that money
into Social Security that they are not being threatened by either
political party.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
