<HEADER>
A1709 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-PIMENTEL-COLUMN-AZR-B     08-03 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIMENTEL-COLUMN-AZR-BC </SLUG>
  
BC-PIMENTEL-COLUMN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    SAME OLD GOP PUTS ON A MORE LIKABLE FACE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    (ADV: CORRECTED VERSION FOR ALL NEEDING.
 &HT;    THIRD WORD IN FIRST SENTENCE IS ENGANA, WITH A TILDE OVER THE
``N.'' THE WORD MAY HAVE COME OVER GARBLED IN EARLIER
TRANSMISSION(a) 
 &HT;    By RICARDO PIMENTEL(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   El que engaqa con aparencia de verdad es impostor(beginitalic).
(enditalic)(He who deceives with a truthful appearance is an
impostor).
</P>
<P>
   An old Mexican saying from a new book on sayings, folktales and
wisdom, It's All in the Frijoles(beginitalic), (enditalic)by
Yolanda NavaThe saying comes to mind as the spectacle that is the
Republican National Convention continues to flit past.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, we've heard such noble notions as compassionate
conservatism and leaving no child behind. We had George P. Bush,
the nominee's Latino nephew, and Colin Powell putting high-profile
faces to the GOP's claims of inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But, we also had a Texas delegation nearly boycotting a speech
on international trade by Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., because he is
gay. Perhaps a dozen satisfied themselves instead by bowing their
heads in prayer during his speech, demonstrating anew that holier
than thou doesn't have much to do with being more caring or polite.
</P>
<P>
   We had a party platform still out of sync with most of the
nation on abortion and that stated flatly that homosexuality is
incompatible with the military and that gays don't deserve the same
protections in law that the rest of us do.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates, despite the more high-profile members, didn't
much look like us either, though we should all aspire to their
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   I'd be surprised if African-American and Latino representation
broke into low double digits, even including those paraded before
the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   We had Arizona Sen. John McCain - who crusades on campaign
finance reform - putting on a happy face as corporate donors hung
their convention banners to signify kinship to and ownership of the
party.
</P>
<P>
   But, for all the transparency at work at the convention, it just
might work.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Americans could be more interested these days in
simply electing someone they can like. That is what this GOP
convention and campaign-to-be is about - donning the mantle of
likability. The fact is, Bush, a likable guy, isn't running against
Al Gore, he's running against Bill Clinton, arguably one of our
most unlikable presidents for character flaws all too fresh in
memory.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, as part of the Clinton administration, Gore should
bear some of the criticism stemming from governance over the past
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, however, is that this has been a moderately
successful administration that has presided over what is generally
accepted as boom times (though everyone seems to gloss right over
that widening gap between rich and poor).
</P>
<P>
   It's simply more important under these circumstances to link
Gore more with Clinton-the-man than with the administration's
policies. Really, it's about being more likable than Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Gore has sins of his own (as does Bush), but they pale in
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Take Bush's VP pick, the consummate insider Dick Cheney. His
congressional voting record makes Newt Gingrich look like Mother
Teresa, but Cheney is described as likable and affable (and gives
an aura of substance to a candidate who desperately needs it).
</P>
<P>
   And this is a campaign about likability. It's not that the
Republicans really have any illusions about minorities flocking to
sign up. They just know that swing votes may come from the larger,
fair-minded middle, which has an equally difficult time with a
party viewed as mean-spirited and selfish.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are tired of losing and that means muting sentiments
and philosophy still very much part of the GOP, truth be known.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's another saying: Don't put on a tutu and prance on
your tiptoes and tell me you're a pretty ballerina.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Pimentel at ricardo.pimentel(a)arizonarepublic.com or
(602) 444-8210. His column appears Tuesdays, Thursdays and
Saturdays.
</P>
</TEXT>
