<P>
   ROSLER-RETROSPECTIVE (New York) _ If you happen to be on
basically OK terms with the world as it is, the alert, irritated,
combative work of the U.S. artist Martha Rosler may not be your cup
of tea. ``Martha Rosler: Positions in the Life World,'' is a
30-year-plus career retrospective divided between the New Museum of
Contemporary Art and the International Center of Photography. By
Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-SOUNDTRACKS (Undated) _ New movies come in on waves of
hype and anticipation, followed, if they're lucky, by swelling word
of mouth. When the waves recede, they leave behind something
tangible: soundtrack albums. If summer is a prime time for movie
releases, it's also a good time to look back over recent albums,
some of which are better than the movies themselves. By Jon
Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DANCING (New York) _ It is summer in New York, this year a
season that jumps from muggy heat to damp chill without warning.
There is relatively little dance in pleasantly climate-controlled
theaters. So what do those mad creatures called dancers do? Forget
about vacations or more trips to the office-temp center. Dancers
dance. So they are taking to the city's parks, rooftops, gardens
and empty buildings over the next four weeks in a surge of activity
that truly offers something for just about everyone. By Jennifer
Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-RENAISSANCE (Undated) _ The presence of what might be
called the eternal modern can be felt in certain great examples of
African, Egyptian and early Greek art and different kinds of Asian
art. Right now this presence hovers like a beautiful mist over
``The Arts of Hon'ami Koetsu, Japanese Renaissance Master'' at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art, which pays homage to a late
16th-century artist who has become known as ``the Leonardo da Vinci
of Japanese art.'' By Roberta Smith.
</P>
