<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYE-SCOOPS-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYE SCOOPS!  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By AUTHOR 
 (Color art is available.) 
 From WWD, W magazine and DNR) 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 PARTY PALACE  
 &HT;    Prince Ernst-August of Hanover and his wife, Caroline of Monaco,
didn't really need an excuse to throw their first ball together at
Marienbourg, Ernst's 19th-century castle outside Hanover, Germany.
 &HT;    But Ernst reportedly told some of the 700 guests, who arrived in
a swarm of private jets, that the occasion was to celebrate the
appearance of their daughter Alexandra's first baby tooth. Security
was tight, and all the invitees _ with the sole exception of
Caroline's old friend Francois-Marie Banier _ were warned not to
bring cameras.
 &HT;    Everyone had to give a secret password to book a room at one of
the hotels Ernst had reserved in advance, although many guests
never actually made it back to their rooms on the night of the
party.
 &HT;    The festivities roared along until 8 a.m. as revelers guzzled
wine, table-hopped and danced to six orchestras _ which played
everything from waltzes to salsa _ through Marienbourg's endless
rooms. (Oversize television monitors allowed diners to keep an eye
on the action elsewhere in the castle.)
 &HT;    The crowd included plenty of nobles, such as Pierre d'Arenberg
and Michael of Greece, as well as the German families of
Furstenberg, Bismarck and Saxe-Weimar.
 &HT;    Then there was Karl Lagerfeld (who designed Caroline's dress and
the one worn by her daughter Charlotte), along with Valentino,
Hubert de Givenchy, Robert and Chantal Miller, Mick Flick, Philip
and Spyros Niarchos, Susan Gutfreund, Judy Taubman and Lynn Wyatt.
A send-off lunch had been scheduled for the next day, but nobody
made it.
 &HT;    ``They were too hungover,'' one guest explained.
 &HT;    
 UNDIE ACHIEVERS  
 &HT;    Having snubbed New York as ``too uptight'' to be the site of
Agent Provocateur's first U.S. store, the creators of London's
infamous naughty-lingerie-for-rich-girls line have decided to open
up shop this September on L.A.'s Melrose Avenue.
 &HT;    And word is that the company's first fragrance will make its
debut at the shop soon thereafter.
 &HT;    ``I think people like to look sexier in L.A.,'' says
designer/owner Serena Rees, whose peephole bras and sheer culotte
panties have found fans in Gwyneth Paltrow, Nicole Kidman and
Madonna. ``I mean, just look at how much they care about breasts
here.''
 &HT;    
 KRAVIS IN PARIS  
 &HT;    Paris is quietly whispering that Henry and Marie-Josee Kravis,
New York's billionaire Francophiles, are coming to town.
 &HT;    The Kravises, whose palatial New York spread is crammed with
major 18th-century furniture assembled with the help of decorator
Francois Joseph Graf, are said to have bought an apartment on
discreet rue de l'Universite.
 &HT;    Although it's reportedly a small pied-a-terre, the Kravises have
again enlisted the services of Graf, who's known as ``the emperor''
for his grand personality and grander work for such clients as
David and Olympia de Rothschild.
 &HT;    
 SILICON ICON  
 &HT;    He was the first designer to dress Hollywood, and now Giorgio
Armani has moved upstate to Silicon Valley.
 &HT;    The designer has positioned a particularly proactive manager in
his San Francisco store to help transform sartorially challenged
dot-com nerds.
 &HT;    ``We're talking about women who show up for an event dressed in
dresses and ... Nikes,'' said one fashion observer.
 &HT;    An Armani spokesman put it another way: ``These are people who
want to evolve from a very casual look to something easy but
elegant.''
 &HT;    
 JERSEY JON  
 &HT;    Guess who's no longer wearing head-to-toe Versace? Jon Bon Jovi.
 &HT;    The rocker/actor was spotted at a recent party in Monte Carlo
wearing a suit by a little-known L.A.-based company called Lords.
 &HT;    ``I'm breaking out of my mold,'' said Bon Jovi, showing off the
big-shouldered dark blue suit. ``But I still wear Italian suits:
Lords is designed by two Italian guys from Jersey.''
 &HT;    
