A1733 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-MONEY-MATTERS-FAIRCHI     08-03 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-MATTERS-FAIRCHILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABES IN MONEYLAND  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By SHARON EDELSON 
 From W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    ``When Are You Entitled to New Underwear and Other Major
Financial Decisions'' ... ``Prince Charming Isn't Coming: How Women
Get Smart About Money'' ... ``A Girl Needs Cash: How to Take Charge
of Your Financial Life.''
 &HT;    Judging by the titles of these recent financial self-help books
for women, you'd think that the fairer sex was positively clueless
about matters of money.
 &HT;    That common perception may help to explain the plethora of
candy-colored book covers and financial seminars packaged with
girlish pursuits.
 &HT;    Henri Bendel recently hosted an event called ``Make Over Your
Financial Future'' which paired the Laura Mercier team of makeup
artists with a Merrill Lynch financial adviser.
 &HT;    Then there's the marketing blurb for the personal-finance book
``Girls Just Want to Have Funds,'' which begins, ``If you know how
to deal with a bad hair day, you have what it takes to be a smart
investor.''
 &HT;    Jennifer Lang, an editor at Hyperion Press, which published
``Girls Just Want to Have Funds,'' says the title and marketing had
a lighthearted approach because ``a lot of the people who are going
to buy this book are younger women.''
 &HT;    But not everyone in the business of offering financial advice
thinks female equals flighty.
 &HT;    ``Publishers and authors sometimes underestimate women,'' says
Sue Herera, the co-anchor of CNBC's ``Business Center.'' ``More
women than ever are managing their portfolios or their family's
portfolios. Women are becoming a huge force in controlling wealth
in this country.''
 &HT;    And there is some evidence that authors and publishers are
catching on.
 &HT;    ``Some titles are a bit patronizing to women, and so are the
books,'' says Fred Hills, a Simon &AMP; Schuster vice president. ``They
presume that women are ignoramuses, when in fact, there are more
women entrepreneurs running small businesses than men.''
 &HT;    When Mary Farrell, a senior investment strategist at
PaineWebber, wrote her latest book, ``Beyond the Basics,'' she
included plenty of hard information on index funds, mutual funds
and identifying future financial trends.
 &HT;    ``There's nothing cutesy about Mary or the title or tone of the
book,'' says Hills, who edited ``Beyond the Basics.'' ``She is the
intelligent spokesperson for female investors, as opposed to the
dumb-blonde approach.''
 &HT;    Farrell, in fact, claims her book isn't specifically designed
for women (though book editors say the picture of her on the cover
is aimed at a female audience).
 &HT;    ``I did some research when I was trying to decide whether to
write a book,'' Farrell says. ``I was very surprised and angry at
how many feel-good books there are but not many books with hard
knowledge. So many of the books were like crisis management. They
just presented one anecdote after another of women as victims.''
 &HT;    Best-selling financial guru Suze Orman's ``9 Steps to Financial
Freedom,'' for example, offers more anecdotes than advice on stocks
and bonds.
 &HT;    Orman takes a psychological approach based on her belief that
women need to overcome their money fears _ about having it and not
having it. While many experts say women have made great strides,
Orman, who travels the country giving seminars, begs to differ.
 &HT;    ``It all depends on where the women live,'' she says. ``In
middle America, a lot of women still are clueless and have this
belief that their husbands know what they're doing with the
money.''
 &HT;    Maybe Orman has an audience among beginners, but financial
experts point out that female-only investment clubs regularly beat
the returns of men-only or mixed clubs.
 &HT;    Judith Briles Ph.D., author of ``10 Smart Money Moves for
Women,'' says men act on hot tips while women do more homework, and
a study by the University of California, Davis, found that men
trade more frequently than women _ and often earn lower returns as
a result.
 &HT;    The need for gender-specific financial advice may be a matter of
style more than substance.
 &HT;    ``Women like communicating with other women,'' says Jennifer
Openshaw, who founded wfn.com (Women's Financial Network). ``They
face different issues. They live longer than men, so they need to
save more in their lifetimes.''
 &HT;    Of course, the latest battleground for the hearts and wallets of
women is the Internet, where female-oriented Web sites such as
msmoney.com offer a no-nonsense approach, dispensing with feel-good
psychobabble and providing investment strategies for different
stages in a woman's life.
 &HT;    ``One of the big pluses for women is that there's never an issue
of being patronized or ignored on the Internet,'' says Briles, who
is also a spokeswoman for wingspanbank.com.
 &HT;    But even some New Economy entrepreneurs believe investment sites
need bells and whistles in order to be compelling to women.
 &HT;    Openshaw, for one, hired Sela Ward _ the actress who plays Lily,
a financially awkward single mom on ABC's ``Once and Again'' _ to
promote wfn.com.
 &HT;    ``Sela could be the poster child for everywoman,'' Openshaw
says. ``She says, 'Finances make my eyes glaze over.''' c.2000
Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Sharon Edelson is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
