<HEADLINE>
FORD'S FOCUS FILLS A NICHE, BUT ITS SEATS COME UP EMPTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, let's talk about the biggest flaw in the Ford Focus and
get right to the bottom: the front seats.
</P>
<P>
   They are just too uncomfortable. When I drove the
top-of-the-line 2000 Focus ZTS in October of last year, I noted
that the seats were ``a bit soft'' but also said they were
comfortable. What was I thinking?
</P>
<P>
   I got the soft part right, but this time, in the 2000 Focus ZX3,
the base model, they proved not only soft, but too restrictive,
even pinching, up the back, and tiring on a long trip.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has done everything else with this car in such a superb
manner, here's hoping they broaden the seat backs and give better
thigh support in the future. But enough grumping.
</P>
<P>
   It is refreshing to see an American auto manufacturer step
effectively into the fray to sell in a market _ small, inexpensive
cars _ that American manufacturers have either virtually given up
on or competed poorly in of late.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors' Ron Zarella, the company's North American
president, acknowledged that GM has essentially lost the market to
Koreans. And certainly, this has been a niche dominated by Asian
manufacturers: Toyota Echo, Honda Civic, Nissan Sentra, Daewoo
Nubira, Hyundai Elantra, Kia Sophia. Dodge jumped in with the Neon,
and Ford has entered with great fanfare and acceptance with the
Focus.
</P>
<P>
   And they've done it obviously understanding that small and
inexpensive doesn't have to mean cheap, dangerous, or underpowered
anymore. Four-cylinder engines with 16 valves can crank out plenty
of power. Air bags, child-safety-seat tethers, and spaciousness can
be part of any small car.
</P>
<P>
   The Focus, which can be purchased from $12,000 to $16,000, is
offered as a three-door coupe (the ZX3 of this review), four-door
sedan, and five-door wagon. Two engines, both inline fours, are
offered, one that produces about 110 horsepower, the other 130.
Interestingly, the more powerful 2.0-liter, 16-valve Zetec is
standard in the ZX3, the entry-level car. Four-speed automatic and
five-speed manual transmissions are available, and I'm a fan of the
manual. It makes this front-wheel-drive car more fun.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier test of the top-of-the-line ZTS showed it to be so
roomy it had a van-like feel, from the high roof to the huge
windshield and the hood that dropped away so quickly you could not
see it from the driver's seat. Ford, with its ``New Edge'' styling
has gone distinctly European with the Focus and that trait may be
most noticeable in the ZX3, which struck me as a bigger, crisper
version of the Volkswagen Golf.
</P>
<P>
   The New Edge program is meant to appeal to younger drivers and,
given their need to carry gear _ skis, boards, camping equipment,
the ``three-door'' _ OK, let's say hatchback like in the old days _
may be the most appealing model. The trunk is cavernous and with a
tall roofline can be piled high, especially if you fold down the
60/40 split rear seat. You could sleep back there waiting for a
morning assault on the barricades at the next Phish concert.
</P>
<P>
   Dashboard ergonomics are modern _ an airplane-cockpit feel to
the tilt-to-the-driver presentation of audio and climate controls,
while all instrumentation is behind the wheel, with the tachometer
and speedometer at center, and the fuel and temperature gauges at
opposite ends of this instrument oval.
</P>
<P>
   There is good storage space in front-door slots _ though the car
could use a between-seats bin up front _ and the glove compartment
is big, as well.
</P>
<P>
   While the 135-horsepower engine has plenty of zip, it is aided
by the fact that Ford kept this car light. Both engines have
aluminum cylinder heads, pistons, and oil pan. The three-door
weighs just over 2,500 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It gives you a graceful and quiet ride, cruising smoothly at 55
while turning just over 2,000 rpms and hitting 3,000 only when
passing at 75. This effortless power let the Focus get just under
28 miles per gallon in mixed highway and country driving.
</P>
<P>
   In designing the ``ride'' for the Focus, Ford tried to find a
middle ground behind hard and soft.
</P>
<P>
   You may have seen the commercial: a group of Gen-Y'ers, all with
some sort of drink in hand, is in a Focus as it cruises toward a
railroad crossing. ``Dude!'' each of the passengers says in warning
that the driver ought to slow down so that no drinks will be
spilled. ``Dooooooood!'' they cry in happy unison when the car,
still at speed, romps smoothly over the tracks without a drop of
spillage.
</P>
<P>
   Effective _ though not as daring as a commercial I remember from
a ``Saturday Night Live'' skit in which a circumcision was
performed in the back seat of a bouncing auto _ but what does a
ride so soft really mean?
</P>
<P>
   It means you get a certain floatiness, particularly in the
steering, on the highway and a softness in cornering. Straight
ahead, the ride is wonderful. However, given that Ford is aiming
this car at younger _ and presumably somewhat more aggressive _
drivers, they ought to tighten it up a bit for some in-corner
handling.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be hard to tweak, with a front suspension that
includes struts, coil springs, dampers and antiroll bar, and a
fully independent rear setup with damper units and antiroll bars.
</P>
<P>
   They also ought to go with disc brakes all around.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, this is a great debut of a new model for Ford and I am
sure you will spot Focuses on college campuses all over America
this year. To help lure young buyers, Ford offers options for the
active lifestyle _ bicycle racks, backpacks that hang over the
backs of the front seats, switchable seat covers. And while a fine
car for the young, the Focus would be a good buy for older drivers
looking for that get-around-town car.
</P>
<P>
   Now if only they'd improve those front seats.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The child-safety-seat tethers at the tops of the seat. They
show somebody was thinking about who would be buying this car.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --Antilock brakes are a $400 option. They ought to be standard
on every car built today, and if that means the base price has to
be $400 higher, so be it. Safety should not be an option.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
