A1755 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-CVN-MURRAY-COLUMN04-C     08-03 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MURRAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bolsheviks for Bush
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Here I am, a Democrat being trampled in stampede
of Republican elephants. That's as good an excuse as any to act
like a jackass.
</P>
<P>
   This was no spur-of-the-moment bad decision. I had given it a
lot of aforethought before I ever got here.
</P>
<P>
   It was an idea that goes back a decade.
</P>
<P>
   That's when, on assignment in the old Soviet Union, a Russian
friend presented me with a red velvet Communist banner complete
with a picture of Lenin and some sort of party slogan emblazoned
across it.
</P>
<P>
   I forgot to ask at the time, and never had a way to later find
out, exactly what the slogan said.
</P>
<P>
   But I've treasured the banner ever since and proudly display it
on the wall of my office.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, it caught my eye as I was packing for the
trip to Philadelphia to cover the GOP National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Without thinking twice, I stuffed it into my bag. You just never
know when you're going to need a Communist banner, particularly at
a GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it came in handy.
</P>
<P>
   A multitude of delegates and members of the media were being
housed at hotels at the airport. Shuttle buses were running for
anyone who needed a ride. So it was that most days I'd join folks
from the North Carolina delegation for the trip to the convention
center.
</P>
<P>
   I always made it a point to dress appropriately, coat and tie,
for rubbing well-tailored elbows with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But the next to last night, I made an exception. I made a
fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   My determination reinforced by influential beverages, I put on
my old faded blue jeans, a wrinkled cotton shirt, a flaming red
gimme cap advertising my hometown's ZOO park railroad and then...
and then ...
</P>
<P>
   And then I draped the Communism banner around my neck.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans claim they are for inclusiveness. I wanted to
see just how inclusive them could be.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-inch cigar clamped between my teeth, I arrived early at
the bus stop behind the hotel. By the time the bus got there, we
had a full load -- all the better to gauge reaction.
</P>
<P>
   But they're shifty, those Republicans. They be looking at my
banner, but when I'd look at them, they'd look away. Everytime, it
was the same.
</P>
<P>
   After awhile I started singing just loud enough to be heard,
``Look away, look away, look away, Re-pub-li-cans.''
</P>
<P>
   We all spilled off the bus at the convention center. They went
their way, I went my mine. I was almost home free when a woman
security guard stopped me for a closer look at my credentials.
</P>
<P>
   But what she was really eyeing was my banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does that say?'' she asked, her jaw set.
</P>
<P>
   Casually, I removed the cigar from between my teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bolsheviks for Bush,'' I said, evenly.
</P>
<P>
   She paused a long moment, looking at me and then again at the
banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' she finally nodded, ``go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, if that's not inclusiveness I don't know what it is. The
Republicans have even made room for compassionate communists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I was a little disappointed nobody asked who the picture
was. I was ready for that.
</P>
<P>
   I was going to tell them it was George W. Bush's grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
