<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-EGYPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK MEETS EGYPTIAN LEADER TO DISCUSS PEACE WITH PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak met Thursday
with President Hosni Mubarak, saying he wanted to clarify for the
Egyptian leader his desire to reach a peace agreement with the
Palestinians once they show ``responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, in the port city of Alexandria, lasted about two
hours. Mubarak had met with the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat,
on Wednesday in Alexandria, Arafat's summer residence.
</P>
<P>
   It was Barak's first excursion outside Israel since returning
from the peace talks in Camp David, Md., last week and then
watching his governing coalition begin to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 days of negotiations ended without an accord, and Israel
has blamed Arafat for their failure, an accusation that Arab
leaders, including Mubarak, have rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found in Egypt a listening ear to the complexity of the
problem,'' Barak was quoted by the Associated Press as saying after
his meeting Thursday. ``I clarified that we are ready to do what is
necessary to achieve an agreement, but we have important interests,
and an agreement will only be achieved if the other side
demonstrates openness, seriousness and responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Egypt has played a pivotal role during the past seven years as a
mediator for the Palestinians and successive Israeli prime
ministers. The first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel, in 1979, Egypt has also had the closest ties to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting at Camp David, and its aftermath of
recriminations, have soured Mubarak's relations with both
countries. Still, the Egyptian president has been meeting
constantly with fellow Arab leaders since the negotiations broke
down, in an attempt to maintain some momentum in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of Palestinian sovereignty over Arab East
Jerusalem, which Egypt has supported and Israel has steadfastly
rejected, Mubarak has given no indication that he will bend in
consideration of Barak's domestic troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we supposed to pressure President Arafat to make
concessions on Jerusalem?'' said Foreign Minister Amr Moussa after
Thursday's meeting. ``It is not our role to ask any side to accept,
without discussion, a stand proposed by the other side. Our role is
to make the two sides reach a fair, reasonable and balanced
stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, meanwhile, continued on his own peripatetic mission to
explain his position. He has already visited France, as well as
North Africa and several other Arab states, and Thursday he arrived
in Johannesburg for a meeting with former South African President
Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these meetings between Arab leaders are preparing the Arab
world for compromises on issues other than Jerusalem,'' said
Mohammed Said Said, a researcher at the Al Ahram Center for
Political and Strategic Studies here. ``Egypt is sending a very
clear message to America that, even though Egyptian-American and
Egyptian-Israeli relations are very strained now, it will not
change its stance over Jerusalem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1772 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     08-03 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     (For Release Sunday, August 6)  
 &HT;     Republicans dislike Clinton, but like his political strategy 
 &HT;     (For use by New :York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The relationship between the George W. Bush's
Republicans and Bill Clinton is a fascinating study in
contradictions. On the one hand, GOP leaders express their disgust
with the president's behavior and speak longingly of having a chief
executive worthy of their respect.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, their decision to transform the GOP's image
by opening the party's doors widely to African Americans, Hispanics
and gays copies the strategy that twice won the presidency for
Clinton and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a self-proclaimed new Democrat, moved his party to the
center of the political spectrum and away from its left-wing
moorings in 1992. Bush and his triumphant brethren have shifted the
GOP away from its ultra-conservative base and into the mainstream
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republican platform continues to support a
constitutional amendment to end abortion, Bush, if elected, is
expected to do little to achieve that objective. The platform does
not, as in years past, demand abolition of the Department of
Education. Instead, Bush advocates a strong federal role in
boosting the education of American youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bush's wife, Laura, a former schoolteacher and
librarian, devoted her televised convention speech last Monday
night to the theme that no child should be left behind.
</P>
<P>
   That same night, retired Army Gen. Colin Powell, arguably the
most admired man in America, challenged his fellow Republicans to
``bring the promise of America to everyone'' and to spread the
legacy of Abraham Lincoln throughout the land.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates even applauded him when he announced that he supports
a woman's right to choose, a policy despised by abortion opponents,
and affirmative action, which most Republicans have opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Old Party just ain't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is that the new Republican leadership,
represented by Bush and the man he beat for the GOP nomination,
Arizona Sen. John McCain, have watched Clinton's successful
stewardship of the Democratic party and learned from it.
</P>
<P>
   After months of public attention to his outrageous personal
behavior, Clinton still can thrill a partisan crowd with his
rhetoric and demonstrate that the way to success in politics is
through diversity and the inclusion of voters who once were outside
a party's perimeters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton began his presidency badly by spending an inordinate
amount of time trying to keep his campaign promise clear the way
for gays in the military. Then, after failing to win passage of the
massive health care plan that he and Hillary devised and losing
control of Congress to Newt Gingrich's Republicans in 1994, Clinton
proclaimed that the days of big government ``are over.''
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Clinton was viewed as something of a political
corpse; his presidency was considered to be nearly over.
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly adapted his policies to the realities expressed
by voters in 1994 and defeated Bob Dole for president in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He won the votes of African-Americans, Hispanics, women and gays
by making the Democratic Party hospitable to them.
</P>
<P>
   To convert Clinton's strategy into a winning stance for
Republicans, Bush and Company have played down their ties to the
religious right and their party's tradition of appealing primarily
to white males, leaving African Americans, Hispanics, Asians and
gays outside their door.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, evangelist Pat Robertson, a staunch Bush supporter in
the South Carolina primary, which was dominated by the rightwing,
described the Philadelphia convention as ``four days of Pablum.''
He said he longed for the days when Republicans fought vigorously
over issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Pablum is exactly the main course that Bush ordered served
at the convention that nominated him for president.
</P>
<P>
   Those like Robertson who long for the era of magnificent
Republican confrontations could recall the bitter showdown between
the mainstream forces of Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower and the narrow
conservative and isolationist forces led by Ohio Senator Robert A.
Taft in 1952. Ike won that one.
</P>
<P>
   Or they could look back to 1964, and the vicious battle between
Barry Goldwater's ultra-conservative supporters and the more
liberal wing of the party led by New York Gov. Nelson Rockefeller
It was at the GOP convention in San Francisco that year that
conservative delegates mercilessly booed Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   Goldwater won the nomination but was badly trounced by Lyndon
Johnson in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Convention delegates also might gaze back just eight years to
Pat Buchanan's fiery speech on the ``moral crisis'' in America _ a
lengthy harangue against gays, immigrants, supporters of abortion
and liberals that forced Ronald Reagan to delay his last televised
speech to a Republican convention until after prime time.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's convention, Bush and his brethren arranged for
African-Americans and Hispanics to play highly visible roles in the
televised unfolding political drama. They served as speakers, as
entertainers, as leaders in salutes to the Stars and Stripes and as
theatrical ``extras'' providing onstage audiences for appearances
by the party's stars.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party of George W. Bush is _ at least on the
surface _ a different party that that of George Herbert Walker
Bush, Ronald Reagan and Bob Dole. In November, we will learn
whether the transition is successful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
