<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETHING SMELLS FISHY IN SWEDEN  

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not too early to book a flight to Sweden for next year,
when the world's first rotten fish museum is scheduled to open.
</P>
<P>
   According to Reuters, the museum will tell the story of a
fermented fish dish called surstromming (sour herring), a Swedish
delicacy that unsophisticated outsiders claim has the aroma of dog
excrement.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, only 2 percent of Sweden's 800,000 cans of surstromming
are exported each year, making it hard to find on the shelves of
your local Publix. For those of you who would like to make some at
home, all you basically have to do is get a tub o' herring,
sprinkle a little salt on it, and then let it stand in the sun
until that mouth-watering kennel-like aroma wafts through your
window, or your house is covered with flies, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   For Sweden, better known for its socialism and pornography, this
is a welcome and long-overdue first step into the lucrative world
of tourist attractions. One might think that it will be difficult
to get people to shell out $35 a head for the privilege of walking
through a museum that smells like a house-full of mastiffs with
tummy problems, but I don't think that will be the case.
</P>
<P>
   The secret, of course, is marketing. Disney World makes more
money in a year than most South American countries, and what are
visitors paying for? The opportunity to stand for three hours under
the kind of sun that can cause one's mouse ears to spontaneously
combust in order to take a 90-second ride that is likely to give
you a migraine headache or make you sick to your stomach, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's back to your $300-a-night hotel room for a quick
shower and another invigorating two-hour wait at one of the
resort's many overpriced restaurants. And then, finally, to bed,
perhaps to dream of a rich relative leaving you a hefty inheritance
so you can pay off your Visa bill sometime before the first woman
walks on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of people from all over the world come to
Orlando to treat themselves to this experience. New theme parks
seem to sprout up on a weekly basis to handle the overflow. The
attractions differ slightly from theme park to theme park but long
waits in the hot sun appear to be the common denominator that keeps
folks coming back.
</P>
<P>
   When you compare the experience of an Orlando theme park in
summer to that of a Swedish museum that walks visitors through the
ancient technique of making fish smell like a failed experiment in
housebreaking, I, for one, have got to go with the museum.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the kids would not be pestering you for snacks
every five minutes. Also, Sweden's climate being what it is, most
tourists will probably come down with a cold or some other kind of
upper respiratory infection that will render them incapable of
smelling fish, fermented or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   And, if all else fails, there is the fine selection of
pornography in the museum's gift shop to keep people's minds off
the stink, which I bet isn't so bad once you get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
