<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-AIRPORT-POWER-TEX     08-03 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-POWER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRPORT FACILITY COULD GENERATE SAVINGS AND REDUCE AIR POLLUTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BRYON OKADA 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS/FORT WORTH AIRPORT _ A power plant that creates
electricity from natural gas could be built at Dallas/Fort Worth
Airport in the next two years, a move that would give the airport
its own environmentally friendly power source.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials are considering building a combined-cycle
cogeneration plant that uses natural gas-powered turbines to make
electricity, then uses heat-capturing equipment to create steam for
space heating.
</P>
<P>
   Having an on-site power source would save the 18,000-acre
airport millions of dollars in utility bills while reducing air
pollution, according to D/FW officials. The airport plans to
convert most of its vehicles to clean-burning engines by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for the power plant discussion is the need for D/FW
Airport to reduce boiler emissions by 70 percent, as mandated by
the region's strategy for meeting federal air quality standards in
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what changed the scope of the project,'' said Rusty
Hodapp, the airport director of maintenance. ``Originally this was
about installing the heating and cooling capacity. Then the plan
targeted boilers for emissions reductions. We had 30-year-old
boilers that weren't going to be impacted. Now we have to do
something to reduce the emission.''
</P>
<P>
   The airport requires about 20 megawatts of electricity for its
operations. That may grow to 70 megawatts, as Terminal D, Terminal
F, the people mover, the Central Utilities Plant, parking
structures and ground support are created or expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Building a power plant would reduce emissions in several ways,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   First, it would take the airport off the market as a consumer.
The airport currently purchases power from TXU Electric &AMP; Gas.
Major tenants, such as American and Delta airlines, contract
separately for power.
</P>
<P>
   The airport has a goal of reducing nitrogen oxide emissions, or
smog, by 70 percent from its current 58 tons, Hodapp said. A new
plant would produce about 16 tons, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The new plant also would use excess heat, usually looked at as
waste, to regulate the temperatures in Terminal D, then use what is
left to increase electricity-making capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benefits of building a power project are that you improve the
reliability of the airport,'' said Katherine Potter, spokeswoman
for San Jose, Calif.-based Calpine Corp., the nation's leading
independent power company, which recently sold a similar
107-megawatt cogeneration plant to the Port Authority of New York &AMP;
New Jersey for use at John F. Kennedy International Airport. ``From
costs and environmental standpoints, it's a win-win.''
</P>
<P>
   D/FW officials said they also believe that the creation of the
plant will save the airport $100 million over 30 years in utility
bills.
</P>
<P>
   The plant probably would be built at the Central Utilities Plant
between the two Hyatt hotels, with a satellite facility nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The deregulation of the electrical industry will take effect in
Texas in January 2002, and standards for nitrogen oxide emissions
will take effect in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to position ourselves to operate in that environment,
being mindful of the emissions being generated,'' Hodapp said.
</P>
<P>
   That the airport is using the next two years as a transition
period is not unique, TXU officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to have D/FW as a customer and we'll compete for them,
but the fact that they are looking at self-generation or
cogeneration is not new,'' TXU spokeswoman Carol Peters said.
``Many companies are looking ahead and trying to manage their
energy consumption in a market that is open. This project would be
considered an independent power project in terms of competition,
and we welcome additional generation in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   A summary of a study on energy needs for Terminal D and the
people-mover system, conducted by Fort Worth-based Carter &AMP;
Burgess, is expected to be submitted today to the Dallas/Fort Worth
Airport Board. A final report is expected in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final piece to this puzzle is as we finish the
comprehensive study with the Terminal D and the energy loads
associated with the people-mover project, the scope of the study
needs to be expanded to include all the development in the central
terminal area,'' Hodapp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'll end up with is a bigger project than what is
currently envisioned.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
