<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-HONG-KONG-IMMIG-620&AMP;A     08-03 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-IMMIG-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINLAND CHINESE SET FIRE TO IMMIGRATION OFFICES; DEPORTATIONS
ORDERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ For the mob of mainland Chinese immigrants who
massed in the 13th-floor lobby of Hong Kong's immigration tower on
Wednesday afternoon, the time for filling out forms or even howling
in protest had passed.
</P>
<P>
   After being turned away yet again by immigration officers in
their quest for residency permits, the immigrants doused the lobby
floor with a flammable liquid and ignited it. The fire raced
through the offices, and by the time it was extinguished by a
sprinkler system, 50 people had suffered burns, and several of them
were in serious condition. Six immigrants were still in critical
condition Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden eruption of violence flabbergasted people in this
normally tranquil city. Most had stopped paying attention to the
lonely struggle of 6,000 mainland Chinese for the right to settle
in this former British colony.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuffed repeatedly by the local courts and facing deportation
to the mainland, the immigrants were a sad reminder of the awkward
relationship between China and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hong Kong reverted to Chinese sovereignty under a July
1997 agreement with Britain, the former colony has retained much of
its autonomy under China's ``one country, two systems'' formula.
That included control over immigration, which means Chinese
mainland citizens here must have residency permits or they will be
sent back.
</P>
<P>
   As the mainlanders have run out of options, they have grown
frustrated and angry. On Wednesday, the anger mutated into a
desperate attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to control our emotions,'' said a mainland
woman who gave her name as Ngai. ``We've been here so long, we
can't work, we can't earn a living. Even our families in China are
now against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ngai, who is 26 and is from Guangdong Province, was not involved
in the attack. She deplored the actions of her fellow immigrants,
which she said were not supported by the vast majority of the
immigrants. And she feared the attack will lead to a backlash
against mainland Chinese here.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Hong Kong government moved swiftly Thursday to crack
down. It announced the immediate deportation of 1,000 mainland
Chinese who are not involved in legal cases, which effectively
stays their deportation orders. Until now, Hong Kong has treated
the mainlanders gingerly, partly for political reasons and partly
to guard its reputation for the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested 15 immigrants in connection with the blaze,
while Hong Kong's leaders condemned the attack in unusually blunt
terms. Tung Chee-hwa, the territory's chief executive, called it
``brutal behavior, irrational behavior that is unacceptable to all
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown between the mainlanders and the Hong Kong
government had been brewing for more than a year. In December, 50
protesters clashed with police outside Tung's offices, hurling
bamboo sticks and flower pots. Last week, 10 mainlanders scuffled
with guards and threatened to commit suicide after immigration
officers refused to meet with them.
</P>
<P>
   Their frustration stems from a ruling by Hong Kong's high court
in early 1999 that granted residency to mainland-born children with
at least one Hong Kong parent. The ruling opened the door to tens
of thousands of mainland Chinese who are the product of
cross-border marriages or relationships. And it terrified the local
government, which claimed that Hong Kong would be inundated by 1.6
million people.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, at the behest of the government, China's
parliament, the National People's Congress, overturned the ruling
by rewriting the parts of Hong Kong's constitution on which it was
based. That closed the door to all but about 6,000 immigrants, who
had already lodged residency claims.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hong Kong allowed those people to remain in the territory to
fight their cases. But the high court recently reaffirmed China's
right to overturn its ruling. And a series of lower courts have
hewed to that line, ruling against the immigrants or refusing to
hear their cases.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here said they have been tolerant of the mainlanders _
allowing them to camp for weeks in front of the government's
offices and to protest almost daily at the immigration tower. But
the rampage could poison the attitude of Hong Kongers toward their
mainland cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Although they share cultural ties _ and in some cases familial
ones _ many people in this affluent capitalist bastion already look
down on mainlanders. They fret that if the immigrants are allowed
in, they will blight Hong Kong, taking jobs and lowering the living
standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very difficult road ahead of us,'' said Ngai, as she
and her friends gathered to talk nervously about their future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
