 ART ADV.: Photos with MEDICAL-ACCESS, AUTOS-COLUMN, PARROT-RESCUER
and FASHION-COLUMN are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service
subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VIGILANTE-PRIEST (Lamitan, Philippines) _ Father Ceritto Nicorda
is a lot like most Catholic priests _ except that he carries an
M-16 along with his Bible. As the leader of a Christian vigilante
group fighting Muslim insurgents he knows he has sinned, and that
he has a problem with anger. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 1450 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-ACCESS (Boston) _ Many health care organizations now
allow patients to view their medical records online. Beth Israel
Hospital has taken the concept one step beyond: Patients can
actually add information to their records. Doctors are outrages. By
Liz Kowalczyk. 1330 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   COOP-EDUCATION (Boston) _ For much of the past century,
Northeastern University has been a national pioneer in blending
college studies with work. But when a typical $10-an-hour job
barely dents the annual $20,000 in tuition, Northeastern has begun
selling students on the idea that the work is part of their
education. For many students, however, cooperative education
translates into menial labor. By David Abel. 1570 words.
</P>
<P>
