<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONE KILL': IT SEEMED LIKE A PERFECT MATCH, AT FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If nothing else, the television movie ``One Kill'' offers the
most unusual language of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day I enlisted my life fell into place,'' whispers a
Marine captain, an attractive blond woman, as she kisses a male
superior officer. As the captain becomes more aroused, she moans,
``I had something to aim for. Duty, honor weren't words, but
something I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The major sighs, ``I used to dream about girls like you _ in
high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, this seemingly perfect match ends up with him dead and her
defending herself against a murder charge and a military conspiracy
(of course). Viewers must defend against unconvincing characters,
murky storytelling and a barrage of cliches. Yes, a pack of
reporters thrusts microphones in the captain's face when she goes
to trial. Yes, the night before she testifies, she sits at a table
and downs a glass of whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Heche does what she can (not much) with the part of Mary
Jane O'Malley, the captain. Shelley Evans has written a character
who may be morally and maternally impeccable. (Her children, by a
former husband, frolic with her and cutely call her Captain.) But
she is also impenetrable. It's hard to imagine what lies behind her
Mona Lisa smiles and self-righteous pronouncements. (``I don't make
deals with my principles,'' she says.)
</P>
<P>
   She isn't popular with the men under her command, though it's
hard to understand why, exactly, from this scenario (except that
they, too, may find her obnoxiously smug). She seems to be the only
woman doing actual soldiers' work on the base. The only other
military women are a clerk and the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The movie wants to make a feminist stand, about the unfair
treatment of women in the military, but seems too tired to put up
much of a fight. It also capitalizes in an unseemly way, given its
message, on Heche's body, with many peeks at her wearing her
underwear and less, during a sex scene. The movie, based on a real
case, makes Captain O'Malley the victim of an anti-female cover-up,
by a Marine establishment bent on protecting the dignity of her
dead lover, a Vietnam veteran with 35 years of service. But the
filmmakers unwittingly created a dramatic obstacle to their polemic
by casting Sam Shepard as the major whom O'Malley kills in
self-defense. Unlike Heche, who seems trapped within the narrow
confines of her character, Shepard has a craggy charisma that
implies depth where there may not be any. You feel some sympathy
for him, another middle-aged man unhinged by hot sex with a younger
woman, even as his behavior becomes erratic and then dangerous
toward Captain O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is billed as a thriller, but its pulse is weak. It
does have one astute line, uttered by Eric Stoltz, playing Captain
O'Malley's lawyer: ``This case doesn't have any heroes, captain.
Nobody likes it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also this weekend:
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to pin down the genesis of creativity, but that's
the ambition of ``Influences,'' a new half-hour series airing 7:30
p.m. on Bravo. Each week, after an ingratiating introduction by
Alan Alda, television writers, directors, actors and comedians
discuss what motivated them. The program is also produced by the
Museum of Television and Radio, so television shows are the
dominant source of inspiration. Parents, however, aren't ignored.
(``All it would have taken is one hug from my father and I'd be an
accountant,'' says Ray Romano, the comedian and star of ``Everybody
Loves Raymond.'')
</P>
<P>
   In the premiere, the least interesting of the first few shows in
the series, Tracey Ullmann pays homage to _ not surprisingly _
Lucille Ball, Mary Tyler Moore and Lily Tomlin, from her
``Laugh-In'' days. Ted Danson reveals that he grew up in a house
without television.
</P>
<P>
   But the old television clips are fun to watch, especially
unfamiliar shows like ``Price of Tomatoes,'' a 1962 television play
starring Peter Falk, that was momentous for the actress Tyne Daly.
``He just leaped out of the television set and grabbed me,'' she
says of Falk's performance.
</P>
<P>
   John Lithgow gives credit to Shakespeare and Milton Berle,
whereas Susan Lucci, who has spent most of her life playing the
duplicitous Erica Kane on ``All My Children,'' found ``The Donna
Reed Show'' important. ``I saw that things were too polite,'' she
says, preferring ``I Love Lucy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That seemed better to me,'' Lucci says. ``They weren't so
polite to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ONE KILL'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Written by Shelley Evans; directed by Christopher Menaul; music
by Eric Allaman; Matthew Herath and Wendy Wilson, co-producers;
Michael Storey, director of photography; Jacques Michel Bradette,
production designer; Joel S. Rice, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Anne Heche (Mary Jane O'Malley), Sam Shepard (Maj. Nelson
Gray), Eric Stoltz (Capt. Walker Randall), Kate McNeil (Maj. Leslie
Nesbitt), Bill MacDonald (Col. Sam Doran), Sean Bell (Lt. Tim
Macey), Carl Marotte (Hap O'Malley), Max Morrow (Harry O'Malley)
and Charlotte Arnold (Callie O'Malley).
</P>
<P>
   `INFLUENCES'
</P>
<P>
   7:30 p.m. on Bravo
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
