</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD EXPECTED TO RECOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Doctors upgraded the condition of former
President Ford Thursday morning, a day after he was admitted to the
neurological intensive care unit of Hahnemann University Hospital
here after suffering at least one small stroke over the last few
days.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin McDowell, Ford's spokesman, said that the former
president's condition had been upgraded from serious to fair.
McDowell, who will hold a second briefing with doctors at noon,
said Ford had risen from his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has been up and had a short, brief walk this
morning,'' McDowell said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, doctors said the prognosis was good that Ford
would make a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should totally recover,'' said Dr. Robert J.
Schwartzman, the hospital's chief neurologist.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 87, was the nation's 38th president, and he has been in
Philadelphia for the Republican National Convention. Only hours
before being admitted to the hospital, near the city's center, he
had been given a rousing salute by convention delegates for his
brief, generally calming and healing stewardship of the nation in
the aftermath of Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Ford arrived at the hospital at about 9 a.m. Wednesday,
complaining of dizziness, weakness in his left arm and slurred
speech. He was admitted, hospital officials later said, after an
imaging scan indicated he had suffered at least one stroke in the
brain stem at the rear of his head.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 hours earlier, around midnight, the former
president had walked in with his usual Secret Service security
detail, complaining of sinus pain. He was given some pain medicine
and released.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials defended their decision to release him
without further tests, saying they felt that they had responded
properly to the symptoms they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he sought was some pain relief,'' said Dr. Wayne Satz, the
hospital's chief of emergency medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what was different about the symptoms during the second
hospital visit, Satz said that they were more acute. He also said
that Ford's wife, Betty, had reported that Ford had also felt ill
earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, before heading for Philadelphia, Ford saw a doctor in
Colorado, complaining then, as later, of head pain, Mrs. Ford told
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In the convention hall on Tuesday night, while Ford was being
honored, he appeared visibly tired and in one interview noticeably
slurred his words.
</P>
<P>
   News of his hospitalization injected a somber note into a
convention that up until then had been one big, joyful celebration
of George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Hahnemann doctors said they were treating Ford with
blood-thinners in an effort to lessen the likelihood of future
strokes. In someone his age, they emphasized, there was a greater
danger of another stroke than in someone younger.
</P>
<P>
   But a minor stroke is not unusual at Ford's age.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman said that Ford was ``perfectly awake, functioning
mentally _ that's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   McDowell earlier described Ford as ``very alert and ready to go
home.'' Should he continue to recover without complications,
hospital officials said, he might be released in five or six days.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman said he did not think Ford had suffered any brain
damage from the stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will all clear, mainly in his balance center,''
he added. ``That should all recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Brott of the National Stroke Association said it was
possible that the signs and symptoms Ford spoke about in his visit
to the hospital Tuesday night, when he complained of pain in his
face, dizziness and sleeplessness, would not have immediately
suggested to doctors that a stroke had occurred. Symptoms described
by a patient, Brott said, are often ambiguous and might point to a
more likely cause than a stroke _ for example, an infection.
</P>
<P>
   On the same point, Schwartzman said that a mild stroke ``looks
like an inner-ear infection sometimes, sometimes it's hard to tell
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   A stroke is usually caused by a blood clot blocking a vessel in
the brain, so that cells beyond the blockage do not receive
nutrients, and can thus be injured or die.
</P>
<P>
   The cells affected in Ford's case are in the lower rear of the
brain where motor activity, like balance, is controlled.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, when the stroke is small, the damaged brain cells
can recover or the killed cells can be bypassed so that other
healthy cells can perform the same function, leading to complete
recovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
