<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1833 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-POTTERPRODUCTS-HNS &LR;      08-03 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTTERPRODUCTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTTERPRODUCTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  RETAILERS HOPE FOR A ``VERY HARRY'' CHRISTMAS &HT;    By SHERRY THOMAS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated)_Pottered out?
</P>
<P>
   Retail giants hope not. Many are banking on a very Harry
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   This has nothing to do with book sales, mind you. J.K. Rowling's
``Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' may have sold 5 million
copies, but that's a bean drop in the beaker compared to the gold
some 45 licensed manufacturers hope to find in the world's favorite
boy wizard.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the faces of Harry and his spellbinding associates to be
plastered everywhere this fall, from sheets to toys to boxer
shorts.
</P>
<P>
   First up, collectible Christmas ornaments. Coming soon, Harry
Potter-themed furniture, electronics, board games, trading cards,
plush toys, dolls _ you name it. Rumor has it Cap Candy is even
developing its version of Bertie Botts Every Flavored Beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of interesting to me,'' said Sally Jordan, owner of
Jeremy's Books and Toys in Webster, Texas, southeast of Houston. At
a show in Dallas in June, ``there wasn't that much (Harry Potter
paraphernalia) showing. But I have a feeling when I go back in the
fall, there will be more now that there's so much publicity about
Harry Potter.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' consumer products division gained all worldwide
licensing and merchandising rights for the Potter series as part of
its film deal with Rowling.
</P>
<P>
   The first movie, based on Rowling's first book, ``Harry Potter
and the Sorcerer's Stone,'' won't hit theaters until 2001. But with
``Goblet of Fire'' making a big goblet of money, and the holiday
retail season fast approaching, manufacturers are being told to get
on the broomstick, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at Cornelius Nurseries in Houston are already taking
orders for Harry Potter ornaments and lights from Kurt S. Adler
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be of Harry playing Quidditch, Harry and
Hedwig, Hermione, and Ron,'' said Pat Nichilo, a designer at one
four Houston-area Cornelius stores. ``We're also going to carry the
Nimbus 2000 broom and Lightning Bolt icicle ornaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that a Harry Christmas tree probably won't come
cheap. One of Adler's Polonaise glass ornaments sells for $50 _ or
you can get a boxed set of four for $200. The light set retails for
$22.50. Other ornaments (including resin and tin) in the collection
sell from $5.50 and up.
</P>
<P>
   But if all your pint-size Potter fan wants for Christmas this
year is a Harry Potter bed (with attached wizard tent), you may be
out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the very end of the year, or the beginning of
next,'' said Steve Paul, a sales representative for P.J. Kids, the
Princeton, N.J.-based company licensed to design and manufacture
Harry Potter bedroom furniture.
</P>
<P>
   He said the line, which will include bedding and accessories
(with stars and lightning bolts, no doubt), is aimed at upscale
department and furniture stores. A retail trade magazine reported
last month that a deal had already been struck with FAO Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Paul nor FAO Schwartz, however, could confirm details.
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Meissner, a manager at Houston's FAO Schwartz store, said
the store is expecting a Harry Potter line before the holidays, but
he wasn't privy to the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably expecting to get the line as of late fall,''
Meissner said. ``The (flagship) store in New York will carry it
first. This store just started carrying Harry Potter recently, so
it's going to take a while before we get the full line in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who has ordered Harry Potter calendars, address books
and playing cards for her Webster store, remained skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a nice add-on. Like this Christmas, we'll have some
nice backpack chains and key chains for people who know their
children and grandchildren really like Harry Potter. But the plush
toys and the other stuff? I don't know,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're selling to readers. And let's face it, there
are a lot more moviegoers than readers _ even of Harry Potter. A
lot of people will buy it (Harry Potter merchandise) just because
it's hot, not really knowing anything about Harry Potter. But the
10- or 11-year-olds? They're not going to want Harry Potter sheets.
They're going to want another book.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
