<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TAO OF STEVE': A BIG MAN CHASING `COOL' ONE CONQUEST AT A
TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no Steve in ``The Tao of Steve,'' the
light-as-a-marshmallow romantic comedy directed by Jenniphr
Goodman. But there is a universal ideal represented by a spiritual
concept proposed by the main character, Dex: The pursuit of the
perfection attained by all-American cool guys like Steve McQueen,
Steve McGarrett (``Hawaii Five-0'') and Steve Austin (``The Six
Million Dollar Man'').
</P>
<P>
   Dex (Donal Logue) never really explains why emulating McGarrett,
a lawman who had roughly one romance a season and a propensity for
chasing down hitmen from the mainland who had brought only one
bullet with them, is a goal to which he aspires. (``Tao'' also may
be a sleight-of-hand pun on the movie's setting, Santa Fe, N.M.,
near Taos.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dex is a likable guy, a walking epitome of the Peter Pan
syndrome. Actually, he's more like a blobby epitome of that
syndrome, a little boy unashamed of his rolls of flab. His size
doesn't prevent him from scoring with the ladies, and his
minor-league obsession with the Steves underscores his devotion to
trivial matters.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is the story of Dex's infatuation with women and how
he eventually has to deal with giving up his one-night stands to
find spiritual truth with one woman, Syd (Greer Goodman, sister of
the director, who worked on the screenplay with her and Duncan
North). Dex's romping with his dog, a happy sun-colored Lab, and
his ease with the preschoolers he teaches are part of what makes
him so attractive to women. He explains himself to each potential
conquest so that his lack of deviousness becomes part of his
come-on.
</P>
<P>
   Logue's winning performance comes out of Dex's own amusement at
the effort he puts into his pleasure-hunting, giving the lie to his
apparent slacker vibe. He's very serious about not being serious.
Dex's Taoism is fairly well worked out; he's a guy with too much
time on his hands who has spent a lot of energy on his world view.
He has quotes from ``Don Giovanni'' and Thomas Aquinas to
rationalize his life.
</P>
<P>
   Logue's turn as Dex won him a deserved acting award at this
year's Sundance Film Festival, and when he is onscreen the picture
glides, in part because Dex has a cherub's glee over what he gets
away with. Maybe too many movies celebrate extended adolescence,
but Logue's breezy and innocent hedonism gives ``Tao'' a roughhouse
affability. He is one of those actors you've probably caught out of
the corner of your eye, the bad guy who gets one scene in a movie.
(In ``The Patriot,'' he's the racist who quickly reforms.) If he
has been biding his time and waiting for the chance to prove he can
carry a movie, ``Tao'' shows he is up to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   He plays off his avoirdupois, commenting on it before anyone
else can and making it part of his arsenal. (At Sundance, he had a
matinee-idol trimness as he accepted his award.) There's an ``if
only he used his power for the good of mankind'' aspect here, as
there almost always is in stories of unregenerate Lotharios.
(``Tao'' does bring up ``Don Giovanni,'' after all.) It is evident
that he is smart and wasting away _ well, intellectually, anyway _
and that all he needs is the right woman to bring things together.
</P>
<P>
   The movie bogs down when he starts to lavish the same attention
on his courtship of Syd, who is still nursing a wound over having
been one of his one-night stands. Goodman has to play the grown-up,
and it's hard to tell if the writing for Syd is subpar or if she is
stiff as an actress. Eventually, Dex's doughy sheepishness and his
attempt to elevate his self-indulgent behavior by mixing in
European philosophy along with Hollywood Boulevard icons feels a
bit like a conceit. The cat-and-mouse game that he and Syd play
stretches out because it's standard-issue plotting. ``The Tao of
Steve'' can't redeem the moves toward its predictable happy ending.
But the movie has a protagonist who has a great time getting there.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TAO OF STEVE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jenniphr Goodman; written by Duncan North, Greer
Goodman and Jenniphr Goodman; director of photography, Teodoro
Maniaci; edited by Sarah Gartner; music by Joe Delia; production
designer, Rosario Provenza; produced by Anthony Bregman; released
by Sony Pictures Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Donal Logue (Dex), Greer Goodman (Syd), Kimo Wills (Dave),
Ayelet Kaznelson (Beth), David Aaron Baker (Rick) and Nina Jaroslaw
(Maggie).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 87 minutes. ``The Tao of Steve'' is rated R (under
17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes
sexual situations and profanity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
