<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BETTER LIVING': A FAMILY SO DYSFUNCTIONAL IT COULD BLOW UP A DAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth has a heart the size of a mountain,'' Gail says
about one of her sisters in ``Better Living.'' In this movie,
everyone has a heart the size of a mountain, and most of the
characters make as much noise as a rock slide. If you've missed the
kind of bellowing in a comedic context that disappeared with the
Norman Lear sitcoms _ called scream theater in the 1970s _ then
this is the movie for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better Living'' is one of those comedy-dramas in which
everyone is a little crazy in a way that is intended to be
ingratiating until a horrible family secret is revealed. Skin-deep
quirkiness is not always adorable, however, especially when
everyone has been conceived as a ``character.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympia Dukakis plays Nora, the delusional mother who is
building an underground structure of some sort under her house. Her
daughters _ Gail (Wendy Hoopes), Elizabeth (Deborah Hedwall) and
Maryann (Catherine Corpeny) _ holler at one another but love their
nutty mom. When their dad, Tom (Roy Scheider), shows up at their
mother's doorstep, it causes some confusion because Nora has been
saying he is dead and doesn't quite recognize him. For whatever
reason, he has been gone for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gail is happy to see him come back. Tom left when she was very
young, and she is looking for a father figure. She snuggles up to
her uncle, Jack (Edward Herrmann), a priest, for encouragement and
advice, and he feigns lack of interest. Elizabeth, a public
defender, is full of rage about her father; she remembers how
turbulent the house was when Tom and Nora were together. And that's
saying something, since there's still plenty of china crashing into
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better Living'' is jam-packed with sarcasm and would-be
eccentricity; the perpetually dazed Maryann has yet to name her
8-month-old daughter and has the free-floating neurosis of a
character from a 40-year-old stage play. The picture feels like a
blocking rehearsal for a play where all the movement is being
coordinated but the underlying emotional notes have yet to be set.
Any sense of reality that the movie tries to build is not helped by
the shouting matches, which come across as actressy tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann comes off best because he doesn't have to shriek his
lines. He is the cynical priest who takes a snort or two from his
flask whenever things get too weird, a condition that seems to be a
constant here. Jack is mournful; a lot of wasted hope seems to be
stored in his jowls. But Herrmann is fleet and smooth; he takes
some pride in his performance. Hoopes has some fine moments.
Hedwall has some powerful scenes; she could be Dukakis' daughter.
It would help if she could take her foot off the gas.
</P>
<P>
   Nora keeps a snapshot of Tom, and it's a photo of Scheider from
his role in ``Sorcerer,'' William Friedkin's remake of ``The Wages
of Fear.'' It was chosen because Tom wears a stingy-brimmed hat
similar to the chapeau Scheider wore in ``Sorcerer.'' One wonders
if, after seeing ``Better Living,'' he fondly looks back on the
days when he was in a movie about transporting nitroglycerine over
the rugged back roads of South America in a truck without shock
absorbers. The circumstances must have been much less volatile.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BETTER LIVING'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Max Mayer; director of photography, Kurt
Lennig; edited by Steve Silkenson; production designer, Mark
Ricker; produced by Ron Kastner and Lemore Syvan; released by
Goldheart Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Olympia Dukakis (Nora), Roy Scheider (Tom), Edward
Herrmann (Jack), Deborah Hedwall (Elizabeth), Catherine Corpeny
(Maryann), Wendy Hoopes (Gail) and James Villemaire (Junior).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 95 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
