<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLPARKS-FOOD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE NEW FOOD AND DRINK ITEMS, BASEBALL FANS STICKING TO
TRADITIONAL FARE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By SEAN WOOD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ When Tim Donegan looks at The Ballpark in
Arlington, he sees an imaginary yellow line encircling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people cross that yellow line their eating habits change
to stuff they don't normally eat,'' said Donegan, manager of The
Ballpark's food service company, Sportservice. ``I've seen it in
Cincinnati. I've seen it in St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoughts of salads, roast pork and bottled water are often
replaced by cravings for nachos, hot dogs and beer. And while you
can get all of the above items at The Ballpark, it is the last
three that drive sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how expansive our menu is, 80-85 percent of fans
still want the traditional ballpark fare of hot dogs, popcorn,
peanuts, beer and soda,'' said Karen Liberatori, public relations
manager for Sportservice's parent, the Delaware North Cos. ``That
holds true whether you're talking traditional concessions or
upscale dining in our suites and clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   You can get grilled scallops, rack of lamb, roast tenderloin and
antipasto salad. And Sportservice continues to tweak its
fine-dining menu and introduce four or five new concession items
each year ``to keep the place fresh and to drive revenue,'' Donegan
said.
</P>
<P>
   But for most sports fans, dining at a ballpark is a matter of
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could design the greatest food concept at the ballpark but
it may not be what the customers want,'' Donegan said. ``Coming to
the ballpark and eating a hot dog never goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the core group of foods still provides most of the
refreshment revenue at ballgames, food service companies continue
to try new items in an effort to offer a little more variety and
perhaps pump up sales a bit.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the new menu items catch on, they can boost the bottom
line for both the food service and the ballpark. Forty-three
percent of the sports and event venues nationwide are reporting
higher spending by fans this year than last, in part because of a
wider variety of menu items, according to a spring report by
Amusement Business, an industry trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Neither The Ballpark in Arlington nor Sportservice will disclose
how much money food and drinks bring in at The Ballpark, or how the
profits are divided. But with fans spending at least $7 per person
on refreshments at each game, it can easily run into the millions
during a season.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Sportservice pays close attention to what fans
like, and dislike.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as The Ballpark in Arlington, they don't have many of
the lighter selections,'' Liberatori said. ``They just don't sell.
They had frozen yogurt. But nobody wants frozen yogurt. They want
ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   One item that has taken off is the 20-ounce plastic bottle of
Miller Lite beer. Miller Brewing Co. and Donegan won't release
sales figures for the bottles, but Donegan said they were a ``boost
to vending.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It keeps the beer colder because it's a double-insulated
bottle wall,'' Donegan said. ``It's easier to handle. It fits real
nice into the cupholder. People still enjoy drnking beer out of the
original package. You just screw the top off. It saves transaction
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Donegan said it cuts at least 20 seconds off of the time it
takes a beer vendor to open a can and pour it into a paper cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Specifically focused on the venues, it's been a phenomenal
success for us,'' said Scott Bussen, spokesman for Miller in
Milwaukee. He said they have plastic bottles in more than 200
venues. ``Our production capacity for those bottles is not enough
to keep up with demand. We're looking for ways to increase our
capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans have been less enthusiastic about some of the other new
items introduced at The Ballpark this year. Tater tots have already
come and gone. While sausage on a stick is still holding on, a
version with jalapenos has been nixed. Funnel cakes, however, have
done relatively well, Donegan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always thought they would,'' he said. ``We've seen them do
well at places like Six Flags.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to finicky fans, there are a number of factors
beyond the control of the concessionaire that can affect sales.
</P>
<P>
   If a team does badly, attendance _ and food sales _ may drop
off. Or loyal season ticket holders who are accustomed to buying
their food at the park may give their tickets to friends or
employees who decide to bring their own food. Even the weather can
affect how much, and what, fans buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People eat more when it's cool,'' Donegan said. ``Hot weather
kills peoples' appetites. It's not good for much of anything except
for waters and frozen lemonade.'' Milder weather in the early part
of summer this year helped drive food and beer sales at The
Ballpark this year, for example, but soda sales were down 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The milder weather also meant that warm foods that Rangers fans
avoid in hotter weather saw increased sales through the end of
June. Jumbo dog sales were up 7 percent, kosher dogs were up 13.6
percent, barbecue chicken sandwiches were up 16.1 percent, cheese
fries were up 26 percent and super nachos were up 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
