r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-03 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLLING GOOD TIMES PRESENT A PROBLEM FOR BUSH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CECIL JOHNSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The urban sprawl of the Cityview section of Fort Worth casts a
specter over this week's whoop-dee-doo in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Inch by inch, acre by acre, mile by concreted and asphalted
mile, the proliferating growth in Fort Worth and other cities
gobbles up the rolling terrain. The profusion of new homes,
apartment complexes, shopping centers, hospitals, schools and
big-footprint superstores has taken on the aspect of a whole new
city swelling within a city.
</P>
<P>
   And that spells trouble for the elephantine celebrators in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   This Cityview phenomenon would not be a problem for the folks
who have convened in Ben Franklin's town to try to catapult Texas
Gov. George W. Bush into the White House if it were unique. Trouble
is, Cityview is far from singular. North Central Texas is studded
with such pockets of rampant growth. So are other parts of the
state and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Half a century ago, a musician named Louis Jordan popularized a
song called ``Let the Good Times Roll.'' That's the kind of
economic music that this nation is making today. And America's
Cityviews are reflections of the strong, vibrant, pulsating
economy.
</P>
<P>
   To most Americans, that's just a little short of wonderful. But
it makes it hard for Bush to argue that the nation would be better
off with him as president than with his opponent, Vice President Al
Gore, who is part of the current administration.
</P>
<P>
   How does one argue against letting the good times roll? If Bush
suggests that his economic policies will be significantly different
from those of the Clinton administration, he risks scaring away
voters who are now enjoying the fruits of one of the most
prosperous periods in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   These rolling good times in which most Americans are immersed
explain in large measure why the public is paying so little
attention to the presidential election campaign, why the Republican
convention is attracting such unimpressive numbers of television
viewers, and why the poll numbers at this stage of the campaign are
nearly irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps something will be said in the waning hours of the
convention that will really grab the public's attention. It is a
pity that Gen. Colin Powell spoke so early in the convention, when
hardly anyone was watching and listening. He delivered the best
oration at a Republican convention since Ronald Reagan waxed
eloquent.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's speech, however, was not the kind of oratory that most
of the delegates came to hear. And the applause for him was
underwhelming. Except for his obligatory lauding of Bush near the
end of his speech, Powell's remarks seemed more suited for a
Democratic convention. Perhaps that was why he was scheduled so
early.
</P>
<P>
   Powell did nothing to help solve Bush's Cityview problem. The
sloganizing about not leaving any children behind when Texas has
one of the highest rates of child poverty in the nation didn't do
it. Nor did the misleading assertions about all that voucher
advocate Bush has done for education in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming increasingly clear that the Republicans, instead
of focusing on matters economic, are going to try to run against
President Clinton and damage Gore with guilt by association.
</P>
<P>
   When the good times are rolling, that won't work. Americans for
the most part always have and always will vote their pocketbooks.
And because of that, Clinton _ despite the rantings of the
moralistic ideologues and professional Clinton-haters _ would
probably be re-elected to a third term were he constitutionally
eligible for it.
</P>
<P>
   To overcome the Cityview factor, Bush will have to convince the
American public that he will do nothing fiscally or monetarily to
stop the good times from rolling. But that could be difficult to do
without making the same promises as his opponent. If he says
something different, he could scare off voters.
</P>
<P>
   As November approaches and the voters begin to pay more
attention to the election, they are likely to become wary of
electing a Republican president because they will recall the
history of economic downturns during Republican administrations.
Thoughts of what a Republican administration in league with a
Republican-controlled Congress could do to the economy just might
scare the bejeebers out of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   The good times are rolling. The Cityviews are blooming. Bush
must convince America that he will do nothing to change that, or
the party affiliation of the man in the White House won't change.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a retired columnist and editorial writer for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
