r e BC-MOVIES-SHOWER04-COX     08-03 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SHOWER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Go with the gentle flow of charming `Shower'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knowing where it's going doesn't really spoil the charm of
``Shower,'' a gentle Chinese comedy about the restorative power of
water, tradition and family ties. Despite its title, the movie is
mainly about baths, mainly those in the small-town bathhouse run by
old Master Liu (Zhu Xu). It's the heart of the community, where the
men gather to soak and gossip and wager over cricket fights.
</P>
<P>
   Quick and efficient showers, by contrast, represent the quick
and soulless city life personified by Liu's oldest son, Da Ming (Pu
Cun Xin). He returns home after getting a cryptic postcard from his
mentally retarded brother, Er Ming (Jiang Wu), who lives with their
father and helps run the family business.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Danish film ``Mifune,'' with which it shares several
narrative similarities (including the character of a mentally
challenged brother), ``Shower'' takes the figure of the prodigal
son and turns him into a profit-minded one. You'll guess pretty
quickly that the laid-back pace of village life and the desire to
mend his relationship with his aloof dad will keep Da Ming in town
longer than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Like a variant of Fellini's ``Amarcord,'' the movie introduces
us to regulars at the baths, with their problems and quirks. One
young man sings ``O Sole Mio'' as he bathes, but chokes up in
public without the inspiration of a showerhead. Another admits he's
grown impotent, shamed by the lengths his wife went to in
retrieving a gift from him that a thief snatched from her. (Master
Liu brews up a peacemaking bath for the couple, adding a very
specific ingredient to the water.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie also digresses several times, telling the story of
dwellers in dusty northern climes, where water is so scarce it's an
expensive commodity. These scenic interludes lend ``Shower'' an
extra, fablelike shimmer. As refreshing and as fleeting as an
afternoon thunderstorm, the movie makes for a genially conservative
summer treat. Writer-director Zhang Yang handles his tale with a
delicacy that makes you overlook its slightness.
</P>
<P>
   It's only after you leave the theater that you realize somebody
in the community would probably love to swipe Da Ming's return
train ticket to the big city and get the hell out of there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shower''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Zhu Xu and Pu Cun Xin. Rated PG-13 for profanity and
nudity. In Mandarin with subtitles. 1 hour, 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Simple and refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
