 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, Aug. 4. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta) _ Sick, bewildered and besieged at
his home by angry protesters, former President Suharto was formally
charged Thursday with corruption during his 32 years of unchecked
power in Indonesia. The charge involves only a small portion of the
widespread corruption that characterized his rule, but it sends a
significant signal of Indonesia's attempts to overhaul its economy
and political system and lay the basis for the rule of law. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-SHIP (Ottawa) _ Canadian troops stormed on board the
U.S.-owned cargo ship GTS Katie Thursday after a high-seas standoff
in which hundreds of millions of dollars of Canadian military
equipment had effectively been held hostage. The Katie was the
focus of a bitter commercial tug-of-war between its owner and the
firm that chartered the vessel to transport the equipment. The
squabble drew in the Canadian government, which grew increasingly
impatient to get its cargo of 590 tanks and other military vehicles
back from Kosovo _ abot one-tenth of the army's hardware. (Summary
from wires) By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-RDP-NYT (Philadelphia) _ A convention roundup: Republicans
open the final day of their national convention, preparing to make
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas their presidential nominee and
relishing the fight that he has already started with Vice President
Al Gore. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUSH-SPEECH-NYT _ On the speech Gov. George W. Bush is
scheduled to deliver Thursday evening. The speech, which has been
ready for two months, and how it was prepared offer a window into
the discipline and strategy of the candidate and his campaign. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ASSESS-NYT _ A news analysis on what the GOP has
accomplished and what lies ahead for the party _ and for the
Democrats. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ECON-ASSESS-NYT _ The Bush campaign portrays his economic
agenda as all about helping single mothers and small business
owners. Just as Clinton worked to give Democrats a claim to fiscal
responsibility, Bush is working to give conservatism a claim to
solving social problems, but Bush is also seeking to avoid drawing
attention to the fact that his tax plan would largely benefit the
wealthy. And to the degree he engages Gore on economic issues, he
is moving onto tricky turf, given the widespread prosperity. By
Richard W. Stevenson. (900 words)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
