<HEADER>
A1851 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-GIRL04-COX     08-03 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GIRL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From unhappy housewife to porn star
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Stacy Baker switched her last name to Valentine, it was the
start of major changes. The Oklahoma housewife moved to Los
Angeles, found a porn-flick manager and ditched her controlling
husband _ the husband who first persuaded her to have breast
implants and encouraged her to pose for a nudie magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In Christine Fugate's documentary ``The Girl Next Door,''
Valentine is an engagingly slippery subject. She's part feminist
self-actualizer, part pawn of sexual stereotypes, undergoing a
series of plastic surgeries that transform her into a live-action,
hard-core Barbie doll. (Some of the procedures, including
liposuction, are shown onscreen; anyone buying a ticket out of
titillation also needs a strong stomach.)
</P>
<P>
   Sweet-faced and driven, Valentine admits that going into the
adult film industry was a choice she made from among meager
options. Raised to be a housewife by her supportive mother, she
found herself in a loveless marriage, aware of only one real
talent: ``I know I'm good at sex,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She proves this in scenes that show her professionalism in the
casually insane world of pornography. When ants interrupt an act of
alfresco coitus, she sensibly grabs a broom and sweeps the suckers
away. And in one all-night shoot, she endures 38-degree weather and
some special-effects smoke that irritates her lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Work becomes her life. She lives alone; she doesn't date. ``If I
need affection, I have my cat,'' she says. Things change when she
meets the one-named porn actor Julian, ``on the set.'' The
documentary becomes an interesting look at the ways a couple who
spend the day having sex with other people can manage (or fail) to
maintain love and trust at home.
</P>
<P>
   Though a whiff of doom hangs over the relationship, you find
yourself rooting for these two to find some normalcy in their
topsy-turvy world. But Julian admits he's in love with Stacy Baker,
whereas Stacy Valentine, her celebrity-seeking alter ego,
continually gets in the way.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to Cannes, France, for a porn film festival,
Valentine crosses the line into prostitution, and the choice
creates a sadness that the movie never shakes. Admitting that she
faked pleasure during the liaison, she chirps, ``So I guess I can
act.'' But she can't cover the unease in her smile.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Annabel Chong, subject of the documentary ``Sex: The
Annabel Chong Story'' (screened last week at Cinefest), Valentine
comes off as a relatively stable person, loved by her mother and
stepfather and not driven by childhood demons. In the end, ``Girl
Next Door'' is like a dual biography, showing us the ways some
people develop a second personality to get ahead. In this way, it
becomes a microcosm of Los Angeles, a city where looks count for
everything and where everyone, to some degree, puts out for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Girl Next Door''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Stacy Valentine. Unrated, but contains nudity and
hard-core sex acts. $3, $5 after 6 p.m. Through Thursday at
Cinefest (Georgia State University). 404-651-2463.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An interesting, evenhanded look at a woman trying
to make her mark in porn.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
