<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MAMBO04-COX     08-03 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MAMBO04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Main draw of `Mambo' is Russell's auburn mane
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing ``Mad About Mambo'' is truly mad about is Keri
Russell who, judging from her cascading curls and second billing,
must've filmed this uneven Irish charmer before becoming the WB's
``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in Belfast (meaning the Troubles provide an intriguing,
ever-present backdrop), the picture focuses on a soccer-mad lad
named Danny (William Ash) who dreams of playing for United,
Belfast's pro team. He faces two problems. First, he's Catholic
and, with the exception of an imported Brazilian superstar, United
is overwhelmingly Protestant. Second, Danny doesn't always have the
talent to match his passion. As his coach advises, ``Unless you do
something drastic to improve your game, you won't make it on any
team.''
</P>
<P>
   So Danny does something drastic. Inspired by his Brazilian
hero's remarks that ``when we play football, we don't run with the
ball, we dance,'' Danny signs up for Latin dance lessons. That's
where he falls for Lucy (Russell), who's rich, spoiled and
Protestant. The only thing going for him is her boisterous dad (a
movie-stealing Brian Cox), who loves his self-involved daughter
almost as much as he likes shaking her up.
</P>
<P>
   As a comedy, the movie has its moments _ especially the scenes
with Danny and his irrepressible pals. But as a romance, well, the
stars have almost zero chemistry. Filmmaker John Forte apparently
was so distracted by Russell's luxurious auburn mane and long legs
(she does a mean samba) that he failed to realize that Lucy comes
off as more than a bit of a pill. The notion that she's someone who
needs to be taken down a peg is fine, but the more we see of her,
the less we like her. It's the sort of movie where boy meets girl
and we don't really care if boy gets girl.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because there are a lot of delightful little touches.
For instance, Danny's older brother speaks only Irish and dismisses
soccer as ``a British imperialist sport.'' On the other side,
there's the well-off Protestant matron who, when told Danny is
getting home by bus, smiles politely, ``Ah, we still have buses. I
thought your people had burnt them all.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is, Russell is probably the only reason ``Mad About
Mambo'' is getting a stateside release, yet she's the weakest thing
in the film. It's a star vehicle with an as-yet-unformed star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad About Mambo''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring William Ash and Keri Russell. Directed by John Forte.
Rated PG-13 for profanity. 1 hour, 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Can't really dance to it.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
