<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV06-C     08-03 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HERE'S A COUPLE OF POLITICAL SECRETS
 &HT;    Moving in the (k) commentary and (p) political categories for
release Sunday, Aug. 6.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The 15,000 journalists who came to the Republican
National Convention endured threatening thunderclouds amid a
drought of political news. Caught in what one headline writer
dubbed ``the Bushworld archipelago,'' reporters were reduced to
guessing how much of a post-convention ``bounce'' the Texas
governor would get in the national polls.
</P>
<P>
   While there will be no lack of polls in the next three months,
they really don't reveal too much. That's due to a little secret of
U.S. presidential politics: There won't be a national election
either.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution mandates 51 stand-alone contests in each state
and the District of Columbia. Save for Maine and Nebraska, it's
winner take all.
</P>
<P>
   That means political strategists for George W. Bush and Al Gore
are planning how best to allocate money and candidate time to
attain the 270 electoral votes needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's political master builder, thinks in such
terms. He focuses on the battleground states in what he views as
likely the closest presidential race in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Within each pivotal mini-race, both sides target swing voters.
For the Bush camp, as Rove sees it, they are suburbanites,
especially those who live in older, close-in suburbs; Catholics,
and non-Cuban Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   While every survey taken during the GOP convention showed Bush
running ahead of Gore, Rove expects the race to tighten in the
fall, when Bush meets Gore in what will likely be two televised
90-minute debates.
</P>
<P>
   To see why Rove's views may be on the mark, take a look at the
1988 electoral map, when George Bush the Elder won the presidency
with 426 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Give his son West Virginia, which the Democrats won in 1988 but
where Bush the Younger now runs well ahead. Then take away from him
Bill Clinton's Arkansas and Al Gore's Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, subtract eight more states that the elder Bush captured
but that his son could plausibly lose to Gore in a tight election:
California, New Mexico, Missouri, Ohio, Maryland, Pennsylvania, New
Jersey and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The result: the rivals would wind in up in a dead heat of 269
votes each, thereby throwing the contest into the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Such speculation leads to the second little secret of U.S.
presidential politics: A winner's capacity to govern effectively
depends largely on his ability during the campaign to muster a
working majority for his policies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to build up his overall vote count in 1966, Clinton
stiffed bread-and-butter Democratic spear carriers. In time, he
paid price that included a Senate impeachment trial that halted
work on what mattered to him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who makes a political point out of his having worked well
with a Democrat-run legislature in Texas, now runs a similar risk.
He ought to know that the scene in Austin, where the lawmakers meet
only every other year for 140 days, is quite different than what he
would find in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to prevail, Bush seems to feel that he must run apart
from congressional Republicans. In the end, he too may pay a price.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
