<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOLLOW-FILM-REVIEW-NY     08-03 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOW-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLLOW MAN': OH WHERE, OH WHERE HAS OUR SCIENTIST GONE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The beginning of ``Hollow Man'' is witty enough. An innocent rat
skitters along the floor of an apparently empty steel cage toward a
dish of water, only to be snatched up and devoured by an unseen
predator, whose voracious maw is outlined in the hapless rodent's
blood while the rest remains invisible. Cut to Kevin Bacon in his
apartment, burning the midnight oil in front of his computer. He
stops to do to a Hostess Twinkie what the spectral animal (who
turns out to be a gorilla named Isabelle) has just done to the rat,
and then his computer screen, which has been performing some kind
of 3-D molecular modeling, flashes a dire warning: ``STATUS:
UNSTABLE.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes indeed. In short order we discover that Bacon's character _
a scientist named Sebastian Caine, head of a top-secret,
Pentagon-financed research project _ is a peeping tom, a
self-pitying egomaniac and a very difficult co-worker. How
Hollywood mad scientists have changed since the days of white lab
coats and heavy black-rimmed glasses! Sebastian drives a sleek
silver Porsche and wears a half-length black leather coat that
would make Shaft jealous. Your tax dollars at work, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Caine and his team _ which includes his ex-girlfriend Linda
(Elisabeth Shue) and her current beau (Josh Brolin), as well as a
movie-diverse assortment of specialists _ are at the cutting edge
of a burgeoning new science making stuff invisible, or, more
precisely, is causing living creatures to ``phase shift out of
quantum sync with the visible universe.'' This involves injecting
the subjects with a bright blue serum, which first induces seizures
and then the gradual disappearance of their bodies, one layer at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   We first see the process in reverse with Isabelle, whose bones,
organs, and muscles slowly come into view as she writhes on a
gurney. Before long, in response to pressure from the doddering
generals who control his financing, the impatient Sebastian decides
to become the first human to undergo the process.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, well-known for his willingness to appear nude in films,
strips down, quite literally, to nothing. Luckily the lab is
well-stocked with infrared goggles, allowing the still-visible
scientists to keep track of their elusive boss. Later on they whip
up some latex to help him look almost human, or at least like a
half-melted Kevin Bacon Halloween mask.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of work has clearly gone into the special effects in
``Hollow Man,'' which uses the latest computer-generated imagery to
update the cinematic obsession with invisibility that dates at
least to James Whale's ``Invisible Man'' in 1933. (It also uses
some tried and true film techniques, including that scary movie
staple, the bad guy's point-of-view shot). Actually, according to
the production notes, ``Hollow Man'' belongs to an even older
tradition, since ``the theme of invisibility is familiar in
premodern narrative,'' figuring prominently, for example, in the
second book of Plato's ``Republic.'' And that's not all: ``From
`The Tragical History of Doctor Faustus' to H.G. Wells' `The
Invisible Man,''' the notes elaborate, ``the idea of invisibility
has been a source of wonder and curiosity, and will doubtless
remain so until the day it becomes a reality.'' Doubtless.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking for wonder, or even passable
entertainment, you'd do better to curl up with Plato _ or with the
latest work of literary scholarship from Columbia's publicity
department _ than to endure the long, slow, unraveling of this
movie, which can't even muster the intelligence to be pretentious
or the bravado to be amusingly bad. This is a shame, since the
director, Paul Verhoeven, can usually be counted on for lurid
thrills or for splashy special-effects sublimity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollow Man'' has neither the ripe atmospherics of ``Basic
Instinct'' or ``The Fourth Man'' (the kinky Dutch sex thriller that
earned Verhoeven a ticket to Hollywood) nor the full-throttle
excitement of ``Total Recall'' or the first ``Robocop.'' It even
lacks the howling shamelessness that has turned ``Showgirls'' into
a cult favorite among connoisseurs of guilty video pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Verhoeven and the screenwriter, Andrew Marlowe, have taken what
could have been a fascinating, creepy psychological thriller and
turned it into a labored, implausible piece of action-movie hack
work. Once nobody can see him _ and once he no longer has to look
at himself in the mirror _ Sebastian becomes intoxicated with the
power and freedom that his new state confers. The best part of the
movie tracks his rapid slides from petulant narcissism into
demented evil.
</P>
<P>
   He sneaks up on the high-strung veterinarian (Kim Dickens) and
unbuttons her top while she sleeps and then quickly and with a
minimum of soul-searching descends from hide-and-seek pranks to
raping his neighbor, spying on Linda and taking out his
frustrations on a helpless invisible dog.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of exploring the underside of Sebastian's
personality, or the tantalizing liberty that invisibility might
offer, ``Hollow Man'' quickly becomes a pallid retread of ``The
Terminator'' crossed with a half-dozen second-rate horror movies,
as his fellow scientists pursue Sebastian through their mazelike
underground compound and he dispatches them in the most predictable
order possible.
</P>
<P>
   Fire extinguishers, bags of human blood and a sprinkler system
provide occasions for some show-offy effects as Bacon's unclothed
frame is outlined by computer-enhanced mist and moisture. At the
very end, for reasons doubtless having to do with the finer points
of quantum synchronization, Bacon takes on the appearance of a very
angry anatomical model, all veins and muscles and popping eyeballs,
that has escaped from a medical school classroom to take revenge on
humanity _ or to steal one last kiss from his old flame. Some
things are better left unseen.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HOLLOW MAN'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Paul Verhoeven; written by Andrew Marlowe, based on
a story by Gary Scott Thompson and Marlowe; director of
photography, Jost Vacano; edited by Mark Goldblatt; music by Jerry
Goldsmith; production designer, Allan Cameron; produced by Douglas
Wick and Alan Marshall; released by Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Elisabeth Shue (Linda McKay), Kevin Bacon (Sebastian
Caine), Josh Brolin (Matthew Kensington), Kim Dickens (Sarah
Kennedy), Greg Grunberg (Carter Abbey), Joey Slotnick (Frank
Chase), Mary Randle (Janice Walton) and William Devane (Dr.
Kramer).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 114 minutes. This film is rated R. (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes nudity
__ some of it visible with the aid of infrared lenses _ graphic
violence, and cruelty to invisible animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
