u e BC-GRACE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-03 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRACE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SAVING GRACE': EVERYBODY, APPARENTLY, MUST GET STONED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rulers of Britain may have embarked on an aggressive
campaign of modernization _ what with the Millennium Dome, the
transformation of the House of Lords and all that throbbing techno
music _ but a segment of the entertainment industry remains
stubbornly wedded to ancient notions of the British character. The
once-mighty empire remains, if recent movies are to be believed, a
nation of absent-minded vicars, codgers and goosey, tea-swilling
ladies who populate cozy crofts and seaside villages and
manufacture eccentricity for the export market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Grace,'' which tries to do for marijuana-dealing what
``The Full Monty'' did for male striptease, is this summer's bait
for the Anglophiles who keep shows like `` Bean'' and ``Keeping Up
Appearances'' running on public television. Though it might be
described as a BBC sitcom as imagined by Cheech and Chong, ``Saving
Grace,'' directed by Nigel Cole, springs from the imagination of
Craig Ferguson. Ferguson wrote the screenplay with Mark Crowdy and
helped to produce the picture, in which he also stars.
</P>
<P>
   A regular on ``The Drew Carey Show'' on ABC and the writer and
star of a recent big-screen hair-care comedy called ``The Big
Tease,'' Ferguson is a leading contender for the title of World's
Most Amusing Scot. Here he is fairly subdued in the role of
Matthew, a transplanted Glaswegian working as a gardener in a
picturesque town in Cornwall and enjoying, in addition to the
traditional pint at the pub, a friendly toke or two with his pals,
including the local doctor, played by the very amusing Martin
Clunes.
</P>
<P>
   But then Matthew's employer, a local widow named Grace (Brenda
Blethyn), encounters some serious money trouble, owing to the
financial irresponsibility of her late husband, who has jumped from
a plane, leaving her with a mountain of debt. Grace must raise
$450,000 or lose her picturesque stone house, and so she and
Matthew decide to clear the orchids from her greenhouse, install a
bunch of hydroponic lights and set about growing some high-quality
hemp.
</P>
<P>
   Mild complications bump the plot along. Some are farcical _ as
when Grace goes to find a dealer in London, decked in an outfit
inspired by either Barbara Cartland or ``American Pimp''_ and some
more serious, like the fact that Matthew's girlfriend, a local
fisherwoman (Valerie Edmond), is pregnant. The movie has a gentle,
silly vibe, and it would peter out in triviality if not for
Blethyn's gift for finding the pain and frustration behind Grace's
facade of housewifely capability.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, all the jokes exploit the same tired premise, which
is the spectacle of variously dotty and stuffy Englishmen and women
getting stoned, wittingly and not. A long set piece involving the
two biddies who run the town convenience store, and who brew up a
pot of tea from the plants they find in Grace's greenhouse, sets
the tone. They giggle uncontrollably and then come down with the
munchies, just like everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   That they're English and elderly apparently makes their antics
screamingly funny to people who would turn up their noses at
similar humor in a film like ``Scary Movie.'' But dopiness, as it
were, transcends culture and nationality, though it is a bit
annoying when it masquerades as good taste and sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SAVING GRACE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Nigel Cole; written by Craig Ferguson and Mark
Crowdy, based on a story by Crowdy; director of photography, John
de Borman; edited by Alan Strachan; music by Mark Russell;
production designer, Eve Stewart; produced by Crowdy; released by
Fine Line Features.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Brenda Blethyn (Grace), Craig Ferguson (Matthew), Martin
Clunes (Dr. Bamford), Tcheky Karyo (Jacques), Jamie Foreman
(China), Bill Bailey (Vince), Valerie Edmond (Nicky), Tristan
Sturrock (Harvey), Clive Merrison (Quentin) and Leslie Phillips
(Vicar).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes. ``Saving Grace'' is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes some
good-humored Anglo-Saxon profanity and a great deal of enthusiastic
drug use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
