<SLUG> BC-BLOOD-DIRECTORS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some trivia behind the Coen brothers' first movie
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  The movie has been trimmed by about eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A prologue has been added in which a pipe-smoking film
preservationist praises the ``digital enhancement,'' the ``ultra
ultra sound'' and adds that ``the boring parts have been taken
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Blood Simple,''' he sighs philosophically. ``Forever young.
Forever young.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frances McDormand, who later won a best actress Oscar for her
pregnant cop in ``Fargo,'' made her film debut in ``Blood Simple.''
However, her first professional acting job was here at the Alliance
Theatre, as Viola in Kent Stephens' production of ``Twelfth
Night.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Helping the Coens in their ``luridly playful'' camerawork was
cinematographer Barry Sonnenfeld, who went on to direct ``Men in
Black'' and ``Get Shorty.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The voice heard on one of the characters' answering machine
belongs to Holly Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In their news conference at the New York Film Festival in the
fall of 1984, the brothers explained they had shot the movie in
Texas because one of them (Joel) had ``lived there for awhile and
knew the area. I knew we could make a low-budget feature there. And
the weather was good.'' Brother Ethan's eerily un-prescient
addition was, ``Texas is a more exotic place for murder than
Minneapolis, which is where we come from.'' Um, you betcha.
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
