<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TVWEEKEND04-COX     08-03 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVWEEKEND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weekend TV lineup
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceToday
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``100 Greatest Rock 'n' Roll Moments on TV'' (6-11 p.m. on
VH1; replays from midnight-4 a.m.) _ VH1 counts 'em down again,
with the final new episode airing at 10 p.m. (280758) And still
they don't include Steve Martin doing ``King Tut'' on ``Saturday
Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Denis Leary: No Cure for Cancer'' (10 p.m. on Comedy
Central, 934452) _ Leary's blistering one-hour stand-up routine of
several years back stands as one of the comedy highlights of the
'90s. Comedy Central will have to bleep it heavily, but Leary has
never been as brutally hilarious as he was in this show.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Quarantine'' (8 p.m. on ABC, 2899) _ In this new disaster
flick about a lethal virus that threatens the world, Harry Hamlin
is the president of the United States, and Nastassja Kinksi is a
research scientist. Hey, it could happen!
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dave Chappelle: Killin' Them Softly'' (11 p.m. on HBO,
401327) _ Film audiences know Chappelle for roles in ``The Nutty
Professor'' (the Eddie Murphy version) and ``Blue Streak,'' but
he's mainly a sharp stand-up guy. In this new special, rated TV-MA
(mature audiences, for language), he takes on racial stereotypes as
well as police encounters with blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Frontline: From Jesus to Christ: The First Christians''
(12:30 p.m. on WGTV, 414544) _ WGTV reruns this four-hour
``Frontline'' special from 1998. It's a fairly rigorous analysis of
what historians think they can know with certainty about the life
of Christ, followed by a chronicle of the rise of the early
Christian church. Matters of faith (such as the virgin birth and
the resurrection) are dealt with barely or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Influences'' (7:30 p.m. on Bravo, 933761) _ A new half-hour
series lets stars talk about who inspired them. In Sunday's
premiere, Tracey Ullman pays tribute to Lily Tomlin's ``Laugh-In''
days while Ted Danson singles out John Cleese of ``Monty Python's
Flying Circus.'' Alan Alda hosts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``One Kill'' (8 p.m. on Showtime, 930693) _ Anne Heche (right)
stars as the defendant in this new courtroom drama, on trial for
the murder of her lover and commanding officer (Sam Shepard).
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The 10th Kingdom'' (Part 1 of 4 at 8 tonight on NBC, 51433 )
</P>
<P>
   If you missed this magical miniseries back in February when
there was so much sweeps competition, do yourself a favor and give
it a try in its first rerun.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Simon Moore (``Gulliver's Travels'') re-imagines every
fairy tale you ever heard (and some you haven't) into a deliriously
wacky Freudian jumble that's both contemporary and timeless. A New
York waitress (Kimberly Williams) and her oafish dad (John
Larroquette) travel through a magic mirror into an enchanted land
where revisionist versions of legendary characters abound (Snow
White, Cinderella, Red Riding Hood, the archetypal Evil Queen). But
there are many fresh twists (magic mushrooms singing Procol Harum's
``Whiter Shade of Pale,'' a voracious but tender-hearted wolf/man
like nothing you've ever seen, beer bottles multiplying in a fridge
like the brooms in ``The Sorcerer's Apprentice'').
</P>
<P>
   Eight hours long, ``10th Kingdom'' can leave you exhausted,
exhilarated or both and can be too much of a good thing. But that's
rarely a problem with TV, particularly in the summer. Continues at
8 p.m. Saturday (23037), 7 p.m. Sunday (29761) and 8 p.m. Monday
(50945).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
