<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOON-COUPLE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET THE REIGNING POWER COUPLE OF THE BALLOON SET
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, AUGUST 3, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With two photos, of Kelli Sipp (NNS4) and the set-up
for the GOP's balloon drop (NNS5) 
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Pulling the strings at the Republican and
Democratic balloon drops is the reigning power couple of decorative
balloon art.
</P>
<P>
   In the GOP's corner is Treb Heining, owner of Balloonart by Treb
in Newport Beach, Calif., who was set to loose up to 200,000
balloons Thursday night in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A living balloon legend, he created the world's first balloon
arch and performed massive balloon drops, or releases, for the
opening ceremony of the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles,
numerous Super Bowls, presidential inaugurations and Oscar shows.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, also dropping nearly 200,000 balloons in Los
Angeles on Aug. 17, is Heining's girlfriend, Kelli Sipp, owner of
Kelli's Balloon Studio in La Verne, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Sipp was the 1999 International Designer of the Year, besting
more than 1,150 balloon artists from 39 countries at the 15th
annual International Balloon Arts Competition. She's the only
designer to simultaneously hold first place in large sculpture,
table centerpiece and buffet arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The two met four years ago at -- where else? -- a balloon
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Just as opposing politicos Mary Matalin and James Carville
didn't discuss work during the 1996 presidential campaign, Sipp,
40, and Heining, 46, aren't swapping any information.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept his drop a total secret from me,'' Sipp said.
</P>
<P>
   They have worked together in the past, however, most notably on
the millennium celebration in New York's Times Square. As the
``airborne effects'' manager, Heining supervised a crew of more
than 100 that dropped tens of thousands of balloons and tons of
confetti at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Sipp said Heining's balloon drops have a distinct style. ``I was
watching him on CNN on the floor of the convention'' during
preparations in Philadelphia, she said. ``I could see his touches.
Unique.''
</P>
<P>
   What would those touches be? Sipp turned evasive. ``I shouldn't
speak too much for him,'' she said. ``There are lots of secrets
that go on in balloon drops.''
</P>
<P>
   Sipp did let slip one detail: She'll be using special
``signature balloons'' that delegates may have autographed.
</P>
<P>
   Heining's response: ``Oh, I wouldn't know anything about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by cell phone on the frantic eve of his balloon drop,
while finalizing preparations amid the chaos of the convention
center floor, he had little time to say more.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, each political party is just as hush-hush. The
balloon drop is the colorful climax of the convention, just after
the presidential hopeful has accepted the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Balloons are suspended in netting from catwalks. Workers pull
cords to send the balloons cascading down atop the delegates. The
spectacle usually lasts up to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that all-important moment, signaling the end of the
convention and beginning of the official campaign, is known among
pundits as ``when the balloons drop.''
</P>
<P>
   So both Republicans and Democrats fret about being outdone,
particularly in the number of balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were suffocating in balloons,'' New York Rep. Carolyn
Maloney told a reporter after the '96 Democratic convention in
Chicago. ``They were up to your nostrils.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few scant details that each party did reveal
regarding convention balloons:
</P>
<P>
   -- About 40 students from the music program at Penn High School
in Lansdale, Pa., inflated balloons for the GOP drop. The red,
white and blue balloons used were 9-inch, ''100 percent
biodegradable'' latex.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Democrats issued a statement that in Los Angeles,
``balloons and confetti released at the conclusion of the 2000
Democratic National Convention will be environmentally sound. ...
Latex or rubber balloons will be featured at the close of the
convention. They are 100 percent biodegradable.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hoopla comes cleanup. Sipp said that despite the huge
number of balloons, not many are left to haul away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of people like popping them, or they take balloons when
they leave,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is good for Sipp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day after my drop the cast of `The West Wing' TV show is
coming in and taping a scene,'' she said. ``So we have to have it
all cleaned up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
