<HEADER>
A1886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-REVIEW-FORD-SUV0804-C     08-03 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-FORD-SUV0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A sensible Escape
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite its rather fanciful name that continues Ford's
penchant for E-word monikers for its sport-utility vehicles (it
follows the Explorer, Expedition and Excursion), the Escape is a
perfectly sensible mini-SUV.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, between its positive attributes and consumer-friendly
base price of $18,160, the 2001 Escape may be the pick of a field
that includes the Chevrolet Tracker/Isuzu Vitara, Honda CR-V,
Nissan Xterra, Suburu Forester and Toyota RAV4.
</P>
<P>
   The test Escape did total $24,295, but it was the line-topping
XLT (base price: $20,820), and Ford loaded it with just about every
option offered except leather interior ($870). It had all the
comforts found in a comparably priced sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the ride, of course. But say this for the Escape: It
had a very acceptable ride. Given tires more in keeping with its
use on paved surfaces instead of the 15-inch Wilderness tires, the
ride would have been a lot smoother and certainly a lot quieter.
</P>
<P>
   The XLT's 200-horsepower V-6 engine is clearly preferable to the
only other available powerplant _ a 130-hp four-cylinder motor _
and the price paid for the 3 to 4 mpg lost is rather negligible
(the EPA figures are 20 and 24 mpg on regular unleaded). Gas prices
have fallen some, but the Escape's figures shame those of its
bigger siblings.
</P>
<P>
   The V-6 makes the Escape a speedy SUV, too _ Mazda credits its
version, the Tribute, with a zero-to-60 mph clocking of under 10
seconds, which is respectable by all but sports-car standards. The
test XLT had no trouble keeping up with traffic on expressways, and
it felt stable with little inclination to wander at those speeds.
Its power anti-lock brakes remained effective in jump-and-stop
traffic with little indication of fade.
</P>
<P>
   The Escape's four-wheel-drive system has a dash-mounted switch
for automatic selection or locking it in all-wheel drive, with the
latter being useful only when there's really bad weather or if _
perish the thought _ someone actually takes an Escape off-road and
finds the going really rough.
</P>
<P>
   In the areas of comfort and interior design, the Escape is
decidedly more carlike. Its five-passenger capacity isn't a
stretch, and there's good leg and head room up front and in the
rear. The 70/30-split rear seat folds flat, and the presence of an
upward-opening rear gate _ the window will open separately _ means
it's relatively easy to load and unload.
</P>
<P>
   Grab handles on the front A pillars assist entry (ground
clearance is 7.8 inches, so the Escape is not a lowrider) and the
optional side step bars ($275) are helpful getting in and out. They
also help the appearance, which, face it, is boxy, like that of
other SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   The white-on-black instrumentation is quite utilitarian _ a
120-mph speedometer, an 8,000-rpm tachometer (with no redline), and
fuel and temperature gauges. But the Escape has enough
idiot/warning lights _ a baker's dozen _ to blind its driver should
they all come on at once.
</P>
<P>
   Several drivers noted, as have other reviewers, that the chief
complaint with the interior and layout of the Escape is the
column-mounted shifter and the hard-to-use wiper controls. Drivers
tend to find the shifter awkward to operate, and it's long enough
to interfere with access to the ignition switch and stereo
controls.
</P>
<P>
   Cabin storage is good with a deep, lidded center console and
real-world drink holders up front and at the bottom rear of the
console. There are no door pockets, but the Escape has nets on the
rear of both front seats, and the cargo area gets a cover and four
tie-down hooks.
</P>
<P>
   From front to back, then, it seems Ford has pretty much nailed
the target with the Escape's accommodations and utility. Plus, it's
not so big or so thirsty that it's going to be much of a target for
the anti-SUV crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
