<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      08-03 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASKED MEN AND GRINCHES
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Rick Baker's makeup and animatronics studio is on a
scruffy commercial strip at the foot of the back side of the
Hollywood Hills, but inside it's all fantasy and artifice. A creepy
mock graveyard includes headstones for many of the creatures
created by Baker, a four-time Oscar winner, as well as some members
of his current staff. Upstairs, the entrance to his office is down
a tall, narrow corridor of Gothic arches, at the end of which
stands a huge, hooded wraith. In the office, another Gothic marvel
filled with antiques, skulls and other creepy artifacts, sits
Baker, wearing a T-shirt and denim pants, his salt-and-pepper pony
tail hanging over the back of a wood chair.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the movie business is moving deeper into the
virtual illusions of computer effects, Baker represents an older
school of actors in rubber suits, robotic creatures and layer upon
layer of face-altering makeup. ``I really don't think that
computers are going to do away with the makeup side of my
business,'' he said. ``But the animatronics? Maybe. I don't know. I
do kind of hate to see the rubber monster business disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Baker takes on only one project at a time. At the
moment, he is working on Tim Burton's remake of ``The Planet of the
Apes.'' Tim Roth, who will play one of the chief apes, was
downstairs for a makeup test, and on a nearby table were sculptures
of musclebound apes, looking a lot more ``Conan the Barbarian''
than the apes in the original 1968 Charlton Heston film.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, Baker said he had two offers he could not
refuse: to transform Eddie Murphy into a half-dozen characters for
``Nutty Professor 2: The Klumps,'' in theaters now, and to
transform Jim Carrey (and 90 other actors) for a big-screen version
of ``How the Grinch Stole Christmas'' to be released this
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like to do them one at a time, if I can,'' he said.
``I'm real hands-on. I don't like to spread myself too thin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutty Professor 2,'' a sequel to a remake, was a particular
pleasure, he said, because Murphy is so adept at bringing Baker's
creations to life. In the film, Murphy plays several members of the
Klump family, and the various characters had to be designed to look
as if they were related but still had their own distinctive
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all actors do, but Eddie kind of likes being hidden,''
Baker said. ``He liked being someone else. It's fun to watch. What
he does is he lets me do my thing, then he takes a look at the
result in the mirror and decides what kind of voice should come out
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also grueling was the process of applying makeup to so many
actors for ``Grinch.'' A kind of assembly line, more complicated
than anything he had attempted before, was set up on a Universal
Studios stage. But the skills he learned doing that are likely to
come in handy when he and his crew have to transform dozens of
actors into apes, especially since 20th Century Fox is eager for
the film to be ready for next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Baker said, he does not design for the camera; he
designs for his own eye. ``I make stuff that looks as good as it
can look,'' he said. ``No matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   REEFER MADNESS
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Blethyn's sense is that public attitudes toward marijuana
and other illegal drugs are just about the same in Britain, where
she lives, as in the United States. But she hopes that not too much
emphasis is placed on the dope-smoking aspects of ``Saving Grace,''
the new comedy in which she stars as a Cornish housewife persuaded
by her gardener to grow and sell pot as a means of saving her
impoverished estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I believe that it's ridiculous that tobacco and
alcohol are legal but marijuana is not,'' Blethyn said while
relaxing before an incongruously raging fire (it was a scorching
day outside) in the air-conditioned lobby of the Four Seasons Hotel
in Los Angeles. ``I don't condone drug use in any way, but perhaps
we ought to think about legalizing it. I mean, what we're doing now
doesn't seem to be working.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opens on Friday in New York and some other
cities, is the work of the first-time director Nigel Cole and was
one of the hits at the Sundance Film Festival in January. Blethyn
was drawn to it, she said, by the plight of her character, who
suddenly discovers that her husband has lied to her for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did like it,'' she said. ``The idea: to wake up one morning
and discover that 25 years of your life had been a fiction and to
suddenly be left destitute.''
</P>
<P>
   Blethyn is probably best known for her Oscar-nominated role in
Mike Leigh's ``Secrets and Lies.'' While she tends to do most of
her work in independent films, in Britain and America, she said she
had no aversion to working in a big studio film, if the part was
right.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, she is also awaiting the release of ``Sleeping
Dictionary,'' in which she plays a not altogether sympathetic role
as the wife of Bob Hoskins, marooned in the Sarawak jungles of
Borneo. Her memories of that shoot are vivid, if not altogether
pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fascinating, really,'' she said. ``We had a few snakes
turn up, and iguanas sauntering onto the set. I mean, 7-foot ones.
And there were bugs as big as tennis balls attacking you now and
then.''
</P>
<P>
   She did an imitation of what it was like to try to shoo away a
huge insect screeching toward her head. A few people in the lobby
paused, looked over with mystification and gradually moved on.
</P>
<P>
   JACK WARDEN'S GAME
</P>
<P>
   The voice on the phone was unmistakable, stretching back over
the years, from ``The Verdict'' in 1982, ``Shampoo'' in 1975, all
the way to ``From Here to Eternity'' in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, but this was the first time I ever got to work
with Gene Hackman,'' said Jack Warden, who plays a relatively small
role in ``The Replacements,'' a comedy about the National Football
League. ``We're friends, but I've never acted with him before. It's
an amazing thing, you know. I stand there, and I can't see him
acting. Some of these actors, you stand there and you can see them
acting, but with him, he's just there. He just is. What better
compliment can you pay an actor?''
</P>
<P>
   Hackman plays a football coach hired by the team's owner
(Warden) to recruit a squad of has-been players to take the place
of striking superstars. Keanu Reeves stars as the team's new
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it, I think, because of the subject,'' Warden said.
``I was a fairly good athlete when I was younger, so I was very
familiar with the game. I haven't seen the finished movie yet, just
some of the rushes. A friend of mine saw some clips, and he said it
looked very funny. What else is he going to say? I guess we'll find
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
