<HEADER>
A1892 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-OPERA-VENUS-HNS &LR;      08-03 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-VENUS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SANTA FE OPERA'S POWERFUL _ AND CONFUSING _ `VENUS' &HT;    (Photos available from
http://www.santafeopera.org/PressPhotos/PressPhotos.htm.)
 &HT;    By CHARLES WARD
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ When two striking dancers enter as a stallion
and mare, complete with stylized masks and hoof-shaped boots,
audiences at ``Venus and Adonis'' may forget momentarily the
ageless tale of love unfolding in Hans Werner Henze's latest opera.
</P>
<P>
   Yet beneath its layers of innovative form, ancient mythology _
and dramatic murk _ it's a simple story of jealousy and its tragic
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Based in part on a Shakespeare poem, ``Venus and Adonis'' is
receiving its American premiere at Santa Fe Opera. The ``opera in
one act for singers and dancers'' (Henze's description) is the
sixth work of his to be staged by the company. The first was ``King
Stag'' in 1965. However, among important 20th-century opera
composers, the German-born Henze is the least familiar to opera
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the strength of Henze's newest opera is bringing the
veiled wisdom of mythology to fresh life. His powerful music _
dissonant, colorful and propulsive _ contrasts with, and clarifies,
his dense storytelling, which isn't surprising for a work born in
post-World War II Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus'' presents an opera-within-an-opera, wherein three
modern-dress singers, who are rehearsing a work about Venus and
Adonis, act the myth out in ``real life.'' The Hero-Player (Mars)
discovers the Prima Donna (Venus) falling for the younger Clemente
(Adonis). The Hero-Player kills his rival in a lightning-fast act
of brutality.
</P>
<P>
   In a second opera-within-an-opera, a group of six madrigalists
and six dancers also tell the traditional story of Venus,
Adonis &UR;  &LR; and the jealous Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a third level of complication emerges in Alfred Kirchner's
staging. Much of the time the dance and operatic stories unfold
simultaneously; the dancers, through choreography by Ron Thornhill,
tell the same story being set out in song.
</P>
<P>
   Though theoretically fascinating, after a while the multiple
layers blur. The mind _ and eyes _ begin to swim while darting
between the tales unfolding onstage and the English translations of
the text shown on a tiny screen in front of each seat.
</P>
<P>
   The vocal cast comprises the three principals and the
madrigalists, shepherds in white commedia dell'arte dress. Six
dancers also portray Venus, Adonis and Mars, plus the stallion and
the mare _ and the boar that kills Adonis.
</P>
<P>
   In a further abandonment of traditional opera, Henze composed
the work in 17 movements of three types: Madrigal, Recitative, and
Bolero and Dance-Song.
</P>
<P>
   Henze's music is always powerful, and his orchestration
captivating. The choral writing for the madrigalists is
breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Some dramatic touches are memorable.
</P>
<P>
   The stallion and mare, appearing with no dramatic justification,
are stunning. When the stallion senses the mare, the dancers
intertwine with an eroticism soon matched by Adonis and Venus.
</P>
<P>
   The boar that kills Adonis bursts through a side wall of the
main set, a large, off-white room with industrial skylight and
exposed pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Performances are consistently strong. Among them: soprano Lauren
Flanigan as the Prima Donna, tenor Christopher Ventris as Clemente
and bass-baritone Stephen West as the Hero-Player. Dancers Sarita
Allen (Venus), Brock vonDrehle Labbenz (Adonis) and Peter Mantia
(Mars) acquit themselves well, as do conductor Richard Bradshaw and
the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, despite such committed work on all sides, the
potential of ``Venus and Adonis'' is not realized. Kirchner's
staging and John Conklin's set muddle rather than clarify. Above
all, the production needs visual spaciousness, where Henze's
fascinating story can unfold freely.
</P>
<P>
   XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
