   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Half a century ago, a musician named Louis Jordan
popularized a song called ``Let the Good Times Roll.'' That's the
kind of economic music that this nation is making today. To most
Americans, that's just a little short of wonderful. But it makes it
hard for George W. Bush to argue that the nation would be better
off with him as president than with his opponent, Vice President Al
Gore, who is part of the current administration. By CECIL JOHNSON.
Story has moved in ``k'' commentary category. &QL; 
