<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0804-COX     08-03 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: The most important, make-or-break,
moment-of-truth speech of his life
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush facing the biggest moment of his short political
career, vowed to speak ``from my heart'' when he accepts the
Republican presidential nomination tonight. He said his message
would be positive and uplifting. Bush did not plan to launch
personal attacks on President Clinton and Al Gore but would lament
the administration's ``failure to get anything done,'' aides said.
The tone, according to communications director Karen Hughes, would
be ``regretful rather than critical.'' Bush isn't known for his
oratorical skills and is sometimes prone to mangle even the
familiar phrases he has used over and over again, but he has run
through his speech many times with the help of the TelePrompTer.
</P>
<P>
   FORD'S CONDITION UPGRADED
</P>
<P>
   Former President Gerald Ford was ``in good spirits and doing
much better,'' and expected to make a full recovery after being
hospitalized a day earlier for a stroke, his doctors said today.
George W. Bush who visited Ford shortly after noon, said Ford gave
him some advice for his acceptance speech tonight: ``He told me to
practice.'' The health problems of the nation's 38th president
dampened the mood at an otherwise jubilant GOP celebration.
</P>
<P>
   AND THEN THERE WERE SIX
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has narrowed his search for a running mate to five
members of Congress and a female governor. The Associated Press
reported that the closely guarded list consists only of: Sens. Evan
Bayh of Indiana, John Edwards of North Carolina, John Kerry of
Massachusetts and Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut; House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri; and Gov. Jeanne Shaheen of New
Hampshire. Gephardt and Shaheen have said they don't want the job.
The AP said Gore left open the remote possibility that he could
consider a dark horse candidate who has not been publicly
discussed, the source said. He plans to announce his selection
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   MISSION ACCOMPLISHED
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is gaining ground during the convention among the
exact voters he's targeting, surging 18 points ahead of Al Gore
among independents and 6 points ahead among women, according to a
bipartisan poll released today. The two were virtually tied among
both groups at the start of the week in the Voter.com-Battleground
poll. Bush has long held a commanding lead among men, now at 21
points. Bush's advantage includes bigger leads among key groups
Democrats very much need such as white women 65 and older and white
married working moms. In the overall presidential race, Bush leads
Gore 48-34 percent, with Ralph Nader getting 6 percent and Pat
Buchanan getting 2 percent. The poll has an error margin of 3
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ALL LOCKED UP AND NOWHERE TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of protesters at the convention remained in jail today,
many because they are not cooperating with authorities, police
said. Some took their clothes off or refused to give their names to
authorities. About two dozen were released early this morning. The
demonstrators were arrested in the last three days of protests at
the convention, during sometimes-violent clashes with police and
several demonstrations that blocked traffic, police said. ``We're
not letting our guard down until the gavel sounds tonight,'' Police
Comissioner John Timoney said, referring to the end of the
convention. About 60 people were camped at a park near police
headquarters, where most of the arrested protesters were being
held.
</P>
<P>
   BILLY RAY'S BACK
</P>
<P>
   A tuneful mixture of country, rock and roll and blues describes
the new GOP campaign anthem, to be introduced tonight after George
W. Bush completes his acceptance speech. Aimed at working families
and called ``We the People,'' the song includes lyrics such as ``We
pay the taxes, we pay the bills so they better pay attention on
Capitol Hill.'' The song is a new composition being released by
country singer Billy Ray Cyrus, he of the 'Achy Breaky Heart' fame.
Joining Cyrus in singing the new song will be John Anderson, Waylon
Jennings, Danni Leigh, Montgomery Gentry and Yankee Grey.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY POOPER
</P>
<P>
   As guest of a news organization that wanted to observe him
observing Republicans, Green Party presidential candidate Ralph
Nader is at the convention and has a lot to say about it. ``The
Republican National Convention is a political orgy that has reached
new depths of cravenness,'' he said. As for the kinder, gentler
George W. Bush, Nader wasn't buying it: ``He hasn't yet made his
speech, but it's pretty predictable. It's going to be full of sweet
talk, and not backed by the reality of his own performance in Texas
as governor,'' he said. Nader was however impressed with retired
Army Gen. Colin Powell, but said Sen. John McCain, left him
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   GREENS ROLLING OUT THE GREEN
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader said he plans to spend $500,000 to roll out ads
arguing for his inclusion in fall debates. The ads will air in San
Francisco, Los Angeles, New York, Portland, Ore., and possibly
other markets where he's being received well. One group he hopes to
attract is organized labor. While Republican leaders met with
International Brotherhood of Teamsters president James P. Hoffa
earlier this week, Nader said he's also had talks with the
Teamsters and he thinks there's a chance they won't endorse anyone.
That, he said, helps him the most. Nader stands at 8 percent in
some polls nationally despite spending only about $1 million on his
campaign so far.
</P>
<P>
   SAY IT TO MY FACE
</P>
<P>
   Denying a story that appeared in the Washington Times yesterday
saying he's ready to endorse George W. Bush, Minesotta Gov. Jesse
Ventura said that as a third-party activist, he cannot endorse
either the Democratic or Republican nominee. ``I stated clearly,
`No I will not,' `` Ventura said. He added that he will endorse the
candidates' policies when he agrees with them, as he did when he
backed Al Gore's call for increased federal funding for
special-education services. Ventura also fired back at Minnesota
Republican Party chairman Ron Eibensteiner, who introduced
Minnesota's delegates to the Philadelphia convention as being from
``the land of 10,000 lakes and one goofy governor.'' ``I wonder if
he'd be so brave if it was just me and him in a room,'' Ventura
said.
</P>
<P>
   WATTS HE UP TO NOW?
</P>
<P>
   The latest buzz developing at the convention is about a
potential John McCain-J.C.Watts ticket down the road. McCain and
Watts maintained that they are working as hard as they can to elect
George W. Bush president, but the duo did fuel speculation when
they launched a new Web site that enables voters to get into direct
contact with the two lawmakers. Talk2Us2000.com arrived weeks after
McCain and Watts unveiled a plan to tour swing congressional
districts later this month. Meanwhile, the Oklahoma congressman
said he is not interested in becoming HUD secretary in a Bush
administration. Watts said he ``would rather be judged by a
half-million people every other year than by one person every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   NOW THIS IS MORE LIKE IT
</P>
<P>
   For those troubled by the tightly controlled, stubbornly
saccharine convention, there's plenty of nastiness and partisanship
to be found _ it has simply oozed to the outskirts of the
convention after organizers banned slime on to be two things: I
want to be an actor and I want to be a dentist,'' she said, before
quickly adding: ``And I want to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Saeed Ahmed from staff and news reports.
</P>
