<SLUG> BC-FILM-HOLLOW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLLOW MAN' TIMID, UNADVENTUROUS REMAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kevin Bacon was a good casting choice for Hollywood's latest
remake of H.G. Wells' ``The Invisible Man.'' He has a certain
malevolent charisma, but his angular features are not easy to look
at in large doses, and you don't miss not seeing him. Invisibility
suits him.
</P>
<P>
   But this dubious achievement aside, Paul Verhoeven's ``Hollow
Man'' is not much.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't do anything new or interesting with its (familiar)
premise. Its special effects are often captivating but add little
to the story, and it is relatively suspenseless and often
distastefully crude.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a curiously timid and unadventurous movie that doesn't
even try to challenge its audience and seems a particular
disappointment coming from a director whose other failures
(``Showgirls,'' ``Starship Troopers'') have tended to be epic,
outlandish and daring.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon plays a hotshot young research doctor of a top-secret
government project who, as the film opens, long ago found the
secret of turning test animals invisible and _ Eureka! _ has just
made the final breakthrough by discovering the secret of returning
them to the visible world.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of handing over his findings to his government funders,
however, the somewhat arrogant and delusional doctor injects
himself with invisibility serum.
</P>
<P>
   When the return serum fails, he finds himself trapped in the
state, gradually goes insane and turns into _ what else? _ a serial
killer.
</P>
<P>
   William Goldman, who wrote the script for the last major
invisible-man movie _ 1992's ``Memoirs of an Invisible Man'' _ once
said that the big drawback of the premise for today's
special-effects-happy horror filmmakers is that its chief effect is
a lack of anything visible. It has to scare us by ``what we don't
see.''
</P>
<P>
   James Whale's 1933 classic, and still best, version of Wells'
novel employed some clever effects _ clothes on a formless void,
etc. _ to explore the visual incongruities of invisibility, but
it's mostly a film of suspense that relies heavily on the
imagination of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   With the success of last summer's ``The Sixth Sense'' and
``Blair Witch Project'' as evidence of a new willingness on the
part of the visually-jaded horror audience to go along with this
kind of film, Verhoeven might well have turned out a similar
shocker that evoked some genuine chills from the unseen.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he loads the film down with expensive but not very
scary visual effects, makes sure his hero/villain can almost always
be seen by the cast and audience via special goggles (which
essentially negates the premise), hammers home every scene with
Jerry Goldsmith's blaring score and spills more blood than ``Saving
Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   It's every bit as overblown an invisible-man movie as last
summer's ``The Haunting'' (ironically, made by Verhoeven's former
filmmaking partner, Jan de Bont), which was so heavy-handed,
hammily acted and lacking in any subtlety that it's unintentionally
funny, recalling such monstrosities of the genre as ``The Ghost in
the Invisible Bikini.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Verhoeven _ no doubt alarmed by the poor box-office
showing of his last few films _ is clearly out to pander to a
teenage audience. His research scientists all talk and act like
annoying high school sophomores, and as the invisible maniac starts
picking off members of the team one by one, the film turns into a
clumsy take on the ``Scream'' formula.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLOW MAN
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Paul Verhoeven
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Andrew W. Marlowe
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Elisabeth Shue, Kevin Bacon, Josh Brolin
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: Rated R for horror, violence, nudity
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
