<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CODE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TIC CODE': EVEN AFFLICTED CHILDREN HAVE TANTRUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One encouraging element of ``The Tic Code,'' a small, sincere
film with an educational agenda, is its refusal to make its plucky
11-year-old hero, Miles (Christopher George Marquette), a 100
percent adorable movie moppet. A stubborn, hypersensitive youth who
knows how to throw a mean tantrum, Miles insists on playing a
vaguely ghoulish question-and-answer game, ``Which would you
rather,'' with his mother, Laura (Polly Draper), that gives her the
creeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which would you rather have: no feet or no hands?'' asks the
boy, whose excruciating physical self-consciousness is a result of
his suffering from the nervous ailment known as Tourette's
syndrome. In addition to uncontrollable facial tics and jerky
muscular spasms, Miles sometimes emits strange noises that people
mistake for laughter. At moments of peak stress, he involuntarily
babbles socially inappropriate words. In a challenging role,
Marquette delivers a strong, dry-eyed performance utterly devoid of
shameless heartstring-tugging gestures.
</P>
<P>
   Like most movies that examine specific ailments, this gawky,
occasionally touching film has the feel of a dramatized case
history whose purpose is to educate as much as it is to tell a
story. And like most such movies, ``The Tic Code,'' whose title
refers to a strategy by which Miles fools the class bully into
believing his facial tics are a secret code, is better at educating
than at storytelling. Although the rites of passage Miles endures
on his path toward fuller self-acceptance are believable, they are
an overly contrived chain of events culminating in a melodramatic
cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Miles is unusual in more ways than one. A jazz piano prodigy, he
lives in Lower Manhattan with his divorced, fiercely protective
mother, who works as a tailor to support the two of them. After
school he hangs out at the legendary Village Vanguard, where he
occasionally sits in with seasoned musicians. Miles' father (James
McCaffery) is also a musician and is constantly on the road.
Through overheard telephone conversations, the audience learns that
he is in deep denial about his son's condition, which he believes
to be neurotic rather than neurological. When he finally appears
late in the film, he turns out to be such a monstrous narcissist
that he becomes the movie's designated villain.
</P>
<P>
   At the club Miles develops a protege-mentor relationship with
Tyrone (Gregory Hines), a successful jazz saxophonist who also has
Tourette's (with much less pronounced symptoms) and who shares the
boy's feelings of shame. When Tyrone begins dating Laura, her
verbalized concern with her son's ailment brings out Tyrone's own
buried rage and insecurity. Fiercely proud, he refuses to discuss
the ailment. When she persists, he accuses her of both exploiting
and pitying him. Although Hines imbues Tyrone with a slouching,
hooded-eye cool, his performance seems so detached it remains one
step removed from the character.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tic Code'' is the brainchild of Draper, who wrote the
screenplay and who is married to Michael Wolff, a successful jazz
musician with Tourette's. (Wolff composed the effectively moody
soundtrack.) If her screenplay adheres to well-worn dramatic
formulas, it is a useful and informative guide to an ailment that
is largely misunderstood. (As a sidelight, the movie suggests that
Thelonious Monk's stage eccentricities may have been signs of
undiagnosed Tourette's.)
</P>
<P>
   Draper's taut, self-effacing, extremely quiet performance is the
best thing about the movie. She makes us feel the intense pain and
devotion of a dedicated single mother who has choked her own
desires to see her son through a difficult phase of his life.
Without begging for sympathy, she shows the human cost of her
self-sacrifice. When her romance with Tyrone rekindles her adult
desires, she conveys the quaking insecurity and discomfort of a
woman rediscovering a sexuality she had put aside so long ago she
almost forgot it existed.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TIC CODE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Gary Winick; written by Polly Draper; director of
photography, Wolfgang Held; edited by Bill Pankow; music by Michael
Wolff; production designer, Rick Butler; produced by Draper, Wolff
and Karen Tangorra; released by Avalanche Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   With: Gregory Hines (Tyrone), Polly Draper (Laura), Christopher
George Marquette (Miles), Desmond Robertson (Todd), Carol Kane
(Gimpole) and James McCaffery (Michael).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes. This film is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes some
strong language and sexual situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
