<SLUG> BC-CVN-PREZ-FEUD04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH-CLINTON FEUD REACHES A SHAKY TRUCE
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A rickety political truce emerged Thursday
between two feuding members of one of the world's most exclusive
clubs: presidents of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The verbal brawl between President Clinton and the man he
defeated in 1992, former President Bush, served to enliven an
otherwise tightly scripted and relentlessly upbeat Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   It sputtered to a halt because handlers for both George W. Bush
and Al Gore saw the war of words as a risky detour for the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was widely viewed as having struck the initial blow at a
Democratic fund-raising event last weekend in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``As near as I can tell,'' the president said, ``the message of
the Bush campaign is: 'How bad can I be? I've been governor of
Texas. My daddy was president. I own a baseball team.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The former president sprang to his son's defense in an interview
Tuesday on NBC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what I'm going to do,'' Bush said. ``I'm going
to wait a month. And if he continues that, then I'm going to tell
the nation what I think about him as a person and a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has now recanted. In an appearance with his wife, Barbara,
on ABC-TV, he said in his trademark cryptic style: ``Period.
Future. Now. Anytime. Nothing. Not going to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, restoration politics remained in the picture
Thursday when the Republican nominee pointed with pride at his
parents during his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had various takes on the episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds everybody that Bush thinks the presidency is an
office you can inherit,'' said Democratic National Committee
Chairman Joe Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore camp quietly sent word to the president to drop the
subject lest a continuing exchange rob Gore of his turn in the
political spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The bad blood may have its roots in the hard-fought 1992
campaign, but some recall a sharp escalation at the 1996 Republican
convention, when Bush said in his address to the delegates:
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, as president I worked hard to uphold the dignity and
the honor of the presidency, and I tried, as did my superb staff,
to treat both the White House and the presidency itself with
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks my heart when the White House is demeaned, the
presidency itself diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, Bush operatives have made the theme of
restoring dignity to the Oval Office a prominent one. They say such
criticism is justified because Democrats have made clear that
attacks on Bush will be a major part of their campaign strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the (former) president said is justified because
we're going to be under a relentless attack,'' said Haley Barbour,
a top Bush adviser. ``All they know is slash-and-burn, leaving a
scorched earth.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, denied that the
Bush-Clinton spat had upset the convention's
outreach-through-civility formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what's more important is that the vice president is
such a weak candidate that he's forced to rely upon a constant
barrage of attacks launched by President Clinton,'' he said. ``I
think people see it as inappropriate and it paints a picture of Al
Gore as a weak candidate and a weak leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, Clinton's press secretary, also sought to minimize
the feud in an appearance on ``The Late Show'' with David
Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the president did beat him in 1992. He had to move. He
had to pack, move out. But other than that, they're fine. They get
along very well. I think the president went out and poked a little
fun at George W. Bush, which is not a hard thing to do. His father,
being a father, wanted to defend him and he did,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is no sure thing _ given the large egos, the competing
legacies and the prize at stake _ that the truce will hold up until
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass' e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
