<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPACE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-03 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPACE COWBOYS': VOICES OF EXPERIENCE, ROCKETING TO THE RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' begins in 1958, with jaunty western guitar
music on the soundtrack and black-and-white vistas of the big sky
and empty land around Edwards Air Force Base in the California
desert. The first scenes follow the adventures of a group of
reckless young pilots who crash their expensive military plane,
bicker and fight among themselves and lose the chance to be the
first Americans in space to a chimpanzee named Mary Ann and a new
civilian agency called NASA.
</P>
<P>
   There is something odd about the four smooth-faced, jaunty young
men who make up Team Daedalus, as the pilots are known. Their faces
have the clean, generic good looks we've come to associate with the
bygone days of the Eisenhower administration, but their voices have
the rasp of hard experience, as well as an uncanny familiarity,
since they belong to Tommy Lee Jones, Donald Sutherland, James
Garner and, most recognizably, Clint Eastwood, who also directed
the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The overdubbing of these craggy, worn voices is a kind of
subliminal foreshadowing of the movie's theme, which is that while
youth may be pretty to look at, ripeness is all. After the
black-and-white prologue, the scene shifts to the colorful present,
where the members of Team Daedalus, their voices rejoined to their
aching, wizened bodies, reunite to settle scores with the oily
officer who grounded them (James Cromwell) and haul their tired
carcasses triumphantly into orbit. It seems that a Russian
communications satellite outfitted with an operating system like
the one Frank Corvin (Eastwood) designed for Skylab has run into
trouble, and Frank is the only man alive who knows his way around
such obsolete material.
</P>
<P>
   So Frank rounds up his old comrades, none of whom seem to have
eased into graceful retirement. Tank (Garner) has become a Baptist
minister, Hawk (Jones) gives stomach-turning thrill rides in an old
crop duster, and Jerry (Sutherland) _ the only team member with a
two-syllable name and without a Southwestern twang in his voice _
designs roller coasters and chases women half his age. Frank
himself has devoted his golden years to fooling around in his
garage.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow they endure the razzing of their cocky younger
colleagues, the meddling of their bosses (Cromwell and William
Devane) and the rigors of NASA's physical fitness program _
including a medical examination scene obviously filmed without body
doubles _ and find themselves cleared for takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   By the time their space shuttle pierces the earth's atmosphere,
``Space Cowboys'' has already ascended to surprising heights of
entertainment. The movie's release has been preceded by some
derisive eye-rolling, since it appears to be an unlikely hybrid of
two incompatible genres: the geezer ensemble comedy and the
trouble-in-space action adventure _ ``Grumpy Old Astronauts,'' or
``The Sunshine Boys on the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Tank, Hawk, Jerry and Frank school their arrogant,
by-the-book young understudies (Loren Dean and Courtney B. Vance)
in the low-key, seat-of-the-pants machismo of an earlier era, so do
the scarred show business veterans who portray them knock some
sense, and some manners, into a youth-besotted film industry. Back
in the late 1950s, when the X-Men were still a gleam in Stan Lee's
eye, Eastwood and Garner, both now in their early 70s, were rival
television gunslingers _ on ``Rawhide'' and ``Maverick,''
respectively _ and they bring to their roles here the easygoing
wisdom and humor of long experience.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Jones and Sutherland, who nearly sneaks off with the
movie in his hip pocket, they seem to be in a contest to see who
can give the most understated performance. Sutherland's reedy
whisper delivers a stream of pickup lines that seem to come from
the October 1958 issue of Playboy his younger self is seen perusing
early in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, nearly 20 years younger than Garner but with a face that
says otherwise, has the most complex role, since Hawk is not only
the hot-headed foil for Frank's glowering stoicism, but also the
film's romantic lead and its tragic figure. A widower, Hawk falls
in love with Sara Holland (Marcia Gay Harden), a NASA engineer who
has sacrificed her own dreams of space flight. Harden, in spite of
a credibly unflattering government-scientist haircut, performs with
her usual intelligence and charm, while Jones gives his deepest,
most controlled performance since ``Blue Skies,'' in which he also
played an Air Force pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Once the mission itself gets under way, ``Space Cowboys''
surrenders a little to convention. There's not a lot of fresh life
to be breathed into the Houston-we-have-a-problem technical
difficulty narrative, but the outer-space scenes have a welcome
grandeur and luster and enough of a feeling of real danger to keep
you interested.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood is ordinarily a rather earthbound director, more
interested in the efficient (and sometimes graceless) conveyance of
story and character than in visual beauty, but here the special
effects, by Industrial Light and Magic, add depth and richness to
the movie without distracting from the greater pleasure of watching
four great actors reclaim their prime.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his directing career, Eastwood has quietly
advanced a revisionist notion of masculinity, a critique from
within of the brutal individualism that made him famous as an
actor. His films explore the possibility that the best parts of the
old code of manly virtue _ loyalty, good humor, a certain reckless
bravado _ might be retained even as its less attractive features
are abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   This time, without succumbing to bitterness or nostalgia or
overstating the case for one generation's virtues, he and his
cohorts mount a vigorous and funny defense of maturity _ the last
thing you might expect from a summer action picture, and one of the
reasons ``Space Cowboys'' is one of the best entertainments this
season has yet offered.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SPACE COWBOYS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Clint Eastwood; written by Ken Kaufman and Howard
Klausner; director of photography, Jack N. Green; edited by Joel
Cox; music by Lennie Niehaus; production designer, Henry Bumstead;
produced by Eastwood and Andrew Lazar; released by Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Clint Eastwood (Frank Corvin), Tommy Lee Jones (Hawk
Hawkins), Donald Sutherland (Jerry O'Neil), James Garner (Tank
Sullivan), Marcia Gay Harden (Sara Holland), William Devane (Eugene
Davis), Loren Dean (Ethan Glance), Courtney B. Vance (Roger Hines)
and James Cromwell (Bob Gerson).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 105 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' is rated PG-13 (parents strongly cautioned).
It includes the kind of salty language and occasional fisticuffs
you'd expect from cantankerous old flyboys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
