<HEADLINE>
FORD, MAKING GOOD RECOVERY, MEETS WITH BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to update w/Bush meeting and rewrite. Changes byline.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Pleasing doctors with the speed of his recovery
from a small stroke, former President Ford regained his sense of
balance, took a short walk and met with Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas in the hospital Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and a Ford spokesman depicted a strong-willed, almost
stubborn patient who was anxious to leave Hahnemann University
Hospital here, where he was admitted Wednesday morning with
symptoms that included slurred speech, loss of balance and weakness
in the left arm.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 87, first sought treatment at the hospital Tuesday
evening; a sinus problem was diagnosed, and Ford was treated for
it. Hospital officials have rejected the suggestion from
journalists that doctors released him prematurely. Ford's
spokesman, Calvin McDowell, said the Ford family was completely
satisfied with the care given.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events and activities of that evening were totally
controlled by the president,'' said McDowell. Despite being
encouraged to undergo a CT scan on his first trip to the hospital,
``It was the president's decision to go back to the hotel,''
McDowell said. He said it was unclear just when Ford suffered the
stroke. Doctors have said he might have suffered more than one, but
tests uncovered evidence of only a single stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, Ford's condition was upgraded from serious to
fair after he had a restful night and took a 30-to 40-foot walk
down a corridor. He was taking blood-thinning medicine to prevent
the recurrence of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with his progress and expect him to have a
full recovery,'' said Dr. Robert J. Schwartzman, the hospital's
chief neurologist. Ford's balance and the use of his left hand were
back to normal, and Ford was expected to recover from
stroke-induced speech slurring soon.
</P>
<P>
   A complete recovery in such situations takes from six weeks to
three months, said Dr. Carole E. Thomas, director of the
neurological intensive care unit. Ford could be released this
weekend or early next week. He was already demanding to look at his
calendar to prepare for upcoming events, McDowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prospects for a full recovery, the stroke left Ford
shaken, his spokesman said. Ford had not had so much as a cold in
3{ years, ``so he was nervous. This was a wake-up call,'' McDowell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, the 38th president, was in town for the convention, over
which he casts something of a patriarchal shadow. His chief of
staff as president was a 34-year-old Dick Cheney, who on Wednesday
evening was nominated for vice president. And McDowell pointed out
that Ford gave the Republican presidential candidate's father a
major career boost, naming George Bush director of the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush spoke to Ford on the phone, as did other
Republican figures, including Henry Kissinger and Brent Scowcroft.
George W. Bush stopped by for a 10-minute visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Ford is doing great,'' the presidential candidate
said at a lunch in downtown Philadelphia. ``He told me to tell
people he can't wait to get out and campaign with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
