<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I'M THE ONE THAT I WANT': BEYOND ASIAN STEREOTYPES, THIS COMIC
SETTLES SCORES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
(Eds: This review contains language that some readers may find
objectionable.) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are moments in the filmed concert of Margaret Cho's
successful and hilarious one-woman show, ``I'm the One That I
Want,'' when her cheeks puff up, her eyes crinkle, her mouth curls
into a wicked little smirk and she swings out at the injustices of
the world like an Asian-American Roseanne.
</P>
<P>
   Like her feisty forerunner in stand-up comedy, Cho, who is
Korean-American and grew up in a bohemian section of San Francisco,
has a hefty stash of volatile personal baggage to unload. Much of
it has to do with body image and the pressure on women (especially
in show business) to be fashion-model slim. Add to that the media
stereotyping of Asians as humble, polite, bowing-and-scraping
servants and you have a full arsenal of accumulated resentments
ripe for comic detonation.
</P>
<P>
   Cho is a superb mimic of body language, and her show is strung
with killingly funny parodies of Asian women as meek, supplicating
flower girls. Cho is anything but meek. She is a lusty,
full-figured 31-year-old dynamo whose outrage is tempered by an
empathetic sweetness. A major figure who runs through her show is
her all-knowing Buddha-like mother, whom she impersonates with a
complicated mixture of love and ridicule that tilts just enough
toward love to make us care about her.
</P>
<P>
   Cho's experiences in mainstream show business are a chilling
lesson in ethnic stereotyping. As she discovered first hand,
ludicrous, patronizing preconceptions about Asians and
Asian-Americans still extend to the heart of America's popular
myth-making machine. The spine of the show, filmed at the Warfield
Theater in San Francisco, is Cho's appalling true story of her
experiences starring in the short-lived ABC sitcom ``All-American
Girl,'' the first mainstream television comedy built around an
Asian-American family.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Cho recalls, she believed that all her dreams had
come true and she had found acceptance for the first time in her
life. But those dreams were quickly dashed. No sooner had she won
the role of a character loosely based on herself than the network
tried to revamp her appearance and her personality. Although much
of Cho's stand-up comedy had involved the affectionate ridicule of
her parents, such jokes became taboo on the show. Insisting she
lose weight, the producers hired a personal trainer and
nutritionist to slim her down quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate result of being forced to lose 30 pounds in two
weeks was having her kidneys collapse. But even more damaging was
the loss of personal identity as she dutifully acceded to her
bosses' market-tested notions of who she should be. At one point,
she says, she became so obsessed with slimming down that all she
could think about when watching ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' was the
effectiveness of cross-carrying as a weight-loss regime. The
crowning humiliation was the network's hiring of a special
consultant to instruct Cho on how to seem ``more Asian.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately Cho's sense of herself was so thoroughly undermined
that she went into a suicidal tailspin and became addicted to
alcohol and drugs. She is even able to make this miserable chapter
of her life funny in a bit in which she parodies two drunks
unsuccessfully trying to have sex.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of sex, Cho is refreshingly, uproariously raunchy.
A self-proclaimed ``fag hag,'' ``trash talker'' and
``hetero-phobe'' who was ``raised by drag queens,'' Cho muses
loudly, profanely and at length on gay and lesbian mating habits,
oral sex and pornography, both gay and straight. (She has
particularly nasty things to say about the men in straight porn,
who she believes are selected for their unattractiveness so they
won't threaten male viewers.) As enamored of gay men as she is, Cho
is hardly intimidated by them and has some tart things to say about
their manners in bars. Discussing the Proustian moments that
transport us back to childhood, her most vivid, she says, isn't the
Christmasy fragrance of evergreens but the scent of men in
pantyhose.
</P>
<P>
   How funny is ``I'm the One That I Want?'' Several times while
watching the movie I laughed until the tears were running down my
face.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `I'M THE ONE THAT I WANT'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Lionel Coleman; written by Margaret Cho; edited by
Robyn T. Migel; music by Joan Jett and the Blackhearts; produced by
Lorene Machado. Cast: Margaret Cho.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 96 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
