<HEADER>
A1907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SANTEFE-OPERA-REVIEW-     08-03 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTEFE-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTE FE OPERA: LOVE, MODERN AND MYTHICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALLAN KOZINN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ There is a faintly bittersweet atmosphere at
the Santa Fe Opera this summer, the company's 44th season and its
last under the directorship of its founder, John Crosby. Crosby,
74, has asked the company not to make too much of his retirement,
and that wish is largely being honored. When the subject is
mentioned, it is mostly in the context of plans for next season, to
be directed by his successor, Richard Gaddes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few opera companies have been so closely associated with
a single person, and for so long. It is not lost on anyone here
that Crosby's vision has been the primary draw for the 60 percent
of the company's audience that comes from outside New Mexico.
Having built (and rebuilt and revamped) an attractive, acoustically
superb open-air opera house in the mountains here, he has filled
its stage with a careful balance of standard repertory, rarities
and new operas, including nearly 50 world or American premieres.
</P>
<P>
   This summer the company adds Hans Werner Henze's ``Venus and
Adonis'' to the American premiere column of its ledger, where it
joins five of Henze's earlier works. On Wednesday evening the
company gave the second of three performances of the opera. The
last is to be on Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the Shakespearean poem, Henze and his librettist,
Hans-Ulrich Treichel, have expanded the story into an operatic
psychodrama with an exquisitely ornate structure. Dance, operatic
vocal writing and madrigals for a six-voice choir alternate in a
series of 17 short scenes lasting 70 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The opera's design calls to mind the masques of Purcell's time,
although Henze's variegated score inhabits a different musical
universe, with its dense layering, dreamlike textures and stretches
of both gritty dissonance and touching lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   The work is set in several worlds. One describes a mythological
triangle, evoked by dancers: Mars lusts after Venus, who rejects
him in favor of Adonis. Adonis is too self-absorbed and
free-spirited to notice, but when he finally responds, after
encountering mating horses that awaken his own sexuality, he is
killed by a wild boar.
</P>
<P>
   A parallel story, evoked in vocal music, shows three singers,
Prima Donna, the Hero-Player and Clemente, rehearsing an opera
about Venus, Mars and Adonis. The attractions and tensions between
the mythological characters are mirrored in the singers'
relationships, and at the moment the boar kills Adonis, the
Hero-Player stabs Clemente. The libretto, in German, sometimes
conveys the singers' thoughts and sometimes those of Venus, Mars
and Adonis; emotionally, they are identical.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is equal to the work's complexities. Stephen West's
solid bass-baritone drips with the Hero-Player's (and Mars')
bitterness and frustration, just as Christopher Ventris' tenor
evokes Clemente's (and Adonis') innocence. Both sing Henze's
angular lines with an Expressionistic edge. Lauren Flanigan, as
Prima Donna (and Venus), moves beyond that angularity, sometimes
giving her music a Straussian gloss that suggests her characters'
seductiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The principal dancers _ Peter Mantia as a mechanical, posing
Mars; Brock vonDrehlecq no space here Labrenz as a fluid,
naturalistic Adonis; and Sarita Allen as a limber, predatory Venus
_ executed Ron Thornhill's choreography with corresponding
vividness.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Kirchner's production is set in a spare, whitewashed
rehearsal-room set by John Conklin, with eye-catching if slightly
motley costumes by David C. Woolard. Richard Bradshaw conducted an
energetic reading of Henze's complex score.
</P>
<P>
   The friction between sexuality and innocence is also at the
heart of Verdi's ``Rigoletto,'' which the company is offering in a
new production by Mikael Melbye, a young Danish baritone who has
taken up directing. Melbye's Mantua is clean, uncluttered and
traditional, but what enlivened the performance on Monday evening
was the degree to which Melbye had persuaded his singers to step
beyond familiar characterizations.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Josephson's Rigoletto, for example, was less twisted and
mean-spirited than most, and as a result his anguish was more
sharply defined. In the scene in which he harassed the unfortunate
Monterone, this Rigoletto knew immediately that he had gone too
far. He was pierced by Monterone's curse the second it was uttered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
