u e BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT &LR;      08-03 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visitors to Blockbuster stores on Sept. 1 may be startled to
notice kiosks displaying DirecTV, which beams movies by satellite.
Why would the country's largest provider of videocassettes open the
door to a competing type of movie delivery? Several types, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Late this year or early next, Blockbuster plans to dispense
movies via TiVo, a digital service in California that can serve up
films in the home through a device placed on television sets. Last
month, Blockbuster announced a deal with Enron, a Houston company,
to supply movies on a video-on-demand basis over fiber optic lines
and high-speed digital subscriber lines, or DSL's.
</P>
<P>
   Moves like these could obviously be stirred into doomsday
scenarios for the video store, which some analysts say will go the
way of the dodo once people can get the movies they want with a
click. John Antioco, Blockbuster's chairman, predicts no such
disappearance for stores but said he did see a time eventually when
customers could receive ``the full Blockbuster experience basically
online without having to leave their home.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, he said, stores will act as supplying agents, so
to speak, for a mix of services in a vastly broadened video scene
that will include traditional rental and sale of cassettes and
especially DVD's (already approaching 10 percent of the video
market), pay-per-view via satellite and digital cable, and video on
demand from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo and Enron are carriers. Blockbuster supplies content. It is
not yet clear how extensive the new service will be. Antioco refers
to ``Blockbuster on demand.'' And what is ``video on demand,''
beyond vague jargon? ``One minute you want to watch a movie and 15
seconds later you can be,'' Antioco said. Stores can't satisfy
that, of course, nor can anyone else. Blockbuster's initial DSL
inventory will be about 200 films, he said. Later, greater
broadband and Internet access will speed things considerably.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, stores needn't be shut out. Blockbuster outlets,
he said, will be selling products like DirecTV, high-speed DSL
connections and video-on-demand services connected to the Web. Much
of that can be ordered from home, of course, but it seems you'll
still be able to leave the house.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever new technology takes hold, studio accountants can't
fault the videocassette. In its weekly list of 40 best renters,
Video Business magazine compares movies' video revenue to their
theater box-office take. For big theater titles like ``The Green
Mile'' or ``American Beauty,'' the box office outstrips video
rental, but when it comes to smaller films, especially those with
some critical acclaim that may have been missed during their
theater runs, the cassette takes over.
</P>
<P>
   For example, after 10 weeks in stores, ``Boys Don't Cry'' had
taken in $17.5 million in rentals versus $3.7 million in theaters.
After 11 weeks, ``Mystery, Alaska,'' a worthy sleeper, has taken in
$9 million in theaters but almost $20 million on tape. And ``Girl,
Interrupted'' took seven weeks on video to pass its theater run,
$30 million to $29 million.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Holy Smoke
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God it's Quantas!'' cries Ruth Barron's mother (Julie
Hamilton), on her way to Sydney from India with her headstrong
daughter, Ruth (Kate Winslet), whom she has been trying to extract
from her guru. Back home Ruth is turned over to a tough ``cult
exiter'' named P.J. Waters (Harvey Keitel), but gradually he is
overmatched. Though it has sensual allure, Jane Campion's film
isn't helped by a screenplay that, Janet Maslin wrote in The New
York Times, ``threatens to become heavy-handedly ideological
beneath its outward whimsy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 114 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Reindeer Games
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan in the dead of slate-gray winter a dimple-chinned
convict named Rudy (Ben Affleck) gets out of prison and goes home
to romance Ashley (Charlize Theron), with whom a recently deceased
prisoner has been corresponding. Ashley has never seen her pen pal
or his picture, so Rudy slides by on that front, but he has trouble
when Ashley's lowlife brother (Gary Sinise) wants to use his
expertise to rob a casino on an Indian reservation. John
Frankenheimer's film reflects his bent for swift, scary violence,
but at the end ``a needlessly complicated mechanism is a blow to
the breakneck wiliness that has come before'' (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   _ 2000. Dimension. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 104 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Bedrooms and Hallways
</P>
<P>
   Rose Troche's comedy reaches for Noel Coward, but without the
sharp class distinctions and with a lot more sex. A love-starved
gay artisan named Leo (Kevin McKidd) has an affair with Brendan
(James Purefoy). But then there is Sally (Jennifer Ehle), Leo's
high school sweetheart, who is breaking up with Brendan. Does Leo
tell her he's sleeping with her former boyfriend? Having begun to
explore the ins and outs of bisexuality, the film then ``loses its
nerve and turns into a shallow sitcom in which everyone is abruptly
and mechanically paired off'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. First Run Features. $79.95. 96 minutes. Release date:
Aug 8.
</P>
<P>
   The Grandfather
</P>
<P>
   Now impoverished, Rodrigo, Count of Albrit (Fernando
Fernan-Gomez), determines to discover which of his granddaughters
(Cristina Cruz and Alicia Rozas) is of his blood. Complicating that
question, their mother, Lucrecia (Cayetana Guillen Cuervo), who was
unfaithful to Don Rodrigo's son when he was alive and now profits
from a liaison with a government minister, uses her influence to
throw the old man off the track. Part paean to the genuine riches
of life, Jose Luis Garcia's film ``brims with understandings of the
complexities of relationships, the frailties of humankind and the
possibilities of joy'' (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 147 minutes. Spanish with
English subtitles. PG. Release date: Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEATLES COLLECTION. Four DVDs, slickly packaged, include
``Help!'' (90 minutes), with a mad scientist and demented mystics
chasing the boys around the world after the ring on Ringo's finger;
``Magical Mystery Tour'' (50 minutes), a psychedelic gambol through
the countryside; ``The First U.S. Visit'' (83 minutes), with three
performances on the Ed Sullivan Show) and ``You Can't Do That! The
Making of `A Hard Day's Night''' (60 minutes), with Phil Collins
reflecting on the evolution of Richard Lester's movie about an
imaginary day in the life of the group. 2000. MPI. $79.99. Release
date: Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ROSETTA. Tired of being poor, a desperate 17-year-old Belgian
girl (Emilie Dequenne) is determined to land work at any cost.
Foraging for her existence, she scratches for sustenance and covets
a friend's position as a cook at a waffle stand, to the extent that
she hesitates to rescue him when he falls into a river. Luc and
Jean-Pierre Dardenne's stoically drab film won the top prize at
last year's Cannes Film Festival, with Dequenne named best actress,
and the Darwinian struggle to survive makes a great subject. But
``this time the Dardenne brothers pushed too hard,'' Stephen Holden
wrote in The New York Times. ``Instead of feeling universal, the
movie feels claustrophobic.'' 1999. USA. $56.49. 95 minutes. French
with English subtitles. R.
</P>
<P>
   STRANGE IMPERSONATION. An interesting piece of '40s noir,
Anthony Mann's film involves a lab accident, a scarred face,
swapped identities and revenge on former lovers and enemies. 1946.
Kino. $24.95. 68 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
