<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much less humid air will spread from the eastern Great Lakes to
the interior Northeast in the wake of a cold front. Meanwhile, high
humidity will linger near the southern New England and Middle
Atlantic Coast Friday morning as the front moves slowly east.
Scattered thunderstorms will develop in the sultry air near the
front from southern New Jersey to the Carolinas at midday and in
the afternoon. By Saturday, dry air will cover a large area from
the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley to the Northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Southeast will have limited sun with scattered
thunderstorms. A cluster of strong thunderstorms will plague the
Tennessee Valley and southern Appalachians as a jet stream
disturbance passes overhead.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, very warm weather will persist. Thundershowers will
be common over many peaks in the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FIRST SUNSET
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday at 1:16 a.m., the sun dipped below the horizon for
36 minutes at Barrow, Alaska. It was the first sunset since May 10
at the nation's northernmost weather station. Daylight will dwindle
at Barrow until, beginning on Nov. 18, two months of total darkness
will mark the depths of arctic winter. During the next few months,
the deepening chill in the north will gradually increase the
temperature contrast between pole and equator. The storms which
derive energy from these contrasts will eventually strengthen
enough to draw cold, polar air south for the winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
