<HEADLINE>
`COYOTE' BLENDS LIKABLE LEAD, SWEET STORY INTO CROWD-PLEASER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ad campaign for ``Coyote Ugly'' makes it out to be the
cheesecake movie of the summer: what looks like an explosively
salacious remake of ``Cocktail'' with five flashy, hip-swinging,
supermodel bartenders instead of one Tom Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the film is more a remake of ``Flashdance,'' a
rather likable and very sweet-spirited story about young love in
the big city and one naive but determined young woman trying to
make her dream happen against all odds.
</P>
<P>
   That woman is Violet (Piper Perabo), an aspiring but painfully
shy young songwriter who, as the film opens, has quit her longtime
job in a New Jersey greasy spoon and _ against the wishes of her
father (John Goodman) _ is leaving home to try to make it in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Everything goes wrong, of course, but she soon finds a
sympathetic boyfriend (Adam Garcia) and a job as a bartender in a
popular watering hole called Coyote Ugly, where the bartenders are
women and the crowds of men behave like sailors on liberty in
Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The movie becomes a question of whether she will be able to fit
in this raucous environment, whether her father and boyfriend will
approve of her working there and whether the public exposure will
help her overcome her crippling stage fright.
</P>
<P>
   As these questions are answered, there are few surprises, but
the movie is still a genuine crowd-pleaser and works mostly off the
casting of Perabo, who stole what there was to steal in ``The
Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' earlier this summer and has
the kind of looks, presence and self-deprecating sense of comedy
that could make a career.
</P>
<P>
   She also works especially well off other actors, so her scenes
with the equally ingratiating Garcia make a surprisingly winning
love story, her scenes with Maria Bello (as her boss) sparkle with
charm and her scenes with Goodman are so warm and enjoyable they
could probably be re-worked into the pilot for a successful
TV-sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coyote Ugly'' is clearly no masterpiece and suffers from the
usual heavy hand of super-producer Jerry Bruckheimer (``Con Air,''
``Top Gun''). But coming as it does in the midst of a summer in
which every new movie seems to be outdoing the last in the depth of
its scatology and low comedy, it's a small breath of fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   COYOTE UGLY
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: David McNally
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Gina Wendkos
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Piper Perabo, Adam Garcia, Maria Bello, Melanie Lynskey,
Tyra Banks.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 94 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: PG-13 for sensuality and rowdy bar scenes
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JERUSALEM-THEATER-REV     08-03 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERUSALEM-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JERUSALEM SYNDROME': WHEN LIFE IS RIDICULOUS AND YOU ARE LIVING
IT 
</HEADLINE>
   By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is plenty of laughter in Marc Maron's
``Jerusalem Syndrome,'' but this unusual theatrical concoction by
one of the leading practitioners of alternative comedy in New York
City is not a joke. Ambiguity is expected of Maron: One reason he
and a few like-minded comics adopted the label alternative in the
mid-1990s was to signal audiences that they were not quick-laugh
artists like most stand-up comics. Maron in particular has often
explored fairly sophisticated ideas in sizzling exchanges with his
audience. ``Jerusalem Syndrome'' takes his approach into very
different territory.
</P>
<P>
   He performed an early version of this work last year at P.S. 122
as part of a citywide comedy festival. It involved stringing
together several riffs he had first tried in comedy clubs into a
unified story. He and his director, Kirsten Ames, have continued
working on it, and the Off Broadway production by the Westbeth
Theater Center is clearly meant to invite recognition of it as a
new form of alternative theater. Whether as comfort to him or as
reassurance to his fans, Westbeth has kept a hint of the club
setting, with viewers drinking at crowded tables and
brain-shattering music preceding the show. But this show is a long
way from the stand-up clubs and even from Maron's favorite haunt,
the Luna Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   The title is a name given by psychiatrists to a delusion of some
visitors to the Holy Land that they are biblical prophets or divine
emissaries. On the face of it, the thought of God acting through
Maron _ who for years has trumpeted a respect for religion that is
decidedly inferior to his knowledge of it, which is nil _ is funny
enough to get a laugh without being mentioned. The show's theme,
the spiritual journey of a radical materialist, is a good framework
for Maron's fanciful recollection of his life, beginning with a
college flirtation with a beatnik cult.
</P>
<P>
   His examination of the Beat phenomenon as religion, with sacred
texts, established rituals and even pilgrimages (``any car ride
with music and no destination'') is not only good comedy but also
astute criticism, and a poem about visiting Jack Kerouac's grave is
excellent parody. If cocaine addiction in Hollywood seems a detour
on his journey, he does get a real spiritual insight from it:
``When you hear voices, it is never one, but many, and you spend a
lot of time getting them to pick a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   The high point of his quest is a visit to a cigarette factory.
Maron's reflection on brand loyalty as a commitment of faith leads
to a hilarious litany of corporate emblems enshrined in the modern
pantheon of stuff. But real revelation comes in the tobacco works,
where workers all along the assembly line smoke the product of
their craft, as does Maron onstage throughout this show. In most
religions heaven is an eternal life of fulfillment of people's
deepest desires, and to Maron the factory is paradisiacal: ``This
is what socialism should have been!''
</P>
<P>
   But the search disintegrates in Israel, in part because his
conceit of merging with a camcorder is awkwardly intrusive, but in
part by design. His vision of ending a hopeless peace process and
inviting the Disney Co. to turn Jerusalem into the peaceful heart
of a heavenly kingdom is vintage Maron. But his confrontations with
extremely religious Jews at the Western Wall is a jolt. He says he
grew up in a Jewish family in which religion was almost never
mentioned, and through his life it never touched him. In Israel it
cannot be avoided, and he seems nervous about that. He does not
express distaste for the practices of some of the people he mimics
at prayer; he says, ``I don't like them.'' Every glance and gesture
telegraph his discomfort and suggest he is talking about a part of
himself he does not want to recognize.
</P>
<P>
   In club acts this man was the specialist in alienation; his
ferocious assaults on assertive audience members, driven by a
formidable intellect, can spread waves of discomfort all around
him. Suddenly he is the alien, facing himself as an alien. He is
clever enough to make this hapless self-awareness amusing, but
under it is a murmur of sadness that makes the audience restless.
Throughout the performance there is a slightly unnerving suggestion
that he would like some understanding, and in the last segment that
he could use some warmth. A warm hug was never his metier unless he
had a stiletto up his sleeve, and this new persona is a bit
alarming.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if in his search for a new form he has returned to the
old Italian idea of commedia, as Dante used it or as Pirandello
did: Life is ridiculous, but not always to those living it. If
``Jerusalem Syndrome'' falters as theater, it is because Maron has
not created a clearly defined character for him to inhabit and be
transformed by. Audiences as well as actors are brought to life by
roles, which they cooperate in endowing with a soul. If he can ever
step outside himself far enough to invent such a role, or if he can
find a collaborator who can write one, he and his audience will
find out at once if he is an actor. Here he has taken a step that
makes me hope he will take the leap.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JERUSALEM SYNDROME'
</P>
<P>
   A one-man show written and performed by Marc Maron; directed and
developed by Kirsten Ames; sets by Jessica Krause; lighting by Roy
Trejo; sound by Gregory Kostroff. Presented by Westbeth Theater
Center, Arnold Engelman, producing director. At 151 Bank St. in
Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
