<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-03 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLISHED ARISTOCRATS, PROW TO STERN 
</HEADLINE>
   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American romance with sports champions may have started in
the 1920s. ``In golf there was Bobby Jones, tennis had Bill Tilden,
in boxing there was Jack Dempsey, horse racing had the great Man o'
War, the Yankees had Ruth and Gehrig, and speedboat racing had Gar
Wood,'' writes Anthony S. Mollica Jr. in ``Gar Wood Boats: Classics
of a Golden Era'' (MBI Publishing, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Garfield Arthur Wood, creator of the handsome Gar Wood mahogany
runabout, was known as America's Speed King because he dominated
speedboat racing for decades. ``He influenced the whole direction
of motor boating,'' Mollica said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gar Wood was an inventor and a very successful
industrialist, but his passion was racing. He designed and built
his boats in his own shop, and after beating his compatriots for
several years running he successfully competed abroad. He branched
out and manufactured hand-crafted runabouts, knockabouts, launches,
commuter yachts and cruisers. Today, these antique Gar Woods are
cherished and proudly paraded around the Thousand Islands and Lake
George in New York, Harbor Springs, Mich., and Mount Dora, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Gar Wood's insistence on uncompromising quality,
superior design and outstanding performance that attracts the
classic boat collectors around the world,'' said Mollica, who took
care of his family's Gar Wood on Oneida Lake in New York, beginning
at age 13. ``The firm maintained its standards even in the worst of
times, in the Depression.''
</P>
<P>
   Gar Woods, known as ``the aristocrats of motorboats,'' were
costly. Their buyers included Gordon Hammersley, a New York tobacco
mogul who was the first to name his boat a ``cigarette''; William
Wrigley, John Dodge, William Randolph Hearst and Lord Louis
Mountbatten. Gar Woods will be on parade during Wooden Boat Week in
Tahoe City, Calif., from Thursday through Aug. 17. The Tahoe Yacht
Club, which was founded in 1925, is sponsoring the 28th Concours
d'Elegance, a show of hundreds of antique wooden boats. There will
be boat restoration clinics, boat sales, dinner dances and picnics.
Information: (530) 583-0447.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1880, Garfield Arthur Wood was the third of eight sons
of a ferryboat captain and staunch Iowa Republican. He was named
after a successful Republican presidential ticket, James Garfield
and Chester Arthur. One of 13 children, Wood grew up around boats
and was piloting an early gas engine launch in Duluth, Minn.,
before he was 20.
</P>
<P>
   In 1910, after graduating from the Armour College of Technology
in Chicago, Wood founded his own machine shop in Duluth. In 1911 he
invented the hydraulic lift, automating the dumping of loose
materials from trucks. He received a patent on the system, built a
factory in Detroit and began supplying the lifts to the trucking
industry.
</P>
<P>
   When World War I came, the War Department ordered trucks with
his hoists. He also designed and built furnaces, tank bodies for
trucks, bulldozers, cranes and tractor attachments. Totally
self-made, he amassed $50 million before 1940.
</P>
<P>
   His first love, however, was speedboat racing. In 1914 he
designed Little Leading Lady, a boat that was hauled by horses on a
wooden trailer, and he won every race he entered it in. In 1916 he
bought a majority share in a boatyard in Algonac, Mich., north of
Detroit, owned by Chris Smith, who in 1922 founded Chris Craft
boats. Until 1922, Wood and Smith together built a series of
streamlined and nearly unbeatable boats, which Wood personally
piloted, beginning with the 1917 Gold Cup in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   But style and competitiveness cannot explain all of Wood's
successes. Wood, who went to bed by 10:30 p.m. and rose at 5:30
a.m., was an inveterate inventor. He decided to try airplane motors
in boats. In 1918, he launched the first hydroplane successfully
equipped with an aircraft engine and drove it to win the Thousand
Islands Trophy and the 1918 Gold Cup. After the war, he purchased
4,500 government surplus Liberty aircraft engines and established
the Detroit-Marine-Aero Engine Co. to convert the lightweight
engines to marine use.
</P>
<P>
   By 1920, Wood had piloted the Liberty-powered Miss America to
victory at the World's Speedboat Championship in Cowes on the Isle
of Wight, the One-Mile North American Championship, his fifth
consecutive Gold Cup and the Express Cruiser Championships in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He then challenged the Havana Special, the Miami-to-New York
express train, to a race, and won the 1,260-mile trip in 47 hours
and 23 minutes, beating the train by 21 minutes. The press ate it
up.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, he took on the 20th Century Limited in a race from
Albany to New York City. ``Tens of thousands, perhaps even
millions, who were unable to reach the river were kept in touch
with the progress of the train and the boat by radio,'' Mollica
writes. ``Half a dozen airplanes accompanied the boat, one of them
broadcasting a minute-to-minute account.'' Again he won. He was a
national hero.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, Wood produced longer wooden boats for cruising,
exploring and sport fishing. ``One long, narrow, 70-foot prototype
had five Liberty engines in it,'' Mollica said. ``This was the
precursor of the PT boat.''
</P>
<P>
   In World War II the Gar Wood plants converted to military
production and churned out Navy boats by the hundreds. After the
war, Wood retired; the company closed in 1947. He died in 1970 at
age 90. He had built 3,300 Gar Woods between 1922 and 1947.
</P>
<P>
   James W. Ogilvie-Knowles and Justus Hayes, authors of ``Wood
Through Water: Classic Power Boats'' (Michael Friedman Publishing,
1999), write that there are two kinds of antique wooden-boat owners
today: the generation that grew up with them, for whom maintaining
and operating them is a labor of love, and the younger school, for
whom the woody represents a return to a simpler, more genuine way
of life.
</P>
<P>
   Gar Woods attract both. Not that they are easy to buy. Only
about 500 survive. The Gar Wood Society web site (www.garwood.com)
lists five for sale. There are none from the 1920s, three from the
1930s and two from the 1940s. Each costs $18,000 to $45,000.
``These prices are modest compared to what you will see in Tahoe,''
Mollica said. ``A 28-foot Gar Wood is now $100,000. The 33-footers
are $150,000 to $200,00 _ and you have to beg the owners to sell
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand has increased strikingly. ``Gar Wood design and overall
styling are recognized as the best of their day,'' Mollica said.
``Their materials, ride and performance are superior to all the
boats of their era and equal to or better than many modern craft.
They used real leather in every model as well as furniture-quality
mahogany from Honduras.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tahoe, there is a perfect view of the festivities from a
restaurant in Carnelian Bay on Lake Tahoe. Its name? Gar Woods:
Home of the Wet Woody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
