<HEADER>
A1924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-03 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FINALLY, REALITY BREAKS THROUGH &HT;    By MARIANNE MEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Everyone knew it wouldn't _ couldn't, shouldn't _
last. All that gooey sweetness just wasn't real.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential campaign is meant to be a brutal scrap, not a tea
dance. It's supposed to be about the conflict between deeply held
convictions, not a competition for the best superficial smile.
</P>
<P>
   For the first two days of the Republican National Convention,
party leaders were obsessed with the notion that honey attracts
more flies, or independent voters, than vinegar. But the salad
dressing of power politics benefits from a dash of tart sauce. It's
the American way.
</P>
<P>
   Mama and papa Bush promptly shook off the sugar fix, rising to
provocative bait thrown out by President Clinton and eager to
defend their son against a perceived slur. Actually, all Clinton
did was to say that Texas Gov. George W. Bush's presidential
campaign is just a ``pretty package '' based heavily on the fact
that ``daddy was president.'' A rather modest insult, as insults go
these days, and not all that far from the truth. But the
oversensitive senior Bushes took umbrage at the suggestion that
their boy wasn't a bigtime politician in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   The former Republican president grumped that Clinton was unfair
in that attack and said that ``if he continues that, I'm going to
tell the nation what I think about him as a human being and a
person.'' Actually, the nation already has a good idea of what Bush
thinks of Clinton. He is known to be resentful toward the man who
defeated him in 1992, but never mind. Few losers like their
vanquishers. That's politics.
</P>
<P>
   His wife Barbara, famous for her tart tongue, added her own sour
note by observing that she was ``disappointed'' that the incumbent
she didn't name didn't ``respect'' the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy Bush said later he ``made a mistake''' in letting Clinton
get his goat, acknowledging _ surprise! _ that the race is not a
repeat of his contest with Clinton but a battle between Dubya and
Gore. Yet his son has spent more pre-convention time indirectly but
unmistakably accusing Clinton of lacking honor and integrity than
pointing out his policy differences with Gore, which are many and
are supposed to be what the campaign is all about.
</P>
<P>
   After he selected former Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney as his
running mate, Dubya praised Cheney as knowing ``what the meaning of
is, is,'' a clear reference to one of Clinton's most famous
legalistic dodges in denying under oath his dalliance with Monica
Lewinsky. Bush even admitted that the jab was aimed right at
Clinton and wasn't just another one of those generalized laments
about declining moral standards in the White House that are so
popular at his convention. This rare burst of candor, however, came
in the face of the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with honeyed tones is that they can turn anything
into glop. There was Elizabeth Dole, for instance, telling
convention delegates that Bush will end ``the smashmouth politics
of recent years.'' Such sneak attacks on Clinton's combativeness
are not very satisfying. They are too inclusive, to use a favorite
convention word. Whose smashmouth politics, please? We are tempted
to think of a long list here, including those of many Republicans,
including the Bush operatives who ran mean and misleading
commercials during the New York primary that nastily, and
inaccurately, called Sen. John McCain heartless toward breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The convention delegates, however, love all the cute comments
about bringing decency back to the presidency. They go wild when
that happens. They know what it's all about. They came here to be
entertained, not uplifted. The Republicans have been dying to kick
out Clinton for more than seven years, even trying to get around
the election returns with an unpopular crusade to impeach him. To
that end, they will put up with a little subtlety if Bush insists,
but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   They'd like it even better if the Bush team simply came right
out and uttered the words ``Monica'' or ``impeachment.'' What fun.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the convention hall, out in the country where the
voters are, the strange idea is taking hold that Gore is the
opponent, not Clinton. After the Democrats make Gore's nomination
official, the truth of the matter will become inescapable. And
whatever his political failings, Gore is no Clinton. His personal
rectitude, like his intelligence, is not in doubt. Bush's chief
strategist, Karl Rove, asked his goal for Bush in the coming formal
debates with the more experienced Gore, snapped: ``survive.'''
</P>
<P>
   To get around Gore's seriousness, the Republicans are determined
to bind the vice president to the president with industrial-grade
duct tape. The message is that the two are twinned forever.
``Somehow we will never see one without thinking of the other,''
Cheney said in a forceful acceptance speech Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He skipped the treacle and gave the crowd the tough talk it
wanted. He may be an indifferent campaigner, but he can sure rise
to the occasion. ``We are all a little weary of the Clinton-Gore
routine,'' he thundered. ``It is time for them to go.'' The line
galvanized the convention crowd much the way a similar exhortation
must have aroused Oliver Cromwell's supporters as he led the
winning struggle against England's weak King Charles I in the 17th
century. ``You have stayed long enough ... to do any good any
longer. In the name of God, you should go,'' Cromwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful stuff, then as now. Very good for an introductory
performance. But much depends on whether the Republican vinegar
runs out before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
