<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-POLITICS-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL CRITICS SILENCED IN WAR ON FUNDAMENTALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Ali Salem recently wrote the script for an
unfinished 10-minute public service announcement that encourages
his fellow Egyptians to shed their cynicism and vote in elections.
</P>
<P>
   The state now says that makes him a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Salem, a big, rumpled, chain-smoking, 64-year-old satirist who
has 25 plays and 15 books to his name, was charged July 22 with
threatening national security and harming the national interest.
After handing over his identity card and being released on his own
recognizance, he still could not believe it. ``It's the first time
I've ever heard my name used in this way,'' Salem said, sipping
strong coffee in the hotel cafe where he holds court with his
artist and actor friends each day. ``Not the Egyptian Ali Salem,
not the playwright Ali Salem, not the columnist Ali Salem. But the
accused Ali Salem.''
</P>
<P>
   In a country that has criminalized many forms of political
criticism and debate, that sobriquet puts him in the company of
Islamic militants, journalists, union officials, human rights
activists and academics who have offended the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt boasts of having a constitution and democratic
accouterments like courts, elections, a lively private business
sector and a Parliament. Even its internal critics acknowledge that
it is more free, and more mindful of its own laws than most of its
neighbors in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last five years, the government of President Hosni
Mubarak has also frozen the funds of nearly every professional
union and trade organization in the country. It has rejected all
petitions for new political parties. It has ignored appeals to end
the 19-year state of emergency, which permits the authorities to
restrict political activity and send adversaries to jail with no
right of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mubarak won re-election in a yes-or-no referendum last
fall with more than 94 percent of the vote, his government has
stepped up its campaign. It jailed human rights activists last
winter when their reports on Muslim-Christian violence were deemed
to threaten national security, and it has continued to jail writers
when their articles are found insulting to Egyptian institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In June, it closed down a research institute, the Ibn Khaldoun
Center, which was producing Salem's get-out-the-vote film as well
as a conference on minority rights in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Saad Eddin Ibrahim, a sociologist who directed the center and
holds a U.S. passport, has been held without charge in Tora Prison
outside Cairo since June 30. His detention has spurred protests
from human rights groups around the world as well as the Middle
East Studies Association of North America and the U.S. Embassy in
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, a State Security Court judge extended his
detention for another 15 days. Ibrahim's lawyers have said he is
being accused of inciting sectarian strife through his seminars on
religious relations and defaming Egypt by mentioning public apathy
and past election fraud in the aborted film written by Salem about
voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has called on Egypt to clarify the accusations
against Ibrahim or release him.
</P>
<P>
   Many people active in public life in Cairo said that the
offensive against the Ibn Khaldoun Center, and now Salem, is the
latest example of how the Mubarak government's 10-year-long war on
Islamic fundamentalists has eroded political life, making
casualties of all independent political voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a kind of political stability, and we don't have the
luxury of miscalculations,'' said Wahid Abdel Maguid, a political
analyst with the governmental Al Ahram Center for Political and
Strategic Studies, who believes the limits on opposition political
activity are justified by a continuing threat from Islamists. ``We
have undemocratic forces here that are more undemocratic than the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other governments in the region, the Egyptian government
faced an insurgency by fundamentalists beginning in the early
1990s. It began by imprisoning thousands of suspected militants and
then turned its attention in the mid-1990s to trade unions it saw
as infiltrated by fundamentalist groups like the Muslim
Brotherhood. Hundreds of leaders of the Brotherhood and various
unions were tried in military courts and jailed. A third wave of
arrests _ some 1,300 people so far this year, by Brotherhood
estimates _ is now under way.
</P>
<P>
   Now the government is delaying scheduled union elections,
effectively maintaining its freeze on associations that once were a
forum for political activity. The Lawyers' Syndicate, for example,
which represents nearly 300,000 attorneys, has had its elections
postponed, prompting some lawyers to call for nationwide strikes
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want no headaches, and every election brings with it a
competition,'' said Essam Elerian, a Brotherhood activist in the
nearly defunct doctors' syndicate who just completed a jail term
after being arrested in an earlier crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   To control charitable and nongovernmental organizations that
could be used by fundamentalists, Mubarak also last year pushed
through Parliament a law requiring each group to submit its board
members' names and their funding sources to the government for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups, which are almost all organized as
nongovernmental organizations, vowed to ignore the new law, which
they said was an attempt by the government to censor and silence
them. The law was recently declared invalid by the Constitutional
Court on the technical grounds that it had not been submitted to
the proper legislative bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people didn't pay attention because they said the
government was only fighting fundamentalists, but that's not
true,'' said Abou Elela Mady Abou Elela, a former Muslim
Brotherhood official. ``Only now are others in civil society
realizing how dangerous what the government is doing can be. It's
only because of what happened to Saad Eddin Ibrahim.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Abou Elela, who has twice had his petition to form a new
political party rejected by Mubarak's government, said he is not
surprised that, as he put it, ``finally one liberal'' has run afoul
of the regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He crossed the lines,'' he said of Ibrahim. ``He started
dealing with sensitive issues like religious minorities, democracy
and elections. The government goes wild over these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In a message sent from prison and released by his wife, Ibrahim
said he is being detained because he planned to set up a monitoring
group to observe the upcoming elections for the 444-seat
Parliament. ``Certain forces,'' he said, ``are hoping to rig
elections again in peace and quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling National Democratic Party now controls 97 percent of
the seats, a dominance that it has maintained for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is using Saad as a bogeyman to scare him and
other organizations from intervening in the coming elections,''
said Tahseen Bashir, a former Egyptian diplomat and spokesman for
Mubarak's predecessor, Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   But the battle to suppress Muslim fundamentalists, he added,
does not justify a scattershot crackdown on anyone who brings up
potentially contentious social issues or tries to create political
parties to challenge Mubarak's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not calling for chaos, but I'm calling for studied steps
for change,'' Bashir said. ``Too much stability is deadness, a
paralysis of the political system.''
</P>
<P>
   No member of the government would comment on Ibrahim's case, and
prosecutors have not said they are investigating his
vote-monitoring project. They have, however, summarily closed down
a group related to the Ibn Khaldoun Center that was devoted to
encouraging women's participation in elections, and indicated that
the short film was the trigger for their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay that Salem wrote for the film focuses on an
Egyptian couple who reflect on how they can best assure themselves
a bright future. In one scene, a group of men are sitting in a
coffee shop in Cairo complaining. One says there is no good health
care. Another says the education system is bad. Another grouses
that there is no national dream.
</P>
<P>
   The couple ends up scolding them. ``You can become a partner in
the future by participating in elections,'' they say.
</P>
<P>
   Salem said he tried in vain to explain to the prosecutors that
the coffee shop complaints were a dramatic device to set up the
theme of the film, which was meant show that Egyptians should vote
rather than just gripe to assure themselves a good future.
</P>
<P>
   But the government interrogators, he said, just kept asking him
why he wrote all those bad things about Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``To explain a joke is a miserable job,'' Salem lamented, adding
that it reminded him of another joke from the 1960s, when President
Gamal Abdel Nasser was in power and suppressed political debate.
</P>
<P>
   In the joke, a man is arrested by the police for carrying a bag
of blank papers. When he asks the police why, they reply: ``Do you
think we should wait until you write something bad on them?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
