<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      08-03 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURRELLS FOR NATIONAL GALLERY; KOONS FOR THE WWW; BOLTONSKI FOR
BOSTON; A MERGER FOR MODERN CLASSICS AND A HOTELIER FOR
CHRISTIE'S 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To beef up its contemporary-art holdings, the National Gallery
of Art in Washington has acquired four early works by the
installation artist James Turrell. After hearing of the purchase,
Turrell said he would give the gallery a fifth work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is certainly an artist whose work belongs in any museum,''
said Earl A. Powell III, the gallery's director. ``We're beginning
to focus on areas like minimalism. We had no installation pieces in
our collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The four projection pieces, bought with the help of the Brown
Foundation in Houston, represent Turrell's early classic work from
the 1960s. ``Royce'' and ``Artar'' are single-wall projections, in
which pure shapes are created with white light from a single
projector. ``Amba'' and ``Orca,'' two-projector end-wall pieces,
are among the first of many works by the artist that fill an entire
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Weiss, head of the department of contemporary art, said
the donated work would either be an existing piece or a new one
created specifically for the gallery from his ``Space Division''
series. In this series the artist divides a single room into two
sections with separate lighting and an aperture in the dividing
wall. The viewer stands in one space looking through the opening
into another.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the early works we've acquired are all black-and-white,
the `Space Division' series is all in color,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery has not decided exactly when the Turrells will go on
view, said Weiss, who is aiming for 2002. They are to be installed
in the East Building, home to the gallery's collection of
20th-century art since it opened in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   NEW MARKET FOR KOONS
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Koons has always gone for mass appeal. Every day this
summer, hundreds of people have been paying homage to ``Puppy,''
the 43-foot-tall flower-covered topiary in the form of a West
Highland terrier prominently displayed at Rockefeller Center.
``Split Rocker,'' a 40-foot tall topiary shaped like a rocking toy
in the form of a half pony, half dinosaur, has been on view in the
Benoit XII Cloister in the Papal Palace in Avignon, France.
</P>
<P>
   In the same spirit of accessibility, Koons has signed a contract
with eyestorm.com to sell photographic prints in editions of 1,000
of three of his 1999 paintings: ``Hair,'' ``Cut Out'' and
``Loopy.'' They will cost $500 each and be available at the end of
the month.
</P>
<P>
   Koons was traveling and could not be reached for comment, but
Elizabeth Markevitch, the Internet company's vice president for
content, said the prints ``will give the public the chance to own a
Koons for $500.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not targeting art-market people,'' she added, ``but
rather consumers who find the art world intimidating or
inaccessible.''
</P>
<P>
   A BOLTANSKI FOR BOSTON
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery isn't the only encyclopedic museum finally
paying attention to installation art. The Museum of Fine Arts in
Boston commissioned the French Conceptual artist Christian
Boltanski to design a site-specific installation. It will be on
view from Wednesday through Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The work is meant to complement another show, ``Charlotte
Salomon: Life? Or Theater?'' which also opens on Wednesday; it runs
through Oct. 29. Salomon, a Berlin-born artist, created a
semi-autobiographical series of colorful gouaches before she died
in Auschwitz at 26. Organized by the Royal Academy in London, the
show was first exhibited in Amsterdam in 1961 and has been seen in
Germany, France, Japan and England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having both works creates a great dialogue,'' said Cheryl
Brutvan, curator of contemporary art at the Museum of Fine Arts.
``Both consider issues like memory in a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   Boltanski said he had agreed to make a site-specific piece for
the museum because he admired Salomon's work and thought he could
create a good complement to it. His work uses archival photographs
of crimes from 14-year-old newspaper clippings because, he said, he
liked the images. Half the photographs show criminals, and half
show victims. They are illuminated on white fabric placed in the
middle of a gallery. Black mirrors frame the walls of the space.
``It's about memory and faces and the issue of being guilty and not
guilty,'' Boltanski said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has other installation works on its schedule,
including one by John Borofsky, most recently known for his
large-scale sculptures, opening in the fall, and another by Sara
Sze, the Manhattan-based installation artist, planned for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   A LONDON-U.S. MERGER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Artemis Fine Arts, the London gallery that specializes in old
master and 19th-century paintings, is joining forces with Lawrence
Greenberg van Doren, which has galleries in New York and St. Louis
showing a mixture of modern masters and emerging artists. The joint
venture, to be called Artemis Greenberg van Doren, will focus
mainly on modern American classic painters like Sam Francis, Yves
Klein and Andy Warhol. ``Everyone can benefit from this,'' said
Timothy Bathurst, a director of Artemis. ``It gives us a broader
outreach and we're keen on the American market. We do a lot of
business here.''
</P>
<P>
   HOTELIER TO THE RESCUE
</P>
<P>
   With news that Christie's is contemplating building a hotel on
the block it owns in St. James', London, it may be fitting that the
French-owned auction house has appointed an international chief
operating officer with a background in hotel management.
Jean-Claude Noel, 53, has worked at both Hilton International and
TNT Post Group, a $9 billion leader in mail, communications and
logistics. He will be based in New York, supervising the standard
of client services and operational procedures for Christie's
offices worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
