<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1939 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-EMINEM04-COX     08-03 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMINEM04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Children of the '60s and '70s who vowed never to censor their
kids' music now face the next shock wave
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eminem has ruled the charts this summer with his catchy,
melt-in-your-mouth raps _ about getting high, killing his enemies
and sleeping with his mother. His popularity with young fans has
left some parents with a messy _ and acutely familiar _ problem on
their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Brenda Moseley.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem suddenly appeared on Moseley's radar screen when she was
getting ready for work on Monday, listening to a local radio
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The station was bleeping out the words. You couldn't hear what
he was saying, but you knew exactly what he meant,'' said Moseley,
of Ellenwood. ``I don't object to rap music, I like some of it. But
I don't want my kids listening to suggestive lyrics like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the 39-year-old mother of two had heard
``The Real Slim Shady,'' a comedic, catchy tune laced with
profanity that has been a fixture on the R&AMP;B and hip-hop charts for
two months.
</P>
<P>
   Most tracks on Eminem's latest album, ``The Marshall Mathers
LP,'' are too raunchy or violent for radio airplay. The Eminem song
Moseley heard was a ``clean version,'' with the most offensive
lyrics omitted.
</P>
<P>
   The Eminem incident conjured up a teenage memory for Moseley:
She once conned her religious mother into letting her attend a
concert at the Omni by claiming the rock band Aerosmith was a
contemporary Christian group.
</P>
<P>
   Now Moseley knows what it's like on the other side of the
musical generation gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid listening to Bobby Sherman or the Osmonds, I
wasn't paying attention to the words much,'' Moseley said. ``Now
kids are inundated with words and sexual content that is
influencing them. You can see and hear how much things have
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, things have changed. Jim Morrison's ``The End''
included a line about Oedipal sex 30 years ago, but in a punk- and
rap-influenced pop world, such psychedelic Doors songs sound almost
quaint. And in that world, Eminem stands out as someone who doesn't
just push the envelope of good taste, but folds, spindles and
mutilates it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been fighting over music across the generations since
the beginning of time,'' says Jaye Shaner, a professor at Georgia
State University who specializes in intergenerational
communication. ``But there has been a trend in recent years where
groups are being more explicit in their lyrics. Nothing is left to
the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents trying to censor, or at least monitor, their children's
musical tastes are also fighting on a broader battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem has a top-selling CD in record stores, his hardcore
lyrics are widely available on the Internet, his sanitized singles
are played frequently on radio, he's a darling of cable's MTV. This
at a time when, thanks to tamer videos on Disney, CDs at McDonald's
and the like, younger kids are being introduced to popular music.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta fans get Eminem close-up, personal and uncensored
tonight. Teaming up with his gangsta mentor Dr. Dre, the rapper is
in the midst of a successful, multi-city ``Up In Smoke'' concert
tour, which plays Lakewood Amphitheater at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Along with fellow rappers Snoop Dogg, Nate Dogg and Xzibit,
Eminem is expected to perform hit songs, some of which praise
violence and drug use, and which have been criticized for promoting
hateful attitudes towards gays and women.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem's ability to express adolescent confusion and rage is
part of his appeal, especially to younger fans. It's also what
makes him so disturbing to some adults.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the late comedian Andy Kaufman, Eminem goads audiences
into loving and loathing him at the same time, pushing them to
examine their own hypocrisy and prejudice. Or not.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Wyman, a cultural critic for the online magazine Salon,
says that subtle message is often lost on younger listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unquestionably a serious and smart artist,'' Wyman says
of Eminem. ``But I think his lyrics are the most hellaciously cruel
and hateful that we've ever heard. I think it's bad art that hurts
kids.'' Chervon Pannell, 15, of Lithonia is a big Eminem fan, and
will be at his concert tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best rapper out there right now, because he's had a
messed up life, and he's so creative the way he talks about it,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   So Chervon's mother, Cassandra Pannell, 39, pays close attention
to the songs playing on her daughters' radio.
</P>
<P>
   A native of the South Bronx, where rap was spawned, Pannell is
no stranger to slang words, such as ``bitch'' and ``ho,'' that some
rap and pop artists use to describe women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're going to hear these words,'' Pannell says.
``But I also ask them what kind of boy would call them that, and
why would they want to date somebody who thinks of them that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pannell is also a veteran of the generational music wars. As a
teenager, one of her favorite songs was ``Pillow Talk'' by Sylvia,
a breathy ballad in which the singer moaned and groaned as if
having sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother was like to have a stroke when she found out I
was listening to that,'' Pannell remembers. ``But when my mother
came home she was more open about it, and she talked to me. I
always said I was going to be the same way with my kids. I want to
keep things open with them, even if I'm shocked by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Barringer of Dunwoody wasn't shocked to find out that he
had an Eminem fan in his household, but he was surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Barringer, a 64-year-old retiree, is a loyal and longtime fan of
Little Richard and the Rolling Stones, performers whose lyrics and
performances once outraged grownups.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent shopping trip to Northlake Mall with his
10-year-old son, Jackson, Barringer was asked about Eminem.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean the candy?'' he asked, looking puzzled. After
learning the difference between M&AMP;M's and Eminem, Barringer said,
``Nope. My son likes 'NSync. He doesn't listen to rap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do,'' Jackson blurted out. ``I like 'NSync, but I like
Eminem too, even though he curses on his records sometimes, and I
don't think that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Before heading home, Barringer exacted a promise from his son
not to listen to Eminem any more _ on the radio or anywhere else.
Jackson, a mini- Eminem look-alike with a pug nose and naturally
platinum-blonde hair, sheepishly agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't watch MTV, and I thought I new the knew most of the
artists he listened to,'' said the older Barringer. ``I guess I'm
going to have to start paying more attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Moseley of Ellenwood, said it's critical for parents to stay
tuned in to the soundtrack of their children's lives. Even if you
don't share their tastes, it's important to share your values.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing ``Slim Shady'' on the radio, Moseley told her
daughter Elizabeth she didn't approve of the bad-boy rapper's
lyrics. Counter to teen stereotypes, the 14-year-old didn't argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my mother I agree with her,'' Elizabeth says. ``When it
comes on the radio I change the station, especially if my little
brother is around.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
