<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1940 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-FEAROFFLYING-CURE04-C     08-03 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEAROFFLYING-CURE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virtual reality helps vanquish fear of flying
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only last year, Shannon Orr feared flying ``more than dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she's a pilot, who soloed for the first time last week.
</P>
<P>
   Orr mastered her flight phobia, which is shared by millions of
Americans, by confronting her fears as part of a joint study by
Georgia Tech and Emory University. At the Tech campus offices of
Virtually Better, a virtual-reality start-up partly financed by the
universities, Orr sat through four sessions in a Darth Vader-like
mask and a ``Thunderseat,'' both hooked to a computer loaded with
flight-simulating software.
</P>
<P>
   The setup works like this: Look to the left and you see the
tarmac out the window. Look up and see buttons that control lights
and air, down at your hands and knees _ even rumpled newspapers in
empty seats. Then the flight attendant comes on, reminding you to
buckle up. In an instant, the plane hurtles down a virtual runway _
you hear the noise and feel the vibrations _ and you're airborne,
zooming over a virtual Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A therapist sits nearby, asking how you're feeling and trying to
soothe frayed nerves. If you're doing OK, he'll turn on the
turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really brought out the anxieties,'' says Orr, a 38-year-old
technical writer. ``After a few sessions, I was noticing a great
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   So were most of the others in the study, results of which were
released today.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our research shows is, it works,'' says Barbara Rothbaum,
director of Emory's Trauma and Anxiety Recovery Program. ``Ninety
percent of those in the study have reported flying voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure why so many people are petrified of
airplanes. Many terrified fliers say that fear of crashing is their
biggest concern, even though they may not worry about getting
behind the wheel of a car, which is much more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally irrational,'' says Ken Graap, president of
Virtually Better. ``If you had to fly every day of your life,
probabilities indicate it would take you 26,000 years before you
would succumb to a fatal airplane accident. The odds of being hit
by lightning are five times greater than dying in a plane crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr's phobia began on a return flight to Atlanta years ago. The
weather was bad, and the plane had to circle. She became
disoriented and had a strong feeling that ``something could go
wrong. I didn't know what was going on, so I got scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Scared enough to keep her off of airplanes for years. Until
recently, she says, she ``wouldn't have taken a free trip to Hawaii
with a hotel thrown in.''
</P>
<P>
   But now she'll fly anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Tech-Emory study didn't place phobic fliers in virtual
planes right away. In their first four sessions, subjects were
taught stress-reducing breathing techniques and
``thought-blocking,'' which helps them think of something besides
their fears. Then, during four more sessions, they ``took off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The therapy just has to be real enough to feel something like
the real experience,'' says Samantha Smith, a researcher involved
in the study. ``The images don't look real, but for some reason,
after a while they feel real, which is why it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Simah Benyamin, 55, a flight-phobic who works in an office near
Virtually Better, volunteered to demonstrate the therapy last week.
The simulated air journey made her knuckles turn white.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little scary,'' she said. ``But it was a lot better
than my last real flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Some psychologists use another type of exposure therapy _ taking
patients on real airplanes. The Tech-Emory study found that that
approach worked about as well as the virtual-reality therapy, but
it is much more costly and time-consuming. Therapists can buy
Virtually Better's system for $5,000 plus $400 per month; insurance
often covers the cost for patients.
</P>
<P>
   Other traditional remedies involve drugs. Many phobics resort to
alcohol or tranquilizers, neither of which is a good solution,
Rothbaum says. ``If you're sloshed at a business meeting, you're
not going to be effective. And tranquilizers can become addicting.
``We want to help people confront and conquer their fears,'' she
declares, ``not medicate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Her fears conquered, Orr can't wait until her next solo flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken an incredible leap,'' she says. ``Some anxiety is
still there, but that's good. It helps you concentrate. And it's
really neat up there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: Virtually Better: www.virtuallybetter.com
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
