<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The wave of economic reforms that has
washed over Latin America first touched shore in Chile. That small
nation, with an economy roughly the size of New Jersey's, was the
first to tear down import barriers, liberalize exchange-rate
policy, bolster the domestic savings rate and otherwise whip itself
into shape for the new global economy. Now it wants to go further.
By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   STRATEGIES-COLUMN (Undated) _ One the investment world's great
unsolved mysteries has been why the dividend yield model stopped
working about a decade ago. This model, based on stocks'
dividend-to-price ratios, used to be one of Wall Street's
most-respected valuation models. Not any more. Today's investors,
who are fixated on making a quick buck, are likely to wonder how
anyone could ever have been interested in something so obviously
irrelevant as dividends. By Mark Hulbert.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Books aimed at the growing, and
increasingly affluent, senior market are steadily filling bookstore
shelves around the country. By Fed Brock.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY&AMP;MEDICINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ It is a familiar sequence of
events to anyone who has spent much time in a doctor's office. You
have blood taken, you call for the results, you get on with your
life _ and then weeks, months or even years later, you receive a
bill from the laboratory or explanation-of-benefits letter from
your insurance company. These missives can be maddening. By
Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUTCARS-MERCEDES (Undated) _ The Mercedes-Benz brochure of the
1980s described the marque's philosophy thus: A Mercedes should not
inspire aggressive driving, but if you find yourself in a bind _
say, roaring into a tight turn too fast _ the car will get you
through. That, at least, was the gist. The Mercedes was an
automotive Clark Kent, serious and sedate, but ready to fling off
its eyeglasses and soar to the rescue. There is nothing
mild-mannered about the Mercedes-Benz of today. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   CARSMART-MERCEDES-ARMOR (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ James Barron
takes a ride in the armored Mercedes S-Class sedan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
