<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAPANESE-RENAISSANCE-     08-03 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPANESE-RENAISSANCE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MANY-SPLENDORED MINIMALIST BRUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Japan)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As far as I'm concerned, it can't be demonstrated too often that
the aesthetic principles considered basic to modernism are neither
very recent nor especially Western. It's as comforting as it is
humbling, the idea that the 20th century didn't create modernism
from scratch, that it's not a relatively local, possibly exhausted
aberration whose death one may celebrate or mourn. Whatever it is,
the desire for simplicity, directness and abstraction is part of
our very humanity and repeatedly finds expression.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of what might be called the eternal modern can be
felt in certain great examples of African, Egyptian and early Greek
art and different kinds of Asian art. Right now this presence
hovers like a beautiful mist over ``The Arts of Honami Koetsu,
Japanese Renaissance Master'' at the Philadelphia Museum of Art, a
small miracle of an exhibition that pays homage to a late
16th-century artist who has become known to scholars and admirers
as ``the Leonardo da Vinci of Japanese art.''
</P>
<P>
   Containing 70 works in calligraphy, lacquer and ceramics, this
is the first show in the West devoted to Koetsu, who was born in
1558 and died in 1637. It comes with a sensitive installation, a
catalog detailing his achievement as never before and rarely lent
work from Japanese museums, several important cultural properties
among them. It is spread throughout three smallish galleries, where
the low light levels required by its fragile works create an almost
magical sense of time travel. (Fragility also dictates that nearly
two-thirds of the show will be rotated starting on September 19.)
</P>
<P>
   Like Leonardo, Koetsu was a polymath: versatile, erudite,
technically adept and lastingly influential. As Leonardo was
respected for his unparalleled draftsmanship, Koetsu was revered
for his calligraphy, which he mastered in several styles, both
Chinese and Japanese. The show's spine is a progression of
calligraphic works, that range from early letters and a list of
master swordsmiths _ Koetsu came from a family of prominent sword
connoisseurs in Kyoto _ to Buddhist texts made at the end of his
life, when he retreated with family and friends to Takagamine, a
small village north of Kyoto built on land ceded to him by the
shogun Tokugawa Ieyasu in 1615.
</P>
<P>
   The show's ethereal ambience is set by several examples of the
works that Koetsu is perhaps most famous for, the poem scrolls and
little poem cards on which he collaborated with the painter
Tawaraya Sotatsu (who died circa 1640), sprinkling his flowing
calligraphy over Sotatsu's equally effortless abbreviations of
natural motifs _ a mountain slope, a stand of pines, a pair of
deer, drifting chrysanthemums, clustered bellflowers or cherry
blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   The opening work is one half of a double six-fold seasonal
screen interesting not so much for its lovely garden image, which
was painted in the late 1600s in the manner of Sotatsu, but for the
small square poem cards that are thought to be Sotatsu's and
Koetsu's first collaboration. They punctuate the surface of the
image like a series of elegant thought balloons or close-up views
of nature's calendar. These complex little addenda of script and
image (the labels translate) in particular attune the viewer to the
exquisitely nuanced responses to nature that lie at the core of
Japanese art.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, the show's first gallery includes later, more dynamic
poem-card collaborations between Koetsu and Sotatsus, mounted on
hanging scrolls or displayed in albums, that are astounding for
their off-hand power and varieties of pictorial space and scale. In
these seemingly minimal works Koetsu's calligraphy hovers above
landscapes, floats beneath waves that dance with the reflections of
trees or dangle among peach blossoms like tendrils of vine or moss.
Here, the viewer can acquire an instant initiation into the
splendors of calligraphy, up close and personal.
</P>
<P>
   Also like Leonardo, Koetsu's achievement can have an elusive
quicksilver quality, and his legacy of ideas, taste and design may
be almost as important as anything he actually touched. An
inveterate collaborator, and one suspects, something of a
charismatic, he is also sometimes called the world's first ``art
director.'' For example, it is thought that he never actually
worked in lacquer, but excelled at its design and is responsible
for the introduction of base metals, which set up a rich contrast
with the more traditional silver and gold, as exemplified by the
small writing box that features a reed boat in lead inlay in this
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Koetsu's multifaceted career thrived during the brief, brilliant
Momoyama period (1573-1615) that served as the glittering hinge
between medieval and early modern Japan. This four-decade cultural
renaissance ensued when the country was finally united under the
authority of the successive warlords Nobunaga, Hideyoshi and
Tokugawa after more than 100 years of civil disorder, violence and
social fragmentation.
</P>
<P>
   It was an age of building, recovery and revival, extensive
cultural patronage and competitive displays of ostentation. All the
arts seem to have been called up for active duty. The castles being
erected at a rather frantic pace in and around Kyoto required
lavish furnishings and decorations, especially painted screens and
panels, and the more gold leaf the better.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the mercantile elite of Kyoto, Koetsu was both
connected to artists and artisans of all kinds and trained in a
discipline, sword connoisseurship, that involved the appraisal of a
series of skills, effects and materials, both decorative and
practical. For starters, swords and their sheaths involved fine
forging, metalwork and lacquer. Even sword polishing, which was
Koetsu's specialty until his late '40s, was close to an artform.
</P>
<P>
   But Koetsu had several pans on the fire. Koetsu was a respected
practitioner of the tea ceremony, gatherings for which served as
artistic and literary salons in Momoyama Kyoto. He figured in the
upsurge in book publishing that began in the late 16th century,
working with a Kyoto-based publisher to produce high-quality
editions of literature. (His calligraphy served as a model for the
design of the woodblock typeface that made these books possible.)
He was especially familiar with the aristocratic traditions of the
Heian period (794-1185), Japan's first golden age, which saw the
founding of its calligraphy and literature and which exerted a
refining influence over the frequent exuberance of Momoyama.
</P>
<P>
   He became both a connoisseur and master of calligraphy, possibly
studying in his late 30s under Prince Soncho, less for the latter's
calligraphic talents than his hereditary position as abbot of the
Shoren-in monastery, an important repository of ancient Chinese and
Japanese calligraphy. Although records are sketchy, he was involved
enough with the production of lacquers, whether as a designer,
advisor or influence, that the phrase ``Koetsu lacquerware''
continues to connote a certain boldness of shape and surface
decoration.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at Takagamine, where he spent more and more time after
1615, he devoted himself seriously to raku ceramics, then a
relatively new form. (It had emerged in late 1570s, when Sen no
Rikyu, the period's most influential tea ceremony master _ and thus
an important arbiter of taste _ asked Chojiro, a maker of
exceptionally handsome roof tiles, to adapt his techniques to the
making of tea bowls.)
</P>
<P>
   An unusual combination of hands-on technique and aestheticism
came together in Koetsu, and it's reflected in this show, which is
noticeably low on the technical fireworks and dazzling material
display that was so central to the Momoyama period. Koetsu's art
exemplifies some of the most essential elements of the Japanese
sensibility, including its signal indifference to the distinction
between art and craft, or the migration of similar motifs from one
medium to another. Deer graze among the calligraphy in Koetsu and
Sotatsu's famous ``Deer Scroll'' and also along the slender
cylinder of a lacquer flute case. A rabbit, thought to have been
drawn by Koetsu, appears on a fan and also hides among the grasses
on a little salmon-colored incense container.
</P>
<P>
   But he also exemplifies what might be called the ``other''
Momoyama, which adhered more closely to the often rarefied ideals
of the Heian period. Gold as used here is just one of several
almost always transparent tones. The main metallic glow comes from
the covers and pages of the printed books he was involved with, for
example, Noh libretti decorated with faint natural motifs and
patterns in mica, a Heian invention, that are most visible from a
raking angle.
</P>
<P>
   Koetsu's achievement may have been to renew Heian
otherworldliness by bringing it down to earth, giving it an
understated but undeniable directness of touch. We do not gasp at
the technical prowess of these works and wonder how they were made.
Their making is always visible, in fact it is the heart of the
work: we can see the quick unlabored strokes of the brush, the flow
of ink and paint, the natural give and take between language and
form with their unending spatial interactions.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the tactility and intimacy of Koetsu's art,
this exhibition includes two of the most ingenious uses of
interactive computers yet to worm their way into an art museum.
These enable the viewer to virtually hold and manipulate a digital
facsimile of the ``Crane Scroll,'' Koetsu's most famous
collaboration with Sotatsu (which will be part of the September
rotation) , and his black and rust raku ``Shichiri (Seven
Leagues)'' tea bowl, feeling the textures and asymmetries of its
surface while observing the pictorial subtleties of its glaze on a
small screen.
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the 20 raku tea bowls attributed to Koetsu _ including
the ``Shichiri'' _ conclude the exhibition, some with the more
traditional rounded hip, others with the squarish one that he
originated. Each has a shape and surface that is completely its own
and, like so much else here, looks as if it were made yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
