<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOME-DETENTION-2TAKES     08-03 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-DETENTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT ON BAIL, MOB SUSPECTS FIND THEY CAN'T REALLY LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The leak in the ceiling had been there for weeks, a
nasty bruise of moldy plaster and peeling paint. Though Anthony
Spero had been trying his best to get a handyman in, there wasn't a
guy in all of Staten Island who would take the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to come out here,'' Spero, the reputed
consigliere, or counselor, of the Bonanno crime family said the
other day as he glared at the ugly water stain. ``They gotta give
their Social Security number, their date of birth and go through a
background check. No repair guy I know is gonna want to go through
that.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the domestic troubles of ``wise guys'' subjected to a
new and remarkably restrictive form of house arrest. In the last
two years, a handful of men accused of mob-related crimes have been
freed on bail before their trials and forced to live with tapped
phone lines, draconian visiting rights and round-the-clock
surveillance as their private castles are turned into virtual
jails.
</P>
<P>
   Though only a small number of people have borne the kind-of-in,
kind-of-out existence that characterizes the home-as-jail, a
judicial order issued in a Brooklyn court in June has made it
tougher for mob defendants to be freed on bail, meaning that those
who are released are more likely to wind up shuttered inside their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The cases have piqued the interest of prosecutors and defense
lawyers, who naturally disagree on whether releasing a defendant
from custody on the condition he convert his house into Sing Sing
is fair and safe. And given that the defendants themselves must
foot the bill for the harsh security measures, questions have also
arisen about whether it is only the richest suspects who can pay
the price of freedom by creating a prison atmosphere at home.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has fought these so-called super-bail
packages every time they have been offered. To let a suspected
gangster out of custody before his trial, they say, is to invite
jury tampering, witness intimidation _ or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``At bottom, these packages have an element of trust built into
them because the guards can't watch these guys 24-7,'' said one law
enforcement official who spoke on the condition that his name not
be used. ``And if they're not watched round-the-clock, there's
always the potential that they'll call their associates and
continue committing crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers, on the other hand, repudiate the notion that a
man locked up inside his house with his phone lines tapped, his
friends kept away and his movements watched by federal agents could
manage to slip an illegal message to a crony or carry on with a
criminal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bail system itself has an element of trust built into
it,'' said Gerald L. Shargel, Spero's lawyer, who is widely
credited with devising the home-as-jail. ``Unless you put someone
in a dungeon and chain them to a wall and put tape around their
mouths, there's always the possibility of some kind of
communication being sent.''
</P>
<P>
   Spero, 70, is to go on trial in September on charges that he
ordered the deaths of four men while running what the government
has called a particularly vicious Bonanno family crew. He posted
$13.5 million in bail in May 1999 and for more than a year has been
awaiting his day in court inside his pleasant house on Edgegrove
Avenue with its airy parlor and cream-colored sofa set.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange life, waking up in your own bedroom every morning
but feeling as though you were still in jail, he said one afternoon
last week. After all, videocameras are trained on every window and
door. Armed guards must be present when his daughter stops by.
There is a lovely pool in his small backyard, but he cannot use it.
The electronic bracelet he wears beneath a tube sock on his ankle
must not be submerged or removed.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the family complications, mainly revolving around
his live-in companion and her 26-year-old daughter, who also lives
in the house but cannot have boyfriends over or talk on the
telephone without sharing her innermost thoughts with the FBI. And,
of course, there are the challenges of living in such close
quarters with the private security guards who must accompany every
guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cook for the guards all the time,'' said Spero's companion,
who asked that her name be withheld. ``One of them even gave me a
great recipe for stuffed escarole the other day,'' she said, over a
lunch of cheese cubes and turkey wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's all that easy, she added. ``The worst is when the
agents come over to search the house at random. I'm always
thinking, `Oh God, are the beds made? Is everything clean?' I mean,
you've got strangers walking through your home.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Spero was quick to insist that he is overjoyed to
be out of jail. He gets to see his grandchildren. He gets to eat a
sausage and pepper sandwich at any hour. He gets to sleep on a real
bed, not some back-breaking cot.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you can watch TV whenever you want when you're at home,''
he said as the Mets game blared from a nearby set. `` 'Cause when
you're in jail, they're the ones that control the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   This version of house arrest is generally reserved for
defendants charged with violent crimes or accused of having
tampered with witnesses or juries in the past. Under federal law,
defendants who apply for it must convince a judge of two things:
that they pose no danger to their communities and that they will
return to court on their appointed day.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, putting up a healthy sum of money will do the
job, but, in a handful of recent cases, high-profile mobsters have
had to subject themselves to considerably more.
</P>
<P>
   The first of these was John A. Gotti, the son of John J. Gotti,
the imprisoned Gambino family boss. The younger Gotti was freed
from jail in October 1998 after he secured his release with $10
million and oaths to wear an electronic bracelet that tracked his
every move, to allow his phones to be monitored by the FBI and to
permit a guard to be posted outside his home in Oyster Bay.
</P>
<P>
   At the detention hearings in the case, federal prosecutors
argued, among other things, that Gotti should not be released
simply because he could afford the cost of his circumscribed
freedom. Why, they asked, should a rich defendant be granted house
arrest but a poor defendant be denied?
</P>
<P>
   Shargel, who represented Gotti in the case, countered that a
defendant's pockets _ no matter how shallow or deep _ should never
be used against him. If a poor man cannot afford to outfit his
house like Rikers Island, he argued, it doesn't mean that a rich
man should be penalized just because he can.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has no centralized office that tracks
defendants who ask for and are granted highly restricted house
arrest, but, as it turns out, most do have vast resources. Some are
like Chris Paciello, a wealthy Miami nightclub entrepreneur accused
of robbery and murder, who is living under lock and key just miles
from Spero's home. Others are like Carmine Agnello, the elder
Gotti's son-in-law, who was charged with arson and extortion but
was denied bail in June even though he offered to transform his $4
million Long Island home into a comfortable sort of jail.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge who rejected Agnello's application, Nina Gershon
of U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, does not like the idea that the
rich can buy a more comfortable jail. She wrote in her order that
suspects should not be free simply because they are ``able to pay
the cost of extravagant release conditions.'' Yet legal experts say
that it would be unconstitutional to deny bail automatically to
every racketeering suspect. So the home-as-jail may be the only
option for prosecutors looking to prevent a suspect from fleeing
the country or committing more crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Spero is spending a good deal of money on house arrest, his
lawyers said, though nowhere near the $20,000 a month that the
young Gotti paid. In fact, Spero hardly thinks about the money. He
is wrapped up in more quotidian concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cleared it with the government that Anthony could take the
garbage out,'' his companion said as she showed a visitor around
the house. ``But he's always saying he can't do it. He's not
allowed past the driveway. The electronic bracelet is to blame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
