<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 
 PERSONALS: Xxxxxxxxxxx Xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SAY THE SECRET WORD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The secret word that guests had to use to get into the Brad
Pitt-Jennifer Aniston wedding last week was ``pianist,'' reports
MSNBC. No news on whether guests were required to pronounce the
word _ a combination of ``pi'' for ``Pitt'' and ``anist'' for
``Aniston'' _ PEE-anist or pi-YAN-ist, a question Personals'
dictionary ducks, too.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New York magazine says that designer  &UR; Randolph &LR; 
 &UR; Duke &LR;  threw such an exclusive party at his estate in the Hamptons
recently that he had the invitation printed in ink that disappeared
in two days, could not be photocopied or faxed and was delivered by
hand.
</P>
<P>
   The designer's aide told the magazine that this was necessary
because invitations left around people's houses or in their rental
cars could result in uninvited guests, and the U.S. Postal Service
couldn't be trusted, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- Forty paintings rescued on their way to the dump are on
display at the  &UR; George Krevsky &LR;  Gallery in San Francisco.  &UR; Dorothy &LR; 
 &UR; Winslade &LR; , who lived in San Francisco and Millbrae, painted the
hills and street scenes of San Francisco and the Bay Area, and her
work was well known in the '30s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   After her death, in 1973 in Santa Cruz,  &UR; Bart Wilson &LR;  was hired
to haul her things, including the paintings, to the dump. But
Wilson happened to have studied art history at school, and refused
to comply. Eventually, the paintings were entrusted to his
management; he brought them to Krevsky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- At the Republican convention,  &UR; Barbara Bush &LR; , no slave to
fashion, was watching a tribute tape to her husband's
administration, wearing the same suit she wore in the tape, when
her husband was in office, the New York Post's  &UR; Cindy Adams &LR;  writes
admiringly. The Chicago Sun-Times also noted that while male
ex-presidents  &UR; George Bush &LR;  and  &UR; Gerald Ford &LR;  were teary-eyed
during the video tribute to  &UR; Ronald Reagan &LR; ,  &UR; Nancy Reagan &LR; ,
 &UR; Maureen Reagan &LR;  and  &UR; Betty Ford &LR;  were stoic and strong.
</P>
<P>
   -- Name That Plane suggestions:  &UR; Cliff Barbanell &LR;  thinks
 &UR; George &LR; 
 &UR; W. &LR; 's plane should be the ``Bushwhacker'';  &UR; G. Daulton &LR;  suggests
the flying Al-oplane be called the ``No Controlling Legal Authority
One.'' And to keep the flying field perfectly level, let's say that
 &UR; John Cross &LR; ' suggestion, ``Spirit of St. Dufus,'' could be applied
to either candidate's plane, as could  &UR; Charles &LR; 
 &UR; Landy &LR; 's ``Fortunate Son.'' Finally,  &UR; Chris Beach &LR;  mentions the
possibility of the candidates' amassing frequent-liar miles.
</P>
<P>
   -- Spam Oven Roasted Turkey, a white-meat turkey version of
traditional Spam, will be introduced in September. ``If you buy
turkey at a deli,'' the company's  &UR; Nick Meyer &LR;  told Advertising
Age, ``you have to eat it within five to seven days, but you could
eat this product years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Everything I make fun of in my movies I secretly like. With &LR; 
 &UR; `Cecil B. Demented,' I'm making fun of myself and about what is &LR; 
 &UR; cutting edge. Why does everything always have to be about &LR; 
 &UR; `cutting edge' now? ... If it's not cutting edge, it's not `in.' &LR; 
 &UR; Which is just as ludicrous as making `family' movies.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John Waters &LR;  on KQED's ``Independent View,'' which will be
broadcast Friday, Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
