<HEADER>
A1954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ACCOUNTING-NORRIS-COL     08-03 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: BULL MARKET MULTIPLIER: A LITTLE REVENUE WENT A LONG WAY
</HEADLINE>
  By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bull markets may not cause companies to fiddle with
their books, but they certainly increase the rewards to be gained
from creative accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of the Unify Corp., which this week put its
two top officials on leave and said that its revenue for the last
fiscal year, and perhaps the one before that, had been overstated.
The company's board has begun an investigation, and trading in its
shares has been halted.
</P>
<P>
   Details are skimpy. Even if you assume that the board's audit
committee is right that the company reported revenue that it should
not have, there is no way to know how it happened or the amounts
involved.
</P>
<P>
   One fact is obvious, however: The amounts involved were
minuscule compared with the market value the company attained. For
the 15 months ending in January, Unify reported revenue of $45
million, of which $20 million came from its Internet-related
products, software that helps companies integrate their basic
businesses with their Internet sites. It was the Internet business
that impressed investors, who saw rapid growth and valued the
company on the assumption that it would continue.
</P>
<P>
   Unify's market value rose from $25 million at the end of October
1998 to a peak of $750 million last December.
</P>
<P>
   Some, probably most, of that Internet-related revenue was real.
So, the overstatement, if there was one, is likely to turn out to
be a fraction of the $20 million. But the excitement that small
amount helped to produce sent the stock soaring. Insiders got $10
million by selling shares that had been worth barely $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   All of this illustrates the pressures companies face in a bull
market. Numbers that indicated that growth was slowing would have
been devastating.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than the revenue and the accompanying profits that
made Unify a shooting star. The Internet mania helped, as did Unify
announcements, just as the Linux mini-boom was starting last year,
that it was offering Linux-compatible products. But Unify wouldn't
have moved without good numbers, and it delivered them.
</P>
<P>
   Unify's stock had already tanked before the bad news came out
this week. That reflected both the decline of Internet infatuation
and concerns over a heart attack that forced the chief executive,
Reza Mikailli, to take a medical leave in June. Whether rumors had
spread regarding accounting issues is not clear.
</P>
<P>
   The company's announcement that the audit committee believed
revenue figures had been inflated in the fiscal year that ended in
April, and perhaps in the one before that, came just as the audit
was being completed by Deloitte &AMP; Touche. It would be nice if it
turned out that the auditors had uncovered the problem and taken
the matter to the audit committee. Neither Deloitte nor the company
would discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Mikailli and Gary Pado, the chief financial officer, have been
placed on administrative leave while the investigation proceeds.
Both were heavy sellers of stock, a fact that the Securities and
Exchange Commission will no doubt wish to discuss with them if the
investigation indicates that they knew the accounting was faulty.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known if the Unify board suspects fraud or just thinks
the company misapplied complicated accounting rules. What is known
is that the greatest bull market in American history provided
phenomenal rewards to companies that investors believed were
growing rapidly. The temptation was there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHICAGO-ART-REVIEW-NY     08-03 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDY CHICAGO: GOOD CHEER AND THE HUMANIST VALUES, ALL RENDERED IN
CLICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEN JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Judy Chicago's ``Resolutions: A Stitch in Time,'' an
installation at the American Craft Museum, is an excellent
candidate for worst New York museum show of the year. Chicago's
first solo venture in New York since 1987 and first museum show
since her famous ``Dinner Party'' installation was exhibited at the
Brooklyn Museum 20 years ago, this show is aesthetically vacuous,
conceptually inane and morally disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Dinner Party,'' a vast, triangular table with place
settings designed to memorialize great women of the past,
``Resolutions'' is the product of collaboration between Chicago and
a group of craftswomen. This time it is mainly a picture show, and
the focus has expanded to embrace a whole basket of liberal,
humanist values. The spirit, unlike that of, say, Barbara Kruger,
is not adversarial; rather, the mood is weirdly cheerful, like a
visual art version of Up With People. The 19 easel-size
compositions look like posters produced by a group of unimaginative
but eager-to-please high school students for a small-town community
center.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures are arranged in seven thematic groups: Family,
Responsibility, Conservation, Tolerance, Human Rights, Hope and
Change. Each combines a familiar verbal slogan and a bland,
cartoonish illustration that calls to mind the deliberately generic
style of Mark Kostabi but without any of his mordant cleverness. In
the Family category, we have ``The hands that rock the cradle shape
the world,'' with two mothers flanking a baby in a cradle; the
image of a proud graduate in cap and gown rises up behind them like
a prophetic dream. In Tolerance we have wolves and sheep reaching
out to each other in peace and the slogan ``Live and let live.''
And Hope offers ``Hitch your wagon to a star,'' with the image of a
family of hopeful African-Americans driving an old wooden wagon
within the decorative framework of a star.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that makes these works at all worth looking at is
the embellishment added by Chicago's collaborators. For each piece,
a woman skilled in some form of needlework enhanced Chicago's drawn
and painted design through embroidery, needlepoint, macrame, petit
point, applique, quilting or some other technique. At best, as in
``Home Sweet Home,'' in which all sorts of dwellings _ an igloo, a
teepee, a wood-framed house, a high-rise apartment building _
encircle a globe, embroidery by Pamella Nesbit gives the otherwise
vapid picture a satiny, jewel-like richness. (In a sidebar to the
exhibition proper, a series of didactic text panels describes the
various techniques used and includes enthusiastic comments from
each of the collaborators.)
</P>
<P>
   The installation is set up as a spiral, the sequence of pictures
ultimately leading to a life-size statue with a beige plastic
surface. The figure is bald and has abstracted features, but its
conical, dresslike lower half suggests it is female. She holds out
muscular maternal arms and has an embroidered valentine heart
embedded in her chest, gold at the center with a purple and red
halo. Colorful embroidery spirals up around her dress parallel to
words in different languages routed into the surface. In English
the words say, ``Find it in your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's project is not, after all, without a coherent and even
audacious vision. Almost always when modern art has addressed
social issues, it has done so negatively from the point of view of
the romantically alienated individual, seldom offering an image or
a program to inspire communities of optimism and good will. Against
this background it may be radical to promote a message of love,
peace and understanding, and to do so through collaboration with
nonartists using popular crafts.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to imagine an intelligent viewer taking seriously
the bromides asserted by Chicago's glorified posters. Of course,
she knows she is dealing with cliches, and part of her purpose is
to bring back to life certain basic human values that
Postmodern-style irony has lost sight of. Nothing she does,
however, gives exhortations like ``Get into the swing of things''
or ``Do a good turn'' any social, political or moral urgency. You
have to wonder whether Chicago herself really believes in these
sentiments. There is a feeling of condescension, like that of an
insensitive schoolteacher talking down to children.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the feminism. Though not specifically feminist
in its general aims, the ``Resolutions'' project emerges from the
same feminist thinking that gave rise to ``The Dinner Party'':
against patriarchal privileging of high art and masculine genius it
pits domestic, traditionally female crafts and shared labor (with
Chicago nevertheless receiving star billing). Nonhierarchical,
cooperative and noncompetitive effort is put forth as the way to
make a better world.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may still like this 1970s-style feminism, while
others will find it old-fashioned and naive. In any event, the
actual dispiriting experience of the ``Resolutions'' project does
not make a good case for the theory's practical viability.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago Chicago made some beautiful airbrushed mandala
paintings, and some of the dishes she designed for ``The Dinner
Party,'' whether or not you liked the gynecological iconography,
were seductively lush. But her messianic ambitions have taken her
far beyond the limits of her real artistic competence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resolutions: A Stitch in Time'' will remain at the American
Craft Museum, 40 W. 53rd St., (212) 956-3535, through Sept. 3. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
