<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROSLER-RETROSPECTIVE-     08-03 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSLER-RETROSPECTIVE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: AN ICONOCLAST TO WHOM THE PERSONAL IS ALWAYS
POLITICAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Exhibition notes at end of review.) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you happen to be on basically OK terms with the
world, meaning that the world is doing all right by you, the alert,
irritated, combative work of the American artist Martha Rosler may
not be your cup of tea.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you find yourself nagged by a few social
questions that just won't go away _ like, why the ``haves'' have so
much, or why race and class dictate where people live and how they
die _ then her art of ideas-that-lead-to-actions is well worth
getting to know.
</P>
<P>
   There's no better chance to make its acquaintance than in
``Martha Rosler: Positions in the Life World,'' a career
retrospective of more than 30 years that is also the artist's first
major museum show and is divided between the New Museum of
Contemporary Art in Soho and the International Center of
Photography on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the split in venues and Rosler's long-standing habit of
dividing her energies among several media at once, the show is of a
piece. It is crowded, garrulous, agitated and funny _ the subway
ride uptown from the New Museum feels like an extension of it _ and
all but inseparable from the urban landscape that is Rosler's
native milieu.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Brooklyn and went to school there in the 1950s
and '60s, first to a yeshiva, then to Brooklyn College, where she
earned a degree in English and studied art with Ad Reinhardt. She
painted in an Abstract Expressionist vein but also took photographs
of city streets, inspired partly by socially conscious artists like
Walter Rosenblum, who was teaching in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important _ Rosler says so in the show's excellent
catalog, which was edited by Catherine de Zegher and looks like a
textbook, right down to the scuff-proof binding _ was her youthful
involvement in New York's experimental poetry scene, then in the
middle of the so-called mimeograph revolution. From this, one
guesses, she learned how art could be produced outside both the
market and academia, and she got a sense of the loaded, slippery
power of language, which plays a crucial role in her work.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to California to study linguistics in 1968, a
mind-boggling moment in American culture, equally idealistic and
bummed out. Rosler became involved in the peace movement and
feminism. She abandoned painting for other forms, to which she
brought two very American attitudes: a candid,
hey-what's-going-on-here moral brashness and a TV-generation sense
of the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   The multifarious art that resulted was based on some simple
guidelines. Aware of the co-opting power of the market, she chose
mediums that were either ephemeral (installation, performance) or
easily reproduced and distributed (video, photography). She also
opted out of developing a signature style, a decision that makes
her retrospective, organized by Elizabeth A. Macgregor of the Ikon
Gallery in Birmingham, England, and Sabine Breitwieser of the
Generali Foundation in Vienna, look less like a solo exhibition
than a lively collaborative effort.
</P>
<P>
   The show mixes all kinds of things together, with the bulk of
photography and video uptown and the large-scale installations at
the New Museum. The installations are Rosler's most didactic works,
and she continues to produce them. Each has homed in on a specific
topic _ atomic weapon production in the United States, the military
dictatorship in Chile _ and fleshes it out with a wealth of
research materials: news clips, maps and political documents
attached directly to the gallery wall or available in handouts.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a total immersion in concentrated information,
though one with little visual allure. This may not have been a
problem in the alternative spaces for which some of these
installations were originally created. But in museums _
institutions that prefer seductive objects, foster short attention
spans and have a temperamental intolerance for most conceptually
based art _ it is. On two visits, I saw people giving text collages
only the briefest scan before moving on, which is too bad: the
daily news, Rosler's greatest resource, is the weirdest, saddest,
scariest story ever told.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, people did linger over the installation titled
``Monumental Garage Sale,'' which fills the museum's basement
gallery. First presented in 1973, it's just what it says it is: a
sprawling cash-and carry bazaar of the castoff contents of
innumerable household attics and closets, including the artist's
own. (Everything is for sale, cheap. The proceeds will go to a
local charity.)
</P>
<P>
   Although it's not apparent at first, the items have been
carefully arranged. The ``best,'' most attractive objects are at
the front of the room, while at the back, which is dimly lighted,
one finds a stash of odd, disconcerting things: old underwear,
soft-core pornography, family snapshots and other abject,
embarrassing, unpresentable items; their presence undermines the
fragile barrier between private and public space, home and the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The intersection of these spheres _ the personal and the
political is another way to define them _ is at the core of much of
Rosler's most trenchant and innovative work, beginning with two
interrelated series of photomontages, ``Bringing the War Home:
House Beautiful'' and ``Bringing the War Home: In Vietnam,'' at the
ICP.
</P>
<P>
   Both series were made between 1967 and 1972, and each combines
images lifted from popular magazines: interiors from House
Beautiful and Vietnam combat pictures from Life. In one montage, a
wounded Southeast Asian child limps, as if dazed, through a chic
modern living room; in another, a suburban picture window looks out
on a battlefield. Rosler designed all the work for reproduction in
alternative journals, not for gallery display.
</P>
<P>
   She uses the same cut-and-paste technique in the feminist series
``Beauty Knows No Pain, or Body Beautiful'' (1966-72), at the New
Museum. Here she packs female body parts snipped from Playboy
magazines into ads for top-of-the-line refrigerators. She makes the
sex-sells strategy of lingerie ads explicit by pasting in genitals
and breasts, and in the piece ``Untitled (Cargo Cult)'' (1974), she
shows faces of fashion models being crated for shipping: a Western
ideal of beauty sent abroad.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
