<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1961 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROSLER-RETROSPECTIVE-     08-03 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSLER-RETROSPECTIVE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: sent abroad.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite her self-description as a ``ham-fisted'' artist with an
anti-style, anti-mastery aesthetic, Rosler's photomontages are full
of subtle touches. In one of the war series, a skeletal Giacometti
sculpture, an icon of 1950s existentialist despair, seems to be
striding out of the living room into the battle beyond. And in a
``Body Beautiful'' piece about domestic entrapment, one finds,
hanging on a hallway wall, a Robert Indiana poster for Virgil
Thomson's opera ``The Mother of Us All,'' which is based on the
life of Susan B. Anthony and has a libretto by Gertrude Stein.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere does Rosler tackle feminist themes with more imaginative
panache than in her videos, several of which are on continuous view
in a gallery at the International Center of Photography. One of the
earliest is ``Semiotics of the Kitchen'' (1975), a deadpan cross
between a Julia Childs demonstration and a ``Saturday Night Live''
skit, with the artist dressed in an apron and robotically wielding
cooking utensils as if they were weapons. It's six minutes long and
it's great.
</P>
<P>
   A piece like this, widely influential over the last 25 years,
has naturally begun to acquire a period feel. After all, it emerged
from a time when feminist art and the video medium were both in a
start-up phase. A text-and-photo installation completed at the same
time, however, looks as fresh today as when it was made and seems
to point the way to what Rosler is doing now.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``The Bowery in Two Inadequate Descriptive Systems''
(1974-75), it is composed of black-and-white unpeopled shots of
Manhattan's skid row, alternating with typed lists of slang words
for drunkenness. Simple as it sounds, it has a lot going on. The
piece is historically erudite, with its references to Minimalist
grids and the American tradition of Social Realist photography. The
single words in irregular stacks have the abstract insistence of
concrete poetry but also interact with the words on shop signs and
liquor bottles in the pictures. The themes are ones this artist has
dealt with repeatedly: consumption and its hazards, and the
intersection of private and public in social space. For many Bowery
residents, the doorways Rosler photographed were home.
</P>
<P>
   But far from nailing down a hard-and-fast message, the piece
stays oblique, suggestive, open-ended. The same is true of the most
recent photographs, a series of color images of shop windows and
street posters titled ``Transitions and Digressions'' (1997). All
the elements that have fascinated Rosler for decades are here _ the
female body, language, absurdist comedy and the economics of
acquisition _ but are given a haunted, poetic resonance.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Rosler has sustained her political focus and pushed
her art ahead, neither of which is easy. This doesn't make her a
prime candidate for mainstream stardom. True, she's joined a New
York gallery (Gorney, Bravin &AMP; Lee in Chelsea), a move she resisted
for decades. But most of her work will probably still have little
to say to the viewer for whom taste, style and beauty are the
essential building blocks of art.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably fine with Rosler, who, one suspects, has an
opinion or two about the present New York scene, with its big
bucks, big spaces and slightly desperate glamour fixations. (Check
out her 1978 deconstruction of the fashion industry in the video
``Martha Rosler Reads Vogue.'') At the same time, this mid-career
summary coincides with a diffuse, anything-can-happen interlude of
germination in contemporary art, one in which her practical and
deeply skeptical utopianism has an important place.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha Rosler: Positions in the Life World'' is on view at the
New Museum of Contemporary Art, 583 Broadway, near Prince Street,
Soho, (212) 219-1222, through Oct. 8 and at the International
Center of Photography, Fifth Avenue at 94th Street, (212) 860-1777,
through Oct. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
