<HEADER>
A1962 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-SCENE04-COX     08-03 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SCENE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS MEMBERS FIND A HOME NEAR THE HALL
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It took a village to convince Rep. Jack Kingston
to come to his party's national convention.
</P>
<P>
   The four-term Republican from Savannah, Ga., skipped the 1992
and 1996 GOP gatherings to be with his family. Politics already
kept him away from his wife and children more than he wanted, and
he disliked dragging them to events where they were stuck in hotel
rooms or receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my kids couldn't have come, I wouldn't have either,''
Kingston said. He and his wife, Libby, have four children, ranging
in age from 17 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, the Kingstons are among more than 100
congressional families staying in a ``Congressional Village''
hastily assembled in a former naval shipyard about 1,000 yards from
the First Union Center, where the Republican National Convention is
being held.
</P>
<P>
   The housing is a far cry from the luxury hotels where many
delegates are lodged. The congressional families are staying in
former Navy barracks in the former shipyard, now owned by the city
of Philadelphia and leased to private industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment-like structures have kitchens and hardwood floors
and are ``adequate,'' said Kingston. Rep. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash., described them as ``nice but spartan'' to the Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   But the facility is extravagantly family-friendly. There's a
dining tent, a Ferris wheel, a swimming pool, pool tables, a
basketball court, a horseshoe pit, Ping-Pong tables, a volleyball
court and video games.
</P>
<P>
   Families can ride in a hot-air balloon, view Philadelphia by
helicopter, tour an old aircraft carrier or work out in a gym. They
ride loaned bikes around the secured 1,200-acre facility.
</P>
<P>
   The site is guarded and off limits to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Since the village is within sight of the convention hall,
members avoid long commutes from hotels and spend more time with
their families. It's about a five-minute walk from to the
convention hall, but official GOP shuttle buses take twice that
long of security checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things about today's Congress ... is that most
House members with families commute to Washington'' while their
families live in the home districts, said Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get to know each other's families,'' said Kingston.
``Now I see my 12-year-old playing with Dave Weldon's
13-year-old.'' Weldon is a Republican congressman from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The village was arranged by Pennsylvania Reps. Curt Weldon, a
Republican, and Robert Brady, a Democrat. Local volunteers provide
village services, and contributors ranging from defense contractors
to a swimming pool company set up the facilities. Each lawmaker
made a token $250 contribution to the city. The arrangement was
cleared by the House ethics committee.
</P>
<P>
   The set-up has stirred controversy _ not because of the bargain
housing, but because Weldon arranged for the Pentagon to display
some high-tech weaponry at the shipyard. Weldon chairs the House
Armed Forces subcommittee on research and development.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is not supposed to be involved in partisan
politics. Weldon and Defense Secretary William Cohen responded to
criticism by describing the display as educational and well away
from the political business of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the village, there has been an assortment of parties for
members and visiting delegates. The fare has ranged from Philly
cheesesteaks to Cajun food brought in for a Mardi Gras gala
sponsored by Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La.
</P>
<P>
   Although his lodging has a kitchen, Kingston said, it hasn't
been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently food and politics go together,'' he said. ``There's
no such thing as starving at a convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
