<HEADER>
A1966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SMITH-ART-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-03 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AMERICAN PANORAMA AS DONATED TO SMITH COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In high summer, when pleasure is at the prow, people
who love looking at pictures often remember the art museum at Smith
College in Northampton, Mass. Not only is the collection quite
remarkable in itself, but it represents a collective effort over
many generations by the faculty of the college, by the successive
directors of the museum and by discerning, devoted and
strong-minded alumnae.
</P>
<P>
   These three elements make a formidable combination. Anyone who
studies the catalog of the collection will find that it is very
difficult to guess at what age the donor in question came forward
with this or that gift. The museum has never hewn to any specific
line in the development of art. As the 21st century dawns, it is as
alert to the multicultural input of Betye Saar and Jaune
Quick-to-See-Smith as its founders were to the granitic severity
that John Singleton Copley, in the 1770s, could give to the
features of the Honorable John Erving, who had arrived in America
as nobody and ended as one of the most powerful men in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is unfortunate, then, that the museum will be closed ``for
renovation and expansion'' until 2002. The good news for New
Yorkers, however, is that 74 of its paintings and sculptures are
now on loan to the National Academy of Design museum in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Smith College Museum of Art cuts a swath of some 250 years
in American art, and here and there in the show at the National
Academy there is something particularly enticing. One such work is
Edward Hopper's ``Pretty Penny,'' painted in 1939. It was given to
the museum in 1964 by the actress Helen Hayes, who received an
honorary doctorate from Smith in 1940. As is well known, Hopper was
not one to seek out the brighter side of American life. Nor did he
want to be commissioned to do portraits, whether of people or of
houses. He saw it as a moral duty to dwell on the darker side of
American architecture, and he was rather put out to be offered
$2,500 to paint Helen Hayes' house. This was tradesman's work, and
he had had enough of that in his earlier days.
</P>
<P>
   The Hayes house, in Nyack, N.Y., was joyous, carefree,
light-inviting and altogether out of sync with Hopper. He agreed to
go see it. But he and Hayes did not exactly hit it off. After his
visit, she said: ``I had never met a more misanthropic, grumpy,
grouchy individual in my life. He was like a big hellcat of anger
and resentment at the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But these problems were resolved when Hopper finally produced,
after careful preliminary drawings, a painting that is direct,
straightforward and almost ecstatic in its rendering of the Hayes
house. It looks like a real estate agent's dream. The famed
loneliness and alienation that so often permeated Hopper's
paintings of houses were banished, and all parties seem to have
been pleased with the result.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more inventive directors of the Smith College museum
was Henry-Russell Hitchcock. Though best known as an architectural
historian, Hitchcock was fascinated by paintings that happened to
tickle his fancy.
</P>
<P>
   One of these was Florine Stettheimer's portrait of Henry
McBride, an art critic who wrote for some of the best American
journals of the 1920s. The portrait is an anthology, and almost an
alphabet, of McBride's looks, tastes and activities. When read
closely, it reveals itself as a true document of its times. It also
tells us why Marcel Duchamp organized a memorial retrospective for
Stettheimer at the Museum of Modern Art in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Exemplary as some of the museum directors have been, there is
something particularly loving and persistent about the patience
with which the alumnae of Smith College have helped to keep the
collection apart from its contemporaries in other places.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, too, a major artist has stepped in, as Frank Stella
did when he gave his ``Damascus Gate (Variation III)'' of 1969 to
the college. Ten feet high and 40 feet wide, it fulfills the wishes
and hopes of Smith's first president, L. Clark Seelye, who said in
July 1875 that he wanted every Smith student to have direct access
to ``the famous masterpieces.''
</P>
<P>
   When Seelye himself began to buy for the museum, he went
straight to what we now see as the top, with paintings by Thomas
Eakins (bought in 1879 for $100) and Albert Pinkham Ryder (bought,
probably, from Ryder himself).
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the college's art museum had some remarkable
directors over the last 125 years, but the level of gifts from
grateful alumnae has been consistently high as well. The collection
amounts, in fact, to a concise history of American art since 1880
that has been built up generation by generation.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there, a terrible poignancy strikes us among the Smith
College paintings on display at the National Academy. One of the
most haunting images in American painting is the ``Mourning
Picture'' by Edwin Romanzo Elmer (1850-1923). It is a family
portrait, with father, mother, a daughter who had died not long
before and a pet sheep against the backdrop of a house of which the
artist was clearly rather proud. When it was first shown in a post
office in 1890, the local paper said that `` Elmer is quite an
artist.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not seen again until 1950, when the artist's niece
showed it to Hitchcock, who saw at once that it was an astonishing
achievement by an artist who had died unknown. From the moment that
Smith College acquired the painting, it made its way into one
magazine after another. Wherever it was shown, and not least in
Europe _ Frankfurt, Rotterdam, Munich, Brussels _ its elegiac power
was interpreted as expressly American. Familiar as it may now be in
reproduction, it has kept its secrets, and the delicacy of its
feelings, intact.
</P>
<P>
   The general tone of the show is, however, anything but elegiac.
There is Charles Sheeler's famous ``Rolling Power'' (1939), the
most glorious compliment ever paid in art to the steam locomotive
at the height of its power and importance.
</P>
<P>
   There is also Winslow Homer's ``Shipyard at Gloucester'' (1871),
which shows a fishing schooner on the stocks in its every least and
last detail. Nothing escaped Homer's eye in such matters, and we
can sense the prodigious speeds that these schooners could achieve.
It is in paintings like these that American art could ``accentuate
the positive'' and make us feel that in such a country anything was
possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
