<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS WORKING OUT FOR BELICHICK, PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ Bill Belichick has worried all preseason that
the Patriots haven't gotten the most of their workouts. Prior to
this week the weather was not hot, humid, and physically taxing
enough. That has changed dramatically with muggy conditions at
Smithfield, R.I., Wednesday and equally clammy days in Canton,
Ohio, earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Friday night's game is in the Silverdome,
which will house the Lions for two more seasons before the covered
Ford Field is ready in 2002, it is not air conditioned.
</P>
<P>
   While uncomfortable for the fans, it's perfect for Belichick,
who is trying to prevent comfort for his players.
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few Patriots who are a little overweight and
are being fined $151 per pound, per day for being over their
assigned weights. Collections of these fines (approaching the
$100,000 mark) could pay for the college education of Belichick's
children as they approach the $100,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots made a strong opening statement against the 49ers,
but six of the 49ers' front seven were missing. Running back
Raymont Harris didn't have Ken Norton Jr. or Winfred Tubbs to avoid
on his way to 58 yards on nine carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make some corrections from that game,'' said Belichick.
``We'll tell them they need to do better, how to improve and what
mistakes were made. Then, after Detroit, we need to solidify things
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lions should provide better competition, though their
outstanding defensive end, Robert Porcher _ who ended his contract
holdout Wednesday by signing a one-year deal for $4.253 million _
won't play, nor will starting quarterbck Charlie Batch, who is
recovering from a broken bone in his right leg. In his place, the
Patriots defense will look at 15-year veteram Mike Tomczak, who for
the moment is the starting quarterback on Opening Day, even though
he hasn't looked that great.
</P>
<P>
   Also out is defensive tackle Luther Elliss, who had knee surgery
Wednesday. Once again, the Patriots' young offensive line will go
up against at least two backup players in the Lions' starting unit.
</P>
<P>
   A stationary target, Tomczack could provide more ammunition for
pass rushers Willie McGinest and Chris Slade.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe will start at quarterback, but look for his
appearance to be slightly more than the one-series cameo he made
vs. the 49ers. Belichick said the rotation will be similar; Michael
Bishop relieves Bledsoe and rookie Tom Brady relieves Bishop. Brady
is returning to Michigan, where he starred in Ann Arbor, not far
from the Silverdome. Veteran John Friesz will get his first action
against the Redskins Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions have some problems in the secondary with free safety
Kurt Schultz gone after signing with Buffalo. Strong safety Ron
Rice is out with a shoulder separation, replaced by former Patriot
Corwin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   This is a pivotal game for some Patriots, because Belichick will
begin his evaluations. Since there's been so little time between
the first two games, Belichick has spent more time preparing than
evaluating. Some young members of the offensive line have caught
Belichick's eye, and that situation could potentially become
disruptive when his veteran starters return from injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far we've seen some good things, they're holding their
own,'' said Belichick. ``You have a veteran player who can perform
at a certain level and you have a younger player who isn't quite at
that level. You could see the younger player going to a higher
level. Those are decisions, and they are tough ones, that come up
every year and every coach and every team is going to be faced with
at some point in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Things to watch:
</P>
<P>
   --Michael Bishop II: He loosened up after missing three wide-
open receivers early in his stint last week, but he's still the
show in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   --The running game: Raymont Harris has the opportunity to
distance himself from the rest of the backs with another strong
performance. J.R. Redmond practiced Wednesday, but he may be a week
away from playing. Kevin Faulk has also looked exciting as a
multi-purpose back.
</P>
<P>
   --Bledsoe: The Patriots have been filming Bledsoe extensively in
practice, focusing on his handoffs. Coaches may be trying to
improve his play-faking.
</P>
<P>
   --The linebackers: This unit is a little banged up. Tedy Bruschi
fractured a bone in his hand last Monday and is sporting a cast.
We'll see how much playing time he gets. While Ted Johnson
practiced Wednesday, it doesn't appear the veteran middle
linebacker, who has missed almost two weeks with a hamstring
injury, will suit up. The focus could be on young linebackers Marc
Megna, Casey Tisdale, and Maugaula Tuitele.
</P>
<P>
   --Brandon Mitchell, who has missed a lot of sessions with a
strained calf, may return on a limited basis. He should be a
starting defensive end and needs to have a big year to land a big
paycheck as an unrestricted free agent next season.
</P>
<P>
   --Tebucky Jones: You'll likely see more of him at free safety.
The Lions have a decent receiving corps, so this should be a good
test.
</P>
</TEXT>
