<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX PLAY THE `GETTING TO KNOW YOU' GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Shaughnessy-Column)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A few hours after yielding a walk-off, game-losing
homer to Mike Cameron, Jeff Fassero stood at his locker and got
dressed for the final game of the Red Sox western swing through
Oakland and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the makeshift nameplate atop the adjacent locker
that had ``Croushore'' scribbled in black magic marker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's that?,'' Fassero asked.
</P>
<P>
   He was informed that Rick Croushore was a pitcher acquired in
Boston's seven-player deal with the Rockies. He'd been called up to
replace Ramon Martinez, who'd been disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starter or reliever?,'' Fassero asked.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever he was told.
</P>
<P>
   No one saw the mysterious Croushore for a while. He apparently
arrived sometime during the night when Pedro Martinez was beating
the Mariners, 5-2, and saving the beleaguered Boston bullpen (18
scoreless innings Monday and Tuesday). After the game, Jimy
Williams said he hadn't seen Croushore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he here? I don't know,'' said the manager of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Red Sox clubhouse. It's quite the opposite of the
old Cheers Bar _ ``where everybody knows your name.'' The Sox
locker room in 2000 is where (itals)nobody knows your
name.(unitals) Not even some of your teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The team that returns from the 4-3 trip is not the same unit
that left town after losing two straight to the Twins. Fassero, who
pitched in relief Tuesday, starts Friday night in the first game of
a three-game Fenway set with the Royals and he'll be followed to
the mound by new starter Rolando Arrojo Saturday. Second baseman,
Mike Lansing, is another new face. Rico Brogna was picked up on
waivers Thursday. Meanwhile, Morgan Burkhart is back from the
minors and Croushore is expected to have his own nameplate at
Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's series features the much-anticipated return of
Jurassic Carl Everett, the multi-talented center fielder who Friday
night will serve the final game of his 10-game suspension. The Sox
are 4-5 since Everett began his punishment for bumping an umpire at
Fenway three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing well, no matter who goes down or goes out,'' said
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, who is hitting a torrid .393. ``We've
been playing hard and when Carl comes back, that'll be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon, who appears to be the new leadoff man while Jose
Offerman (bruised knee) serves time on the disabled list, said,
``We probably should have been 5-2 on that trip, but we couldn't
get a run across in that 19-inning (5-4 loss). But those were two
good teams we were playing. I think we're pretty happy. We're
getting closer to having Carl back. It may take him a couple of
games to adjust, but then again, he's so talented, he'll probably
do some damage from Day 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the stretch run now. There's no more saying,`Yeah,
plenty of games left.' We've got to play well and stay in position
to make our run. It's up for grabs in the AL East and the wild
card, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clubhouse that's already housed 46 players (the Sox record
is 55, set in the first-place season of 1995), Nixon and catcher
Jason Varitek are emerging as young leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek played all 19 innings behind the plate Tuesday, got to
sleep at 5 a.m., then went back to work Wednesday, catching
Martinez's nine-inning masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're playing good baseball without one of our key
hitters,'' said the catcher. ``To go out West and win the way we
did. Now we can come together and get on a good stretch and I like
our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is not their friend. It's absurd to play seven
games in Oakland and Seattle, return to Fenway for three, then fly
to Anaheim for a three-game set that starts Monday night. After
Anaheim, the Sox play in Texas before returning home again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could have just stayed out here,'' Martinez said
after beating the Mariners. ``But we don't make up the schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland-Seattle junket started last Thursday with a
thrilling comeback win on the same day Duquette made the
seven-player deal. The Sox trailed, 4-3, in the ninth, but battled
back and won in extra innings. Pedro won the next night, 4-1, then
Fassero was drubbed and the Sox lost, 12-1. Arrojo made his debut
in the final Oakland game and beat himself with five walks and two
gopher pitches to No. 9 hitter Sal Fasano.
</P>
<P>
   The opener in Seattle was much like the first game in Oakland.
Boston fell behind, 4-0, in the first when Ramon Martinez
surrendered a grand slam to Jay Buhner. Boston was still behind,
5-4, in the eighth, but Nixon (RBI single) and Varitek (three-run
homer) beat closer Kazuhiro Sasaki and the Sox won, 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-inning marathon was next and it can be said almost
without argument that Everett's tirade cost his team this game.
It's impossible to imagine Everett going to the plate nine times in
19 innings without helping his team score at least one run. The Red
Sox did not score in the final 16 innings and went 14 straight
frames without getting a man to second. If Everett plays, they win.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the Sox, Pedro (13-3, 1.42; 9-0, 1.21 on the road)
pitched the next night and put a happy face on the road trip. Able
to do whatever it takes to help his team, Pedro cut back on the
strikeouts (six) and pitched an economical five-hitter (Seattle
sluggers Alex Rodriguez and Edgar Martinez combined to go 1 for 27
in three games against Boston pitching). The Sox bullpen was toast
and Martinez knew what he had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had to go as deep as possible and pick up the
bullpen,'' he acknowledged. ``So I gave those guys a rest. They
really needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the occasion calls for,'' said pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big performance for our club,'' said Williams.
``Going home 4-3 is good.''
</P>
<P>
   What about getting Everett back, Jimy?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not back until Saturday. Come see me then,'' stated the
manager. ``He's been working hard. There's no physical problems. We
certainly look forward to having him back this weekend I know he's
looking forward to it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Red Sox aren't saying who'll start against the
Royals Sunday. It might be Tim Wakefield. It could even be Bret
Saberhagen if Boston chooses to rush the veteran back into the
rotation. A minor league call-up (Tomo Ohka?) is an option.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it might be someone unknown to even the Red Sox
players. Such is life in the Sox clubhouse in the summer of 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
