   GOP-BUSH-SPEECH-NYT _ Gov. George W. Bush's Thursday-evening
speech has been ready for two months, and how it was prepared
offers a window into the discipline and strategy of the candidate
and his campaign. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KY-SCHOOL-RAMPAGE (West Paducah, Ky.) _ After their lives were
changed by a 14-year-old killer, the parents of three girls who
were gunned down in a school shooting here sued more than 50 people
they said shared responsibility for the deaths. They sued the
killer and his parents, teachers, school officials, other
teen-agers, neighbors, and the makers of violent video games, Web
sites and movies. But, after a string of recent legal defeats in
which two judges have dismissed virtually all of the claims, there
will be just one defendant remaining: the killer himself, Michael
Carneal. He is the only one the courts have said can be held liable
for the deaths. The story of the lawsuits shows how difficult it is
to assign blame to the many people who, in retrospect, might have
been able to prevent rampage killings and it shows how hard it is
to unravel what really happened in cases that are, by definition,
unfathomable. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOLS-RACE (Undated) _ The town of Nyack, N.Y. has
unofficially done what New York state and many other states will
soon require of all school districts: It has broken down academic
achievement by race. But its experience provides a cautionary tale.
The release of the numbers divided what had been seen as a diverse
and tolerant community in a way most people thought nothing ever
could. Some black parents decried how schools were segregating and
shortchanging their kids while white parents defended the schools,
pointing the finger at what they called neglect in black families.
Many affluent black parents decried the statistics themselves for
perpetuating painful stereotypes. In the tension, car windows were
smashed, confrontations erupted on the sidewalks. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
