<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1983 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-DAVID-LINK-PROFILE-$A     08-03 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVID-LINK-PROFILE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING FAITH AND JUSTICE INTO A NEW LAW SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Minn., Ohio, Australia, South Africa)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It happened 30 years ago, but it's still one of David Link's
favorite stories.
</P>
<P>
   He was a partner at the Chicago law firm Winston &AMP; Strawn, and
the Greyhound Corp., his biggest client, had struck a deal to buy a
small company. Link discovered that the target company had
undervalued its inventory by nearly $1 million. He persuaded
Greyhound, which was at first reluctant, to increase its bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many law schools teach that a lawyer's obligation ends at
maximizing the client's profits,'' Link said. ``I say there's a
moral obligation to get justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, Link was content to promulgate that idea at the
Notre Dame Law School, where he had been the dean for 24 years. But
then, the Rev. Dennis Dease, president of St. Thomas University in
Minneapolis, asked him to design and run its new faith-based law
school, to open in September 2001. He jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a challenge!'' said Link, who is 63. ``I get to start a
new Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   As Link sees it, doctors heal the body, ministers heal the soul
and lawyers heal society. ``I don't think there is a legal question
that doesn't have a moral facet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not _ but should lawyers act on those moral facets?
</P>
<P>
   Definitely not, said Mario Cuomo, the former New York governor
who is now a lawyer at Wilkie, Farr &AMP; Gallagher. He remembers once
bridling when an appeals court applied concepts of morality to a
breach-of-contract suit. ``The chief judge wrote, `The result was
unjust; the case is reversed,''' Cuomo recalled. ``My reaction was,
what standard is he applying? The Koran? The Talmud? How can anyone
use the law to make people behave in ways that are not required by
the law itself?''
</P>
<P>
   To Alan Dershowitz, the Harvard Law School professor, Link's
concept of lawyer as healer is a pragmatic impossibility. ``Clients
will say, `You are not my priest, you are not my mother; I've
decided to make money, and if you won't help me, I'll get another
lawyer,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are all professors at Catholic law schools in tune with
Link's approach. Here is how John Q. Barrett, an associate
professor at St. John's University School of Law in New York,
reacted to the Greyhound story: ``It's the seller's lawyer's
responsibility to notice that assets were undervalued.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Link does not agree. ``You can't teach law as though
it's value-free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is setting up St. Thomas to reflect that idea. He has signed
up local lawyers whose values he likes as mentors to St. Thomas'
students. St. Thomas will help pay off the loans of students who go
into public service jobs. It will offer joint degrees in law and
social work, divinity, education or business, and will staff its
law clinic with people from those disciplines as well. ``If
someone's problem has more than a legal aspect, we can walk them
across the hall,'' Link said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has 183 accredited law schools _ three in
Minneapolis alone _ and 25 Catholic law schools, but Link is
garnering converts nonetheless. Dease says that St. Thomas has
received more than 500 letters of inquiry from prospective
students, and more than 360 letters from would-be faculty members.
</P>
<P>
   ``David believes so strongly in faith-based law that he is an
apostle,'' Dease said.
</P>
<P>
   David Link grew up in Sandusky, Ohio, the youngest of six
children in a strict Catholic home. He often visited his father, a
car dealer, at work. Early on, he was struck by how well his father
treated customers _ and how much repeat business he got.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom taught us that ethics were necessary even if they
hurt,'' Link recalled. ``My father showed me that ethics could help
make you successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Link attended Notre Dame in South Bend, Ind., and majored in
advertising and philosophy. He had expected to take over his
father's dealership with his brothers; the plan was scrapped when
his father sold the business.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief time he toyed with becoming a journalist _ after
all, he met Barbara, now his wife of 42 years and mother of his
four children, while working on his high school newspaper _ but
wound up attending Notre Dame Law School.
</P>
<P>
   When he graduated in 1961, he became a lawyer for the Internal
Revenue Service. He became friends with the IRS chief counsel,
Crane Houser _ ``He liked my JFK imitations,'' Link recalled _ and
when Houser joined Winston &AMP; Strawn, Link followed him. He took a
leave in 1970 to help Notre Dame set up a program for teaching tax
law. He never came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, I'm in my 31st year of leave,'' said Link, who
became the dean of the Notre Dame Law School in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he has' stayed put since then. In the late '80s he took
a leave to set up a Catholic law school in Australia. He visits
South Africa three times a year, to consult for a law school he
helped set up there.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Link has helped to build houses for homeless people in
South Bend. He was a mentor to Notre Dame's minority students.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of African-Americans balk at going to a Catholic school
in the Midwest, but Dean Link helped us recruit,'' said Elton
Johnson, a second-year law student at Notre Dame
</P>
<P>
   Even former students who have gone into politics _ a profession
not always known for its ethical stances _ say they have been
influenced by Link's willingness to walk the walk.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Durant, a 1976 Notre Dame law school graduate, consulted
with Link before running unsuccessfully for a Michigan seat in the
U.S. Senate in 1990. ``I always valued David's counsel, his belief
that being a leader goes beyond just teaching law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph A. Cari Jr., another of his former students at Notre
Dame, was Sen. Joseph Biden's campaign manager in his bid for the
Democratic nomination for president in 1988, and when his candidate
got crushed, his first reaction was to leave politics. ``But I kept
hearing David's voice, saying you must do constructive things in
times of pain,'' Cari said.
</P>
<P>
   Cari is now finance chairman of the Democratic National
Committee. Last year, when Cari was named chairman of the Woodrow
Wilson Center for International Scholars in Washington, he invited
Link to the swearing-in ceremony. ``It just wouldn't have felt the
same without David,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1846EDT &QL; 
