<SLUG> BC-FORD-RECOVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD RECOVERING FROM APPARENT STROKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former President Gerald R. Ford continues his rapid recovery
from a pair of mild strokes, taking a short stroll around his
Philadelphia hospital and giving GOP presidential nominee George W.
Bush some oratory pointers.
</P>
<P>
   But while the 87-year-old politician appears to be on the road
back to health _ he should be discharged by early next week _
questions were raised Thursday about his initial care. Doctors at
Hahnemann University Hospital first diagnosed Ford with a sinus
infection and quickly discharged him, a decision that thrust them
into a harsh, though likely fleeting, international spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of restless journalists, with little tangible news to
report from the heavily scripted GOP convention, peppered officals
from the 618-bed hospital with openly skeptical questions. The
Hahnemann staff defended their initial call, claiming they made the
correct decision based on the information they had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe there was any misdiagnosis there,'' said
Michael Halter, the hospital's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Halter said that the former president did not exhibit all his
stroke symptoms when he checked into the hospital at 1 a.m.
Wednesday complaining of pain in his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ford's spokesman said the former president was
interested only in pain relief at the time, and refused a CAT scan
so that he could return to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The activities that evening were totally controlled by the
president,'' said the spokesman, Calvin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   It was eight hours later, after a clearly ailing Ford gave
numerous TV interviews, that it was determined he'd suffered a
stroke. The delay in diagnosis does not appear to have affected his
prognosis: Doctors said he suffered no brain damage or any other
permanent injury. The strokes, which cut off blood flow to the
balance center of his brain, slurred Ford's speech and upset his
balance. Though Ford appears to be recovering, his short-term
neurological distress continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's having some problem with his tongue and a little bit of
slurred speech,'' said Dr. Robert Schwartzman, the hospital's chief
of neurology.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Philip J. Kistler, director of stroke services at
Massachusetts General Hospital, which treats the power elite from
around the world and is the stand-by hospital when the president is
in the Boston area, said he doubts that Ford's refusal of initial
treatment was given special weight because of his stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treat everyone the same,'' he said. ``I can't imagine they
did any differently.''
</P>
<P>
   But if blatant symptoms are absent, as Hahnemann officals said
was the case, then a patient's words are all a doctor can go by,
said Kistler.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to believe what people say,'' he said. ``Sometimes
the brain doesn't recognize its own symptoms. But sometimes family
members do, especially wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was Ford's wife, Betty, who gave doctors the detailed
information about his odd recent behavior that allowed them to
diagnose the strokes, one on Sunday and one Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush visited Ford for about 15 minutes, saying the
political veteran told him to ``keep practicing'' his acceptance
speech for the GOP nomination, which he gave later.
</P>
<P>
   The former president also walked about 40 feet along a hospital
corridor with some assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was definitely much steadier than he was yesterday,'' said
Dr. Carole Thomas, director of neurological intensive care at
Hahnemann.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Staff writer Anne E. Kornblut contributed to this report from
Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
