<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX     08-03 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH HAS DONE WHAT A PRESIDENTIAL NOMINEE HASN'T DONE SINCE 1984
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB RAY SANDERS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It would be easy to say that Gov. George W. Bush,
a privileged child of an important American family, once again got
something he wanted, and that this time it was a gigantic present:
his party's nomination for president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be simplistic and unfair, and it terribly
understates a man whom people have tried to label as a shallow,
inattentive ``frat boy'' whose main purpose in seeking the nation's
highest office is to avenge the defeat of his father in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Bush has had plenty of help in his bid for the White
House, and he's had lots of money. But make no mistake about it,
the governor carried his own water in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' quadrennial meeting that ended here last night
was Bush's convention. He set the stage, the tone and the agenda.
The entire event reflected his ideas and ideals.
</P>
<P>
   He proved months ago, during the grueling primary season, that
he could take a punch, that he could learn _ and learn fast _ from
his mistakes, and that, despite any distractions thrown at him by
opponents, he knew how to stay on course, stay on task and stay on
message.
</P>
<P>
   You've got to give it to him. He's been an excellent candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his Grand Old Party put on a humdinger of a convention,
one that was upbeat, more diverse than any other Republican
convention in history and one that generally made for good
television. Yes, it was scripted and programmed, with some
artificial feel-good moments, but then what major political
convention isn't?
</P>
<P>
   This candidate has been able to do what no other Republican
nominee has done since at least 1984. He unified his party.
</P>
<P>
   There are still some major philosophical differences within the
party. But because Republicans want to win so badly, they have been
able to put aside most of their differences long enough, they hope,
to get their man elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having said all that, Bush will not be a shoo-in. He still
has to convince doubters that he is capable of being the chief
executive of the world's only superpower.
</P>
<P>
   He will have to make people believe that he and the party as a
whole are sincere about compassion, inclusion and diversity. And he
can't make that case by simply parading a bunch of people of color
across the television screen. There has to be some action that
speaks to their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will try to do that by touting his record in Texas. In
politics, like on the old vinyl discs, there are two sides to every
record. His opponent, of course, will be broadcasting the side that
has had the least air play.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans undoubtedly got a big bounce from their convention
and the nomination of Dick Cheney as Bush's running mate. Democrats
will need much more than a bounce. They may need one of those
rocket boosters from Cape Canaveral to help get presidential
candidate Al Gore off the ground, much less into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It can be done. Gore likes running from behind, although not
this much behind. Still, I'm convinced he will run a hard-hitting
campaign with a running mate who will offer a great contrast to
Cheney and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats already know, as was signaled here this week, that
Bush-Cheney will be running as much against Bill Clinton as Al
Gore. By election time, Republicans will want us to believe that
Clinton and Gore are joined at the hip, unable to be separated,
surgically or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to the voters to decide if that strategy will
work.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
