<SLUG> BC-NY-DANCING-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE PARTY OUTDOORS
</HEADLINE>
  By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is summer in New York, this year a season that
jumps from muggy heat to damp chill without warning. There is
relatively little dance in pleasantly climate-controlled theaters.
So what do those mad creatures called dancers do?
</P>
<P>
   Forget about vacations or more trips to the office-temp center.
Dancers dance. So they are taking to the city's parks, rooftops,
gardens and empty buildings over the next four weeks in a surge of
activity that truly offers something for just about everyone.
Festivals and special events are everywhere, and many of them are
free.
</P>
<P>
   The granddaddy of summer series is the free 30-year-old Lincoln
Center Out of Doors festival, which opens on Saturday and runs
through Aug. 27. This year's theme is ``Celebrate Good Times.''
Does this mean there will be nonstop partying spilling out across
the plazas and into the band shell at Lincoln Center for the month?
Jenneth Webster, the festival's irrepressible director, admits she
did contemplate ``Let the Good Times Rule'' for this year's title.
</P>
<P>
   Good times, Webster said, are ``like the moment you're in, if
it's a good moment. Everything from meditation to a conga line. So
there's a whole spiritual slant to this festival.''
</P>
<P>
   The first artists to approach her about appearing in the
festival this summer were the Drepung Loseling Monks of Tibet, who
will perform chants and dances on Aug. 17 in ``Sacred Arts of
Tibet.'' Webster built a week of mystical arts around them, with
Ali Akbar Khan, the virtuoso sitar player on Aug. 13 at 8 p.m., and
``Pauline Oliveros' Deep Listening For-Tunes,'' a celebration of
the mystical composer's 50th year in music, on Aug. 17 at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Oliveros' music is well known to audiences for avant-garde
dance, and Khan's concert promises to be a kind of performance
event, given that Webster will build a tent and provide a rug for
the musicians. Purists will be heartened to know that Donald Byrd
and his high-energy company, the Group, will be on hand that week
to shake things up, to music by Duke Ellington performed by David
Berger and the Sultans of Swing (Aug. 15 and 16).
</P>
<P>
   The festival's dance events begin Saturday afternoon with an
international family dance party featuring Estampas y Tradiciones
of Mexico, Korean Masked Dancing and Reginald Yates' Bantaba of
Africa. And that conga line may get going, at least
impromptu-style, with ``Encuentros Dominicanos'' on Sunday
afternoon. There will also be performances by established
modern-dance troupes like the Parsons Dance Company (on Aug. 8) and
the Paul Taylor Dance Company, whose program will include
``Cascade'' (Aug. 11 and Aug. 12).
</P>
<P>
   The festival is also a good place to see newer artists. Two
promising programs this year are ``Subtle Changes: Speaking the
Truth,'' an afternoon of choreography by Hope Boykin, Ayodele
Casel, Kerri Edge, Cheryl Godineaux, Jamie Philbert and Laila Sales
(Aug. 9) and a performance by the Pascal Rioult Dance Theater (Aug.
22).
</P>
<P>
   Is the experience of performing outdoors at all different from
dancing inside the three walls of a traditional proscenium stage?
Edward Morgan, a charismatic performer whose love for ballet finds
expression in his small company's joyous classicism, once performed
in the ultimate outdoor theater space, the amphitheater in Athens
while on tour with the Joffrey Ballet. And the MorganScott Ballet,
founded in 1997 with Daniel Scott, has had its share of competing
with urban distractions in outdoor performances in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   For their performance on Aug. 11 at ``Bryant Park Presents
August Dance,'' Morgan and Scott have taken into account not only
the expressiveness of their performers and the need to slightly
rechoreograph for a stage without wing space but also the angle of
the audience from the stage. They pick dancers with the extra
personality or natural projection for outdoor performances and
tailor the program for the casual observer. ``We normally start
with classical work and then go into something more contemporary,''
Morgan said. ``But outdoors, if you start with something a little
more contemporary, you may be able to draw the audience into the
classical piece that comes next.''
</P>
<P>
   The same philosophy appears to govern the dizzyingly
wide-ranging free new Bryant Park series, developed by Ethan
Lercher of the Bryant Park Restoration Corp., who operates on the
principle that the more dance the better for New York City. The
series opens tonight with Nick Palumbo and the Flipped Fedoras and
Dancers, a group of swing musicians and dancers who encourage the
audience to join in, and continues on successive Fridays with
modern dance by Nicholas Leichter (Aug. 18) and Hernando Cortez
(Aug. 25).
</P>
<P>
   Despina Stamos, the producer and curator of the free ``Deli
Dances in Times Square'' festival, chose five advisers known for
their engagingly oddball creativity in downtown dance and
performance art. ``They do interesting work for people who don't
see a lot of dance,'' Stamos said. ``We wanted to show that dance
is colorful, bold and hopefully accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which begins formally at 12:30 this afternoon,
will present more than 40 individuals and groups in afternoon and
evening performances through Aug. 18 at 135 W. 42nd St. The
sponsoring organization is Chasama, which puts on performances in
empty buildings managed by the Durst Organization. (The series got
its name from the former delicatessen where it was held last year.)
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
