u f BC-AMES-BRADLEES-BOS &LR;      08-03 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMES-BRADLEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMES, BRADLEES FACE TOUGH SELL AGAINST NATIONAL CHAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world filled with such national giants as Wal-Marts and
Targets, is there still a niche for a regional discount chain?
</P>
<P>
   A year ago the answer in New England might have been yes.
</P>
<P>
   After emerging from bankruptcy protection in early 1999,
Bradlees Inc. of Braintree, Mass. showed a lot of resilience. And
as it completed its acquisition of Hills Stores Co., Ames
Department Stores Inc. of Rocky Hill, Conn., was wowing Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, nearly everything seemed to go right for Ames and
Bradlees, but in the first half of 2000, nearly everything has gone
wrong, beginning with bad weather and high gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices in particular can be a problem for the moderate- and
low-income consumers who shop at Ames and Bradlees.
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's release of July sales figures, both chains had
more bad news to report. At stores open at least a year, July sales
at Bradlees dipped 4.6 percent, and at the much larger Ames, July
sales fell 2.6 percent at older stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a battle,'' said Peter Thorner, Bradlees chairman
and chief executive. ``We're not anyone's darling this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent subpar performance of Ames has surprised some
investors. A strong second half is ``critical'' to ``demonstrate
the company's earnings model is back on track,'' said Steven A.
Richter, an analyst with Tucker Anthony Cleary Gull.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Ames' difficulties may be its 1999 acquisition of
Hills, of Canton, Mass.; it has not gone as smoothly as planned and
has loaded Ames up with debt, other retail analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting a solid second half, Ames chairman and chief
executive Joseph R. Ettore said: ``We're obviously going to ride
this out.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bradlees and Ames underperform, the question again arises
about the long-term future of regional discount chains.
</P>
<P>
   Giants such as Wal-Mart Stores Inc. can use their size to buy in
volume and offer low prices. Giants can use their size to gain
efficiencies and get the best locations for new stores.
</P>
<P>
   Such factors put smaller retailers at a disadvantage and may
partly explain the demise of Caldor Corp., the $2.5 billion
Connecticut-based retailer that went out of business last year.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for small regional chains is ``guarded,'' said Kurt
Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   That hardly means surviving regional chains are doomed. One
scenario is that small chains will be swallowed up by larger ones.
That could be the ultimate fate of Bradlees, said Eric Beder, an
analyst with Ladenburg Thalmann.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long term, there's a potential they would be
acquired,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the last few months have been tough on many
retailers, especially those selling apparel. Ho-hum fashions, bad
weather, and interest rate hikes have hurt many chains.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the stock prices for many publicly traded
retailers have dropped sharply, but even among a group of
underachievers, Bradlees and Ames stand out.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Bradlees shares were trading just above $20 on
Nasdaq; they closed Thursday at $3.25, down 3.125 cents.
</P>
<P>
   And Ames shares were trading above $40 a year ago; Thursday they
hit a 52-week low of $5 before closing at $6, down 31.25 cents for
the day on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get stupid overnight,'' said Ettore of Ames. ``This
is the worst first half (of a year) for weather I've ever seen, and
I've been in the business since 1961.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the weather was nearly perfect, and Northeastern
retailers did a brisk business in barbecue grills, patio furniture,
fans, air conditioners, and seasonal apparel.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, however, the weather has been awful, and
seasonal merchandise has languished on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   For a big national chain with stores from coast to coast, bad
weather in one region can be offset by good weather somewhere else.
Regional chains don't have that advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The juxtaposition of a nearly ideal 1999 with a horrid early
2000 makes for tough comparisons when it comes to monthly sales
figures, numbers Wall Street follows closely.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, both chains said they expect momentum to pick up in
the second half of 2000 when month-to-month sales comparisons won't
be so difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its size, analysts think Ames has a chance to regain
momentum and keep larger rivals at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Ames operates 467 stores in 19 states, while Bradlees operates
105 stores in seven states.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Ames earned $17.13 million on sales of $3.84 billion;
Bradlees lost $9.37 million on sales of $1.49 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The chains have slighly different customers. Ames goes after
customers with household incomes between $25,000 and $40,000,
particularly consumers 55 and older. Bradlees targets customers
with household incomes between $45,000 and $55,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ames still may be struggling to digest its early 1999
acquisition of Hills, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ames did very well up until the time Joe Ettore went out and
bought Hills,'' analyst Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   Hills wouldn't be Ames' first bad acquisition. After acquiring
the Zayre chain of Framingham, Mass., Ames spent several years in
bankruptcy protection in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Such comparisons are unwarranted, Ettore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing about the Hills acquisition resembles the Zayre deal
in any way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradlees, according to chief executive Thorner, got a big lift
in 1999 from the demise of Caldor. The two chains competed against
each other in about 60 locations, and when Caldor closed its doors
many Caldor customers flocked to Bradlees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, many Caldor locations have been leased, and about 55
Bradlees stores find themselves with new rivals. At 32 of the
former Caldor sites, Bradlees now is near a new store operated by
Kohl's Corp., a Wisconsin chain that opened stores this spring in
New Jersey, New York, and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   According to Thorner, Kohl's department stores typically appeal
to a more upscale consumer than do Bradlees stores.
</P>
<P>
   But when Kohl's opens new stores, it advertises heavily and
offers discounts and promotions that attract Bradlees customers,
Thorner said; when promotions end, customers return to Bradlees.
</P>
<P>
   While bullish on the second half of 2000, Thorner offered no
rosy scenarios for the future of Bradlees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect to break even this year,'' he said. ``It's real
difficult for me to look down the road five years from now and
predict where we'll be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ettore offered a different view. Regional chains, he said, can
compete successfully against the giants if they can carve out a
niche, as Ames has done with blue-collar seniors. That's allowed
Ames to go up against Wal-Mart in 400 locations.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ettore: ``I honestly believe that 80 percent of our
shortfall is due to the weather.''
</P>
</TEXT>
