u e BC-NY-DANCING-2NDTAKE-NY     08-03 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DANCING-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: last year.): 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Deli Dances'' aims for an audience new to dance. Stamos hopes
that tourists and shoppers at the big theme stores in the
neighborhood may wander into this ``no budget'' event, as she puts
it. ``This is also an opportunity for choreographers to show their
work in an area they normally don't,'' Stamos said. To whet
audience appetites, a sample of dances was performed earlier in the
week in a Times Square subway station. There will also be ``open
stage'' nights on Tuesdays when anyone can sign up to perform.
</P>
<P>
   Six other far-flung festivals will present dance throughout the
city. Dancers and musicians from the Djoniba School will perform on
Aug. 9 in Summer in the Square 2000, a festival in Union Square
that runs through Aug. 30. Other dance events include a program by
performers from the Martha Graham Dance Company in works they or
guests have choreographed, on Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Central Park SummerStage and Celebrate Brooklyn! will go out on
a limb with dance that is exciting and good-looking but also
demands fully committed attention. The hard-driving, gutsy O
Vertigo Danse from Canada will share the bill with the quietly
thought-provoking Gina Gibney Dance from New York in Central Park
on Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Down in Prospect Park on Aug. 12, Celebrate Brooklyn! will stage
work by Hope Clark and Sarah East Johnson, the two choreographers
this year in the festival's forward-looking residency program. The
piece by Clark will blend voice, video, aerial movement and digital
effects. Johnson's all-female company draws on acrobatic feats,
trapeze work and even wrestling for what has been described as a
mix of circus and dance. Byrd and his company follow on Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swing Week,'' designated by Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani from
Aug. 14 to 20, will spill out through Manhattan, the Bronx,
Hoboken, N.J., and on the Internet. This celebration of swing, a
dance developed in the 1920's at the Savoy Ballroom in Harlem, has
been organized by the producers of the Broadway musical ``Swing!''
But Marc Routh, one of those producers, makes a believable case for
the festival's having as much to do with the sheer joy of swing
dancing as with the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the dance in its simplest form has to do with that
wonderful tangible thing of holding on to a partner and trusting
another person,'' Routh said. Most swing dancers do not progress to
the kind of complicated, airborne feats that the cast performs. But
essentially swing is an uncomplicated matter of ``right, left, back
step,'' he said. ``It's a lot of fun and offers the opportunity to
hold another human being real close and laugh and enjoy yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The events, some of them free, include demonstrations, lessons
and performances, four of them outdoors in the New York Botanical
Garden in the Bronx, in Bryant Park, at Orchard Beach and in
Central Park. Archival videos will be shown on Aug. 16 in a salute
to 75 years of swing at the Sandra Cameron Dance Center in
Manhattan. There will also be six swing-club contests, with
finalists competing on the stage of the St. James Theater during a
``Swing!'' intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Dance will also be performed this month at the Hudson River
Festival and the 19th Annual Downtown Dance Festival, which opens
on Aug. 27 with the exuberant foot-stompers known as the Vanaver
Caravan.
</P>
<P>
   What should audiences get out of all this? ``What we always
hope,'' Webster said, ``is that the audience will come and leave
with a tolerance for the new and unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Airborne Festivals &QL; 
