   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.N. BORDERS ON INSANITY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UN-BLURS-`BLUE-LINE'-INDEPENDENT-FISK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ Everyone expected the United Nations to move its
peacekeeping army down to the Lebanese border _ not to go mad. But
urgent orders in the early hours of last Friday morning to dispatch
Irish and Ghanaian U.N. troops from their bases in southern Lebanon
through the Israeli frontier to positions on the other side of the
Israeli-Lebanese fence do raise serious questions about the sanity
of the peacekeeping army....By Robert Fisk, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONLY WE WERE SURPRISED BY CAMP DAVID'S DISMAL FAILURE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMP-DAVID'N'GOLIATH-INDEPENDENT-FISK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ When the world's media _ and more than a few diplomats
_ predicted violence in the aftermath of the failure of the Camp
David talks, it was a sign of just how out of touch we all were.
Commentators on the Middle East waffled on about the ``dangerous
vacuum'' that existed after Yasser Arafat and Ehud Barak returned
home last week. But our reaction was really about our own
arrogance. Why should the Arabs turn to voilence now? After all,
they have realized for years _ as we in the West have not _ that
the Oslo agreement was doomed. But as usual, of course, we knew
best....By Robert Fisk, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TWO BRAVE VOICES CONFRONT CONFORMIST AMERICA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE'S-US-OUTRAGE?-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ Fadia Rafeedie is a courageous lady. In just a few
short, eloquent paragraphs, she accused U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright _ introduced to the audience at Fadia's
University of California at Berkeley commencement ceremony as ``the
greatest woman of our times'' _ of serious charges. Of lying by
omission, of responsibility via U.N. sanctions for the deaths of
tens of thousands of innocent Iraqi civilians, of failing to tell
her audience that it was an American company that had supplied
Saddam Hussein with his chemical weapons and the CIA that had
earlier funded him. At almost the same time, on the other side of
the U.S., a guilt-striken former Israeli soldier, James Ron, was
baring his soul in the normally pro-Israeli Boston Globe. Two brave
voices in a conformist land _ one Palestinian, one Israeli _
demonstrate that even in America, it's sometimes possible to hear
the unvarnished truth about the Middle East....By Robert Fisk, The
Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 125-word OPTIONAL TRIM at 825; total uncut is 1,200
words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEPOSED CHAUDHRY FEARS MASS FLIGHT OF INDO-FIJIANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIJI-EXODUS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The deposed Fijian prime minister, Mahendra Chaudhry,
fears that 300,000 Indo-Fijians _ the majority of the ethnic Indian
population _ will leave the country in the wake of the armed
nationalist coup led by George Speight. ``People of Indian origin
feel shattered and insecure,'' he said. With Fiji now ruled by an
interim government committed to rewriting the constitution to
exclude ethnic Indians from power, Chaudhry is considering forming
a government-in-exile _ either in western Fiji, his support base,
or in Australia. ``We can't just close shop and leave it to the new
regime,'' he said....By Kathy Marks, The Independent &LR;  &QL;
</P>
