<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SALOMON-BONDS-NYT &LR;      08-03 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALOMON-BONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALOMON OFFERS TO BUY U.S. TREASURY STRIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Salomon Smith Barney on Thursday offered to buy $94.5
billion worth of the interest portion of Treasury securities, known
as strips, from institutional and retail owners.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon said it wanted to combine the interest portions with
bond principal to create whole bonds that would be eligible for
sale back to the Treasury as part of the government's buyback
program.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Treasury is expected to buy back as much as $30
billion of Treasury bonds with maturities of 10 years to 25 years
remaining. The government is reducing borrowing amid growing budget
surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street firms often break up the interest and the principal
portions of a bond and sell them separately as zero-coupon bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon has an oversupply of the principal portions of existing
bonds but a shortage of the interest-rate portion. And if the firm
wants to take advantage of the premium prices the Treasury is
paying to buy back existing bonds, it needs to reconstitute the two
portions into whole bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offer will allow us to continue to be actively involved
in the Treasury buyback program,'' said Charles Parkhurst, co-head
of the U.S. government bond department at Salomon.
</P>
<P>
   The $94.5 billion is the face value of the interest portion of
the bonds. But these would be bought at a discount to the price so
the total cost would be less than $94.5 billion. Salomon is
offering investors cash for the interest portions of the bond, or
would swap them for a principal portion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
