<HEADLINE>
BLACKOUTS LOOM AS CALIFORNIA STRUGGLES TO PROVIDE POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the state facing the threat of rolling
blackouts, the California Institute for the Arts has voluntarily
cut its power three times this week.
</P>
<P>
   To help save the power grid from failing, drawing classes at the
Valencia-based institute have met outside under shady trees, while
others have gathered around sunlit windows. But even with thousands
of schools, office buildings and industrial plants across the state
agreeing to pull the plug during peak hours in exchange for lower
electric rates, California's power system appears to be in danger
of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a precarious situation, to say the least,'' said
Steven Hansen, a spokesman for Southern California Edison, which
has 4.2 million customers. ``This is the tensest we've ever seen
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Already this summer, the state's power manager has declared a
``Stage 2'' emergencies a record nine times, including Thursday,
meaning reserves had fallen below 5 percent of demand statewide.
That's just one step short of mandatory rolling blackouts for all
customers _ a move that would interrupt everything from home air
conditioners to traffic lights in the nation's most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the California Independent System Operator, the
nonprofit, state-chartered manager of about 75 percent of the
state's deregulated power grid, said a ``Stage 3'' alert is highly
unlikely. That level emergency has never been declared before. But
no one is ruling one out, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland-based Bonneville Power Administration, which
markets power from the massive federally owned hydropower dams in
the Pacific Northwest, said it was warned Tuesday that blackouts in
California were imminent, but the ISO denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news that it didn't happen, but we were under the
impression that it was a virtual certainty it would go this way,''
said Bonneville spokesman Edward Mosey. The discrepancy ``is
mysterious to us, unless our engineers misinterpreted the warning
from California, and they tend to be sticklers for details.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, President Clinton ordered federal agencies in the
state to cut their power use by an estimated 5 percent, and told
the federal power marketing administrations to maximize the amount
of electricity available in the state.
</P>
<P>
   No plant failures or downed power lines are behind the latest
crisis, utility officials said. Temperatures have been high, but
not at record levels in most cities, although a San Francisco area
heat wave did leave more than 90,000 customers without power in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a number of factors have combined to bring California _
as well as several other states _ to the edge of a power outage.
</P>
<P>
   Utility specialists said that deregulation of the industry,
intended to benefit consumers, caused uncertainty over future
profits that kept private investment in new power sources low. At
the same time, California's economy has been booming, raising the
demand for power by high-technology companies that use enormous
amounts of electricity and individuals whose homes are increasingly
filled with electric-powered gadgets. Increasing demand in other
states has also made importing power more difficult. The warm
weather only contributes to the power crunch, as air conditioners
become another drain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short-term, California has got a serious problem,'' said
Michael Shames, executive director of the Utility Consumers Action
Network, a San Diego-based consumer group. ``It's garbage that no
one saw it coming. They knew it last year. Power consumption is no
greater than expected.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, the first city where uniform electric rates were
lifted under deregulation, electric bills have doubled or even
tripled this summer. On Tuesday, the ISO cut the wholesale price of
power in an attempt to reduce consumer bills.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities also continued to encourage businesses and homeowners
to sign up for a program that lowers rates in return for cutting
use during peak demand periods. More than 1,000 large businesses
and 130,000 residential customers participate in Southern
California Edison's program, Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what you can do to get by without electricity
when you have to,'' said Sullivan, whose California Institute for
the Arts has backup generators to provide emergency lighting in the
hallways. ``We've had no electricity three times this week, the
most we've ever had. But the savings are worth it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
