<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brewer `likes to obsess on things'
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charles Brewer's resignation as chairman of EarthLink
Inc. Wednesday raised questions about the direction of the firm
without him at the helm. EarthLink President Michael S. McQuary,
who also was MindSpring president, is a close friend of Brewer. He
addressed some of the concerns in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Charles seems to have made a complete break from EarthLink.
He didn't just resign from the board, but he sold most of his stock
in the company. Should other shareholders be wondering what they
should do with their stock?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think (the stock sale) says anything about the
company in this instance. It says something about Charles as an
individual. I think I have a unique perspective about Charles; I've
known him since 1982, and we were roommates when I moved to
Atlanta. He likes to obsess on things one at a time and then move
on. The last few years his obsessive focus has been on EarthLink,
and now he wants to make a completely clean break.
</P>
<P>
   Charles goes through obsessions. There was a six-month health
obsession. It was ``Operation 5'' _ he wanted to run the
five-minute mile, and that was what he was focused on and nothing
else mattered. Then it was ``Operation Washboard,'' and he was
doing all these sit-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what is he obsessed with now?
</P>
<P>
   A: His obsession has moved to his family. We'll see how long
this passion for crying babies and changing diapers will last, then
he'll move on to the next thing. It's Charles' manner to always
make a clean break.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you or any of the other former MindSpring executives feel
extra pressure to ``carry the torch'' now that Charles is gone _ to
make sure that the core values and beliefs are still a priority
even at such a large company?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is a feeling among some of the MindSpring old-timers
that we have to talk about what the core values mean to the new
hires. We were there in the early days when we could see how
effective core values and beliefs were in inspiring a company. If
you go way back in the history of MindSpring when Charles moved me
into the president position, he placed a lot of trust in me to not
waiver from his vision. I still carry that mantle, and it's my
responsibility and I don't take it lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will his departure change anything about how EarthLink is
structured as a company?
</P>
<P>
   A: Charles' goal was always to build a great company, and we are
a great company. He can be very satisfied that he set out what he
wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   Sky's (Dayton, EarthLink's new chairman) passion has always been
to harness the power of the Internet to change people's lives and
make things happen. He still has a long way to go to make his
vision happen. We're lucky to be able to replace one icon with
another icon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But for EarthLink employees and customers it's business as
usual.
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely. With all this talk about Sky and Charles and
visionaries, (EarthLink CEO) Garry Betty gets overlooked. We spend
so much time on that fact, I don't think Garry gets his due. It's
easy to overlook him because he's the guy who's happy being under
the deck shoveling the coal. But I really want to say it's the CEO
who's the most important person in any company. He's unflinching in
his resolve to make this company great, and I don't think we are
going to miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
