</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2006 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-KY-SCHOOL-RAMPAGE-2ND     08-03 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KY-SCHOOL-RAMPAGE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WEST PADUCAH: the shooting.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By this February, Michael Carneal testified in a deposition. He
was no longer the scrawny 5 feet 2 inches he was at the time of the
crime. Now, he was 17, 6 feet 1 inch and 243 pounds, nearly an
adult, who had had time to think about consequences.
</P>
<P>
   No one else had been involved, he said. He said he had invented
the conspiracy story to tell the police ``what they wanted to
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers following the case say appeals courts could well reverse
Shadoan on the dismissals against these teen-agers and say a jury
should decide if there is enough evidence that others participated
in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, the judge said he had not seen evidence that
any of the teen-agers other than Carneal believed there was a plan.
When the shooting started, he said, ``These kids ran, just like all
the other kids.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PARENTS
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the killings, John T. Carneal, a prominent
Paducah lawyer, went to see the principal of the school where his
son had committed murder. ``I am the head of the house, I am
responsible,'' he said, weeping, the principal testified.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the murdered girls came to agree. Michael was a
``ticking time bomb,'' Hadley said.
</P>
<P>
   After the killings, Michael told psychiatrists he had sometimes
sobbed for no reason before the crime and was so fearful at home
that he had sometimes walked from one piece of furniture to another
at so he would not risk having some imagined person cut off his
feet.
</P>
<P>
   He once stabbed himself with a sewing needle, leaving a bruise
the size of a silver dollar but had told his parents he had been in
a bike accident. He testified that he was suicidal, ``mad at the
world,'' and hated being compared with his older sister, a model
student. The year before the killings, his mother knew, he had been
humiliated when a gossip column in the school newspaper speculated
that he and another boy had feelings for each other.
</P>
<P>
   But his father testified, ``I saw no evidence that Mike had any
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carneal's lawyer, Michael D. Moore, said, ``Michael never
did anything in front of them to indicate he had even the potential
for violence.''
</P>
<P>
   THE TEACHERS
</P>
<P>
   The picture of Michael at school is a chilling portrait of a boy
unraveling. In one school paper he said other children ``mocked and
slaughtered my self-esteem.'' In another he described a fantasy of
mutilating ``preps'' and described a boy opening fire on a group of
schoolmates.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's father testified that no one at the school had
mentioned those troubling papers. The teachers were unaware that
the boy had brought a gun to school and that he had courted
attention by giving away stolen property and talking about taking
over the school or a mall.
</P>
<P>
   But in Kentucky, as in many states, school officials are
generally protected from suits by rules of sovereign immunity that
shield government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   When he dismissed the cases against the teachers and school
officials last year, Shadoan cited those rules. ``We cannot expect
those teachers and administrators to be psychiatrists, lawyers,
psychologists, or physicians,'' he wrote. ``They are to educate our
children. Nothing more and nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   PLANNING APPEALS
</P>
<P>
   As the lawsuits have ground on, fury over them has grown here.
Some people say the three families have blamed too many people who
did nothing wrong. Nancy C. Holm, the mother of a boy who was
injured in the shooting, wrote a letter to the editor of The
Paducah Sun last year that drew widespread comment here. It
suggested that the three families had been influenced by their
lawyer in a search for dollars. ``Things are getting out of hand,''
Holm wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews, all three sets of parents said they were
too troubled by what they had learned about the missed chances to
avoid the killings to drop their suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of money could bring back our kids, and we would
rather have our kids back than any amount of money,'' said Judy
James, whose daughter Jessica was killed. ``All we're asking for is
for people to be accountable and responsible for what happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
