<SLUG> BC-TREK-JAMES-CAMERON-PREVIEWS-DARK-ANGEL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDID CAMERON: BEHIND THE SCENES ON `DARK ANGEL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of
producer/director/screenwriter James Cameron.) 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Science fiction is to James Cameron what the Mafia was to
Michael Corleone _ an irresistible force that pulls him back in
time and time again.
 &HT;    Cameron rewrote the sci-fi-film playbook with ``The
Terminator,'' ``Aliens,'' ``The Abyss'' and ``Terminator 2,'' and
this fall he will return to the genre with ``Dark Angel.''
 &HT;    But ``Dark Angel'' unfolds on the small screen, and Cameron
isn't directing. Instead he's co-creating the series and
co-writing/co-executive-producing a two-hour pilot with Charles
Eglee, a longtime Cameron crony who penned the director's infamous
1982 debut, ``Piranha 2: The Spawning.''
 &HT;    ``Dark Angel,'' set to launch Oct. 3 on Fox, introduces Max
(Jessica Alba), a genetically engineered young woman trying to
understand her past, hide from a dark-hat military sort named
Lydecker (John Savage) and get by in post-apocalyptic Seattle,
circa 2020. All of Max's plans are scuttled, however, when she
meets Logan Cale (Michael Weatherly), a cyberjournalist toiling
beneath the radar in a high-minded effort to right wrongs and make
a difference.
 &HT;    ``The opportunity to have a young female protagonist in a future
urban environment intrigued us,'' Cameron says by telephone from
his Los Angeles production offices. ``But we didn't want it to be
futuristic in a `Blade Runner'' sense, but in a plausible,
post-info-calypse, new-Depression, new-dustbowl era in America.
That was appealing.
 &HT;    ``Everybody projects out on a curve, as if economic prosperity
will continue, as if we'll build these great, gleaming edifices and
these starships, and all that,'' Cameron says. ``Nobody embraces
the lessons of history. The Chaos Theory shows these things can
reverse trends very rapidly.
 &HT;    ``What if there was a depression?'' he asks. ``Things in the
1920s felt very much like they feel right now. 2020 Seattle can
easily be 1932 Chicago. How you get to that could have been a
computer virus or something like that. We chose a terrorist attack
with an EMP (electro-magnetic pulse) device, which would certainly,
plausibly, do exactly what we say.''
 &HT;    Weekly hours will delve into Max's history as she seeks other
like her. The show will also follow Lydecker as he pursues Max, and
shadow Max and Logan as they deal with a mutual attraction that
circumstances, guilt and shame prevent them from pursuing ... for
now.
 &HT;    Cameron, who will likely write future episodes and might even
direct one, asserts that ``Dark Angel'' will push the envelope,
that it will make people think. Already he's catching flak for the
fact that Max's best friend is a lesbian.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to say, `Look, there are different ways to do
sci-fi,''' he says forcefully. ``You can show the future with
people walking around in silver jumpsuits, or you can show the
future as a society that has evolved down a certain road.
 &HT;    ``One of the roads, despite the fact that we show a lot of
negative evolutionary trends back to a much more corrupt society,
is that we're beyond it being an issue what your gender preference
is,'' Cameron says. ``It's just not an issue anymore.
 &HT;    ``Some people may say, `Well, that's not positive evolution.'
But you know what? Screw them. We're saying it is.''
 &HT;    While genre fanatics are intrigued by ``Dark Angel,'' they're
distressed that Cameron has dropped out of various other projects,
including ``Terminator 3,'' the ``Spider-Man'' movie and a remake
of ``Planet of the Apes.'' All three projects are now moving
forward, with others calling the shots.
 &HT;    Cameron has given his blessing for Arnold Schwarzenegger to star
in ``T3,'' but he himself won't be involved.
 &HT;    ``There are other things I want to be doing,'' he says simply.
 &HT;    ``Spider-Man'' got lost in a web of legal difficulties, Cameron
adds, while ``Planet of the Apes'' fell victim to creative
differences.
 &HT;    ``I thought I had a pretty good take on it, and I was going to
write it and produce it,'' Cameron says. ``I brought that
presentation to Fox, to (ex-film division boss) Bill Mechanic, and
Bill Mechanic disagreed with my choice of director. I said, `All
right. Fine. If we disagree, we disagree,' and that was that.
 &HT;    ``It was just one of those things where I sensed it was their
baby,'' the filmmaker says. ``At that time, it was like their
zero-billion-dollar franchise, because they'd done dick with it for
30 years or 20 years, whatever it's been.
 &HT;    ``I thought I had a way of creating something interesting, but I
got a real strong sense it was theirs,'' Cameron says. ``Having
gone through that with `Terminator,' I went, `You know what? Let it
be yours.''' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Dark Angel,'' consult the Fox
Web site at www.fox.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Inside Trek and Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
