<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LAUNCHES CAMPAIGN WITH APPEAL TO SWING VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   By STEWART M. POWELL   
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
PHILADELPHIA _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush accepted the Republican
nominatof for president Thursday night by seeking to appeal to
independent voters and crossover Democrats in his quest to become
the first son to follow a father to the White House since 1824. 
Bush, an affable, pragmatic Republican, told cheering,
placard-waving delegates and guests packed into the 22,000-seat
convention center that the nation ``can begin again'' led by a
party of ``idealism and inclusion.'' The 54-year-old son of former
President George Bush urged the nation to ``seize this moment of
American promise'' and ``use these good times for great goals.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush sketched plans to overhaul public schools, strengthen
Social Security and add prescription drug benefits to Medicare _
themes that are more often invoked by Democratic candidates than
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time for Republicans and Democrats to end the
politics of fear, '' Bush declared. ``I want to change the tone of
Washington to one of civility and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush vowed to ``confront the hard issues'' such as threats from
abroad and problems besetting Americans' health and retirement
systems at home before ``the challenges of our time become crises
for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush voiced regret about the impact of the Clinton-Gore years,
citing ``so much promise to no great purpose.'' Karen Hughes, his
campaign spokeswoman, said the two-term governor hoped to inspire
more than criticize. &QC; 
``I know the tone I want to set,'' Bush said before taking the
podium to deliver remarks that he crafted to court swing voters in
his battle with Vice President Al Gore as well as lay to rest
voters' residual concerns about his heft as a leader. ``We're going
to do things differently if given the chance to lead the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush emphasized that his brand of ``compassionate conservatism''
would reach out to disadvantaged Americans who feel left behind by
the longest economic boom in American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are their country too,'' Bush told delegates, adding:
``Each of us must share in its promise or that promise is
diminished for all.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest bipartisan Voter.com-Battleground public opinion
survey, conducted by Democratic pollster Celinda Lake and GOP
pollster Ed Goeas, showed that the four-day GOP convention that
emphasized diversity had given the Bush-Cheney ticket a sizable
14-percentage point edge over a Gore-led ticket. Bush leads Gore,
48 percent to 34 percent. &QC; 
The survey showed Bush seizing an 18 percentage point edge over
Gore among independents and a 6 percentage point edge among women _
both constituencies won by the Clinton-Gore ticket in the last two
presidential elections to enable the elected Democrats to hold the
White House for two successive terms for the first time since
1936. &QC; 
Gore hopes to begin a comeback with his scheduled announcement on
Tuesday of his Democratic running mate. In 11 of the 12
presidential elections since 1952, the candidate who led in the
polls on Labor Day won the election. Only Ronald Reagan came from
behind in 1980 to beat President Jimmy Carter. &QC; 
Bush and Cheney planned to storm out of the GOP gathering on Friday
for a three-day campaign trip by train through Midwest swing states
including Ohio and Illinois. Republicans closed out their sixth
convention in Philadelphia since 1856 with a new GOP anthem,
entitled ``We the People,'' a blend of rock &QC;
</P>
<P>
   , blues and country written and released by country singer Billy
Ray Cyrus.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, grandson of the late Sen. Prescott Bush, R-Conn., has been
governor of the nation's third most populous state for
five-and-a-half years _ making the Republican standard bearer the
least experienced politician to lead the party since former World
War II allied commander Dwight D. Eisenhower sought the presidency
in 1952. &QC; 
Bush's running mate has been away from the political fray since
1989, serving as the Bush administration's defense secretary and
later as chief executive of Halliburton Corp., a worldwide energy
services firm based in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried to turn his shortage of national experience into a
political asset in his address. Bush said that while he ``may lack
the polish of Washington'' he wasn't burdened by ``a lot of things
that come with Washington experience'' such as ``enemies to fight''
or a ``stake in the bitter arguments of the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush seeks to become the first presidential son to capture the
presidency since John Quincy Adams followed his father, John Adams,
to the White House 24 years after his father's term ended. Bush
hopes to win back the White House from which his father was ousted
by then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton and then-Sen. Al Gore, D-Tenn.,
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his speech ``speaks from my heard,'' adding that he
hoped his national audience would come away saying, ``This is a man
who sees a positive America _ an America for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush lightly brushed off any suggestion that his address would
be the most important of his life, quipping: ``The most important
speech was when I asked my wife to marry me _ and that went okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Before exercising on a stationary bicycle and reviewing his
speech, Bush stopped by Philadelphia's Hahnemann University
Hospital to visit former President Gerald Ford, who was admitted on
Wednesday following two minor strokes. Bush spent 20 minutes with
the 87-year-old former president, who told Bush, ``I'll be
campaigning for you in a couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Ford was expected to make a full recovery. &QC; 
Bush said ``it did my spirits good to see that he had good color
and was alive and active and anxious to talk about the
convention.'' &QC; 
Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway fired a salvo at Bush even before
the GOP candidate had mounted the podium to deliver his address. &QC; 
``Given the high praise his father received in 1992, George junior
has a lot to live up to tonight,'' said Hattaway. ``Tonight,
America will see if there is any substance behind the smirk.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address s &QC;
</P>
<P>
   tewarthearstdc.com ) &QC; 
