<HEADER>
A2015 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-CAR-NASCAR-INDY04-COX     08-03 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-INDY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Formula One event solidifies Indy's mystique
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The inscription on the Hall of Fame Museum at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway that calls IMS the ``Racing Capital of
the World'' is now accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, the declaration was debatable. Sure, since 1911
the track has annually hosted the most storied race in the country,
the Indianapolis 500. And in 1994, track officials added the
Brickyard 400, a race that's part of the NASCAR circuit, the most
popular racing league in America.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Brickyard 400 is Saturday, but IMS officials have
Sept. 24 circled on their calendars. That's when the fabled track
moves to a higher level _ an international level _ by hosting a
Formula One race, the United States Grand Prix, for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may say (the inscription on the museum) is presumptuous
with just one race,'' said Fred Nation, IMS' vice president of
corporate communications and public relations. ``But the Brickyard
400 solidified that reputation and we have underscored it with the
Formula One Grand Prix.''
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate Formula One, IMS has undergone a face-lift the
past two years, erecting a pagoda at the start-finish line to serve
as a control tower, a suite on the top of it, a media center
directly next door and pit-side garages to house the 22 Formula One
cars.
</P>
<P>
   The road course for the U.S. Grand Prix is 2.6 miles long, 1
3/10 of which winds through the infield and the other half the
actual oval.
</P>
<P>
   For officials at IMS, adding Formula One and NASCAR races was
the culmination of talks that began in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``(NASCAR founder) Bill France Sr. started attending the
Indianapolis 500 in the late '40s,'' Nation said, ``and he and
(former IMS owner) Tony Hulman had a lifelong commitment to
bringing NASCAR and Winston Cup to IMS. The same is true with
Formula One.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hulman's position was he was always open to doing
additional races here, but it had to be a big event. When Tony
George became president, one of his goals was to add a second
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Nation said George first approached Formula One officials in the
early '90s about adding a second race. He said the two parties
talked feverishly, but George decided the time wasn't right because
the last time Formula One had raced in the United States, it wasn't
overwhelmingly successful.
</P>
<P>
   Still, hosting Formula One remained a priority for George, who
instructed golf-course designer Pete Dye to make room for a grand
prix when Dye touched up the IMS' links in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   George shifted his attention to NASCAR and renewed talks with
the circuit's officials. In 1992, NASCAR tested at the track and
two years later, the Brickyard 400 was held there.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR may have its Daytona 500, a race that challenges the Indy
500 as most prestigious, but NASCAR drivers say winning at IMS is
the ultimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it in perspective,'' said driver Ricky Rudd, who won
the Brickyard in 1997, ``I think we've won 20 Winston Cup races,
but I don't think anybody would probably remember any of them with
the exception of maybe the Indy race.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's just because there's something about Indy. What
probably makes Indy so neat is that it would be like going to a
museum or historical landmark and being able to race around in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers, like CART's Juan Montoya, are awed by the track.
Montoya made his first trip to IMS a good one, winning the Indy 500
in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot being here,'' Montoya said. ``I think what
makes this place special is the people. The people who come here,
how do you say it? They're alley cats. The people have been good
and it's a friendly place.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
