<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace maneuvers to contend for title
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Rusty Wallace won at Pocono Raceway two weeks ago
and raced into contention for the Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Pennsylvania 500, Wallace jumped from ninth to
fifth in the points standings. The 1989 Winston Cup champion now
trails leader Bobby Labonte by 268 points with 15 races remaining.
</P>
<P>
   At Indianapolis Motor Speedway, site of Saturday's Brickyard
400, Wallace has five top-10 finishes, but he has not won it in the
six years of the event. He was fourth in the 1994 inaugural event
and second the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of track position will be at an all-time high
this weekend at Indy,'' Wallace said. ``Like I've said so often
this season, these cars are so sensitive to track position, it's
unreal. If you get behind a car, you lose all your downforce on
your front end, and you can't hardly pass cars. So even if you put
four tires on and think you're gonna have better tires than
everybody else, you get so hurt in aerodynamics that it really
doesn't show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where all the big-time importance with pit strategy
comes into play, and, hopefully, (crew chief) Robin (Pemberton) and
our team will make the best decisions on race day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's performance at Pocono made up for a bad decision in
the June race there. He ruined his chance to win when he insisted
on taking four tires instead of the two tires the rest of the
leaders took. Wallace finished a disappointing 10th and later
second-guessed his stratethat the in-house teams were getting. I
understood that going in, and you have to accept that, but I got to
the point where I needed to improve the performance of my race
teams, so we switched to Ernie Elliott engines. He's in the
business to provide engines to race teams, and I felt like I was
going to get a better piece of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't do it in house and you're not a multi-car team, you
need to look for the best technology and the best information
that's out there. We're looking to partner with another Ford team
so we can make sure that we're gaining as much information as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your restrictor plate and aerodynamics program is lacking.
What can you do to change that?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have not been able to get in the wind tunnel with our
restrictor-plate cars, and that has just shot us in the foot. We're
going to work very hard to get better prepared for Talladega this
year and for the 2001 Daytona 500. We've got to spend a lot more
money on that part of our program _ money that was not in the
budget for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you rate the Brickyard 400 in importance to the sport?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's probably No. 2 behind the Daytona 500. But as far as
testing, you only go there once a year, so you question putting the
money and resources into it for one race. But there's a lot you can
learn there because there is so much on-site timing and other data
available. Indianapolis is the best-known race track in the world,
and it's an honor for NASCAR's Winston Cup Series to be racing
there.
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP NOTES
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth leads rookie battle
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kenseth holds a 21-point lead over Dale Earnhardt Jr. in
the NASCAR Winston Cup Series Rookie of the Year standings. Most
figured ``Little E'' would be a shoo-in for the award, but
Kenseth's steady driving has gained the low-key rookie plenty of
respect from other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth is his own toughest critic, saying ``The beginning of
the year, toward the first third, we were pretty fast but not very
consistent. The one thing I've really worked hard on since
Rockingham and Atlanta is to be consistent. We have improved over
the last few months, finishing regularly in the top 20; we just
haven't been as fast as we needed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for `Mr. Excitement' to be singing the praises of
Indy
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to describing the world's most famous race track,
most Winston Cup drivers speak with respect. One driver who doesn't
consider Indianapolis Motor Speedway to be paradise, though, is
Jimmy Spencer. Let's just say it has to do more with two wrecks in
six starts at the historic 2.5-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never had a good finish here _ I've been in the hospital so
many times in Indy, they know me personally,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   In the inaugural Brickyard 400 in 1994, Spencer's ride blew a
tire and wrecked into the wall. It hit so hard that Spencer broke
three ribs and his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, I was put into the wall and spent three days in the
hospital and three weeks out of the car,'' Spencer recalls. He
blames his history at the track, which includes no top-10 finishes,
as ``tough luck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go in thinking that the track owes you, that's a
mistake,'' Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
   Good memories of Indianapolis
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Jones will be racing just down the street from
Indianapolis Motor Speedway in Friday's Busch race, the Kroger 200
at Indianapolis Raceway Park. Jones won his last pole at IRP in
July 1998. His only other career pole was at Rockingham in October
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Qualifying is crucial at IRP,'' Jones said. ``If you don't
start up front you may get stuck having to put on two tires instead
of four during pit stops just to gain track position.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin a favorite in IROC race
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Saturday's Winston Cup race, Mark Martin also
will be competing in Friday's IROC race. Martin is the clear
favorite, winning both of the previous IROC races at Indy. He
started 10th last year, but led the most laps and won the race. He
ended up finishing second by one point in the final IROC standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was disappointing,'' said Martin, who will be starting
11th in the 12-car field Friday. ``I did everything I had to do,
but sometimes that just isn't quite enough. I'm in a little better
shape this year to win a fifth championship. I don't have quite as
much ground to make up in just one race.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin holds the ninth spot in the Winston Cup standings with
2,487 points.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
