<SLUG> BC-GAPOWER-BIAS0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Power taking racial bias suit 'very seriously'
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Juanita Baranco, the Atlanta businesswoman who will
co-chair Georgia Power Co.'s new diversity council, says she will
approach racial discrimination charges against the company with an
open mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking it very seriously,'' Baranco said of the lawsuit
filed last week by three Georgia employees against the utility and
its parent Southern Co.
</P>
<P>
   Baranco is out of town this week and said she has not seen the
lawsuit and will reserve comment on the particulars until she has.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Fulton Superior Court, alleges that
Georgia Power fosters a ``pattern of discriminating against
African-Americans'' who work there and shows ``reckless
indifference'' to a racially hostile workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power President David Ratcliffe responded immediately,
naming Baranco, one of the company's three African-American board
members, to co-chair with him a Diversity Action Council that
includes senior company executives.
</P>
<P>
   Baranco, speaking by telephone from Minneapolis, said she was
surprised, ``very much so,'' by many of the allegations in the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power is committed to diversity, she said. ``Their track
record is pretty open and pretty accessible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Baranco said, ``we need to make sure we have an open-door
policy all the way to the top'' for workers to make complaints of
racial discrimination. ``Having an open, honest forum so employees
will feel completely comfortable in expressing their opinions will
be critical,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Baranco is co-owner with her husband and executive vice
president of Baranco Automotive Group.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Power has until Aug. 28 to file its response to the
complaint. Ratcliffe has said the company is open to a settlement,
but lawyers for the two sides have not reported any meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both in the beginning stage of litigation,'' said Steven
J. Rosenwasser, attorney with Boudarant, Mixon &AMP; Elmore, which is
representing the three Georgia Power employees. The Atlanta firm is
also one of the firms representing Coca-Cola Co. employees in a
similar suit.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for a costly settlement or judgment against the
company does not seem to have registered on Wall Street. Southern
Co. stock, following a trend in the utility industry, has risen by
more than $1 a share since the suit was filed Thursday. ``We have
not been considering it in our evaluation of Southern Co. stock,''
said Barry Abramson, an analyst with PaineWebber.
</P>
<P>
   But the suit has attracted notice in the U.S. Virgin Islands,
where Southern Energy Inc., Southern's international subsidiary, is
negotiating with the government to purchase 80 percent of the
island's water and power company for $400 million. The legislature
votes on the deal a week from today. Two local newspapers published
stories about the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our sister company that the suit was filed against. We
have never had an incident like that at Southern Energy,'' an SEI
spokesman was quoted by the Independent newspaper as saying. ``This
is something we just won't put up with. We are a multinational
company. We have to deal with multiple cultures, races and
religious beliefs of our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Kuemmel, a reporter for the Independent, said politicians
who are critical of the hotly-debated sale have been talking about
the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the fact that Georgia Power is a sister company of
SEI means the issue probably ``won't have much weight'' when the
legislature votes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
