<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-LAURADF.803-HNS &LR;      08-03 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAURADF.803-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LAURA BUSH PROMISES TO WORK ON EDUCATION &HT;    By DAN FREEDMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspaper
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Laura Bush told an audience of 2,200 Republican
women Thursday that if her husband, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, is
elected president, she will be an advocate for preparing young
children to go to school.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing members of the National Federation of Republican
Women, she talked about her effort as first lady of Texas to ``help
preschoolers develop skills to begin school ready to read and
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The other goal of her ``early childhood initiative'' in Texas
was to help parents understand ``the importance that early love and
nurturing'' have on a child's future prospects, she said, adding
that if she becomes first lady, ``I'll expand my committment to
helping children and families all over America.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush spoke at a $150-a-plate luncheon tribute to her
organized by the federation, which netted about $100,000 for its
grassroots effort to promote Republican ideas on education during
the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you and I raise our children today will profoundly
impact our society tomorrow,'' she said. ``My experience as a mom
and as an elementary school teacher taught me how smart children
really are, how eager they are to learn and how easily we can fail
them ... if we don't have high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The tribute included a biographical video on Laura Bush in which
her mother, Jenna Welch, talked about how she read books to Laura
as a child and how Laura practiced teaching before her dolls.
</P>
<P>
   The governor introduced his wife's speech just hours before
delivering his own acceptance speech at the Republican National
Convention. Comparing her convention speech Monday night with his,
Bush said, ``Laura certainly raised the bar, if you know what I
mean.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Monday night speech, Laura Bush gently tried stealing
some of the Democrats' thunder on education. Referring to Vice
President Al Gore, she said, ``George's opponent has been visiting
schools lately and sometimes when he does, he spends the night
before at the home of a teacher. Well, George spends every night
with a teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   She was a teacher and librarian in Austin and Houston before her
marriage to Bush in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   He has declared that education is a cornerstone of his campaign.
He often mentions that test scores of minority students in Texas
have gone up in the five years since he was elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   In his prepared acceptance speech, he pledged to make ``Head
Start an early learning program, teach all of our children to read,
and renew the promise of America's public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's education program stresses high standards and
accountability for student learning. Under his plan, federal funds
earmarked for schools in academic trouble could be diverted into
vouchers for parents who want to send their children to other
schools, including private ones.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches, he uses phrases such as ``there are no second-rate
children, and there are no second-rate dreams,'' and says he wants
to make sure that ``every child is educated and no child is left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also stresses high standards and accountability but focuses
on school construction and on hiring more teachers to make class
sizes smaller. He has proposed spending $115 billion of the budget
surplus to create an Education Reform Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, most polls showed Gore leading Bush on the issue
of who would do a better job on education. But Bush has been
closing the gap. In a Los Angeles Times poll released earlier this
week, Gore led by one percentage point on education, 42 percent to
41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Education ranks high as a campaign issue. The Battleground Poll,
taken during the convention by Republican pollster Ed Goeas and
Democratic pollster Celinda Lake, showed education in second place
behind ``restoring moral values'' as a key concern to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are aware of the extent to which education has been
an Achilles heel for them in past elections.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's luncheon, Florence Shapiro, a Texas state senator
from Plano, Texas, who preceded Mrs. Buksh at the podium, said,
``For too long, Democrats have acted like they own the issue of
education.,'' But she added that now, ``the message is clear: From
this day forward, education is our issue.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
