<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-MARYLAND-PREVIEW0     08-03 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MARYLAND-PREVIEW0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Terrapins looking to rebound from disappointing '99 season
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last year, Maryland started 5-2, its best beginning
since 1984. The Terps weren't wondering whether they were going to
bowl but what their choices might be. But a funny thing happened to
the Terps on the way to postseason play. They didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   After the auspicious start, Ron Vanderlinden's crew was
dispatched by Duke, N.C. State, Florida State and Virginia in the
last month of the season and went home with a 5-6 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 5-2, we thought we were pretty secure with a bowl spot,''
said senior free safety Shawn Forte, an all-America candidate. ``It
was so close last year and it actually came down to the last drive
in the last game of the year against Virginia. That was a
heart-breaker. We left everything on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland has several things going for it this time around.
</P>
<P>
   The first is senior tailback LaMont Jordan, who is being touted
as a Heisman Trophy candidate. Jordan rushed for 1,632 yards last
season, averaged 6.1 yards per carry and rushed for 148.4 yards per
game, fifth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The only potential problem is that Jordan must do well in summer
school to be eligible. Although the Maryland folks are playing down
Jordan's situation, the word is that the coaching staff is holding
its breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``LaMont's situation is going to be fine,'' Forte said. ``Look,
we're ready to get it on, move on to 2000. LaMont is a vital part
of our team, and I'm not worried. He's working out, and he looks
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is a legitimate Heisman candidate, Forte said. ``The
first thing you notice about him is his feet,'' he said. ``He's
really shifty for a person his size. I think it's everybody's dream
to be on the same field with a Heisman Trophy candidate. This is
great for us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's quarterback, freshman Cal McCall, might not be the
starter this fall. McCall completed 52 percent of his passes for
1,264 yards and rushed for 256 yards. But transfer Shaun Hill was
rated one of the top junior-college quarterbacks in the nation at
Hutchinson Junior College in Kansas, and Hill is listed as a
co-starter on the Terp depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta native Latrez Harrison, the quarterback who rejected
Auburn to go to Maryland, is no better than No. 3 on the depth
chart.
</P>
<P>
   The Terp defense was in the middle of the ACC in 1999, but it
might suffer from the absence of All-American cornerback Lewis
Sanders, who went early to the NFL. Maryland's defensive line is
being rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   But Forte said Maryland has strengths. ``Linebacker is going to
be a strong suit,'' he said. ``We're going to put more emphasis on
throwing the ball. Losing our last four games last year has been
nothing but a motivator. There's been a steady progression, and
we've gotten better every year. We're right on course.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte has set his own goal. ``Our students tore down the goal
posts last year after a big basketball win,'' he said. ``Maybe we
can get a football win for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
