<HEADER>
A2026 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KASHMIR-MASSACRES-BOS     08-03 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-MASSACRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACRES MAR TALKS BETWEEN INDIA, KASHMIRI SEPARATISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTISINGHPORA, India _ This week an end to a half century of
violence finally seemed within reach in the Kashmir Valley, the
strategic Himalayan region over which nuclear rivals India and
Pakistan have fought two wars.
</P>
<P>
   After the largest group of separatists fighting Indian rule
declared a ceasefire last week, India reciprocated, and Thursday
sat down with the militant group for the first peace talks since a
deadly rebellion erupted in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But even before negotiations began, powerful forces struck, in
an attempt to derail an armistice. In nine attacks over a 24-hour
period that ended Wednesday night, more than 100 people lay
slaughtered across Jammu and Kashmir state _ the worst single day
of massacres of unarmed civilians in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   As with so much of the violence that has wracked this verdant
valley, there is scant proof of who is behind the bloodshed. But,
by Indian army and Kashmiri estimates, from 29,000 to 70,000
civilians have been killed in the uprising.
</P>
<P>
   India blamed bands of Pakistan-supported Muslim militants who
opposed last week's ceasefire declared by the largest guerrilla
group, the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen. The militants denied it, saying
their targets are military, not civilian. Pakistan accused
``renegade elements'' of India's security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee vowed to go forward
with peace efforts, even as his military forces announced a major
assault Thursday to rout out the suspected killers. Vajpayee's
envoy held historic, first-time talks with the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen,
but Hezb-ul's leadership threatened to revoke the ceasefire by
Tuesday if India refuses to include Pakistan in negotiations, a
condition New Delhi has long opposed.
</P>
<P>
   New Delhi regards Kashmir _ a former princely state whose Hindu
ruler acceded to Indian rule after an invasion by armed Pakistanis
_ as a part of the Indian state. Pakistan sees Kashmir, India's
only Muslim-majority state, as part of the Islamic nation of
Pakistan born out of the partition of India in 1947. A large number
of Muslim Kashmiris used to favor Pakistan, but many are by now so
disillusioned and tired of the carnage that they want independence
from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   With each new massacre, more Kashmiris lose trust in authorities
who claim to represent their interests _ Indian security forces,
Kashmiri separatists, and Pakistanis who raise a battlecry for a
free Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   In Chattisinghpora, just a few miles from two of this week's
attacks, residents can feel the pain of the newest victims more
acutely than most. It was here one night in late March that men in
fatigues burst into the isolated village at the end of muddy
hilltop road brandishing weapons. They went from one
earthen-floored home to another in this village of 300 families,
and hustled out 36 Sikh men _ a religious sect that has been
neutral and previously untouched by the insurgency. Along a fence
next to the Sikh temple and in front of a shrine, the attackers
lined up the men and shot them.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes of the victims lie in silent testimony beneath the
brick temple wall where bullet holes are still visible. At the end
of a rugged path where the other 18 were slain, a blackboard lists
their names.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, on a visit to New Delhi when the massacre
occurred, denounced the violence, and Prime Minister Vajpayee
immediately blamed Pakistan-backed militants intent on disrupting
Kashmir. Pakistan accused Indian agents of disguising themselves as
militants to tarnish the image of Muslim separatists and their
supporters in Islamabad during Clinton's visit. Residents of this
traumatized village still don't know who to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The signs are confusing and contraditory. Witnesses say the
attackers wore military-type uniforms, but civilians shoes. They
spoke Urdu, the language of Pakistan _ not the local Kashmiri
dialect, nor Hindi, the language of most Indian security forces _
but they shouted ``Long live India!'' One attacker brandished a
liquor, unimaginable for an Islamic jihad warrior. But the one man
whom locals recognized was a local Muslim militant.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurriyat, a coalition of separatist leaders, ``say the
government is behind the attack. The government says Pakistan is
behind it. We have been betrayed and we don't know who did this,''
said Ravinder Paul Singh, 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were Afghan militants helped by Kashmiri guides,''
declared an inspector with India's Border Security Forces, who was
one of the first to respond to the crime scene. ``Ask yourself: why
would Indian security forces come to attack in uniform? Whey would
they shout pro-India slogans? Why wouldn't they dress in civilian
clothes and shout slogans for Pakistan?''
</P>
<P>
   Bitti Kour, 25, lost her husband, Karnal Singh, a 30-year-old
businessman. Her head covered with a black shawl, she recounted in
a halting voice that the attackers went from house to house at
dusk, rounding up the men of the village and telling their wives
they would be playing a game with them. Fifteen minutes later, she
heard shots and screams, and she rushed out to see the bleeding
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who she believed was responsible, Kour abruptly ended the
conversation when a neighbor interjected that she should keep quiet
to protect herself and her two children. ``We don't suspect
anyone,'' she said curtly.
</P>
<P>
   Local newspapers have their own ideas. The Kashmir Observer
called the string of massacres ``a deep conspiracy against the
people and the state.'' The paper implied Indian forces were behind
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only those on the embattled Indian side of Kashmir who
have been slain under mysterious circumstances. Tens of thousands
who live along the heavily-militarized line separating Indian
Kashmir from Pakistani Kashmir are caught in daily crossfire
between the two militaries, losing their limbs or their lives. Some
villages have endured ambushes. Almost anyone who lives along the
line believes the army on the other side targets civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Abdul Hamid, 70, a farmer from Lanjot village in the
Kotli sector of Pakistan-held Kashmir who lost 14 family members,
including his wife, two sons, one daughter, and four grandchildren
in a midnight assault this year on his tiny home less than 100
yards from Indian military posts.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid had gone to the Pakistani city of Rawalpindi for an eye
operation, and was not at home asleep like the rest of his clan
when green-uniformed murderers attacked. His eyes still go
bloodshot and wet with tears when he is asked to speak about the
attacks months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family has been slaughtered!'' he cried, beating his chest
with fists as he crouched over the 14 graves _ mounds of earth clad
with white sheets, strands of colored tinsel and plastic flowers,
five of them miniature-sized because the victims were children.
Every morning, Hamid prays for an hour over the bodies, raising his
open palms heavenward to ask for God's guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid and soldiers from the nearby Pakistani military posts are
sure Indian commandos were responsible for the dastardly act.
Indian officers say they would never target civilians, and blame
Pakistani soldiers and militants for killing their own civilians to
sway Kashmiri opinion against peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is behind them, the recurrent massacres have served to
entrench public opinion against soldiers and authorities on both
sides, and the militants who have made life miserable, hardening
most Kashmiri people's resolve that their land will be safe and
peaceful only when it is free.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want independence until death,'' declared Muhammad Yunus,
40, who lost his wife and two children and was himself injured in
the Lanjot massacre. ``I had only one son and he was sacrificed for
Kashmir. If I had 10 sons, I would sacrifice them all. Till the
last drop of blood, we want independence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
