<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-POLE0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace maneuvers for position
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rusty Wallace won at Pocono Raceway two weeks ago and
raced into contention for the Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Pennsylvania 500, Wallace jumped from ninth to
fifth in the points standings. The 1989 Winston Cup champion now
trails leader Bobby Labonte by 268 points with 15 races remaining.
</P>
<P>
   At Indianapolis Motor Speedway, site of Saturday's Brickyard
400, Wallace has five top-10 finishes, but he has not won in the
six years of the event. He was fourth in the 1994 inaugural event
and second the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of track position will be at an all-time high
this weekend at Indy,'' Wallace said. ``Like I've said so often
this season, these cars are so sensitive to track position, it's
unreal. If you get behind a car, you lose all your down force on
your front end, and you can't hardly pass cars. So even if you put
four tires on and think you're going to have better tires than
everybody else, you get so hurt in aerodynamics that it really
doesn't show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where all the big-time importance with pit strategy
comes into play, and, hopefully, (crew chief) Robin (Pemberton) and
our team will make the best decisions on race day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's performance at Pocono made up for a bad decision in
the June race there. He ruined his chances to win when he insisted
on taking four tires instead of the two that the rest of the
leaders took. Wallace finished a disappointing 10th and
second-guessed his strategy. After his win in the next Pocono race,
two weeks ago, Wallace was so excited in the post-race news
conference that he said the team could have five victories by the
end of the season. He has two, with the other coming in the first
Bristol race.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has had excellent qualifying runs, with seven poles this
season. But he has not won after starting first.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
