<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-SCOOTER-COLUMN     08-03 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-SCOOTER-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOOT OR BE SCOOTERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, Aug. 3, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you dropped from another planet or a distant time zone into
the United States of the year 2000, the first thing you'd ask would
be: where is everybody going, and why are they using so many weird
contraptions to get there?
</P>
<P>
   We've never had so many options when it comes to getting around.
As I roamed the Chicago metropolitan area over the weekend, I
tallied up nearly 20 different modes of transportation, from the
radical to the relaxing to the ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   It started when I was strolling downtown Chicago on Saturday
morning and I encountered a family of five on Wabash Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Mom and Dad were holding long cardboard boxes; each of their
three children was carrying a shiny metal device. At first I
thought they had golf clubs _ but when they began to unfold the
contraptions, I realized the excited kids were new owners of those
lightweight scooters that have been popping up everywhere on city
and suburban streets in the last several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Made of aluminum or stainless steel, these non-motorized
scooters weigh only about 6 pounds and can be collapsed into a
tight bundle that resembles a folded-up telescope.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent research revealed that stores from Wal-Mart to Jewel
Osco to Sharper Image have been stocking various models with names
like the Razor Rollerboard, which retails for about $75-$125. (More
advanced versions can go for several hundred dollars.)
</P>
<P>
   The lightweight scooter craze was launched a couple of years ago
in Asian cities like Tokyo and Hong Kong. Now there are more than
1.2 million scooters on the streets of Japan, while in Hong Kong
there's been an outbreak of counterfeit scooter sales _ cheap,
unsafe knockoffs.
</P>
<P>
   By late last year, the fad had spread to Europe; now it's
sweeping North America. Huffy's Micro Scooter, for example,
currently is the top-selling sporting goods product in the United
States. In Calgary, one store sold its entire supply of 600 Oxygen
scooters in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I tried to navigate some side streets with one of
these scooters _ a top-level, $279, K2 Kickboard, on loan from a
Chicago dealer who told me he gets 20 calls a day from prospective
scooter buyers, and can barely keep up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after I started pushing and gliding, I was accosted by
three hair-dyed boys on their bikes who were begging to try it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to your room,'' I told them.
</P>
<P>
   I felt like an idiot as I zigged and zagged down the block, and
eyewitnesses confirmed that I looked like an idiot. For kids and
twentysomethings, though, I think these things are great. It's sort
of like surfing on pavement.
</P>
<P>
   So now the scooter-cruisers have joined the parade of busy
travelers jamming our sidewalks, roads and waterways. Try to walk _
just walk _ along any lakefront or popular tourist area in a major
city these days. It's an exercise in dodging, weaving, bumping,
stopping, starting, stopping again, starting again and reacting to
the warnings of ``On your left!'' and ``Right behind you!'' from
bicyclists and in-line skaters and, I don't know, goofs on Pogo
sticks and unicycles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the streets of the city, you have pedestrians,
power-walkers, parents with strollers, joggers, joggers who push
their babies in three-wheeled devices, skateboarders,
motorcyclists, more in-line skaters, bicyclists, buses,
automobiles, taxis, vans, SUVs, construction trucks,
horse-and-carriage drivers, motorized scooters and roaming bands of
hacky-sackers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still waiting for my personal jet-pack to be invented, as
was promised by the futurists of the 1960s and 1970s, and it better
happen soon. We're running out of room on the ground and in the
water.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
