<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-ARMEY-JOKE-0804-C     08-03 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-ARMEY-JOKE-0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARMEY MAKES ANTI-GAY JOKE WITH HOMOSEXUAL LAWMAKER AS THE PUNCH
LINE
 &HT;    Eds: Note language in 6th graf.
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, made
an anti-gay joke to a group of journalists at a party here that
used Rep. Barney Frank's, D-Mass., homosexuality as the punch line.
</P>
<P>
   The remark was the second time Armey has referred to Frank's
sexuality to journalists, and it occurred in the context of a
Republican convention that was tightly scripted to highlight the
GOP's inclusiveness. The convention, which ended Thursday, featured
an openly gay speaker, Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Armey spokeswoman Michelle Davis said the comment was taken out
of context. But, after talking to her boss, she confirmed that
Armey had made a joke to five political cartoonists and humorist
Dave Barry when they met at a crowded late-night party on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mike Luckovich, the Pulitzer Prize-winning Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's cartoonist, the following exchange occurred:
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you really Dick Armey?'' Barry asked.
</P>
<P>
   Armey replied, ``Yes, I am Dick Armey. And if there is a dick
army, Barney Frank would want to join up.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry reported in his own column today (Friday) that Armey told
a dirty joke linked to his name, but omitted any reference to
Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the Armey spokeswoman, was not at the party. But she got
Armey's account before returning a telephone call for this story.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said Armey anticipated that someone in the group would use
the joke and decided to utter it first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad joke and he was just trying to get it over with,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Armey called Frank ``Barney Fag'' in an interview with
broadcast journalists. Armey immediately apologized, saying, ``I
don't use the word in personal conversation. I would not use such
an expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank was traveling Thursday and could not be reached for
comment, said Maria Giesta, an aide in his Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he told Armey that he understood the remark had not
been intended. But Frank said the episode disturbed him. ``But I
could not accept that it was wholly accidental. . . . I just had to
believe that it was somewhere in the back of his mind,'' Frank
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin-themed party Wednesday was a hot ticket among
politicians and journalists covering the convention. It was hosted
by Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Sherman can be e-mailed at: marks(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
