<SLUG> BC-MA-SCOUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST MASS. UNITED WAYS TO RETAIN FUNDING FOR SCOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite national concerns about the Boy Scouts of
America's effort to secure the right to bar gay scout leaders, most
Massachusetts United Way organizations have decided to continue
funding scout troops.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 United Way chapters in Massachusetts, only
Massachusetts Bay has so far cut funding to local Boy Scouts, while
Greater Fall River stands poised to end its scout support next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The moves by the United Way, a leading financial supporter of
the Boy Scouts, follows a US Supreme Court decision in June
allowing the scouts to bar gays as troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Council of Massachusetts United Ways said
Thursday that most of the independent local agencies, while
reviewing policies and meeting with scout leaders, decided to
continue funding their local troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a neutral policy. We believe that these are personal,
moral decisions and the United Way does not have a role in deciding
those things for individuals,'' said Paul Mina, the chairman who is
also president of the United Way of Tri-City, based in Framingham.
His agency donated $130,000 to two scout councils last year.
</P>
<P>
   The two scout councils funded by Tri-City, he said, ``do not
exhibit any homophobic behavior. They are anything but exclusive.
To punish them for the national organization's position is not our
job.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mina said, only 20 of the nation's 1,400 United Ways
have decided to stop funding scout troops since the highest court
found that Boy Scouts of America, a private organization, has the
right to define homosexuality as hurtful to children and ban gays
as troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the United Way of Massachusetts Bay has cut $288,000 from
five local scout councils because of the discriminatory policy of
the Boy Scouts of America. But the funding agency has agreed to
give $240,000 to a popular school-based program traditionally run
by Boy Scouts called Learning for Life, since the scouts agreed to
turn it into a separate entity.
</P>
<P>
   In southeastern Massachusetts, the United Way of Greater Fall
River has told the Moby Dick scout council, as well as 34 other
agencies the United Way supports, that it must sign a revised
anti-discrimination agreement in April 2001 that will specifically
include sexual orientation, or forfeit funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be their decision,'' said Bob Horne, Greater Fall
River's executive director. ``If they do not sign, they are saying
they do not want to be a member of our United Way.'' For the Moby
Dick scouts, that would mean losing $49,000. The Moby Dick council
executive did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Boy Scout membership has grown nationally from 4.3 million in
1997 to nearly 5 million. For 90 years, the organization has
enjoyed a reputation for giving young people a taste of adventure
while promoting personal growth and values, like honesty.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other council leaders, Brock Bigsby, scout executive
for the Boston Minuteman Council, said his council has a
``don't-ask policy'' when it comes to sexual orientation, and has
never discriminated.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the United Way of Massachusetts Bay cut means losing
$220,000, or 10 percent of the council's operating budget, he said.
Minuteman serves 18,300 youngsters in South Boston, Dorchester and
other neighborhoods, as well as 27 neighboring Boston towns, like
Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can imagine the impact that will be felt'' on low-income
children, Bigsby said Thursday. ``I don't know when we will feel
it, but it's coming. I want to make clear that we have always been
in compliance with United Way's policy on diversity and
non-discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Chase, United Way of Massachusetts Bay's senior vice
president for community investment, agreed with Bigsby. But she
said her agency is caught in a dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had two very strong values in conflict,'' Chase said.
``One is the value that no organization should be discriminatory,
and the other is the value that we have as a priority services that
support youth, particularly disadvantaged youth.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the decision to fund the Learning for Life education
program ``mitigates that conflict to some extent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
