<HEADER>
A2042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AMTRAK-GUARANTEE-NYT &LR;      08-03 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-GUARANTEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK TRYING TO RESTORE CONFIDENCE AND BUILD GOODWILL AFTER A
NIGHT OF DELAYS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Pa.)  By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing its first widespread service problem since
adopting a new ``satisfaction guarantee,'' Amtrak says it has had
to give more than 400 passengers coupons good for a free trip,
because of delays of up to five hours on 22 trains on its Northeast
Corridor on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad, trying to build confidence, is throwing extra
equipment into service on Friday to help get people home from the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a tree fell south of Baltimore and knocked power
cables into the signal system, zapping the fuses for a distance of
40 miles. But passengers' reaction to the disruption indicates that
the railroad may not face enormous penalties when widespread delays
occur. While there were approximately 10,000 people on the trains,
only 446 of them, or about 5 percent, asked for coupons good for a
free repeat trip. The railroad announced the ``satisfaction
guarantee'' policy on July 6.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad said it was sending out coupons worth $30,275 in
total, with an average value of about $68.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to put too good a spin on it,'' said William
Schulz, a spokesman for the railroad. ``Clearly this was very
difficult for us, and there are still many people who found this to
be a dreadful situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Train crews gave out free food and beverages from the cafe cars
but ran out of food on many trains; one train that left
Philadelphia at 7:15 p.m. did not reach Washington until nearly 1
a.m., Schulz said. The scheduled time is 1 hour and 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But, Schulz said, the railroad hoped that issuing the service
guarantees would build customer loyalty. ``We have gone out of our
way to publicize what we think is a very bold commitment to our
customers,'' he said. ``We think if you treat them right, they'll
come back. This hasn't changed our thinking one inch.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the railroad believed it had done better than in
previous incidents in keeping passengers informed about the
problem, but was still reviewing what it could do better. One
improvement under consideration, he said, is making it easier for
passengers to leave the train, if dispatchers know that long delays
are likely. For example, he said, passengers bound for home in
Washington but stuck near the station at Baltimore-Washington
International Airport might have chosen to get off and call for
someone to pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of violent thunderstorms and high winds, a tree
between Baltimore and Washington struck the overhead catenary
system, which provides electricity at 12,000 volts for the trains'
motors, and pushed one of the lines into the signal system. ``It
blew 300 fuses over a 40-mile stretch,'' said Schulz. The railroad
had to dispatch diesel engines to pull some electric trains, and
those had to creep along because of lack of a signal system. In
addition, in some places the tracks were under water, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
