<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2046 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CANADA-FREIGHTER-BOS &LR;      08-03 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-FREIGHTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMANDOS SEIZE ROGUE FREIGHTER LOADED WITH MUNITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Helicopter-borne Canadian Navy commandos Thursday
stormed and seized of a rogue American superfreighter in waters
south of Newfoundland, ending a 2 1/2-week high-seas standoff in
which the GTS Katie held hostage a cargo of fighting vehicles,
troop carriers, and other war gear representing 10 percent of
Canada's armored might.
</P>
<P>
   There were no casualties as the 14-member boarding force
rappelled onto the pitching upper deck from a Sea King helicopter
launched from the destroyer HMCS Athabaskan. Freed in the ship's
capture were three Canadian soldiers assigned to guard the
equipment being returned from peacekeeping operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's captain, Vitaly Khlebnikov, in a bid to thwart the
landing, ``violently maneuvered'' the Katie and radioed
international distress signals, said Navy Captain Drew Robertson,
commander of the Athabaskan and operational head of the boarding
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sea King pilot held rock steady and the team was able to
gain control of the vessel within 45 or 50 minutes,'' Robertson
said from the Canadian warship. ``The captain was quite theatrical
in his objections, but otherwise there was no resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Katie was seized in international waters outside Canada's
maritime jurisdiction. Khlebnikov accused Canada of acting
recklessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very dangerous what they do,'' he said by satellite
phone as a Canadian helicopter swooped over the stern. ``We have
500 tons of explosives aboard and my crew is placed in danger by
these Canadians.''
</P>
<P>
   But Canadian officials said the government had no choice but to
act, especially given that the ``hijacked'' cargo included
highly-sophisticated electronics surveillance gear and other
sensitive weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being held hostage, having our equipment held hostage, was
simply unacceptable,'' Defense Minister Art Eggleton told reporters
in Ottawa shortly after the 1:45 p.m. boarding of the cargo ship.
``In the end we had no choice but to take the military option.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the freighter that so stubbornly refused to head
for harbor was steaming across the Gulf of St. Lawrence under close
escort by Canadian warships, bound for a port near Montreal. The
Katie's captain remained at the helm, but course and speed of the
freighter were directed by the Canadian military and the vessel was
expected to dock at Becancouer, Quebec, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States raised no objection to the capture of the
American-owned vessel since the Katie flies under a flag of
convenience, registered in the tiny Caribbean nation of St. Vincent
and Grenadines, and thus is not entitled to US protection in a
commercial dispute. The 23 crew members of the Soviet-built ship
are Ukranians, Russians and Croats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a private shipping company and there is no US military
involvement,'' said Pentagon spokesman Bryan Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   The US Embassy in Ottawa said Washington had been given
assurance that St. Vincent and the Grenadines approved Canada's
plan to board the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Canada acted after being held up to international ridicule for
its reluctance to rescue its military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been made to look fairly ridiculous,'' said retired Col.
Brian MacDonald, a Canadian military analyst. ``It's low comedy _
the country that can't defend the very equipment upon which it
depends for national defense.''
</P>
<P>
   What started as a business bluff by Third Ocean Marine
Navigation Co. of Annapolis, Md. _ owner of the Katie _ had by this
week escalated into a tense showdown involving shipping companies,
the US State Department, the government of St. Vincent and the
Grenadines, and legions of Canadian military personnel, diplomats,
justice ministry lawyers and international commerce officials.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Prime Minister Jean Chretien, after two weeks
of more or less shrugging off the situation, finally slipped into
crisis mode as the standoff turned into a national embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   But the American owners of the Katie refused instructions to
head to port even after Canadian warships arrived on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it took three Canadian warships, an Aurora
surveillance aircraft, helicopters, and, finally, the naval
boarding party to bring the Katie to bay. Before the raid the
750-foot freighter, with its unarmed crew, was shadowed by a trio
of Canadian warships, including the Athabaskan and frigates HMCS
Montreal and HMCS Ville de Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff began on July 18, two days after the Katie was
scheduled to arrive in Becancour, Quebec, to begin unloading the
cargo of 580 armored vehicles and sea container packed with weapons
and more than 500 tons of ammunition. The estimated value of the
cargo is approximately $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Katie, one of the largest and fastest ships in the
world, started tracing giant circles in the fog-shrouded North
Atlantic, refusing to enter Canadian waters for fear, according to
its owner, that the ship would be confiscated in a complicated
financial wrangle with the Canadian firms that acted as
subcontractors for the military.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. ``Flip'' Walters, chief executive for Third Ocean, said the
company was caught between debt and the deep blue sea, with
creditors poised to seize the ship the instant it docked in
Montreal because of payments owed not by Third Ocean itself but
Canadian shipping firms that subcontracted the ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two victims here, the Canadian government and Third
Ocean,'' Walters said. ``We're not pirates, we are not hijackers,
we're a reputable company that has transported (equipment for) the
British Army, the German Army and the US Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If this was cotton bales or Toyotas, we could head
to France or somewhere and auction off the cargo'' to satisfy the
debts apparently owed Third Ocean by a Montreal shipping firm,
Andromeda Navigation. ``But since the cargo belongs to Her
Majesty's Canadian Forces, we're in a desperate spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada once boasted one of the most formidable navies in the
world, but massive budget cuts over the past decade have
drastically reduced the NATO member's military power.
</P>
<P>
   The country is still an enthusiastic participant in UN
peacekeeping operations, but it no longer possesses the heavylift
ships or cargo aircraft to carry its troops to foreign trouble
spots, so it relies on hired civilian vessels, such as the Katie.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Eggleton announced that the Canadian government
is now considering building a fleet of military transport vessels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
