<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2047 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-RDP-ART-2NDLD-WRI     08-03 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RDP-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S SPEECH DEPICTS A CANDIDATE WHO CAN BRIDGE PARTISAN DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES thruout with excerpts from Bush's speech. This early
version will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a story by R.W. Apple
Jr.)  
(ART ADV: Photos, including CVN3, are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ On the final night of the Republican National
Convention, Gov. George W. Bush will argue that the nation's
current wealth provides an opportunity to accomplish reforms and to
transform the nation's politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush will try to use his acceptance speech Thursday
night to present himself as a bipartisan leader who can get things
done, he is also likely to use the opportunity to pursue his fight
with his opponent, Vice President Al Gore, in an effort to further
delineate the contrast between them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush officially became the party's nominee during Wednesday
night's roll-call vote when delegates from Wyoming _ the home state
of his running mate, Richard Cheney _ put him over the 1,034
convention votes needed for a majority. But the big
balloon-dropping celebration will come Thursday night when the last
of the 2,066 delegate votes will be delivered from the floor of the
First Union Center by the Texas delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will seize this moment of American promise,'' Bush planned
to say, according to excerpts of his speech released by the
campaign. ``We will confront the hard issues _ threats to our
national security, threats to our health and retirement security _
before the challenges of our time become crises for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night will be a defining moment in Bush's political
career. He and his speechwriter have been working for weeks on the
acceptance speech that the governor will deliver before a
nationwide audience, albeit one that is likely smaller than in past
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I believe, I know what I want to say, I know what
I want America to hear, and I'm going to give it my best shot and
see what happens,'' Bush told reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides have said he will lay out five priorities for his
presidency on which he will campaign, including reforming Social
Security, increasing military readiness, cutting taxes, improving
education and expanding prescription drug benefits for Medicare
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,900-word speech has been through at least 17 drafts, said
Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman. The campaign hopes the remarks
will signal to the nation that Bush is a different kind of
conservative who has transformed his party so that it can appeal to
groups not traditionally receptive to the Republicans' message.
</P>
<P>
   Although his aides have emphasized the positive themes of Bush's
speech, Hughes acknowledged Bush will needle Gore and lament the
current administration's failure to accomplish critical tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much promise, to no great purpose,'' he was to say,
according to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign said he would also call for improving character and
responsibility, a call meant to be an implicit reminder of the
impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to his arrival here, Bush has become
increasingly aggressive in his criticism of Gore, his Democratic
rival for the presidency, and of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While the attacks on the Clinton-Gore administration are popular
with the Republican rank and file, the Texas governor is also
trying to convince independent voters, who in recent elections have
embraced the centrist position, that Bush has transformed his party
in the same way that Clinton changed his. But Bush must also be
careful not to alienate the conservatives who are the Republicans'
bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of time in the opening days of the convention was
devoted to projecting a centrist image, with issues like
immigration and education dominating, and the stage filled with
racially diverse speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush planned to pick up on these themes as well, arguing that he
would reach out to Americans who feel left out of the current boom
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will extend the promise of prosperity to every forgotten
corner of this country,'' he was to say.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in many previous conventions, candidates in hard-fought
congressional races _ like Rep. Rick Lazio of New York, who is
battling Hillary Rodham Clinton, the first lady, this fall for a
Senate seat from New York _ were kept out of the spotlight. So too
were many elements of the Republicans' battles with President
Clinton over the last six years. Issues like family values,
abortion rights and the culture wars were not showcased.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush used the week leading up to the convention to pacify
conservative delegates. He allowed a plank opposing all abortion
rights to stand and chose a conservative running mate with a voting
record to match.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also making a point of courting people outside the
party. Thursday afternoon, Bush appeared at a luncheon rally for
his wife, Laura, in downtown Philadelphia. At the gathering, Bush
made a point of thanking not only Republicans but also Democrats
who had worked with him and his wife on education issues in Texas.
He said that if he was elected president he would bring a more
positive and bipartisan approach to government.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's campaign said that in his speech, Bush also would
promise to work with Democrats to improve Social Security and early
childhood education. Bush planned to suggest that, as an outsider
to Washington, he could help change the way politics is conducted
in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have enemies to fight,'' the excerpts said. ``And I
have no stake in the bitter arguments of the last few years. I want
to change the tone of Washington to one of civility and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, promises of bipartisanship and civility are not getting
in the way of attacks on his opponent. On Wednesday night, right
after Cheney emphasized Bush's ability to work with the other side,
the vice presidential candidate began a lengthy attack on the
current administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all a little weary of the Clinton-Gore routine,''
Cheney told cheering Republicans. ``But the wheel has turned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
