u p BC-GOP-ECON-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-03 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ECON-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUSH PORTRAYS TAX CUTS AS BOON TO ALL, NOT JUST THE
RICH 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ What Gov. George W. Bush is trying to do with
Republican economic orthodoxy resembles in many ways what President
Clinton has tried to do for Democrats over the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   By emphasizing elimination of the federal budget deficit and the
national debt, Clinton sought to soften the perception, if not
erase it, that Democrats are the party of profligacy and high
taxes. In the end, doing so gave him more freedom to press for
substantially more spending on the issues at the core of the
Democratic agenda, especially health and education.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, Bush is looking to counter the idea that
Republicans stand for sweeping tax cuts that are fiscally reckless
and a boon only to the country club set. As showcased at the
Republican National Convention this week, tax cuts are a prudent
way to spur entrepreneurship, give a boost to people looking to
reach the middle class, and provide an economic pick-me-up should
the long business expansion begin to flag.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal to create individual investment accounts within
Social Security is packaged not as a gift to Wall Street but as an
opportunity for all workers to build wealth in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the Republican call, much heard after Newt Gingrich led
the party to take control of the House in 1994, to shrink the size
and influence of government by starving it of revenues through tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the emphasis here on single mothers, struggling
family farms and aspiring Hispanic small-business owners _ and
although his plan does contain elements intended to help the
working poor _ Bush's tax proposals vary little from traditional
conservatism in giving the biggest tax cuts to those who pay the
most in taxes, by definition the people who make the most money.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than backing off from any of the tenets of supply-side
economics, Bush seems intent on demonstrating that helping people
who have not yet made it economically is perfectly consistent with
helping those who have.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats look at the Bush tax plan and see 43 percent of the
benefits going to the top 1 percent of households by income, those
making more than $319,000 a year, according to Citizens for Tax
Justice, a liberal-leaning research group.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence B. Lindsey, Bush's chief economic adviser, said
Republicans remained focused on the incentives that tax cuts
provide to earn and save more, whether for a waitress earning
$18,000 a year or the entrepreneur who wants to be able to pass a
painstakingly built business along to her heirs without being
subject to a hefty federal estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   So the spotlight at the convention has not been on the usual
parade of supply-side sales people from the ranks of elected
Republican officials, but on working people struggling to attain
some financial security.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my surprise, I discovered the road to financial success had
a toll booth,'' said Kim Jennings, a single mother who was chosen
by the campaign to bring its economic message to life on Wednesday
night. ``The more I worked, and earned, the more the government
took from me in higher taxes. That is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   To Democrats, it is all bunk. They say that Republican economic
policies, whether those offered by Bush or those pursued over the
last six years by the Republican majority in Congress, are mostly
about rewarding the wealthy people and powerful interest groups
that finance Republican campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, they say, Republicans are going about it in a way that
would squander the projected federal budget surpluses and leave
nothing for priorities like adding prescription drug coverage to
Medicare benefits or modernizing schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time there's an option to choose between targeting low-
and middle-income people and giving most of the benefits to the top
20 percent,'' said Laura Tyson, an economic adviser to Vice
President Al Gore, ``the Republican leadership has revealed its
position through its actions,'' by choosing the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Recasting an ideology without sacrificing its core is a tricky
business. In Bush's case, it is made trickier by the prosperous
environment in which he is trying to do it.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Thursday night, Bush emphasized how much more
could be done to take advantage of prosperity, and he suggested
that Clinton and Gore have squandered their chance. And Republicans
are heartened by polls showing that tax cuts are picking up support
from voters as the budget surplus swells.
</P>
<P>
   But to the extent that he emphasizes the substance of economic
policy _ and all signs this week were that he is more interested in
emphasizing character and leadership _ Bush risks not only an
onslaught from Gore over class politics and fiscal rectitude, but
also focusing voters on the fact that the Clinton-Gore years have
been pretty good for most people.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, Bush's vice presidential running mate, illustrated
that risk, no doubt inadvertently, in his speech to the convention
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anyone, Republican or Democrat, seriously believe that
under Mr. Gore, the next four years would be any different from the
last eight?'' Cheney asked.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment at 4 percent, inflation under control, incomes
rising across the board and most indicators of social well-being
improving, Democrats will no doubt be eager to make the case when
they gather for their convention in Los Angeles that the next four
years will in fact be exactly like the last eight if Gore is
elected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
