u f BC-ROCKPORT-AD-COLUMN-NY     08-03 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKPORT-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: SHIRTLESS HUNKS PEDDLING SHOES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An offbeat new campaign embraces the philosophy of the comedian
Jeff Foxworthy in declaring: ``No shirt. No shoes. . . . No
problem!'' What in the world are the shirtless hunks and hunkettes
peddling in the ads? Shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes in question are made by the Rockport Co., a division
of Reebok International known for selling comfortable footwear that
is, as the brand name implies, rock-solid, rock-steady _ and about
as stylish as Plymouth Rock. The campaign, by AG Worldwide in New
York, an agency that specializes in fashion advertising, seeks to
change perceptions of the Rockport label as the company embarks on
a redesign of its offerings to make them seem less stodgy.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign begins with print advertisements, photographed in
arty black and white, that depict bare feet being massaged,
caressed and nuzzled by attractive nude young men and women. There
will be outdoor posters in a similar vein, followed by a revamped
Web site and television commercials. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rockport account has been more peripatetic than a hiker
climbing a mountain range in the company's shoes, moving in less
than six years from Bartle Bogle Hegarty in London to the Leo
Burnett unit of the B Com3 Group in Chicago to Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP;
Partners in New York to AG. The most recent previous campaign came
from Kirshenbaum Bond, which handled the account for three years
before resigning in September. Those ads, featuring personages
ranging from Muhammad Ali to Ru Paul to Spalding Gray, carried this
theme: ``Be comfortable. Uncompromise. Start with your feet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of `uncompromise' was a strong one,'' said Stefanie
Lucas, recently named vice president for marketing at Rockport in
Marlborough, Mass., `because it talked about being uncompromising
in the way you act and think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We did research showing consumers knew the brand was practical
and well made, but there was really no emotional connection,'' she
added. ``We knew that's what we needed to build and that's what
drew us to AG and Peter Arnell.''
</P>
<P>
   Her reference was to Arnell, chairman and executive creative
director at AG, which in March became part of the Draft Worldwide
unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies. AG, also known for
developing and burnishing brand identities for marketers like
Banana Republic, Hanes hosiery, Tommy Hilfiger, Donna Karan,
Ray-Ban and Samsung, will introduce the theme ``Don't just walk''
to embody the new image of Rockport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're establishing a lifestyle versus pushing a shoe,'' said
Arnell, who joined Lucas for a recent interview to offer a preview
of the campaign, which is to be accompanied by a redesign by AG of
the Rockport corporate identity including its logo, packages and
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign is not driven by the seasons'' like other
fashion-oriented advertising, Arnell said, ``but by a bigger idea,
adoring the foot, expressing love for the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   The footwear category ``is getting a lot more crowded,'' he
added, ``and the company felt it needed to break through.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its second-quarter earnings last week, Reebok
reported that sales at Rockport fell 6.9 percent, to $96.8 million,
compared with $104 million in the period a year earlier. In a
statement, Paul Fireman, chairman and chief executive of Reebok,
directed the attention of analysts to Rockport's plans to introduce
footwear that will ``comprise a significant portion of the Rockport
product line and provide the consumer with new and refreshed looks
while still adhering to Rockport's heritage of engineered comfort
and fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping customers who like Rockports for those features while
attracting shoppers who buy footwear on looks is a trickier task
than Sarah Jessica Parker faces when walking in high heels on ``Sex
and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would want people to say Rockport is modern but still
comfortable,'' Lucas said. The budget for the campaign for the rest
of 2000 is about $3 million; spending is to increase significantly
next year, when four TV commercials featuring unclad and unshod
models like the print ads and posters are to begin running.
</P>
<P>
   While the folks in the spots will be as barefoot as Robert
Redford at the end of the Neil Simon film set around Washington
Square Park, two will include shots of Rockport shoes.
</P>
<P>
   If one model in the Rockport campaign looks familiar, Arnell
said, it is because he appeared in ads, posters and packages that
Arnell designed and produced for Samsung. The model, Charles
Andrews, was also shirtless then, toting a microwave oven.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someday, Andrews will land a campaign for Arrow. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
