u p BC-GORE-VEEP-NYT &LR;      08-03 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE NARROWS LIST OF RUNNING MATES TO 7 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FIGURE EIGHT ISLAND, N.C. _ Winding up a weeklong vacation by
the sea, Vice President Al Gore on Thursday said that he had
narrowed his list of potential running mates to six plus one ``wild
card,'' for a total of seven.
</P>
<P>
   The list, according to Democratic officials, consists of Sens.
John Kerry of Massachusetts, Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, John
Edwards of North Carolina and Evan Bayh of Indiana, as well as Rep.
Dick Gephardt of Missouri and Gov. Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's down to six, with one wild card that I haven't completely
eliminated,'' Gore told reporters who gathered on the beach for a
quick photo opportunity of him and his wife, Tipper, walking
hand-in-hand along the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the six are believed to be on the list for strategic
purposes _ that is, to suggest that Gore is looking at a woman, for
example, when in fact he is not. Both Shaheen and Gephardt have
said they are not interested in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Officials close to the campaign said that all six had spoken
with Warren Christopher, who is heading Gore's search process, and
had been fully vetted.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said that clearly off the list at this point
were former Sen. George Mitchell of Maine, Sen. Bob Graham of
Florida and Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa. All three are in their 60s and
the selection of any one of them would run counter to the Gore
campaign's assertion that it wants to present an energetic ticket
that is oriented toward the future.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been hashing over his possibilities and looking for
political feedback from his family, Christopher, Bill Daley, his
new campaign chairman, and Alexis Herman, the secretary of labor.
It is not clear how much actual winnowing he has done while on
vacation, since he said on the way here that his list contained
fewer than 10 people, and now it contains barely seven.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear whether there really is a serious ``wild card''
candidate. Gore would not say whether the ``wild card'' was someone
whose name was in the public mix of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Daley said that there would be no surprises. ``Nobody's
sneaking under the radar,'' Daley said in an interview. Another
Democratic official suggested that the purpose of mentioning a wild
card at this point was to allow Gore to ``keep his options open.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley said that he expected Gore, who is to leave North Carolina
on Friday morning for a campaign stop in Chicago before heading
back to Washington, was close to making up his mind. ``He's going
to come back Friday, and in my opinion, if he's not 100 percent
there, he'll be 80 percent there.'' He added: ``I know he hasn't''
made a decision. The announcement is scheduled for noon on Tuesday
in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Daley also dismissed a plea by Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota,
the minority leader, to steer clear of naming a Democratic senator
whose replacement would then be picked by a Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not stop him from going with somebody who he thinks
he's comfortable with and is the best candidate,'' Daley said of
Daschle's entreaty. ``Be great if he could pick somebody from a
Democratic state, but as you know, there aren't a hell of a lot of
Democratic states out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley shrugged off the daily boomlets of different names,
attributing those to lobbying done on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not based upon anything that's coming from Gore,
okay?'' Daley said. ``Those of us who are involved in this sort of
suck it in and analyze it and pass it on to him and say, `Here are
three people who called saying they really think the Bob Kerrey
idea is a great idea, here's why, so if you're still open to
people, figure this in.' So it bounces within him, but this boomlet
is not coming from him or coming from us.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those with an edge in the lobbying department is Edwards.
A number of his advisers in his successful 1998 Senate race, in
which he ousted the incumbent Republican, Lauch Faircloth, are
among Gore's top campaign officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Edwards supporters say that the 47-year-old trial lawyer is
the candidate who would most reinforce Gore's message against the
Republican ``old guard.'' He also happens to come from a state with
a Democratic governor.
</P>
<P>
   The major drawback to selecting Edwards is his relative
inexperience. He has been in the Senate only two years, and his
selection could undermine Gore's repeated assertion that the most
important criterion in a running mate is that the person be ready
to take over from Day One.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore operatives are working on a way to sell Edwards
instantly to voters as someone who is capable of becoming
president. One suggestion is that immediately upon the
announcement, a number of longtime Democratic senators make
testimonials to Edwards's brilliance and how he represents a
once-in-a-generation talent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
