<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-TOM-SELLECK-IN-RUNNING-MATES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNING WILD: TOM SELLECK CAMPAIGNS IN `RUNNING MATES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Tom Selleck
with Nancy Travis in scenes from ``Running Mates.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    'Tis the season of balloons, straw hats, streamers and confetti,
of elephants and donkeys, of smoke-filled rooms and gas-filled
speeches.
 &HT;    In short, it's political-convention season, and sandwiched
between the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia and the
Democratic gathering in Los Angeles, a new presidential candidate
is stepping up to the microphones: Gov. James Reynolds Pryce of
Michigan.
 &HT;    Never heard of him? Well, he looks a lot like Tom Selleck minus
the mustache.
 &HT;    He's a fictional character, of course _ the protagonist in
``Running Mates,'' the Turner Network Television original movie
that will air on Aug. 13, starring a clean-shaven Selleck as a
40-something Harvard Law School graduate, former congressman and
current governor, a man who has spent his entire adult life in
politics.
 &HT;    Pryce has a reputation for up-front honesty _ as a congressman,
he even voted to close an Army base in his own district. He's also
pretty smart, though _ he saw to it that a factory opened on the
site of the closed base, bringing three times as many jobs to the
area as the closing had lost.
 &HT;    Now Pryce is a presidential candidate focused on
campaign-finance reform, and has emerged from the primaries with a
lock on the nomination. The only question left: Who will be his
running mate?
 &HT;    It's down to the wire between two senators, one a Washington
insider in the pocket of big business, dead set against finance
reform, and the other an idealist who refused to take
special-interest money for his own presidential campaign and,
unsurprisingly, was forced to drop out for lack of funds.
 &HT;    Will Pryce stay true to his principles and pick the straight
arrow, or will he compromise with the forces of ``politics as
usual'' in the interest of winning the presidency?
 &HT;    ``I think most people run for office for good reasons and noble
purposes,'' says the very electable-looking Selleck, still sans
mustache as he visits a hotel in Pasadena, Calif., to promote the
movie _ he doesn't wear one in the film because politicians rarely
do, recalling that the last presidential candidate to sport a
mustache was Thomas Dewey, who beat Harry Truman only in the
newspaper headlines.
 &HT;    ``Pryce does a couple of things differently from the norm that
are extremely refreshing,'' Selleck continues. ``For one, he does
not claim to have the magic bullet or the magic solution. He also
doesn't say that the sky will fall if his opposition wins.
 &HT;    ``But he knows that people running for office have been put in
situations where they have to choose between the money and the
influence of the large corporations and what the people want,'' the
actor says. ``Ultimately candidates need to decide how much they
are willing to compromise themselves and their agendas to get into
office.''
 &HT;    Helping Pryce stay on the straight and narrow are four powerful
women _ each of them, coincidentally, past or present romantic
partners. His wife Jenny (Nancy Travis) apparently doesn't mind his
continuing professional relationships with his campaign manager
(Laura Linney), a Hollywood mogul's powerful wife (Teri Hatcher)
and the slightly hysterical wife (Faye Dunaway) of the powerful
senator (Robert Culp) who is Pryce's mentor.
 &HT;    At the very least, the arrangement testifies to the governor's
political skills! Even if it isn't very plausible.
 &HT;    Executive producer Al Ruddy, himself a veteran of the Hollywood
political trenches, says while these four and women like them are
the faces, the brains and often the brawn behind political success
stories, they virtually never win power in their own right.
 &HT;    ``The fact that has always intrigued me about women in politics,
especially in Hollywood, is that they have no power,'' Ruddy says.
``They throw all the parties, like the `Come to Barbra Streisand's
home to hear her sing' fund-raiser for the Democratic National
Committee. But the truth in fact is, come the first of December,
the women are out for another four years. It was a fascinating idea
to develop in this movie.''
 &HT;    If ``Running Mates'' seems to have a better grasp of political
realities than a typical television movie, that's probably because
of Ruddy's partner, executive producer Gerald Rafshoon. After all,
Rafshoon has been there: He ran Jimmy Carter's successful campaign
for the presidency, then became Carter's White House communications
director.
 &HT;    ``I can personally vouch for some of the incidents that happen
in the picture that have their match in real life,'' Rafshoon says.
``The film was actually developed before I came along, but I added
to it some personal reminiscences of conventions. I did two of them
for Governor Carter and then President Carter, and there were some
actual incidents that we were able to put in there and just sort of
add the real feeling, as well as some current issues.''
 &HT;    Rafshoon says that even before the success of NBC's ``The West
Wing,'' nominated for 18 Emmys this season, Hollywood was
comfortable with politics and politicians. Actors understand
politicians, he says, and vice versa.
 &HT;    ``You get to the pinnacle of politics or of show business, and
there's a lot of people you can't run around with,'' Rafshoon says.
``You're comfortable with these people, because you don't have to
worry about a sense of awe. You don't have to worry about not
understanding when the cameras are around.
 &HT;    ``And the Hollywood people are not like the fat cats who want to
give $100 million to do away with environmental concerns,'' he
adds. ``They are political activists who are sincerely interested
in issues that really don't do anything for them personally.''
 &HT;    The film is obviously timely, with Pryce choosing his running
mate just as George W. Bush and Al Gore are doing the same.
Neither, however, is using the criteria that Selleck _ who says
he's been a registered independent for 10 years _ would apply to
such a search.
 &HT;    ``The answers I want to hear from a political candidate in
today's world are `I don't know' and `That's none of your
business,''' Selleck says. ``I'd probably vote for that person.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
