<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO POLITICAL VETERANS VIE FOR GEORGIA'S VACANT SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The unexpected race to replace the late Sen. Paul
Coverdell has become a contest between two of the best-known names
from Georgia's political past, both of whom are nearing 70 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, former Sen. Mack Mattingly became the leading
Republican in the race after Lewis Jordan, an airline executive,
announced he would not run. Mattingly, 69, will face former Gov.
Zell Miller, 68, a Democrat who was recently appointed to fill
Coverdell's seat until the Nov. 7 election.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, 61, a Republican, died of a brain hemorrhage on July
18. Gov. Roy E. Barnes persuaded Miller to assume the seat last
week, hoping that Miller's lingering popularity with voters would
keep lesser-known Republicans from entering the race.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked _ a large group of the state's Republican
congressmen spent 10 days wrestling with the risk of giving up safe
seats to challenge Miller, and none decided to make the race. Party
leaders turned to Mattingly, hoping his name recognition would help
raise money quickly to compete against Miller's head start.
</P>
<P>
   But Mattingly, who served one term in the Senate before being
defeated in 1986, was never as popular in the state as Miller.
Several national Republican leaders urged the state party to hold
out for a younger, more forceful candidate, which led to Jordan's
brief interest in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, chairman of the National
Republican Senatorial Committee, said earlier this week that Jordan
was the stronger candidate because he was willing to spend $3
million of his own fortune on the race. In a television interview,
he said Mattingly could not win, and would not get any financial
help from the national party.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 56, was the founder of ValuJet Airlines, which later
changed its name to AirTran Airways. He has spent the week in
Philadelphia at the Republican National Convention, hoping to win
over Georgia's delegation. But given Mattingly's firm decision to
run, Jordan was eventually convinced that having two Republicans on
the ballot would increase Miller's chances of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the interest of party unity, and after careful
consideration of what I believe is in the best interest of my
family, I have chosen not to run,'' he said in a written statement
issued by his office late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The special election is technically nonpartisan, with no party
affiliations listed on the ballot. Three other lesser-known
candidates have also entered the race, and if no one gets more than
half the vote, there will be a runoff between the top two
candidates on Nov. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly, a member of the party's conservative wing, ran a
lackluster re-election campaign in 1986, for which he apologized
six years later in a letter to supporters. ``I am not a good
politician,'' he said in the letter, written when he was briefly
considering another run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He decided not to run for the Senate that year, saying he did
not feel committed to the race, and has otherwise kept a low
political profile. In 1987, he was named NATO's assistant
secretary-general for defense support, and in 1992 President George
Bush appointed him to be ambassador to the Seychelles. Last summer,
he became a paid lobbyist for the defense contractor Lockheed
Martin, urging former colleagues in the Senate to help preserve the
company's $65 billion F-22 stealth fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Clay, the chairman of the state Republican Party, said he
was relieved that the party had settled on a single candidate, but
made it clear he was aware of the difficult road ahead for
Mattingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a tough situation, but Mack knows how to run a race,
and that's important when you've only got 90 days against a 45-year
political veteran like Zell Miller,'' Clay said. ``Hey, there ain't
no perfect candidate, but at least we're all behind one candidate
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
