A2072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MATTINGLY-PROFILE0804     08-03 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTINGLY-PROFILE0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Party activist raises profile again as Senate candidate
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former U.S. Sen. Mack Mattingly took the scenic route
back to St. Simons Island after losing his seat in Washington 14
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A stint in Belgium as a NATO official, then an ambassadorship to
the Seychelles, an island nation off the eastern coast of Africa,
capped off a resume filled with roles as a GOP party-builder in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But once back in coastal Georgia, where the Indiana native has
lived for four decades, Mattingly was expected by his friends to
stay put, content to continue his role as a behind-the-scenes
player in Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to ask him, 'Mack, when are we going to run another
campaign?' `` said Betty Jones, a former vice chairman of the state
GOP who worked in Mattingly's successful 1980 Senate bid. ``He'd
say, 'Been there, done that.' He didn't have a clue about getting
back into politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the man who defeated Democratic icon Herman Talmadge two
decades ago to become the first Republican elected to the U.S.
Senate from Georgia since Reconstruction is hoping to vanquish
another venerable Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly, 69, was one of the first candidates to qualify
Wednesday to challenge newly appointed U.S. Sen. Zell Miller in a
Nov. 7 special election to fill the remaining four years of the
late Sen. Paul Coverdell's term. Coverdell died July 18 from a
brain hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   Even state and national GOP leaders admit Mattingly faces an
uphill climb against the popular former governor.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly's name hasn't been on the ballot in Georgia since the
1986 Senate race he narrowly lost to Democrat Wyche Fowler. Since
then, thousands of new residents have moved to Georgia and the
Atlanta suburbs, where Mattingly found much of his support for the
1980 upset against Talmadge. And most of those newcomers are
unfamiliar with the former office equipment salesman.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time, though, that Mattingly has faced a
tough race.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Mattingly was a political novice running against
four-term incumbent Talmadge, the last of a Georgia political
dynasty who'd been tarnished by alcoholism, a messy divorce and a
Senate investigation into his finances.
</P>
<P>
   Talmadge entered the general election campaign damaged, from a
bitter Democratic primary with Miller, to face Mattingly. It wasn't
until the last suburban votes were counted the morning after the
election that Mattingly seized victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really thought we'd win,'' said Matt Towery, a
political analyst and former state legislator who began his
political career writing speeches for Mattingly. ``But Mattingly
never, ever believed he'd lost. I can understand why he believes
this is doable because he's faced more daunting odds.''
</P>
<P>
   But that 1980 victory was short-lived. After one six-year term,
Mattingly's Senate career ended in a loss to Fowler, whom he'd
tried, unsuccessfully, to brand as a liberal congressman from
Atlanta who skipped too many votes in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing Fowler's voting record, however, meant Mattingly had
to spend time in the Capitol casting votes himself in the weeks
before the election, rather than campaigning in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got bad advice, and he took it,'' said Jay Morgan, a former
GOP state director. ``The thing that is discomforting to a lot of
GOP leaders is they don't know which Mattingly they will get on the
ballot this time. Will it be the insightful Mattingly or will we
get the Senate candidate we had in 1986?''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat didn't end Mattingly's political career. He was
appointed to NATO as the assistant secretary general for defense
support, helping U.S. allies coordinate arms programs. Later,
President Bush tapped Mattingly as the U.S. ambassador to the
Seychelles.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, Mattingly has spent much of his time
serving on a handful of public and nonprofit boards. But in
Republican circles his name was never forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   A former state party chairman installed during the Gerald Ford
years, Mattingly is one of the GOP's most reliable workers.
Applauded for his political instincts, he was among the triumvirate
_ including Coverdell and Newt Gingrich, the future U.S. House
speaker _ who met regularly during the late 1970s and early '80s to
guide the embryonic party in Georgia toward grass-roots organizing
rather than an emphasis only on presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   A low-key figure with a dry sense of humor and gift more for
organization than oratory, Mattingly continued regular briefings
with Coverdell after Republicans seized power in Congress in the
mid-1990s. Dot Burns, who headed Coverdell's campaign committee,
said Mattingly talked with the late senator weekly and would have
been Coverdell's choice for a successor.
</P>
<P>
   Though he loved trav
</P>
</TEXT>
