<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARTHLINK-BREWER0804-     08-03 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK-BREWER0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring founder ponders next move
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former EarthLink Chairman Charles Brewer seemed in a
chipper mood Thursday as he was leaving the Commerce Club monthly
board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   His sudden departure from EarthLink on Wednesday appeared to
have lifted a burden on his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to be freed up to do something new,'' Brewer said.
``For me, this is a good thing, not a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, the charismatic founder of MindSpring _ which merged
with EarthLink in February _ has become one of Atlanta's leading
citizens of the new economy. How his departure from the Internet
service provider will affect Brewer's involvement in the community
and EarthLink's commitment to Atlanta are understandable concerns.
</P>
<P>
   As for his role in Atlanta, Brewer said he's not going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bailing,'' he said, adding that he plans to have a
Midtown office close to his home.
</P>
<P>
   As for his plans for the future, Brewer said, ``I want to
accomplish something that's worthwhile, important and makes a
difference. That might be starting another business or something
else. It might be more than one thing. I'm at a point now where I
can choose to do something. And making money is not a big
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed more about his next move in life, Brewer, 41,
acknowledged that he probably will start a new business, just like
he started MindSpring in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably better at starting something than managing,'' he
said. ``I have a lot of advantages that I didn't have when I
started MindSpring. I'm a lot smarter in business than I was then.
I have a lot more capital. And I have a lot more relationships and
contacts. That would definitely give me a good head start.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer really did not want to discuss the particulars of what
happened after the merger with EarthLink that prompted him to
leave, sell all his stock and have no official role with the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to make a clean break,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer did say he had placed a portion of his stock before the
sale into his charitable foundation, and that he and his wife,
Jenny Brewer, will work on philanthropy together.
</P>
<P>
   As to the future of EarthLink in Atlanta, Brewer said, ``I would
be shocked if the headquarters didn't stay in Atlanta.'' And he
said he would expect Gary Betty, EarthLink's chief executive who
has a home in Atlanta and intends to move his main office here, to
take on a larger community role.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good, capable people working in management
at EarthLink,'' Brewer said. ``I certainly wish them well.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brewer is busy with his two young children (one of 13
months and one a week old) and negotiating a lease for his new
office.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Brewer's laid-back style is not going to
change despite his estimated worth of nearly $100 million as
reported in Forbes magazine. His three-legged dog, Louie, will
continue to be his trusted companion, and expect his office to have
some of his trademark junk furniture he bought when he first went
in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no new office that does not allow Louie. That's
nonnegotiable,'' Brewer said. ``The plastic chairs broke. But I
still have the plastic table. I think they will let me keep that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the board meeting at the Commerce Club, he drove away in
his electric vehicle _ yet one more example of Brewer's independent
and progressive style.
</P>
<P>
   So while EarthLink will lose Brewer's charming and humorous
personality, Atlanta will not.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
