<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-TV-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      08-03 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TV-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY FALTERS AS CONVENTION SPEAKER, GIVING BUSH EASY ACT TO
FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush had an on-screen audition Thursday night for the
role of president, and his performance was helped by an unwanted
piece of luck. The previous night's acceptance speech by the vice
presidential nominee, Dick Cheney, gave Bush an easy act to top.
</P>
<P>
   Speeches rarely make good television, but there are ways to
overcome that. The speaker can be dynamic enough to leap off the
screen (think of how well Bill Clinton plays to the camera,
long-winded though he is). Or the words can reveal something about
him as a leader. Cheney flopped spectacularly on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected Cheney, with his placid and deliberate manner,
to display rock-star charisma. David Letterman has done as much to
define the Cheney style as anyone. ``He's a babe magnet,''
Letterman often says with a straight face, playing sounds of
squealing women whenever anyone on ``Late Show'' says ``Dick
Cheney.'' It's hard for a politician to shake off that kind of
on-target satire.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers might have expected a more television-friendly speech,
though. The lines that jumped out (Bush ``will restore decency and
integrity to the Oval Office'') echoed like a rerun of a year of
impeachment television. Such campaign lines may have stirred up the
loyalists on the convention floor (they were roused to what Tom
Brokaw on NBC called a ``not-so-spontaneous demonstration''), but
did nothing to grab an audience wondering whether to watch more,
flip to HBO or just give up and go to bed.
</P>
<P>
   In a television-driven campaign, lame speeches are not minor.
With every network and cable channel covering the acceptances, this
was the first chance the candidates had to speak directly and at
length to an audience so large. (Though viewers have sensibly fled
from this convention, even low ratings add up. Nearly 11 million
people watched Cheney on ABC, CBS and NBC combined. While that
would be a modest number for an entertainment show on just one
network, it is many millions more than have seen him on the air
before.)
</P>
<P>
   The Cheney speech was typical of what the Republicans did
throughout this convention. For four days they had the kind of
television time campaign contributions cannot buy, and largely
wasted it. Many commentators have called the choice of Cheney a
``first, do no harm'' approach, but a safe strategy is bound to
backfire if the point is to get eyeballs to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans staged a complacent show, assuming the audience
would be theirs. And they outfoxed themselves with a convention so
scripted that all anyone could talk about was its lack of surprise.
Newt Gingrich, the former speaker of the House, was kept off the
podium, so he turned up on every talk show, defending his record.
The celebrity bookers seemed to be slacking off, too, settling for
Bo Derek and the wrestling star The Rock, star power of dim
wattage.
</P>
<P>
   The one true star was the candidate's nephew, George P. Bush,
telegenic, astonishingly smooth for a 24-year-old, proud of his
half-Mexican heritage. He was scheduled to deliver a bilingual
speech just before his uncle's acceptance, and for days before
turned up in dozens of profiles and interviews. One profile
included a clip of him being introduced to a crowd as ``the hottest
member of the Bush family.'' He even charmed interviewers. When
Brokaw asked whether his grandfather, former President Bush, had
warned him about journalists, the young Bush smoothly said, ``He
loves you guys, don't believe the hype.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of four days, this fresh face had turned familiar,
but surely the Republicans didn't go to all this trouble just to
make George P. a star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
