   CVN-GORE (Philadelphia) _ Vice President Al Gore hopes to blunt
George W. Bush's momentum with the announcement on Tuesday of his
running mate. A list of six finalists put out by the Gore campaign
includes five members of Congress and a female governor. By BENNETT
ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-FORD (Philadelphia) _ Former Pres. Gerald Ford is ``in good
spirits and doing much better,'' and is expected to make a full
recovery after being hospitalized a day earlier for a stroke,
according to doctors. By LETITIA STEIN.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-GAYS (Philadelphia) _ Leaders of the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's oldest gay political organization, hold a
news conference decrying what they call a Republican ``double
standard'' on homosexual issues. The party welcomes gays as
individuals but opposes laws protecting homosexuals from
discrimination or allowing them to serve in the military. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-LAURA-BUSH (Philadelphia) _ Texas First Lady Laura Bush
tells an audience of Republican women that if her husband wins the
presidency, she will work to help families around America. She
talks about the importance of parents teaching their children to
read. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-BLACKS (Philadelphia) _ While the diversity theme of the
convention has brought African-Americans to the podium and stage,
it also has generated plenty of criticism about the contrasting
white face of the convention delegates. It would be fine with the
Republicans if they drew some more black votes, but that would
probably just be icing on the real goal: reassuring white, suburban
moderates that they can vote Republican without voting for the
intolerance evident among certain elements of the party. By LORI
RODRIGUEZ.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-TEXANS (Philadelphia) _ Giddy Texas delegates cast the final
votes to complete the process that has nominated their governor for
president. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-LOGISTICS (Philadelphia) _ Behind the scenes, things mostly
went as planned at the Republican convention. The tents didn't leak
much despite heavy storms, the lights stayed on and traffic flowed
well (except on one day at a few protest sites). By DAVID
IVANOVICH.
</P>
