<HEADLINE>
MILLER REVIEW: JUST SIT TIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's been in a self-imposed exile, experimenting with such
things as using pork rinds as an herbal colonic, analyzing the
stock potential of ostrich farming and writing insurance policies
for UFO abductions _ all from his secret retreat cottage, otherwise
known as the custodial quarters of the Shangra La Motor Inn just
this side of the Al Davis Landfill in Irwindale.
</P>
<P>
   But the other day, after adjusting his satellite dish an extra
two degrees southeast to graze the edge of the RPD-6 satellite
hovering in space directly above Bowlegged Bay, Ark., that's being
used exclusively to help government surveyors strategically plan
the next trailer park multiplex, a strange phenomenon occurred on
his TV set.
</P>
<P>
   Something besides the highlights of Anna Kournikova upsetting
Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, it caused Mr. Wise Guy _ yup, the all-knowing,
all-seeing sage of sports television who in the past often took
time to give his smart-aleck responses to your moronic questions
about the business _ to not only leap out of the heavily duct-taped
La-Z-Boy but temporarily emerge from his darkened existence and
actually respond to the burning issues of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   So, before he changes his mind or any of his other
undergarments, fire away:
</P>
<P>
   __ Question: All right, since everyone else seems to have an
opinion on it, and they're still talking about it, what was your
take on . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Answer: I knew that was coming, so let's get it out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Dickerson _ stinky-poo.
</P>
<P>
   Next question.
</P>
<P>
   __ Q: No, what about . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ A: Melissa Stark? Stark-ravin' weak.
</P>
<P>
   __ Q: OK, but then there's . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ A: Grizzly Adams? Oh, right Dan Fouts . . . as exciting as a
low-grade headache. Take the ``F'' and the ``S'' out of his last
name and you've got that one nailed. Boomer, stop laughing.
</P>
<P>
   __ Q: You know, if you just let me finish a question . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ A: The ``ump cam'' _ it'll only work when a QB throws over
the middle and drills the suicide-seeking official right in the
coconut. Then we'll see some interesting footage _ of the trainer
hovering over him with smelling salts . . .
</P>
<P>
   OK, no more stupid stalling. This isn't building toward
anything. But you're after the same thing everyone else is _ more
instant analysis about the funny guy paid to give us scripted groin
jokes on ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   Only we ain't gonna get caught in that trap again.
</P>
<P>
   We got a lot of opinions, sure. Sometimes, we're forced to give
them because everyone else seems to be talking about it, and we
don't want to look like we're out of the loop.
</P>
<P>
   So before we all get hyperventilated over the moment that's apt
to permanently mark our strange place in pop-culture history
somewhere between Andy Warhol's soup cans and genetic
reconstruction for fun and profit, let's review a few key things:
</P>
<P>
   1) That was an !ital!exhibition game last Monday night.
Completely different flow, completely different storytelling, than
a !ital!non-exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you'll get a sense of what Dennis Miller _ OK, I said his
name _ can do on the broadcast _ and he made it worth watching. But
you aren't going to get the full monty, nor should you.
</P>
<P>
   2) That was Miller's !ital!first NFL live broadcast. Give him
until November or December before Denny's Grand Slam puns start
satisfying your appetite.
</P>
<P>
   3) That was the ``Monday Night Football'' telecast with a new
producer, new director and a new set of broadcasters. Al Michaels
is about the only holdover from last year's gang, except for a few
cameramen and one or two redundant graphic machines.
</P>
<P>
   4) Of course, the ratings were miserable. The game started at
four !ital!freakin' o'clock out here. At that time of day, I'm just
trying to figure out which undersized value meal I'm gonna pick for
lunch down at the Micky D's over at Haskell and Ventura in Encino _
you know, the one with the drive-thru window on the wrong side of
the building. (I drive a refurbished U.S. Mail truck, so it works
for me.)
</P>
<P>
   5) There is no No. 5. Besides, I'm weary from all this.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to hear about it from the guy himself, watch his HBO
show tonight. Surely, he'll confess it wasn't perfect, then get off
on a rant about whatever them nouveau intellectual types like to
talk about.
</P>
<P>
   That's his job. Yours, for the time being, is to sit tight, you
little sea monkeys. Go vote on ESPN.com's Web site if it's that
important to you (more than 200,000 did, with more than a third
giving Miller a ``B'' grade).
</P>
<P>
   Cosell ain't coming back and there's still a long hot summer
ahead of us, so if you start blowing your stack over something like
this, you'll lose sight over the fact you're about to elect a new
president who might or might not have enough arm to throw out the
first pitch on Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   And that, friends, will be much more embarrassing in the big
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Next question.
</P>
<P>
   __ Q: Have you been watching the . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ A: Uh, hey, love to help you with that one, but there's a
dead armadillo in the parking lot I need to tend to. You know, the
more you run over it with a car, the flatter it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Kinda like Dennis Miller critiques.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Heavy rumors _ again _ of Mike ``Mayor McCheese'' Thompson
bailing out at AM-1150 as its programming director to take a job
with a budding all-sports station in Atlanta. Thompson wants to get
his mitts on some of the new programming scheme for the Fox Radio
Network, scheduled to launch . . . who knows when. But if he does
for that what he's already done for the 1150 lineup, it's probably
best he does exit, stage left. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The International Olympic Committee has released a statement
predicting that the record 3.7 billion viewers who watched the 1996
Summer Games from Atlanta will be broken when the world focuses on
Sydney next month. An IOC survey released Thursday indicates 88
percent of the people in Japan responded that they are
``interested'' or ``very interested'' in watching the Games on TV.
The United States (72 percent) fell in behind South Korea (81),
Ireland, Finland and Lithuania (80), China and Greece (79) and
Australia (78). You think the U.S. numbers would be higher if the
folks here knew there'd at least be an hour of live programming
during those two weeks? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Some final shots at KCOP-Channel 13 sports anchor Michelle
Bonner. On Ron Fineman's ``On The Record'' media-review Web site
(www.ronfineman.com), he tried to drum up some pro-Bonner responses
after a week's worth of those that supported an original posting
about how extremely difficult the station's camera people find her
to work with. Fineman didn't receive any supportive e-mails, so he
hesitantly posted the latest two from cameramen who worked with her
in other TV markets, and the sentiment was pretty much the same.
Fineman writes that he doesn't want his ``Inside L.A. TV'' link to
be a weekly Bonner bashing session _ but it has been. And that's
even without any responses from the former KCOP sports anchors who
privately are thankful they don't have to work with her any longer,
either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
