<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2086 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-CHENEY-LEVINSON-     08-03 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-CHENEY-LEVINSON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 TEXANS, NOT 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, Aug. 4, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By SANFORD LEVINSON    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Republicans have chosen a ticket that seems
certain to win one state _ Texas _ almost effortlessly. But at the
December balloting of the Electoral College, could the Texas
electors really vote for both George W. Bush and Dick Cheney? They
will have to ask themselves where Cheney is an ``inhabitant.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12th Amendment to the Constitution says the presidential
electors shall ``vote by ballot for president and vice president,
one of whom, at least, shall not be an inhabitant of the same state
with themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past eight years Cheney has lived in Dallas, where he
was chief executive of an oil services company. Though two weeks
ago Cheney transferred his voter registration back to Wyoming, this
scarcely seems sufficient to change his habitation. Could the
electors vote for both Bush and Cheney?
</P>
<P>
   They could abstain, but that could change the result. If neither
vice presidential candidate had a majority in the Electoral
College, the Senate would have to choose between them.
</P>
<P>
   Since President Clinton's attempt to parse words in answering
charges that he lied under oath, Republicans have gotten political
mileage from saying that only obfuscating lawyers could question
the meaning of ``is.'' Is the meaning of ``inhabitant'' any more
complicated? Most people _ whether nonlawyers or the constitutional
law professors with whom I participate in a nationwide e-mail
discussion _ have little trouble recognizing that Cheney's
last-minute change of voting registration has almost literally
nothing to do with what state he currently inhabits.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Bush appears to be confident in the assurances of his
lawyers that the 12th Amendment will not be a problem. But if it is
a mere technicality to be overcome by clever legal manipulation,
then constitutional interpretation is a more complex exercise than
the simpleminded reading of the text _ or dubious historical forays
into recapturing the intentions of the Founding Fathers _ favored
by two Supreme Court justices whom Bush says he admires: Antonin
Scalia and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   One might well argue, of course, that no rational citizen should
care which state Cheney lives in. But the Framers no doubt thought
they were doing something important in discouraging any all-New
York or all-Virginia tickets and encouraging recognition that the
country was made up of quite different states and regions.
</P>
<P>
   If they are strict constitutionalists, the Texas electors could
find themselves required to abstain when asked their choice for the
vice presidency.
</P>
<P>
   (Sanford Levinson is professor of constitutional law at the
University of Texas Law School.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
