<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2090 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-JORDAN-SENATE0804-COX     08-03 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-SENATE0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airline exec quits senate quest, avoids crash taunts
 &HT;    By Alan Judd and Jim Galloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lewis Jordan flew to Philadelphia this week confident
in his plans to run for the U.S. Senate. He finished with a lesson
in how political life can be rougher than the corporate boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican activists attending their party's national
convention advised Jordan, the former chief executive of ValuJet
Airlines, that he would be compared with fellow Atlanta businessman
Guy Millner, who lost three statewide elections despite spending
millions of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   And they warned that the taunting could escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Already, they said, Democrats were alluding to the ValuJet plane
that went down in the Florida Everglades in 1996 and referring to
the potential GOP candidate as ``Crash'' Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   So the political newcomer quickly got off the stage. Late
Wednesday evening, a day after declaring he was ready to run ``in a
big way,'' Jordan issued a statement announcing he would not seek
the seat formerly held by the late Sen. Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Jordan attributed his sudden change of
heart to the needs of his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I weighed this thing as a businessman,'' Jordan said. ``I
talked to all my advisers and my friends. The feedback I got,
overwhelmingly, was, 'Yes, you could' `` get elected. But after
considering the effect a campaign would have on his family, Jordan
said, ``we chose to step aside with, I think, honor and dignity and
go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan denied a report in an online political newsletter that
quoted him as complaining about ``political trickery'' by
supporters of another GOP candidate, former Sen. Mack Mattingly.
</P>
<P>
   But the newsletter's publisher, Bill Shipp, stood by the report,
saying that Jordan's comment was captured on tape. And Georgia
Republican leaders acknowledged that discussions about potential
Senate candidates sometimes turned harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a short time frame,'' Chuck Clay, the state
Republican chairman, said Thursday. ``Everybody needed to get their
views out on the table. You don't have time to be Mr. Nice Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Philadelphia, Jordan received numerous calls from
Republican leaders ``stressing the importance of unity and of
issues that might be raised,'' said state Sen. Tom Price. Among
those issues, Price said, was the 1996 Everglades crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an unbelievable 72 hours,'' Price added. ``And they
began to appreciate what a political campaign was all about. The
implications of an intraparty struggle became very clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The rawness of politics shocked Jordan's family, said John
Sours, a convention delegate from Smyrna, Ga., who supported the
former airline executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did was take one last look at it and back away,''
Sours said. ``Politics is a nasty business. It's a contact sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 56, the largest shareholder in AirTran Airways, as
ValuJet is now known, had pledged to spend $3 million of his own
money on the race. Initially, Republican leaders encouraged his
candidacy, saying his personal resources would make him competitive
against former Gov. Zell Miller, the Democrat appointed to
temporarily fill Coverdell's seat. In a single day last week, 18
Republican congressmen called to urge Jordan to run, said Tom
Perdue, an Atlanta political consultant advising Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an honest-to-God draft,'' Perdue said Thursday.
``There was a groundswell like I've never seen in my life for this
man. The time just wasn't right for this man and this family.''
</P>
<P>
   But state Republican leaders worried that an intraparty contest
in the nonpartisan election would allow Miller to waltz to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said all along that two strong Republicans would
inevitably put guns on each other,'' Clay said. `` . . . We have
avoided that.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipp's web site quoted Jordan as saying the experience had
given him ``a Ph.D. in political trickery. I never knew people
would do what some of these people have done. . . . This experience
has taught me why many good people are afraid to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan said Thursday that the actions of others had not
swayed his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In politics, there are many people who have their different
ideas about what should be done,'' he said. ``But I'm not aware of
any trickery. I received no pressure from anybody. To the contrary,
I received resounding support from people who said, 'You would be a
fine candidate.' ``
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
