<HEADLINE>
TREASURY ISSUES BOLSTERED BY THE FEDERAL RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices were higher Thursday but well off their
highs of the day after technology stocks recovered from an earlier
slide and investors reversed a flight to quality into government
securities.
</P>
<P>
   While sliding stock prices early in the session were the main
catalyst in lifting Treasury prices, the Federal Reserve also
bolstered prices by staging a coupon pass, in which the central
bank buys Treasury securities and adds permanent reserves to the
banking system. On Thursday the Fed bought maturities ranging from
Aug. 15, 2020, through Nov. 15, 2028.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond, the onetime benchmark for
Treasury interest rates, rose 11/32, to 107 9/32, while its yield,
which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 5.74 percent from
5.76 percent on Wednesday. The closely followed 10-year note,
meanwhile, gained 5/32, to 103 31/32. Its yield dropped to 5.95
percent from 5.97 percent. The government reported Thursday that
factory orders surged 5.5 percent in June, the largest increase
since 7.3 percent in July 1991. The report helped to cap Treasury
gains. But, excluding a record increase for aircraft and other
transportation equipment, orders rose 0.3 percent. The government
also revised the gain in June durable goods orders down slightly,
to 9.7 percent from the staggering 10 percent reported two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said its July
nonmanufacturing business index sank to 55.5 in July from 64 in
June, while the Labor Department said jobless claims rose to a
seasonally adjusted 276,000 in the week ended July 29, slightly
less than forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are that Friday's July unemployment report will
show little job and wage growth, providing the central bank with
more information as the Federal Open Market Committee heads toward
its next meeting on interest rates on Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Reserve is carefully perusing the continual flow
of economic statistics in order to determine the best course of
action at the upcoming FOMC meeting,'' said Donald J. Fine, chief
market analyst for Chase Asset Management. ``Using real GDP as a
yardstick, the year-over-year trend rate of economic growth now
stands at a prodigious 6 percent, so obviously the expectation of a
slowdown in the economy's pace is not a particularly heroic
assumption.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What really matters,'' he continued, ``is the extent, timing
and sustainability of the slowdown, and most importantly, whether
or not an impending slackening of economic growth will be enough to
definitively forestall inflationary pressures in the eyes of the
Fed.'' In this regard, Friday's July labor market data will play a
crucial role. Fine said that if the numbers were weak, market
participants would conclude that the Fed was finished raising
rates, but if they were strong, the future course would be
uncertain.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
