<HEADLINE>
GEORGE P.'S COMPARISON OF UNCLE GEORGE TO CESAR CHAVEZ FALLS FLAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The biggest name in town this week does not
include a ``W.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest name in town _ yes, even the biggest Bush _ has been
chased everywhere by adoring groupies and spying news cameras. He
is the No. 1 topic at every party and the No. 1 rumored sighting in
every restaurant. His daily habits are covered in
hors-d'oeuvre-devouring detail on a daily page in a Philadelphia
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of three guys here named George Bush. But he is George
P. Bush, 24, the potential First Nephew of a George W.
administration.
</P>
<P>
   He turned down a lot of interviews this week. Now we see why.
</P>
<P>
   The kid was trusted to introduce Uncle George at a ``Bienvenidos
a Filadelfia'' party Wednesday morning on the Philadelphia Museum
of Art steps.
</P>
<P>
   So what does he do?
</P>
<P>
   He says his Uncle George is a hero just like Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that was a stretch even by political convention
standards, Nephew George told how his mother, Florida first lady
Columba Bush, cried when the peaceloving hero of California farm
boycotts died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   George P. Bush was 17 then. He said his mother, a native of the
city of Leon in the Mexican state of Guanajuato, told him to find
somebody who ``represents what you believe _ who represents our
people, who represents our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That person,'' he said, pausing, ``is my uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the pro-Bush welcome crowd responded with stunned silence
and weak cheers.
</P>
<P>
   I bet not many Republicans could accurately identify Cesar
Chavez, a peacekeeping leader of workers in California and an early
civil rights champion for working Americans and Americans of
Hispanic descent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has loaded up this convention with Hispanic and Latino
culture, choosing U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla of San Antonio as a
co-host. Yet the Republicans are still new at this cultural
sensitivity thing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them probably don't know as much about Cesar Chavez as
they know about baseball's Cesar Cedeno.
</P>
<P>
   The United Farm Workers quickly offered to help. Chavez's
son-in-law is now president of the union, and Chavez's widow, Helen
Fabela Chavez, still lives close to his grave at the union
headquarters near Keene, Calif., where the UFW quickly issued a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Without going too hard on Nephew George, son-in-law Arturo S.
Rodriguez basically said the Texas governor is no Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   The family and the union welcome Bush's ``sentiments'' about his
mother's instilling the values of Chavez: ``Cesar's messages about
nonviolence, self-sacrifice and social justice certainly transcend
partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the partisan politics: ``We believe that policies are
more important than rhetoric and we question whether George W. is
that leader.''
</P>
<P>
   George P. Bush did not show yesterday at a flashy luncheon for
Hispanic Republicans. But again, he was a popular topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the comparison'' with Chavez, Mary Helen Cantu of
rural Webb County said delicately. Her husband, Fernando Cantu, is
chairman of the Republican National Hispanic Assembly of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he meant that George W. Bush is somebody who is proud
to bring Hispanics to the table,'' she said, switching targets.
``The Democrats all tell us, `Vote for me!' _ but they never bring
us to the table to share the success. George W. Bush has proven
that he will bring us to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncle George calls his nephew ``el Bush guapo'' _ the
``handsome'' Bush.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he would have been better off just making all the
tables.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
