<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CITRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITRUS CANKER WAR FOUGHT YARD BY YARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK BRAGG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For 40 years, more than half her life, Kitty Field
nurtured her trees. There was one orange, one lime, one grapefruit,
and the blossoms and fruit filled the yard with fragrance and
color. It just looked like Florida somehow, and she and her
husband, Ernest, grew old under their leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaves are green,'' said Field. ``The fruit is perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   What could be more harmless, she wonders, than her tiny grove?
</P>
<P>
   But recently, state inspectors searching for the dreaded citrus
canker disease came into their yard in North Miami Beach and
painted a red ``X'' on all three trees, marking them for
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``These trees are like our children,'' she said. ``We have
watched them grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of citrus trees, mostly in commercial
groves, in South Florida have already been chopped down to stop the
spread of canker, a disease that threatens Florida's citrus
industry, which is second only to tourism in the money it takes in.
But it is the house-by-house eradication of the canker that seems
to be causing the most pain.
</P>
<P>
   Most people, like Catalina Leal, 86, of Miami, and Elvia Perez,
69, of Hialeah, only wept in their yards as Florida Department of
Agriculture workers chopped down old citrus trees. But others are
more determined. Five times this year, South Floridians met state
inspectors with guns or threats of guns.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent was on Tuesday. The police said Carl E. Lawson,
62, fired his shotgun after two state inspectors approached his
home. No one was hurt, but Lawson was charged with two counts of
attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   The saddest case came in March, in the city of Tamarac in
Broward County. State inspectors had already chopped down three of
95-year-old Nelson Edwards' grapefruit trees.
</P>
<P>
   When they came for the last one, Edwards, who can barely see and
does not hear well, came to his door with a rifle. It was not
loaded, but he worked the rifle's bolt, once, anyway, to try and
scare them off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just an old man,'' said Edwards, when he was asked why he
did that.
</P>
<P>
   It did not save his tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's history,'' he said. ``It's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Such cases are an extreme. Most people here fire off letters,
instead. ``We have written our political representatives,'' said
Field. ``We will do what is necessary to keep our trees.''
</P>
<P>
   But yard by yard through South Florida, where citrus trees had
stood for decades, there are just stumps now. ``They gave me
shade,'' said Perez, of her trees. ``They gave me happiness. Every
morning, I would throw the leftover coffee grounds around the
trees. Now, I just throw it in the garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been three outbreaks of canker in Florida since 1913,
and the most recent was detected in 1995. ``That one tree has
spread to 700,000,'' said Richard Miranda, public information
director for the state's Citrus Canker Eradication Program.
</P>
<P>
   When state inspectors find a tree with canker, they condemn all
trees within 1,900 feet. Trees that show no signs of the disease
still must be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The state offers $100 to compensate the owners of the trees, to
help offset the costs of planting new trees.
</P>
<P>
   But what good will it do, ask some of the elderly homeowners, to
plant a new twig in the ground this late in their lives? It will be
years before the trees really bear fruit, and decades before they
grow tall and full enough to shade them.
</P>
<P>
   For people in their 70s and 80s, what good is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to plant a new tree now won't help them much,''
conceded Miranda. But, he said, ``if it actually gets into the
groves, it can be crippling to the economy of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Canker manifests itself on the fruit in raised, brown, corky
lesions, surrounded by yellow rings. ``It attacks the immune system
of a tree the same way that HIV affects humans,'' and eventually
kills the tree.
</P>
<P>
   While those whose trees have signs of the disease hate to see
them chopped down, those whose apparently healthy trees are within
the 1,900-foot kill zone are livid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that were sick were next door, not mine,'' said
Perez. ``My daughter tells me, `Mami, get over it, it's just
plants,' but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Leal planted her trees, oranges and other citrus, 23 years ago.
She pruned them with a machete, and used boards studded with nails
to keep cats off them.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing she could do to keep the inspectors away,
though she let them know how it hurt her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried in front of them, because I felt very bad,'' Leal
said. ``But they went ahead and cut them down anyway. I figured I'd
have to let them because they're the government.''
</P>
<P>
   She cannot get used to the sight of the stumps. Her trees were
so giving, she said, of fruit, of shade. ``I grew to love them.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing that some here will miss most is the simple act of
reaching up and plucking a fresh orange or grapefruit or lime, and
the taste _ as different from a store-bought fruit as a
made-from-scratch meal is from a microwave dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mornings, we put on a pair of slippers and go out to
pick oranges, and have them for breakfast,'' said Gil Muratori, 61,
a pharmaceutical sales manager in Miami whose trees are under the
state's death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of being in Florida, of being Floridian. Chopping
them up, to many people here, is as wrong as setting fire to a
flamingo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
