u p BC-GOP-INCLUDE-BOS &LR;      08-03 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-INCLUDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITY DELEGATES FEEL WELCOME AT GOP CONCLAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ As Dylan Glenn, 31, a Georgia delegate strides
through a media tent and onto sprawling floor of the First Union
Center, he gives a tight-fisted hand shake to an African-American
television producer. Then, he pats the back of an elder white
politician from Georgia before espousing the conservative ideology
of his party to a passerby.
</P>
<P>
   The son of two African-American educators, he says his values
are reflected here at the National Republican Convention, among a
sea of white faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am comfortable here. This is my party. They share my own
values,'' he said. ``The reason I am a Republican today is because
my daddy always preached individual hard work and responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, the president of South Georgia Economic Development
Corp., is among a small pool of minorities who are delegates _
African-American, Hispanic and Asian who call themselves the new
messengers of the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first day of the convention, the Republicans have
assiduously emphasized inclusiveness. Five out of 12 speakers
during the opening night of the convention were minorities. Outside
the convention halls, African-Americans, Asian and Latino delegates
who makeup less than 5 percent of the delegation have been courted
at luncheons especially for them. This week, Republicans ran
Spanish radio ads in some of the nation's largest markets.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the television lights, the politically-correct
advertisments and emotional speeches, minority delegates like Glenn
say they were drawn to the Republican Party's strong positions on
free enterprise, family values and military defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I belong,'' said Texas delegate Juntas Poderno,
42, who is Hispanic-American. ``I am a new Republican. Young and
inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gil Medina, a prominent businessman and New Jersey
delegate, ``I truly believe that the GOP will be the party of the
future for minorities _ black, white and Hispanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Others like Dan Lewis, a Native-American delegate from Arizona
and Mary Torres from Guam said the GOP's hardline pro-defense
position is the reason more minorities are turning to the
Republican Party, which minorities have long accused of ignoring
them. Torres said additional closings of military bases could
economically hurt Guam. While Lewis says Native-Americans believe a
weak military that could result in a high number of American
casualties could leave tribal reservations without leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But even optimistic Republicans concede that George W. Bush and
other party leaders have a long road ahead of them if they really
want to capture more minority votes. Prior to the New Deal, blacks
voted predominantly Republican, the party of Abraham Lincoln. And
as Condoleeza Rice reminded the delegates Tuesday night,
Republicans signed up black voters when the Dixiecrats turned them
away.
</P>
<P>
   But that hold the party once had on the African-American vote
disappeared a long time ago. Since the 1960s, Africans-Americans
have been the most loyal of all Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have along way to go,'' said Senator Orrin Hatch, the Utah
Republican. ``But personally I am tired of the Democrats thinking
they own the black vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 percent of black voters supported Bush's father in 1992.
That same year Bill Clinton won 72 percent of the black vote. While
Clinton also brought in a whopping 61 percent of the Hispanic vote
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats now say the Republicans' display of diversity this
week was a mirage since only 4 percent of the delegates are
Hispanic and 5 percent are African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our convention takes place, you won't only see a stage of
minorities, but you will be able to look across the the audience to
see delegates that look like America,'' said Fred Humphries, a
political director for the Democratic National Convention, which
opens Aug. 14 in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics question if Bush really is interested in minority
isssues after chosing Dick Cheney as a running mate. Cheney, while
a congressman in the 1980s, voted against freeing Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Humphries said the Democrats' support of affirmative action,
civil right's issues and empowerment zones is hard proof that the
party is truly interested in minority issues.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Medina, who was born in Puerto Rico but grew up in
Camden, N.J., said the lessons of hard work and self reliance
taught by his parents reflect the ideology of the Republican Party
not the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Medina said when he began asking Democrats in New Jersey to
invest in businesses in the area's poorest communities, they
refused. He said it was Republican businessmen and GOP civic
leaders who began providing loans and grants to struggling minority
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Medina became New Jersey's first and only Hispanic
commerce secretary under Republican Governor Christine Todd
Whitman. He points to himself, as well as former General Colin
Powell and Rice, who is Bush's foreign policy adviser, as shining
examples of how Republicans are providing gifted minorities with
opportunities while also using their skills to shape the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a child my family was dirt poor, and yet under a Republican
I was chosen to become secretary of commerce,'' said Medina.
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, Bush's popularity is growing among Hispanic
voters. In Texas, Bush won 40 percent of the Hispanic vote in 1998.
Part of the appeal, said Medina, is the fact that Bush speaks
Spanish, has a Mexican-born sister in law and has promised to
improve relations with Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Bush's appearance at the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People convention in July was a clear sign
he is working to bridge a long-standing gap between black voters
and the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   At the NAACP, Bush chided his party for ignoring black issues
and declared that civil rights would be the cornerstone of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, he even courted Hispanics at the National Council
of La Raza in San Diego and black members of the Congress of
Equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for real,'' said Glenn who is also running for
Congress. ``This is not a show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
