<HEADLINE>
GEORGE P.'S COMPARISON OF UNCLE GEORGE TO CESAR CHAVEZ FALLS FLAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The biggest name in town this week does not
include a ``W.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest name in town _ yes, even the biggest Bush _ has been
chased everywhere by adoring groupies and spying news cameras. He
is the No. 1 topic at every party and the No. 1 rumored sighting in
every restaurant. His daily habits are covered in
hors-d'oeuvre-devouring detail on a daily page in a Philadelphia
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of three guys here named George Bush. But he is George
P. Bush, 24, the potential First Nephew of a George W.
administration.
</P>
<P>
   He turned down a lot of interviews this week. Now we see why.
</P>
<P>
   The kid was trusted to introduce Uncle George at a ``Bienvenidos
a Filadelfia'' party Wednesday morning on the Philadelphia Museum
of Art steps.
</P>
<P>
   So what does he do?
</P>
<P>
   He says his Uncle George is a hero just like Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that was a stretch even by political convention
standards, Nephew George told how his mother, Florida first lady
Columba Bush, cried when the peaceloving hero of California farm
boycotts died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   George P. Bush was 17 then. He said his mother, a native of the
city of Leon in the Mexican state of Guanajuato, told him to find
somebody who ``represents what you believe _ who represents our
people, who represents our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That person,'' he said, pausing, ``is my uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the pro-Bush welcome crowd responded with stunned silence
and weak cheers.
</P>
<P>
   I bet not many Republicans could accurately identify Cesar
Chavez, a peacekeeping leader of workers in California and an early
