</P>
<P>
   Most of them probably don't know as much about Cesar Chavez as
they know about baseball's Cesar Cedeno.
</P>
<P>
   The United Farm Workers quickly offered to help. Chavez's
son-in-law is now president of the union, and Chavez's widow, Helen
Fabela Chavez, still lives close to his grave at the union
headquarters near Keene, Calif., where the UFW quickly issued a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Without going too hard on Nephew George, son-in-law Arturo S.
Rodriguez basically said the Texas governor is no Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   The family and the union welcome Bush's ``sentiments'' about his
mother's instilling the values of Chavez: ``Cesar's messages about
nonviolence, self-sacrifice and social justice certainly transcend
partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the partisan politics: ``We believe that policies are
more important than rhetoric and we question whether George W. is
that leader.''
</P>
<P>
   George P. Bush did not show yesterday at a flashy luncheon for
Hispanic Republicans. But again, he was a popular topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the comparison'' with Chavez, Mary Helen Cantu of
rural Webb County said delicately. Her husband, Fernando Cantu, is
chairman of the Republican National Hispanic Assembly of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he meant that George W. Bush is somebody who is proud
to bring Hispanics to the table,'' she said, switching targets.
``The Democrats all tell us, `Vote for me!' _ but they never bring
us to the table to share the success. George W. Bush has proven
that he will bring us to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncle George calls his nephew ``el Bush guapo'' _ the
``handsome'' Bush.
</P>
<P>
   This week, he would have been better off just making all the
tables.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
