<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-FREEAGENT     08-03 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FREEAGENTS0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Undrafted, but not unnoticed
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Doug Johnson could have been a quarterback with the
Cowboys, Packers or Cardinals. Maurice Smith nearly became a
running back for the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite radically different college backgrounds, Johnson and
Smith are wearing black and red in Japan today because the Falcons
offered the best sales pitch to each in the spring. The Falcons
beat out Saturday's American Bowl opponent, the Dallas Cowboys, and
several other teams to get Johnson after his Florida career. NFL
teams don't offer scholarships, but they sometimes recruit like
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Before the draft even each year, team officials work the
telephones furiously, letting agents know that if their clients
don't get drafted, there's an NFL team interested in signing them
as a free agent. As with colleges, it often comes down to which
team has the most to offer _ or the best connections. Johnson and
Smith both liked the idea of staying close to home. The
relationship between Falcons national scout Mike Hagen and
Johnson's high school coach, John Hunt, also helped.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, a member of the Florida staff, was Johnson's coach at
Gainesville (Fla.) Buchholz High. Years ago, Hunt worked in the
Cowboys organization with Hagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I place a lot of stock in what John says, and he had good
things to say about the Falcons and coach (Dan) Reeves,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Smith came with sterling recommendations from Hagen,
Tampa-based area scout Boyd Dowler and Atlanta-based area scout Ken
Blair.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT PLACE FOR SMITH
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson routinely played in front of SEC crowds of 85,000
and more, Smith toiled in front of crowds sometimes one-tenth that
size at Division I-AA North Carolina A&AMP;T in Greensboro, N.C. But
his 6.1-yard average per carry did not go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   After the draft, Falcons officials told the 6-foot-1,
225-pounder that ``they wanted a bigger guy because they weren't
sure what was going to happen with (running back) Jamal
(Anderson),'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   That Atlanta is close to Smith's hometown of Palmyra, N.C.,
where he grew up with four brothers and three sisters, was
important. The Falcons' offense was a nice match, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Reeves obviously likes to run the ball, and when I was
researching the teams that were interested in me, that stuck out,''
said Smith, who is a few courses short of a degree in agricultural
and biosystems engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the team worked out a two-year deal with Smith by
telephone on draft day, Falcons vice president of football
operations Ron Hill was worried that he might change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a long time ago working with (former Cowboys general
manager) Gil Brandt that when you want to do something, you do it
now,'' Hill said. ``So I said, `Get on a plane and go sign him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pro personnel assistant Mark Olson caught a plane to Greensboro
and signed Smith in a Waffle House near midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``About five or six teams called after the Falcons,'' said
Smith, who led all rushers in Saturday's 20-13 win over the Colts
with 58 yards on nine carries. ``I'm in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has been asked to ``get close'' to Smith and take him
under his wing. But Smith already has shown that he doesn't always
need help.
</P>
<P>
   Early in training camp, after linebacker Keith Brooking hit him
hard, Smith shot back, ``I'm coming to get you.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Smith, rarely asked to block in college, jacked
Brooking in blitz-pickup drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a rookie, undrafted no less, calls out a veteran, you got
to respect that,'' Brooking said. ``Rookies are going to get tested
to kind of see what they're made of. He plays hard.''
</P>
<P>
   OVERCOMING A REPUTATION
</P>
<P>
   Playing hard was one of the question marks about Johnson. An
inconsistent college career convinced NFL teams that he was too
risky to draft.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's tenuous relationship with Florida coach Steve Spurrier
was well documented. The low point of his career came when he was
the starting quarterback as a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the top-ranked Gators were upset at LSU, a game
in which Johnson completed just 3 of 6 passes for 46 yards, a
caller to a local sports radio show said he had seen the
quarterback at a bar after curfew before the game. Johnson was
suspended for a game and the rest of his Florida career was like a
yo-yo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought I was a head case,'' Johnson said when asked what
scared away the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things that went on inside the program
that you couldn't see from the outside,'' he said. ``There wasn't
anything I could do, except shut up and play. People probably just
thought I was immature, inconsistent and couldn't be counted on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagen's relationship with Hunt helped the Falcons look deeper.
The team also got a start with Johnson when they were the only team
that paid to fly him in for a workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else did that,'' said Johnson, who visited Atlanta the
same weekend the Florida basketball team played in the SEC
championship game in the Georgia Dome. ``And I wanted to go to a
team that had a good, veteran quarterback to learn from.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, with Troy Aikman, and the Packers, with Brett
Favre, met some of the criteria, too. But not all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are close to home,'' Johnson said of the Falcons.
``They're in the Southeast, and I wanted to stay in this part of
the country. I love Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
