<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAPAN0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weary team hits Tokyo
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Atlanta Falcons arrived in the Land of the Rising
Sun on Thursday looking at a setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   As players, coaches and staffers staggered off buses and into
their hotel in Japan, it was the Atlanta equivalent of 6:35 a.m. It
was 7:35 p.m. in Tokyo. The team's charter flight left training
camp in Greenville, S.C., Wednesday about 12:30 p.m. Including a
stop in Atlanta to pick up cheerleaders, the team spent 18 hours on
a plane.
</P>
<P>
   The bus ride from Narita airport east of Tokyo took nearly two
more hours, because highways were choked with rush-hour traffic in
the early evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons should be rested by the time they play the Dallas
Cowboys in the American Bowl NFL exhibition. The game is at 11 a.m.
Sunday in Tokyo, which is 10 p.m. Saturday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday morning _ or night _ they were whipped. ``That bus
ride was the worst,'' equipment manager Brian Boigner said.
``(Assistant Thom) Kaumayer said we should have taken the train.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaumayer, who is new to the Falcons' staff, has coached in the
Japanese football league.
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches were subjected to a series of lectures from
coaches, customs officials and, finally, the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had to hear about the Japanese jail system and other
odd pieces of information that they hope they won't need to use.
Upon arriving at the Tokyo Dome Hotel, which opened just two months
ago next to the Tokyo Dome, or ''Big Egg,'' as they call it here,
the Falcons went through another briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, some of them went in search of food. Wide receiver Terance
Mathis was on his way out with rookie wide receiver Mareno Philyaw
and rookie cornerback Darrick Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   They looked chipper after taking showers. ``The bus ride didn't
bother me,'' Mathis said. ''I was asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches had the option of taking medication to help
them sleep on the Japan Air Lines 747 that the NFL chartered for
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Bob Whitfield was surprised to see Falcons super fan
Col. Joe Curtis, a longtime supporter who claims to have attended
all but one Falcons home game since 1966.
</P>
<P>
   He might be the only fan who made the 6,600-mile trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd known you were coming, I'd have stayed home,''
Whitfield said. ``I'd have let you take my place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will have two days to tour Tokyo. They practiced at
10 a.m. Friday (9 p.m. Thursday, ET) and will practice again at
10:30a.m. Saturday (9:30 p.m. today, ET).
</P>
<P>
   Tickets still are available for the game, at prices ranging from
5,000 to 50,000 yen. That's about $48.50 to $485.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
