<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2110 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-CHINA-SILICON-VALLEY-     08-03 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SILICON-VALLEY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BEIJING, STUDENT ENTREPRENEURS FORGE A CHINESE-STYLE SILICON
VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Anyone searching for the soul of China's Silicon
Valley can find it here, up four flights of concrete stairs, past
walls with peeling paint and ledges strewn with beer bottles, down
a darkened hallway and inside what was once the student activity
room at Qinghua University Dormitory No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   It is here that a visitor will find the makeshift research and
development offices of the fledgling company called Beijing East
Doctors Information Technology (``doctors'' as in Ph.D.'s, not
medical doctors).
</P>
<P>
   With the blessing of the administrators at Qinghua, China's
leading technical university, six graduate students are sharing
their pursuit of a legend borrowed from the opposite side of the
Pacific Ocean, in the original Silicon Valley _ the birthplace of
companies like Hewlett-Packard and Yahoo, whose roots lie deep in
the student life of Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   As Yang Diange, a 27-year-old computer science student who is
the chief executive of Beijing East, put it: ``That is our dream _
to be just like a Cisco or a Sun Microsystems.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the best and brightest technology companies in
Silicon Valley, Hewlett-Packard, Sun and Cisco were founded by
students, faculty and staff members at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Beijing East, which is developing a Web site that will
match technology experts with Internet users, is one of perhaps 500
or 600 recent home-grown Internet start-ups in Zhongguancun, a
chaotic Beijing neighborhood that is both the site of some of the
nation's best universities and the Chinese government's designated
high-technology industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
   Zhongguancun, in the Haidian district in northwest Beijing, is
home to a fledgling Internet industry as well as better-known
Chinese computer and telecommunications companies like Legend
Computer Systems, Founder Computer Systems and Huawei Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Internet arrived in China only in 1997, Beijing
students, when their experience is measured in ``Internet years,''
have already weathered a boom-and-bust cycle. Many tiny start-ups
here have gone out of business in the months since the April
decline of the Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   For the young founders of Beijing East, however, Zhongguancun is
the perfect incubator. Next year the company plans to move off
campus and commercialize its Internet computer support Web site.
</P>
<P>
   And though they work half a world away from the world's
better-known high-technology mecca, this group of graduate students
is in many ways closer to the authentic entrepreneurial spirit that
drives Silicon Valley than many of the world's ersatz Silicon
Deserts, Mountains, Glens and Forests, which are most frequently
the public relations products of overzealous economic development
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been remarkable to me how similar the entrepreneurial
high-tech Chinese are to their American counterparts,'' said Kai-Fu
Lee, an American-educated computer scientist who is director of a
research laboratory that Microsoft has established in Zhongguancun.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the oppressive humidity that visits Beijing each summer,
the Qinghua students spend 15 to 18 hours a day packed into their
dormitory room with six personal computers hooked to their campus
network.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the students have drawn no salaries and raised about
$36,000 from friends and family that was spent mostly on computers
and the wages paid to some undergraduate students for programming
help.
</P>
<P>
   They are now adding the finishing touches to their Web site,
which is intended to take advantage of the latest Internet trend, a
peer-to-peer service and support network. In their case, it is
meant to bring together China's best technology experts with what
they hope will be tens of thousands of Internet and PC novices
hungry for online help in everything from surfing the Web to
questions about both the Windows and Linux operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Yang expects the company to need as much as $500,000
to start its business. Despite some concerns about a recent cooling
down in venture capital investment in China, he foresees no
difficulties in raising the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he feels the group needs to be picky even in choosing
its investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not very difficult for us to find an investor for our
next stage,'' he said. ``But we don't want to cooperate with common
investors; we'd like to find some famous investors. We will grow
faster with the help of famous investors such as International Data
Group, Softbank, CMGI, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Yang's confidence is echoed by other Zhongguancun start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have venture capitalists coming to our door every week,''
said Jia Enchen, general manager of eefind.com, a Chinese-language
search-engine technology development company in an office park just
south of the Qinghua campus.
</P>
<P>
   Like Beijing East, eefind is a clear example of why the Chinese
start-ups should be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have access to sophisticated software technology
and bright programmers, and they are operating on a shoestring
compared with their Silicon Valley counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Although eefind's extremely cramped two-room office on the top
floor of the 10-story Qinghua Pioneer Park building makes even the
most crowded Silicon Valley office or garage look spacious, the
company has spent only about $130,000 so far in developing its
search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, eefind.com exemplifies a second significant aspect of
the Chinese technology boom.
</P>
<P>
   Many entrepreneurs who are founding companies are technologists
who are moving here because they see the Internet boom here as
real. A sense seems to prevail that in the 21st century the
Internet will increasingly be dominated by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Eefind's founder, Ming-Jer Lee, is computer science graduate
student from Taiwan who moved to Beijing to found the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where the Internet market will be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the recent growth of the Chinese Internet suggests that
he may even be understating the future. July survey statistics
reported by the China Internet Network Information Center show that
the number of Chinese Internet users has almost doubled, to 16.9
million from 8.9 million, in just seven months.
</P>
<P>
   By one estimate, the annual value of e-commerce could pass $1
billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   That the Internet is catching hold in urban China can easily be
seen by even a casual visitor to Beijing. A majority of the
billboards that bracket the city's freeways now come equipped with
Internet addresses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the first U.S. companies to realize that the spirit of
the Zhongguancun Internet boom was a resource to be exploited was
Microsoft. Nearly two years ago, it set up a research laboratory
here and tapped as its director Kai-Fu Lee, who had previously
served as a vice president at both Apple Computer and Silicon
Graphics, where he worked on voice recognition and 3-D software.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft laboratory, now well established, is beginning to
contribute to Microsoft products under development. Lee has
recruited a number of American computer experts to lead the
laboratory's research teams and has hired leading Chinese
scientists, programmers and mathematicians.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his research group leaders are ethnic Chinese who agreed
to return from the West, or to move from Taiwan, to build the new
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, the laboratory, which occupies a single floor
of a new office building in the Zhongguancun zone, plays host to
180 student interns who are developing software programs for
Microsoft. The laboratory is scheduled to expand to a second floor
of the building in August.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite his optimism about the potential Chinese
technologists, Lee is still cautious about the possibility that
Zhongguancun could rival Silicon Valley for sheer entrepreneurial
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent article in People's Daily, he asserted that cultural
differences remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the `real' differences between Silicon Valley and
Zhongguancun are: culture, different types of talent, different
definitions of innovation, different types of venture capital and
different involvement of academic institutions,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley has evolved a culture that is tuned to
market-driven innovation, Lee noted, while in China, innovation is
still largely driven by technology.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote that venture capital is not playing the same role
in China that it plays in Silicon Valley, where investors are
frequently an integral part of a company's day-to-day operations.
Things are changing in China, but until recently venture investors
had been used only as a source of financing.
</P>
<P>
   There may be another crucial difference as well. Despite an
intensifying housing shortage, highway traffic problems and
declining quality of life in Silicon Valley, it still seems like an
earthly paradise compared with the rapidly industrializing Beijing,
with its chronic pollution.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent lunchtime meeting at the Microsoft lab here, a
visitor asked seven of the American computer experts recruited by
Lee what they missed most about the United States. In unison the
group answered, ``Fresh air!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
