<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      08-03 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;    State making education standards tougher for Texas schools &HT;    By KATHY WALT 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas schools will have to meet tougher standards to
get high marks under the state's school rating system, Education
Commissioner Jim Nelson announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this new blueprint will allow us to build on a very
strong system to make it even stronger,'' Nelson said in announcing
the changes, some of which take effect this fall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Under the state's school accountability system, schools are
rated exemplary, recognized, acceptable or low-performing. The
ratings are based primarily on standardized test scores and dropout
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will be phased in over several years, starting this
fall when dropout rates will be lowered and fewer campuses will be
exempted from being held accountable for minority students'
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The dropout standards are not as stringent as Nelson had
originally outlined, but he said he agreed to back off his proposal
after weighing concerns from superintendents and other school
district officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many felt that it was too much too fast,'' Nelson said of his
original plan to require schools to reduce their dropout rates by 1
percent each year for the next two years. ``But they can anticipate
a continuing move toward more rigorous dropout standards in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he has warned school administrators to get ready
now, ``because it will come to pass. They should start looking at
how they can strengthen their dropout prevention and recovery
programs and look at ways that they can keep more kids in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current standards, the dropout rate must be no more than 1
percent for a school to claim the exemplary rating, a figure that
remains unchanged this fall and next year.
</P>
<P>
   For the recognized rating, the current dropout rate is 3.5
percent or less; for an acceptable rating, the dropout rate is 6
percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, those who seek recognized or acceptable
status will have to reduce their dropout rates by half a percentage
point this school year and another half-percentage point in the
next school year. So by 2001-02, ``recognized'' schools must have a
dropout rate of 2.5 percent or less and ``acceptable'' schools must
have a rate of 5 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   New passing rates on the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills,
the state's controversial high-stakes testing program, will kick in
during the 2001-02 school year, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning that school year, officials will require
``acceptable'' schools to post a 55 percent passing rate for all
students. Social studies will be added to the test, with a 50
percent passing rate required in that category for an acceptable
rating.
</P>
<P>
   TAAS passing rates for exemplary and recognized schools will
remain unchanged at 90 and 80 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   School districts and campuses will get a break from the ratings
_ a system that has caused angst in some districts that have failed
to make the grade or show improvement _ in the 2002-03 school year.
</P>
<P>
   No school ratings will be reported for that school year, Nelson
said, because that will be the first year Texas administers a new
series of standardized tests. The Legislature has mandated that the
skills tests be made even more difficult, increasing the academic
areas tested and moving the high school exit test from the
sophomore to junior year.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he has not decided whether to raise the TAAS passing
standard for 2004 and beyond because he wants to see how students
do on the new exams first.
</P>
<P>
   None of the changes will affect the 1999-2000 school performance
ratings, which are scheduled to be announced Aug. 17, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement drew criticism from State Board of Education
member David Bradley, R-Beaumont, who complained that board
members' advice was not sought by Nelson in setting the new
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some authority over (these issues) but once again the
TEA has ignored the input of the board,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
