<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GOP-BUSH-NYT &LR;      08-03 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GOP-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MAN FROM MIDLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Aug. 4:
</P>
<P>
   It will be 96 days before Republicans know if Gov. George W.
Bush was right to bypass standard GOP ideological fare and center
this convention on the twin themes of inclusion and personal
testimony. The shape of the convention, like Bush's highly
autobiographical acceptance speech, reflected his determination to
incite a public appetite for change and emphasize the personalities
of the candidates over issues and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Bush delivered a spirited case for a change of style and values
in the White House in spite of the generally sunny national mood
right now. The underlying invitation was for voters to take a leap
of faith on the promise that Bush will develop into a more
effective, resolute and likable leader and role model than Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   This presentation of an admittedly late-blooming candidate as a
work in progress carries certain risks. Not since Jimmy Carter in
1976 has there been a presidential candidate to whom the act of
introducing himself to the American people _ of making himself
known, trusted and familiar as well as simply famous _ was more
important. The speech marked the toughest test for the new nominee
before the debates this fall, when he and his aides expect a
swarming attack from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of Bush's situation right now is that, despite his
familiar name and the seasoned characters surrounding him as policy
advisers, he is actually not very well known even to many who
support him and voted for him in the primaries. His six-year stint
as governor of Texas is one of the briefest times in public life of
any recent presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But serving in Austin probably has less meaning to the voters
than the associations they bring to him because of his family
background and his distance from the Washington world epitomized by
Gore and President Clinton. In speaking of being a ``different''
kind of Republican, Bush hopes to communicate that he will stand
for a broad change in the political culture in the direction of
``civility and respect'' and actually deliver on the ``kinder and
gentler'' Republican policies promised some years ago by his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Running a campaign for change is complicated by the fact that
Americans are satisfied with the economy, and the polls show them
broadly supporting the Democrats' approach on budget issues, as
well as abortion, guns, health care and Social Security. The
oratorical doorway for Bush has been to speak from, and about, his
heart, and Thursday night he charged that the Democrats had used
prosperity ``to no great purpose.'' Tactically, he attempted a
Clinton-like trick of putting a rhetorical lasso around the other
party's issues _ in this case, Social Security, Medicare and Head
Start.
</P>
<P>
   But the glue that holds all this together is the promise of
personality suited to the office, yet free of historical baggage.
In service of that theme, Bush invoked the values of Midland and
boasted that he would come to Washington without inherited enemies
and with ``no stake in the bitter arguments of the last few
years.'' He asserted that his would be an administration guided by
convictions and character rather than polls and focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   A world of difference lies between Bush and Ronald Reagan, the
last Republican Convention nominee to stir the kind of hope among
Republicans that could be heard Thursday night. But like Reagan,
Bush promised that if given a chance he would rise above
expectations, and like Reagan, he is attempting to create a market
for change in the summer convention and then cash in this fall.
Also like Reagan, he promised a regime of homespun values in place
of the policy sophistication or taste for legislative maneuvering
of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, this down-home emphasis is sharply at odds with the
privileged educational and financial background of Bush and many of
the delegates here _ a condition that has led some to say this
ought to be known as the illusion convention instead of the
inclusion convention. But Democrats should make no mistake about
the themes laid down here or the stump performance of George W.
Bush and even that of his running mate, Dick Cheney. They represent
a considerable danger for Gore and his party this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
