<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-MERCEDES-ARMOR-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUIT OF HIGH-TECH ARMOR TO FOIL LATTER-DAY HIGHWAYMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 6) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES BARRON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ We were speeding along in what the
Mercedes-Benz executive at the wheel had promised would be a
two-part demonstration of a new S-Class sedan _ 0-to-30
acceleration, followed by 30-to-0 braking. He did not tell us about
the third part, involving three guys with .44 Magnums who
surrounded the car as it screeched to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   In less time than it takes to say ``faster than a speeding
bullet,'' they fired six shots at the back-seat window next to me.
</P>
<P>
   As you have probably figured out, I survived, but not because I
can deflect bullets like a superhero. The guns were loaded with
soap pellets that left pinkish splotches on the window. But
Mercedes says that if the bullets had been real, the ultrathick
glass and the lightweight armor in the door would have kept me
safe.
</P>
<P>
   I was riding in a production-model armored car, the first that
Mercedes-Benz has brought to this country. The S500 Guard looks
almost the same as a regular S-Class, but has factory-installed
equipment meant to turn an already solid car into a fortress on
wheels. In addition to the body armor and the glass (which Mercedes
says can withstand gunfire if no three shots are closer together
than about 5 inches), the car comes with run-flat tires.
</P>
<P>
   The S500 Guard starts at $153,950, making it the high-priced
entry among factory-built armored cars. BMW's 740iL and 750iL
Protections are $99,400 and $124,400.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are hoping to capitalize on Americans' fear of
highway violence. Mercedes expects to find 1,000 buyers a year; BMW
projects far fewer sales.
</P>
<P>
   Worried drivers can have their old cars armored by companies
that specialize in making body panels Superman-tough, but Mercedes
and BMW are betting that some buyers would rather have factory
equipment. ``Retrofitting means you disassemble and reassemble the
car,'' said Rob Allen, manager of special vehicles for
Mercedes-Benz and the driver in the demonstration. ``Anytime you
have to take a car apart to armor it, when you put it back
together, it's not going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the S500 Guard had 300 armored parts and weighed 800
pounds extra _ not that anyone is likely to notice. ``The
security's as incognito as possible because you do not want to be
reminded of your own vulnerability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So nothing in the car's ``occupant cell'' indicates that the car
withstood 128 bullets in a test to see whether it met European
security-industry standards for ``street violence where the victim
is chosen randomly.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is more to the S500 Guard than a bullet-resistant
body. The engine has been beefed up to handle the extra weight;
security experts say that one way to foil bad guys is to make a
speedy getaway. The S500 Guard can go from 0 to 60 in 7.3 seconds
(about a second longer than an ordinary S500).
</P>
<P>
   ``No special protection car is impregnable,'' Allen said. ``The
reason you buy a car like this is to get out of trouble. You don't
want to just stand there and take shots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
