<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2124 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MONEY&AMP;MEDICINE-COLUMN     08-03 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY&AMP;MEDICINE-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING THE CODE OF LAB BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a familiar sequence of events to anyone who has spent much
time in a doctor's office. You have blood taken, you call for the
results, you get on with your life _ and then weeks, months or even
years later, you receive a bill from the laboratory or an
explanation-of-benefits letter from your insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   These missives can be maddening, and not only because they
arrive so long after the fact. There is usually no way for a layman
to discern the test in question or which doctor ordered it; all you
see are a few numerical codes. Unless you own the handbook that
explains what ``82947'' stands for, you're at least one phone call
away from an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   I received one of those letters recently _ 14 pages, printed on
both sides, concerning blood tests from a mere two summers ago.
According to Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield, my insurer at the
time of the tests, I still owed the laboratory $186.85. I called
the lab, which deciphered the identity of the doctor and test, and
further informed me that I owed nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Two representatives at Empire Blue Cross, whose recent
television ads have promised improved customer service, gave me the
telephonic version of the blank stare. I eventually established
that I am indeed in the clear.
</P>
<P>
   Why do these cryptic letters arrive so late? How are ordinary
people supposed to make sense of them?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the answer depends on whom you ask.
Laboratories say the blame rests squarely with doctors, who do not
give them all the information needed to process bills. Doctors have
a relationship with their patients, they say, but labs are just
hired guns, processing tests at the doctor's behest and then
issuing bills to insurers and patients.
</P>
<P>
   Lab representatives say they often do not get complete insurance
information or proper diagnostic codes from doctors. As a result,
they say, lab bills are misdirected or are rejected by the
insurance company. ``Our mantra is that we don't see the patient,''
said Joanne Glisson, vice president for governmental relations at
the American Clinical Lab Association, a trade group. ``We really
are like a middleman.'' In other words, at the mercy of the
doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors don't see it that way. Dr. Lawrence Ossias, a
hematologist in Manhattan, said he recently stopped using one lab
because of its billing practices. He had contracted to have
services ``bundled'' _ a package deal of sorts for a half-dozen
blood tests. But managed-care companies insisted on itemized bills.
When the claims managers saw the lab's much higher piecemeal rates,
they were ``laughing and paying $20,'' Ossias said _ even less than
the bundled rate he had negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   So, he said, the lab started itemizing its bills to all
patients, apparently hoping that some would pay retail and make up
for the low HMO payments. ``It has been a real nightmare,'' he
said. ``Patients assume their insurance companies have been billed,
and then six months later a bill shows up and they wonder what it
is.'' He found himself having to negotiate with the lab on
patients' behalf, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Hawkins, the president of ClaimsPro, a claims processing
company in Toledo, Ohio, said she could deal with these headaches
better than the labs and doctors could. Her company takes outgoing
bills and screens them, using special software to make sure that
all the coding and other essential information required by insurers
is where it belongs. Bills go out the door within 24 hours after
she receives them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ClaimsPro collects a fee only when the screened bills are paid,
so it is motivated to be accurate and fast. ``A lot of labs do
their billing in-house and are very slow,'' Hawkins said. Companies
like hers, she added, are gaining business as insurer requirements
become more stringent and as coding grows more complex.
</P>
<P>
   What can patients do?
</P>
<P>
   Start by calling the lab to make sure that it has your correct
insurance information. When you receive a bill, follow up and make
sure it is correct; if I had simply paid my bill without question,
I would have dumped nearly $200 out the window. If you are having
extensive tests, go over billing issues with your doctor's office
in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is a limit to how much aggravation you can head
off. ``It is a very frustrating process,'' said David Nichols, vice
president for marketing at Clinical Diagnostic Services in
Englewood, N.J., where my lab work was done. ``Doctors frustrate
labs, labs frustrate patients, patients frustrate insurance
companies. This is what is wrong with health care in a nutshell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
