<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2125 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-R-ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES     08-03 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ABOUT-CARS-MERCEDES-$ADV06-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY CAR IS SMARTER THAN YOUR CAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to change photo note to graphic note.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Mercedes-Benz brochure of the 1980s described the marque's
philosophy thus: A Mercedes should not inspire aggressive driving,
but if you find yourself in a bind _ say, roaring into a tight turn
too fast _ the car will get you through. That, at least, was the
gist. The Mercedes was an automotive Clark Kent, serious and
sedate, but ready to fling off its eyeglasses and soar to the
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing mild-mannered about the Mercedes-Benz of today.
The company boasts of having the fastest sport utility on the road,
the ML55, alongside V-12 sedans and luxury hot rods tweaked by AMG,
its high-performance-tuning operation. Still, the cutting-edge Merc
of today, the CL500 coupe, seems in many ways an evolution of that
previous thinking, not a break with it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the car is gorgeous, the only true pillarless hardtop in
showrooms today; its roofline is a graceful curve and the
traditional Mercedes grille is swept back into a long hood. The car
that I tested, in almandin black with light java leather, garnered
admiring glances on interstates and even on the jaded streets of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, it was powerful. Car and Driver magazine found that
the 302 horses of the 5-liter V-8 pushed the two-ton chariot to 60
miles per hour in a scant 6.2 seconds, and through a quarter-mile
in 14.7 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   For those who would dare yawn at that, the CL600 is now arriving
at dealerships, with a supersophisticated V-12 generating 362
horsepower. In November there will be a CL55, a souped-up AMG
version of the V-8 that makes 355 horsepower. Ergo, the car is
striking and fast, and destined to be faster.
</P>
<P>
   So where's Clark Kent?
</P>
<P>
   His legacy lives in the CL500s emphasis on intelligence over
brawn or beauty. If BMW celebrates driving, and Jaguar promotes
sensuality, Mercedes venerates technology _ and its showcase is the
CL. My pleasure in guiding the car on winding, rude backroads of
the Endless Mountains in Pennsylvania came not from speed or
cornering force, though these I tried, but from the way the
electronics and engineering anticipated and mastered every
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Turn as sharply as you dare, then stomp brutally on the brakes,
and the big machine remains almost mystically level and composed.
The feat is achieved by sophisticated hydraulic plungers at the
four corners that react in split seconds to keep the car
unflappably level no matter what the laws of physics try to do _
there is no dive, no squat, no roll, no wallow, no pitch, no sweat.
</P>
<P>
   When the paving runs out, a gentle nudge of a button nestled in
the burled walnut raises the starship an inch or two above the
nasty pebbles. As you accelerate back onto the highway, the car
snuggles down again to hug the pavement, ready to negotiate
whatever speed you dare.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes calls this system ``active body control,'' or ABC, and
it comes with ESP (electric stability program) and ASR (automatic
slip control). These are only the most impressive of a host of
electronic innovations that put the CL500 at the sharpest edge of
automotive technology.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking here of gizmos that do little besides twinkle
little red lights, but of stuff that really is useful, like the
ultra-low-profile windshield wipers that go on automatically, and
at the right frequency and speed, when they're needed; like the
ventilated and heated seats that can be adjusted 14 ways and _ get
this _ will give front-seat passengers a pulse massage; like the
doors and trunk lid that pull themselves closed; like the
five-speed automatic transmission that can figure out how sporty
the driver is, or that cedes the shifting to him or her. Not all of
this is unique to the CL500, of course, but it's all there in one
car, along with an automatic climate control with charcoal filter,
auto-dimming mirrors, Xenon headlamps, air bags everywhere and
laminated windows that filter infrared rays.
</P>
<P>
   The driver is not even aware of many touches, like aerodynamics
that channel water from the rear window, or the plastic fenders,
aluminum hood and roof and magnesium inner doors that keep the
weight far below that of previous big Mercedes coupes.
</P>
<P>
   To continue in this vein, I should describe how the 10 speakers
of the Bose audio system soothe the soul and whatnot, but that
would be premature. You do not learn on your first spin, or even on
the second, how to manipulate the ``Comand'' system _ the screen
and knobs that control the stereo, navigation computer, telephone
and probably many other things. Even a dedicated gadget lover will
find the centralized controls frustratingly unintuitive. Besides, I
wonder if the best of such systems _ like those operated by
touching the screen _ is truly safe. The glowing maps, messages and
instructions all require looking away from the road for at least a
few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, only the Comand system can be accused of being
distracting. What is impressive is how unobtusive, intuitive and
forgiving the rest of the electronics are. That, I think, is the
true link to the Mercedes philosophy of the 80s, the notion that
one could put more faith in the car's intelligence than in the
driver's. Some of these smarts are discreetly concealed, in the air
bags, the air filters, the adaptive transmission. In other matters,
the driver can override the automation _ by shifting the gears,
turning on the lights, turning off the wipers, switching off the
traction control. But in every instance, the CL500 demonstrates
what electronics can do _ and what, before long, they may be doing
in far lesser cars.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not pretend the ride is cheap. That terrific back massager
is $1,550 extra, and the multicontour seats add $1,050. The rest is
standard, and with $1,000 in gas-guzzler tax and $595 for shipping,
the CL500 I drove came within $300 of $90,000. (The SL600 is
$117,200 plus add-ons; the CL55 will be around $10,000 below that.)
</P>
<P>
   But then, many electronic features that we take for granted,
from engine management to air bags, were exotic extras not so long
ago. Traction control, antilock brakes, electronically controlled
transmissions have become commonplace in inexpensive cars. So who's
to say that a $20,000 sedan won't be giving massages before long?
</P>
<P>
   More intriguing, where will Mercedes go from here? Next year,
the CL is expected to have a cruise control that keeps track of
what the car you are following is up to, and automatically slows
down or speeds up to keep you at a safe distance behind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
