<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT &LR;      08-03 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA DIARY: A GIG, A BABE TURNED POL, AND THE RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI and MATTHEW PURDY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Republican audiences this week have been prosperous and
vanilla and the stage always a Gap ad of vivid ethnicity. But
sometimes, the models have thoughts of their own.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, a group of children sat at school desks on the
convention-hall podium behind Laura Bush as she addressed the
delegates. On Thursday, at a ``Tribute to Laura Bush'' luncheon,
young performers from Philadelphia's Rainbow Company were her
backdrop in a packed hotel ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The children were excited, but some members of the troupe, a
musical theater group, seemed to feel more like props for the
Republicans' message of inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how male presidents can understand about
abortion and pregnancy,'' said Katie Gould, 15, before the company
performed for the Bushes, who oppose abortion. ``Like they say
they're not for welfare and they're not for abortion. They've never
experienced it _ not that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a show,'' said Will Brock, 27, who plays keyboards for
the group. ``But they've got to do some things to get some votes
they don't usually get, some black and Hispanic votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Martin, the director of the theater, said he liked the
exposure and money from the event and being part of what he called
history. ``I'm certainly not doing it because I believe in the
Republican ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some on stage were more coy. Asked if she supported George W.
Bush, Lauren Brown, who just turned 18, smiled politely and said
``I know who I'm voting for, but it's a secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Brooks left the stage thrilled that Governor Bush had
spoken to her, and she said, ``I tend to favor Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   As the performers ended their program with a rousing ``God Bless
America,'' the Bushes worked their way into the middle of the group
so they were surrounded by the children.
</P>
<P>
   Shrugged Brock, the keyboard player, ``It's a gig, man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tale of Two Dans
</P>
<P>
   Pop political quiz: Which Dan is at the Republican National
Convention, Quayle or Rostenkowski?
</P>
<P>
   Guess again. Rosty, the once-powerful Democratic House
leader-turned inmate-turned corporate consultant, is offering
convention commentary for Fox's Chicago television station.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle, the once-youthful vice president and surrogate son
of President Bush-turned national amusement-turned political orphan
when a real Bush son emerged, is home in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Through his office in Phoenix, Quayle, who made a brief and
ill-fated bid for the GOP presidential nomination, said he was
making himself scarce to allow the light to shine on George W.
</P>
<P>
   Let's ask a veteran commentator. ``I hate to say this about him,
because he was vice president,'' Rostenkowski said. ``Dan Quayle
was never taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Rostenkowski once was, but at the convention, he said, people
looked at him quizzically. ``I'm just doing a job here,'' he
growled.
</P>
<P>
   For Republican Women Who Rock
</P>
<P>
   Congresswoman Mary Bono's new women's organization _ in a play
on the name of the women's group more typically affiliated with
another political party _ is called Right Now. It made its national
debut with a party Wednesday night at a nightclub called The Five
Spot.
</P>
<P>
   The party was pretty tame: The club typically has a burlesque
show with some nudity every Wednesday, but they canceled it and
hired a swing band in deference to the Republican women.
</P>
<P>
   Bono said she and a couple of friends were sitting around having
a beer last year when they came up with the idea for Right Now.
``We were just talking about how there were young women in the
Republican party who don't really have a place to go. They needed
someplace hipper than the Republican Women's Federation.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Bono's aides described that venerable group as ``the
blue-hairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we're rock 'n' roll Republicans,'' Bono said, sipping a
vanilla martini. Then she made a whooping sound, like the exuberant
exhalation of a teen-ager at a rock concert, holding a lighter
aloft:
</P>
<P>
   Whooooo!
</P>
<P>
   Bono said that she decided to call the group Right Now because
feminists like Gloria Steinem and Patricia Ireland, the president
of the National Organization for Women, had defended Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, NOW is extremely ticked off at the abuse of
their name. Patricia Ireland, NOW's president, said, ``I think they
will be as successful in starting a grass-roots organization as
they will in holding on to our name. I have sent a notice to our
general counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Derek Conversion
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years can sure change a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Derek used to be the bodacious babe in the movie ``10,''
bouncing along the beach in a macrame bikini that wouldn't provide
enough material for a potholder. In those days, she was an
apathetic California Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward two decades. Bo Derek is now a Republican
operative in a gray pants suit, a stump-speechifying campaign
junkie, a 43-year-old George W. Bush acolyte. Along with Lee
Greenwood, the Rock and Chaka Kahn, she is providing the GOP's
celebrity firepower.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Derek spoke about her political awakening
and her excitement about appearing at the convention, where she
introduced a California assemblyman on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out as a Democrat because I had the impression that
they were nicer people,'' she said. ``But I have spent a lot of
time out of the country, and you can't help but compare governments
and see how things function, and you start to see that what works
here is due to Republican policies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Derek differs from the Bush gospel on at least one major
issue: abortion. ``I am pro-choice,'' she said, then brightly
added, ``But I am really, really completely behind George Bush's
ideas about reforming education.''
</P>
<P>
   After the convention, Derek will start filming a new movie,
playing an alcoholic defense lawyer. She's no longer playing beach
babes.
</P>
<P>
   Would she ever run for office?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but people have asked me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Soggy Scenes of Summer
</P>
<P>
   Don't take it as a sign from God that it rained every day of the
Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   But the weather in Philadelphia sure did contribute to sodden
energy levels by the final day of the Republican convention on
Thursday. California delegates were popping gingko-biloba capsules
to stay alert. Donors and delegates on their way into yet another
PAC party began to complain of gout. On ``Good Morning America,''
Charles Gibson stood on the floor of the convention hall and
pointed out a flashing sign to Diane Sawyer, who was in New York.
It read: We need fresh laundry, Diane!
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday night's grand finale, Kentucky delegate Joey
Stanton was dragging himself to the final happy hour sponsored by
House Whip Tom DeLay's political action committee, aboard a VIP
train car parked outside the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back hurts,'' he complained, ``My toenails hurt. My
bellybutton hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Borden of Texas said that friends had e-mailed him saying
he had looked asleep on C-Span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I e-mailed them back saying, `well, you dopes, I should have
looked asleep because I was asleep,''' he said. ``I am dying for
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it takes a grizzled professional to negotiate the
grueling party schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the former presidential candidate, looked spry and
expertly made-up on his way into the PAC party caboose. ``Having
been on the campaign trail, this is duck soup,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
