<SLUG> BC-GOP-DONATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CURBING DONATIONS, COMPANIES FIND NEW WAYS TO COURT KEY
REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When General Motors became the first corporation
to voluntarily stop writing large checks to political parties in
1997, the automaker's executives sent a powerful message that they
were disgusted by the political culture of cash and influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the principle,'' said GM's vice chairman, Harry J.
Pearce, after announcing the decision in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, GM has stuck to its pledge to forswear soft money,
the unrestricted gifts, after donating $750,000 to political
parties in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But outside the convention hall and around town this week, the
nation's largest automaker demonstrated that it has hardly
abandoned the campaign finance arena, finding different ways to
curry favor with current _ and possibly future _ Republican
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   GM provided 400 Cadillacs, sport utility vehicles and minivans
for use by the organizers of the Republican National Convention,
part of a package of ``in-kind contributions'' that the host
committee here estimated was worth $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday, GM sponsored two lunch receptions at different
downtown locales _ one honored House Speaker Dennis Hastert and the
other saluted Lawrence B. Lindsey, the chief economic adviser to
the campaign of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Of the more than 30 corporations that have eschewed soft money,
GM is not the only company here to play the political influence
game without handing out checks.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, which stopped making soft money donations last
year, was one of the sponsors of a gaudy packed party on Wednesday
night at the nightclub Shampoo to honor a House entertainment task
force.
</P>
<P>
   GM's receptions were less flashy but attracted more high-powered
political stars.
</P>
<P>
   At the lunch at the Philadelphia Naval Yard, GM designers showed
off the newest prototypes, called concept cars, for Hastert, an
unabashed automobile buff. The speaker was joined by members of the
House Transportation Committee and was given a miniature replica of
a vintage GM truck, a 1950 Chevrolet Bullnose pickup, that he is
restoring at home in Illinois. The menu was seared tuna, red wine
and strawberry souffle.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, Hastert squeezed into several of the concept cars
on display, including a voice-activated Buick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are leading the way and creating the transportation system
that is leading the world,'' Hastert told GM executives. ``We
salute you and your industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across town, GM and GMAC Financial Services held a
brunch honoring Lindsey, the lead economic adviser to Bush who is
also a consultant to GMAC and a board member of its subsidiary,
Escrow Bank U.S.A. of Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The brunch allowed GM to showcase its relationship with Lindsey.
In his introduction, John Finnegan, the chairman of GMAC, hailed
Lindsey as ``one of the best economic minds in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   After speaking to a group of 100 GM executives, lobbyists and a
few House members, Lindsey seemed surprised when he was asked if it
was appropriate for the automaker to sponsor the brunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a three-year relationship with GM,'' Lindsey, 46,
said. ``It's a natural thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Several GMAC vice presidents drew a distinction between the
corporation's discarded practice of making soft-money donations and
their current practice of holding receptions for consultants and
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the game we like to play,'' a GMAC senior vice
president, Scott Rombach, said of the practice of giving soft
money. ``But this is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Another GMAC vice president, Jim Farmer, said, ``This is just a
kind gesture to Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   With much fanfare last November, Time Warner announced it would
no longer make soft money donations. The company's chairman, Gerald
Levin, said much of the soft money had been used for misleading and
negative advertising that had cheapened political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Wednesday night, Time Warner's raucous party was
attended by about 1,000 lobbyists, House staff members and
journalists. As thousands of free drinks were served and the
singers Jon Secada and Celia Cruz performed, the attendees toasted
Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., and the House Entertainment Industry Task
Force, a loose coalition of House members whose decisions affect
the media and entertainment industries.
</P>
<P>
   The party was also sponsored by News Corp., Seagram/Universal
Studios, the Recording Industry Association of America, the Motion
Picture Association of America, Viacom and Walt Disney Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Adler, a senior vice president at Time Warner, did not
return telephone calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Another party sponsor, Viacom, the parent of CBS, gives
virtually no soft money to political parties, but its political
action committee contributes sizable sums to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, several corporations have stopped giving soft
money because their executives have said that they had found better
uses for their resources, such as lobbying, building political
action committees and sponsoring fund-raising events. Some
executives have complained that it was harder to justify the
expense of large contributions to shareholders because the
membership fees of the parties' most elite donor clubs had outpaced
the rate of inflation, jumping this year to $250,000 from $100,000
.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at other corporations that sponsored parties and
receptions this week said they believed the events are most
effective at marketing the corporate brand-names to
convention-goers.
</P>
<P>
   Providing 400 vehicles to the host committee is ``a great
product exposure opportunity for us,'' said William Noack, a GM
spokesman attending the convention. ``We also do it for the
Olympics and events like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
