<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES END BROADLY HIGHER TO RECOVER FROM EARLY SKID 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks pulled out of an early skid and rallied to
finish broadly higher on Thursday, with the technology-dominated
Nasdaq composite index posting a hefty 2.8 percent gain after being
down as much as 3.8 percent in the first half hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index and Dow Jones industrial
average traced similar but less pronounced patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the sharp reversal to a combination of
bargain-hunting, Motorola's denial of a report that it had cut its
estimate of cellular telephone production, and a surge of
confidence that the government's monthly report on jobs and pay, to
be released on Friday morning, would make the Federal Reserve less
likely to raise short-term interest rates when it meets on Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is still searching for technological investment,'' said
Ned Riley Jr., chief investment officer at State Street Advisors in
Boston. He cautioned, however, that the Federal Reserve will sooner
or later succeed in curbing economic growth and that when it does,
high-technology businesses will be hurt as well as traditional,
more cyclical, companies.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor stocks were under particular selling pressure on
Thursday morning after Kulicke &AMP; Soffa, a top maker of equipment
for assembling chips, warned of deferred orders. Its shares slumped
to 13 9/16 and recovered only to 16 5/8, down 5{. Credence Systems
was among other industry losers, falling 9 49/64, to 39.
</P>
<P>
   But other technology stocks regained all their lost ground and
then some, with Cisco Systems, the most highly valued company after
General Electric, slipping to 58{ before rallying to close at 64
3/8, up 3 7/16. Cisco is to report its quarterly results on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index ended the day with a gain of 101.42
points, at 3,759.88. This shrank its loss so far this year to 7.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 advanced 13.86 points, or nearly 1 percent, to
1,452.56, paced by Cisco, Oracle, Intel, Sun Microsystems, EMC and
Nortel Networks.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-chip Dow Jones industrial average, many of whose
components have been recent havens for investors fleeing
technology, rose 19.05 points, or 0.2 percent, to 10,706.58. The
Dow is down 6.9 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and brokerage firm stocks joined technology among the
day's biggest winning sectors. J.P. Morgan, up 3, to 135, was the
best-performing Dow stock, accounting for 17 points of the 19-point
rise in the blue-chip average.
</P>
<P>
   Clorox reported a big profit gain but cautioned about prospects
and its stock slipped 3 11/16, to 39 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Gap's profits disappointed Wall Street and the shares fell 7/8,
to 31\.
</P>
<P>
   But Viacom beat expectations and rose 2 3/16, to 71 9/16, while
Disney, reporting after the 4 p.m. close of the market, gained 2
points in late trading.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which changed hands for as little as 33{, ended at 35
15/16, down 11/16, while AT&AMP;T touched a 52-week low before
finishing at 30 5/8, down 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton Hotels eased 9/16, to 9 9/16, after announcing higher
second-quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Battipaglia, chief market strategist at Gruntal, was
among analysts saying the Federal Reserve can still refrain from
raising rates at this month's meeting despite mixed evidence that
the economy's blistering pace has appreciably slackened. He
predicted it will decide that the series of six increases since
mid-1999 ``is all we have to do for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sundeman, an analyst at Schaeffer's Investment Research,
said that the market had rallied sharply on recent job reports that
suggested inflation remained largely in check.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange rose on Thursday to 1.1
billion shares from 994.6 million as 74 issues made new highs,
compared with 57 new lows. But declines outnumbered advancing
issues by 1,545 to 1,338, roughly reversing Wednesday's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq turnover was 1.83 billion shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
