<HEADER>
A2136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SOUTHERNERS-BADRAP080     08-03 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERNERS-BADRAP0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Study finds bastion of bias: Y'all with an accent need not apply
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A heavy regional accent, including a Southern drawl,
works against job candidates, a University of North Texas study
concludes.
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey participant in the study was ranked by potential
hirers as the least employable of 10 men from various regions of
the United States. Although he had a doctoral degree, he was
perceived as uneducated and hostile.
</P>
<P>
   The second-lowest ranking went to a North Georgia man, who was a
doctoral candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Accent bias is often subtle but has significant impact, the
study found.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters in the study regarded people with Southern drawls,
for instance, as stupid and assigned them to jobs where they had
little contact with the public. ``You mean to tell me if somebody's
a cardiologist and you need surgery, you're going to deny your life
just because he's got an accent?'' reacted Lee Pederson, an Emory
University linguist.
</P>
<P>
   ``After spending my professional career studying dialects in the
North and South, I find it offensive that observers are making
incorrect observations about people's speech,'' Pederson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although other studies have focused on attitudes toward accents,
the Texas study is believed to be the first related to people's
getting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas researcher Patricia Cukor-Avila said bias against
people with noticeable accents has become ``an acceptable form of
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   The study had 56 executives with hiring authority listen to
recordings of 10 men reading the same 45-second passage. The
speakers were from Boston, Chicago, Minneapolis, Louisiana,
Alabama, California, Texas and North Carolina, in addition to
Georgia and New Jersey. All of the speakers were college-educated.
The executives hire people for white-collar jobs in banking,
telecommunications, government, agriculture, higher education and
other fields.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring executives perceived the man from Georgia as friendly
and said he would do well in a job with little public contact.
</P>
<P>
   A Californian and Minnesotan in the group ranked high mostly
because their accents were neutral, researcher Dianne Markley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ties in to the fact that in the U.S., we tend to go for
nondescript accents based on those of national broadcasters and
actors,'' said Cukor- Avila.
</P>
<P>
   HOW THE ACCENTS RANKED
</P>
<P>
   California
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   Texas
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina
</P>
<P>
   Boston
</P>
<P>
   Alabama
</P>
<P>
   Chicago
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana
</P>
<P>
   Georgia
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``The Effect of Regional Accents in the Hiring Process:
A language Attitude study,'' University of North Texas, Denton,
Tex.
</P>
