u i BC-YUGO-ARMS-ARRESTS-315     08-03 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ARMS-ARRESTS-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS HOLD 4 WESTERNERS IN ARMS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The Yugoslav army said Thursday that it
had arrested two Britons and two Canadians in Montenegro, accusing
them of possessing weapons and explosives, in what appeared to be
another effort to stimulate fears of Western encirclement before
elections next month.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second arrest of four foreigners reported this week
by Yugoslav authorities. Four Dutchmen whose detention was
disclosed on Monday were seized last month on Serbia's border with
Montenegro, reportedly because they were trying to kill President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The army said Thursday that the Britons and Canadians were
employees of the NATO-led forces in Kosovo and were suspected of
training pro-Western secessionists in Montenegro, Serbia's tiny
sister republic, to commit ``terrorist actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges were rejected by British and Canadian forces, who
said the four were simply returning from a weekend vacation in
Montenegro to nearby Kosovo, the Serbian province that NATO-led
forces now control, and were not carrying arms or explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest follows days of Serbian and Yugoslav army statements
about the need to preserve Yugoslavia, which is made up of Serbia
and Montenegro. Belgrade has accused the West of training the
Montenegrin police in preparation for Montenegro's secession, and
the charges today appear to fit that pattern.
</P>
<P>
   President Milo Djukanovic of Montenegro has broken with
Milosevic, talks of an independent Montenegro and is openly
supported by the West. Milosevic controls the Yugoslav army in
Montenegro, while Djukanovic controls the police, which he has
built up with Western help.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats fear that Milosevic is not merely creating a
sense of threat to help his election campaign, but may also be
laying the groundwork for military or police action in Montenegro
to bring down Djukanovic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NATO provided Montenegro a security guarantee in its air war
against Serbia last year. But that guarantee is no longer in place.
NATO and Western officials regularly warn Milosevic not to move
against Montenegro. But they do not specify what NATO might do
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has called federal, local and presidential elections
for Sept. 24. Djukanovic has resisted calls by the Clinton
administration to participate in them and, together with the
Serbian opposition, try to defeat Milosevic. Djukanovic argues that
to participate after recent constitutional changes forced through
by Milosevic would only legitimize the elections, which Milosevic
is widely expected to rig.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has also been unable to persuade Vuk Draskovic,
leader of the Serbian Renewal Movement, the single largest
opposition party in Serbia, to participate in the elections. But
Draskovic appears to be willing to have his party run for local
offices and at least support a unified opposition candidate for the
presidency, if one can be agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic presents himself as the best defender of Serbs against
outside enemies and paints his opposition as traitors in the pay of
the Western countries that bombed Yugoslavia last year and took
over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats regard the arrest of the four men near the
Montenegro-Kosovo border sometime between Monday night and Tuesday
morning as a ploy for domestic purposes. In a statement faxed to
news agencies in Belgrade, the Yugoslav army said, ``There are
indications the foreign citizens arrested trained special units of
the Interior Ministry in the Republic of Montenegro and are
specialists in demolition and performing terrorist actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Britons _ Adrian Pragnell, 41, and John Yore, 31 _ work
in Kosovo training police officers at the police academy, said
their employer, the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, which is based in Vienna. A spokeswoman for the
organization, Melissa Fleming, said in a telephone interview that
the two men were unarmed, and that they had been taking a ``weekend
excursion'' to Montenegro and were to return to England on Sept. 4,
after a year in Kosovo. Fleming said descriptions of the men as
experts on explosives were ``absolutely absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   The office of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe in Kosovo has warned its employees not to travel to
Montenegro, but it is not clear that all employees received the
warning, Fleming said. It is possible that the four arrested men do
not have visas for Yugoslavia, she said, ``but probably that's the
extent of their wrongdoing.'' The organization does not know where
the men are being held, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians _ Shaun Going, 45, and his nephew Liam Hall, 19 _
had also gone to Montenegro from Kosovo for a weekend break,
employees told Agence France-Presse in Pristina. Going owns
Meridian Resources, a construction company with headquarters in
Calgary, Alberta. For a year, he has been running its office in
Pristina, where the company has 20 contracts, mostly with the
NATO-led forces. Going was said to be friendly with the Britons and
was traveling with them.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Yugoslav authorities played a videotape at a news
conference that showed the Dutchmen arrested in August confessing
to the charges of plotting to kidnap or assassinate Milosevic and
the former Bosnian Serb leader, Radovan Karadzic.
</P>
</TEXT>
