u f BC-INVEST-DISCLOSURE-NYT     08-03 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DISCLOSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC TO REVISE PROPOSED RULE RESTRICTING CORPORATE DISCLOSURES
</HEADLINE>
  By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite an outpouring of support from individual investors and
consumer groups, federal securities regulators are still scrambling
to revise a proposed rule against selective disclosure of corporate
information before it comes up for a vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is scheduled to vote on
Aug. 10 on the new rule, designed to prevent corporate officials
from sharing important information only with limited groups of big
investors or Wall Street analysts. People close to the commission
said they expected the rule, a pet project of Arthur Levitt, the
chairman of the commission, to be passed over the vocal opposition
of investment banks and brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt has repeatedly said that by ``feeding'' information to
analysts before the rest of the investing public, some corporations
have put ``a stain on our markets.'' Two of the three other
commissioners have expressed concerns about particular aspects of
the proposed rule.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure passage, these people said, the commission is
rewriting the rule to make clear that senior executives will not be
punished for sharing information with reporters and bond-rating
agencies and that lower-level employees will remain as free as they
are now to talk to people outside their companies. The commission
also is making changes to protect executives from civil lawsuits
over public disclosures of corporate information.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is exempting information gathered by reporters to
appease some critics in the media, including Dow Jones &AMP; Co., the
publisher of The Wall Street Journal. Dow Jones objected to the
rule, arguing that it could restrict the ability of reporters to
gather information from company executives.
</P>
<P>
   Peter G. Skinner, executive vice president and general counsel
for Dow Jones, said Thursday that he had heard that the company's
concerns had been addressed, but he declined to comment before
seeing a revised version of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has received thousands of letters and e-mail
messages expressing support for the rule from individual investors,
as well as the Consumer Federation of America, the Council of
Institutional Investors and the Financial Executives Institute. On
Thursday, the AFL-CIO said its investment officers supported the
rule.
</P>
<P>
   One group that has not been appeased is the Securities Industry
Association, the main trade group for Wall Street firms. On
Thursday, the association reiterated its strong opposition to the
proposed rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental problem with this is that, with the best of
intentions, it will end up hurting investors,'' said Stuart
Kaswell, general council for the association. ``They're taking a
swing at Wall Street and they're going to hit investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaswell said that the rule would do more harm than good because
it would sharply curtail communications between company executives
and analysts and, in turn, the investors those analysts advise.
Analysts no longer will be able to meet privately with corporate
executives and try to ``ferret out'' information that may be useful
to investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will have what amount to presidential-style press
conferences where corporate officials will be able to answer as
much or as little as they care to answer,'' Kaswell said. ``The
chance to ask hard-hitting questions in private will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Kaswell, Joseph McLaughlin, a securities lawyer at Brown &AMP;
Wood in New York, argues that the rule will put a chill on
corporate communications. ``The natural thing to do is to be
extremely careful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But groups representing major corporations, such as the Business
Roundtable, have not stood in the commission's way. ``We talked a
lot about whether there would be a chilling effect,'' said Philip
Livingston, chief executive of Financial Executives Institute. ``We
didn't really think so.''
</P>
<P>
   To protect reporters' ability to gather news, the commission
plans to spell out who cannot receive material information from
corporate officials that is not available to the general public.
That group of recipients will be limited to include securities
analysts, brokers, mutual fund managers and other big investors.
The association opposes that change, Kaswell said, because
brokerage firms regard news reporters as competitors in a race to
gather valuable information about companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is standard practice at most companies to hold
separate meetings and conference calls for analysts and for
reporters. Privately, some securities regulators say the Wall
Street firms are fighting to maintain the advantage they have in
gathering information from companies whose stocks they rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the fear is that information is being given out
selectively as a way of keeping analysts in check,'' said Harvey
Goldschmid, a law professor at Columbia University who helped draft
the proposed rule when he was the commission's general counsel.
``Fundamentally, for the average person, there will be a sense of
the markets being fairer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
