<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bessemer Trust to Acquire Two Units of a Rival Firm
</P>
<P>
   Bessemer Trust, one of the oldest firms in the business of
managing money for wealthy families, will announce Friday that it
is buying the private client and institutional equity groups of a
rival, Brundage, Story &AMP; Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed. But executives said the
deal would add $4.5 billion in assets under management and about
800 clients to Bessemer, which has $33 billion under management and
1,300 clients. Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette is buying Brundage,
Story's institutional fixed-income division.
</P>
<P>
   Spirit of Silicon Valley Lives in China
</P>
<P>
   Zhongguancun, a chaotic Beijing neighborhood, is both the site
of some of China's best universities and the government's
designated high-technology industrial zone _ its Silicon Valley _
where there are 500 to 600 recent home-grown Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Profit Increases 48 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney reported a 48 percent rise in third-quarter profit,
citing strong advertising sales at its ABC television network. The
strong advertising market, buoyed by hit show ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' kept Disney well ahead of Wall Street's
expectations. Before Disney announced its results, its shares
closed at $42.3125, up $2.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom said second-quarter profit fell because of good-will
expenses for its purchase of CBS, but the results still beat
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Reverse Slide and Close Up
</P>
<P>
   Stocks pulled out of an early skid and rallied to finish broadly
higher. The Nasdaq composite index gained 101.42 points, or 2.8
percent, to 3,759.88. The Dow Jones industrial average edged up
19.05 points, to 10,706.58, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index rose 13.86 points, or 1 percent, to 1,452.56.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy Defects to Michael Ovitz
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of Michael Ovitz's return to power as a
Hollywood deal maker, Ovitz has persuaded the thriller writer Tom
Clancy to defect from his longtime agent, Robert Gottlieb at the
William Morris Agency.
</P>
<P>
   No Gene-Altered Food for Novartis
</P>
<P>
   Novartis, one of the world's leading agricultural biotechnology
companies, said that it had eliminated genetically engineered
ingredients from all of its food products.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Emerges to NTT in Japan
</P>
<P>
   Japan Telecom, one of Japan's largest telecommunications
companies, plans to offer local phone service, which would put it
into direct competition with Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, the
former government phone monopoly. Haruo Murakami, president of
Japan Telecom, said that his company had applied to NTT for the
right to tap into its local network. Japan Telecom could offer the
new service in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Law Firm Mergers Cross Borders
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by globalization and a boom in corporate law involving
mergers and acquisitions, law firms in Europe are undergoing
combinations of their own. The changes are also affecting law firms
in the United States, as links are forged across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Group Invests in Supercomputer
</P>
<P>
   The National Science Foundation said it had made a $45 million
award to the Pittsburgh Supercomputing Center to buy what will be
the world's fastest nonmilitary supercomputer when it is completely
installed next year, said Compaq, the computer's maker.
</P>
<P>
   Retail Sales Gained 3.7 Percent in July
</P>
<P>
   Sales in stores open more than a year, a crucial figure for
measuring the health of the retail industry, rose 3.7 percent in
July.
</P>
</TEXT>
