<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WILLIAMS400-0804-COX     08-03 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS400-0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who is the next Ted Williams?
 &HT;    By Joe Capozzi
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ About a year ago, Ted Williams sat down
to breakfast with some guests at his Hernando home. There were a
couple of New Hampshire state troopers who were longtime friends
and a few others, but the Hall of Famer didn't notice the slender
kid with the ballcap pulled close to his bird's-beak nose.
</P>
<P>
   Between bites of eggs and fruit, the baseball talk started
flowing. Someone asked Williams what he thought of the young
shortstop for the Boston Red Sox, Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great hitter. Graceful. Powerful,'' replied Williams, 81,
the last man to hit. 400. ``And if anyone can hit .400 again, it's
Garciaparra.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the table, Garciaparra flipped off his cap and grinned.
The table erupted in laughter. Good thing you complimented the kid,
someone joked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's the truth,'' said Williams, who was 23 when he hit
.406 in 1941. ``If anyone can do it, this guy can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday, Garciaparra, 27, was batting .398 with two
months left in the season. Plenty of hitters over the years have
had high averages in August only to see them fall to more human
levels come September.
</P>
<P>
   But in this era of Cartoon Baseball, many are wondering whether
the same elements that have altered the home-run records will lead
to the first .400 hitter in nearly 60 years _ and whether that
hitter just might be Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought a few years ago that Tony Gwynn was the only guy,''
said George Brett, who in 1980 made the most serious run in 39
years, batting .400 as late as Sept. 19 before finishing at .390.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the numbers are so inflated right now. You had Roger
Maris' (single-season home run) record stand for so long and now
guys are flying past it. Pretty soon somebody is going to get on a
hot streak. I definitely think someone else is going to do it. It's
going to happen, but it's going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE TO THE HITTERS
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be tough, all right. Hitters travel to different
time zones, see more than just one pitcher per game and face a
crush of media. But there are advantages that didn't exist in the
days of Ty Cobb and Teddy Ballgame: diluted pitching from expansion
and stronger, better-conditioned players _ benefiting from
advancements such as laser eye surgery, nutritional supplements and
year-round strength programs _ hitting with smaller strike zones in
smaller ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good hitters out there,'' said pitcher
Randy Johnson of the Arizona Diamondbacks, ''but I don't know if
anyone will (hit .400 again). I think it might be more difficult
now because there are so many specialty pitchers coming out of the
bullpen. They get to face up to four different pitchers in a game,
all coming with different stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that the road to .400 may not be an
impossible journey. Darin Erstad, a left-handed hitter for the
Anaheim Angels, is on pace to break the single-season record for
hits (257 in 1920 by George Sisler, who hit .407 that year).
</P>
<P>
   And entering the All-Star break, 11 players _ six in the
National League and five in the American League _ were batting .350
or higher. Only twice in the past 10 seasons have as many as seven
players been hitting that high by the All-Star break, according to
the Elias Sports Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's average stood at .389 at the break, followed by
Colorado's Todd Helton at .384. In 1993, John Olerud was hitting
.395 and Andres Galaragga .391 at the break. A year later, Larry
Walker was at .398.
</P>
<P>
   Still, only two players since 1941 have hit .400 into August _
Olerud in 1993 and Brett in 1980. And for Garciaparra to finish the
season at .400, he would have to at least match his best career
numbers for August (.372 in 1997) and September (.393 in 1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting .400 is probably the closest to impossible feat there
is,'' said Braves third baseman Chipper Jones, the reigning NL MVP.
``Some guys hit .400 for a month. That's a hot month. You stay hot
for six or seven months, that's unheard of. Guys just don't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   GETTING BREAKS ESSENTIAL
</P>
<P>
   Wade Boggs did it. For a span of 162 games, he hit .404 _ from
May 1985 to May 1986. (Boggs finished 1985 at .368 and 1986 at
.357.) But Boggs, now retired and working in the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays' front office, and Williams are among those who do not
subscribe to the theory that the Power Ball-era elements will spike
batting averages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think home runs and average are conducive to one
another. You can go one for five with a home run and hit 65 home
runs and not hit for average,'' Boggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for someone to hit .400, you have to enter September
hitting .420. And even then, the only way to hit .400 is to barely
qualify for the title, have the minimum number of at-bats or be
injured part of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Brett's season went in 1980, when he missed 45 games
because of injuries, including an ankle injury that sidelined him
for six weeks. By Aug. 30, with his average at .406, Williams and
Maris were saying they thought Brett could hit .400.
</P>
<P>
   In that final month of 1980, Brett recalled, the pressure
finally got to him. He was hounded by reporters. The ball no longer
looked like a cantaloupe. Fielders seemed to rob him of hits with
great defensive plays.
</P>
<P>
   He went 4 for his next 27, dropping to .384, then went on to get
10 hits in his next 19 at-bats to finish with the highest average
since Williams in '41.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with the media was tough,'' Brett recalled. ``Whoever
is going to do it, that last month of the season is going to be
hard to deal with. I'm still getting calls on (the 1980 season) 20
years later.''
</P>
<P>
   POWER VS. AVERAGE
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the question of whether players want to hit .400 _
and accept all of the baggage that comes with it. Garciaparra
refuses to talk about numbers and insists he doesn't pay attention
to where his average is.
</P>
<P>
   In the record-breaking home-run season of 1998, there was a
feeling players were more infatuated with power than for average.
``Big home-run hitters are being paid a lot of money,'' Mike
Hargrove, then managing the Cleveland Indians, told a reporter that
year, ``and I think a lot of people are concentrating on homers.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the skeptics agree that few offensive records, power or
average, are safe anymore. ``I never thought I'd see major-league
players hit .370 with 55 home runs and 160 RBI,'' Brett said.
``That just didn't happen when I played, and I've only been out of
the game since 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Boggs, ``I don't think anybody can say 'never' about
anybody, not when you have Sammy Sosa hitting 60 home runs for two
years in a row and never leading the league. That's
mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Many agree that a left-handed hitter would have the best shot at
.400. Because most pitchers are right-handed, a left-handed hitter
more often than not has a better view of the pitch. However, these
same people think the right-handed Garciaparra is a hitter who
might have the intangibles to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's unreal,'' Boston pitcher Pedro Martinez said
Friday after Garciaparra went 3-for-4 in Oakland. ``I've never seen
anybody _ never, ever _ any pitch, any count, you can whip it up
there and he can hit it. I just pray to God he stays healthy. I've
seen something very weird in Nomar's bat and he only seems to hit
the ball with the barrel of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, whose Braves played the Red Sox this month, was impressed
at the way Garciaparra was able to hit breaking balls going away
from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps everything so simple,'' Jones said. ``He's got very
little movement. His mechanics are perfect. He's got a perfect
swing. He plays in a great ballpark where he can hit 290-foot
doubles all day. But he doesn't just try to do that. He'll take the
ball the other way. He's got some juice to all fields. He's very
quick to figure out what a pitcher's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why the last man to hit .400 says he thinks
Garciaparra will be the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar is going to do it. He's going to hit .400,'' Williams
said in a phone interview Saturday. ``I'm predicting that on the
record and I've been saying that for a while. He has the instinct
and the patience and the discipline, and the proof is in the
average.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
