r k BC-DIAZ-COMMENTARY_SFCHR     08-03 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAZ-COMMENTARY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY _ 650 WORDS _ SFCHRON
</HEADLINE>
 _ SFCHRON
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GOP CONVENTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN DIAZ, Editorial Page Editor &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
GOP TO YOUTH: DO AS WE SAY, NOT AS WE DO
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it is in Politics 2000. Subtlety and specifics _
or risky ideas _ are for losers. So are worries about perceptions
about how much it costs to include a member of Congress in your
foursome for golf.
</P>
<P>
   Message is everything _ get the money and get the images on
television. Republicans here were hoping the nation would hardly
notice that the welcoming theme of inclusion from a parade of
diverse speakers was contradicted by hard-line remnants in the
party platform.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Colin Powell's eloquent opening night call against
``preferences for special interests'' failed to lighten the crush
at all the corporate-sponsored parties for delegates. The best
skyboxes in the house remained reserved for the ``Regents,'' the
title bestowed on the 137 people and companies who have contributed
at least $250,000 this election.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be considered gauche for a
politician to raise money at a convention. Not anymore. Rep. Tom
DeLay, the Texas Republican last seen on the national stage
whipping the troops into line to impeach President Clinton, kept a
low profile while leading the fund-raising frenzy all week. He
spent his time behind rope lines, schmoozing contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, the GOP throng here is so quick to note, will be
doing the same thing in Los Angeles. Get over it; enjoy the party _
``Hey, look, there's Jon Secada!'' As DeLay told a Washington Post
reporter about his legendarily aggressive fund raising, ``That's
what politics is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton and Al Gore showed how ruthless devotion to the
bottom line _ in money and message _ could succeed in 1992 and
1996, and everything about this convention suggests the Republicans
have learned their lessons well.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy may be winning elections, but it is losing the
faith of young people. Poll after poll has found a deep
disillusionment with politics among the people who are at an age
where they can be inspired to enter into the world of politics or
public service.
</P>
<P>
   I did, however, find at least a glimmer of youthful idealism at
this Republican gathering. In return for its $27 million
contribution to the two conventions, the federal government
required the two parties to set up programs to encourage young
people to participate in the political process. The Republican
National Committee brought in 600 people, ages 16 to 25, for a week
of seminars at the University of Pennsylvania and
convention-related duties, such as painting signs or serving as
pages on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   What I found in interviews with a handful of the participants
was the sense of idealism _ that issues, not images matter _ that
seemed so lacking from other convention events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you: I was a little ticked off with the
way it seemed they were trying to overplay the representation of
minorities in the party,'' said Yuwynn Ho, a 21-year-old UC
Berkeley economics and political science student.
</P>
<P>
   Ho, born in Malaysia, became a U.S.
citizen just three months ago. His parents left Malaysia because
the government allotted few slots for Malaysians of Chinese
descent. ``They knew I had zero chance of getting a good education
over there,'' he said. Ho now opposes racial preferences in any
form _ even for the selection of convention speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Ho's appreciation of American freedom also led him to pass up a
lucrative investment banking internship for an unpaid position at
the White House press office. Yes, the  &LR; Clinton &LR;  White House.
</P>
<P>
   Ho hopes to someday apply his newfound skills in a Bush
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Tobin, a 20-year-old college student from Delaware, said
he understood and accepted the strategic reasons for keeping the
convention programming on the benign-and-blurry side. He quickly
rattled off a number of items on his agenda, most of which involved
tax policy and limiting the role of government. The university
sessions gave him a sufficient dose of substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like we're having our own little convention
here,'' said Tobin, adding that the experience has ``definitely
inspired me to run for office.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the among the young people involved in major-party
politics; unfortunately, a rarity these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``These have been years of prosperity ... but little purpose,''
Dick Cheney said
in accepting the vice presidential nomination Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the Clinton White House. His words also
could be applied to the state of the major political parties.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail John Diaz at  &LR; diaz &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
