<HEADER>
A2145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-03 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Breaking down the art of the Philly cheese steak
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Before leaving town, it's time to blow the
whistle on Philadelphia cheese steaks. That's the depth charge of a
sandwich that _ the Liberty Bell and Rocky Balboa statue aside _
seems to be the reason most people bother to get off the train
between Washington and New York.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I've gone along with the game, traipsing about town
with crazed locals who want to show me where the really best cheese
steak is made. Regretfully, I've concluded there is no such thing
as a really good cheese steak, at least in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A Lebanese guy who ran a diner across the street from the
Chronicle's Washington bureau made a better cheese steak than I've
ever had here.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've lived in Waxahachie, Texas, all your life,
perhaps you need the cheese steak short course. It comes on a long
roll (cf submarine, hero, hoagie). And immediately run away
shrieking if a Philadelphian tries to tell you there's a
significant difference in these three essentially indistinguishable
types of gummy white bread.
</P>
<P>
   The eponymous ``steak'' is paper-thin shavings of mystery meat
fried up in great gobs on a grill. The cook slashes at the mass
with a couple of spatulas, trying to whack it into further
unrecognizable shreds. I'm duty-bound to note that I've never seen
a stray dog near Ninth and Passyunk, cheese steak ground zero.
</P>
<P>
   Now here's the really rich part. The ``cheese'' can be ersatz
American or ersatz provolone (which has never been closer to Italy
than Bayonne, N.J.). But it can just as easily be Cheez Whiz or
even less distinguished orangey glop (dished up from the bubbling
can in which it was formulated at the laboratory).
</P>
<P>
   Cheez Whiz is perfectly fine as the base for a frozen spinach
dip at a
 &UR;  &LR; suburban wife-swapping party, but it can't seriously be considered
a prime ingredient in a supposed culinary landmark.
</P>
<P>
   That's the basic cheese steak.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the options. The best course is to plead for a lot of
fried onions, and the greasier the better, as the undressed
sandwich is pretty dry. Slivers of canned ``Italian'' peppers (see
geographical note on provolone above) are almost always on offer,
but they don't help much and can lead to Alka-Seltzer abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps visiting Republicans have been lured by the hype to
sample a cheese steak in its native precincts. But convention-goers
may not be easy pushovers on the junk food front. Recent Democratic
and Republican confabs have been held in cities with far more
distinguished candidates for the sandwich hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic delegates in New York (1976, 1980, 1992) could
experience first-hand the pleasures of pastrami and corned beef.
Many a post-session caucus was convened at the Carnegie Deli or
Katz's (Motto: ``Send a salami to your boy in the Army``).
</P>
<P>
   The GOP convention in New Orleans (1988) was a revelation to
those untutored in po' boys (shrimp or oyster versions at Mother's
or the drippy, fully dressed beef entry at Parasol's). Or
muffulettas (the cold cuts and cheese delight topped with olive
salad, preferably from Central Grocery). Houston (1992) opened the
world of real barbecue to many an outlander's tastebuds.
</P>
<P>
   And in just a week or so, Democrats in Los Angeles can join the
fight over the real birthplace of the French-dip. (I'm a firm
backer of Philippe's across from Union Station and intend to sing
its praises more fully if I'm allowed back into this space when our
magical mystery tour reaches the Coast).
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle columnist Cragg Hines is writing convention reports
this week in addition to his regular Sunday and Wednesday columns
on the Chronicle's editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
