u f BC-CLANCY-OVITZ-NYT &LR;      08-03 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLANCY-OVITZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM CLANCY LEAVES AGENT OF 18 YEARS TO JOIN OVITZ 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another sign of Michael Ovitz's return to power as a
Hollywood deal-maker, Ovitz has persuaded the best-selling thriller
writer Tom Clancy to defect from his longtime agent Robert Gottlieb
at the William Morris Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb was irate at the news. He discovered Clancy's first
manuscript, ``The Hunt for Red October,'' 18 years ago at a book
fair. Gottlieb went on to negotiate contracts for 47 of his books,
roughly 10 of them still be to published, along with film,
television and other deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clancy was raided,'' Gottlieb said. ``What Mike Ovitz has done
is put his company in an adversarial position with a major agency.
I believe it is open season on him.'' Gottlieb said Ovitz had
similarly alienated Creative Artists Agency, another major agency,
by luring away the actor Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz first rose to prominence in Hollywood as the founder of
Creative Artists Agency but quit for a 14-month career as a studio
executive at the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz had previously advised Clancy on film and television deals
but will now take over his representation completely, including
negotiating book contracts. Ovitz is handling Clancy's latest
thriller, ``The Bear and the Dragon.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz began managing Clancy's film and movie deals two years
ago, when he returned to Hollywood to open Artists Management
Group, a talent management firm with a sideline producing its own
films and television shows.
</P>
<P>
   An agent represents a client, collecting generally 10 percent of
his earnings, and helps negotiates contracts. Managers do not
negotiate contracts but oversee a client's career, often collecting
15 percent. In recent years the line between the two have become
increasingly blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy had said previously that he was unhappy that just four of
his many thrillers had been made into films. Ovitz's firm recently
began producing a film based on Clancy's novel ``Rainbow Six,''
which had languished at a studio.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ovitz nor Clancy were available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb said that Ovitz's poaching would soon make him a
``pariah.''
</P>
<P>
   No agent would refer a client to Ovitz in his role as a
Hollywood business manager if he began trying to steal their
business as agents as well, Gottlieb said. ``He has made it clear
that he is neither fish nor fowl, neither agent nor manager nor
lawyer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-LAWYERS-NYT &LR;      08-03 1055
