<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KAN-CREATIONISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: KANSAS, EVOLVING 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Aug. 4:
</P>
<P>
   The earth is billions of years old, and will again be so in
Kansas, despite reckless attempts by the state Board of Education
to deprive its children of modern scientific thinking. Voters put
an end to the madness by expelling conservative board members who
had gutted statewide science standards last year to eliminate
evolution as an explanation of the origin of species and the Big
Bang theory to explain the start of the universe. The balloting was
a triumph for common sense, and a resounding defeat for
creationists whose religious zeal threatened to imperil their
schoolchildren's education.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a 1987 U.S. Supreme Court decision, no state can
compel the teaching of creationism in its public schools. But last
year the Kansas board took the opposite tack _ banishing evolution
from its standards and assessment tests, by a 6-4 vote.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's Kansas Republican primary, three of the six
conservatives responsible for that vote were defeated. The
triumphant moderate Republican nominees and their Democratic
opponents in the general election have pledged to return evolution
and the Big Bang to the standards tests, and will have the votes to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   The primary results send a strong message. Voters in the
nation's heartland will not stand to have their children's
education hijacked by those who would repudiate modern science in
the name of religion. They know full well that in today's world,
their children would be left behind. It is a matter of natural
selection.
</P>
</TEXT>
