A2150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-LOGISTICS-HNS &LR;      08-03 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-LOGISTICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;    EDS: Spectacor is CQ &HT;    Philly sweeps up as Republicans head home
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By DAVID IVANOVICH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It is time for them to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' call for an end to the Clinton/Gore years also
described the scene late Thursday after the balloons and confetti
had rained down and the GOP faithful filing toward the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Their national convention had come to a close and waiting in the
wings were workers ready to move in, mop up and tear down.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,000 workers spent six weeks getting ready for the $63
million Republican bash here at the First Union Center,
transforming the sports and entertainment complex into an
international media center.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they'll have 10 days to clean up the property before the
next major event, an AC/DC rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's Humpty Dumpty being put back together again,''
said Ike Richman, a spokesman for Comcast-Spectacor Ventures, which
owns and operates the center.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the speechifying and politicking ended here late
Thursday night, union crews began removing chairs and scooping up
balloons and confetti, dismantling risers and clearing out
dividers.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the 4,132 delegates and alternates, the 15,000
reporters and and more than 15,000 staff members, volunteers and
interns, convention organizers gutted VIP boxes, erected huge,
white tents for use as makeshift newsrooms and even laid temporary
railroad tracks to bring in antique rail cars.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the army of reporters in attendance, convention
organizers installed 6,000 miles of fiber-optic cable and more than
800 miles of computer cable.
</P>
<P>
   Although summer thunderstorms blew through the Philadelphia area
repeatedly during the convention, convention participants and the
media had to deal with only minor leakage problems and an overly
aggressive air condition system.
</P>
<P>
   The vintage Union Pacific rail cars were scheduled to leave
later this morning, and railroad officials hope to pull up the
track by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days, the massive tents will be gone from the arena
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This'll be like a desert when we're done _ gone,'' said Ed
Reynolds, a member of the Carpenters Union Local 8.
</P>
<P>
   All the plywood that can be salvaged from the site, union
members said, will be donated to Habitat for Humanity, the
home-building charity associated with a president Republicans drove
from office 20 years ago _ Democrat Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
