<SLUG> BC-CVN-TEXANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;    EDS: Pittsburg, Texas is CQ &HT;    Texas GOP delegates cast all their votes, toss all their hats
for Bush
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Already convinced that the sun revolves around
their governor, Texas Republicans rejoiced Thursday evening as they
finally cast their 124 presidential nominating votes for George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Tossing dozens of white cowboy hats into the air on the closing
night of a lovefest officially known as the Republican National
Convention, they didn't care that the carefully scripted moment was
totally devoid of suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most exciting thing. I think I'm at an Aggie football
game,'' said David Kent, a retired Texas A&AMP;M tennis coach and
delegate from Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not only energized Texas (for Bush), we've energized
other states as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming, home state of Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, already
had given the Texas governor enough votes for the GOP nomination on
Wednesday. But Texas completed the roll call Thursday night,
building anticipation before Bush delivered his acceptance speech
to the Republican faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' votes were cast by Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, the delegation
chairman and head of Bush's presidential campaign in Texas, and
delegate Martha Sanchez Metzger of Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   Perry praised Bush for his bipartisan record in Texas and,
countering Democratic attacks, said the Texas governor had made his
state a better place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush set out in Texas to make our schools better, our
streets safer, and our economy stronger, and he did. And he will do
the same for America,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Thorburn, a delegate from New Braunfels, said she was
having a ``grand time'' boosting, she hoped, the political future
of her governor.
</P>
<P>
   Praising Bush for his ``integrity,'' she said, ``It's time
someone went in and washed the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other delegates in Philadelphia, Thorburn wore a red,
white and blue vest. But hers was the only one that had ever been
fished out of the Guadalupe River. After her home was destroyed in
a flood in 1998, the vest and other political memorabilia were
recovered days later about 300 yards downstream.
</P>
<P>
   B.R. ``Skipper'' Wallace, a delegate from Lampasas, said that
nominating Bush was the ``greatest honor that we could have.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the greatest political leader we've ever had. When he
tells you something, you can take it to the bank,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Boerner, a delegate from Pittsburg, in East Texas, said
Bush, despite his limited governmental resume, was well-prepared
for the presidency, partly because of his family ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a front row seat to this all his life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Faith Johnson of DeSoto, an alternate
delegate and one of a handful of blacks in the Texas delegation,
said Bush's greatest strength in the White House would be his
ability to work with all people, ``black, white, purple, green,
what have you.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
