<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BROGNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GET BROGNA FROM PHILLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox have claimed Rico Brogna off waivers, as
general manager Dan Duquette won his battle of wills with the
Phillies and acquired the veteran first baseman for next to
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Brogna, 30, who was born in Turners Falls in Western
Massachusetts and lives in Watertown, Conn., has not played in his
seven major league seasons with a team that finished over .500 or
closer than 18 1/2 games off the pace. He played with the Tigers
and the Mets before he joined the Phillies in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to play for the Red Sox and be in a pennant
race,'' Brogna told reporters in a conference call from Denver
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the offense sputtering, Duquette in recent weeks had
coveted Brogna, a lefthanded hitter who averaged 21 home runs, 33
doubles, and 97 RBIs over his last three full seasons with the
Phillies. After the All-Star break last year, he hit .297 with 13
homers and drove in 58 runs.
</P>
<P>
   But with Brogna headed for free agency in October, Duquette
refused to part with a number of players the Phillies wanted for
him, including infield prospect Donnie Sadler. Sox pitcher Bryce
Florie's name also surfaced in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies fished for top Boston prospects until Monday's
trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted more talent than we were willing to give up,''
Duquette told reporters. ``We took the risk that we would have an
opportunity to claim him by the waiver process.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Phillies settled for the Red Sox picking up the
balance of Brogna's $4.2 million salary, about $1.5 million for the
rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players offered on Monday did not balance with the money
that we had to take back,'' Phillies general manager Ed Wade said.
``We talked to Boston again this morning, but it still wasn't
enough, so we made the deal and recouped his entire salary.''
</P>
<P>
   The question facing Brogna when he reports Friday to Fenway Park
is similar to the quandary that other recent Red Sox arrivals have
confronted: What role will he play?
</P>
<P>
   Joining a team desperately seeking consistency, Brogna will
instantly rank as the only first baseman with lengthy major league
experience and a superb defensive resume. He led National League
first basemen in 1995 with a fielding percentage of .995.
</P>
<P>
   Putting Brogna at first base full time would bump Brian Daubach,
who as a first baseman has hit .284 with seven home runs and 30
RBIs. As a designated hitter, Daubach is hitting .234 with six
homers and 19 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman was also playing often at first base before he
went on the disabled list this week with a deep knee bruise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I fit in exactly,'' Brogna said. ``Maybe I
can be the lefthanded bat in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he would leave it to manager Jimy Williams to fill
out the lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daubach has done a nice job,'' he said. But the general
manager also noted that Brogna is the only established first
baseman on the team and only player to have received votes for a
Gold Glove at the position.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox must also clear a spot Friday on the 25-player roster.
Among the options would be demoting the Frontier League legend
Morgan Burkhart, who was called up to fill Offerman's slot.
</P>
<P>
   Brogna began the season as Philadelphia's starting first
baseman, after his second straight 100-plus-RBI season and third
consecutive year with 20 or more home runs. But when he returned in
June from a two-month absence after his left forearm was fractured
when he was hit by a pitch in Montreal, Brogna had lost his job to
young phenom Pat Burrell.
</P>
<P>
   The misfortune came a decade after former Tigers manager Sparky
Anderson said of Brogna, who was then 19, ``He's the finest young
player I've seen since Johnny Bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have attributed to Brogna's struggle, and his physical
condition was likely a key factor Thursday among the teams that let
him pass on the waiver wire. Under major league rules, every team
with a record inferior to Boston's had a shot at him before the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   After he ended the 1999 season with a 49-game errorless streak,
Brogna last October had arthroscopic surgery on his right shoulder.
In January, he had arthroscopic surgery on his right knee. Then
came the fractured forearm. He also has coped with spinal
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   In 38 games this year with the Phillies, Brogna hit .248 and
drove in 13 runs. But he hit only one home run in 129 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said Brogna, who coaches the Watertown High freshmen
basketball team in the offseason, told him he is eager to make his
Fenway debut. ``This is a homecoming for him,'' Duquette said.
</P>
</TEXT>
