<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-DESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES IN FORD EXPLORER AIM AT PROTECTING OTHER MOTORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (11 p.m. ET EMBARGO) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ The Ford Motor Co. said Thursday that its next
generation of Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles, scheduled to go
on sale in January, would be extensively changed from current
models so as to reduce the danger to other motorists during
collisions and decrease the risk of deadly rollovers.
</P>
<P>
   The sturdy frame that runs the length of the Explorer, the
nation's best-selling sport utility vehicle, will be as low at the
front of the vehicle as that of Ford Taurus sedans, considerably
reducing the risk that the sport utility vehicles will override
cars' bumpers and door sills in crashes, Ford officials said. The
front foot or so of the frame will absorb more energy in a
high-speed crash, reducing the risk of injury in both vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an impact, the vehicles can share the energy of
the event, instead of the Explorer imparting it to the passenger
vehicle,'' said Stephanie Sweeney, Ford's crash safety supervisor
for Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Dale E. Claudepierre, Ford's director of midsize sport utility
vehicles, said the Explorer's design reflected a shift in the
company's approach to safety. ``More so than in the past, we are
concerned about the impact our vehicles have on other vehicles,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said Ford had also improved the safety of Explorer
occupants by adding ceiling-mounted side air bags that protect them
during rollovers, which are responsible for three-fifths of all
deaths in sport utilities. The manufacturer also widened the
distance between the front wheels and between the rear wheels by
two and a half inches and lowered the entire vehicle slightly to
make it more stable and less likely to tip over when it strikes
curbs, guard rails and lower-riding vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ford made a point of saying that the changes would not
compromise the vehicle's off-road performance. Thanks to suspension
changes, Ford will increase ground clearance by an inch, to 9.2
inches, one of the highest clearances for any sport utility.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also improved the Explorer's brakes, to stop the vehicle in
135 feet when fully loaded and traveling 60 miles an hour _ similar
to a car's stopping distance. The current Explorer needs 164 feet
to stop. Sport utilities will not be required to meet brake
standards for cars until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Independent safety experts said Ford appeared to have made
important progress toward improving the safety of motorists who
share the road with Explorers, although they cautioned that they
would like to study the new vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has not lowered the hood of its Explorer, choosing instead
to mount lower in the vehicle the long, stiff ``frame rails'' that
form the vehicle's skeleton. High hoods increase the risk of head
and neck injuries when they strike cars in the side, experts said,
although the low frame rails on the Explorer make it less likely
that the new model will override cars' door sills and project its
hood into cars' passenger compartments during crashes. With a new,
optional third row of seats, the Explorer will also be 200 pounds
heavier, which could also slightly increase damage to other
vehicles in crashes.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerald Donaldson, senior research director at Advocates for
Highway and Auto Safety, a nonprofit group in Washington, said he
was impressed that Ford was addressing rollovers and risks to other
motorists even in the absence of government regulation in either
area. ``I am amazed to see it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Explorer has been the nation's best-selling sport
utility by a wide margin every year since 1991, although its share
of the sport utility market has steadily eroded, to 13.8 percent in
the first seven months of this year, as manufacturers have
introduced many more models. The Mercury Mountaineer, also
redesigned for the new model year, shares a common underbody and
other mechanical underpinnings with the Explorer but has different
sheet metal, grille, headlights, taillights and interior. It had
just 1.4 percent of the market in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under Alex Trotman, Ford's chairman and chief executive until
his retirement at the end of 1998, the company contended that sport
utility vehicles inevitably posed risks to other motorists and that
nothing could be done about this. In an interview in 1997, Trotman
said a collision between a sport utility vehicle and a car was like
smashing two rocks together; the larger rock would be less likely
to suffer damage.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Ford's top management turned over when Trotman
retired, and the company's perspective has changed. Claudepierre
said that by changing the frame rails the company had found a
surprisingly simple and inexpensive solution to the problem of
sport utility damage to other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Frame rails look like two railroad rails, only they curve up and
down somewhat from the front to the back of the vehicle. They are
connected by a series of cross bars, and form the vehicle's
foundation, providing anchor points for the engine, transmission
and suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The foot-long segments of the frame rails in front of the front
cross bar are known as the frame horns. On most models, including
current Explorers, the frame horns curve up slightly to just behind
the bumper or the grille, a design that makes them prone to
overriding cars' bumpers and door sills and spearing passenger
compartments and their occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Claudepierre said Ford had found it could simply turn over the
front segments and have them curve down instead. While this
involved some engineering changes in the front end of the vehicle,
he said, it is fairly easy to manufacture, because factory robots
make roughly the same welds as before but with the front segments
inverted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up nothing by flipping them upside down,'' he said.
``That really puts it at the height of a Taurus.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford installed energy-absorbing, horizontal steel bars last year
below the bumpers of its immense Ford Excursion, which has very
high frame rails. But Sweeney said that on the new Explorer, ``We
don't need the Excursion blocker beam because we lowered the frame
by over two and a half inches _ we didn't just lower the bumper, we
lowered the frame.''
</P>
<P>
   General Motors disclosed last March that it was taking a smaller
step in the same direction, using suspension changes to lower the
frame rails on its new Chevrolet Blazers, GMC Envoys and Oldsmobile
Bravadas by up to two inches as they are introduced this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also made the front ends of the new Explorer's frame rails
less stiff, by drilling holes in them so that the rails will
crumple slightly during high-speed crashes, absorbing some of the
force of an impact. Such changes are possible partly because the
new Explorer will no longer share a common frame with the Ranger
pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the frame horns, the rest of the Explorer' frame
rails are slightly lower than before, partly because of suspension
changes that will also make the ride less bouncy and more carlike.
Ford took the unusual step of mounting the rear suspension through
holes in the frame rails.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the new Explorer accommodates the optional third
row of seats that is mounted low enough to allow ample headroom
even for adults up to 6 feet 6 inches tall. The extra seats could
lure families out of larger, far less fuel-efficient sport
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has also introduced two more fuel-efficient engines, so
that even with the additional weight of the optional row of seats
the vehicle will get an extra mile per gallon on the highway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
