r f BC-BOFA-BROWN-SFCHRON &LR;      08-03 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-BROWN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOFA FIRES KATHLEEN BROWN, PLANS TO SHUT S.F. BANKING UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM ZUCKERMAN  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bank of America has fired Kathleen Brown, one of
California's most visible leaders and a member of one of the
state's most prominent political families, from a high-ranking
executive post at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   BofA announced the departure of the former state treasurer and
1994 Democratic gubernatorial candidate in a statement Thursday,
explaining that Brown had ``decided to leave to pursue other
personal and career interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown lost her job as part of a wide-ranging purge of senior
executive ranks at the bank, one well-placed source said. Last
week, BofA said it would slash up to 10,000 jobs during the next
year, more than 6 percent of its workforce, to cut costs. The
cutbacks are focused on top- and middle-level managers.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who was based in Los Angeles, had been president of
BofA's private banking operations in the West, which provides
banking and money management services to wealthy clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had an incredible run, for which I am most grateful,''
Brown said in an interview. ``Times have changed, and its time for
me to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown declined to comment on the circumstances of her departure.
``I'm not going to go there,''` she responded when asked if the
bank blundered in giving a high-profile female executive her
walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank went through a reorganization, of which I took part''
in designing, Brown continued. ``We didn't need three presidents of
private banking. This is a better structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's departure comes two years after North Carolina's
NationsBank bought San Francisco's BofA and took its name.
Observers said the matter will fuel perceptions that the bank is a
carpetbagger in California.
</P>
<P>
   Brown ``is a highly respected female executive. She represents
the essence of the California team,'' said John Wilson, an
executive recruiter with Korn/Ferry International.
</P>
<P>
   Forcing her out is ``incredibly insensitive. It sends a very bad
message,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BofA also said it is shutting its Northern California
retail banking unit based in San Francisco and moving its functions
into a single statewide organization headquartered in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, San Francisco will no longer be a consumer banking
administrative center for BofA. That represents one of the biggest
losses for the city inside the bank since NationsBank bought
BofAtwo years ago, creating the nation's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of BOFA04 (91833 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  To replace Brown as Western private banking chief, the bank named
Connie Beck, a NationsBank executive in Texas who was brought to
San Francisco last year to run the Northern California retail bank.
Beck will stay in San Francisco and continue as the bank's liaison
with local government and charitable groups.
</P>
<P>
   The bank did hand the old BofA an important prize, naming Liam
McGee, a Los Angeles veteran of the former California bank, to run
the newly formed statewide operation.
</P>
<P>
   Brown joined the old BofA in 1995 as a California private
banking manager, shortly after losing the governor's race to Pete
Wilson. When many other senior female executives from the old BofA
quit the bank following its 1998 takeover, Brown stayed and
publicly defended the new bank's record on hiring and promoting
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has alway been an incredible ambassador for the bank,''
said San Francisco Treasurer Susan Leal.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was rewarded early in 1999 with the job as Western private
banking chief.
</P>
<P>
   On the headquarters issue, BofA officials said despite the
bank's move to close its Northern California retail banking unit,
it still considers the Bay Area a vital market.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, McGee, the new statewide banking chief, said he
plans to appoint several key deputies based here: ``San Francisco
does quite well. There will not be a Southern California
concentration of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   McGee cited his own appointment as evidence that the bank is
willing to give power to executives from the old BofA. ``Most
people wouldn't have thought it possible that I could get this
job,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Executive recruiters said the 45-year-old McGee may have won the
confidence of the bank's leaders because he is an effective manager
who has changed loyalties several times in his career. McGee worked
for Wells Fargo for more than a decade before jumping to Los
Angeles' Security Pacific, which in turn was bought by the old BofA
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to make money,'' said Los Angeles search
specialist Bob Rollo. ``His entire career has been based on getting
results.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA is competing for the city of San Francisco's business with
Wells Fargo and Union Bank of California. Leal wouldn't comment
specifically on how the latest moves BofA's standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say, though, one of the things we will be looking at is
organizational stability,'' Leal said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
