<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-VOICEDIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT OFFERS VOICE DIALING ON CELL PHONES 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Could the phone keypad soon go the way of the
rotary dial?
</P>
<P>
   Some wireless companies seem to think so.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS introduced a service Thursday to allow a subscriber
to make a call by pronouncing each digit in the phone number.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, customers can also set up an address book at their
desktop computers so they can simply call out the name of the
person they want to call.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, several carriers, including Sprint, already offer
specialized handsets that understand spoken commands. But customers
have to train the phones, made by manufacturers like Qualcomm and
Samsung, to understand that particular person's cadence. Customers
with a cheaper phone were out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Sprint executives say its service will work with
any telephone and doesn't need to be trained.
</P>
<P>
   They say the speech-recognition software is more sophisticated
because it runs on powerful computers linked to the Sprint network,
instead of on tiny chips wedged inside a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   The price for the ``voice command'' will range from nothing to
$10 per month, depending upon which pricing plan a customer has.
</P>
<P>
   Other wireless carriers plan to follow suit. Nextel plans to
offer a similar service within six months. And AT&AMP;T Wireless is
testing the technology at its Menlo Park, Calif., research center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be the way everyone dials their phone,'' said
Ronald Croen, chief executive of Nuance Communications in Menlo
Park, which developed the speech recognition software used in the
Sprint service.
</P>
<P>
   Nuance, which traditionally sold its software to companies for
automated answering machine systems, is now duking it out with
rival Speechworks of Boston in the cell phone market.
</P>
<P>
   However, AT&AMP;T spokesman Ken Woo said the current
state-of-the-art technology might still be too primitive to work
reliably, especially while driving down the freeway or on a noisy
street in downtown San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the demonstrations I've seen have been with someone in
a quiet room, wearing a headset and a mike very close to their
mouth,'' Woo said. ``Of course, it works great, but that's not
exactly a real world test.''
</P>
<P>
   Woo hadn't tried the Sprint system. But other voice-recognition
systems routinely make errors even under ideal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, voice-activated phone dialing could just be
the beginning of a vast array of services activated by spoken
commands, from directions to movie listings.
</P>
<P>
   These services are already offered by a couple of dozen existing
``voice portals,'' including TellMe Networks in Mountain View and
BeVocal in Santa Clara, both launched in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   However, to access voice portals, customers usually must dial a
toll-free number and wait for the call to connect. By contrast,
cell phone companies might let customers simply flick on their
phone and say a key word such as ``Weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Group analyst Adam Zawel said independent voice portals
could still survive by offering better features. But if it's even
close, Zawel figures customers will just stick with the default
service offered by the wireless telephone carrier instead of
dialing up a voice portal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's true,'' said Croen of Nuance, which also sells
its software to voice portals like TellMe.
</P>
<P>
   But BeVocal co-founder Amol Joshi said he expects most wireless
companies will team with an existing voice portal instead of
replicating the service themselves. He said BeVocal is in talks
with several of the top six largest wireless carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clearly have the brand and the infrastructure, but they
lack the applications (or software),'' Joshi said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint spokesman Bob Kelley confirmed the company plans to work
with outside partners. ``I don't think we are building our own
portal,'' he said. Kelley said the company probably wouldn't expand
into the area until next year.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T appears to be moving in this direction, having invested $60
million in TellMe three months ago. But Joshi said AT&AMP;T could still
pick a different partner for its voice portal, since the investment
didn't come from its wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless companies could make potential money in several ways,
such as selling advertising, receiving money from portals, charging
customers for the time they spend using the service or even taking
a cut of any purchases people make while shopping on their phone.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless company executives also say voice portals will be a
boon for customers, since it can be awkward to drive while fumbling
around a cell phone keypad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
