<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2162 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-COPA-NETSAFETY-SFCHRO     08-03 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPA-NETSAFETY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GROUP'S HEARING EXPLORES INTERNET SAFETY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARRIE KIRBY &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; C. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Installing software that blocks out
objectionable Web sites may not be the best way to protect children
who use the Internet, a disparate group of experts told a
congressional commission Thursday in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   In the third of a series of hearings to consider different
strategies for protecting kids online, dot-com executives,
librarians, children's advocates and even pornographers gathered at
San Jose State University to testify before the Commission on
Online Child Protection.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the commission has heard from makers of filtering
software such as Net Nanny and from people who want to separate
pornography from the rest of the Internet by giving such sites
their own domain name endings _ perhaps .xxx instead of .com.
</P>
<P>
   This time, witnesses suggested other technological solutions _
such as using special portals just for kids, like Yahoo's
Yahooligans. They also put forward nontechnical answers such as
setting and enforcing rules that children must follow when using
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of parents conducted by FamilyPC magazine suggests that
filtering software is not considered relevant by many parents.
Fewer than half of parents use filtering software or a filtered
Internet service provider, according to the survey, presented to
the commission yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   And while the software focuses on blocking out ``bad'' Web
sites, parents told the magazine their top concern is Internet
privacy, not pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Filtering software has been controversial because some people
believe it violates Web-page-makers' freedom of speech. But many of
yesterday's witnesses focused on the software's effect on children
who use it.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on filtering software such as Net Nanny or Cyber Patrol
to keep kids safe online can be shortsighted, said Nancy Willard,
director of a University of Oregon group called Responsible
Netizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping kids fenced in does not teach them to take care of
themselves in the real world,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents must gradually teach their children to deal with online
dangers and unpleasantness, which ranges from pornography and child
predators to false information and swindles, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incumbent upon us to give them the education to avoid
becoming a generation of victims,'' said Judith Krug, director of
the American Libraries Association's Office for Intellectual
Freedom, which opposes using filtering in public libraries.
</P>
<P>
   But some commissioners questioned whether just talking to
children about online dangers is enough. Former Sen. Gary Hart
confidante Donna Rice Hughes, who runs the Protectkids.com, said
education should be used alongside other precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preferred solution has always been a comprehensive solution
_ shared responsibility between the public, the technology
community and law enforcement,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of COPA04 (90084 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Danni Ashe, chief executive officer of a pornography site called
Danni's Hard Drive, said children's safety advocates and porn
merchants have some of the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Responsible'' adult sites do their best to keep kids out by
charging a fee payable only by credit card, Ashe said.
</P>
<P>
   But when porn sites' images are copied by viewers and posted for
free elsewhere on the Internet, kids can see them without a credit
card. ``We need stronger copyright laws and more cooperation from
ISPs and law enforcement agencies'' to prevent theft, Ashe said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the commission as part of the Child Online
Protection Act, a 1998 law that banned Web sites from making
``harmful'' material available to children.
</P>
<P>
   The law was quickly blocked in court after being challenged by
the American Civil Liberties Union as a violation of the First
Amendment and has never been enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Although the future of the Act or other legislation on the
subject is uncertain, the commission is going ahead with its
mandate to study the different methods of protecting kids from
online porn.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, the commission will hear how emerging technologies
such as broadband Internet access may affect children's exposure to
harmful material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission may not recommend new legislation'' in its
report to Congress, due November 30, said George Vradenburg III,
America Online's representative on the commission. ``But hopefully
it will set an agenda for the whole Internet community.''
</P>
<P>
   Other commission members include executives from Yahoo and
Disney's Go.com, as well as representatives from the Federal Trade
Commission and the U.S. Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carrie Kirby at ckirby(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of COPA04 (90084 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
