<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-BUSH-SPEECH-BOS &LR;      08-03 1604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-SPEECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BELITTLES DEMOCRATS AS HE ACCEPTS NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Basking in the adoration of Republicans who
believe he is destined to recapture the White House, Texas Governor
George W. Bush triumphantly accepted his party's nomination
Thursday night, declaring that the Democratic administration that
ousted his father from the White House eight years ago has had ``no
great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, vowed to ``seize this moment of American
promise'' and ``extend the promise of prosperity to every forgotten
corner of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the speech's many promises, occasional platitudes and even
a bit a even bit of Robert Frost poetry, the governor did not shy
away from the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``For eight years, the Clinton-Gore administration has coasted
through prosperity,'' Bush said in remarks prepared for delivery.
The governor laid out a litany of lapses, accusing the
administration of having ``squandered'' world leadership, overseen
a ``steady erosion of American power'' and leaving millions of
children ``trapped in schools where violence is common and learning
is rare.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration had its chance,'' Bush said, in what was
intended as the evening's signature statement. ``They have not led.
We will.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most important political speech of Bush's life, aimed
beyond the beribboned convention hall to a nationwide television
audience of millions, including many undecided voters who may have
heard little beyond some 30-second ``sound bites'' from the
governor until his acceptance oration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 54, who until six years ago had never held elected office,
began writing the remarks months ago, and continued to revise them
as late as Thursday. But the themes echoed his campaign stump
speeches: Using prosperity for a greater purpose, restoring honor
to Washington, broadening the Republican platform to include voters
across the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now the party of ideas and innovation...The party of
idealism and inclusion...The party of a simple and powerful hope,''
Bush said. ``My fellow citizens, we can begin again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush then sought to directly answer Gore's charge that Bush's
plans for large tax cuts and the partial privatization of Social
Security as ``risky schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the sum of his message,'' Bush said. ``If my opponent
had been there at the moon launch, it would have been a `risky
rocket scheme.' If he'd been there when Edison was testing the
light bulb, it would have been a `risky anti-candle scheme.' ''
Then, alluding to Gore's assertion that he helped invent the
Internet, Bush said mockingly, ``If he'd been there when the
Internet was invented...well, I understand he was actually there
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six months after Bush sewed up the nomination, and after
days of choreographed convention speeches, the evening injected
some drama into the presidential campaign by underscoring how much
is at stake between now and election day.
</P>
<P>
   A subplot was seen in every banner: this was also singular
moment for the Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   In a box seat sat the nominee's father, former President Bush,
himself the son of a US senator. Ousted from office by the
Clinton-Gore victory in 1992, former President Bush has largely
refrained from dwelling on his defeat but this week he dutifully
made the rounds of television interviews to promote his son.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention floor stood another Bush son, Jeb, the
governor of Florida and the man whom some family friends initially
believed was most likely to seek the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   And on the stage was the graduate of Sam Houston Elementary
School in Midland, Texas _ as well as the elite institutions of
Andover, Yale and Harvard _ who presented himself as the outsider,
a man who ``may lack the polish of Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush portrayed his lack of Washington experience as a virtue.
``I don't have enemies to fight,'' Bush said. ``And I have no stake
in the bitter arguments of the last few years. I want to change the
tone of Washington to one of civility and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, said brother Jeb Bush, the Texas governor
``looks like a president to me now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago I wouldn't have told you this,'' Jeb Bush said in
an interview on Good Morning America. ``In all honesty, I thought
he had the capacity to be a president, but today when I see him,
it's different. ... He's got the right stuff, and I'm incredibly
proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's other brother, Marvin, gave a similar
assessment. Saying he would not have imagined this of his older
brother two decades ago, Marvin Bush said the Texas governor had
``channeled his energy into positive things, and as a result of
that, he's been a great achiever ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have suggested that being the son of George Bush is an
easy thing. It's not. So he is a survivor,'' Marvin Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, candidates look for a post-convention bounce after the
acceptance speech, but Bush headed into the evening enjoying a
sizable jump in the polls from his choice of Dick Cheney as vice
president and the party's seamless convention. In a poll taken
before Bush spoke, the Texas governor led Al Gore by 48 percent to
34 percent, according to the ``Battleground'' survey sponsored by
the Internet company, Voter.com. The survery has a reported margin
of error of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for even more bounce in the polls, Bush treaded carefully
as he approached the political battles of the fall. Twelve years
ago, his father erased a 17-point deficit in the against Michael
Dukakis with an acceptance speech promise of a ``kinder, gentler
America,'' a theme the Texas governor echoed in tone in his speech.
But there were major differences: The elder Bush told voters that
the best follow-up to eight years of Reaganism were a continuation
of Republicanism. Bush's son, known universally as ``W,''
implicitly acknowledged the prosperity during eight years of
Clintonism, but said a different party should occupy the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bush made no surprising policy declaration as his
father did with the 1988 vow of ``Read My Lips, No New Taxes.'' The
promise helped elect the elder Bush but the breaking of that vow
played a major role in his defeat by the Clinton-Gore team in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   A week of carefully planned festivities, filled with mostly
sunny speeches and rousing musical appearances, built toward Bush's
moment. The Bush campaign oversaw every aspect of the convention,
ordering up themes of diversity and unity while playing down
dissent. Many issues that divide Republicans went unmentioned:
Colin Powell didn't mention his support of abortion rights, nor did
Senator John McCain's press his case for overhaul of the campaign
finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did bring up the issue of abortion, which has long divided
his party, but gingerly. Instead of vowing to work for passage of a
constitutional amendment to ban abortions, as called for in the
newly adopted GOP platform, Bush laid out a milder-sounding marker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know good people disagree on this issue, but surely we can
agree on ways to value life by promoting adoption and parental
notification, and when Congress sends me a bill against
partial-birth abortion, I will sign it into law,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush devoted a portion of the speech to concrete policies,
emphasizing the five ideas he routinely features on the campaign
trail: Social Security, education reform, tax-cutting, building the
military and expanding Medicare to include prescription drugs. He
honed in on a specific program, saying: ``Now is the time to make
Head Start an early learning program, teach all of our children to
read, and renew the promise of America's public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea was not new; Bush has long said he hopes to move the
Head Start program into the Department of Education. But Head Start
has been in the news ever since Bush's announced his running mate
pick of Dick Cheney, who voted against funding for Head Start while
a member of the US House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not follow the example set by Cheney on Wednesday
night, when when the former defense secretary elicited thunderous
applause with by borrowing an attack first used by Gore in 1992
against Bush's father. ``It's time for them to go!'' Cheney said of
Clinton-Gore, just as Gore had said of Bush-Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush instead appeared as a gentler warrior, preaching harmony,
civility and respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will seize this moment of American promise. We will use
these good times for great goals,'' Bush said. ``We will confront
the hard issues _ threats to our national security, threats to our
health and retirement security _ before the challenges of our time
become crises for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the wave of publicity generated by his formal
nomination, Bush plans to embark Friday on a three-day train trip
through swing states, starting in Pittsburgh and ending on Sunday
night in Missouri after a detour through Michigan. He is then
expected to spend several days at home in Austin, before heading to
the West Coast next week to campaign with McCain, his former rival
who during the convention emerged as an outspoken supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting Robert Frost, and indirectly raising the issue of
President Clinton's conduct in the Oval Office, Bush said that the
highest hope of the Founding Fathers was ``to occupy the land with
character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And that, 13 generations later, is still our goal,'' Bush
said, ``to occupy the land with character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2166 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-1S     08-03 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-1STLD-WRITETH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LAUNCHES CAMPAIGN WITH APPEAL TO SWING VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   (EDS: New material throughout based on speech text)
 &HT;    By STEWART M. POWELL   
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
PHILADELPHIA _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush accepted the Republican
nomination for president Thursday night by vowing to extend the
``promise of prosperity to every forgotten corner'' of America as
he sought the support of independent voters and crossover Democrats
in his quest to become the first son to follow a father to the
White House since 1824. &QC; 
Bush, an affable, pragmatic Republican, told cheering,
placard-waving delegates and guests packed into the 22,000-seat
convention center that the nation ``can begin again'' led by a
party of ``idealism and inclusion.'' The 54-year-old son of former
President George Bush vowed to ``seize this moment of American
promise'' and ``use these good times for great goals.''
<P>
   Bush, accusing the Clinton-Gore administration of having
``coasted through prosperity'' and ``squandered'' opportunities,
ignited partisan loyalists with the repeated refrain: ``This
administration had its moment. They had their chance. They have not
led. We will.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's acceptance speech was the dramatic climax of the GOP's
four-day convention that was characterized by soft-pedaling of such
divisive social issues as abortion and gay rights. The roster of
convention speakers included a large number of minority-group
members, a selection that contrasted sharply with the
overwhelmingly white ethnic composition of the delegates. It was
all part of Bush's efforts to redefine his party as mainstream with
no radical tinges.
</P>
<P>
   With his parents proudly watching from the audience, Bush
broadly sketched plans to overhaul public schools, strengthen
Social Security and add prescription drug benefits to Medicare _
themes that are more often invoked by Democratic candidates than
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He vowed to ``confront the hard issues'' such as threats from
abroad and problems besetting Americans' health and retirement
systems at home before ``the challenges of our time become crises
for our children.'' Bush added: ``Prosperity can be a tool in our
hands _ used to build and better our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush declared: ``Grant me a mandate and I will use it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a hallmark address that he worked on for weeks, Bush
emphasized that his brand of ``compassionate conservatism'' would
reach out to disadvantaged Americans who feel left behind amid the
longest economic boom in American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are their country too,'' Bush told delegates, adding: ``We
will extend the promise of prosperity to every forgotten corner of
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a graduate of Yale and Harvard Business School who ran oil
companies, the Texas Rangers baseball team and advised his father
during the Bush presidency, cast himself as a rough-hewn,
plain-spoken political outsider ready to take on the entrenched and
unpopular powerbrokers in the nation's capital. Bush said his life
in the big sky country of Midland, Texas, had left him with ``more
than an accent'' _ it had given him ``an outlook'' of can-do
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Bush contended that while he ``may lack the polish of
Washington'' he wasn't burdened by ``a lot of things that come with
Washington experience'' such as ``enemies to fight'' or a ``stake
in the bitter arguments of the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush lamented the lost ``promise'' of President Clinton, a
fellow Baby Boomer blessed with ```so many talents, so much charm,
such great skill'' _ all harnessed for ``no great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized Vice President Al Gore more directly, deriding
his rival's repeated criticism of GOP policy proposals as ``risky
schemes.'' Bush said Gore is ``always seeing the tunnel at the end
of the light'' and he played off the Great Depression phrase of
President Franklin D. Roosevelt to sum up Gore's approach as ``the
only thing he has to offer is fear itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush implicitly contrasted himself with Gore's alleged reliance
on polls, saying that he ``did not need to take your pulse before I
know my own mind,'' adding: ``I do not reinvent myself at every
turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, linking Gore closely with Clinton, said that after the
Clinton-Gore administration's failures ``they come asking for
another chance, another shot.'' Bush countered: ``This is not a
time for third chances. It is a time for new beginnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush underscored his bipartisan appeal to swing voters by paying
homage to Republican and Democratic presidents alike, including
Abraham Lincoln, Theodore Roosevelt, Harry Truman and Ronald
Reagan. He spoke sadly of Clinton, rather than critically.
</P>
<P>
   Bush warned his allies that what lies ahead before election day
on Nov. 7 will be ``a tough race, down to the wire.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke amid fresh evidence that the GOP was winning support
for its nominee by devoting the convention to showcasing diversity
and avoiding messy ideological squabbles. The latest bipartisan
Voter.com-Battleground public opinion survey, conducted by
Democratic pollster Celinda Lake and GOP pollster Ed Goeas, showed
that the four-day GOP convention had given the Bush-Cheney ticket a
sizable 14-percentage point edge over a Gore-led ticket, with Bush
leading Gore, 48 percent to 34 percent. &QC; 
The survey also showed Bush seizing an 18 percentage point edge
over Gore among independents and a 6 percentage point edge among
women _ both constituencies won by the Clinton-Gore ticket in the
last two presidential elections to enable the elected Democrats to
hold the White House for two successive terms for the first time
since 1936. &QC; 
Gore hopes to begin a comeback with his scheduled announcement on
Tuesday of his Democratic running mate. In 11 of the 12
presidential elections since 1952, the candidate who led in the
polls on Labor Day won the election. Only Ronald Reagan came from
behind in 1980 to beat President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney planned to storm out of the GOP gathering on
Friday for a three-day campaign trip by train through Midwest swing
states including Ohio and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans closed out their sixth convention in Philadelphia
since 1856 with a new GOP anthem, entitled ``We the People,'' a
blend of rock , blues and country written and released by country
singer Billy Ray Cyrus. The convention came to an end with 150,000
red, white and blue balloons showering down upon the delegates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush, grandson of the late Sen. Prescott Bush, R-Conn., has been
governor of the nation's third most populous state for
five-and-a-half years _ making the Republican standard bearer the
least experienced politician to lead the party since former World
War II allied commander Dwight D. Eisenhower sought the presidency
in 1952. &QC; 
Bush's running mate has been away from the political fray since
1989, serving as the Bush administration's defense secretary and
later as chief executive of Halliburton Corp., a worldwide energy
services firm based in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seeks to become the first presidential son to capture the
presidency since John Quincy Adams followed his father, John Adams,
to the White House 24 years after his father's term ended. Bush
hopes to win back the White House from which his father was ousted
by then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton and then-Sen. Al Gore, D-Tenn.,
in 1992. Bush gave the next generation of the Bush clan a boost by
awarding his 24-year-old nephew, George P. Bush, son of Florida
Gov. Jeb Bush, the chance to address the GOP convention in both
English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The election is the first contest since World War II in which
neither candidate served in a fateful conflict that shaped the
modern world.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Bush lightly brushed off any suggestion that
his address would be the most important of his life, quipping:
``The most important speech was when I asked my wife to marry me _
and that went okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Before exercising on a stationary bicycle and reviewing his
speech, Bush stopped by Philadelphia's Hahnemann University
Hospital to visit former President Gerald Ford, who was admitted on
Wednesday following two minor strokes. Bush spent 20 minutes with
the 87-year-old former president, who told Bush, ``I'll be
campaigning for you in a couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Ford was expected to make a full recovery. &QC; 
Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway fired a salvo at Bush even before
the GOP candidate had mounted the podium to deliver his address. &QC; 
``Given the high praise his father received in 1992, George junior
has a lot to live up to tonight,'' said Hattaway. ``Tonight,
America will see if there is any substance behind the smirk.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewarthearstdc.com ) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
