<HEADLINE>
VERIZON TO CREDIT BAY STATE CUSTOMERS WITH $42 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Regulators Thursday ordered Verizon Communications to
give its Massachusetts customers nearly $42 million in credits and
rate cuts even though the service problems that prompted the
reductions were corrected more than four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say the controversial decision prompted heated
discussions among the five commissioners of the state Department of
Telecommunications and Energy. Four of the commissioners ultimately
voted in favor of the ruling, while the commission chairman, James
Connelly, refused to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling means Verizon will have to issue a one-time credit
sometime this year of about $5 per line and make a similar-size
reduction in its rate structure next year. But the philosophical
underpinnings of the decision were more controversial than the
actual dollar amounts.
</P>
<P>
   The price-cap formula state regulators use to set Verizon's
rates in Massachusetts is a complex equation involving
productivity, inflation, and service quality. In 1995 and 1996, the
first two years of the price-cap system, Verizon, formerly Bell
Atlantic, failed to meet service quality standards and saw its
rates reduced as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon has met the service standards every year since, but
because of the way the rate-setting formula is calculated the
earlier service problems continue to have a carryover effect.
According to Thursday's decision, the carryover effect is $20.87
million this year and next year.
</P>
<P>
   In its November rate filing, Verizon did not seek to recover
some $55 million in rate reductions in 1997, 1998, and 1999 that
were also tied to the service problems from previous years. But it
did withhold $20.87 million in rate reductions that would have been
required this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Telecommunications and Energy Thursday agreed
with Verizon's analysis but said it wasn't going to start tampering
with the formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree with Verizon that the current operation of the
price-cap formula leads to the result described,'' said the ruling.
Despite that, however, the agency said it was not about to change
the rules in the middle of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make a change to these pricing rules would be inconsistent
with what we've done in the past,'' said Michael Isenberg, director
of the DTE's telecommunications division.
</P>
<P>
   The current rate-setting system is scheduled to expire at the
end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed the DTE did not approve our request to
eliminate ongoing penalities for service levels in 1994 and 1995
that we've long since improved,'' said Verizon spokesman John
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   George Dean, chief of Attorney General Thomas Reilly's regulated
industries division, applauded the ruling, saying the formula used
to set Verizon's rates is working as it was intended. ``They're
just trying to erase their past problems,'' Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, the attorney general's office was
unsuccessful. In its November rate filing, Verizon said it was
going to accomplish part of this year's rate reductions by
eliminating the $1.46-a-month touch-tone charge for business lines.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's office argued it was unfair to eliminate the business
charge entirely while continuing to charge residential customers 46
cents a month for touch-tone service. ``It's unfair to give it away
to one group and not another,'' Dean said.
</P>
<P>
   But the DTE allowed Verizon to proceed with its rate
adjustments, noting business and residential rates often differ in
many respects.
</P>
<P>
   A DTE spokesman Thursday declined comment on why chairman
Connelly refused to sign the ruling. Sources said Connelly
supported Verizon's position but decided not to write a dissent or
even sign the order given the majority against him. Before being
appointed chairman, Connelly was the consumer representative on the
commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
