s f BC-SENIORS-COLUMN-$ADV06     08-03 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME GUIDES TO A REDEFINED RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 6) 
 By FRED BROCK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Books aimed at the growing, and increasingly affluent, senior
market are steadily filling bookstore shelves around the country.
Here is a sampling of some recent additions, which touch on
subjects from retirement to the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT MATTERS _ Retiring means more than just quitting
work. It is one of life's major transitions that can carry
heavy-duty emotional and psychological issues, involving nothing
less than a redefinition of the self. ``Breaking the Watch: The
Meaning of Retirement in America,'' by Joel S. Savishinsky (Cornell
University Press, $26), and ``Taking Retirement: A Beginner's
Diary,'' by Carl H. Klaus (Beacon Press, $16), both grapple with
the meaning and ramifications of this transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking the Watch,'' which will be available in October,
takes a broader look at retirement by examining the lives of 26
people _ 13 men and 13 women from various backgrounds and
professions _ in an upstate New York town. ``Taking Retirement'' is
the diary of one man's efforts to come to terms with his first year
of full retirement. But despite this difference in focus, both
books go right to the main issues, practical and otherwise, that we
all are facing or will face one day.
</P>
<P>
   Savishinsky, a professor of social sciences at Ithaca College,
does an admirable job of interviewing his 26 retirees on a wide
range of topics. Partly, he succeeds because he lets his subjects
have their say. The book is divided into six major chapters and a
final, smaller one, ``Conclusions: Lesson and Cautions.''
</P>
<P>
   One nit: The author does not use the real names of the town,
which he calls ``Shelby,'' or the people he interviews. He writes
that this is to protect their privacy. Well, maybe, but there are
plenty of nonfiction books about considerably more controversial
subjects that don't need that cover.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's the voices of the retirees that power the book:
</P>
<P>
   _``Retirement is like a progressive illness _ and a spiritual
experience. There's a loss of efficacy, but the moral side grows.''
</P>
<P>
   _``In retirement, it's not the watches that get broken, it's the
promises. No one who talked to me about a job ever came through. I
came to feel you can't rely on anyone, and I'd never felt that way
before.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I call it `drift time.' It's not being in a fixed frame of
work or routine. You bicycle instead of drive through life, letting
each day unfold, taking you wherever it does.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My children are so uptight. Where did I go wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Taking Retirement,'' Klaus, 68, a former college professor
and the founder of the nonfiction writing program at the University
of Iowa, uses his diary to take us inside his struggle to come to
terms with a new life after 42 years of teaching. His musings
chronicle the highs and lows as he copes with worries about money
and health and with fears that he has been cast adrift, without the
moorings of work. In the end, it is partly the work he continues to
do _ his writing _ that lets him find balance in his new life.
</P>
<P>
   BITS AND BYTES _ For seniors who are anxious about jumping into
the world of computers and the Internet, two books can be a big
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer Friendly,'' by Raymond Steinbacher, is a guide for
those who are really beginners. Clearly written and easy to follow,
it begins with the assumption that the reader knows nothing about
computers. The book is available only from the publisher, Green
Tree Press in Erie, Pa., (800-834-3888). The price is $15.95,
including shipping.
</P>
<P>
   `` Modem's Internet Guide for Seniors,'' by Richard Sherman
(Sybex, $19.99), is an excellent map for navigating the Internet.
Its lists of Web sites are especially valuable. However, the book's
constant efforts at cuteness can get a little tiring.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL SECURITY _ If you're confused by the political discourse
over the future of Social Security, two books from the University
of Chicago Press may help sort out the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security: The Phony Crisis,'' by Dean Baker and Mark
Weisbrot ($22), argues that because of overly conservative economic
projections, Social Security is not in danger and doesn't need to
be ``saved'' by putting some of its funds into individual stock
market accounts, as George W. Bush, the Republican presidential
candidate, and others advocate. This is a very readable book by two
economists that is actually influencing the political debate..
</P>
<P>
   ``Making Sense of Social Security Reform,'' by Daniel Shaviro
($25), is due out next month and does a good job of explaining the
nuts and bolts of Social Security. In the end, Shaviro, a law
professor, comes down in favor of what he calls ``progressive
privatization,'' in which some money would be transferred at
retirement from the individual accounts of people who have done
well with them to those who have not. I wouldn't want to bet on
that idea getting past conservative Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
