<HEADLINE>
SRI LINKA CONSIDERS NEW CONSTITUTION TO BENEFIT TAMIL MINORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENNAI, India _ After years of procrastination, Sri Lanka's
governing coalition proposed Thursday in Parliament that a new
constitution be adopted to give greater political autonomy to the
minority Tamil population in an attempt to help end the
17-year-long war waged by separatist rebels for a Tamil homeland.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure faces a highly uncertain fate. Despite months of
talks aimed at building bipartisan support for the new
constitution, the main opposition organization, the United National
Party, decided recently to vote against it.
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration that was typical of Sri Lanka's rancorous
highly partisan politics _ especially with national elections
scheduled for the fall _opposition members of Parliament booed
President Chandrika Kumaratunga on Thursday as she introduced the
document and then tore the pages of the proposed constitution to
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaratunga is quite unlikely to win passage of the measure in
the House without some defections from the United National Party,
as well as support from small Tamil parties. The government needs a
two-thirds vote to pass the constitution, but has only a narrow
majority in the House. If adopted by Parliament, the measure would
then face a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This endeavor, in the final count, would be the only
alternative to violence and murder in resolving the Tamil question
and for peace in our land,'' the presidential secretariat said in a
statement. It has been the lack of a clear-cut two-thirds majority
that had discouraged Kumaratunga from introducing the constitution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The six-year term of this Parliament ends on Aug. 24, and she
has apparently decided to gamble that she can cobble together
enough votes or go to the voters seeking a bigger parliamentary
majority that would help have the constitution passed later.
</P>
<P>
   The years of delay in introducing the constitution have deeply
disappointed Tamil voters, who joined with voters from the majority
Sinhalese population to support Kumaratunga in large numbers in
1994, when she was elected president on a peace platform.
</P>
<P>
   Early in her term, Justice Minister G.L. Peiris and a Tamil
constitutional scholar, Neelan Tiruchelvam, went to work to draft a
constitution to gave Tamils more power. But for years it languished
as the governing People's Alliance and the United National, both
dominated by the mostly-Buddhist Sinhalese majority, bickered.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Tiruchelvam, the leading moderate Tamil
parliamentarian, was assassinated by a suicide bomber widely
believed to have been a member of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, the separatist group that has been fighting for 17 years for
a separate state in the north and east, where Tamils, mostly
Hindus, are in the majority. More than 60,000 people have died in
the war.
</P>
<P>
   The idealistic hopes that many moderate Sri Lankans had for the
constitutional proposal have been worn down in the years of
waiting. The measure was greeted Thursday with demonstrations that
show the deep ethnic divisions between the Tamils and the
Sinhalese.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand people demonstrated against the proposed
constitution Thursday in Colombo, among them influential members of
the Buddhist clergy and hard-line Sinhala groups who say the
measure gives the Tamils too much power and could lead to a
division of the country. The banned Tiger rebels were, of course,
not in evidence, although heavy security was evident on the
streets. They have already declared their opposition to the new
constitution on the ground that nothing short of an independent
nation will satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Kumaratunga said, the draft constitution will be
sent to the Tigers. ``Stop the war and come for talks,'' she said
in her speech, addressing the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
