<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR A RARE DOUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After winning the Pennzoil Indiana Sprint Week, Jay Drake has
put himself in position to pull off a rare feat in United States
Auto Club competition.
</P>
<P>
   Drake, the former Val Verde, Calif., resident and Buena
(Ventura, Calif.) High graduate who makes his home in Indianapolis,
has a chance to win the USAC Sprint and Midget car championships.
He is second in both series.
</P>
<P>
   If he can earn both titles, he would be the first to do it since
Tony Stewart _ who also won the Silver Bullet Series title _ in
1995. The only other USAC driver to win the Sprint and Midget
titles in the same year was Rich Vogler in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were five (Sprint) races I didn't even go to,'' the
30-year-old Drake said. ``To be second in points is pretty
impressive. I wasn't expecting to run for either points titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake is coming off a week in which he won four of seven races
over 11 days in the Indiana Sprint Week. He also earned nearly
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty tough deal,'' Drake said. ``There were 50 cars
in each race and we won four of them. We actually should have won
five.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last three races of Indiana Sprint Week, Drake won twice.
His first win came July 28 in the Tony Hulman Classic at Terre
Haute Action Track, where he led all but two laps of the 30-lap
feature.
</P>
<P>
   In the next race the following day, Drake took the lead on lap
seven at Lincoln Park Speedway in Putnamville and won the 30-lap
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Drake won the pole but finished sixth in the final race of
Sprint Week on Sunday at Tri-State Speedway in Haubstadt.
</P>
<P>
   Cory Kruseman of Ventura won the final race of Indiana Sprint
Week.
</P>
<P>
   Drake finished with a 76-point lead over his nearest competitor,
Tony Elliott, who is leading the Sprint Car season standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ran the dirt races at the start of the season,'' Drake
said. ``I didn't run any of the pavement. Now I've been able to run
(Elliott) down lately. I just wish I'd have run those other
races.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake trails Elliott by 88 points in the Sprint Car standings.
The Midget Car standings are a little tighter, with Drake trailing
Kasey Kahne by 73 points.
</P>
<P>
   The USAC Sprint Car Series makes its next stops at Hartford,
Mich., on Aug. 11 and at Salem, Ind., on Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rookies rule on NASCAR Busch Series: A week after NASCAR
Busch Series rookie Ron Hornaday Jr. won his first race of the
season, fellow first-year driver Kevin Harvick followed with a
first-place finish Saturday night in the CarQuest 250 at Gateway
International Raceway in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   `'It's a feeling you don't get to feel very often,'' the
Bakersfield resident said of winning his first Busch Series race.
Just the memories of that night I will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that Harvick, a former NASCAR Winston West champ
and Truck Series driver, should follow Hornaday to victory lane. It
seems as though Harvick has been following in Hornaday's tire
tracks for the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday is also a Winston West champ and the king of the
Craftsman Trucks, with a series-best 25 wins and two championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you eager after he gets his first win,'' Harvick said
after Hornaday's win. ``I really enjoy racing against Ron. It makes
it nice to have someone else out there who's going through the same
thing as you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Harvick had to follow Hornaday to victory lane,
Harvick is leading the way in the Busch rookie and season
standings. He has an 11-point lead in the rookie race and is fourth
in the season standings. Hornaday is fifth in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone expected us to win,'' said Harvick, who drives the AC
Delco Chevrolet owned by Richard Childress. ``This is a huge
pressure off my back.''
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Busch Series schedule is the Kroger 200 at
Indianapolis Raceway Park today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
