<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-R-LAWN-BOWLING-2TAKES     08-03 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LAWN-BOWLING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE OUTFITS, BLACK BALLS AND THAT PERFECTLY GREEN GRASS
</HEADLINE>
  (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT21 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRIS BALLARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All that stood between me and victory was 90 feet of
immaculate green grass. At the far end, a cluster of black balls
huddled around my target: the jack, a white ball the size and shape
of a cue ball. To win, I had to curve my ball through the globes
and nudge the jack. Misjudge it by more than an inch and I'd lose.
I might as well have been trying to sink a putt from the rough with
a broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   But then I never thought lawn bowling was going to be easy, as I
was finding out on a warm Sunday in Central Park. This sport of
kings and commoners _ an ancient relative of boccie played by Henry
VIII and William Shakespeare _ was not only enjoyable but also
quite challenging.
</P>
<P>
   My first memories of lawn bowling stem from two pre-teen years I
spent in England, where the sport is almost as popular as golf is
in America. Ever since then I've harbored a grainy home-movie image
of the game in the recesses of my brain. I recall stately older men
and women dressed in all-white outfits and wide-brimmed hats. I
remember much murmuring, appraising and bending. And I remember
thinking they were using a perfectly good soccer pitch for what
appeared to be slow-motion bowling.
</P>
<P>
   Though lawn bowling has but a minuscule following in the United
States _ there are only 160 greens in the country, according to the
American Lawn Bowls Association _ the sport has been popular in
England since the 12th century and still draws celebrities (Diana,
Princess of Wales, was a frequent bowler) and big crowds across the
United Kingdom and in Australia and New Zealand. Initially popular
in the colonies, lawn bowling didn't fare well in the United States
after the Revolution, perhaps because it was seen as a relic of
British rule.
</P>
<P>
   Here in New York the first green was built in 1664 on the parade
grounds of Fort Amsterdam, and the green at what is now Battery
Park was erected 60 years later. It was not until 1926 that bowling
came to Central Park, when the New York Lawn Bowling Club was
formed and the greens were built near the West 69th Street entrance
to the park. Recently, the club has received competition from the
Metropolitan Bowling Club, headed by a former New York Lawn Bowling
Club president, Richard Keoseian, a lively man who once tried to
arrange a celebrity lawn bowling tournament overseen by Robin
Leach, host of ``Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd never played the game while living in England, but I was
always a bit curious. So when I heard that people lawn-bowled right
here in Manhattan, in Central Park no less, I decided to have a go.
If nothing else, the game had to be more fun than cricket, for me a
soporific British sport that had tormented me as a youth. I called,
and arranged for a lesson the next Sunday with Tony Reynal,
president of the New York Lawn Bowling Club. (The Metropolitan Club
had yet to start its season.)
</P>
<P>
   I arrived at the greens, north of the Sheep Meadow in Central
Park, just after noon. Situated on a slight rise, the matching
120-foot-by-120-foot swathes of grass (one is used by a croquet
club) are enclosed by a five-foot-tall green fence and covered with
the type of pristine, short-cut grass one would find on a putting
green in Augusta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the greens were an oasis of inactivity amid the
Frisbee fiends, sunbathers and soccer players who cluttered the
park. As I approached, I saw a solitary figure rolling balls down
the grass, placing each within a foot of the jack. It was Reynal,
looking ready for breakfast at Wimbledon in white shorts, a
white-collared shirt, white socks, and white tennis shoes. The only
sign that I was dealing with a born-and-bred New Yorker was the
Yankees cap atop his head.
</P>
<P>
   I introduced myself and he ushered me inside the fence. ``First
off, the balls are not called bowling balls,'' he said. ``They're
called bowls.'' This, it seemed, was not only a very common
misconception, but also an important point. I came to understand
that one risked calling them balls at one's own peril.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he said, ``despite appearances, this isn't much like
boccie.'' He was referring to the Italian game in which players
throw wooden balls toward a small metal one. ``We roll, not toss,
and our bowls aren't round.'' As he spoke, a white-haired woman to
our right dutifully made her way around the edge of the green,
trimming the frayed edges of the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Leading me around the green, Reynal spoke about the dimensions
of the green. It is divided into lanes, or ``rinks,'' and eight
games can take place simultaneously. Players toss the jack at least
60 feet down the rink, marked off only by posts at the end of the
green, and then take turns bowling from a small plastic mat that is
placed at the opposite end of the rink.
</P>
<P>
   Our tour complete, Reynal brought out the bowls, hard plastic
spheres each weighing three to four pounds each. They were the size
of softballs. The purpose of the game, he said as he hefted a bowl,
is simple: Put as many of your bowls as possible as close as
possible to the jack. Matches are broken up into ``ends,'' which
are similar to innings in baseball. In each end, players roll all
four of their bowls. (In singles and pairs, bowlers get four bowls;
in triples, they use three bowls, and in 4-on-4 games, each bowler
uses two bowls.)
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of each end, players (or teams) get one point
for every bowl they have placed closer to the jack than their
opponents' nearest bowl. Games are typically played to a set number
of ends, usually 12, 14 or 16, and may take a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded easy enough to me:Just toss that sphere down near the
jack. But the catch, Reynal said with a slight grin and a raised
eyebrow, was how the bowls rolled. They are all unevenly weighted,
heavier on one side, so that, depending on how you align them, they
will sweep in an arc that curves either to the right or the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``See how the emblem on this side is larger than the one on the
other side,'' Reynal said, pointing to the design on one side of a
bowl. ``That means that this side is heavier, so keep that emblem
on the side you want the bowl to curve.''
</P>
<P>
   I held the bowl with my thumb pointing up, as he directed, and
kept the larger emblem to the right. Sure enough, after about 50
feet, the bowl began veering right. I smiled; it was like a magic
trick. Unfortunately, the bowl did not end up anywhere near the
jack. That would have to be the next trick.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   I rolled again. Not much closer. Reynal reminded me to keep my
arm straight and step into the bowls. After about 10 practice
rolls, I began to get the hang of it and even put four in a row
around the jack. Not too hard, I thought, especially when there
aren't any other bowls in the way.
</P>
<P>
   That, he told me, is the real challenge. Your opponent _ or
opponents if you are playing in a threesome or foursome _ will
often block your path with their bowls or send them into the jack.
(This is the closest the sport comes to matching the thunder of its
offspring, 10-pin bowling.) And considering that depending on how
many people play, there can be up to 18 bowls on the green at one
time, it can become nearly impossible to find a path to the jack.
</P>
<P>
   Reynal left me practicing. I focused on the jack and worked on
estimating my ``draw,'' the amount of curve on my rolls. ``Hey, 10
bucks says you can't hit it.'' I turned around to see three thick
men carrying a cooler toward the Sheep Meadow. They had stopped to
watch. I felt as if I were in a zoo. I nodded at them, as if to
say, ``Oh yeah, watch this,'' and then promptly rolled the bowl
four feet to the right. The men laughed and walked on. I had a way
to go.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, the other club members arrived, 11 in all on
this day. (Reynal said there were ``about 60'' in the club.) Like
the 60-year-old Reynal, a retired computer programmer, most members
were dressed in white and eligible for the senior citizen movie
discount, or at least closing in on it. In the group there were a
teacher, an actor, an investment banker and a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   I watched as Reynal split up teams and the games started. As
they rolled, partners stood at opposite ends of the rink, directing
one another's bowls using an elaborate system of hand signals,
similar to a third-base coach's signs to a hitter, indicating to
their teammates the score, where the jack was and where the
opponents' bowls were.
</P>
<P>
   Talking is discouraged in the game, hence the tradition of hand
signals, The conversation, what there was of it, was limited.
``Right down the middle, Frankie!'' exhorted one bowler. ``You got
it, Frankie, you got it!'' Frankie did not have it; his bowl
drifted to the right. Oh, well.
</P>
<P>
   After witnessing most of one game, I was ready to go up against
Frankie, or at least try my hand in competition. Fortunately for
me, David Fainkich, a 31-year-old Brooklyn lawyer who has been
bowling for three years, had arrived late. He lent me a spare set
of four bowls and we began a game of singles. We played with four
bowls each, trading off rolls, and decided to play to 12 ends.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, I managed to take an early lead on Fainkich, going
up 4-1 by finishing closer to the jack in four of the first five
ends. But he answered right back with a three-point end, clustering
three of his bowls closer to the jack than any of mine. On the
fourth end, Fainkich pulled out a pocket tape measure to determine
whose ball was closer. On the fifth end, he moved the mat forward _
the winner of each end gets to place the mat and roll the jack in
the next end _ effectively shortening the distance by 15 feet and
throwing me off.
</P>
<P>
   ``A common strategy, but you'd be surprised how often it
works,'' he said, proving his point by making one. The score
wavered back and forth _ 8-7, 9-8, 11-9 _ until we came to the
final end. Fainkich was up 12-9 on me; I needed a few monster
rolls. Fortunately for me, his first three bowls were off the mark.
If I could get to the jack on my fourth bowl, I could take the
game. It was all-or-nothing time. I bent down and sent my final
bowl spilling onto the carpet of grass. It sailed down the right
side and began slowly curving back to the left. I hopped on one
leg, exerting all kinds of body English from 60 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just as I was preparing to stifle a shout of ``Boo-yah!''
(there's absolutely no gloating allowed in lawn bowling), I heard a
sickening clank. I'd hit one of his bowls; the gantlet _ and my
opponent _ had won. Fainkich smiled and shook my hand. ``Good game,
especially for a beginner,'' he said. ``You should come back some
time.'' I just might, I told him, I just might.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
