<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-SHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA BOARDS SHIP TO RESCUE WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Ending a naval wrangle that highlighted the
logistical weakness of the Canadian military, Canadian troops swung
down from a helicopter on Thursday to board an American merchant
ship that for almost three weeks had held three Canadian soldiers
and 10 percent of Canada's armored might hostage on the high seas
over nonpayment of a shipping bill.
</P>
<P>
   Without any sea-lift capacity of its own, Canada moves its
personnel and materiel either by private freighter or by arranging
rides to wars and peacekeeping assignments aboard the ships of
other NATO countries. On Thursday afternoon, with the money owed by
a Montreal shipping company still unpaid, Canada's defense
minister, Art Eggleton, ordered soldiers from a Canadian naval
vessel, the Athabaskan, to board the merchant ship, the Katie,
which had been anchored in international waters off the southeast
coast of Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   The boarding of the ship, which flies the flag of St. Vincent
and the Grenadines, took place without injuries, although Reuters
reported that the Ukrainian captain, Vitaly Khlebnikov, ``engaged
the ship in violent maneuvers'' as a Canadian Sea King helicopter
lowered the soldiers by cable. After the boarding, the freighter,
escorted by a Canadian frigate and destroyer, resumed course to its
original destination, Becancour, a port downriver on the St.
Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boarding this vessel became necessary after all other
reasonable solutions were exhausted,'' Eggleton said at a news
conference after the incident. Referring to the billing standoff,
which was almost a month old, he added: ``There was no end in sight
to this dispute. No responsible government can allow interference
with its military personnel or equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   For Canadians, the spectacle of $150 million worth of tanks and
munitions held hostage over a $100,000 bill was either a joke or a
sad commentary on how Ottawa has starved successive military
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the ``amusing'' side, The Globe and Mail in Toronto
editorialized Thursday about the ``comic opera,'' saying, ``The
Ukrainian crew of a Soviet-era ship flying the flag of that great
naval power, St. Vincent and the Grenadines, holds hostage Canadian
military equipment because of a financial dispute that does not
even involve the Canadian government.''
</P>
<P>
   But The National Post, Canada's conservative national newspaper,
saw the standoff as a national humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to decide which is the most pitiful part of this
story,'' the newspaper said Thursday, before the boarding. ``Is it
that Canada's navy, which in 1946 was the third largest in the
world, today doesn't even have the ability to transport our army to
battle?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it that a key element of our national security was
delegated to a foreign company?'' continued the newspaper, which
routinely criticizes the Liberal government for squeezing military
budgets. ``Is it that fully 10 percent of Canada's armored force
can fit on a single ship?''
</P>
<P>
   Returning from a Canadian peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, the
cargo included 580 tanks, armored personnel carriers and
reconnaissance vehicles as well as 390 sea containers loaded with
500 tons of weapons, ammunition and electronic warfare gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exposure to salt and humidity are decidedly bad for tanks,
vehicles and high-tech equipment, no matter how well wrapped they
may be,'' The Globe and Mail said Thursday. ``National Defense must
get the equipment back as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Under international maritime law, a boarding may occur if
permission is granted by the captain, by the owner or by the
country of registry. St. Vincent and the Grenadines told Canada
that it did not object to the boarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still regard it as a commercial dispute,'' Mary Ellen
Gilroy, public affairs officer for the United States Embassy in
Ottawa, said Thursday evening. ``We hope the commercial dispute
will be resolved satisfactorily.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Margan, president of the company that owns the freighter,
Third Ocean Marine Navigation of Annapolis, Md., has said that
halting the Katie in international waters was the only leverage he
had over the delinquent company, Andromeda Navigation of Montreal.
Andromeda stopped payment to Margan's company on July 5 because of
counterclaims against it. A month of negotiations failed to resolve
the billing dispute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
