<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, AUGUST 4. 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Thse corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-PALESTINIAN-CAMP-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
2 about a summer camp at Nablus, in the West Bank, where 25,000
Palestinian teen-agers are trained in games of war, referred
incorrectly to the shift in control of the towns and villages where
the youths live. It was Israel that ceded the areas to Yasser
Arafat's Palestinian Authority, not the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ISRAEL-PERES-NYT (moved Monday, July 31)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 31
about Shimon Peres' defeat in a parliamentary vote for the
presidency of Israel misstated the length of the term. Moshe
Katsav, the winner, will serve a single term of seven years, not
five. The article also overstated the legislative experience of
Yosef Lapid, a supporter of Peres. He is a first-time member of
parliament, not a veteran lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GOP-BUSH-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
2 about George W. Bush misstated his family relationship to
President Franklin Pierce. The relationship is through Bush's
great-grandfather Scott Pierce, but Bush is not a direct
descendant. None of Pierce's children survived to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-HALBERSTAM-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service obituary sent on Wednesday, August
2 of Grand Rabbi Shlomo Halberstam of the Bobover sect included an
incomplete reference from family friends to the members of his
family who survived the Holocaust. Although several relatives were
killed, his mother, a brother and six sisters _ not just his eldest
son _ survived.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CELLPHONES-RISKS (moved Wednesday, July 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service Circuits article sent on
Wednesday, August 2 about potential health risks of cellular
telephone use misstated government agencies' findings. They have
said that available evidence does not indicate whether cellular
phones are safe or unsafe; the agencies have not said the phones
are safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
