<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2192 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-GEORGEP04-COX     08-03 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GEORGEP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GEORGE P. JOINS RANKS OF BUSHES ON A NATIONAL STAGE
 &HT;    By BRIAN E. CROWLEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ George P. Bush brought tears to eyes of his
father and grandfather as he gave his first nationally televised
campaign speech to the Republican National Convention on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old nephew of Texas Gov. George W. Bush spoke
directly and earnestly in English and Spanish about his mixed
heritage, telling the cheering crowd that if his uncle is elected
president he will look out for ``those of us whose faces look
different.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and his Mexican-born mother,
Columba, took to the stage as if he had been born there. He waved
to the crowd pointing to people he recognized, throwing a kiss and
pausing just the long enough for the excitement to build before he
spoke.
</P>
<P>
   So strikingly handsome that he is being called the Ricky Martin
of the Republican Party, Bush showed the crowd the political skills
he has inherited as the first member of the fourth generation of
Bushes to be involved in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Calling his uncle someone who ``has been determined to do what
is right,'' he said the two of them ``not only share the same name.
We share the same dream. The dream for a leader who will bring
people together to solve problems, not create them; who will get
the people's work done for the good of the people, not for
political careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a leader who really cares about those he was elected to
serve, including those of us whose faces look different. You see,
I'm American, but like many I come from a diverse background, and
I'm really proud of it. I respect leaders who respect my
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who taught ninth-graders for a year after graduating from
college, said that he and his uncle also share a passion for
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will give teachers and schools and parents the support they
need to help all children in our country get the best education
they possibly can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, both his father and grandfather, former
President Bush, had tears in their eyes. His grandfather and
grandmother, Barbara Bush, appeared not only thrilled but awed by
Bush's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new day. Now is the time to end the cynicism and the
fussing and fighting in Washington,'' Bush said as the cheers from
the crowd grew louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time to make sure the American dream touches every
willing heart no matter the color of your skin or the accent of
your speech. You can do that by electing my uncle. Now is the time
to restore a sense of honor and decency to the White House. We can
do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then with a final flurry of Spanish repeating what he said in
English, Bush raised his fist in the air. The crowd jumped to its
feet as he strolled off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Barbara Bush walked over to Columba Bush and
gave her a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Bush begins law school at the University of Texas in a few weeks
but promises to be back on the campaign trail whenever his uncle
needs him.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
