<HEADER>
A2193 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-LOPES-LADN-(SLANG     08-03 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOPES DOESN'T DWELL ON DODGERS PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ There are many who are outraged that Davey Lopes
is not pictured on the Dodger Stadium outfield fence that serves as
a shrine to the club's glorious past.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Lopes is not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Garvey is up there; Ron Cey, too. Bill Russell was there
last year. With Lopes, those three combined to form the longest
infield run in major-league history and helped the Los Angeles
Dodgers to four pennants between 1974 and '81.
</P>
<P>
   To Lopes, that '70s Show left town long ago. He is proud of his
past but prouder of the future. When Lopes steps onto the field
tonight at Chavez Ravine, it will not be as a nostalgia act. It
will be as manager of the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about players who would make great managers, he
was always at the top of the list,'' said Tom Lasorda, Lopes'
former manager. ``He was a great leader and a great student of the
game. I am so happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before a 15-year career that included 557 stolen bases
ended in 1987, Lopes began preparing to run a team. His fire as a
player ignited those Dodgers championship seasons. But in a sport
that has been slow to integrate minorities into management
positions, Lopes looked as if he might never get his chance. (He is
of African, Irish and Portuguese descent and grew up in Rhode
Island.)
</P>
<P>
   For five years, he was the first-base coach in San Diego. Before
that, he coached in Texas and Baltimore. The Dodgers called twice
with jobs in their farm system, but Lopes had bigger plans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's in and even though the Brewers are near the bottom of
the National League Central, Lopes, 54, says it was worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity,'' Lopes said. ``It's a very
challenging experience. It's very rewarding at times and very
frustrating at times. But it's the closest thing to an adrenaline
rush that I've had since I retired.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopes has mellowed some from the player who once went into the
stands after fans at Candlestick Park. But he bristles when he
hears that managing the lowly, small-market Brewers is some sort of
consolation prize for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people question, `Well, look at the job you have.' Look
at the job I have? I have one of 30 jobs. I've been chosen as one
person who has the ability to manage a major-league ball club. I
don't slight any job opportunity and people who do, what do you
expect?
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, you're not going to get the Yankee job. You're
not going to get the Boston Red Sox job. You're not going to get
the Atlanta Braves-type job. That's OK. All you want as a minority
is an opportunity. That's all you ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   __ With a $36.5-million payroll (23rd overall), the Brewers were
not expected to improve much from 1999's 74-87 record under Phil
Garner.
</P>
<P>
   __ It hasn't helped that outfielder Jeromy Burnitz, one of the
league's top run producers the past few years, has been batting
around .220 all season and has struggled especially against
left-handed pitching.
</P>
<P>
   __ Opening-day starter Steve Woodard was 1-7 with a 5.96 ERA
when he was sent to Cleveland in a six-player deal at last Monday's
trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   __ In that trade, the Brewers received slugger Richie Sexson but
gave up closer Bob Wickman and starter Jason Bere.
</P>
<P>
   __ Shortstop Mark Loretta has missed more than two months after
breaking a bone in his left foot. Loretta, batting .305 when
injured, is expected back in mid-August. The Brewers are 23-31
since he left.
</P>
<P>
   But there also have been plenty of poor defensive plays, missed
cutoff men and runners stranded in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is up to us to perform,'' Burnitz said this season. ``His
career speaks for itself and he brings a great deal of respect with
the players. He has a great passion for the game and I think that
wears off on the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopes has had the job only four months, but he says there is no
added pressure being a minority, who often don't receive second
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it may be an issue now only as to `where' we're going
to manage as opposed to `if' we can manage,'' he said. ``I don't
think they doubt the ability of minorities to manage any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Still plenty wait, including Jerry Royster, former Dodgers
infielder and now a member of Lopes' staff. After several years as
a top minority candidate, Royster made a lateral move last year
from Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it is now after what Dusty (Baker) has done with the
Giants and Cito Gaston (in Toronto) and Felipe Alou (in Montreal),
it's not as difficult now for me,'' Royster said. ``I don't think
it's as difficult for Davey. We understood prior to these hirings
that we were capable. It's just better now that these guys have
come through.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, who took last year off after a successful run in
Colorado, had his choice of jobs during the winter before selecting
the Chicago Cubs. He had an offer from the Angels, where he was
American League MVP in 1979. And before deciding on Lopes, the
Brewers talked to Baylor, who had coached in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a double standard?'' Baylor said. ``What I've noticed
that happened in the '90s was guys would get fired and there would
be no interview process whatsoever. Or, they'd showcase some people
as a directive from the upper echelon, so that's the frustrating
part for guys like (Chris) Chambliss and Willie Randolph. Now Hal
McRae is bitter about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, there are two minority managers, Baylor and the
White Sox's Jerry Manuel. Baylor isn't sure that would happen in
Los Angeles or New York although the Dodgers have thought wistfully
about Baker twice in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about middle America,'' Baylor said of Chicago.
``Would you ever see it with the Dodgers? Probably not. Dusty might
have a chance because he played there and there's a lot of things
that could happen. I had a chance to go to Anaheim. That was
different because they didn't have a general manager. If they hire
the manager first and then the general manager, there's going to be
friction.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopes knows all those stories. There also were reports that his
brash on-field demeanor did not play well in the interview process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people feel that (being outspoken) may have kept me back.
Once we get in this position, we have to speak up about things we
feel that are unjust. Baseball's a great game. It's a great life. I
have a passion for this game. But there are some things that could
make it better. I think it's my responsibility as well as any other
minority who's in this position to choose and promote people who we
feel are capable of doing what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopes refuses to wonder whether he had taken one of the minor-
league jobs with the Dodgers, he would have risen in the
organization after Lasorda retired in 1996 and the club was sold
two years later by the O'Malley family.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, Lopes' former double-play partner, replaced Lasorda and
was fired midway through the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew even if I had taken that job, I would not have been
next in line to succeed Tommy. I know that. You just have a gut
feeling about things. It's nothing derogatory about the team. It's
just my gut feeling that that was not the right place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers claim their outfield mural is based not on players,
but on great moments in team history. Another stipulation was no
players could be affiliated with other clubs. This seemed
particularly trivial two years ago when Fernando Valenzuela was
excluded because he was pitching in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Lopes will not be saluted in pregame ceremonies but will be part
of a media gathering before tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hold any animosity toward anybody,'' he said. ``That's
a misunderstanding that a lot of people have. People question, `Why
isn't your picture up on the wall there when they have all three
infielders and mine just happened to be left off?' I don't know. I
don't really care, to be honest with you. It would've been an
honor, but just because they don't, I don't feel slighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. O'Malley and that regime decided to do something like
that, then I'd have some bad feelings. My allegiance was to the
O'Malley regime. I don't know anybody over there. I haven't been a
Dodger since 1981. People think I was there last week. It's a new
regime, new era, new tradition. Let them do what they have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
