<SLUG> BC-GOP-SPEECH-GERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPEECHWRITER: SERIOUS MAN OF SERIOUS WORDS CREATES FINE PHRASES
FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ In many ways, the man who put many of the words
into Gov. George W. Bush's mouth Thursday night could not be more
unlike his boss. Michael Gerson, the campaign's chief speechwriter,
is short, bookish, given to conversing in finely rendered sentences
and self-effacing to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   Gerson's seriousness makes him a ripe target for Bush's kidding.
One of the governor's advisers said that Bush, in reviewing drafts
of Gerson's speeches over time, would try to guess what Gerson's
favorite line was, instantly point it out and say that it had to
go. Only after Gerson's face had lost all color would the governor
let him know that it was all a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, so quick with nicknames, calls Gerson, 36, the scribe, and
it befits Gerson's demeanor. He is a philosophical man who studied
theology in college, calls himself a born-again Christian and is
conversant in the work of a wide array of political philosophers
and poets.
</P>
<P>
   Although fundamentally conservative, Gerson was an early convert
to the school of thinking now often called compassionate
conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Gerson got his start in politics writing speeches and developing
policy for former Sen. Dan Coates of Indiana, then helped to write
speeches for Bob Dole in the 1996 presidential race. In the Bush
campaign, he plays an unusual dual role, sitting in not just on the
communications staff's meetings but also on the policy staff's as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a speechwriter can do his job unless he's
involved in that,'' Gerson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
