u p BC-CVN-GORE-HNS &LR;      08-03 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE RELEASES SHORT LIST OF RUNNING MATES 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Even as Republicans feted their freshly nominated
candidate Thursday, the Gore campaign sought to steal some of the
media spotlight by releasing a short list of running mates being
considered by the Democratic contender.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore hopes to blunt some of the momentum the
Republicans will get out of their convention, which ended Thursday,
by announcing his vice presidential choice next week in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation over the likely pick heated up as campaign officials
privately confirmed that Gore had narrowed his list down to six
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   They were identified as Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C., Sen. Evan Bayh,
D-Ind., New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, and House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   However, the more realistic list is probably closer to four
since two of the candidates, Shaheen and Gephardt, have said they
don't want the job.
</P>
<P>
   As is the tradition, Gore has remained largely out of sight
during the Republican convention, vacationing with his family in
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Democratic convention a little over a week away, he
has been busily narrowing down his running mate options.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's down to six, with one wild card that I haven't eliminated
yet,'' Gore said, while walking on the beach at Figure Eight
Island, N.C. His aides were not aware of the ``seventh wild card''
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ends his vacation today and will hit the campaign trail in
Chicago and New York before flying to Tennessee on Sunday to make
the final decision on a running mate. He is scheduled to introduce
his choice Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Gephardt, none of Gore's prospects come
from battleground states. Gephardt could also help Gore mend ties
with organized labor, which is angry at the vice president for his
support of free trade pacts. But Gephardt has said he wants to
focus his energy on helping Democrats take back the House, which
would propel him to the powerful position of speaker.
</P>
<P>
   While his name is on the short list, Gephardt's spokeswoman
Laura Nichols said ``nothing's changed'' in regard to her boss'
position on the vice presidential spot.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen, a former teacher who played a key role in Gore's New
Hampshire primary win, also told the Associated Press, ``I'm not
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the other possible contenders were non-commital.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Gerstein, a spokesman for Lieberman, said the Connecticut
senator was ``sticking by his vow of silence. We are not commenting
at all about the selection process.''
</P>
<P>
   A centrist Democrat, Lieberman would be the first Jewish person
on a major presidential ticket. As one of the most outspoken
critics of President Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky,
political observers believe he could help inoculate Gore from voter
fatigue with scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, a decorated Vietnam War veteran who eventually protested
the conflict, could help Gore, who also served in Vietnam, to
provide a contrast with Bush and Cheney, neither of whom served in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   A Kerry spokesman would not comment on the process and said the
Massachusetts senator was out West with his family because of the
death of his father.
</P>
<P>
   Both Edwards and Bayh each would bring a fresh new moderate face
to the ticket. However, since both men were elected to the Senate
in 1998 they may be considered too green.
</P>
<P>
   As the list became public, Republicans assessed the pluses and
minuses of facing the various running mates in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Former Republican National Committee Chairman Haley Barbour said
he wouldn't mind going up against Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so liberal and he's from Massachusetts. He'd suit me
fine,'' said Barbour, who is now a lobbyist in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbour suggested Lieberman would provide a tougher target
and make it harder for Bush to make inroads with traditionally
Democratic Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going after Lieberman. He's an honorable man, a good
man, more liberal than he lets on sometimes,'' Barbour said. ``It's
a plus for the Democrats.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
