<SLUG> BC-NY-STAB-ATTACK-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN'S ARREST LED TO BROTHER AS SUSPECT IN '99 MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For 14 months after Amy Watkins died with a knife in
her back on a tree-shaded sidewalk in Brooklyn, David Jamison
managed to escape the notice of dozens of detectives hunting for
her killer.
</P>
<P>
   He cut off his dreadlocks. He apparently spoke little about the
crime. He spent nine months in Pennsylvania until returning to
Prospect Heights, the neighborhood in Brooklyn where, police say,
he killed Watkins in a botched robbery in 1999, leaving behind the
$8 in her pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison's undoing began in May, with the arrest of a 37-year-old
woman _ identified by investigators as his sister _ in two bodega
robberies in the Sheepshead Bay section of Brooklyn, law
enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While the woman, Geneva Jamison, said nothing to the authorities
about her younger brother, the officials said her arrest set in
motion a series of events that led detectives to arrest Jamison on
Wednesday, accusing him of plunging a large carving knife into
Watkins' back on March 8, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   After Geneva Jamison's arrest, the officials said, someone who
knows her and her brother made a remark about the killing of
Watkins within earshot of a police informer.
</P>
<P>
   The informer eventually persuaded the person to whom the remark
was made to go to police with the information. That information,
coupled with a call to the police Crime Stoppers line, prompted the
detectives to focus on Jamison.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Jamison, 27, who the police said admitted to his
role in the killing, was arraigned in Criminal Court in Brooklyn on
a charge of first-degree murder, for which he could face the death
penalty. He was also charged with first-degree robbery and weapons
possession. Judge Joseph McKay ordered him held until a bail
hearing on Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   With Jamison standing before the judge in an oversize white
T-shirt and baggy black pants, Michael Vecchione, the first deputy
assistant in the office of the Brooklyn district attorney, said the
killing was a ``crime of opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy Watkins was simply in the wrong place at the wrong time,''
said Vecchione, adding that Jamison and his co-defendant, Felix
Rodriguez, 20, set upon her ``to satisfy their need for a small
amount of money, stabbing her with a knife that went virtually all
the way through her body.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, 26, had come from Kansas to attend the Hunter College
Graduate School of Social Work. In court on Thursday, Vecchione
called her ``an angel among us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, whose sister is Jamison's girlfriend and the mother
of his 3-year-old daughter, was also held pending an Aug. 10
hearing. He was arraigned before Judge John Carter in a separate
courtroom on charges of second-degree murder, first- and
second-degree robbery and weapons possession.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison's lawyer, Jonathan D. Sims, acknowledged that his client
had had brushes with the law, but said they resulted in a single
misdemeanor drug conviction, for which Jamison completed his
probation.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said he planned to ``vigorously challenge the
authenticity'' of Jamison's confession, especially ``how the
confession was elicited by the police,'' but he would not elaborate
Since his probation on the drug charge, Sims said, his client ``had
been on the right track.'' Outside the courtroom after the
arraignment, Vecchione said, ``He certainly didn't take the right
track that night.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jamison and Rodriguez and a third suspect, Pierre Antoine, 26,
met at least five years ago when two of Rodriguez's sisters were
dating the other two men, some of their friends and family members
said. Jamison lives with Tanya Rodriguez, together with their
child.
</P>
<P>
   The men's friendship blossomed as Jamison _ who friends said was
known as Sinister or Sin _ and Antoine played basketball in the
Dean Street Park, not far from where Watkins was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine, who, according to Jamison's statement to police, fled
after the robbery with the purse Watkins was carrying, was released
on Thursday to officials of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service, who said they would begin proceedings to deport him,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine, who was held on an old petty larceny warrant from
Schenectady, N.Y., and was questioned in the killing for about 24
hours, was born in Haiti, family members said. He grew up in
Brooklyn, graduating from high school there and winning a
basketball scholarship to Schenectady County Community College, but
he dropped out after a conviction on drug charges, family members
said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said they believed that Antoine served as a lookout
in the attack, but the only evidence they have against him is from
the other men, and under New York State law, that is not enough to
win a conviction, authorities said. After he completed a six-month
shock-incarceration sentence for his drug conviction, immigration
authorities could have moved to deport Antoine, but state parole
officials and his family said they did not.
</P>
</TEXT>
