r a BC-GOP-ANALYSIS-SPI &LR;      08-03 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ANALYSIS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHTLY SCRIPTED CONVENTION MAY BRING RESULTS GOP LOOKING FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The 37th Republican National Convention ended
Thursday, right on time, right on message and most significantly,
just slightly to the right of center.
</P>
<P>
   A convention that was designed to showcase moderation and
diversity and keep the party's famous factions from spinning
embarrassingly out of control succeeded on all counts, delegates
and party officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have a unifying convention that would bring
together and energize everybody. That's what we did,'' said
Washington Rep. Jennifer Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   The questions left to be answered are these: Will a successful
convention largely ignored by the networks and public help elect
the party's nominee, George W. Bush? Will the hipper, louder,
faster, flashier 2000 convention become a model for the future?
</P>
<P>
   Full answers will not emerge until November and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But early indications are encouraging for Republicans. Tracking
polls conducted during the convention showed that Bush was picking
up support among the groups the convention was designed to
influence _ women and independents. According to a bipartisan poll
released Thursday, Bush is 18 points ahead of Al Gore among
independents and 6 points ahead among women. The two candidates
were virtually tied among both groups at the start of the week in
the Voter.com-Battleground poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message of the convention does seem to be coming across,''
said Republican pollster Ed Goeas, who conducted the survey with
Democratic pollster Celinda Lake.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention floor, no poll was needed. As delegates filed
out of the First Union Center for the last time, they left unified,
enthralled and breathless _ much like the crowd after a Las Vegas
supershow. In many ways, the four-day convention more closely
resembled an extravagantly produced show than a political
instrument, relying on a quick tempo, non-politicians to make
political statements and a tight script to keep the focus squarely
on Bush.
</P>
<P>
   This convention, said Norman Ornstein, a resident scholar at the
American Enterprise Institute and an authority on U.S. politics,
contrasts this with previous GOP conventions because ``it has been
organized, unified, enthusiastic and the nominee has been fully in
charge. ... Things have definitely gone according to plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Ornstein is less certain about whether future GOP conventions
will follow from a similar mold. The reason has less to do with
philosophy than with the power and mechanics within the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a confluence of circumstances that don't occur
often,'' Ornstein said. ``Republicans have been out of the White
House for eight years, they believe they can win and that has
brought everybody together.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Ornstein said, the Bush campaign has been
fantastically well organized and informed, resolving problems
before they take root.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest example came Tuesday when Rep. Jim Kolbe, the only
openly gay Republican congressman, spoke. Conservative delegates
from Texas threatened to revolt but the Bush campaign intervened.
Instead of a loud and potentially disruptive protest, the delegates
silently bowed their heads in prayer while Kolbe delivered his
three-minute speech.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, the convention never strayed from a script so
detailed it included ``talking points'' for delegates to follow
when interviewed by one of the 15,000 reporters on site.
</P>
<P>
   It conformed with Bush's goal to expand the party by reaching
out to minorities, women and independent voters, groups that
historically have been shunned by more conservative elements that
had controlled the party.
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone had any doubts about the seriousness of that goal,
it was on display every night on the podium. Few politicians had
speaking roles. Instead, there was a long line of African
Americans, including an R&AMP;B singer in tight black leather pants,
and a Baptist minister. It included the first ever convention
speech delivered entirely in Spanish, as well as a Muslim cleric
and celebrities from professional wrestler The Rock to actors Rick
Schroder and Richard ``Shaft'' Roundtree.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in his acceptance speech Thursday night, made clear that
the Philadelphia convention would be the launch pad for a new
direction. ``We are now the party of ideas and innovation. ... The
party of idealism and inclusion. ... The party of a simple and
powerful hope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Steve Forbes, who was a large thorn Bush's side during the
primaries, accusing him of abandoning the party's conservative
values, voiced the party line of unity, diversity and progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very real,'' Forbes said of the bond that was
forged during the convention. ``I think one of the reasons all the
activists are excited is that they feel that, for example, on taxes
that by the time the term is done more is going to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention followed the script so precisely that when asked
to find a flaw, Haley Barbour, former chairman of the Republican
National Committee, could offer only this: ``They did finish two
minutes late last night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
