<SLUG> BC-NY-WEST-NILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST NILE FOUND IN DEAD BIRDS IN FIVE MORE UPSTATE NEW YORK
COUNTIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J.)  By EUN LEE KOH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dead birds testing positive for the West Nile virus
were found in five more counties in upstate New York, indicating a
statewide presence of the mosquito-borne virus, the State Health
Department announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Traces of West Nile were found in dead birds found in Albany,
Dutchess, Putnam, Warren and Washington Counties, some of which are
far from New York City and the suburban counties hit hardest by the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   According to the health department, the birds were too young or
weak to have flown that far from the city, indicating that they
probably contracted West Nile from local mosquitoes carrying the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That news shouldn't result in unnecessary alarm,'' said
Antonia Novello, the state health commissioner, adding that New
Yorkers should take precautions to protect themselves from mosquito
bites.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said the threat of the virus was not great
enough upstate to begin a pesticide spraying program similar to the
one in the metropolitan region, but the health department has
produced a public service announcement, for radio stations
statewide, urging New Yorkers to get rid of stagnant water around
their homes where mosquitoes can breed.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, 119 birds and 38 samples of mosquitoes had been
found infected with the West Nile virus, a slight increase from
Wednesday, but officials said they have not confirmed the presence
of the virus in any humans. Last year, the disease killed seven
people and seriously sickened 55 others. The elderly, young
children and people with weakened immune systems are most at risk
for a serious reaction to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, a dead crow infected with the virus was found in
the town of Columbia, the first known case in eastern Connecticut.
There were no immediate plans to spray the town, according to state
officials, but the state's chief entomologist predicted that the
virus would spread through the state and across New England.
</P>
<P>
   The findings come as New York City braces itself for another
round of pesticide spraying Friday night in northern Manhattan and
parts of the Bronx and Queens. Central Park was scheduled to be
sprayed again in the early morning hours Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the virus continues to be concentrated in the New
York City area, especially on Staten Island. So far, the city has
ruled out 160 possible human cases of the virus, and is awaiting
the results of tests on 40 other people, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, state officials have referred six suspected cases
to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta. The
people who were ill showed symptoms of the disease and they lived
in counties where dead birds infected with the virus have been
found. The test results are expected sometime next week. About 50
people from New Jersey have been tested for the virus so far, but
none have tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms of the virus, which can cause encephalitis, an
inflammation of the brain, include high fever, muscle weakness,
disorientation and signs of infection in spinal fluid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2315 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-SPEECH-ANALYSIS-H     08-03 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SPEECH-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Candidate Bush saves tough words for Democrats for acceptance
speech
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEWS ANALYSIS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By R.G. RATCLIFFE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ After a year of delivering only soft criticisms
and allusions to scandal, Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush went on a hard offensive Thursday against the Democratic
administration, portraying it as a failure.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to millions of Americans directly for the first time in
his speech accepting the GOP nomination, Bush left no doubt that
his campaign had shifted gears from the primaries to the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   Where Bush had once seemed unwilling to engage his Democratic
opponent, Vice President Al Gore, too directly or too often, the
Texas governor drew clear lines in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush's vision of the future was one of renewal, his rhetoric
was that of a man determined to win _ to win for himself and his
country and in some ways avenge the loss his father, former
President Bush, suffered to President Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was the last president of a great generation, a
generation of Americans who stormed beaches, liberated
concentration camps and delivered us from evil,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Without directly mentioning the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal,
Bush said Clinton has failed his generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current president embodied the potential of a generation.
So many talents. So much charm. Such great skills. But in the end,
to what end?''
</P>
<P>
   The speech made a case for why America should not elect Gore as
Clinton's successor as much as it made a case for why Bush should
be elected.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged the prosperity the nation has seen under
Clinton and Gore, but he portrayed them has having squandered an
opportunity. Prosperity, Bush argued, gave the administration a
chance to strengthen the military, improve schools and shore up
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had their moment. They have not led. We will,'' Bush
said. ``This is not a time for third chances. This is a time for
new beginnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Though only mentioning Gore by name three times, Bush was
belittling of the vice president's campaign against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of the proposals I've talked about tonight, he has
called a `risky scheme' over and over again,'' Bush said. ``It is
the sum of his message _ the politics of roadblock, the philosophy
of the stop sign.''
</P>
<P>
   While releasing his volley, Bush also tried to frame this fall's
political debate in a way that makes his own attacks defensive
while Gore's are acts of aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their war room is up and running, but we are ready. Their
attacks will be relentless, but they will be answered,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign, even before the text of Bush's speech was
delivered to reporters Thursday night, unleashed a ``prebuttal''
against it. The prebuttal criticized Bush's policies on Social
Security, tax cuts, education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final dance at the masquerade ball will be the Texas
two-step,'' said Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took no defensive positions in his speech, however. And he
even dared to bring up the issue that often most clearly divides
Democrats from Republicans, abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will lead our nation toward a culture that values life _ the
life of the elderly and the sick, the life of the young and the
life of of the unborn,'' said Bush, who opposes abortion except in
cases of rape, incest or to save the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech recognized that the swing constituency in this
year's election _ women and independents _ has been alienated in
recent years by both Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sought to reassure these voters that if they choose him
over Gore he will be a different kind of Republican, a man who
would lead honorably with an agenda that is tough but not
hardhearted.
</P>
<P>
   And though he is the son of a president, Bush sought to portray
himself as the outsider in this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of things that come with Washington
experience. I don't have enemies to fight,'' Bush said. ``And I
have no stake in the bitter arguments of the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas political science professor Bruce Buchanan
said Bush, by putting distance between himself and the Washington
establishment of both parties, is reaching out to disillusioned
voters.
</P>
<P>
   And for those voters, Buchanan said, Bush also was able to build
an agenda of ``leadership issues'' that showed his campaign is
about more than just winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It addresses their concerns by combining goals with high
uplift,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   The basic themes of Bush's speech were those that he has been
laying out over the past year of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promised to improve schools, strengthen Social Security and
give prescription drug benefits to those on Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues are meant to appeal to those Americans who have
been turned off by the attempts of congressional Republicans to
dismantle or cut social programs. Bush cut himself free of the
congressional budget-cutters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big government is not the answer, but the alternative to
bureaucracy is not indifference,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   These themes also slash at the heart of the traditional
Democratic agenda, forcing Gore to play defense on his home turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's issue trespassing,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   The speech gave Bush an opportunity to convince Americans that
he is a man of substance and quell fears that he lacks the gravitas
to hold the nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the speech did he try harder to establish himself as
a leader of substance than on the issue of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security has been called the third rail of American
politics _ the one you're not supposed to touch because it shocks
you,'' Bush said. ``But if you don't touch it, you can't fix it,
and I intend to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
