<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2360 &Cx1f; tad-z
b p BC-CVN-GOP-MAIN-0804-COX     08-03 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-MAIN-0804-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH ACCEPTS GOP NOMINATION, PROMISES TO RESTORE ``CIVILITY AND
RESPECT'' TO WASHINGTON
 &HT;    By JENA HEATH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush accepted his party's
presidential nomination Thursday night, offering himself as an
inclusive leader who will broaden the Republican Party, restore
``civility and respect'' to Washington and bring back an ethos of a
simpler time.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech repeatedly interrupted by cheering delegates
concluding their four-day convention, Bush urged Republicans and
Democrats in the nation's capital to stop feuding and ``end the
politics of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, the speech was a denunciation of President Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore as babyboomers who ``coasted through
prosperity'' and squandered their eight years in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current president embodied the potential of a
generation,'' Bush said. ``So many talents. So much charm. Such
great skill. But, in the end, to what end?
</P>
<P>
   ``So much promise,'' he added, ``to no great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling his father, former President George Bush, ``the last
president of a great generation,'' Bush called upon his own
generation to ``extend the promise of prosperity to every forgotten
corner of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had their moment. They have not led. We will,'' he
declared, to thunderous applause and cheers. ``Our generation has a
chance to reclaim some essential values _ to show we have grown up
before we grow old.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech emphasized the themes Bush has relentlessly pursued
on the campaign trail: greater accountability for public schools,
strengthening Social Security, building up the military and cutting
taxes. Bush also wove in a recent theme, offering the elderly
Medicare coverage for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore campaign spokesman Douglas Hattaway ridiculed Bush's
speech even before it had been delivered, describing it in a
statement as ``the Texas two-step'' being played at ``the GOP's
masquerade ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway said ``George Bush attacked Al Gore tonight to draw
attention away from his agenda of cutting Social Security benefits,
lavishing most of the tax cuts on a few, raising Medicare premiums
for seniors, failing to ensure access to health insurance to every
child and failing to expand pre-school or college opportunity for
the next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's prime-time speech appeared aimed beyond the boisterous
GOP faithful inside Philadelphia's First Union Center. It consisted
of a full basket of themes and promises intended to attract swing
voters, disaffected Democrats, minorities and young citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Bush mocked Gore, painting him as an obstructionist and a
pessimist who practices ``the politics of the roadblock, the
philosophy of the stop sign.'' And he ridiculed the vice president
for repeatedly characterizing Bush's proposals as ``risky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If my opponent had been there at the moon launch, it would
have been a, 'risky rocket scheme,''' Bush said. ``If he'd been
there when Edison was testing the light bulb, it would have been a,
'risky anti-candle scheme.' ...He now leads the party of Franklin
Delano Roosevelt. But the only thing he has to offer is fear
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed Gore, the son of a U.S. Senator and a lifelong
Washington insider, while recounting his own story of growing up in
Midland, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That background may lack the polish of Washington,'' he said.
``Then again, I don't have a lot of things that come with
Washington experience. I don't have enemies to fight. And I have no
stake in the bitter arguments of the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to change the tone of Washington to one of civility and
respect,'' he said, prompting cheers from delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called on Republicans and Democrats to work together to
save Social Security, reshape the Head Start program for poor
children and, ``renew the promise of America's public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wife, Laura, wearing a white suit, entered the convention
hall at 8:30 p.m. (EDT) and took her seat in the family's box. The
couple's twin daughters, Jenna and Barbara, 18, were also in the
box, along with President Bush and his wife, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bush told reporters he felt upbeat about the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I want to say,'' Bush said. ``I know the tone I
want to set.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected to feel emotional the moment he took to the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a moment of high drama and a lot of energy in the
hall,'' he said. ``It is a very close setting, so I'll be right on
top of the Texas delegation and the California delegation, where I
have a lot of friends. And the Ohio delegation will be to my
left... I'll be able to see my family easily. So it is going to be
a moment I'm really looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked with reporters after visiting President Ford, who is
recovering at Hahnemann University Hospital from two mild strokes.
The visit lasted about 20 minutes. Ford's wife, Betty, his
daughter, Susan and two sons, Jack and Steve, were also there.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
