<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-MAIN-HNS &LR;      08-03 1560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PLEDGES TO LEAD NATIONAL RENEWAL 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Gov. George W. Bush, a president's son, pledged
in a surprisingly stinging speech Thursday night to be the father
of a national renewal ``in times of plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had promised to keep his rhetoric positive. But in the
course of accepting the Republican presidential nomination, he
denounced President Clinton as immature and ineffective, Vice
President Al Gore as a fear-monger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had their moment. They have not led. We will,'' the Texan
said.
</P>
<P>
   With the mission of convincing America he has depth to match his
charm, and facing his largest television audience ever, Bush closed
out his party's national convention by casting himself as a
Washington outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of things that come with Washington
experience,'' he said. ``I don't have enemies to fight. And I have
no stake in the bitter arguments of the last few years. I want to
change the tone of Washington to one of civility and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush emerged last year as the favorite for the nomination after
Republican leaders and voters looked to anoint a contender with few
obvious ties to the battle-scarred GOP majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But, sounding as if he had joined those battles, Bush said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation has a chance to reclaim some essential values,
to show we have grown up before we grow old. But when the moment
for leadership came, this administration did not teach our
children, it disillusioned them.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not directly mention the impeachment trial that sprang
from Clinton's adultery, or the ethical questions surrounding
Gore's 1996 campaign fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   Convention delegates, finishing a four-day meeting that
soft-pedaled their conservative views while elevating Bush's pitch
to moderates and minorities, showered him with adoring applause and
bellows.
</P>
<P>
   Bush offered to take the nation beyond the economic prosperity
that blossomed in the Clinton years. ``We will seize this moment of
American promise,'' Bush said. ``We will use these good times for
great goals. We will confront the hard issues.''
</P>
<P>
   His eyebrows tight with intensity, Bush hit on issues normally
carried by the Democrats. He promised to tackle problems with
public education, the Head Start pre-school program, Social
Security and Medicare. He denounced bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   He also raised traditionally Republican concerns, saying the
nation needs tax cuts, a rebuilding of the military and respect for
``the life of the unborn'' _ a reaffirmation of his opposition to
abortion. He emphasized his proposal to let families use government
money to send their children to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, he said, ``embodied the potential of a generation. So
many talents. So much charm. Such great skill. But in the end, to
what end? So much promise, to no great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Gore's criticisms of Bush's economic proposals as
risky schemes, Bush said the vice president only creates obstacles
to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd been there when Edison was testing the light bulb, it
would have been a `risky anti-candle' scheme,' '' Bush quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic operatives criticized Bush's prime time address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Gov. Bush does not want to talk about his record in
Texas, or his running mate's record in Congress, he offered up only
the tired, old Republican formula of personal attacks, vague
phrases and rehashed platitudes,'' Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway
said. ``Gov. Bush failed to tell the whole story about how his
plans favor the few over America's working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the pivotal convention moment was extraordinary for
Bush and the Republican Party, which usually awards the
presidential nomination to tested political veterans.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time since the nomination of Dwight Eisenhower
in 1952 that the curtain-closing GOP acceptance speech was
delivered by a man who had never sought or served in the presidency
or vice presidency before. The nominees in the interim were Richard
Nixon, Barry Goldwater, Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan, George Bush and
Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor's speech was also a link with the past.
After a day that included a visit to Ford in the hospital, Bush
delivered his speech to a convention audience that included his
parents, former President Bush and Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The governor called his father ``the most decent man I have ever
known'' and ``the last president of a great generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dad, I am proud to be your son,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 54, is seeking to become the first presidential offspring
to fill his father's shoes since John Quincy Adams in 1824.
</P>
<P>
   With running mate Dick Cheney, who served as Pentagon chief
under the governor's father, Bush now sets out on a campaign to
defeat Gore, who teamed with Clinton in 1992 to end the Bush
presidential administration. The Bush campaign gets to declare the
convention a success to the extent that voter surveys show Bush's
lead over Gore has increased.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was scheduled to attend a prayer breakfast today,
then fly to Pittsburgh, Pa., to start a campaign train-and-plane
trip through Midwestern states where the Nov. 7 election is
expected to be the closest.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is scheduled to announce his selection of a vice
presidential nominee Tuesday, six days before the start of the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Challenging the Democrats' franchise on representing the
down-trodden, Bush used his speech to urge his party to attend to
Americans who feel left out. ``We are their country, too,'' he
said. ``And each of us must share in its promise, or that promise
is diminished for us all.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We will extend the promise of prosperity to every
forgotten corner of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Answering criticism that he lacks the experience for the White
House, Bush said he had made difficult decisions under pressure as
governor and in private business. After running an oil company, he
was managing partner of the Texas Rangers baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Warm-up speakers included Jan Bullock, widow of the late Texas
Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's friendship and bi-partisan work with Bush was
considered a key to Bush's successes as governor. Bullock endorsed
Bush for re-election in 1998, encouraged him to run for president
and died in 1999 a few months after Bush declared his national
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, I am honored to join in his nomination,'' Bullock's
widow said. ``I consider it to be a part of Bob Bullock's
unfinished business.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush returned the compliment in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he is with me in spirit in saying to those who would
malign our state for political gain: Don't mess with Texas,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was introduced to the convention by the Rev. Kirbyjon
Caldwell of Windsor Village United Methodist Church in Houston, the
city Bush listed as his home address for 15 years of his childhood
and early adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The influential African-American clergyman, who calls himself a
politically independent admirer of Bush's performance, created a
controversy in Houston by agreeing to play a convention role. Some
blacks said Caldwell was being exploited by a party hostile to
their interests; others defended his right of expression. ``I am
here tonight because I place policy above and beyond politics,''
Caldwell told conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   The events Thursday night were the the culmination of Bush's
remarkable rise to the crest of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush followed his father's path to the nomination without his
father's portfolio of service in Congress and the diplomatic corps.
Republican Ronald Reagan and Democrat Bill Clinton captured
presidential nominations after serving longer in governorships than
Bush has.
</P>
<P>
   But, on a steady updraft designed by his Austin-based political
consultant, Karl Rove, Bush led the early preference polls among
Republican voter by virtue of his family name, fund-raising
potential, overwhelming gubernatorial re-election in 1998 and
distance from the controversial GOP leadership in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to raise a record-high $90 million for his campaign,
starting with donations from Texas executives and those who had
supported his father.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's campaign ran into stiff resistance from
reform-minded Sen. John McCain, Bush prevailed in the primaries
thanks to his dominating warchest and outreach to conservatives,
who are the GOP bedrock. His hard work aside, Bush's run through
the primaries was as breezy as his speaking style on the campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day convention, choreographed and packaged for TV video
in the style of its forerunners, was plotted by the Bush campaign
to emphasize his message instead of the party platform, his stances
rather than the legislative warfare of the party's congressional
leaders, and women and minorities rather than conservative white
men, who were a majority of the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of sentiment, the Texas delegation was called on
last to cast its votes for Bush's nomination. The party tallied the
total vote and officially awarded the berth to Bush Thursday night,
although other states gave more than the amount needed the night
before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
