<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2361 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-RDP-ART-4THLD-WRI     08-03 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RDP-ART-4THLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PLEDGES TO `USE THESE GOOD TIMES FOR GREAT GOALS'
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to add editors' note re availability of speech text on
Web.)  
 (UPDATES thruout with Bush's speech. Story is now by R.W. Apple
Jr.)  
(Eds: The complete text of Bush's speech will be available at the
New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com) (ART ADV: Photos CVN3,
CNV5, CNV6, CVN 8 and CVN 10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Introducing himself to a nation that barely knows
him, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas pledged Thursday night to
``confront the hard issues _ threats to our national security,
threats to our health and retirement security'' that he said the
Clinton administration had ducked.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a jubilant final session of the Republican National
Convention, he argued that ``times of plenty'' were times to solve
major problems, not to sit back and relax. With that, he sought to
cut the ground from beneath his Democratic rival, Vice President Al
Gore, whose strongest electoral argument is his association with
the prosperity of the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   With his parents and many other members of his large family in
the VIP seats, Bush offered this curt verdict on Bill Clinton's and
Al Gore's time in the White House: ``So much promise, to no great
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused the vice president of indulging in ``the politics
of the roadblock, the philosophy of the stop sign.'' He turned
Franklin D. Roosevelt's famous first inaugural address around and
aimed it at Gore, charging that ``the only thing he has to offer is
fear itself.''
</P>
<P>
   He mocked Gore by saying, ``I do not need to take your pulse
before I know my own mind. I do not reinvent myself at every turn.
I am not running in borrowed clothes.'' Yet he himself has been
successively moderate, conservative and moderate again, as the
nominating campaign progressed.
</P>
<P>
   In a further though more indirect thrust at the president he
hopes to succeed, the Republican nominee quoted the poet Robert
Frost, remembered by older Americans for his appearance at John F.
Kennedy's inaugural four decades ago, on the need to ``occupy the
land with character.'' Few if any of the thousands who filled the
First Union Center in south Philadelphia, and few of those watching
on television, could have missed the allusion to Clinton's sexual
involvement with an intern, which led to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration had its chance,'' Bush asserted. ``They
have not led. We will.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he had vowed, much of Bush's text was upbeat. ``Tonight
we vow to our nation: We will seize this moment of American
promise,'' he said. ``We will use these good times for great
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few jibes Thursday night and Wednesday night's more
hard-edged speech by Dick Cheney, his running mate, Bush and his
party have tried all week to avoid the kind of sniping, to say
nothing of the internal bickering, that they know the U.S. public
hates.
</P>
<P>
   They succeeded, but not without cost; lacking debate or drama,
the convention experienced considerable trouble in luring
television viewers. Many preferred Regis Philbin or ``Friends'' to
the GOP's voter-friendly show.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier sessions had had something of the tone of a sales
meeting, long on team spirit and short on specifics. But Thursday
night the governor spelled out, far more completely than other
speakers here, his agenda for action.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed major reforms in the public schools, in the Social
Security system and in the federal tax code. He promised to abolish
the inheritance tax and guaranteed that on his watch no one would
have to pay more than a third of their income to the government _
considerably less than the 39 percent plus some now pay.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to modernize Medicare, and to add prescription
benefits ``for every senior who needs them,'' stressing the last
item more than he had before. He vowed to rebuild the nation's
military strength. He said the moment had come ``to make Head Start
an early learning program, teach all of our children to read and
renew the promise of America's public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In a striking passage, he told the strongly conservative
Republican gathering, hostile to most new government initiatives,
that he intended ``to extend the promise of prosperity to every
corner of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that far too many in the United States felt left out
and left behind, and he described that as a challenge ``to the very
heart of America.'' Speaking in much the same vein as retired Gen.
Colin Powell on the convention's opening night, and implicitly
reminding his audience of his own doctrine of ``compassionate
conservatism,'' he declared, ``We are their country, too, and each
of us must share in its promise or that promise is diminished for
us all.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``When these problems aren't confronted, it builds
a wall within our nation. On one side are wealth and technology,
education and ambition. On the other side of the wall are poverty
and prison, addiction and despair. And, my fellow Americans, we
must tear down that wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The point was underlined in a lengthy video that depicted Bush
as a longtime friend of Hispanics and African-Americans in his home
state.
</P>
<P>
   At 54 years of age, Bush has already succeeded where many have
failed. He is only the second son of a former president ever
nominated for president by a major party; the other was John Quincy
Adams in 1824. Since then Robert Todd Lincoln fell short twice and
Robert Taft did so three times.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's speech was a crucial moment for Bush, more so
than for most nominees. It was the speech of a lifetime for a
politician whose time in elective office has been confined to a
bare six years as governor of Texas. Not since Dwight D.
Eisenhower, war hero and political neophyte, has a presidential
nominee offered so sketchy a political resume.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dealt candidly with that problem, as well as Gore's
extensive experience on Capitol Hill and in the White House, and
sought to turn his inexperience into an asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may lack the polish of Washington,'' he said. ``Then again,
I don't have a lot of things that come with Washington experience.
I don't have enemies to fight, and I have no stake in the bitter
arguments of the last few years. I want to change the tone of
Washington to one of civility and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strong signal that he intends to run as an outsider _ a
U.S. political tactic dating back to Andrew Jackson, but one
surprising in a man whose father was president and whose
grandfather was a senator.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's was shorter and leaner than many past acceptance
speeches. It had a touch of humor or two _ he took the blame for
his mother's white hair _ and a few emotional appeals, like a
tribute to his father and other members of the World War II
generation.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates, Republican loyalists all, loved what they heard,
and they stood and cheered for much of the evening, enveloped in
the now-obligatory falling balloons. Most were in no mood to make
dispassionate judgments of Bush as a rhetoritician or, indeed, as a
party standard-bearer. Nights like this are for brassy bands and
funny hats, whistles and silly signs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the impact of the speech on independents and other swing
voters, on whom the outcome in November will probably depend, that
remains to be seen _ not only whether they give him the customary
``bump'' in the polls but whether it lasts once Gore gets his four
days in the convention sun in Los Angeles later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush, who would never claim to be in the same league as
an orator with Clinton or with Ronald Reagan, gave a credible
account of himself and made a start at the process of convincing
the country that his legs are long enough to reach the stirrups of
leadership at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Andrew H. Card Jr., the convention's major-domo, said before
Thursday night's session began that it, like the last three days,
would ``be about the future, not about the past.''
</P>
<P>
   One manifestation of that was the marginalization or the
outright absence of many of the important figures in the Republican
party's recent past, including former Vice President Dan Quayle,
former House speaker Newt Gingrich, Jack Kemp, Lamar Alexander,
Steve Forbes and, of course, Pat Buchanan, who is now contending
for the Reform Party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   There was no place for any of them on Thursday night's four-hour
program, which included a number of not-quite-hip singers, a former
Miss America, four videos, a number of little-known politicians and
non-politicians, Bo Derek, several friends of the nominee and his
24-year-old nephew, George P. Bush, who gave part of his speech in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   George P. Bush described his uncle as a man who would ensure
that all Americans of all origins ``can share in the promise and
the prosperity of el sueno Americano _ the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to George W. Bush, the only prominent politicians to
speak were Sen. Bill Frist of Tennessee and Gov. Tom Ridge of
Pennsylvania, both of whom Bush briefly considered as possible vice
presidential nominees. But a non-politician was called upon to lend
weight to one of the Bush's campaign's main arguments on behalf of
their man: that he has shown a talent for working both sides of the
aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Bullock, the widow of Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock of Texas, talked
of her husband's cooperation with Bush in Austin. Bullock, a
Democrat, got along so well with Bush that he endorsed him for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush described the year 2000 as ``a remarkable moment
in the history of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Prosperity can be a tool in our hands, used to build
and better our country. Or it can be a drug in our system, dulling
our sense of urgency, of empathy, of duty. Our opportunities are
too great, our lives too short, to waste this moment.'' Praising
Reagan and his father for having helped to end the Cold War, he
accused ``the Clinton/Gore administration,'' as he called it, of
having squandered the momentum generated by the fall of the Berlin
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a steady erosion of American power and an
unsteady exercise of American influence,'' he said. But at the very
end of his speech, he had reassuring words for the Republican
faithful and for others listening to him: ``The night is passing,
and we are ready for the day to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
