<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-UT pitcher Williams getting ready for 2nd Olympics
 &HT;    By Curtis Johnson Jr.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ At home watching gymnast Mary Lou
Retton compete in the 1984 Summer Olympics, Christa Williams told
herself the Games were a place she wanted to be one day.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she was there. Now she's back, and the excitement and
honor of representing the United States at the Sydney Games next
month has not waned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first found out that I made the team in '96, I was
ecstatic,'' said Williams, a former pitcher for the University of
Texas. ``I felt every emotion possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Those emotions are still present for Williams, one of six
pitchers on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their ``Central Park to Sydney Tour,'' the team made
a stop in College Station on Wednesday night to play the Texas
All-Stars, a team of former and current college players. The tour
will include at least 31 cities leading to its completion on Sept.
3 in Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Getting ready for the Olympics is no easy task. The travel,
although good for promoting the sport and the Olympics, is taxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of pressure,'' Williams said. ``I know that no
matter how good or bad I do, my family will still love me, but you
don't want to come in and fail either.''
</P>
<P>
   Failure. Williams? Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1996 Games, Williams was 2-0 with a 9-0 shutout of the
Netherlands and a 4-2 win over Canada. She posted a 0.00 ERA with
15 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The current U.S. team is 43-0 through Wednesday, including 11-0
and 10-0 routs in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   Williams leads the team in victories at 9-0 and has one save.
She has pitched a team-high 58 2/3 innings, allowing 14 hits with
110 strikeouts, just five walks and a 0.00 earned run average.
Opponents have a .075 batting average against Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Life is good now, but her first time around as an Olympian was a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then I was young and didn't care a lot about anything,''
said Williams. ``I didn't care who I was pitching against. I was
trying to be someone I wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a graduate of Pasadena Dobie High School, pitched a
perfect game with 14 strikeouts and drove in the game-winning run
to lead the 33-0 Lady Longhorns to the Class 5A state softball
championship in 1996. Her energy and desire began to slump some in
college and the weight of expectations was heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Williams played one season at UCLA and earned All-America honors
before the school was placed on probation for NCAA rules
violations. That's where softball almost lost Williams and Williams
almost lost softball. She vowed never to play again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to pay the penalty for someone else's mistakes
or lies (at UCLA),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then a friend, Univesity of Texas softball player Nikki
Cockrell, suggested that Williams join her at Texas. Williams made
the move, and it was a good one.
</P>
<P>
   Williams earned All-America honors the next two seasons at
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father (Ed Williams) is responsible for all of my
success,'' Williams said. ``He literally made me the player I am
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
