<SLUG> BC-GOP-RICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AIDE CRITICIZES CLINTON-GORE FOREIGN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Clinton-Gore administration has run a
``messy'' foreign policy in which the United States finds itself
immersed in crises ``without knowing what it is trying to
accomplish,'' George W. Bush's chief foreign policy adviser said
Thursday night in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has been much more interested in the news of the
day, and not interested in the long-run ramifications of what we
do,'' Condoleezza Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, believed in line to be the first woman to serve as White
House national security adviser should Bush win the presidency,
cited free trade as about the only issue on which Bush has fully
agreed with the Clinton administration. The Texas governor
supported the White House on ratification of the North American
Free Trade Agreement. He did so again in the recent Capitol Hill
battle over making permanent China's normal trade status and
clearing the way for its membership in the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   With that said, however, Rice excoriated President Clinton for
focusing so intently on nurturing U.S. ties with China that he has
neglected a half-century's worth of trade and foreign policy links
to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States goes to Beijing for nine
days, but does not stop in Tokyo. ... That is something the
governor found appalling,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, 45, is perhaps the highest profile African American woman
in the Republican Party. The Stanford University provost worked for
the National Scecurity Council from 1989 to 1991 under
then-President Bush, father of the Republican nominee. She
specialized in Soviet policy at a time when the Soviet Union was
collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is especially critical of U.S. policy toward Russia, where
Vice President Al Gore has been a major player. She said Clinton
and Gore stood behind Boris Yeltsin's policies for far too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important not to personalize relations with Russian
leaders. The problem with this administration and Yeltsin was to
adopt his agenda when it was not in our interests,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the United States ``turned a blind eye'' toward
Russia's brutal war of suppression in Chechnya during the
mid-1990s, as well as to the oligarchs ``who were stealing the
country blind.''
</P>
<P>
   As he worked to control the Soviet nuclear arsenal, Gore forged
close ties to Russian Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin, who was
unceremoniously fired by Yeltsin shortly after the premier was
greeted by Gore on a U.S. visit.
</P>
<P>
   Rice described Russia's President Vladimir Putin as ``a pretty
wily and effective leader,'' and noted ``a lot of movement by KGB
veterans'' into the new administration headed by the former secret
police leader.
</P>
<P>
   Rice declined to criticize Clinton over the recent breakdown of
U.S.-sponsored Middle East peace negotiations between Israeli
Premier Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. She, in
fact, praised the president for seeking to work out an agreement
over territories held by Israel since the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they were in the same room talking,'' Rice noted,
adding that ``American presidents have had to put the pieces in
place'' on Middle East peace agreements. In order for any deal to
ever work, however, both sides must ``be convinced it will enhance
their security, a very difficult business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father, who ran in 1988 on the slogan ``a president
we won't have to train,'' Bush has thin foreign policy credentials,
although as Texas governor he has dealt with issues involving
Mexico and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Bush evoked chuckles on the campaign trail with his references
to the people of Greece as ``Grecians'' and residents of Kosovo as
``Kosovians'' (Kosovars is the proper word). He flunked an
impromptu identification quiz of foreign leaders posed by a Boston
TV reporter, and was victimized by a Canadian comedy show's send-up
story that Prime Minister Jean Chretien had endorsed his bid for
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Rice insisted, however, that the best decision-making qualities
of Bush the father are shared by Bush the son.
</P>
<P>
   Does George W. Bush have the ability not only to seek out
quality advisers but to demand more policy choices when he is not
satisfied with what they propose?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Rice replied. ``I have already seen that in
sessions I have held with him. Larry Lindsay (a major Bush domestic
adviser) can tell you the same thing. If George Bush is not
satisfied with the options presented, he will demand more.''
</P>
<P>
   During the elder Bush's administration, Rice noted, the
president not only asked whether a decision was the right thing to
do, but would turn to foreign policy aides with the question: ``Why
might you be wrong?'' It is a question, she added, that Clinton
might have asked Secretary of State Madeleine Albright when she
underestimated the staying power of Serbian dictator Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
