<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-WANG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS HOPE 7-FOOT-1 CHINESE PLAYER WILL SOMEDAY BLOSSOM INTO NBA
STAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Welcome to Texas, Mr. Wang. Welcome to the land of big
cars and big steaks, and, for good measure, big elbows.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Zhi Zhi, a Mavericks' second-round draft pick in 1999 and
current Chinese national team star, admits to being a fan of
Lincolns and the beef staple of a Texan's diet. What he might not
have been expecting on his trip overseas was an early taste of
NBA-style roughhousing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason was jacking him up pretty good,'' Mavs assistant coach
Donnie Nelson said, referring to former Texas Tech and Dallas
Kimball standout Jason Sasser.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser and Greg Dreiling, both former Mavericks players, led a
pickup team that scrimmaged against the Chinese team Wednesday
night at the Baylor/Tom Landry Center. On Wang's] first trip across
the lane, Sasser hit the 7-footer with a strategically placed
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason threw everything and the kitchen sink at him and
\RWang\S did well,'' Nelson said. ``There was some physical play in
the paint. \RWang\S handled it, he was resilient \Rand\S didn't
back down. And there isn't any guy any tougher by NBA standards
than Jason Sasser.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing the Sasser test is only one hurdle in Wang's journey to
the NBA. The 7-foot-1 Wang Zhi Zhi (pronounced Wong Zhu-Zhu) still
has many more obstacles to clear before joining the Mavs for the
2001-02 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to see him play in a NBA jersey,'' said Xia
Song, a representative of the Chinese Basketball Association and
interpreter, adding that it would help promote Chinese basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, 23, said yesterday he hopes to don a Mavs jersey in ``one
year,'' but there is ``not a commitment yet, there's a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are optimistic and hopeful that's the case,'' Nelson said
of the one-year timetable. ``Obviously there are a lot of different
factors that play in a situation like this. I think a lot of it
depends on how they do in the Olympics, and there are some
political ramifications as well. We're working on those.''
</P>
<P>
   As a gesture of goodwill, owner Mark Cuban invited the Chinese
national team to Dallas. Coach/general manager Don Nelson leaves
for China in a little more than a week for more discussions with
Chinese leaders on Wang's future.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being a member of the national team, Wang is a
soldier in the Chinese army, which carries a lifetime commitment.
And though Chinese military service isn't mandatory, Wang joined
the army at a young age to better his quality of life. He plays for
the army's Bayi Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army team is better subsidized than the other teams,'' the
interpreter Xia said. ``His family encouraged him to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang said he makes a good living by Chinese standards playing
for the army, equating his yearly salary to about $40,000. The
interpreter said that the Chinese army and government would have to
grant Wang permission to play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs, Donnie Nelson said, are ``pulling out all the stops.''
Nelson has been to China twice, and he and Cuban are planning trips
there next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forging relationships and developing trust ... I think that's
going to yield us the best result,'' Donnie Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The junior Nelson isn't a beginner in negotiating with foreign
governments. In addition to helping coach Lithuania's Olympic team,
Nelson helped sign the first player from the former Soviet Union
\RSarunas Marciulionis\S to an NBA contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously when you're dealing with a different governmental
structure, there are different challenges. However, there's been a
revolution of change that's happened over the last 10 years,''
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson first met Wang in 1996 while coaching Lithuania. They
were reunited at the 1998 Goodwill Games, when the Chinese team
stayed on the dorm floor above the Lithuanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not your typical Chinese guy,'' Nelson said. ``He's very
aggressive. He's outspoken. He's really kind of an American-type
kid. He's working on his English and there's big-time improvement
there. Culturally the adjustment is going to be easier than your
typical Chinese national person.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang, who lists Tim Duncan and David Robinson as his favorite
players, knows his biggest adjustment will be banging against the
likes of San Antonio's Twin Towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to be ready for the physical game,'' he said through
the interpreter. ``And mentally I need to be ready, be tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson likens Wang's skills to another international member of
the Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's \RDirk\S Nowitzki-like,'' Nelson said, comparing Wang to
the Mavericks' 7-foot forward from Germany. ``He's 7-1 \Rand\S he's
very skilled. He's got some `junk' to his game _ he can pass, he's
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson added that Wang figures to be a project once he reaches
the NBA, possibly needing two years before he begins to make an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Wang is ready to start the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas is a beautiful city,'' Wang said without the help of
the interpreter. ``I hope I can play here someday.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
