<SLUG> BC-GOP-WA-DELEGATES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GENERATION W' ACTIVISTS HOPE TO DRAW YOUNGER CROWD TO GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELA GALLOWAY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ They call themselves ``Generation W.''
</P>
<P>
   They're a loosely organized group of young, Seattle-area
professionals who throw parties, hang with bigshot Republicans and
raise a bit of money with one goal in mind: bringing fresh blood to
the Grand Old Party.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, the George W. Bush backers have kicked off
their campaign to remake the image of their party by adopting
Generation W, a hipper nickname for the Bush campaign's ``Young
Professionals for W'' group.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Young Professionals' sounds so lame,'' said Reagan Dunn, the
29-year-old son of U.S. Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Bellevue, and one of
two Generation W organizers. He, like many in the group, is here as
a Bush delegate to the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   While their numbers are small, the new generation of GOP
activists, many drawn into party politics by the charisma of the
candidate, tend to be more moderate, less dogmatic and more open to
cultural diversity than their elders in the party.
</P>
<P>
   Stacked with the kind of upwardly mobile 20- and 30-year-olds
who make the ``People on the Move'' newspaper columns, Generation W
is a loose collection of future power brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're putting together a very good list,'' said Dunn, a lawyer
from Bellevue with carefully groomed wavy hair and the confidence
and lingo of a political veteran.
</P>
<P>
   At the group's core are a half-dozen active volunteers _ four
lawyers, a construction executive and a fundraiser for Rep. Dunn.
Four were in Philadelphia this week, three as delegates. They spent
the week talking politics and partying at a succession of Irish
pubs, rock-and-roll restaurants and even a Blues Traveler concert.
</P>
<P>
   Generation W has no office or website, and they've only held a
couple of events.
</P>
<P>
   But they have big ideas and those events have drawn GOP stars.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the group played host in Seattle to George P. Bush,
the party's 24-year-old poster child in its effort to pull in a
younger crowd. About 80 fresh-faced conservatives went to admire
the Generation W hearthrob at Mama Lou's _ a restaurant on
Seattle's 5th Avenue that is popular with the just-out-of-college
set.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, about 150 of the young leaders met with
Laura Bush, wife of the presidential nominee, at the trendy W Hotel
_ a swanky spot that sounded just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We planned that,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn and a couple of friends started organizing the group in
November, fired up by a presidential campaign that seemed to
reflect their own energetic approach to politics, as well as life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our candidates are just more exciting,'' Dunn said. ``We've
got a young candidate (for president) this time.''
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, the GOP had nominated candidates who came of
age in the Great Depression. George W. Bush, at 54, is to
Generation W what Bill Clinton was to young, moderate Democrats in
1992 _ a candidate more like them than any they have ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing number of young Republicans in this state
who are fiscally conservative and more middle of the road
socially,'' Dunn said. ``I see more and more of those folks getting
involved. That, for me, is exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see our party go that way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the party will move in that direction is anyone's guess.
But those in Generation W offer the kind of polished and positive
image Bush wants for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative to bring in new blood is long overdue, said the
group's co-organizer, Arthur K. Langlie, whose grandfather was
mayor of Seattle and a three-term governor in the 1940s and 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Lombardi, a clean-cut and dimpled 34-year-old
already-prominent labor lawyer from Issaquah, said recently that
the party needs to improve the way it delivers its message. Younger
Republicans, he said, love the core values of the party and don't
want to change them, but feel the message has become lost because
of negativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The GOP) has done a poor job packaging it,'' he said. ``It's
just kind of how you emphasize it, how you talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The group wants to continue that effort after the November
election, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be another set of elections in two years,''
Lombardi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
