<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2374 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-SURFING-1ST     08-03 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-SURFING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL SURFING: SCENES OF BUSH, PREPARING FOR HIS SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs to replace first 7 grafs with updated material.)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the nominees had spoken and the themes of the Republican
National Convention had coalesced on its final day _ we're not your
grandma's Republican Party, let's wash the Clinton-Gore stain out
of the White House, the sky's the limit _ the cable television
pundits and Internet commentators seemed visibly relieved that they
finally had a firm idea of the agenda they will be bickering about
for the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they were just relieved that it was time for them to
go.
</P>
<P>
   As the time approached Thursday night for the acceptance speech
of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and the twisting rivers of people
on the convention floor began to slow and then build up (``It's
kind of scary for the elderly people here in the Kansas
delegation,'' one Fox floor reporter said.), the television cameras
began to spend more time watching the stage and scanning the crowd.
It was time for the big dog to sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush, that's my final answer,'' read one placard in
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, several television channels were cleaning
out their stash of leftover features about the wonders of
Philadelphia (Jane Clayson of CBS' ``Early Show'' went rowing on
the Schuylkill River with octogenarians, for instance). There were
some lingering arguments about how well the vice-presidential
nominee Dick Cheney's throw-the-bums-out line would play with
moderates or whether the convention had been specific enough on
policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the Democrats are going to say something about us,'' the
Bush strategist Karl Rove told CNN. ``If we'd delivered a four-day
economics lecture from the lectern, the Democrats would have said
we're not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   As was widely reported throughout the day Thursday, people have
not been watching the convention in droves, a subject of much
concern to the people who have paid a fortune to cover the event.
While the major networks had chipped their prime-time coverage down
to an hour or less, shifting the bulk of the work to cable, the
cable all-news channels were attracting viewership numbers that
looked more like the circulation for a medium-sized newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   This is mass media? Perhaps the crowds have moved to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not. One of the most interesting Web projects at the
convention was the partnership between Speakout.com and MSNBC,
which allowed viewers to rate the convention's major speakers, in
real time, while listening to the speech. Afterward, compiled
results were to be posted on the Internet, broken down by gender
and political preference. On Tuesday night, when Sen. John McCain
of Arizona was the featured attraction, only 426 people bothered to
take part, about the size of many high-school graduating classes.
It will never be know how many might have taken part on Wednesday
night, when Cheney delivered his blast at the Democrats, because
the whole thing went kaflooey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to substantial network failure, we were unable to conduct
the scheduled Instant Viewer Response on Wednesday,'' said a notice
on the Web page.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cause of the failure is currently under investigation,''
it added, ominously, before concluding with a more upbeat,
``However, full service has been restored and new results will be
posted immediately following George W. Bush's speech on Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations that resulted in mass arrest on Tuesday in
downtown Philadelphia also seemed to have vaporized by Thursday, at
least as far as television images were concerned. Perhaps it proved
difficult to rally people to the barricades with the slogan: The
whole world's not watching.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, from the Democratic campaign: Every channel had
Thursday's shot of Al Gore walking along a beach in North Carolina,
shaking hands, waving to folks, but saying nothing. On Wednesday,
he was barefoot and his wife, Tipper, was with him. She had shoes
on. On Thursday, he had shoes on, too, but then it did seem a
little windier.
</P>
<P>
   Both CNN and Fox presented Generation X panels to talk about how
young people were reacting to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Bagby, author of ``We've Got Issues,'' said the whole
thing seemed like a big pep rally. ``I would give the Republicans
an A in terms of the pep rally,'' she said. ``In terms of talking
about the issues affecting young people, they did a very cursory
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison Fields of Rock the Vote said she was disappointed that
McCain had not pushed his campaign finance reform message in his
speech on Tuesday. ``He wussed out big time,'' she decided.
</P>
<P>
   The National Journal decided to find out what the convention's
official theme _ ``Renewing America's Purpose. Together.'' _ might
possibly mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say it four times quick,'' the article by Burt Solomon on The
Journal's Web site said. ``Mean anything yet?''
</P>
<P>
   Their reporter went onto the convention floor to ask people what
the slogan meant to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to basics,'' decided Dan Crowley, a Maryland alternate
delegate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work together,'' said Pat Harvey, a volunteer from nearby
Bucks County, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to get spiritual on you,'' warned Cindy Costa, a
national committeewoman from South Carolina. ``America has a
destiny, purposed by God Almighty, and we have gotten away from its
precepts, starting in the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayson capped her week in Philadelphia with a montage of images
from her first-ever national political convention. Yes, a
cheesesteak was involved. Did she have any lessons to bring back to
co-host Bryant Gumbel in New York? ``Even though this was a highly
staged event,'' she said, ``the people behind it were still very
passionate about their politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
