u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT &LR;      08-03 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTEBOOK: CLINTON STUMPS ON LAZIO TURF
</HEADLINE>
  By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  NORTHPORT, N.Y. _ The Clinton 2000 campaign dubbed it the Long
Island tour, with the candidate pitching what she was calling the
``Long Island livability plan.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   For three days, staid and sensible in cream and navy blue suits,
Hillary Rodham Clinton trolled for support in the heart of her
rival's home turf, stopping off to meet with local officials, offer
succor to elderly residents, dine with fishermen on the far East
End. Not only that, she spent that time taking shots at the very
issues that her opponent for the U.S. Senate, Rick A. Lazio, the
Republican Congressman from Long Island, has taken credit for:
lower taxes one day, abortion rights another, the environment the
next.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday it was the environment's turn. With the Long Island
Sound as her backdrop, the sun occasionally poking out of the
clouds in the morning, Clinton rattled off a laundry list of
earth-friendly concerns, from the quality of drinking water in the
state to suburban sprawl to the plight of the lobsters that have
been dying off mysteriously in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A livable Long Island must be an environmentally sound Long
Island,'' she said. ``It bothers me that lobsters have died off.
What does that mean not only to the lobsters but to children and
the rest of us. What also bothers me is that Long Island has the
highest rates of breast cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it went on Thursday, with Clinton touching on everything
from the construction of a water filtration plant in the Bronx,
which she opposes, to requiring municipalities to report water
quality standards online, which she supports.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pointed to her own advocacy for financing breast cancer
research. She lauded the vice president, Al Gore, for ``his
foresight on the environment.'' And she attacked Lazio on his
environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to offer detailed criticism of his environmental
positions, saying she would save that for later. But she once again
linked Lazio to the reign of Newt Gingrich, the former House
speaker, saying that as a deputy whip, Lazio had voted in favor of
measures that would have weakened enforcement of federal
environmental laws.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finding Where to Go  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island tour has not been a combination of
well-choreographed visits with well-wishers and spontaneous
sojourns along the way.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton solicited local reporters for ideas on
where to go on the East End. (They suggested a park or two, spots
to find fishermen, diverse crowds. Clinton's advance team said they
would consult their Hagstrom's guide to Long Island.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Where's Chelsea?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the first time during Clinton's Long Island jaunt
that she was not joined by her daughter, Chelsea, 20, who is taking
the fall semester off from college to help her mother campaign and
spend the last few months of her father's tenure at the White
House. Chelsea Clinton has turned out to be almost as much of a
crowd-pleaser as her mother this week.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing the first lady on Tuesday and Wednesday from park to
senior center to luncheons with advocates and politicians, Clinton,
predictably, was no shrinking violet. She had a fixed wide grin.
She thanked her mother's well-wishers, addressed the men as
``Sir,'' attributing it to her Southern upbringing, signed
autographs and posed readily for pictures, asking simply, ``Where
would you like me to stand?''
</P>
<P>
   The only exception was the news media. Chelsea, fiercely
protected from the press during the last seven and a half years of
her father's presidency, said nothing to reporters. She has
appeared at her mother's side only occasionally during Clinton's
Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton said her daughter had returned to
Washington to see some friends. ``I am a strong advocate for young
people leading their own lives and not being taken advantage of by
people in the public arena,'' she said. ``I'll be looking forward
to having her back.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Chelsea Clinton would rejoin her mother
as she heads to Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard for the weekend.
There will be a fund-raiser on Friday in Nantucket and another will
be held on Sunday in Martha's Vineyard.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lobster Issue  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During her Long Island trip, Clinton has addressed some of
Lazio's main issues. Towing the Republican Party line, he has long
spoken of the need for tax breaks. He has described himself as
being in favor of abortion rights, but as an opponent of using
public money to pay for abortions for poor women. He has also
described himself as an environmentalist, and won endorsements from
the Sierra Club and the League of Conservation Voters in his
Congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton also painted herself as the friend of Long
Island lobstermen _ ``our lobsterman,'' as she put it _ by noting
that her opponent voted with the Republicans against an emergency
appropriations bill that would have included money for the lobster
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody should have been a strong advocate for getting that
money immediately to our lobstermen and getting the money needed to
look into causes of the dying off of the lobsters, it should have
been someone who represents Long Island,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign aides swiftly put out an afternoon news release
attacking the Clinton administration for ``arbitrarily small
quotas'' on the number of fluke that New York fishermen are allowed
to catch for sale. As for the lobstermen, they said Lazio had
fought to include $8 million for lobstermen in the emergency
spending bill but voted against it because it spun off into a
bigger, far more expensive measure.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio dismissed the very notion of the ``livability plan'' put
forth by Clinton. ``If she ever lived on Long Island,'' he told
reporters, ``she would have some basis to talk about a livability
plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
