<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARK-RAMPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICAN PARADE MAY BAN SOME RAP 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two months after the violent aftermath of the
National Puerto Rican Day Parade, parade directors are considering
a ban on some floats carrying rap performers whose music, they say,
glorifies violence and attracts unruly throngs that tarnish the
march's image, a leading board member said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Federico Perez, a board member since the 1960s and a former city
councilman from the Bronx, said he and his colleagues were not
accusing rappers of having incited the rampage that erupted on the
southern fringe of Central Park after the parade.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, Perez said board members were concerned
that many rap lyrics blaring from floats in recent years had been
obscene and did not blend in with the traditional Latin image
parade organizers wanted to project.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can prevent music that is conducive to these acts that
are outside the norm, well, we'll have to do that,'' said Perez,
who serves as spokesman for the 18-member board, a private
organization that oversees the event.
</P>
<P>
   The events that happened early in the evening of June 11 after
the parade ended on Fifth Avenue have caused consternation among
the board members, Perez said. In frenzied attacks that attracted
nationwide attention, hordes of young men, many of whom had
attended the parade, groped about 60 women in the southeast corner
of the park near 59th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The police have charged 30 men in the attacks and are searching
for 17 others.
</P>
<P>
   Perez and other board members said they had not discussed which
rap stars might be banned. But he said the board would, in all
likelihood, enact far-reaching changes in September when it gathers
to plan next year's festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop industry insiders, rap fans and Assemblyman Ruben Diaz
of the Bronx, whose district includes the Bronx River Houses where
rap was born, said they thought Perez's contentions were misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love rap music, and I didn't grow up hassling women,'' said
Diaz, a regular parade participant whose parents were born in
Puerto Rico. ``Somebody who says rap music or hip-hop is not a part
of Puerto Rican culture would be sadly mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   Rap's energy and street-wise message, supporters said, resonates
deeply among Puerto Rican youth, just as it does among young
African-Americans. And Puerto Rican performers like Fat Joe,
Noriega and the late Big Pun have become mainstream stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as saying hip-hop artists are not part of the Puerto
Rican tradition, they're crazy,'' said Vee Bravo, an editor of
Stress, a Queens-based rap magazine that has had a parade float
carrying rap artists since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's censorship if they go ahead and do this,'' said
Bravo, who is of Chilean descent. Fat Joe, whose given name is
Joseph Cartagena, said he and other rappers have long believed that
parade organizers fail to embrace them.
</P>
<P>
   The National Puerto Rican Day Parade, a New York institution
since 1958, is embraced by hundreds of thousands of Puerto Ricans
who enjoy the annual chance to express pride in their cultural
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   But the parade, for many, is also about advertising and
promotion, attracting politicians like Hillary Rodham Clinton and
Rep. Rick Lazio, corporations selling everything from Internet
sites to coffee to corn oil, and musicians looking to connect with
Puerto Rican youth. So for years, the parade has attracted rappers
and hip-hop D.J.'s, Latin and African-American, who pay for their
own floats or are sponsored by radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the parade's board members said they foresaw a ban on
rappers. Carlos Velasquez, who oversees marketing for the board,
said old rules might be dusted off to prohibit obscenities in
lyrics and the practice of throwing merchandise from rap floats,
which promotes rowdy behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
