<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WEIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON WEIS, 78, FILM AND TELEVISION DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Wis.)   (editors: in reference to ``M.A.S.H,'' replace points with
asterisks)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Weis, an award-winning director whose long career embraced
both film and television, died on July 26 in Santa Fe, N.M. He was
78.
</P>
<P>
   Weis' screen career began at MGM, where he first found work
after serving as an Air Force film technician during World War II.
His film credits include ``Just This Once'' (1952), ``Half a Hero''
with Red Skelton (1953), ``The Affairs of Dobie Gillis'' with
Debbie Reynolds and Bobby Van (1953), ``The Gene Krupa Story''
(1959), ``Critic's Choice'' with Bob Hope and Lucille Ball (1963)
and ``Billie'' (1965), starring Patty Duke, for which he also
served as producer.
</P>
<P>
   When he turned to television, Weis quickly became one of its
busiest directors.
</P>
<P>
   He directed dozens of episodes of popular series like
``Suspense,'' ``The Twilight Zone,'' ``Alfred Hitchcock Presents,''
``Perry Mason,'' ``The Love Boat'' and ``Fantasy Island.'' In the
1970s he directed more than 40 episodes of ``M.AS.H.''
</P>
<P>
   His work earned him six awards from the Directors Guild of
America as best television director of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Milwaukee, Weis was a graduate of the University of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the actress Rebecca Welles; two
daughters, Deborah Weis and Pamela Landrum; a stepdaughter,
Elizabeth Welles; and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2386 &Cx1f; tad-z
b p BC-CVN-GOP-BUSH04-COX     08-03 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-BUSH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH DOESN'T SOAR, BUT DELIVERS HIS MESSAGE
 &HT;    830&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The message, competently delivered by a candidate
not destined for the oratory hall of fame, was simple and direct:
Meet the new boss. Different than the old boss.
</P>
<P>
   Riding high in the polls and taking a last shot at making a
first impression with voters, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas accepted
the Republican presidential nomination Thursday night with a speech
that was part core issues and part character.
</P>
<P>
   In a jubilant First Union Center, Bush gave the most important
speech of his life to as friendly and enthusiastic a crowd as he
will see between now and Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had them at ``Mr. Chairman,'' the speech's opening line,
which he had to say four times to get going. He was interrupted by
cheers 100 times during a 55-minute speech that led to a
convention-ending celebration.
</P>
<P>
   True to his style, Bush, who is engaging and animated
one-on-one, stood relatively motionless during most of the speech,
resting his clasped hands between the bottom two rings of the
three-ring binder that held the crucial address.
</P>
<P>
   He used the home-field advantage to its fullest by including
couldn't-miss jabs against President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore, his November foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current president embodied the potential of a generation.
So many talents. So much charm. Such great skill. But, in the end,
to what end? So much promise, to no great purpose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled throughout the speech were code-word efforts to get
this point across: Although Bush is a multimillionaire now trying
to turn the presidency into something of a family business, he
wants Americans to think of him as the nice man next door with the
charming wife and the engaging twin daughters.
</P>
<P>
   He chided Gore as a man who sees issues through the prism of
Washington, ``always seeing the tunnel at the end of the light.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I come from a different place, and it has made me a
different leader,'' said Bush. ``In Midland, Texas, where I grew
up, the town motto was `the sky is the limit' and we believed it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That background may lack the polish of Washington. Then again,
I don't have a lot of things that come with Washington,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hit hard on his baseline issues, but he _ in terms more
subtle than vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney's full-frontal
assault Wednesday night - also talked about character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have enemies to fight,'' he said, ``and I have no
stake in the bitter arguments of the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who often chides his own generation as too heavy on ``if
it feels good, do it,'' said fellow baby boomer Clinton has failed
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation has a chance to reclaim some essential values.
To show we have grown up before we grow old., But when the moment
for leadership came, this administration did not teach our
children, it disillusioned them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, polls show the Bush message, embodied in his speech and
performed here for four nights this week, is working. Nightly
polling by Voter.com-Battleground shows Bush now has a comfortable
18-point lead over Gore among independents, a key group. Bush also
has a six-point lead among women, a group Gore must have to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message of the convention does seem to be coming across,
said Republican pollster Ed Goeas, who conducted the survey with
Democratic pollster Celinda Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will get his shot at a convention bounce later this month
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention floor here, Bush's speech got high grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think America is falling in love with him,'' said
21-year-old delegate Bill Raskind of Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Tracey Edge of North Myrtle Beach, S.C. said the speech
delineated the differences between the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is taking the issues that are on the mind of the American
people, and that is education and taxes,'' said Edge, a state
lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, experts disagreed on the grade earned by Bush. Two
political scientists who have followed the campaign said Bush has
improved, but they disagreed on how much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely more comfortable and seems quite believable.
These's no evidence of hesitancy,'' said University of Texas
professor Bruce Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said Bush touched on many of the same themes as he did
during his campaign, but repackaged them effectively to present to
a national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   University of Iowa professor Arthur Miller was less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take this speech tonight and compare it with the speech
he gave at the Iowa straw poll a year ago, it's better but it's not
tremendously better,'' Miller said. ``It doesn't seem to come
across with any enthusiasm or fire.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the address as ``very safe speech,'' offering no
</P>
<P>
   new campaign themes or bold political initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, it added up to a solid showing for Bush, for whom
big-hall speaking has been a weakness. His State of the State
speeches have done a journeyman job of laying out his priorities,
but never attracted more than routine, appropriate applause.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Bush - who possesses a quick mind and
sometimes quicker tongue - tends to cruise on autopilot during
speeches. One-on-one and small-group mingles have been his campaign
trail bread-and-butter.
</P>
<P>
   An early foray into big-league speaking went poorly three years
ago when he was merely a big-state governor and rising star of the
GOP. Bush, who turned down most out-of-state speaking appearances
until he became a full-fledged presidential candidate, went to
Indianapolis to speak at the Republicans' Midwest Leadership
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP audience of 1,500 people gave him passing grades on
content - he criticized the Clinton administration's handling of a
welfare issue - but far lower grades on delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had a good message. But I thought the
presentation as a little weak,'' Ed Mueller of Laporte, Ind., said
that day, summing up what became conventional wisdom of Bush the
public speaker.
</P>
<P>
   A woman in the audience that day said she also wasn't overly
impressed with the performance, but something caught her eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he may just be the next nominee,'' said Glenna Stephen
of Redkey, Ind. ``He seems different than the rest, so I want to
hear what he has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman's e-mail address is kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
