<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH DOESN'T SOAR, BUT DELIVERS HIS MESSAGE
 &HT;    Eds: Redits to shorten and move up some material.
 &HT;    600&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The message, competently delivered by a candidate
not destined for the oratory hall of fame, was simple and direct:
Meet the new boss. Different than the old boss.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, riding high in the polls and
taking his last shot at making a first impression with voters,
accepted the Republican presidential nomination Thursday night with
a speech that emphasized both core issues and character.
</P>
<P>
   In a jubilant First Union Center, Bush gave the most important
speech of his life to as friendly and enthusiastic a crowd as he
will see between now and Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   While political experts gave the speech mixed grades, Bush had
the crowd at ``Mr. Chairman,'' the speech's opening line _ which he
had to say four times to get going.
</P>
<P>
   He was interrupted by cheers 100 times during a 55-minute
delivery that led to a convention-ending celebration.
</P>
<P>
   He used the home-field advantage to its fullest by including
couldn't-miss jabs against President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore, his November foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current president embodied the potential of a generation.
So many talents. So much charm. Such great skill. But, in the end,
to what end? So much promise, to no great purpose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled throughout the speech were code-word efforts to get
this point across: Although Bush is a multimillionaire now trying
to turn the presidency into something of a family business, he
wants Americans to think of him as the nice man next door with the
charming wife and the engaging twin daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hit hard on his baseline issues, but he _ in terms more
subtle than vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney's full-frontal
assault Wednesday night - also talked about character.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said fellow baby boomer Clinton has failed the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation has a chance to reclaim some essential values.
To show we have grown up before we grow old., But when the moment
for leadership came, this administration did not teach our
children, it disillusioned them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   True to his style, Bush, who is engaging and animated
one-on-one, stood relatively motionless during most of the speech,
resting his clasped hands between the bottom two rings of the
three-ring binder that held the crucial address.
</P>
<P>
   On the convention floor here, Bush's speech got high grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think America is falling in love with him,'' said
21-year-old delegate Bill Raskind of Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Tracey Edge of North Myrtle Beach, S.C. said the speech
delineated the differences between the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is taking the issues that are on the mind of the American
people, and that is education and taxes,'' said Edge, a state
lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, experts disagreed on the grade earned by Bush. Two
political scientists who have followed the campaign said Bush has
improved, but they disagreed on how much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely more comfortable and seems quite believable.
These's no evidence of hesitancy,'' said University of Texas
professor Bruce Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said Bush touched on many of the same themes as he did
during his campaign, but repackaged them effectively for a national
television audience.
</P>
<P>
   University of Iowa professor Arthur Miller was less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take this speech tonight and compare it with the speech
he gave at the Iowa straw poll a year ago, it's better, but it's
not tremendously better,'' Miller said. ``It doesn't seem to come
across with any enthusiasm or fire.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the address as ``very safe speech,'' offering no
</P>
<P>
   new campaign themes or bold political initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Over all, it added up to a solid showing for Bush, for whom
big-hall speaking has been a weakness. His State of the State
speeches have done a journeyman job of laying out his priorities,
but never attracted more than routine, appropriate applause.
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Bush - who possesses a quick mind and
sometimes quicker tongue - tends to cruise on autopilot during
speeches. One-on-one and small-group mingles have been his campaign
trail bread and butter.
</P>
<P>
   An early foray into big-league speaking went poorly thre years
ago when he was merely a big-state governor and rising star of the
GOP. Bush, who turned down most out-of-state speaking appearances
until he became a full-fledged presidential candidate, went to
Indianapolis to speak at the Republicans' Midwest Leadership
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP audience of 1,500 people gave him passing grades on
