<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA BROADENS ITS CASE AGAINST SUSPECTED HACKER  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Prosecutors on Thursday broadened their case against
a suspected teen-age hacker, adding dozens of charges that accuse
the boy of paralyzing several of the most popular World Wide Web
sites in the United States beginning on Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police has evidence that the boy, who
turned 16 on July 17, is responsible for attacks on the Web sites
of Yahoo, Amazon, AtLaw, eBay and Dell, said Staff Sgt. Jean-Pierre
Roy.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the prosecutor in the case, Louis Miville-Deschenes,
charged the boy with three counts of criminal mischief related to
attacks on the CNN Web site. On Thursday, he added 64 criminal
charges related to attacks on the other five sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have direct evidence that places him behind the
computer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, who under Canadian law cannot be identified but who
prosecutors say uses the online name Mafiaboy, made his first
appearance in youth court Thursday as his lawyer entered a plea of
not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Miville-Deschenes said that he was ``prosecuting this case as a
deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy added that police were now working on at least 20 other
computer-related cases. Although more arrests are expected, he said
that there was no evidence of accomplices in the Mafiaboy case.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier reports had linked the Mafiaboy name to a cybergang
called TNT, some of whose members are accused of stealing credit
card information belonging to Internet shoppers. But Roy said no
personal information about users of the victim sites was
compromised. ``It was strictly denial of service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miville-Deschenes acknowledged, however, that sealed court files
contains information that could prove harmful to some of the
corporations that it names.
</P>
<P>
   A distributed denial of service attack like the ones Mafiaboy is
said to have committed involves bombarding a Web site's computers
with thousands of useless messages a minute. The huge volume makes
it impossible to serve legitimate users. The attacker does not do
this directly. Rather, he uses telephone lines to gain access to
large computers linked to the Internet and then programs these
computers to send the deluge of useless data, multiplying the
congestion and masking the source of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Mafiaboy is suspected of using at least 54 computers to stage
his attacks. Most belonged to universities, including the
University of California at Santa Barbara. Roy said the suspect
also used at least two computers in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   If the event of a conviction, the maximum penalty the suspect
could face as a juvenile under Canadian law is two years in custody
and a fine of $1,000. In addition, the criminal record could be
wiped clean five years after the sentence was served.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could have been more than 100 charges,'' Roy said. ``We
decided to set a limit. We don't see why we should add more
charges. There is no reason to go further to identify more
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the prosecutor and the suspect's lawyer agreed that the
trial could last three to four months. ``This will be the longest
youth court trial ever,'' Miville-Deschenes said. He added that the
police collected 50 days of digital and telephone wiretap evidence
and that each day of wiretapping consumes 40 hours of testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Police questioned the boy about the attacks two months before
arresting him in April, before the investigation was complete.
</P>
<P>
   The hacking trial is scheduled for Sept. 28. The suspect is free
on bail but is prohibited from using a computer except at school,
and then only for academic purposes with supervision. He may not
connect to the Internet or go to any establishment that rents or
sells computers. He is subject to a curfew of midnight to 7 a.m.
unless accompanied by a specified adult, except when he works a
late shift at a local restaurant.
</P>
</TEXT>
