<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   CZECH REPUBLIC: JEWISH CEMETERY
</P>
<P>
   The government has been sued in the European Court of Human
Rights in a dispute over how to preserve a 13th-century Jewish
burial ground on the Prague site where an insurance company is
building its headquarters. The suit was brought by the Committee
for the Preservation of Jewish Cemeteries despite a March agreement
between the government and local Jews on encasing the cemetery in
concrete, and building above and below it.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: NEW RULES FOR TROOPS
</P>
<P>
   Washington and Seoul agreed to revise a treaty to give South
Korea greater jurisdiction over U.S. military personnel suspected
of crimes. Previously, suspects remained in U.S. custody until
their trials in South Korean courts ended. Now, they will be turned
over the Korean authorities when indicted.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR: TRUCE RULES
</P>
<P>
   Indian officials and leaders of the anti-India militant group
Hizbul Mujahedeen agreed to set up negotiating teams to set up the
ground rules for a three-month cease-fire announced last week by
the militants. These are the first talks between India and the
rebels since an insurgency began in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: LENGTHY FARM OCCUPATIONS SEEN
</P>
<P>
   One day after President Robert Mugabe announced that black
squatters would probably leave many white-owned farms within a
month, a government spokesman said the process might take
considerably longer. Jonathan Moyo, said the squatters would not
leave until 2 million acres of farmland had been acquired, a
process that could take more than a year.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
