<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-STATE-DEPARTMENT-SECU     08-03 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-DEPARTMENT-SECURITY-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPARTMENT SEEKS $300 MILLION TO IMPROVE SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three months after Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright declared herself ``humiliated'' by lax security at her
department, manifested in one case by the loss of a laptop computer
with classified information, officials there are seeking $300
million to upgrade its headquarters and hire 900 new employees,
most of them security agents.
</P>
<P>
   Those officials, in charge of the department's security, say the
money is needed to protect intelligence and diplomatic secrets in a
culture that has long resisted strict controls. They intend to ask
for three annual $100 million increments, the first of them next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Their plans include overhauling the electronic turnstiles at the
main entrances, using ``biometric'' devices that scan human
features like the eyeball to control access to the most secret
areas and raising the number of diplomatic security agents to
1,500, a 50 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   The financing request, being drawn up by David G. Carpenter, the
department's top security official, is a response to recent highly
publicized breaches at headquarters. One was the disappearance in
February of the laptop computer containing highly classified files.
The FBI is still looking into the loss of the laptop and has issued
no finding as to whether it was misplaced or stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Two months before the laptop's disappearance, investigators
discovered an electronic eavesdropping device in a conference room,
prompting the Clinton administration to expel a Russian diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it,'' Carpenter said in an interview, ``we've been
on fire with a couple of incidents. We see ourselves as a target''
of foreign adversaries, ``and we see it as prudent to go beyond
what our fellow agencies are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the security lapses stirred an outcry on Capitol Hill,
administration and congressional officials predict that the new
financing request will meet opposition from a number of Republican
lawmakers. Some Republicans tend to resist any increased financing
for the State Department, while others maintain that the solution
to this particular problem may have more to do with altering
attitudes about security than with replacing hardware.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican critic of the department, Rep. Benjamin Gilman of
New York, chairman of the House International Relations Committee,
said he would ``carefully examine'' the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I am not willing to just throw money at the problem,''
Gilman said. ``It will also take a change in the culture of
indifference to security at our State Department and an end to the
naive belief that there are no real enemies of our nation in the
post-Cold War era.''
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations being made by Carpenter stem from his review of
department security practices, an effort that was assisted by
experts from the Pentagon, the FBI and the Secret Service, and
included the long-term loan of an adviser from the Central
Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   After the laptop incident, Albright stripped her intelligence
bureau of its right to police itself and said she would promote
Carpenter, a former Secret Service agent, to a newly created post
of under secretary for security. (Not yet elevated, he remains an
assistant secretary.) Since then, officials said, about 7,000
department employees have been freshly briefed on security
procedures, uniformed guards have been assigned to patrol the halls
in search of unescorted visitors, and employees have completed
surveys to outline their need to handle classified information.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some diplomats have privately groused at the measures. Unlike
many of their colleagues at the intelligence agencies, those
involved in diplomatic work are necessarily in regular contact with
the outside world. The State Department's headquarters welcomes
roughly 1,000 visitors a day.
</P>
<P>
   Within that stream of visitors, about one in seven represents a
foreign government, officials say. Moreover, 97 foreign journalists
have direct access to the building. Timothy D. Bereznay, an FBI
section chief, told lawmakers in May that some journalists were
``hostile intelligence officers.'' But Bereznay did not elaborate
on that assertion, and Albright made light of it.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the department recently tightened its escort
policy to prevent visitors from roaming the building freely, and to
restrict journalists to areas of the first two floors unless they
have escorts as well.
</P>
<P>
   Further, officials have already allocated $5 million toward
overhauling the building's turnstile entrances. The new system will
require department employees to punch in a personal identification
number, or PIN, in addition to swiping their identity cards past an
electronic eye. Under the current system, a stolen card could be
used to gain entry, since no PIN is required.
</P>
<P>
   Department experts have also been exploring the possibility of
closing down streets adjacent to the building. In addition to
providing a buffer against armed attack, a closed street would give
security agents the space to search vehicles before they enter the
building's underground parking garage for employees. Currently,
only delivery vehicles are inspected.
</P>
<P>
   But, security officials said, the District of Columbia has e
vigorously opposed shutting down streets in an area where traffic
is already commonly snarled by motorcades, bridge traffic and
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
