<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUST-COMPANY-DEALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BESSEMER TRUST TO ADD KEY BUSINESSES OF RIVAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., Calif.)  By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the oldest firms in the business of managing
money for wealthy families, the Bessemer Trust Co., will announce
Friday that it is buying the private-client and
institutional-equity groups of a rival, Brundage, Story &AMP; Rose,
executives of the firms said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the firms, which are privately held, would disclose
the terms of the deal. But executives of the firms said the deal
would add $4.5 billion in assets under management and about 800
clients to Bessemer, which has $33 billion under management and
1,300 clients.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette said Thursday that it was buying
the other of Brundage, Story's three units, its institutional
fixed-income division with $3.3 billion in assets under management.
The terms of that deal were also not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   With the transactions, the Brundage name will disappear from
Wall Street 68 years after the firm was founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transaction is significant in that it allows Bessemer to
gain size and scale,'' said Henry McVey, a Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality,'' he said, ``is that many of the large commercial
and investment banks are now pushing into this market, and the
independent players need to bulk up.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. said it would buy the U.S.
Trust Co., and just last month Alliance Capital Management, which
is controlled by the French financial services holding company AXA
Group, bought Sanford C. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Moszkowski, a financial analyst at Salomon Smith Barney
said, ``This is another manifestation of the need to be at a
certain minimum scale to maximize your economics in an environment
where more technology investment is needed every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis S. Branin, the chief executive of Brundage, Story,
acknowledged that size was an issue. ``We felt that longer term, it
was probably going to be more and more difficult for medium-size
firms like ours to compete across a broad range of services,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides investing its clients' money in blue-chip stocks like
General Electric, Intel and Home Depot, Bessemer also offers
investments in leveraged buyouts, venture capital and real estate
limited partnership funds. It also provides estate- and
tax-planning services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wealthy individuals want the services Bessemer has,'' said
Branin, who will join the larger firm along with seven partners.
Apart from managing the affairs of his former clients, Branin said,
his position, and those of his old partners, in Bessemer have not
been determined.
</P>
<P>
   For Bessemer, the transaction was ``an opportunity for us to add
some very talented private-client services and investment
professionals,'' said Donald J. Herrema, the chief executive of the
larger firm.
</P>
<P>
   Business has been booming at Bessemer, and it needed more
employees quickly. Its assets under management have more than
tripled over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Bessemer was founded in 1907 as the family office of Henry
Phipps, a partner of Andrew Carnegie in the Carnegie Steel Co. Its
purpose was to invest the $50 million Phipps received in the sale
of the steel business to J.P. Morgan. In 1974, the family decided
to take on outside clients.
</P>
<P>
   Bessemer added Miami to its New York and Palm Beach offices in
1981 and now does business in eight cities. It opened an Atlanta
office last year and expects to open one in Silicon Valley in the
next few months.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum investment with Bessemer is $5 million. The average
client's portfolio is worth $22 million, executives said, and there
are several dozen with investments of more than $100 million.
Brundage, Story's minimum was $1 million and the average portfolio
was worth $5 million to $10 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0462 </DOCNO>
