<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-$ADV06-613&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER PT CRUISER, FORD FOCUS ZX3 RATE POORLY IN CRASH TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6.)  
 By CHERYL JENSEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the nation's most popular new vehicles, the Chrysler PT
Cruiser and Ford Focus ZX3, have fared badly in government crash
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The PT Cruiser received what amounts to a poor rating _ two
stars of a possible five _ for its ability to protect the head of a
driver wearing a safety belt in a front collision, according to
results released recently by the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration. The two-door Focus ZX3 got just one star _ the
lowest possible rating _ for protecting a rear passenger in a side
crash.
</P>
<P>
   The safety agency conducts crash tests on new or popular models.
In the front test, vehicles are run at 35 mph into a solid barrier,
replicating a head-on crash between vehicles of the same size and
weight. In the side test, a movable, crushable barrier _ designed
to crumple like a car _ is rammed into the test vehicle at 38.5
mph.
</P>
<P>
   For the front tests, a five-star rating indicates a 10 percent
or less chance of serious injury. The two-star rating for the PT
Cruiser's driver indicates a 36 to 45 percent chance of serious
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The rating for the front passenger was four stars, meaning that
there was only an 11 to 20 percent chance of serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   In side-impact testing, a five-star rating means the vehicle has
a 5 percent or less chance of a life-threatening chest injury. The
Focus coupe's one-star rating represents a 26 percent or greater
chance of serious injury to a rear-seat passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Focus coupe and PT Cruiser scored better at protecting
other occupants.
</P>
<P>
   The PT Cruiser get four stars for protecting the front passenger
in a front crash, four stars for the driver in a side crash and
five stars for a passenger behind the driver. The Focus ZX3 got
five stars for both driver and passenger in a front crash and four
stars for the front passenger in a side impact.
</P>
<P>
   The Focus sedan did better over all, with four stars for driver
and front passenger in a front impact; four stars for the rear
passenger in a side crash, and three stars for a front occupant in
a side crash. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised by the one star,'' said Sara Tatchio, a Ford
safety spokeswoman. ``We did closely look at the test itself, and
we are not challenging it in any way. But it is not at all what our
internal testing showed, so our work is ongoing to figure out what
the differential is.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nor is DaimlerChrysler satisfied with the PT Cruiser's score.
``We are clearly a little disappointed with our two-star rating,''
said Daniel Knott, director of vehicle development for small cars,
who managed the development of the PT Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to note that if NHTSA gave decimal
points, we would be a 2.9 star,'' he said. If the head injury score
had been 50 points lower, he said, ``it would have been a three
star'' _ the rating suggested by the company's own testing.
</P>
<P>
   By measuring the forces on crash dummies, the agency comes up
with scores indicating the severity of injuries. A head-injury
score of 1,000 indicates the likelihood of serious trauma, like a
skull fracture; the PT Cruiser's score was 1,080 for the driver and
467 for the front passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hurd, a spokesman for the safety agency, said that despite
deployment of the Chrysler's air bag, the driver dummy's head
appeared to hit the steering wheel hard enough to bend it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Knott of DaimlerChrysler said that head-injury scores could vary
by as much 100 points, and thus the PT Cruiser could have received
three stars. But Hurd said his agency tries to remove any
variability from testing. If there is any variation in results, he
suggested, it could stem from how a car is manufactured.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Crash tests use a standard test protocol and are ``very
reproducible,'' said Julie Rochman of the Insurance Institute for
Highway Safety, which conducts its own tests but has not yet
crashed either the Focus or PT Cruiser. ``If you do the same test
you should see the same result,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   R. David Pittle, senior vice president and technical director of
Consumers Union, publisher of Consumer Reports, said the PT
Cruiser's score was a blow to a vehicle that has taken America by
storm. ``I think consumers would be rightfully concerned about the
safety of the driver position that only got a `2' in this frontal
crash test,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For DaimlerChrysler, the poor showing was a second embarrassment
from the testing. The company got unwanted publicity when the
agency had to pay huge premiums to obtain two of the hot-selling PT
Cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   The agency quietly buys from dealers. Although list prices range
from $16,000 to $20,000, the agency had to pay $27,500 and $31,055,
highlighting what consumers were calling price gouging by dealers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very popular vehicle,'' Hurd said. ``My wife says
it's cute. My 16-year-old daughter says it's cute. Buyers are
paying premiums, and we paid a premium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-03-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000803.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-03 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2406 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TOKYO-TEX     08-03 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TOKYO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ADJUSTING TO TOKYO TIME, SMALL BEDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The hotel is huge. The beds are small.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Cowboys players and coaches are enjoying
their stay at the very futuristic Tokyo Dome Hotel, a
two-month-old, 43-story high-rise located downtown and within a
9-iron shot of the Tokyo Dome, aka the Big Egg.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the Cowboys and Atlanta Falcons will meet in Japan's
American Bowl game, 9 p.m., CDT, tomorrow, inside a bustling,
baseball-oriented restaurant and amusement district appropriately
named Tokyo Dome City.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys strongside linebacker Darren Hambrick, a first-time
visitor to Japan, couldn't sleep and was in the hotel lobby by 6:30
a.m., Tokyo time, Friday. After all, his body clock told him it was
4:30 p.m. Thursday in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rooms are really nice ... but the bed is hard,'' said
Hambrick, who found that if you're NFL player-size, you need to
find the proper technique to sleep in these Japanese twin-size beds
that are only two inches off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to hop down in it real quick, then roll into it with
your knee,'' Hambrick said.
</P>
<P>
   This is a ``business trip,'' said Cowboys first-year head coach
Dave Campo, who wants his team to learn how to get its focus on the
road, where the Cowboys have lost eight consecutive
regular-season/postseason road games and seven consecutive
preseason road games.
</P>
<P>
   Campo acknowledges that it's a long way to go _ 6,420 miles _ to
teach his players a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they've got to be able to handle the distractions,'' he
said. ``This isn't exactly a replica \Rof a typical NFL road
trip\S, but it'll give us something to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have played more game abroad than any team in the
league, including the first American Bowl game (1986 vs. Chicago in
London). The Cowboys, however, are 0-6-1, including 0-1 in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Campo had them practice in shoulder pads and helmets Thursday
night (Friday afternoon, Tokyo time) inside the Big Egg, a
21/2-hour workout in front of the Japanese media. The Falcons stay
at the same hotel and work out before of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   These two teams are quite different in media coverage. The
Cowboys are represented by both major newspapers from Fort Worth
and Dallas, plus TV reporters from all four major networks. The
Falcons are being followed by one sportswriter and one TV reporter
from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Players and coaches are fed American food at their respective
team training tables, which means that (aside from those small,
low, hard beds) there is little to complain about until the 12-hour
flight back home.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,007-room Toyko Dome Hotel is posh, to say the least. It
has the enormous feel of an air and space museum, sort of George
Jetson meets Baron Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside the glass elevators that overlook the amusement
section of Tokyo Dome City is a parachute ride that climbs 30
stories, then quickly plunges toward the ground, making the
elevator ride seem slow ... and safe.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's mostly septic-white decor is set against a
background of fancy restaurants, botanical gardens and attentive
hotel workers who are eager to bridge the obvious language barrier
to try to answer questions and provide information to guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the benefit of being with the Dallas Cowboys,''
defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban said. ``Our popularity is known
around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Daily Yomiuri'', the local English-written newspaper,
carried a story in its Friday editions about this game primarily
from the Cowboys' perspective, including a picture of Emmitt Smith
being greeted at Narita Airport.
</P>
<P>
   This is the rainy season in Tokyo. The weather, not unlike
Wichita Falls, is hot and humid. By 6 a.m., the commuters began to
fill the highways around Tokyo Dome City on their way to work, and
the smog slowly began to burn off in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Hambrick found when he tried to hail a taxi in
front of the hotel at 6:30 a.m., but he couldn't get the driver to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrick laughed and walked back inside.
</P>
<P>
   He was just happy to be out of bed.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
