<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFECO-EXECS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TOP EXECUTIVES OUT AS SAFECO SAYS IT'S TIME FOR CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    First name Boh in 7th pgh is correct
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ One of the pillars of Seattle's financial house
shuddered yesterday, as Safeco Corp. announced the upcoming
departure of its chairman, Roger Eigsti, and the immediate exit of
its top property and casualty official, Randy Stoddard.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, Seattle-based Safeco has struggled
with sagging earnings, a stock price that has lost more than half
of its value, difficult market conditions and the digestion of a
major acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   So corporate leaders Thursday said it was time for a change,
issuing a blunt statement saying Eigsti, the company's chief
executive officer, will retire at the end of the year, while
Stoddard, president of Safeco Property &AMP; Casualty companies, will
resign immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that a different style of leadership and executive
involvement is required to restore Safeco to its historic levels of
profitability,'' William Reed Jr., the lead independent director
for Safeco's Board of Directors, said in the statement. ``The
directors had been disappointed with Safeco's financial performance
for several quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   The move comes only 10 days after Safeco reported its
second-quarter earnings plunged 77 percent, due in part to unusual
losses related to storms. The decline was the latest in a series of
disappointing financial performances from the 77-year-old financial
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Only three months ago, Safeco said its first-quarter operating
earnings dropped 76 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco president and chief operating officer Boh Dickey will
take over for Stoddard and also vie for the chief executive officer
slot. The company plans to look inside and outside its ranks for
its next leader.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it may be time for a change. While Safeco is
recovering from its problems, the injection of new leadership could
bolster the effort, according to one analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the turnaround in the company is really in place. . .
. The speed of the recovery is still open to both change and
question,'' said Daniel Nelson, who tracks Safeco for the
Seattle-based investment firm Ragen MacKenzie Group Inc. ``(The
board) needed to send a message that it was minding the store
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street appeared to receive the message, sending Safeco
shares up $3.13, or 14.25 percent, to close at $25.06 in trading
Thursday. The surge stood in stark contrast to the recent
performance of Safeco's stock. The company's stock price has
plummeted from $55 on March 20, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Eigsti and Stoddard caps two Safeco careers
that spanned three decades. Eigsti joined the company in 1972 and
Stoddard came aboard a year later. Eigsti took over as chief
executive officer in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco officials declined to discuss any severance package being
offered to either executive, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials praised Eigsti's performance, but they added
it could be time for a fresh management style.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not been a hands-on, interfering type of manager. Some
greater degree of involvement would help the company take advantage
of the strategic moves that Mr. Eigsti is responsible (for),''
Safeco's Reed said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the company wants to improve certain key
operations, including ensuring they charge proper rates and prices
and cut expense ratios, according to Safeco officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of getting back to the basic things that we do well,''
Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco has also struggled to digest the largest acquisition in
its history, the $2.8 billion purchase of American States Financial
Corp. in 1997. While Reed said the purchase created some
distractions, one analyst said the insurer could have handled the
process better.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't assimilate American States anywhere near as well
as they could have,'' said Ragen MacKenzie's Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, board members will search for a new chief
executive officer. Dickey has emerged as a strong candidate,
although officials promised to conduct a broad search.
</P>
<P>
   ``New blood could reinvigorate the company,'' wrote Paul Latta,
an analyst with McAdams Wright Ragen Inc., in a report. He added
that Dickey offers a style that differs from Eigsti.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey said in an interview with Bloomberg News that Safeco will
increase insurance rates and cut expenses as part of a plan to
increase corporate earnings. Safeco also hopes to record a
healthier financial performance in the third quarter, Dickey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
