<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRETT EXPECTS MUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I sidled up to the USC athletic director Mike Garrett Thursday
at the Pac-10 football media gathering Thursday and wisecracked,
``Are you going to fire Paul Hackett if he goes 6-6 again?'' as
Hackett was at the podium giving his state-of-the-Trojans address.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Garrett shook his head, frowned and coolly ignored the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a tremendously talented team and I think we're
going to have a good year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what if the Trojans have another flameout under Hackett,
whose two-year log at USC stands at a mediocre 14-11?
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very disappointing if we don't have a good year,''
warned Garrett. . . .
</P>
<P>
   To listen to the optimism spewed by the 10 coaches at the annual
shindig held at the Gateway Sheraton near LAX, you'd think every
Pac-10 school actually has a legitimate chance to spend Jan. 1 at
the Rose Bowl, which is simply not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it'll all be roses this season, but I can't
envi &QL; 
- sion us going through what we did last year,'' said UCLA coach
Bob Toledo, whose Bruins wound up 4-7. ``I don't think we should be
evaluated by what happened last year. It was just so freaky because
of the suspensions and injuries. The season seemed to fall apart
after we played the opener against Ohio State with 11 of our
players on suspension.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Bruins, according to Toledo, will be
beefier and stronger this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players put on a total of 600 pounds since last season and
set 90 personal new records in the weight training room,'' related
Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Toledo still might not have a worthy successor to Cade
McNown at quarterback, since two guys who weren't faintly up for
the part last fall, sophomores Ryan McCann and Cory Paus, are once
again competing for the starting position. . .
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hackett, on senior running back Petros Papadakis: ``We
missed his leadership badly when he got hurt (foot injury) a year
ago. He's really focused, and I expect him to have a great season.
He's a madman.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like his fabled father, Big John Papadakis, the former USC
star linebacker and San Pedro restaurateur who now packs 300 pounds
on his 6- foot-1 frame. . .
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising Dodger development this season just might be
the sudden batting surge of shortstop Alex Cora. We all knew Cora
could field, but few thought he could hit in the stout manner he
has in recent weeks. . .
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line with Shawn Green is that he's been a
disappointment with the Dodgers. Sure, he's driven in 73 runs, but
guys earning $14 million a year should be batting above .277 and
should have more than 18 home runs in this HR-crazed season. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Dodger general manager, Kevin Malone, is like Fred Claire in
one respect. As savagely as you knock him, he'll still greet you
with a smile and a handshake. Just like Tom Lasorda does. . .
</P>
<P>
   Never has so much been said about someone as inconsequential to
a football telecast as Dennis Miller. . . .
</P>
<P>
   I'd gladly work for Donald Sterling if he were willing to give
me $8 million across four years, which he was willing to do with
Cincinnati's Bob Huggins. Huggins was a fool to turn down such an
offer, especially considering the array of promising young talent
on the Clippers' roster. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Did you know Donald Sterling's alter ego, Andy Roeser, resides
in Belmont Shore?. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Will someone please explain to me why Carlos Perez still is in
the major leagues?
</P>
<P>
   Sat down the other day with Pine Ave. pioneer John Morris, and
we wistfully reflected on how the Long Beach politicians squandered
an opportunity of a lifetime in the early 1990s to build a football
stadium here that would have lured an NFL franchise. At least these
great visionaries did build a multi million dollar aquarium to lure
a bunch of exotic fish to our community. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The bright new Bonus Baby on our sports staff, Sir Clint
Olivier, isn't related to the late Sir Lawrence Olivier, although
he pronounces his surname the same way. . .
</P>
<P>
   Phil Trani's apprentice chef, Jason Kapono, has packed eight
pounds of new muscle on his 6-foot-7 frame this summer working
under the guidance of the Westwood fitness guru to the stars, Todd
Person. The UCLA sophomore now weighs 203.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Trani has had a lot of celebrities at his North
Long Beach bisto over the years, but none caused heads to turn as
dramatically as did the recent presence of Elizabeth Hurley, the
English sex godess and former boyfriend of Hugh Grant. . .
</P>
<P>
   My pal Dave Marshall, the nationally respected security chief of
the Queen Mary and former major league outfielder with the San
Francisco Giants and New York Mets, recently enjoyed a reunion with
his 1961 Lakewood High classmates. Long-time Met scout Harry Minor
tells me Marshall could have played in the NFL as a running back
had he pursued football. . .
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Lakewood High, one of its English teachers,
Kind-Hearted Kandi Boscon, former Cypress High bowling champion, is
picking up some loose change these sweltering days reciting poetry
and mixing beverages back at the Fish Tale. . .
</P>
<P>
   Butterfields is billing its massive memorabilia auction on Aug.
12 at Dodger Stadium as the as the Sale of the Century in which the
$20 admission fare will go toward Tony La Russa's Animal Rescue
Foundation (ARF).
</P>
<P>
   I'm definitely going to be there, since the 18th home run from
Mark McGwire's record- setting 70-HR season in 1998 will be
auctioned, along with the lineup cards La Russa used with the St.
Louis Cardinals on the evenings McGwire drilled his 500th and 501st
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   How can I continue enduring this cruel world without those
mementos in my overflowing trophy case?. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Kahn &AMP; Lamb, not to be confused with Martin &AMP; Lewis or even
Zeidler &AMP; Zeidler, continue their historic swath through the radio
airways, having just signed a three-year contract to do the Arena
Bowl, not to be confused with the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   You might remember that Larry Kahn and Mike Lamb once did the
USC football play- by-play on radio and have handled similar duties
this season for the Los Angeles Avengers of the Arena Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   The versatile Kahn, who recently quit his post-game talk show
bit for the Angels, will spend this fall doing UNLV football, while
Lamb, a Cypress resident, will do an eight-hour college football
show with Chris Rose for Fox Net Radio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their radio gigs, Kahn &AMP; Lamb also are available
for appearances at birthday parties, bar mitzvahs, high school
class reunions, Sierra Club banquets, NRA rallies, Moose Lodge
roasts and Shriner conventions.
</P>
</TEXT>
